<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-TEACHERS-COMPUTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SCHOOL ARE WIRED, BUT TEACHERS AREN'T 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ariz., N.Y.)   By AMY HARMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The teachers who gathered Thursday in Room 313 at
Public School 122 in Astoria, Queens, for the first day of a
workshop called ``Introduction to the Internet'' were model
students. They studied their list of vocabulary terms like ``home
page'' and ``modem.'' They raised their hands. And when the leader
asked a question, they tried to answer:
</P>
<P>
   ``How do we get from one place to another on the Internet?''
asked Doreen Rose, a technology specialist for the Board of
Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a mouse?'' ventured one elementary school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clicking?'' suggested another.
</P>
<P>
   The correct answer was ``hypertext links,'' and if some
fidgeting occurred during the subsequent explanation, Rose was not
inclined to send anyone to the principal. It was, after all, their
first day of summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   While the Clinton administration praises the growing number of
wired schools and computer classrooms, many teachers say they are
frustrated by their own inability to put their new tools to good
use. And with scant time given to training during the school year,
thousands of educators around the country are using their time off
this summer to confront what they see as their greatest deficiency:
technology literacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do I work with the kids when I don't have the background
myself?'' said Lorraine Attias, a fifth-grade teacher in Astoria
who regarded the four computers that appeared in her classroom last
year with a mixture of fear and longing. ``A year ago I knew
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Attias has since taken several courses with Rose, for which she
gets credits toward a raise, and her class now uses computer
software to produce a monthly newsletter. But some educators say
the smattering of official training combined with voluntary
seminars is not enough to ensure that the promise of applying
information technology to learning _ and the billions spent on it
so far _ will be realized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing lots of schools where they have the equipment,
and very frequently it's either underused or not used at all,''
said Vicki Rafel, a vice president of the National PTA. ``We see it
in the rural areas and inner cities but also in the suburbs.''
</P>
<P>
   That, it seems, is largely because teachers do not know what to
do with it. A study last year by Market Data Retrieval, an
educational research company, found that 61 percent of the
elementary and secondary teachers surveyed felt either ``not at all
prepared'' or only ``somewhat prepared'' to integrate technology
into classroom instruction.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, which recorded 1,576 responses to a
questionnaire mailed to 9,000 elementary and secondary school
teachers, those with 11 or more hours of technology training in the
previous year were far more likely to use technology in the
classroom than teachers who got less. About one-fourth of the
teachers said they had received no technology training during the
previous year. The average number of hours of instruction was five.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Clinton administration awarded $75 million in
grants to train new teachers in technology. And Linda Roberts, the
director of the Office of Education Technology for the U.S.
Department of Education, said that as the teaching work force
turned over, there would be a natural rise in the level of
technology proficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The younger teachers that are coming into our schools have
already grown up with the technology,'' Roberts said. ``They seem
to be able to more quickly appropriate it and find applications
that can support their teaching in the classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the 3 million teachers in the nation's public schools
seek to assimilate the alien machines materializing in their
classrooms, there is also a mounting debate about how, what or
whether to teach the teachers. If teachers are going to spend their
own time learning how to use computers, they are going to have to
first believe that doing so is worthwhile. Not all are convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computers do not change the thinking process,'' said Claire
Dusek, a history teacher at El Dorado High School, east of
Sacramento, who is the recipient of a technology grant under
California's ``digital high school'' program. She sees the primary
value of teaching technology as pragmatic: to get jobs when they
graduate, her students need to know how to use programs like
PowerPoint, Microsoft's program for business presentations.
</P>
<P>
   For some, it may simply be a question of conquering their own
pride. ``It's intimidating,'' said Michelle Finnegan, who is
preparing this summer to teach for the first time in a wired school
next year, Springfield Gardens High School in Queens. ``We're
teachers, so we're supposed to know what we're doing. With this, we
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, students know more than their teachers when it comes to
computers. The key, said Attias of Astoria, is to let them help.
``A lot of times I'll say, `Oh my God, what did I do?' and they'll
say, `You have to do THIS,' '' she said. ``I'm not embarrassed by
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barbara Radecki, a fifth-grade teacher in Coolidge, Ariz.,
said some teachers in her rural district had chosen not to apply
for a grant that would have given them computers and training.
``What has concerned me is the teachers at my school who are
threatened by it so they don't want to do it,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
