<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AZEVEDO HAS COME A LONG WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMITOS, Calif. _ The first time Tony Azevedo met some of
the veterans of U.S. Olympic water polo, long-time Long Beachers
like Chi Kridell, Robert Lynn and Kyle Kopp, he was a 7-year-old
pool rat they used to abuse for the fun of it.
</P>
<P>
   That was more than 10 years ago. His dad Ricardo, now the coach
of Long Beach State's men's and women's water polo teams, was
coaching the junior national team, and Tony would follow pop from
pool to pool and get underfoot as much as possible, because that's
what 7-year-olds do.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to lock me up in the ball cage,'' said the former
Long Beach Wilson High School standout, ``and poke sticks at me.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade-plus later, some things haven't changed. After Sunday's
title game in the UPS International Cup at the U.S. National
Aquatic Center in Los Alamitos, the youngest player in U.S.
national team history was handed the rather unimposing second-place
trophy and told to hang on to it.
</P>
<P>
   As a photographer tried to get the players to take a team
picture, Lynn kept good-naturedly hazing Azevedo from behind. As a
reporter tried to talk to Azevedo as he walked into the team's
locker room, his teammates literally swept him up and carried him
into the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, he's still being abused, but is no longer underfoot.
He's one of several reasons why the U.S. Olympic water polo team is
considered a medal candidate for the 2000 Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The youngster who dominated the Moore League and California
Interscholastic Federation Southern Section for four seasons
(1996-99) joined the national team in 1999 and has quickly earned
his place on the team. He's almost a full generation younger than
some of the thirtysomethings on the team, like goalkeeper Dan
Hackett, two-meter man Chris Humbert and ex-49er Kopp, but one
wouldn't know it from his play in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's 4-3 title-game loss to Yugoslavia, Azevedo had two
shots hit the crossbar and two others just miss their mark. In a
9-8 loss to the same team earlier in the tournament, he scored two
goals and his last-second shot for a tie caught the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony had a great tournament,'' said U.S. Olympic coach John
Vargas. ``He continues to get better. (His age) hasn't been a
difficulty at all. He's a very good, smart player with great
physical skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like his quickness not his physical quickness, but his
mental quickness. That's what gives him his edge. And he's just
starting.''
</P>
<P>
   Azevedo is a respectful 18-year-old who defers to his elders.
It's still special for him to remember when he watched guys like
Kopp and Humbert with awe. But his thoughts now are focused on what
he can do to help the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a great experience, a lot of fun,'' said
Azevedo. ``Being part of this team with these guys, I've learned
how to become an adult.''
</P>
<P>
   Traveling to places like Brazil, Canada, Australia, Croatia and
France can be fun, but he wouldn't be the first teen-ager to chafe
at the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great about Tony for three reasons,'' said his dad.
``One, he played almost the whole game today, so the coaches trust
him. Two, he's adjusted to playing with older players, and they
like him enough to take him under their wing. I can't tell you how
proud that makes me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three, he's being surrounded now, by the press, by kids, by
European professional teams that want to recruit him and he's
smiling, having a good time, and doesn't forget he's part of a
team. He's taking it all in stride.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition this week in Los Alamitos wasn't just a light
tune-up, either. Yugoslavia, Italy, Croatia and Australia are all
Olympic bound, and Yugoslavia is considered the co-favorite for the
gold medal with Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me put it like this,'' said Ricardo Azevedo. ``There are
eight players on that team (Yugoslavia) that just played on the
club that won the European Championship. That's like the (Lakers)
arriving after just winning the NBA title.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Yugoslavia treated two-meter Humbert like The Perfect
Storm treated the Andrea Gail. Every time the ball went in to
Humbert, it was followed by six Yugoslavian hands. The one goal
Humbert managed was a sensational backhand, back-to-the-net,
head-submerged shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played pretty great,'' said Tony Azevedo. ``You've played
good defense when you hold Yugoslavia to four goals. We just had a
few guys join the team, too.'' Kopp and Humbert also just returned
from European play.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. water polo team has been measuring itself against
Yugoslavia forever. Yugoslavia beat the U.S. in the gold medal game
of the 1984 and 1988 Olympics. In 1991, the U.S. beat Yugoslavia
for its first-ever FINA World Cup title, and also posted big
international wins over them in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to train against them,'' said Vargas. ``They've always
been a great training partner. They've always had a very solid,
fundamental program. In the last few years, I'd like to think
they've learned some things from us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, like pay attention to the 7-year-olds hanging around the
pool. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
