A1505 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     07-03 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Hobbled Sampras must watch his step
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Like its reigning six-time male champion,
Pete Sampras, what they're calling the millennium Wimbledon hobbled
through the first week troubled but, by and large, unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was a boycott by a couple of incensed Spaniards
over their seedings, which didn't correspond to their rankings. But
neither Alex Corretja nor Albert Costa would be missed in any way.
Their refusing to play as a show of protest simply saved them from
having to lose badly on a surface that consistently has bedeviled
them.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why, of course, they got seeded where they did.
Grass-court tennis is not for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The London weather has been as gray and gloomy as ever, but the
sporadic rain showers have been mostly a minor nuisance. Tennis'
most meteorologically challenged fortnight resumes today on
schedule, if not completely according to plan. Actually, this
tournament might have profited from some fortuitously timed
precipitation, saving Pistol Pete, inarguably Wimbledon's man of
the millennium, from an early demise.
</P>
<P>
   Suffering from an ``acute'' case of tendinitis in his lower left
leg just above the ankle, Sampras was supposed to go on Centre
Court last against Justin Gimelstob on Friday. But two drawn-out
matches preceded theirs, and when a late-afternoon drizzle set in,
tournament referee Alan Mills didn't hesitate to tell Pete he could
take it to the house.
</P>
<P>
   See, Wimbledon doesn't want to lose Sampras any more than
Sampras wants to lose at Wimbledon, where his record 13th Grand
Slam title is most likely to be obtained.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-hour respite wouldn't keep Sampras from dropping his
first set to the clumsy lummox Gimelstob in shockingly out-of-sorts
fashion, but he recovered to win easily, and Sunday's scheduled day
of rest bought him further healing time. He is, nonetheless, not in
good form, or humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is what it is _ an injury,'' Sampras said of his condition.
``It hurts. It's a big problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonas Borkman, his fourth-round obstacle, would normally be
considered no more than a minor speed bump for a guy whose record
here since the start of his first championship run in 1993 is an
astounding 50-1. As it happens, though, the 28-year-old journeyman
Swede is in both good form and humor. He hasn't come close to
surrendering a set.
</P>
<P>
   But should Sampras play the role of the whale and swallow Jonah,
uh, Jonas, his load lightens considerably. Another Swede,
ninth-seeded Thomas Enqvist, is at present the only seeded player
left between Sampras and Sunday's final.
</P>
<P>
   There have been an inordinate number of upsets _ more than half
the seeds have been banished, including both French Open champions,
Gustavo Kuerten and Mary Pierce _ but the major marquee names _
Sampras, Andre Agassi, Tim Henman, Patrick Rafter, the Williams
sisters and Martina Hingis foremost among them _ are hanging on.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a manner of speaking, Anna Kournikova remains among us,
too. Her sultry jog bra ads are everywhere, even on ubiquitous
rolling billboards trolling outside the gates along Church Road,
although she is personally long gone.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, if looks could play tennis
</P>
<P>
   Damir Dokic, alas, isn't gone. Tennis' latest father from hell,
a fellow who, at his worst, gives drunken louts everywhere a bad
name, was afforded a second chance by the Wimbledon authorities
despite launching a tirade on the sacred grounds during which he
called the women's tour ``fascist'' and, for emphasis, destroyed a
reporter's mobile phone by snatching it and smashing it on the
pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Dokic was treated leniently because he offered his
American Express gold card to pay for the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Damir was escorted from the premises, but he has been given
permission to return for daughter Jelena's remaining matches as
long as he behaves. Happily oblivious to her father's boorish
behavior, the talented young woman could reach the final because of
the muddled state of her part of the draw.
</P>
<P>
   With defending champion Lindsay Davenport scuffling because of a
bad back, Dokic's half is wide-open, providing the long-thwarted
trio of Monica Seles, Jennifer Capriati and Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario
with opportunities each might have believed had passed her by.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, No. 1 seed Martina Hingis probably will have
to go through Venus and Serena Williams consecutively to make it to
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, all of England clings to its slim hope that this
finally will be the year for Henman. When 65 former champions and
singles finalists convened at Centre Court to be recognized on
People's Saturday, the oldest among them was the last British male
to have played in the singles final.
</P>
<P>
   Bunny Austin, who got there in 1938, is 94.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
