<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WATERPOLO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIA BEATS U.S. TO WIN UPS CUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE MINARD  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMITOS, Calif. _ Everything was in place Sunday afternoon
at the UPS International Cup. Capacity crowd, close game between
two world powers, an exciting finish.
</P>
<P>
   So after the Yugoslavian national team edged Team USA 4-3 in the
championship game before an overflow crowd at the U.S. National
Aquatic Center in Los Alamitos, why was U.S. national team coach
John Vargas smiling?
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing those guys (Yugoslavia) is such a tremendous learning
experience. Considering that we've added four players in the last
week and a half, I'm ecstatic about where we're at,'' said Vargas.
``Our effort was excellent. We're making great strides.''
</P>
<P>
   The powerful Yugoslavian team, Olympic gold medalists in 1984
and 1988, owed its second one-goal victory over the U.S. in three
days to an aggressive defense and the standout play of goalie
Aleksandar Sostar.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (U.S.) have a strong team, we respect them. But our goal
is to win a gold medal, and we feel like we have a good chance to
do that,'' said Sostar, who was named the Outstanding Goalie of the
six-team tournament.
</P>
<P>
   For three periods Sunday, it was Sostar and his defense that
dominated the action.
</P>
<P>
   A conservatively played first period was scoreless until
Yugoslavia's Dejan Slavic followed a bar-out by 2-meter man Viktor
Jelenic at 1:33 to make it 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   The second period was even tighter, with the defenses
dominating. U.S. 2-meter man Chris Humbert had a couple of good
shots, and Tony Azevedo hit the crossbar with a shot from four
meters.
</P>
<P>
   On the initial possession of the third period, Kyle Kopp had the
ball stolen and, on the Yugoslavian counterattack, driver Jugoslav
Vasovic beat U.S. goalie Dan Hackett from the left side to make it
2-0 with 6:07 left in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, after the U.S. wasted a 6-on-5 opportunity,
Kopp was ejected, and Predrag Zimonjic made the man advantage
count, beating Hackett from four meters to make it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the final period, the U.S. got its offense going. With
a man advantage, Chris Oeding beat Sostar high to cut the deficit
to 3-1 with 5:56 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   That's when things got interesting.
</P>
<P>
   A minute later, Zimonjic was called for a 2-meter penalty,
giving the U.S. a penalty shot. But Eric Wigo's shot was stuffed by
Sostar, and the Yugoslavians dodged a bullet.
</P>
<P>
   After holding on their next possession, the Americans cut the
lead to 3-2 when Wigo took a pass from Gavin Arroyo and scored at
4:08.
</P>
<P>
   On the U.S. team's next possession, Veljko Uskokovic was
whistled for an infraction, and the U.S. had a man advantage. But
Wigo's pass for Humbert was stolen by Petar Trbojevic, and
Uskokovic scored on the ensuing counterattack to make it 4-2 with
2:20.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. had a breath left, though. Humbert's backhand from two
meters closed the gap to 4-3, but Azevedo's shot was blocked on
their next possession, and with the clock winding down, Humbert was
whistled for a foul with 35 seconds left, giving Yugoslavia a fresh
shot clock, which they ran out for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Asked afterward if he thought this might be a preview of the
Olympic final in Sydney, Vargas smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'd take that in a second,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In other games:
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA 7, AUSTRALIA 5: The strong Croatian team (4-2), which
lost only to the U.S. and Yugoslavia, downed the Aussies (2-3-1)
for third place.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY 9, TEAM UPS 1: The Italians (3-3), fresh off their
physical loss to the U.S. on Saturday, took out their frustrations
on Team UPS (0-6) for fifth place. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
