<SLUG> BC-6TH-GRADE-PRESSURES-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFILES IN PRESSURE, OR THE ABSENCE OF IT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Calif., Mont.)   (With 6TH-GRADE-PRESSURES) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
   ATLANTA _ Like so many children across the country, Aliyyah
Abdur-Rahman and Tajah Muhammad hope to grow up to be professional
athletes. But in addition to the typical pressures, the girls,
African-Americans from devout Muslim families, wear head scarves
while they practice and play.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And there are games during Ramadan, a month when Muslims fast
from sunrise to sundown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running up and down the court and we can't drink
anything,'' Tajah said. ``I love the religion. I just wish we
didn't have to cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Aliyyah and Tajah, best friends who held hands as they chatted
at the Clara Mohammed Elementary School, are as concerned about
tests and college admission as their counterparts in secular
schools. But they are also struggling to learn Arabic, and to win
weekly plaudits for exhibiting what the school calls Islamic
character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we're Muslim, they don't want us to get off the straight
path,'' Aliyyah explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all these earthly things to do _ like basketball
practice and soccer practice,'' she continued. ``Sometimes when I
get home, I'm so exhausted. We have this devil, Satan, Shaitan. He
whispers in my ear. He tells me just lay down, lay down.''
</P>
<P>
   Aliyyah wants to play in the WNBA, then be a chiropractor and a
lawyer _ and the first black woman president. Tajah plans to be a
professional soccer player, but not before she attends Duke
University. ``That's the school I have my destination focus on,''
she said. Both girls have a mix of A's and B's on their report
cards and are constantly trying to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really want to go to college,'' Tajah said. ``Because my
sister and my brother, I want to replace them, because they didn't
do too well in school.''
</P>
<P>
   Aliyyah, meanwhile, is jealous of her brother's straight A's and
top marks in Islamic character.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one in the family who always gets the attention _ I
want some of that, too,'' she said. ``My parents always say,
`Aliyyah, don't go down in your grade-point average, because it's
going to hurt you in life.' They tell me every day.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JODI WILGOREN
</P>
<P>
   SAN CARLOS, Calif. _ It's hard enough to weather sixth-grade
under ideal circumstances, let alone hobbled by cerebral palsy.
</P>
<P>
   What consoles Casey Fowler, 13, whose twisted gait draws
occasional titters from his classmates, is that he was not supposed
to make it to school at all _ but he has become a strong student at
the San Carlos Charter Learning Center, a '60s-tinged experimental
public school 25 miles south of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Born 12 weeks early, at 2 pounds, 4 ounces, Casey was given
little prospect of a normal life, because his brain had been
deprived of oxygen during birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told when he was a year old that he was seriously
retarded,'' said his mother, Debbie. ``That the only job he'd get
would be stacking boxes at Macy's.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fowler quit her nursing job to work full time on physical
and musical therapy with Casey to ease the symptoms of his
condition, which causes slow muscle development and muddled speech.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Casey's mind blossom _ by age 2 he had the
concentration to watch ``The Wizard of Oz'' in its entirety _ but
he pushed himself to ride a bike and skate. Though he has the
running ability of a 5-year-old, Casey played basketball in the
Redwood City Police Athletic League this year on a team that was
coached by his father, Ray.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made a shot yet,'' he said. ``I get close. It
bounced off the rim two times.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Casey's shaky gait and hands make him an easy target for
teasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been called a retard,'' Casey told a visitor. But an
11-year-old classmate cut him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already been through this a million times before, in
class,'' the boy said.
</P>
<P>
   Casey just looked away.
</P>
<P>
   With an encyclopedic knowledge of movies and strong grades in
English, Casey hopes to attend UCLA film school to train as a
director or screenwriter or producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lucky,'' Casey said. ``Other people have it worse.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JACQUES STEINBERG
</P>
<P>
   BLOOMFIELD, Mont. _ Pressure? To Kirk and Brady Boese, it is a
word missing from their sixth-grade vocabulary list.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeses, towheaded twins, are the only sixth-graders at the
Bloomfield School in the Montana plains, 247 miles from the
Billings airport and 27 from the nearest McDonald's. Since
kindergarten, their classroom has been the same white clapboard
building, shared this year with 11 other children, ages 6 to 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year in school, I was just a lot more relaxed,'' said
Brady, who is older but smaller than his brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixth-grade is easier,'' Kirk agreed. ``There's so little
changes in Bloomfield. We haven't even moved our desks.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kirk and Brady, who are 12, this was the year Dad _ who also
went to Bloomfield _ taught them to hunt, for white-tailed deer,
and let them drive the pickup around the 2,000-acre wheat farm.
They rarely have homework, leaving afternoons a carefree mix of
shooting hoops and tidying their collection of Minnesota Twins and
Timberwolves paraphernalia. Friday and Saturday nights, they go
golfing.
</P>
<P>
   As for peer pressure, well, they don't really have peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not really an oddball,'' Brady explained. ``If you
play basketball and you're good at it, you fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, though, the Boeses plan to commute 20 miles to a
school in Richey, the nearest town, so they can play sports. There,
they'll be part of a class of six.
</P>
<P>
   Both Boese boys are good students, but their only thoughts of
college come when watching NCAA games on satellite television.
Cedric Boese, their father, has warned the twins that the farm
could never support two families _ they will have to seek other
jobs, probably somewhere else. Still, the boys' musings on the
future are vague and childlike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just see different places,'' Brady shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of just cows and dogs,'' Kirk added.
</P>
<P>
   ``See the ocean again,'' Brady said. ``Instead of just
farmland.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JODI WILGOREN
</P>
</TEXT>
