<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 THE TIGHTROPE WOMEN WALK In PUBLIC LIFE  
 By JOYCE PURNICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Images of women, selected at random (OK, not totally
at random) from recent newspaper and television accounts:
</P>
<P>
   A reprint of recipes for Tipper Gore's Ginger Snaps and Laura
Bush's Texas Governor's Mansion Cowboy Cookies, as originally run
in Family Circle.
</P>
<P>
   A news story about Jeanine Pirro, the district attorney of
Westchester, seeing her career in ruins after her husband's
conviction for tax fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Reports that women are increasingly comfortable wearing less in
the office.
</P>
<P>
   A feature story about a bosom lift, accompanied by assessments
of the varying virtues of push-up bras.
</P>
<P>
   An excerpt on WNBC-TV from an amateur video, which seemed to
show that among the many women terrified by marauding men in
Central Park after the National Puerto Rican Day Parade, two or
three women enjoyed displaying various parts of their anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   And so on.
</P>
<P>
   What is wrong with these pictures? Just about everything. It is
a sad fact that still, not only do men not know what women want,
women don't know, either. A broad generalization, of course. Many
women know just what they want.
</P>
<P>
   But oh, what society does to us. What we do to ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   This comes to mind now because recently, speaking at Baruch
College, Geraldine Ferraro said, as she has before, that she was
subjected to some of the scrutiny she endured as the Democratic
vice-presidential candidate in 1984 only because she is a woman.
Just as Hillary Rodham Clinton has said that a woman has a more
difficult time running for office than a man does.
</P>
<P>
   These assertions are difficult to refute. It is still true that
strong men are assertive; strong women are strident. Thoughtful men
are flexible; thoughtful women are indecisive. It is still true
that a female candidate is suspect.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more complicated than stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro wasn't quite ready for prime time. She delayed releasing
her income tax returns (a result of her accountant's diligence, she
now says), made things worse for herself by acting as if probing
questions were invasions of privacy and was simply unprepared for
the onslaught of critical attention.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro was not only a victim of her husband's financial games,
but also a beneficiary, who, trial testimony suggested, knew or
should have known about the schemes to defraud the government of
more than $400,000 by deducting the family's personal expenses as
business write-offs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wants it both ways. She wants to be judged for her own
accomplishments. But she piggybacks on her husband's career, was
his fierce defender and, having never run for political office
before, is trying to start near the top in a state not her own.
</P>
<P>
   There is pattern here, of women in public life seeing themselves
as both independent and victimized; as speechmaker and cookie
baker; aggressor and martyr. Of course they do. They don't live in
isolation.
</P>
<P>
   In the very public profession of politics, whose practitioners
(male and female) are subject to intense scrutiny by the opposition
and the news media, women still have to fight deeply ingrained
stereotypes. Unfair. As Ferraro noted, if a female politician has
children, she's accused of neglecting them, and if she is single,
she should expect rumors that she is a lesbian. Clinton was never
more popular than when she was a victim. Another cliche _ woman as
victim.
</P>
<P>
   But women contribute to their own stereotyping: Ferraro saying
that her husband handled all the family finances. Or Clinton and
Pirro ``standing by'' their men.
</P>
<P>
   Which is it, independent woman or loyal wife? Thing is, society
forces women in public life to be both. Most play along, and not
just in public life.
</P>
<P>
   Of course some women respond eagerly to marketers of push-up
bras. Or think they can get away with wearing revealing clothes in
the corporate suite. Or even assume it's fine to bare all in
public. And still have careers outside the home and still be taken
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice indeed if women could do as they wished.
Imagine for a moment the average female politician being as
routinely unimpressive as the average male politician. Or a woman
in public office confessing to marital infidelity and remaining
popular. Someday. Maybe when a woman in politics concedes that she
buys her ginger snaps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
