<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1529 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS-HNS &LR;      07-03 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Braves top Mets, leave Shea with NL East lead intact
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DAVID BARRON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tom Glavine's seven strong innings and Javy Lopez's
two home runs Sunday gave the Atlanta Braves a 10-2 victory over
the Mets and a split of their four-game series at Shea Stadium,
ensuring the only entity to exit this holiday weekend in the red
was the New York Police Department's overtime fund.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred officers _ the NYPD will neither confirm nor
deny numbers _ were on duty for a fourth day to stand watch over
Atlanta reliever John Rocker, who didn't pitch for a third day in a
row. Rocker, who is nursing an injured thumb, said he could have
pitched, but he wasn't needed as the Braves gave Glavine a 7-0 lead
through four innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' departure frees up police to stand watch over
Independence Day weekend activities that will include an appearance
by President Clinton, a parade along the Hudson River of 27 tall
ships and an armada of 70,000 private boats around Manhattan.
Police estimate 28,800 officers will be on duty Tuesday, a total
that puts even Rocker to shame.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, the Braves and Mets can get back to a sense
of normalcy, too. Rocker pitched a 1-2-3 inning in a Braves
victory; he went out to dinner with his girlfriend, Staci Sutton,
the daughter of Braves announcer Don Sutton; he didn't ride the
subway; and aside from a daily chorus of boos from the Shea crowd,
he escaped his return to New York unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it's over,'' Rocker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the back of my mind, I thought something might happen,''
said Atlanta outfielder Brian Jordan. ``New York did a great job
with security, and the fans were really studious. They love their
Mets, and they showed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in part to Glavine's work and Lopez's two solo homers,
Atlanta cooled off, at least for a day, a Mets team that had won
nine of 10 games. The Mets, however, broke even with a team they
have not beaten in a series since September 1998. After pulling
within a game of Atlanta in the National League East with
back-to-back wins, the Mets remain two games back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything was lost this weekend,'' Mets manager
Bobby Valentine said. ``We came in with a pretty hot streak,
knowing that streak would come to an end. We went 2-2. That's
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the added security, the weekend had something of a
festive air. Pitcher Mike Hampton and several other Mets players
brought their children onto the field before Saturday's game, and
New York outfielder Derek Bell tooled through the clubhouse on a
borrowed NYPD bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, meanwhile, had cause to celebrate with the birth of
Larry Wayne Jones III, born to third baseman Chipper Jones and his
wife, Sharon, on Friday night. Jones took a private plane to
Atlanta for the birth, flew back to New York and played Saturday on
two hours' sleep before sitting out Sunday's game with flu-like
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big boy,'' Jones said of the new arrival. ``He was 9
pounds, 14 ounces, 21 inches. I saw him and said, `Holy smoke. He's
bigger than the fish hanging on my wall.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their booing of Rocker, New York fans had even more to
cheer about with the play of catcher Mike Piazza and outfielder
Bell. Piazza was 6-for-17 in the four games with three homers and
eight RBIs, extending his hitting streak to 20 games and his streak
of games with at least one RBI to 15. The record is 17, set by Ray
Grimes of the Cubs in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   Before going hitless Sunday to end an 11-game hitting streak,
Bell had scored in a club-record 11 straight games. He went 4-for-5
with three runs and four RBIs on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets also lost pitcher Rick Reed for two to three weeks
with a broken wrist suffered Thursday night. Appropriately, given
the theatrical nature of the series opener, Reed was hurt when he
was hit by an Andruw Jones line drive that he lost in the backdrop
of the white lettering of the rotating ad boards behind home plate.
</P>
<P>
   But Reed should have other chances. The Braves and Mets must
play nine more times this season _ three games this month in
Atlanta, followed by a pair of three-game series in Atlanta (Sept.
18-20) and New York (Sept. 26-28) in the final two weeks of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The games in September mean a lot more than these do,'' said
Braves outfielder Bobby Bonilla, the former Mets player who was
booed almost as mercilessly as Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of things won't fade any time soon for the Mets and
their fans, however. After losing the opener Thursday, New York
scored 10 runs in the eighth inning Friday night, capped by
Piazza's three-run homer, for an 11-8 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team has to have a game to look back on when the season
is over,'' said the Mets' Matt Franco. ``Now we have ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, in a game that was televised to more than half the
nation, the Mets knocked out Greg Maddux, who had been suffering
from the flu, after only four innings en route to a 9-1 victory. It
was Maddux's shortest starting stint in more than four years and
gave the Mets their first back-to-back wins over Atlanta since
September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   New York could have taken the NL East lead by percentage points
with a win Sunday, but the Mets were never in the game after giving
up four runs in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine (8-5), who had lost four straight decisions since
beating San Diego on May 21, was efficient and silenced the crowd
for six innings.
</P>
<P>
   The lefthander allowed back-to-back homers to Piazza and Todd
Zeile with one out in the seventh but got out of the inning without
further damage and was replaced by Jason Marquis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the same position today as when we came in,''
Glavine said. ``From that standpoint, these are big games. It's
still too early to get too excited. A lot of things could change
before we play again.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle news services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
