</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KREUTER WANTS TO STAY A DODGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Todd Hundley is a free agent after the season.
So are Chad Kreuter and Jim Leyritz. And questions remain in the
organization about prospect Angel Pena's wantonness to catch
regularly in the major leagues, which could leave the Dodgers'
catching situation in disarray after the season.
</P>
<P>
   The price tag to retain Hundley could be too much even for the
Dodgers to afford, but not so to keep Kreuter, who's become an
integral part of the club. He's impressed the Dodgers to the point
of where they will try and re-sign him after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be able to work something out at the proper time,
which is after the season,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone
said. ``He wants to stay, and in all likelihood we'll be able to
work something out.''
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter's importance goes beyond being a backup catcher. He's
turned into pitcher Chan Ho Park's personal catcher, and in the
process helped Park put his career back on the right path. With
Park not eligible for free agency until after the 2001 season, the
Dodgers hope to keep that relationship intact.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter is highly respected by the entire pitching staff, and
the organization has eye on Kreuter helping Pena grow into the
every-day catcher's position by working closely with him next
season, if that scenario unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   It will undoubtedly aid Kreuter that his agent, Scott Boras,
also represents Park, Kevin Brown, Eric Gagne, Darren Dreifort and
Pena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I want to stay,'' said Kreuter, a former Pepperdine
star. ``I knew in spring training this is the place where I wanted
to be. Obviously, I need to perform and then the powers that be
have to continue to stand by me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter is also thankful for the way the Dodgers treated him
since the May 16 fight at Chicago's Wrigley Field. Kreuter was the
first one in the stands after allegedly getting hit in the back of
the head before having his cap stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers have stood by me 100 percent, and it thrills me
that they have,'' said Kreuter. ``I think the fan base has stood by
me close to 100 percent, too. I think that everybody that is a
knowledgeable, well-rounded person probably feels they would have
reacted in the same exact way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every player I've talked to on every team that we've come
across said they'd do the same exact thing. So I know I have the
support.''
</P>
<P>
   GREEN GETS A REST: After starting 79 straight games and slumping
for the last two weeks, right fielder Shawn Green wasn't in the
starting lineup but made a cameo appearance as a pinch hitter. He
struck out with the tying run on first in the seventh inning,
illustrating why manager Davey Johnson wanted to rest him in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   Green's production, and average, dropped drastically in the last
two weeks. He's mired in a 3 for 33 slump during which his average
fell from .332 to .305. He hit just two homers and batted .260 in
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done all right, but I feel I'm not even close to what I
can do,'' said Green, who has 12 homers and 57 RBI. ``I feel a lot
of that comes from going to a new team and wanting to hit a lot of
home runs, or do something like that, and then all of a sudden
getting out of your swing and it becomes a vicious cycle and things
you're trying to do become harder and harder for you because you go
away from what got you there.''
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: Shawn Gilbert started in place of Green, but
it'll be his last one for a while. He's expected to be optioned to
Triple-A Albuquerque before the Dodgers play San Diego on Tuesday.
Middle infielder Mike Metcalfe was batting .320 with 19 RBI in 28
games with Dukes and, after stealing 34 bases at Double-A San
Antonio, leads the minor leagues with 43 steals. ... Right-hander
Gregg Olson pitched a scoreless inning in a rehab stint with
Single-A San Bernardino at San Jose. He allowed one hit, walked one
and struck out two. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
