<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLAUS STILL STRUGGLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Troy Glaus, after missing last Sunday and
Monday with back spasms _ the first two games he missed this season
_ has returned to the lineup. Now if only his swing would.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus is 1 for 21 with 13 strikeouts since his return and has
gone hitless in four games _ the first such stretch he's had this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The third baseman was 0 for 4 Sunday against Oakland with two
strikeouts and failed to hit the ball out of the infield. When he
came to the plate in the seventh with two runners on and the Angels
trailing 8-2, Glaus whiffed at a first-pitch fastball from Jeff Tam
before taking the next two pitches, both fastballs, for called
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus, who leads the Angels with 23 homers but has seen his
average slip more than 20 points in the past week to .296, made
like his swing afterward and disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's off right now,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ``We're
seeing some good swings, but there's a little indecision. It's not
unexpected. This game can be frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   How long Scioscia allows Glaus to swing his way out of the slump
isn't clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping by playing him, he'll play his way out of it,''
Scioscia said. ``Troy's a major part of the offense. There also
comes a time when you're struggling when you consider other
options, but we're not at that point right now.''
</P>
<P>
   SOLID STARTERS: The Angels have been getting solid pitching from
their starting rotation for the last month, but not the kind of
dominating performances they got when Brian Cooper shut out Oakland
7-0 on Friday and Jarrod Washburn took a no-hitter into the seventh
inning of a 7-2 victory Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Angels have held the opposition to two runs or less
just 13 times in 81 games and only one other time _ April 15 and 16
by Kent Bottenfield and Scott Schoeneweis _ did they do it in
back-to-back games.
</P>
<P>
   Performances like Cooper's and Washburn's help the Angels in
more areas than the win column.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are good games to have where you're not, as an entire
team, trying to grind out a win,'' pitching coach Bud Black said.
``Mentally, there's less stress when the pitcher's in control and
the offense is getting the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives the whole club a mental rest, and we haven't played a
lot of games like that this year. It's been battle, battle,
battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis, on the disabled list since June 17 with a strained
rib cage, is continuing to play catch, but no timetable has been
set for his return or rehab program, Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTED? When the All-Star game starters are announced Tuesday,
Oakland first baseman Jason Giambi, the former Long Beach State
star, could become the first Athletic to be voted on since Mark
McGwire and Jose Canseco in 1992. Giambi led Jim Thome by 29,122
votes as of last Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
