<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-SHOCK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS STREAK HITS NINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KERRY MURRAY  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ After his team's offense recorded a 22-point
romp and its defense held the Detroit Shock in check, the Sparks
received nothing but praise from coach Michael Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great effort,'' the first-year WNBA coach said of his
team's 85-63 rout of the Shock on Sunday night at the Forum.
``We're slowly but surely honing our game.''
</P>
<P>
   The win extends the Sparks' winning streak to nine, a franchise
record and the longest this season in the WNBA. Overall, the team
is 13-2.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said he was most impressed with his team's defensive
effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit team scored 96 points in a 12-point loss to
Sacramento on Saturday and is not at all shy about taking shots.
</P>
<P>
   However, constant pressure from the entire Los Angeles team held
the Shock to 36 percent shooting (26 for 72) from the floor, and 11
percent (1 for 9) from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   For the Sparks, Mwadi Mabika scored a team-high 21 points,
including a team-best 4 of 5 from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Saturday) I shot some airballs, so I wasn't too happy with
that,'' Mabika said. ``Tonight I went out worked on my outside shot
before the game and I think that helped. I just came out, took my
shot and was feeling good.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said he also was pleased with the outside shooting,
noting there will be times when his team will have to turn to that
type of game depending on the defense it encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more defenses we get accustomed to the better,'' Cooper
said. ``It will all help when we get into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Sparks' bench came in and took care of business,
holding on to a steady 20-point lead in the final five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Leslie, who absorbed three fouls early, sat out nearly 10
minutes in the first half. She fouled out with a little more than
three minutes left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Depth, however, kept the Sparks in the game as Delisha Milton
and Allison Feaster scored 12 and 10 points, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks are expecting more of challenge Wednesday night when
they travel to Sacramento to face one of the two teams to beat them
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks return to the Forum at 7:30 p.m. Thursday against the
Washington Mystics. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
