<HEADER>
A1535 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-US-BRAZIL-SERLENG     07-03 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-BRAZIL-SERLENGA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERLENGA SURPRISED BY STINT ON US TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ She was one of the thumbnail-size up-and-comers in the
back of the US Soccer press guide this year and that's where Nikki
Serlenga reckoned it would end. ``I figured I'd finish my soccer
career at Santa Clara, graduate, and have a family,'' she says. ``I
wanted to grow up _ or what I thought was growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the phone rang last winter and a voice asked Serlenga if
she wanted to play for the national team in a tournament Down
Under. The Girls of Summer were on strike and the federation was
looking for a few good women. ``A two-week vacation in Australia?''
Serlenga mused. ``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   So it began and so it goes on . . . and on . . . and on for one
of the more intriguing of the fresh faces that coach April
Heinrichs has been running through the US squad.
</P>
<P>
   Serlenga came back from Australia and was invited to camp when
the A team came back to work. Heinrichs gave her a uniform and kept
putting her in games. And when the Americans go to Sydney in
September to chase another Olympic gold medal, the 22-year-old
midfielder from San Diego may well go with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no guarantees, even now,'' Serlenga understands. She
plays Michelle Akers's position _ defensive holding midfielder _
and Akers, the team's ageless Alpha female, is expected back from
shoulder surgery this month.
</P>
<P>
   Serlenga has been splitting time with Lorrie Fair, who played
for last year's World Cup team. Only 18 women will make the Olympic
team and Heinrichs is unlikely to keep three holding mids. It's a
numbers game, and Serlenga knows enough not to try doing the math
in her head. ``If you try to put the A team together,'' she says,
``it drives you nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, when Serlenga has been out there with the A team,
especially in the ongoing Gold Cup tournament, her footprints are
all over the match. She turned the hat trick in the 8-0 demolition
of Costa Rica. ``I hadn't scored three goals since high school,
back when you'd get eight a game,'' Serlenga says.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday in Louisville, it was Serlenga who launched the
sideline-to-sideline pass that set up Shannon MacMillan for the
12th-minute goal that stung Canada and sent the Americans on their
way to Monday night's final against Brazil at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Only Akers does that, US Soccer people were saying. And while
Serlenga doesn't have Akers's power-forward dimensions _ she's 5-5,
130 to Akers's 5-10, 150 _ she has more than a whiff of her
presence. Her long blonde hair, which makes Serlenga identifiable
from the cheap seats, summons up Akers's leonine mane. And her
dead-ball walk is similarly purposeful and authoritative.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Serlenga saw herself as an understudy. She didn't even
watch last summer's World Cup victory over China _ she was flying
East that day. ``The national team wasn't a goal for me,'' she
says. ``It wasn't even a thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Serlenga was a member of the US under-20 pool, she had
only been in camp once for a week. But her college credentials
(twice a first-team All-American for Santa Clara, four times in the
NCAA final four, an unbeaten regular season last fall) got Serlenga
on the short list for the national team.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she had second thoughts when the call came last winter.
If she missed two weeks of classes, Serlenga would essentially miss
the quarter. And she was reluctant to alienate the Girls of Summer
by stepping into their shoes as a replacement player. ``Am I going
to step on anybody's toes doing this?'' Serlenga wondered. ``Won't
they resent me?''
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about it, said Jerry Smith, Serlenga's college coach
(and Mr. Brandi Chastain). Take the opportunity. That's how
Chastain got back on the team after being bypassed for the 1995
World Cup. The players went on strike to protest the Olympic bonus
plan, Chastain was brought in and ended up playing every minute of
the Games and winning a gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   Graduation can wait, Serlenga's mother told her. ``I felt I was
being responsible by thinking I should stay in school,'' Serlenga
says. ``And my mom was like, go play soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   So she did, and scored a goal against the Czechs in her first
international match. ``It was the worst goal, but because it was in
Australia nobody knew about it,'' Serlenga confesses. ``I think the
chunk of dirt I hit went further than the ball. But the goalkeeper
went for the chunk of dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   The JVs ended up winning the tournament and Serlenga got an
invitation to train with the varsity. That ruled out school for the
rest of the winter and spring and it put Serlenga on a magical
mystery tour unlike anything she's ever known.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of these black-and-white, cut-and-dried people,'' she
says. ``I like everything laid out. I write all this stuff in my
day planner. I want to know what I'm doing next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm may know. Nikki Serlenga doesn't. ``I could be in
Germany next week,'' she says. ``And I could be back in San
Diego.'' Serlenga might play against the Brazilians Monday night
and she might not. Heinrichs is still in experimental mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no clue,'' Serlenga shrugs. ``At the end of this
tournament, they'll name the roster for the German trip. That's the
most stability I have right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds are that Heinrichs won't name the Olympic team until the
end of the month, if then. But Serlenga has gone ahead and bought
tickets anyway. ``For my Mom,'' she says. ``If I don't make it, she
can still go. I figure I owe her for all the gas she bought driving
me to soccer all those years.''
</P>
<P>
   If Serlenga doesn't make it, there's another World Cup in 2003,
another Olympics in 2004, and the WUSA pro league next year (she'll
be playing for Atlanta). ``I'll be around,'' she says. ``It isn't
like if I don't make the Olympic team I'll be banned and sent
away.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole year has been a bonus ball, the way Serlenga sees it.
``Who would have thought they would pick someone who wasn't in the
pool?'' she says. The day planner can only plan so much.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Serlenga doesn't even plan dinner. ``We're going out
for Thai food,'' teammate Julie Foudy told Serlenga Sunday &UR;  &LR; night,
while she was sitting around the Sheraton Needham. ``Get dressed.
Let's go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
