<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1538 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-SELES-B     07-03 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-SELES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELES BACK IN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It was the macabre irony of Wimbledon's opening week, a
grievous reminder of how outrageously sports trivialize reality
when winning and losing are equated with life and death.
</P>
<P>
   In each of her first three matches before the tournament's
midpoint respite Sunday, Monica Seles was assigned to Court 2.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the so-called show courts, among the most prominent
at the All England Lawn Tennis &AMP; Croquet Club. But it is more
popularly known by its nickname. Because upsets of prohibitive
favorites have become commonplace on its grass in recent years, it
has been dubbed the Graveyard of Champions.
</P>
<P>
   While the point it illustrates may be harmless enough, the mere
mention of it in connection with Seles is offensive. Her career was
diminished, her life forever altered, her innocence shattered by a
true tragedy on a tennis court.
</P>
<P>
   On April 30, 1993, when she was 19 years old and without peer in
women's tennis, Seles was severely wounded by a crazed spectator.
During a changeover while she was playing Magdalena Maleeva in a
quarterfinal at Hamburg, she was stabbed in the back, just below
the left shoulder blade, by a 38-year-old German, Guenther Parche,
who perpetrated this violence in a manic attempt to restore his
countrywoman, Steffi Graf, to preeminence in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Perversely, it worked. Graf also was traumatized by the
incident, but the fact was that it effectively removed Seles, who
had won eight of the last 10 Grand Slam events she had entered _
two US, three French, and three Australian opens _ as an obstacle.
Seles did not play competitive tennis for the next 27 months.
Meanwhile, Graf again became dominant. And in an interpretation of
justice that could be considered as criminal as the offense,
Parche, in effect, received a suspended sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was so much injustice in there,'' Seles said last week,
``that maybe one day when someone really looks into it, they'll
realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   But no amount of revisionist jurisprudence can provide
restitution for her stolen promise.
</P>
<P>
   Seles hasn't approached her teen level of supremacy since her
return Aug. 15, 1995. She seemed vulnerable, tentative, haunted, as
if waiting for _ fearing _ the next psychotic assault. In the
nearly five full years since her comeback, she has reached four
Grand Slam finals but won only once _ at the 1996 Australian Open.
Remove the knife from Parche's hand and her stockpile of major
championships could have increased tenfold, by conservative
estimate.
</P>
<P>
   As if that were not ordeal enough, she watched her beloved
father, Karolj, suffer horribly from cancer before his death in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   So the Yugoslav pixie with the guttural grunt that punctuates
each shot and the sublime talent forever has been compromised.
</P>
<P>
   Graveyard of Champions, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I had such a clean slate till '93,'' said Seles. ``My
life had been so much tennis, my focus. (It was) obviously totally
different then. I lost two matches a year. I think Steffi and I,
those few years, were just dominating tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then obviously after the stabbing, things became different.
You have to think that I didn't touch a racket for 2 1/2 years.
There were a lot hurdles for me to overcome on my own, and then
obviously some other hurdles, too. But I think that's for sure one
of the biggest things that has been hard, because I was playing so
well at that point in my career. I was at a prime age of 19 for the
sport, and that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   But a remarkable transformation has taken place recently. Seles
appears somehow refreshed, as if she has experienced a catharsis of
sorts. She won the Italian Open in May, then reached the French
quarterfinals before yielding to eventual champion Mary Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   And while she believes Wimbledon, the lone major she lacks,
remains the most elusive because ``it just, unfortunately, doesn't
suit my game,'' the No. 6 seed has advanced to the fourth round
Monday _ on Court 1, mercifully _ against No. 9 Arantxa Sanchez
Vicario.
</P>
<P>
   As she soldiered on through her week at accursed Court 2 _
pulling a great escape against Karina Habsudova before sweeping
aside Els Callens and Sarah Pitkowski _ Seles seemed increasingly
more assured and relaxed, as if treasuring each moment more than
she would have if so many hadn't been taken from her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just really love to play the game of tennis,'' she said. ``I
mean, nothing really besides that really matters to me as much as .
. . my love for the game. Whether that be playing in a Grand Slam
or whether that be practicing at home (in Sarasota, Fla.), I just
love to play. When I wake up in the morning, that's one of my
favorite things to do. I'm just very lucky I can do it
professionally, plus I can do it healthwise and all that other
stuff with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were periods in my life when I didn't have this, and the
last few years have been difficult and there's times I probably
didn't want to be on the tennis court. But I have to say the past
six months, it really appears I was looking forward to going out on
the court. It's really nice to have that feeling back, because for
a long time, it wasn't there _ not on my own, but because of other
stuff outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Her popularity has increased in inverse proportion to her
superiority. At 26, she has become something of a beloved elder,
whereas she was resented for her aloofness _ or more likely her
success _ in her heyday. The change in status is pronounced. While
alleging last week that she had been hazed and subjected to racial
slurs during her first year on the WTA Tour, Alexandra Stevenson
specified Seles as one of the players who welcomed and supported
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think I was unconsciously not nice (before),''
said Seles. ``I was 14, 15, really in my own shell, kind of. Just
said, `Hi,' `Bye,' looked down at the floor. I was very shy. I
think that's how people perceived me in the beginning. Then, by
like when I was 18, they realized that I was different. I changed
probably as a person, too. I was much more open. I wasn't as shy as
I was when I was 14.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, she is perhaps more determined now, though she
still isn't ready to rush down to Ladbrokes to place a wager on
herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personality is that I would not enter a tournament if I
would not believe I could win it,'' she said. ``This tournament is
no different. Winning Wimbledon would truly be amazing. You can't
really even put that in words. But I'm in the fourth round and I
have such a long way to go that all I'm doing right now is focusing
on my next match.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, she cannot lose here, regardless of the outcome.
Startlingly, she has maintained throughout the week that she
harbors no lingering animosity toward her assailant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've moved on,'' she said. ``Certain things are not going to
change. But I have no anger or bitterness over that.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is Seles's ultimate revenge. She won't let Guenther
Parche bother her anymore. That is a victory that transcends games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
