<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERETT FRAY A WELL-WORN TALE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In that American League playoff hunt best known as
``Survivor,'' the Red Sox are about to be voted off the island.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, they finished getting swept by the White Sox and Carl
Everett kicked off the time-tested Boston tradition of blaming the
media.
</P>
<P>
   Inimitable Sox manager Pinky Higgins once pushed the face of our
own Bud Collins into a plate of pasta. Years earlier, a
knife-wielding Boston manager is said to have chased a Hub scribe
through a moving railcar. And who can forget Jim Rice ripping the
shirt off the Globe's intrepid Steve Fainaru?
</P>
<P>
   Now there's Everett trying to have harmless me tossed from the
clubhouse before the latest in a depressing line of Sox losses.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours before Sunday's inevitable 8-2 thrashing, I was
standing at the door of Jimy Williams's office when I heard Everett
in the clubhouse grumbling, ``Who wrote Frye and I were fighting?''
</P>
<P>
   Figuring I might be able to shed some light on the issue, I
walked toward Everett.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I tried to talk to you Friday night,'' I started to
tell him. ``You had no comment and Jeff said you two weren't going
at it . . .''
</P>
<P>
   He heard none of it. I was the bad guy _ ``a curly-haired
(expletive) trying to stir things up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only the beginning of a lengthy, expletive-filled tirade
_ outrageous and obscene even by the lofty standards of what my big
ears have heard over the years. Sox publicist Glenn Wilburn stepped
between us and started to nudge me away from Everett. Wilburn was
just doing his job, but it always has amused me that when a
ballplayer flies off the handle the peacemaker usually tells the
object of ire to move away.
</P>
<P>
   Everett wouldn't stop yelling and swearing. Yeesh. This man, who
points to God after every homer and claims he lives by the word of
the Bible, was using every vile word I'd ever heard _ in the middle
of the clubhouse _ just after the Sox had filed into their Sunday
chapel meeting.
</P>
<P>
   It reminded me of the bad old days of 1986 when a Globe
photographer accidentally stumbled into the Sox' Sunday morning
chapel meeting at Fenway and was confronted by an angry outfielder
who screamed, ``Get the (expletive) out of here. Can't you see
we're having our (expletive) chapel?''
</P>
<P>
   Everett told me never to talk with him again (ouch, there's a
void in my life). He told me to get out of the room. His house, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to be like the Sundance Kid and say, ``If you ask me to
stay, I'll leave,'' but this didn't seem like the time for humor. I
stayed.
</P>
<P>
   While Everett was screaming, Williams asked the writers in his
office who was doing the yelling. They told him it was Everett.
Williams never moved.
</P>
<P>
   Back out in the big room, coach Tommy Harper got in front of
Everett, wrapped him up, and slowly nudged him to the other side of
the clubhouse. Everett was still calling me vile names. I tossed a
few back at him. It had been reduced to your basic schoolyard
(You're fat . . . Oh yeah, you're ugly) argument.
</P>
<P>
   Everett got in the face of Wilburn and told him it was his job
to kick me out. When Wilburn wouldn't do it, Everett started to
verbally abuse the publicist. Everett later apologized to Wilburn.
</P>
<P>
   Ever-mindful that fans don't give a hoot about media problems, I
have avoided writing about these inevitable episodes. It's part of
the game. When you rip someone in the paper, who can blame that
player for ripping back? It's only human, and writers should expect
a measure of this.
</P>
<P>
   When I called Steve Crawford a sack of doorknobs, it didn't
surprise me that he got in my face and made all kinds of threats.
You dish it out, you take it. Fair enough. Mo Vaughn probably had a
reason to unload on me in the Sox clubhouse two years ago. Amid the
glowing stuff, I'd written some harsh things about Vaughn's court
case and his contract talks. Ditto for Wade Boggs, Jim Rice, Bill
Fitch, and John McNamara. This job is going to get guys mad
sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to figure Everett's outburst and it speaks to the
larger problem of Everett as a loose cannon and the Red Sox'
overall frustration. Good clubhouse karma, a signature of the Sox
for the last two years, seems to be eroding.
</P>
<P>
   Some background info. In Saturday's Globe I wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``Frye got into an animated discussion with Carl Everett before
the bottom of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't getting into it,'' said Frye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to say,'' said Everett.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. In Sunday's paper, Gordon Edes explained that Everett
was ``commiserating'' with Frye after the utilityman struck out
pinch hitting for Mike Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   That was the source of Everett's outrage. Two Red Sox were
observed talking in an animated fashion, they were asked about it,
and it was reported with no characterization of negativity. Frye is
fine with it. Everett just doesn't know what was written.
</P>
<P>
   Everett largely has been deified in the Boston papers this year
and he deserves it. He's a legitimate Most Valuable Player
candidate and he deserves to start the All-Star Game. (He ranks
fourth among all outfielders in the latest balloting.) He made
another spectacular catch Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But his five-star nutty was hard to figure. Perhaps he had me
confused with some other smart, handsome, athletic scribe. There
are, after all, so many of us. Perhaps he was trying to light a
fire under the slumping Sox. Perhaps he wants his teammates to
rally around him and think of him as a leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll talk to Carl about this,'' said Sox publicist Kevin
Shea, who was not with the team in Chicago. ``I'm sure Jimy will
talk to Carl. It's probably some frustration because of the way
things are going.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are not going well. But don't tell Everett I said that.
This curly-haired (expletive) doesn't want to be accused of trying
to stir things up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
