<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX UNRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-WHITE SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Jimy Williams notwithstanding, the Red Sox have no
business entering any spelling bees just yet.
</P>
<P>
   Not as long as they're still stumped on this one: W-I-N.
</P>
<P>
   And while it may take the designers in Milan some time to catch
up, here's a hot fashion tip obvious to anyone sitting in Comiskey
Park over the weekend:
</P>
<P>
   White Sox are in.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox? At the moment, clearly passe, after being swept for the
second successive weekend and the third time this season, which is
one more series sweep than they endured all of last year. They've
fallen below .500 (38-39) for the first time since April 11, when
they were 3-4.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, it was the White Sox, baseball's highest-flying team,
8-2, completing a three-game domination. Chicago is now 23 games
over .500 (52-29) after Magglio Ordonez drove in five runs with two
home runs and Frank Thomas hit another and was on base four times,
10 times in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Big Hurt? That may be Thomas's nickname, but it's Boston's state
of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't make any mistakes,'' said losing pitcher Pete
Schourek (2-7), who gave up a three-run homer to Ordonez in the
first and back-to-back jobs to Thomas and Ordonez in the third.
``They certainly don't make any mistakes swinging the bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit a lot of balls hard this series. We didn't have 'em
fooled very often.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, losers of eight of their last nine games, are
drooping as much as Brian Daubach's red socks. Daubach's hose were
back to half-mast after he'd pulled them up for good luck last
Thursday, when he hit two home runs and drove in six runs in a 12-4
win over the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Sox had five singles and Jose Offerman's
too-late-to-matter home run off 11-game winner James Baldwin, who
last season gave up 11 hits and 10 runs in 2 1/3 innings against
the Red Sox but this season beat them twice, allowing two earned
runs in 16 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Neither ancient history nor the recent past _ Baldwin was lit up
for 12 runs in his previous two starts, both losses _ worked in
Boston's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he pitched better than he has in the past,'' Chicago
manager Jerry Manuel said. ``He handled Nomar Garciaparra really
well all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, whose sacrifice fly in the third drove in the Red
Sox' first run, flied out four times.
</P>
<P>
   At least with Izzy Alcantara out of the lineup Sunday, replaced
in right field by Jeff Frye, the Sox cut their errors from three to
one, but it wasn't a dizzy-free game. No one bothered to cover
second base when Chris Singleton stole in the sixth inning. Catcher
Scott Hatteberg's throw, which was on the bag, wound up in center
field, enabling Singleton to skip to third before he scored on
Herbert Perry's single off reliever John Wasdin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It surprised me, surprised me,'' said Hatteberg, still
startled enough to repeat himself after the game. ``Most of the
time I throw to an empty bag, but usually somebody ends up being
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek had hoped to be there in the Sox' hour of need Sunday.
He wanted to deliver something on the order of his previous start,
when he shut out the Orioles on four hits for seven innings, but
while warming up he had a notion that wasn't going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bad time to have nothing,'' he said. ``I didn't throw enough
quality pitches and they took advantage. Every mistake I made, they
hit, and hit well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't give our hitters a chance. I give up three in the
bottom of the first, and the momentum's gone. We scratch back and
get a run, and I give up two more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who scored a total of eight runs in three games here,
offered token resistance to Baldwin, who set down 11 in a row after
Ed Sprague's two-out walk in the fourth. Offerman broke that string
with his fourth home run to open the eighth, but lefthanded
reliever Kelly Wunsch struck out Carl Everett and retired Morgan
Burkhart on a comebacker to the mound with two on to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who with Garciaparra has carried the Sox' offense all
season, now has gone six straight games without knocking in a run,
his longest drought of the season. Until last week, he hadn't gone
more than three games without a ribbie.
</P>
<P>
   Help may be on the way. Troy O'Leary is due to rejoin the club
Monday night in Minnesota after missing two weeks to deal with
personal problems, and veteran outfielder Bernard Gilkey, signed
after being released by Arizona, should be activated as soon as
general manager Dan Duquette creates a roster spot. Add a couple of
big leaguers, subtract a couple of short-timers, and perhaps the
Sox will right themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think eventually we will,'' said Jason Varitek, who struck
out as a pinch hitter to end the game. ``But we're not playing
right. You can play short, but we've got to maintain our focus and
play with a little determination.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who had called a team meeting after a Saturday loss he
described by spelling U-G-L-Y, took comfort Sunday not from his
dictionary but from the Comiskey Park scoreboard, which showed
first-place Toronto losing again to the Orioles for a three-game
sweep by Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I checked that scoreboard up there again today,''
Williams said. ``As few games as we've won, we're lucky we're still
3 1/2 games out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to keep playing, gentlemen. That's all we can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
