<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS SAIL PAST TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The fan balloting is over, but two of
Seattle's potential All-Stars made one last stump for votes Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sele won his 10th game with a strong seven-inning
performance and Edgar Martinez equaled Ken Griffey Jr.'s club
record for runs batted in before the All-Star break with a two-run
homer in the Mariners' 11-4 victory over the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Now it only needs to be seen if the Seattle electorate has any
influence in New York, where Yankees manager Joe Torre, skipper of
the American League team for the game in Atlanta on July 11, is due
to announce the AL voting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After giving up just two cheap runs in the victory, Sele is 8-1
with a 3.92 ERA in his past 10 starts. Martinez had a two-run homer
to cap a seven-run rally in the seventh and leads the majors in
RBIs with 84, the same number rung up by Griffey before the break
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Sele won't come straight out and say he wants to go to the
All-Star Game. It goes against his self-effacing style. He was
elected once before, in 1998, but has never pitched in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a great honor to be selected,'' Sele said.
``Edgar's a lock. The reason they have All-Star Games is so they
can showcase people like Alex (Rodriguez, the likely starter at
shortstop for the AL) and Edgar.''
</P>
<P>
   And is Sele a lock? He's one of five 10-game winners
league-wide, he and Oakland's Tim Hudson having reached that level
Sunday night. And when Torre polled Piniella, Sele got a strong
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have me vote on five starters and five relievers for the
game,'' Piniella said. ``Sele was absolutely on my list. No doubt
in my mind that he deserves to be there. He and Edgar both.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele already has acres of sand, sun and surf awaiting him during
the break. He and his wife, Jennifer, have reservations on the
beach at San Diego, the Mariners' first stop after the break.
Martinez doesn't have plans _ yet. He doesn't know that he will be
selected as a backup, but he's leaving the time open, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's inclusion wouldn't be at all in doubt if this game
had the designated hitter. Being in Atlanta, it doesn't, so
Martinez is left to wait and wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to go,'' Martinez said. ``I know that Aaron
deserves to go. We are where we are because of the way he's
pitched. He's been an All-Star for us.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Martinez himself? He doesn't mask his desire to head to
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to go,'' he said. ``I'd like to take my wife (Holli)
and our boy, Alex, along. I'm leaving the time flexible, but three
days off would be welcome, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He shouldn't plan on getting them. Martinez's homer in the
seventh inning was his 23rd, and his league-leading RBI total (84)
and .354 batting average likely have already resonated all the way
to Torre's desk.
</P>
<P>
   And while Sunday night's bit of last-second lobbying by Sele and
Martinez isn't the baseball equivalent of stuffing the ballot box,
the results might come across as stuffing Texas in a coffin.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time defending champion Rangers aren't dead, but if they
climb out of the 10-game deficit now facing them to win the West,
you could call them Lazarus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a big game,'' center fielder Mike Cameron said. ``We
win the series, and we beat a team in the West.''
</P>
<P>
   Make that the team in the West. Used to be, anyway. The Rangers
are a skeletal representation of the team that had the heart of
Texas going for it the past few seasons. The Rangers had a chance
to win, but one key mistake _ a blown double play thanks to a
throwing error by rookie third baseman Mike Lamb _ gave Seattle an
opening.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners responded by doing what good teams are supposed to
do _ take advantage. After starter Matt Perisho loaded the bases
with no one out in the seventh, pinch-hitter Stan Javier beat out a
potential double-play ball, tying the game, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb's error scored one run, then Cameron came up huge with a
two-out, two-run single. Rodriguez followed with an RBI hit,
Martinez unloaded his bomb, and the crowd would have dissipated
into the Texas night had it not been for the lure of post-game
fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had the only in-game fireworks, however, and those
are the ones that count.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has won nine series in a row and has moved out to a
1{-game lead over Oakland in the West. At 15 games over .500
(47-32) just two days short of the halfway point of the season, the
Mariners are positioning themselves for the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won the series after losing the first game, and to me,
that's big,'' Cameron said. ``When we lost the first game, we just
came back harder and played better.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Rangers couldn't keep up.
</P>
<P>
   The balance of power in the West is changing.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
