<SLUG> BC-GLF-GREATER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEGAY GETS DROP ON CALCAVECCHIA 
</HEADLINE>
 HARTFORD OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROMWELL, Conn. _ His ball sat 22 feet from the hole on the 18th
green at TPC River Highlands Sunday and Notah Begay looked over a
putt that made his knees knock and his hands shake.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not really.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess when you've been through what I've been in my life . .
. I had nothing to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   But the putt? It was a slick, big right-to-left break with a
championship on the line, not to mention a bucket-full of money.
What was he thinking?
</P>
<P>
   ``Making it,'' he said. ``I mean, I couldn't finish worse than
second. I was already in a playoff. I literally had nothing to
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing to lose? He won everything when his birdie putt on the
72d hole of the Greater Hartford Open curled in perfectly over the
right lip to put an exclamation point on his improbable
come-from-behind victory.
</P>
<P>
   Closing with a 6-under-par 64 for a tournament-record 20-under
260 total worth $504,000, Begay became the first back-to-back
winner on the PGA Tour since his former Stanford teammate, Tiger
Woods, won three weeks in a row to open the 1999 season. Begay, 27,
who prevailed in the St. Jude Classic last week, now has won four
times on Tour in the last 10 months, which must put him right up
there with his good friend Woods. Right?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably one of the top one or two most recognizable
people in the world,'' said Begay, laughing. ``I'm just hoping to
be the most recognizable guy in Albuquerque.''
</P>
<P>
   He certainly has no rival when it comes to being the most
heartwarming story on Tour this year. His one-week jail stint in
March after pleading guilty to drunken driving is a topic every
time he tees it up. ``In a nutshell,'' he said, when asked to
summarize his 2000 Tour season, ``we've got the highest of highs
(from) the lowest of lows.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps drawing upon last week's momentum _ though shooting
rounds of 64-65-67 the first three days couldn't have hurt _ Begay
said he felt in complete control as he went head-to-head with Mark
Calcavecchia. Never mind that Calcavecchia owned a three-shot lead
thanks to rounds of 65-64-64.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get to 20 under,'' said Begay, the only Native
American on Tour. ``I knew if I could get to 20, I'd have a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   He got there on the strength of a putting method that could
become the rage if his tear continues. In order to always have a
putt that hooks, he putts lefthanded (on right-to-left breaks) and
righthanded (on left-to-righters). Laugh, if you will, but keep in
mind Begay drained birdies from 15 feet at the second hole, 18 feet
at the fourth, 15 at the fifth, and 17 at the seventh. Oh, and he
nailed a 15-footer to save par at the sixth, dropping that on top
of Calcavecchia's 25-foot par-save.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, he didn't have to make six (long putts) on me, but
he did,'' said a shellshocked Calcavecchia, a nine-time Tour winner
who hasn't tasted victory since 1998. His fifth top-5 finish here
didn't sit well, because after making 19 birdies in three days, he
made just one in the final round and finished with a lackluster
effort, save for a dramatic eagle at the par-4 15th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could say he beat me,'' said Calcavecchia, who
paused, not convinced it was true. ``You know, I should have done
better today. I really should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia made his only birdie of the day at the par-4 third
to get to 18 under, but he was caught at the seventh when Begay
made his fourth birdie. When he put his tee shot into a greenside
bunker at the par-3 11th and couldn't get it up-and-down,
Calcavecchia dropped a shot behind, the first time he had been out
of the lead since the end of Round 2.
</P>
<P>
   Begay pushed two shots in front with a birdie putt _ 20 feet, of
course _ at the 12th, after Calcavecchia ran off three straight
pars. Calcavecchia conceded that at that point his thoughts were
not exactly on winning, but on holding off Kirk Triplett (67_264,
solo third) for second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had pretty much written it off,'' said Calcavecchia, who
stood on the par-4 15th tee two strokes down and watched Begay
drill a 3-wood from 296 yards dead on line with the pin. ``I don't
know how close it came to the hole, but I thought, `Well, there's
another birdie.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the ball never slowed, running past the pin into a
swale behind the green.
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia, still thinking more of second place than first,
toasted a 3-wood that also tracked the pin. Begay, who discovered
that his ball had rolled long, appeared stunned when his opponent's
had come to rest 6 feet from the pin.
</P>
<P>
   Begay putted from behind the green and ran his eagle bid 3 feet
long, then elected to putt out. ``Probably a mistake,'' he said,
for he lipped out the birdie bid and settled for par. When
Calcavecchia rolled in the eagle putt, he was back in a share of
first at 19 under.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened so fast,'' said Calcavecchia, ``but the putt got
easier (when Begay missed what looked like a sure birdie putt.)''
</P>
<P>
   After matching pars at the par-3 16th and par-4 17th and drives
into a fairway bunker on the 18th, it came down to putts of the
same length at a tournament that had been a birdie festival all
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw where he was aiming and I thought he was too far to the
right,'' said Calcavecchia, who saw his 25-footer roll left just as
it got to the hole. ``I didn't think he was going to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   No offense, but Begay thought otherwise.
</P>
</TEXT>
