<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS BOLSTER BLUE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins, whose most pressing need is defensive help,
added depth to their blue line Sunday when they signed unrestricted
free agent Peter Popovic to a one-year-plus-an-option-year
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Popovic, a 32-year-old native of Koping, Sweden, brings size
(he's 6 feet 6 inches, 239 pounds) and experience. He broke into
the league in 1993 with Montreal and played for the Canadiens for
five seasons before being traded to the Rangers. He played 68 games
for New York in 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
   This past season, after going to the Pittsburgh Penguins at the
end of training camp in a deal for Kevin Hatcher, Popovic played 54
games and had one goal and five assists. He missed 21 games because
of a finger injury and seven games with a groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   Popovic is unlikely to provide much offense. He has nine goals
in his career (425 games), but the Bruins aren't concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll provide some stability in our own zone,'' said assistant
general manager Mike O'Connell. ``He likes Boston and he knows what
we've got and he's looking forward to coming.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said coach Pat Burns was in on the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through the (free agent) list and Pat knew him and
spoke highly of him,'' said O'Connell.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he'll be a third or fourth defenseman or more of a role
player remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what happens,'' said O'Connell. ``We don't know the
status of (unrestricted free agent Don) Sweeney. We're looking for
the older guys (27-year-old draft picks Jarmo Kultanen from Finland
and Pavel Kolarik of the Czech Republic) to hopefully give us some
minutes along with Nick Boynton and Jonathan Girard, and Brandon
Smith as well. Then we'd add those to Kyle McLaren, Darren Van
Impe, and Hal Gill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 0124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1548 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CYC-LONGSJOCLASSIC-BO     07-03 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-LONGSJO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOGELS HOLDS ON TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
 CLASSIC-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FITCHBURG, Mass. _ Australian Henk Vogels seems to be having an
awful lot of fun invading the American racing scene. Maybe too much
fun as far as the US bike racers are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the 26-year-old from Perth won the First Union
Classic US Pro Championship in Philadelphia, and Sunday he took the
Fitchburg Longsjo Classic.
</P>
<P>
   The women's side had an international flavor, too, as defending
champion Lynne Bessette of Quebec repeated her win.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day stage started 41 years ago as a one-day race, a
tribute to late Olympian Art Longsjo.
</P>
<P>
   Vogels, who had won two of the three stages, had a lead of 3
seconds going into Sunday's race. So it seemed all he needed to do
to hang on to his lead was stay with the pack, which was sure to
remain together as the 114 racers whizzed around downtown 55 times,
covering each .9-mile lap in just over two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But there was one worry _ the winner of the race would be given
a 10-second bonus. If Eddy Gragus, who was the rider 3 seconds
back, crossed the line first, he would leapfrog to the overall win.
</P>
<P>
   Vogels and his teammates no doubt were concerned when some of
the riders broke away from the pack. Four riders took off and built
a gap of almost half a minute from the field.
</P>
<P>
   But there were still 25 laps to go, and the pack eventually
swallowed up the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I didn't have to do a thing today, because my team
chased every single break,'' Vogels said. ``Hats off to them. I
think Roy Knickman is in the hospital, he must have used 8,000
calories.''
</P>
<P>
   As the pack rode down the final stretch, past the bank
thermometer flashing 93 degrees, 21-year-old Baden Cooke surged
past everyone else to finish in 1 hour 52 minutes 12 seconds.
Cooke, like Vogels, is from Australia, but is living in Los Angeles
while he races.
</P>
<P>
   Gragus said he knew that if he had won the race he could have
taken over the yellow jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was a long shot today, and my best chance was to try
and do something at the finish, but usually I can't outsprint Henk
anyway,'' Gragus said.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's race, Bessette easily defended her overall win,
even though Sarah Ulmer of New Zealand won Sunday's 25-mile race in
1:03.32. Bessette entered the race with a 16-second lead after
winning Saturday's stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some breaks that took off, but my teammates kept
reeling them in,'' she said of the race which, like the men's,
ended in a sprint finish.
</P>
<P>
   Bessette, 25, started racing in 1996 after an injury sidelined
her track and field aspirations. Bessette, from Quebec, is on the
Canadian national team and will compete in the Olympic trials next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Vogels, who rode in the 1997 and 1999 Tours de France with the
French-based Credit Agricole team, last year joined the American
Mercury. He, his wife Cindy, and their 10-week-old son Jett split
their time between Boulder and Perth.
</P>
<P>
   Vogels said he thinks he has a ``90 percent chance'' of
representing Australia in the Olympics when the team is announced
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   He's certainly on the right track.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 0125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
