<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1549 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     07-03 1908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T ASSUME M'S OUT OF RODRIGUEZ SWEEPSTAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It is the middle of the season. The Mariners are
winning, and being run as if someone intends for them to contend.
The clock is ticking, and yet Alex Rodriguez has not made up his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't done anything yet. What have we done? We're at the
(beginning of) July, we're playing well, but what have we done? We
really haven't accomplished anything this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of improvements, and hopefully things
continue to improve. We have an older team. When it's all said and
done, I'll have to sit down and evaluate what the future of this
franchise is, what my future in this organization could be.''
</P>
<P>
   The other day, however, sitting in front of his locker in the
happy Mariners clubhouse in Safeco Field, the shortstop speculated
on how he might look in purple.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks?
</P>
<P>
   Playing for an expansion team down in the culturally and
meteorologically challenged desert?
</P>
<P>
   In those softball uniforms?
</P>
<P>
   He smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez _ the so-called big-city traditionalist everyone
thinks has his heart set on the Los Angeles Dodgers or New York
Mets or Atlanta Braves, or maybe one of those Chicago teams _ is,
true to his word, keeping his options open.
</P>
<P>
   Goodness knows, the Diamondbacks have bought themselves a World
Series contender.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, like many free agents before him, is curious about
the power, the glory and the money-like-water spending of Arizona's
Jerry Colangelo.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez wants to win. He wants to get paid. He wants to know
he's never going to walk into the clubhouse and hear how ownership
is dumping salary like deck chairs off the Titanic and panic
because he's going to get stuck _ the future Hall of Famer with
first-class taste surrounded by farmhands and penny-ante utility
men.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, that was how Rodriguez felt with the Mariners at times
over the past few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every guy in this clubhouse the last two years was pretty
miserable,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were overmatched, and it was draining. You're probably only
as good as your 25th man. Now we're top three in the American
League and top five in baseball, and hopefully we're in a position
to improve ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The club, with a headless-horseman ownership group, squandered
the momentum of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson's status and eventual trade numbed the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The work ethic of former general manager Woody Woodward and a
slow-to-react chain of command foiled any ability to improve the
club.
</P>
<P>
   A stressed-out move to Safeco Field had ownership capping
payroll until revenue streams were in the black.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella threw his hands up, and Ken Griffey Jr.
simmered and stewed about wanting to go home.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Mariner history Rodriguez has on which to base his
decision to stay or go. Maybe that's why, no matter how rosy 2000
seems so far, with CEO Howard Lincoln in control and general
manager Pat Gillick working like a dog, Rodriguez stands firm.
</P>
<P>
   Don't read anything into this.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez has not made up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are still in this thing.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, Rodriguez looked over to his buddy, Edgar
Martinez, one locker away. The quintessential Mariner, Martinez's
status as a one-club player means something to Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot more now than it ever did, because nobody stays
with the same team anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you something. I'm a very straight shooter. Three
years ago, I said I wanted to become a free agent. I've never
changed my posture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years ago, I said, `Come to me when I'm a free agent and
I'll talk to you guys.' Two years ago, I said the same thing. And
this October, when we met in Las Vegas after the Players Choice
Awards, Howard Lincoln said we have a contract offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said: `Listen. Keep that. This is not about me right now.
Let's go see what we do this year. Let's go see what develops,'''
Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew there was no way I was going to come back, I would
have told them in that meeting, like Junior. I would have said,
`Save yourself the time and effort and get rid of me.' I would have
said `Get something for me.'''
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't tell them to call the Mets. He didn't tell them to
trade him to the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   This pleasant, stress-free summer, Rodriguez and the Mariners
are settled into a mutually agreed-upon relationship that says the
free-agent-to-be stays for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   With a World Series appearance, Rodriguez has guaranteed he'll
be a Mariner again. Anything short of that, it's his call.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Rodriguez has watched the free-agent market take a
few interesting turns. Griffey signed in Cincinnati for less than
market value. The Cubs all but drove Sammy Sosa to New York, and
Rodriguez has gained more understanding about the damage that can
be done in free-agent bartering.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, you don't name your own price.
</P>
<P>
   What Sosa did in Chicago, by saying he thought the Cubs should
start thinking about a contract extension for $140 million _ that
is not Rodriguez's style.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't Rodriguez who's talking about being the first $200
million baseball player.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's irrelevant to me. I play the game. I love the game.
Business is not my forte.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, Rodriguez said he felt he was put in a no-win
situation when a reporter asked whether a championship or money
meant more to him.
</P>
<P>
   When Rodriguez said money, in order to take care of his family,
he was slammed across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was being honest. If I said I didn't care about money,
then people would have said I was lying. I'm not going to be
dishonest.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, no circus has followed Rodriguez, the way
Griffey was asked all of last season what his future held.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of speculation, but for the most part it's been
very quiet for me this year. It's been good, because the story has
been our ballclub. So, every city I come to there have been some
questions here and there, but for the most part, it's been OK,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   This week, results of voting for the All-Star Game will be
announced. Ahead by nearly 100,000 votes by the time stadium
balloting ended last week, Rodriguez should be named the starting
shortstop for the AL, unless Internet voters push Derek Jeter,
Nomar Garciaparra or Omar Vizquel to the top.
</P>
<P>
   This is Rodriguez's year to be voted onto the team. He's got the
numbers _ .342 batting average, 21 homers, 71 RBIs, 102 hits, .624
slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   He's also got the MVP aura of a star trying to lead his team to
a pennant.
</P>
<P>
   So Rodriguez will go to Atlanta and represent the Mariners. He
will go to Atlanta and hear what he hears when he goes to New York
or Chicago or Los Angeles: The Braves want Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Why doesn't anyone believe he could just as easily choose to
stay in Seattle?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I'm from Miami, probably,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look at me like I'm a big-city guy. But just for rebuttal
purposes, I don't think I'm a big-city guy. But if you want an
answer, if I was a big-city guy, the biggest stage every year is a
World Series. That's as big as stage as you could ever have.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates like Jay Buhner understand why no one believes the
Mariners have a shot at Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the game. Look what's happened the last few years. The
fans have been burned several times. They've been burned by the
strike, they've been burned by a lot of different things. The way
money's been thrown around. We're getting to a certain point of the
game where if you start paying someone that much money, basically
he's making half the payroll. Fans want to know, how are they going
to be able to support a supporting cast?'' Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't naive. The fans are pretty smart out there. But
if this team stays competitive, why not? Look at the intangibles.
Look at this stadium. Yeah, we paid a lot for Safeco Field, but ...
it's incredible,'' Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will help keep him to stay here. Us winning will have a
lot to do with it, and who we're bringing back. They've got a lot
of guys locked up. So, I think there's a lot of things in favor of
him coming back. The grass isn't any greener on the other side. He
doesn't have any greater opportunity to win anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez understands this, yet he is one of the few who says
you can't judge Griffey's decision to leave Seattle for Cincinnati
_ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't look at the first two months of a 10-year contract
and make a determination. He's on pace to hit 50 homers and drive
in 120, so that's not too bad. And you know he's going to hit
around .300 or .290,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think you can evaluate his decision after five or six
years and see what they've done. Me, personally, I'm not
necessarily one who wants to go back home. I don't think that will
be good for me. Griffey is at a different stage of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   But the void Griffey left behind has cleared the way for
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   What he won't say, what no one in the Mariners organization will
say, is that the dynamics of the clubhouse are very different this
season without Griffey. There is no dominating personality. There
is no superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Griffey could have been happy staying in Seattle,
Rodriguez was diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speak for Griffey and whether or not he'd be happy.
But we're winning. And Griffey would fit in with this club. We're
all just one of 25 guys. The name on the front of our jerseys means
more than the names on the back. Everybody is really focused on
being a winning ballclub,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner said he has noticed a change in Rodriguez this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always been a quiet leader, but he's becoming more of the
guy who will step to the front and say things that need to be said,
keep guys fired up every day in a very positive way,'' Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty good at knowing the game, and knowing when the
time needs to be. I think he's pretty good at knowing everybody's
personality, and when to give a guy a pat on the butt and when to
give a kick in the butt. He's definitely involved into a complete
ballplayer, mentally and physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who wants to be seen as a leader, has the
intelligence, diplomacy and political savvy to understand the
subtlety and importance of team chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lead by example. You've got to ask my teammates. I'm here.
I'm available. I love to work. But we have a bunch of captains. We
have (Mark) McLemore, who's a great leader. We have Rickey
(Henderson), who's got great presence in the clubhouse and on the
field. Jay and Edgar _ everybody here is a leader,'' Rodriguez
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't anyone who's going to run and hide in the training
room. They're going to stand and say, `I screwed up' or `I did a
great job' or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Another half of a season awaits Rodriguez and the Mariners. The
deal struck between Lincoln and Rodriguez in spring training that
no trade will take place seems as if it will stick.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners don't figure to be out of contention by the trading
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   And Rodriguez can assure everyone that the Mariners aren't out
of contention for him, either.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
