<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-EURO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDIRECTION ENJOYABLE 
</HEADLINE>
 2000-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In modern soccer, most major competitions involving
European teams reward defensive play. The USA '94 and France '98
World Cup finals are prime examples, as both Brazil and France
sacrificed spontaneity and style and were rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   The European Nations Cup _ Euro 2000 _ mostly defied the
safety-first maxim and indicated that soccer could be redirected
toward creative, wide-open play in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit for this should go to France, which defeated
Italy, 2-1, in overtime in the title game Sunday in Rotterdam. Les
Bleus have evolved nicely from a team specializing in destructive
play in 1998 to one that can defend and also attack with flair.
</P>
<P>
   The French were seconds away from losing this game, and were
resuscitated only because of tactical adjustments by coach Roger
Lemerre. But the fact that Lemerre had such variety and vivacity in
reserve illustrates the proficiency of this French team.
</P>
<P>
   France always has had artistic, skillful players, but always
seemed to be fatally flawed. Their mentality has changed, though.
French players have gained experience in England and Italy, which
has exposed them to varying styles of play and also more
competitive situations than their national league. France is also
noted for its well-organized youth development programs, among the
best in Europe, along with Portugal and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The Paris daily Liberation also notes the alchemy resulting from
a mixture of ethnicities, which enables France to match ``la
rudesse'' of the Anglo-Saxon countries and also the technique of
the Latin countries, adept at ``la feinte et du geste.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only starters born outside of Gaul were Marcel
Desailly (Ghana), Lilian Thuram (Guadeloupe), and Patrick Vieira
(Senegal). Others can certainly be considered residual products of
French colonialism, including Zinedine Zidane, but this is an
accurate reflection of modern French demographics.
</P>
<P>
   A generation ago, someone like Zidane, the son of an Algerian
who was in the French army during the fight for independence, might
have been ostracized or certainly would have had to contend with
serious identity issues. Zidane thrives, though, in the modern,
globalized Europe, as do many first-generation offspring of
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Zidane also provides the game with a star of major proportions.
Unlike the Brazilian Ronaldo, who was ill-advisedly placed on a
pedestal in a contrived way, Zidane has earned his status. Zidane,
28, now has won a World Cup and a European championship, plus two
Serie A scudetti with Juventus. Zidane legitimately can be marketed
as the face of European soccer, because he has earned it.
</P>
<P>
   Against Italy, Zidane displayed his vast assortment of dribbles
and touches. The Italians mostly neutralized Zidane but completely
neutralized every other opponent in this tournament. And, as
pyrotechnical as Zidane was, France simply would not have won
without the athleticism of David Trezeguet.
</P>
<P>
   Lemerre probably waited too long to send in Robert Pires and
Trezeguet, and was fortunate Swedish referee Anders Frisk added
four minutes of injury time. Trezeguet outjumped the Italian
defense to flick on a header to Sylvain Wiltord for the tying goal
in the final minute of regulation time. And Pires finally got
warmed up and found space in the right side of Italy's defense to
cross to Trezeguet for the winner in the 102d minute.
</P>
<P>
   Lemerre must have noticed the ineffectiveness of Christophe
Dugarry in the first half, but apparently wanted to let Dugarry and
Zidane remain paired as they had been at Bordeaux from 1992-96.
Wiltord gave France speed as they desperately tried to rally, but
what the team needed was the unpredictability of Pires, who finally
entered in the 85th minute.
</P>
<P>
   At least, Lemerre was creative in his maneuverings. His
predecessor, Aime Jacquet, built an indestructible house of Les
Bleus with ``seven players whose vocation is defensive,'' according
to Liberation. Lemerre entered like an interior decorator and
brightened up the place with bright, new wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   There were many wide-open games and dramatic conclusions in Euro
2000, an event Pele considers equal to the World Cup, minus
Argentina and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The Holland-Italy semifinal was an exception, but also a game
unique in the history of soccer. Giampiero Boniperti, who played
for Italy in the 1940s and '50s and was a Juventus director until
recently, said he never had seen a comparable game. But
Holland-Italy was a fascinating joust in which every Dutch thrust
was parried by the Italians, who played with 10 men for 87 minutes.
That game called for defensive tactics by Italy, but coach Dino
Zoff went more offensive in the final, though the absence of
Filippo Inzaghi probably cost the Italians their best chance to
protect the lead.
</P>
<P>
   But after surrendering only two goals in the first 21 days of
the tournament, Italy gave up two goals in 14 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And now France essentially can go on a victory tour. Les Bleus
will not have to participate in qualifying for the Japan/Korea 2002
World Cup or Euro 2004 in Portugal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
