r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      07-03 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    NEW &AMP; NOTABLE(a) 
 &HT;    (Moving in ``E'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   ``William Wegman:Fashion Photographers''
</P>
<P>
   (Abrams, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   Wegman's dogs, those long-suffering Weimaraners, are everywhere
these days. We would not be shocked to see them dancing to Gershwin
in the next Gap commercial. Why aren't we tired of them? There's
something fascinating about Wegman's anthropomorphic photographs,
and something so woefully game about the animals that they don't
inspire backlash even as they teeter on the brink of saturation.
Here the dogs are fashion models, posing in shoes by Yves Saint
Laurent (a bad fit), a fur coat by Isaac Mizrahi, tuxedos by
Valentino, shirts by Armani. We wonder: Do they really sit
willingly like that in wigs and sunglasses? Or does Wegman
tyrannize them somehow, forcing them to pose? Either way, they are
oddly beautiful as they solicit our interest and affection. ``My
Weimaraners are perfect fashion models,'' Wegman says. ``Their
elegant slinky forms are covered in gray, and gray, everyone knows,
goes with anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicken Run: Hatching the Movie''
</P>
<P>
   By Brian Sibley
</P>
<P>
   (Abrams, $35)
</P>
<P>
   We are sick of these chickens already, no matter how good the
movie is. We have a close association with an 8-year-old, however,
and we observed that this book distracted him from the Pokimon
scourge for an entire afternoon. The result: We have built a shrine
to Brian Sibley in our house and are lighting candles daily in his
name. Actually, we enjoyed the book ourselves, because it's about
the extraordinary and exhaustive animation that went into creating
a feature-length film starring a bunch of clay birds. (Sibley also
addresses such questions as, ``How many fluffles are on Bunty's
bottom?'' The answer: 3,077, and aren't they grand?) There are lots
of behind-the-scenes photographs and stories about the making of
the movie, as well as sketches, storyboards, a foreword by Mel
Gibson and a cameo appearance by Wallace and Gromit. And, oh yes,
there are chickens everywhere, and they translate very well to the
page.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Better Angel''
</P>
<P>
   By Roy Morris Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (Oxford, $25)
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 16, 1862, Walt Whitman saw the name of his brother,
George, in a newspaper list of men recently wounded in the Civil
War. George had been encamped at Fredericksburg, Va. Within an hour
Whitman had packed up and left New York, determined to find his
