<HEADER>
A1554 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-ATHLETICS-     07-03 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ATHLETICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A'S START EARLY, BLAST ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Tim Belcher made an early exit for the second
consecutive start. But but this time it wasn't the umpire who ran
him, it was the Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics battered Belcher for seven first-inning runs,
knocking him out after a third of an inning on their way to a 10-3
victory Sunday night over the Angels in front of 21,150 at Edison
Field.
</P>
<P>
   The stint was the shortest of Belcher's 14-year major-league
career and came five days after he was kicked out in the second
inning at Seattle by home plate umpire Lou DiMuro for protesting a
balk call.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no arguing this result.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw batting practice,'' Belcher said after the loss, which
dropped the Angels six games behind first-place Seattle _ a team
coming to town for four games beginning tonight _ and 4 behind
Oakland in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   ``To stay a third of an inning and say that's not easy to take
or painful is not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher said his past two outings were frustrating, particularly
because the one thing he figured the Angels could count on him for
is innings pitched.
</P>
<P>
   When the Angels signed Belcher just before Christmas 1998, he
was coming off three consecutive 200-inning seasons for Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``One was a mental breakdown, the other one was a physical
breakdown,'' said the 38-year-old right-hander of his past two
starts. ``I've taken a lot of pride in that if I do nothing else, I
pitch a lot of innings and save the bullpen. I certainly haven't
done that the last two starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryce Christenson, a light-hitting outfielder from Pepperdine,
showed what kind of night it would be for Belcher when he hit the
second pitch of the game more over the left-center field wall. It
was Christenson's second homer this season in 65 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Velarde then slapped a single to right, Jason Giambi
walked on four pitches and Ben Grieve followed with a single to
bring home Velarde. A single by Olmedo Saenz scored Giambi and a
walk to Matt Stairs on a 3-2 pitch loaded the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Tejada hit an RBI groundout, but after Eric Chavez was
walked intentionally to load the bases, Ramon Hernandez singled to
score Saenz, making it 5-0, and chasing Belcher.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia was given a rousing ovation as he
popped out of the dugout to remove Belcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously Timmy didn't have it,'' Scioscia said. ``He didn't
have a lot of arm speed, he couldn't locate the ball and didn't
have a lot of snap on his breaking ball.''
</P>
<P>
   All the water coolers, light bulbs and anything else in his way
in the Angels clubhouse were safe, something that might not have
been the case earlier in Belcher's career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the energy for that anymore,'' Belcher said. ``I
put a lot of energy in to planning the four days I'm preparing to
pitch. If things go well, I'm exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels exhausted any chance of winning when Mike Fyhrie, who
replaced Belcher, allowed RBI singles to Christenson and Velarde to
make it 7-0 before the Angels came to bat.
</P>
<P>
   And just like that, the Athletics _ who are second in the league
in runs scored _ were back on track after being shut out by Brian
Cooper and no-hit for six innings by Jarrod Washburn the past two
nights.
</P>
<P>
   The big inning proved to be plenty for Tim Hudson, the
24-year-old right-hander who improved to 10-2.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson, who has not lost since April 20, allowed six hits, two
walks, two runs and struck out six in seven innings to win for the
21st time in 25 career decisions.
</P>
<P>
   When Hudson got in trouble in the first and third, he went to
his splitter, which acts like a straight change, to get out of
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   With runners at the corners in the third, Hudson struck out Mo
Vaughn, allowed a single off a fastball to Tim Salmon, and struck
out Garret Anderson and Troy Glaus to keep the Angels at bay. All
three strikeouts were on the split-fingered pitch, about 10 miles
behind his low-90 mph fastball. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
