<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-GIANTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE FORKBALL SPELLS DOOM FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A tie game in the bottom of the ninth, Dodgers
right-hander Mike Fetters on the mound and two left-handers and a
switch-hitter due up for San Francisco. It was a formula for extra
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Then Fetters threw a forkball a hair to high, and Marvin Benard
did something no other left-hander even came close to doing. Benard
dashed a three-run Dodgers comeback with a leadoff homer in the
ninth to give the Giants a 6-5 win Sunday at Pac Bell Park.
</P>
<P>
   Benard's unlikely homer, his sixth of the season, was the third
hit by a lefty against Fetters this season. He had retired 28 of
the 30 left-handers he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to do it again, I'd throw him the same pitch,''
Fetters said. ``I threw him a pretty decent forkball, it was down.
I guess he was geared for it and sat on it and got the pitch. I
felt like I was throwing the ball pretty good, threw some pretty
good pitches. That happens. I'm not perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Giants' second straight win against the Dodgers after
losing the first four games this season. It was the Dodgers' eighth
loss in 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one guy you don't expect to give up a hit to a left-hander
is (Fetters), much less a home run,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said. ``I felt we were in pretty good shape there if we could hold
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Benard's homer made for an ugly finish for Fetters, but everyone
else was placing blame on wasted opportunity after wasted
opportunity long before the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers on the day left 13 runners on base, went 2 for 13
with runners in scoring position and left 10 runners on base in the
five innings starter Shawn Estes pitched.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's as dramatic of a win as we've had in a long time,''
Giants manager Dusty Baker said. ``They threatened all day. Shawn
was in trouble every inning. I keep track of how many times a
starter gets in trouble. I can't remember marking down a pitcher in
trouble every inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Kent hit a pair of solo homers, Nos.22 and 23, for the
Giants as they built leads of 4-1 and 5-3. And though the Dodgers
rallied to tie it 5-5 in the eighth, the frittered-away chances in
the early innings were the underlying factor in the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Estes walked the bases loaded with one out in the third, but
Todd Hundley struck out and Kevin Elster flied out to right. With
two on and one out in the fourth, the only run the Dodgers mustered
came on Mark Grudzielanek's groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Dodgers rallied for two runs in the seventh and
two more in the eighth, it was more what the Giants failed in doing
than what the Dodgers did.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Adrian Beltre scored from second on Felix
Rodriguez's wild pitch and an even wilder throw to third by catcher
Bobby Estalella. Pinch hitter Dave Hansen followed with a single to
score Todd Hundley and make it 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Kent's second homer off reliever Antonio Osuna gave the Giants a
5-3 lead. The Dodgers tied it in the eighth when Gary Sheffield (3
for 4) singled to right to score F.P. Santangelo and a Grudzielanek
scored on Nen's wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of days we missed a couple key hits,'' Beltre
said. ``There's only a couple of guys who are swinging the bat
good, Sheffield and Grudzielanek. We need to step back and be
successful with runners in scoring position.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 0150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
