<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Shiver Creeps Over Los Angeles &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hal Bernson, a Los Angeles city councilman, did not mince words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that this city may regret the day that it ever voted
to bring this convention here,'' he declared, summing up the city's
growing anxiety about the possibility of demonstrations at the
Democratic National Convention there next month.
</P>
<P>
   Bernson was responding to a warning by the Los Angeles police of
the potential for ``a level of activity'' at least as intense as
the violent protest that disrupted a meeting of the World Trade
Organization in Seattle last December. Responding to those
concerns, the council approved a plan to cordon off protesters in a
fenced-in parking lot, and the Secret Service revised plans for
lodging Vice President Al Gore in a nearby hotel. The American
Civil Liberties Union has filed suit against the restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The jittery mood was a counterpoint to the placidity of the
campaign elsewhere. As has become almost pro forma in the campaign,
another multibillion-dollar spending plan was put forth by a
presumptive nominee: Gore unveiled an energy plan that he said
would authorize $148 billion over 10 years to improve mass
transportation and decrease dependence on oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never been afraid to take on big oil,'' Gore said, an
obvious dig at his rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a former
oilman. Bush, however, said Gore was fooling no one, as a member of
an administration that has seen a 50-cent rise in the cost of
gasoline in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   A new dynamic in the debate was fostered by the rise of Ralph
Nader, who after securing the Green Party's presidential nomination
did not wait long to ridicule Gore as ``a gee-whiz techno twit''
who had abandoned the disenfranchised in favor of large
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   If Nader's words threatened to liven the race up a bit, so did
the ruling on Tuesday by the U.S. Supreme Court, striking down a
Nebraska law that banned a procedure known as a partial-birth
abortion. Gore used the decision to remind voters of Bush's
opposition to abortion rights. ``His views about choice are really
quite extreme,'' the vice president said.
</P>
<P>
   _ PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye, America. Hola, Cuba! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whatever emotional problems Elian Gonzalez may develop later in
life, he can never say he was unwanted as a child. For seven
bizarre months, almost everyone seemed to want him _ on both sides
of that odd political fault line off the tip of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the courts had the last word. The Supreme Court
chose not to hear the case, unable to find any grounds for an
appeal. On news of the court's refusal to get involved, Elian and
his entourage (how many 6-year-olds have entourages?) quickly
headed back to a cheering welcome in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   That ended the drama, perhaps, but the ripples still roll onto
both shores. In Cuba, Fidel Castro got a definite jolt of
revolutionary caffeine from the epic Battle for Elian, and now he
wants to keep that energy humming in his unceasing campaign to end,
or at least ease, the U.S. trade embargo.
</P>
<P>
   And, after 38 long years, such a prospect suddenly seemed a
shade more likely. The Cuban-Americans who take a hard line on
Havana _ a group whose political heft vastly outweighs its numbers
_ suddenly found itself on the defensive and reshuffled its
leadership to present a new, younger face to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just Elian, of course. After the 1997 death of Jorge
Mas Canosa, an anti-Castro dynamo who often seemed to dictate U.S.
policy on Cuba, the exile lobby lost steam _ witness the accord in
Congress on lifting the ban on sales of food and medicine to Cuba.
Many in Little Havana got a temporary boost from having Elian
around.
</P>
<P>
   _ HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Looking Into the Books Of Political Fund-Raisers  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Congress approved a bipartisan bill that forces a growing group
of secretive tax-exempt groups that raise and spend money on
political activities to disclose their donors and expenditures.
When enacted, the bill will mark the first major change in the
nation's campaign finance law since 1979. Supporters like Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., said the measure was a small but important step
toward broader election-law overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   _ ERIC SCHMITT
</P>
<P>
   Softening Cuban Embargo  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of negotiations, House Republican leaders agreed to
language that would weaken the economic embargo against Cuba for
the first time in four decades. The bill, pushed by Rep. George W.
Nethercutt Jr., R-Wash., would permit the direct sale of food to
Cuba, similar to a policy allowing the sale of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   But the legislation, designed to benefit agribusiness and to
shore up Nethercutt's re-election chances, is so loaded down with
restrictions that it is more a symbolic step toward normalizing
Cuban-U.S. relations than it is a boon to farmers.
</P>
<P>
   _ LIZETTE ALVAREZ
</P>
<P>
   Drug Benefits for the Elderly  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defying a veto threat from President Clinton, the House approved
a Republican plan to provide prescription drug benefits to the
elderly by offering subsidies to insurers to help defray the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they were responding to the pleas of Medicare
beneficiaries but without creating a a ``big government'' program.
Democrats denounced the plan as a sham, saying insurers would not
offer drug coverage at an affordable price.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will probably address the issue as elections
approach. No one knows whether a new law will emerge this year, but
experts say Congress will surely add drug benefits to Medicare
within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   _ ROBERT PEAR
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: ROBERT PEAR &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Voting Surprises in Zimbabwe
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe awoke to a new political dynamic after voters gave a
nascent opposition party just over a third of the seats in
Parliament. The two days of balloting were largely free of the
intimidation that has marked the political climate for months. The
ruling party, led by longtime President Robert Mugabe, still won
the most seats. His party once held all but 3 of the 150 seats.
With 57 going to the nine-month-old Movement for Democratic Change,
it was a stunning setback for Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
   _ HENRI CAUVIN
</P>
<P>
   Hypothetical Surpluses  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The federal government, which not long ago faced budget deficits
as far as the eye could see, is now anticipating mind-boggling
surpluses. President Clinton revised his 10-year surplus projection
upward by $1.3 trillion, to $4.2 trillion. There is no assurance,
however, that the surpluses will materialize; much is earmarked for
debt reduction.
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD W. STEVENSON
</P>
<P>
   Scraping By in Japan  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday's parliamentary elections delivered a stinging
setback to Japan's governing Liberal Democratic Party. A
surprisingly weak showing resulted in the party barely retaining
control over the powerful lower house. Many already expect calls to
replace the prime minister, Yoshiro Mori.
</P>
<P>
   Live Long and Prosper  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Good times lifted 1.1 million more taxpayers into $100,000 plus
incomes in 1998, the IRS reported. A record 8.2 million returns, 1
in 15, were above that threshold. On the other end, one-third of
tax returns, 40.1 million, showed less than $15,000 of income, but
many of these taxpayers were children who sold stocks at a profit
in their college funds. Capital gains accounted for 9 percent of
all incomes, but 44 percent of the average $6,290 income in this
lowest income class.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID CAY JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   Spying as a Business Tool  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of Microsoft Corp.'s most bitter rivals, the database
software maker Oracle Corp., said it had authorized spying on three
Microsoft-financed lobbying groups. Its effort was revealed last
month after private investigators were caught offering cash to
janitors for the trash of the Association for Competitive
Technology, a group that has been lobbying for Microsoft in its
federal antitrust suit.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOHN MARKOFF
</P>
<P>
   Over the Counter  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As every patient knows, the phrase ``over the counter'' means
medicine for headaches, colds and the like. But with two drug
makers seeking to make their cholesterol-fighting pills available
without a prescription, the Food and Drug Administration began
reexamining its over-the-counter drug policy. At issue is whether
patients can manage chronic conditions, like osteoporosis and high
blood pressure, without a doctor's supervision.
</P>
<P>
   _ SHERYL GAY STOLBERG
</P>
<P>
   Borrowers Misled  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nation's sixth-largest credit-card company, Providian
Financial Corp., agreed to reimburse the millions of customers it
had misled and improperly billed. Providian will pay at least $300
million to about 3 million consumers, according to the federal and
California officials who signed the agreement with the corporation.
Over the last five years, Providian convinced people, many of them
with poor credit histories, to sign up for cards with higher fees
and interest rates than were apparent.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID LEONHARDT
</P>
<P>
   The Toll on Beaches  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Believers in the biblical injunction against building houses on
sand found an ally in the Federal Emergency Management Agency,
which published an analysis of shoreline building with an alarming
conclusion: a quarter of the houses within 500 feet of the coasts
on the ocean and Great Lakes are in danger of falling to the waves
in the next 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   The report says Fema must alter the federal Flood Insurance
Program to reflect this risk _ principally by mapping erosion
hazard areas and raising insurance rates there. But advocates for
coastal dwellers called the report a thinly disguised attempt to
drive residents from the beach.
</P>
<P>
   _ CORNELIA DEAN
</P>
<P>
   Off-Shore Caches  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They look a little like elephants and mice, but the world's
wealthiest nations have put pressure on some of the smallest to
stop offering shelter to tax dodgers and money launderers. For the
first time the developed nations published a blacklist of 35 tax
havens and 15 potential laundering centers, many of them Atlantic
and Pacific island getaways, and told them to clean up their banks
or face sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOSEPH KAHN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
