<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 09:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1598 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-MEXICO-DEMOCRACY-RE     07-03 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MEXICO-DEMOCRACY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICANS GET A CHANCE TO DEFINE DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing)  (The Week in Review)  
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Carmen Salinas, a popular television talk show
host, was warming up a huge crowd for the party in power before a
speech by its presidential candidate, Francisco Labastida. She did
not emphasize his views or personality. ``Labastida is the man, the
good one, the winner,'' she said. It was all the crowd needed to
hear.
</P>
<P>
   In most democracies, parties nominate candidates they hope will
win by persuading citizens to vote for them. But this is Mexico.
And the party was the Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as
the PRI, which has governed Mexico since its founding in 1929. In
that party, things work differently.
</P>
<P>
   During the decades when the PRI held a virtual political
monopoly, its insiders picked the candidate they knew would win and
then instructed citizens to vote for him. Today, the monopoly is
cracking. But even so, PRI voters still expect to be told who is
the likely winner. Their party is still driven by patronage, and
they want to be on the right side of whoever will dole it out. And
so the all-important thing is to know who is ``el bueno,'' the good
one, the winner.
</P>
<P>
   It is a facet of a political culture that sets the PRI apart
from parties born of pluralistic democracy. And that is the
all-important issue at stake Sunday as Mexicans vote.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the PRI is going into a presidential
election in which there is a real possibility that it could lose.
It promises to be the most fair and open election the country has
ever had. Polls show Labastida running even with a moderate
conservative, Vicente Fox, of the National Action Party or PAN (a
leftist, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, is also running.)
</P>
<P>
   All of the candidates call themselves democrats, but Mexicans
are nevertheless making a fundamental choice about the nature of
their democracy. They are choosing between two sharply different
interpretations of it _ a PRI version that says only one party is
needed, and the challengers' version, which says competition
between parties is the very essence of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   There are, in fact, not only candidates but also profound
questions in front of these voters: What makes a country a
democracy? Is it enough to have an election, or does it require
real competition between parties? Suppose the party always in power
is popular because it keeps the society on an even keel and doles
out lots of favors. Isn't that democracy? If so, what about policy?
Can it come only from the leaders, or must it bubble up from the
voters? Months ago, the PRI government promised, and seems to have
delivered, reforms that produced a real election contest. Still,
what the PRI is offering is a continuation of top-down control _
and of public acceptance that it will do whatever it can get away
with to stay in power.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, by contrast, has staged a grass-roots campaign
for citizens' rights and for a balance of powers between the
president and Mexico's legislature. In short, it is democratic in
the way that most U.S. voters understand the term. The PRI is not.
Still, many Mexicans think of the PRI as a party that truly
represents them.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans recognize that the central dispute in the presidential
race is over ``la alternancia'' _ the idea that parties must
alternate in power if democracy is to be achieved. PRI leaders
argue that they can reform their party from within and make it
democratic. ``As long as we have the option of alternating power,
we have democracy,'' said Sandra Fuentes Berain, a top official in
the Labastida campaign. ``Alternating power is not a requirement.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fox and Cardenas represent those who believe that their
country will not become a democracy until the PRI is removed.
Denise Dresser, a political analyst, puts it this way: ``Mexicans
have truly never had the chance to throw the bums out. Tasting that
experience would be extraordinarily empowering. It would inject a
whole new fresh air into the process.''
</P>
<P>
   PRI leaders make no bones about the authoritarian nature and
genius of their party. ``In this election, you are going to see the
machinery of the PRI, like few parties in the world have,'' said
Emilio Gamboa, one of Labastida's top campaign managers. ``I'll bet
not even the party in China has a machine like the one we have
built up over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI, in fact, was created by Mexican strongmen determined to
impose order on the chaos of the 1910 Mexican Revolution. To this
day, Gamboa said, its early work to spread national unity, services
like clinics and schools, and political largesse throughout the
land have cemented its followers' loyalty. ``Our party kept the
social peace,'' Gamboa said.
</P>
<P>
   Many PRI supporters who turned out to cheer Labastida knew
little about him, other than that he was their man. But his rallies
turned into dense crushes as followers pressed to shake his hand
or, with luck, have a picture taken with him that they could
display in transactions with the government.
</P>
<P>
   Wary of change, PRI voters have been forgiving of its corruption
scandals and long-term economic policies that have failed to lift
the poor. ``I'd rather have an old devil I know than a new devil I
don't,'' said Cristina Luna Flores,42, a rural homemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's party, the PAN, has deeply conservative Catholic and
business-oriented roots. But its rightist ideas have been tempered
as it evolved into a a resistance movement against the PRI,
battling to defend electoral victories against PRI fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, to be sure, evokes another anti-democratic figure in
Mexican politics, the caudillo or strongman. He is a strong-willed,
hard-driving and charismatic candidate who overwhelmed and
sometimes even ignored his party. But he forced the PAN to
modernize its platform and endowed it with a new organization for
getting votes. In doing so, he mobilized millions who are not PAN
militants but want something new. They range from young people to
the wealthy elite and even the military. ``We need change,'' said
Fernando Antonio Reyes, 49, an active duty army lieutenant in a Fox
crowd. ``The PRI has taken away all our buying power. We can't take
its corruption anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins, the closeness of the race means Mexico will face
new conflicts. even if Labastida wins, the struggle to topple the
PRI has accelerated. If Fox wins, his own style and the need to
share power with PRI holdovers in the Congress may sorely test the
assumption that change at the top is the soul of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   So even as it evolves, Mexico is likely to remain a strange
hybrid _ an electorate in pursuit of democracy with an
authoritarian force at its very heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
