<HEADER>
A1599 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN05-CO     07-03 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Haiti's industry: drug conduit
 &HT;    For release July 5, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI - As they slide along the murky waters of the Miami River,
a minor stream that cleaves a major city, small coastal freighters
inbound from Haiti now receive more attention than did the
outbounds of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   What used to be going out were hundreds of bicycles, most stolen
from lawns and yards of Miami families, stacked high on the decks
bound for Haiti. While the problem still exists, and has been added
to by other forms of contraband, it's what's coming in _ and how _
that has U.S. Customs authorities in knots.
</P>
<P>
   Its natural resources diminished, its economy bankrupt, its
politics clouded and its people impoverished, Haiti has become an
easy conduit for the Colombian drug trade. Transferring drugs might
just be the country's leading industry.
</P>
<P>
   While the United States plans to devote $1.3 billion to help
Colombia fight drug cultivation and trafficking, someone needs to
pay attention to what's flowing out of Cap Haitian and
Port-de-Paix.
</P>
<P>
   This is where much of the cocaine reaching this country is
loaded onto small freighters that chug their way to South Florida
and up the Miami River, attempting to avoid the eyes of U.S.
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, some of the most innovative ways of sequestering the
drugs have been uncovered by resolute Customs' officers, but one
has to wonder: for every load found, how many get through? The
contraband has been found welded into the hulls of some of the
vessels, or hidden inside balloons within water-filled ballast
tanks.
</P>
<P>
   It's a game of hide-and-seek, wait-and-wonder. Often, days pass
before the freighters begin unloading cargo, in the hope that the
eyes of the Customs' officials might be diverted elsewhere by then.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that 6,000 pounds of cocaine have been seized
since November from ships that originated in Haiti. Inasmuch as
most of what's coming in from there is contraband, and most of
what's going out is contraband (bicycles, weapons and cash drug
receipts), it's a wonder that either the federal, state or local
governments do not simply ban the arrival of the freighters.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping them at sea for a search cannot be an option, as often
the ships have to be lifted from the water, their hulls exposed,
for agents to fully explore every nook of the vessel for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti is a problem that just doesn't want to go away. Despite
the occupation of the country by U.S. troops, and a hoped-for
achievement of political stability, it really hasn't happened,
although last week's elections seemed a step in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Political terrorism still reigns in the small villages,
unemployment is out of sight and Haiti is no further along to a
market-driven democracy today than it was after the slave revolt
from French rule 200 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Colombian drug cartels, seeking new avenues for their
product, have found it easy to access the coasts and forests of
Haiti where law enforcement people seem to be invisible. The drugs
then are loaded onto the coastal freighters bound for South
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials estimated that 14 percent of all the cocaine
that came into the United States from South America in 1999 came
through Haiti. Not only are they coming by sea, but by air as well.
In June, U.S. Customs seized two Air de Ayiti Express planes,
suspecting them of smuggling drugs (and illegal immigrants!) from
Haiti in late night landings at private airports in Miami and Fort
Lauderdale. Thus far, $2.3 million in cocaine has been seized.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., lifted his personal
blockage of $22 million in aid to Haiti, a bounty he was holding
hostage in retaliation for a Houston company being fined by Haiti
for alleged customs irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Lord knows how the $22 million will be used, but Haiti's track
record with foreign aid has not been distinguished. It may appear
hard and cruel to beat on a nation so steeped in poverty, but Haiti
needs to be convinced that it cannot continue as a conduit for
drugs bound for the United States .
</P>
<P>
   Haiti needs to be included in the war on drugs. If there is $1.3
billion available to spend fighting that (losing) war in Colombia,
then some needs to be spent (under U.S. control) to preempt the
traffic coming out of Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   At a congressional hearing last week, Rep. Benjamin Gilman,
R-N.Y., chairman of the House International Relations Committee,
accused Haiti of becoming a ``narco-state.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Customs agents, probing deep into the hulls and ballast
tanks of rusty old freighters on the Miami River, would agree.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
