u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN05-COX     07-03 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Nader's biggest threat is to an apathetic public
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the vanity of third-party candidates to believe that
because the political distance between them and the major parties
is so great, the narrower differences between Democratic and
Republican candidates is trivial.
</P>
<P>
   That was the subtext of the Alabama Gov. George Wallace's
white-backlash presidential campaigns. To yahoo cheers, the
combative states'-righter would declare that there ``isn't a dime's
worth of difference'' between the Republican and Democratic
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Something similar will no doubt be coming from the demagog Pat
Buchanan once he starts running as the nominee of the Reform Party.
(Where is Ross Perot when you really need him?)
</P>
<P>
   And Ralph Nader is keenly huckstering the cliche as the
candidate of the Green Party's muddle of romantic and zealoparty
differences that matter so much in the House and Senate not matter
in the White House?
</P>
<P>
   Republicrats? Democrats would upgrade education by punching up
the resources of public schools. The preferred GOP answer is to use
tax-money vouchers substantially to replace public schools with
private, often sectarian ones.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore would shore up Social Security in strikingly
different ways. (Neither of them, by the way, fully credible.) Bush
is willing unilaterally to abrogate the Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty; Gore seeks only to fine-tune it. Their environmental
records could not be more different.
</P>
<P>
   The list goes on and the distinctions are not just superficial
or ones of only degree rather than of kind.
</P>
<P>
   And because the distinctions matter, Nader's claim is finally
not just nonsense but pernicious nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing it as he does, Nader is unlikely to bring voters
clamoring to his candidacy. Just the opposite. Americans prefer to
keep their political squabbles more over particulars than between
clashing ideological crusades.
</P>
<P>
   Nader's pitch most likely will just reinforce the dismissive
indifference by which a lazy electorate forfeits its democratic
franchise in stay-at-home apathy. The idea that Gore and Bush are
interchangeable fits the dangerous bill of goods we've sold
ourselves to the effect that politics doesn't matter; that it has
no consequences in our daily lives.
</P>
<P>
   Out here in the real world, Nader won't talk many voters into
seeing him as offering a choice. Rather, he'll bolster the sorry
assumption that the realistic democratic choices don't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 0956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
