<HEADER>
A5745 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-GENOME-PROGRAM-REVI     07-03 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-GENOME-PROGRAM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FOUR-LETTER ALPHABET THAT SPELLS LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computers are uncaring devices that run on electrons and the
cold numbers in their programming. They are hard, boxy things and
essentially hateful. People are soft, warm, fuzzy, logic-averse
creatures who like to cuddle and are mostly rounder than they want
to be. Surely nothing connects two such far distant realms.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, something does, something that last week was pried out
from the obscurity where for 4 billion years it has been gradually
evolving its present shape.
</P>
<P>
   Just as surely as any shrink-wrapped Microsoft disk, the human
genome is a program, a set of precisely coded instructions that
evolution has written for the design, operation and unfortunately
rather limited maintenance of a person. That people should be
operated by such a specific script is as amazing as it would be to
find that robots have souls.
</P>
<P>
   The genome's programming language has only four letters,
designated A, G, C and T after the chemical units of DNA, but these
suffice to express the instructions for building the most complex
known object in the universe. The human brain is thought to possess
about 100 billion nerve cells wired together with 100 trillion
interconnections. The connections are so cunningly engineered that
some scientists suspect there is not a single miswiring in the
entire system.
</P>
<P>
   How do you go from four letters to the complexity of the brain?
That's pretty easy. You just build one layer of complexity on top
of another until you have what you need. The four letters spell out
64 three-letter words. The words, in strings of about 300,
constitute some 50,000 instructions, a k a genes, and the body's
cells, of which the brain has about 1,000 different varieties, each
use a special subset of the instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Can our self-image of fuzzy free spirits long survive when the
genome proves that life, at its deepest level, is scripted by a
logical program? The program's control is so tight that, as has
long been known, a single error in the instructions can cause
malfunctions such as sickle-cell anemia and other hereditary
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Even in matters of behavior, the program can be astonishingly
precise. A favorite laboratory animal, the microscopic roundworm
known as C. elegans, can be found in soils around the world,
peacefully eating bacteria. Some C. elegans colonies are very
social and all dine together. In others, solitary feeding is the
rule. Biologists at the University of California in San Francisco
recently discovered that both social and solitary feeding in the
worm are controlled by the same gene. In the 215th word of the
gene, the solitary feeders have the letters G-T-T, the social
feeders T-T-T. Just as in computer programs, a single letter can
make all the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Because the genome's designer has an absolute lock on the
biological software market, the human genome is written in the same
programming code as is that of roundworms. But no doubt our
behavioral instructions have somewhat more wriggle-room than the
worm's because the choices we must make to survive are rather more
complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years we should get to read those behavioral
instructions. Whatever they are _ instincts to slaughter or show
mercy, the contexts for love and hatred, the taste for obedience or
rebellion _ they are the determinants of human nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have caught the first glimpses of our instruction book,
previously known only to God,'' said Dr. Francis Collins, head of
the Human Genome Project, in announcing its decipherment at a White
House ceremony last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Genesis account, to continue Collins' thought, tells us
there were two trees in the Garden of Eden, the Tree of Knowledge
and the Tree of Life. God evicted Adam and Eve because he feared
that, having tasted the Tree of Knowledge, his problem tenants
would eat next of the Tree of Life and live forever.
</P>
<P>
   The genome, to borrow the Genesis writer's metaphor, is surely
represented by both trees, entwined around each other like two
strands of a double helix. Have we not now broken back into the
garden for a second bite?
</P>
<P>
   From the Tree of Knowledge we will learn to read the programming
instructions that shape human nature and determine the implicit
survival rules of human societies. From the Tree of Life we will
learn to fix the programming errors that limit longevity and,
should we choose, to change the program so as to extend lifespan
many decades.
</P>
<P>
   Linguists trying to reconstruct the language spoken by the
ancestral human population have found that the world's major
language groups bear strong echoes of the mother tongue's words for
``one'' and maybe ``two,'' but nothing more. Perhaps the first
people, like many primitive cultures today, had a counting system
that went, ``One, two, many.''
</P>
<P>
   But now that we have lost our innocence and can count the
different degrees of infinity, we can see that that world is
constructed of numbers, just as Pythagoras taught, and that beneath
the velleities of human nature lies the same powerful programming
language whose G-T-T/T-T-T switch determines the sociality of the
roundworm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
