<SLUG> BC-R-LEGAL-LYING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES, A HALF-TRUTH SHALL MAKE YOU FREE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing).  (The Week in Review)  
 Co.  
 By ADAM LIPTAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I think the truth is my friend in this,'' said Vice President
Al Gore as he released the transcript of a contentious sworn
interview with a Justice Department official over fund-raising in
the 1996 election. Ordinary folks trying to untangle the 123-page
document may wonder how Gore really treats his friends.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that Gore's answers were very different from
those in any questioning of a smart, well-prepared witness
disinclined to help his adversary. They were, however, very
different from human conversation.
</P>
<P>
   What is it about legal proceedings and particularly those
pretrial sworn interviews known as depositions that turn
sophisticated people into quibblers, dissemblers or amnesiacs? Why
can't they just respond to the questions posed as people respond in
everyday conversations?
</P>
<P>
   Gore is not alone in having questions raised about his candor
under oath, questions that had House Republicans putting pressure
on Attorney General Janet Reno to appoint a special counsel. The
independent counsel Robert Ray recently concluded that the
testimony of first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton on the dismissal of
several White House travel office employees in 1993 was at least
truthful enough that Ray did not think he could prove beyond a
reasonable doubt that she had lied.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was, in fact, tolerably forthcoming as far as depositions
go. At times, he was precise, even a little funny. He knew that on
the day of the interview he had been vice president for ``seven
years and two months and 28 days.'' He recounted his delight on
learning in the spring of 1996 that his schedule would include a
luncheon at a Buddhist temple in California. ``This ought to be
interesting,'' he said he remembered thinking. ``Little did I
know.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the face of an impressive series of documents that
suggested the contrary, he stoutly resisted his interlocutors'
efforts to make him concede that fund raising was going on at
either White House ``coffees'' (of which he attended either one,
according to Gore, or some 30, according to other reports) or the
luncheon at the Buddhist temple.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the answer for all the parsing is that depositions are
preparation tools meant to prevent surprises at trial. They are
very rarely considered in their entirety or even used at trial.
Lawyers sometimes use them to contradict witnesses who change their
stories on the stand; occasionally the transcripts are read to the
jury when witnesses are unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of videotaped depositions, and their use in and
out of the courtroom, a lawyer's standard advice to witnesses _ to
say as little as possible _ may no longer be wise, particularly
when those witnesses are public figures. The evasive responses of
Microsoft's Bill Gates helped undermine his corporation's case.
President Clinton, on the other hand, is thought to have helped
himself with his garrulous and expansive grand jury testimony,
whatever its truthfulness.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer prepares a witness by stating that the enterprise
embarked upon is an exercise in playing defense, and that the
questioner is the enemy. The object is not to give up any ground.
</P>
<P>
   The witness, the lawyer continues, must become a user-unfriendly
computer, producing a truthful answer but not a particularly
expansive one. The witness is not obligated to reformulate the
questions or respond to what the questioner is plainly, if
clumsily, driving at.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer also reminds witnesses that their names on a document
_ as addressees or perhaps even as authors _ are no proof that they
have ever seen it, much less that what it says is true. The lawyer
will note the value of stock answers like ``I don't know'' or ``I
don't remember.'' It may also be suggested that perjury
prosecutions are rare and that the crime is a long coast dotted
with countless safe harbors. Perjury requires a statement that is
known to be false when said, actually false rather than merely
misleading, and material to the case.
</P>
<P>
   One Supreme Court case demonstrates just how hard perjury is to
prove. A witness was asked, ``Do you have any bank accounts in
Swiss banks?'' He said no, truthfully. ``Have you ever?'' The
witness, who once had a personal account there, replied: ``The
company had an account there for about six months, in Zurich.''
Because the last answer was literally true, although certainly
misleading, the defendant's conviction was reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary conversation is a very different beast. A chat with a
friend over a beer is filled with answers to the question you meant
to or should have asked, with corrections of mistaken premises,
with volunteered information, with little anticipations and
courtesies and clarifications.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, everyday life is full of misunderstandings. It is no
easy task to communicate even where both sides are trying their
best. Now factor in the adversary system, and the chances of
learning anything the witness chooses not to convey diminish
radically.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is to suggest that life outside of litigation is an
Eden of truth-telling. Gore was questioned mercilessly about a
seemingly harmless courtesy letter to a supporter after a visit to
Taiwan. He was made to assess his own truthfulness, sentence by
sentence. ``No, I was actually glad I was not with them on the rest
of the voyage,'' he testified. And, he continued, ``the statement
that the `meetings with the government and business leaders were
fascinating' appears to be an overstatement, as does the
description of the visit to the Fo Kuang Shan facility as being
`almost overwhelming.''' So too ``the statement that it was `the
most enjoyable trip I have ever taken.''' The entire thing was a
tissue of lies or, as Gore put it, ``within the customary bounds of
this sort of communication.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0068 </DOCNO>
