<P>
   The witness, the lawyer continues, must become a user-unfriendly
computer, producing a truthful answer but not a particularly
expansive one. The witness is not obligated to reformulate the
questions or respond to what the questioner is plainly, if
clumsily, driving at.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer also reminds witnesses that their names on a document
_ as addressees or perhaps even as authors _ are no proof that they
have ever seen it, much less that what it says is true. The lawyer
will note the value of stock answers like ``I don't know'' or ``I
don't remember.'' It may also be suggested that perjury
prosecutions are rare and that the crime is a long coast dotted
with countless safe harbors. Perjury requires a statement that is
known to be false when said, actually false rather than merely
misleading, and material to the case.
</P>
<P>
   One Supreme Court case demonstrates just how hard perjury is to
prove. A witness was asked, ``Do you have any bank accounts in
Swiss banks?'' He said no, truthfully. ``Have you ever?'' The
witness, who once had a personal account there, replied: ``The
company had an account there for about six months, in Zurich.''
Because the last answer was literally true, although certainly
misleading, the defendant's conviction was reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary conversation is a very different beast. A chat with a
friend over a beer is filled with answers to the question you meant
to or should have asked, with corrections of mistaken premises,
with volunteered information, with little anticipations and
courtesies and clarifications.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, everyday life is full of misunderstandings. It is no
easy task to communicate even where both sides are trying their
best. Now factor in the adversary system, and the chances of
learning anything the witness chooses not to convey diminish
radically.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is to suggest that life outside of litigation is an
Eden of truth-telling. Gore was questioned mercilessly about a
seemingly harmless courtesy letter to a supporter after a visit to
Taiwan. He was made to assess his own truthfulness, sentence by
sentence. ``No, I was actually glad I was not with them on the rest
of the voyage,'' he testified. And, he continued, ``the statement
that the `meetings with the government and business leaders were
fascinating' appears to be an overstatement, as does the
description of the visit to the Fo Kuang Shan facility as being
`almost overwhelming.''' So too ``the statement that it was `the
most enjoyable trip I have ever taken.''' The entire thing was a
tissue of lies or, as Gore put it, ``within the customary bounds of
this sort of communication.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1609 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN04-CO     07-03 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: It isn't always easy when boys act
like boys
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I raised three daughters, no sons. My oldest
grandchild is also a girl. But my other three are boys.
</P>
<P>
   I tell my daughters not to be too hard on their sons, that it
isn't always easy being a boy.
</P>
<P>
   When they ask me why, what can I say? It's hard to explain.
</P>
<P>
   But here's as good an explanation as any, a story I heard
first-hand from a fellow.
</P>
<P>
   He was new in town, fresh out of law school and just starting
out. A fellow he'd met at the office, an older guy, invited him to
a weekend deer hunt. He said it'd be a good way for him to get
acquainted.
</P>
<P>
   The young guy, being young, believed him.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he arrived at the cabin that Friday night, everyone
else was already there, half a dozen or so, playing cards and
drinking beer.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody so much as looked up to greet him. Nobody offered him a
beer, nobody introduced himself.
</P>
<P>
   He eased over to the side of the table where his friend from the
office sat. But when he tried to speak the other guy shook his
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't you see we're playing poker,'' he growled.
</P>
<P>
   He pulled up a chair and positioned it as close as he could to
the one fellow he knew. Still, nobody said anything to him, nobody
acknowledged his presence.
</P>
<P>
   He looked first at one and then another. One in particular _ the
one they called Mangy Bill _ he tried to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Mangy Bill was a giant of a man, with fiery red hair and, by all
indications, a temper to match. The scowl on his face was
punctuated by a half-chewed cigar, cocked in the corner of his
mouth, like a stubby exclamation point for the string of expletives
he directed at the cards he'd drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Then, before the young man realized what was happening,
everyone's attention was directed at him.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the friend from the office turned to his visitor.
``Hey, don't say that!'' he all but shouted, looking first at him
and then at Mangy Bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``What?'' the young man said, confused. ``I didn't say
anything?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, for your own sake,'' he implored. ``Just keep your
mouth shut.''
</P>
<P>
   But by this time Mangy Bill was on his feet, and the rest of
them were pushing back from the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you accusing me of cheating?!'' he roared, his chest and
arms straining at the vest, his veins bulging in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``What? No! I _ .'' Before the words were halfway out of the
young man's mouth, it was already too late.
</P>
<P>
   In a flash, from out of nowhere it seemed, Mangy Bill had pulled
a Bowie knife, its eight, thick inches of sharpened steel glinting
in the dingy light of the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   One minute the knife was in his hand, the next it was quivering
where he had stabbed it, in the center of the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the count of three,'' he snarled, ``go for it!''
</P>
<P>
   That's when the other guys hit Mangy Bill, gang tackling him and
dragging him down to the floor in a flood of shouts and curses, a
torrent of arms and fists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Run! Run!,'' they were yelling at the young man. ``We can't
hold him long!''
</P>
<P>
   And run he did, across the room and out the door to his car.
Cranking it up and floor-boarding it, tires screaming, he careened
down the country road and into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Monday at the office, when he tried to talk to his friend about
what had happened to Mangy Bill, the older man just shook his head.
``Better that we never mention it,'' he whispered. ``Not now, not
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Not until 20 years later, at a cocktail party when he overheard
his name mentioned by a couple of men who were laughing, did he
learn the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so funny?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you know,'' one of them said, grinning. ``We were talking
about that time at the clubhouse when you first moved to town, when
we had some fun with you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fun?'' he said, his voice barely audible. ``You were having
fun?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' the fellow said, starting to laugh again. ``It was all
a put-up deal, just our way of introducing ourselves. Don't tell me
you never figured it out?''
</P>
<P>
   At first, he just nodded. Then, he grinned. Finally, he managed
a dry, hoarse chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was laughing again, and he laughed with them.
</P>
<P>
   They told him Mangy Bill was a buddy of theirs from out of town,
a dock-worker as a matter of fact, as nice a fellow as you'd ever
meet _ and what a great sense of humor!
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they didn't have to tell him, they said, slapping him
on the back and laughing all the louder.
</P>
<P>
   What can you say? Boys will be boys.
</P>
<P>
   Which is to say, it isn't always easy being a boy.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
