<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENTS-MENINGITIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CDC ADVISES FRESHMEN TO GET BACTERIAL MENINGITIS SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEGAN SCOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the rate of bacterial meningitis on the rise among college
freshmen, the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
recommended for the first time Friday that all incoming students
consider getting vaccinated against the potentially lethal brain
infection.
</P>
<P>
   The communicable disease strikes about 3,000 Americans annually
and kills about 300, according to the CDC. Five people in
Massachusetts have died of the disease this year. Out of these
cases, 100 to 125 occur among college students, and up to 15 die as
a result.
</P>
<P>
   But federal health officials said freshmen living in dormitories
are particularly vulnerable, facing a risk of meningitis that is
six times higher than other college students. They called on
college health clinics and others who provide medical care to
students to make the vaccine available before the new academic year
begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once college students _ and their parents _ are aware that a
vaccine is available to help protect against this deadly disease,
our hope is that they will consider immunization before heading off
to college this fall,'' said David Spilker, president of the
Meningitis Foundation of America.
</P>
<P>
   Meningitis, also known as meningococcal disease, is an
inflammation of the lining around the brain, usually caused by one
of several types of viruses or bacteria. Because the disease
produces flu-like symptoms, physicians often misdiagnose it.
Meningitis then progresses rapidly and can result in permanent
brain damage, hearing loss, learning disability, kidney failure, or
death.
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen who live in dormitories are at a higher risk of
meningitis, in part because of a lifestyle that may include sex,
alcohol consumption, active and passive smoking, shared utensils,
irregular eating habits, and sleeping patterns, all activities that
place them at a higher risk of meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a time when freshmen experiment with a lot of
activities where there's an exchange of saliva,'' said Bela Matyas,
medical director of the epidemiology program at the Massachusetts
Department of Public Health. ``The other reason is people come to
colleges from all over the country, so they're bringing different
strains with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle of Higher Education reported last year that during
the 1998-1999 academic year, 83 cases, six of them fatal, were
reported at academic institutions including Dartmouth and
Muhlenberg colleges, Eastern Illinois and Lehigh universities, and
the University of Iowa, Minnesota, and Wisconsin at Madison.
</P>
<P>
   Many students and their parents don't realize that the vaccine
is 85 percent protective against four out of the five strains of
meningitis. The only side effects may include a low-grade fever and
pain and swelling at the site of the vaccination, but serious
reactions are rare.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Bozof, who lost her son Evan to meningitis two years ago
when he was a junior at Georgia Southwestern State University, said
she only found out about the vaccine after Evan's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know anything about bacterial meningitis,'' said
Bozof, who lives in Atlanta. ``I had no idea how deadly it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Students do not have to be revaccinated, because when the
vaccine wears off in three to five years, many students are no
longer at high risk.
</P>
<P>
   Many colleges have started informing students and parents about
the vaccine, and some schools have provided it on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agree with the CDC's recommendation,'' said Boston
University spokesman Colin Riley. ``We offered the vaccine last
year in conjunction with the flu vaccine, and several hundred
students took advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine, which costs approximately $70 per student, was
advertised in the school newspaper and in dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Harvard University has already sent a letter to the
parents of incoming freshmen recommending the vaccine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
