<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPRECIATION-MATTHAU-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GREAT BUT UNSUNG MOVIE COMEDIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With his ruptured-duck walk and his eyes staring balefully from
a clown's rubber face, the late Walter Matthau was one of the great
but curiously unsung film comedians of the last 35 years. Matthau,
who died at age 79 on Saturday of a heart attack in Santa Monica,
Calif., didn't hit his stride until his mid-40s. Perhaps that had
something to do with it. Although his acting credentials were
impeccable _ postwar study at the New School with Rod Steiger, Gene
Saks, and Tony Curtis, a string of Broadway stage credits _ his
film career got off to an undistinguished start in a series of
villain roles, ranging from ``The Kentuck-ian'' with Burt Lancaster
(1955) to ``Charade'' with Audrey Hepburn and Cary Grant (1963).
</P>
<P>
   In 1964 came a foreshadowing of his persona-to-be. The film was
a comedy, ``Goodbye, Charlie.'' In it, Matthau played a film mogul
widely believed to have been modeled on Alexander Korda, who was
appalled to learn that he would have to suffer the indignity of a
prison term just for shooting, as he so memorably put it, ``wan
lee-tul writer.'' In 1965, his Broadway success as the sloppy,
divorced sportswriter Oscar Madison threw his career into high
gear. Onstage, Matthau played the role against Art Carney. In the
1968 ``Odd Couple'' film, his uptight alter ego was Jack Lemmon.
They had worked together before. Matthau won an Oscar playing the
shyster lawyer brother-in-law of Lemmon's injured TV cameraman in
Billy Wilder's icepick-sharp ``The Fortune Cookie'' (1966).
</P>
<P>
   The tinge of misanthropy in that role completed Matthau's comic
persona. Although they never billed themselves as such, he and
Lemmon became one of film's great comedy teams. In those two films,
in ``The Front Page'' (1994), in three ``Grumpy Old Men'' films
from 1995 to 1997, and in ``The Odd Couple II'' (1998), their
interplay was the stuff of film's classic comedy teams _ Laurel and
Hardy, Abbott and Costello, Hope and Crosby, Martin and Lewis _
with Lemmon playing the prissy superego vainly attempting to impose
control on the messy ambulatory id, done to such perfection by
Matthau, who extended his cantankerousness to the role of an
old-timer refusing to go quietly to pasture in a film Lemmon
directed, ``Kotch'' (1971).
</P>
<P>
   In all, they collaborated in 11 films. They appeared in ``The
Grass Harp'' (1995), directed by Matthau's son, Charlie, but did
not have scenes together. Both did the movie to give Charlie
Matthau's career a boost.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath his armor of wise-guy humor, there was a warm, smiling
side to Matthau that seldom made it to the screen. But it did
surface in his wise, kindly old father figure in ``The Grass
Harp.'' As soon as he acquired clout in the early '70s, Matthau
made a point of doing certain projects simply for enjoyment. In
``Earthquake'' (1974), he had fun contributing a cameo as a drunk
at a bar, mugging outrageously, using in the credits the name he
was born with: Walter Matuschanskayasky.
</P>
<P>
   One of his favorites among his films was ``Hopscotch'' (1980), a
spy thriller costarring Glenda Jackson. He liked it because it
allowed his character, Charlie Dark, to succeed with his wits, not
bullets and explosions, and because he insisted on _ and got away
with _ having his favorite composer, Mozart, on the soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   At 6-foot-3, Matthau was taller than he appeared on screen, and
walked with a bit of a slouch, which of course fed into his comic
persona. It wasn't conscious, he once told this writer. It was
because he arrived at his full height early and felt self-conscious
at school. Because he so often played loosely wrapped, vinegary
characters, his pinpoint timing and technical skill as a physical
farceur were generally overlooked, or insufficiently credited.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a thoroughly forgettable film, such as ``Dennis the
Menace'' (1993), his disguised grace at dodging the falling objects
crashing down around his head, as the arch-tyke systematically
demolished the world of Matthau's Mr. Wilson, remains an object
lesson for actors. In later years, Matthau enjoyed incorporating a
disheveled look into roles as Einstein in ``I.Q.'' (1994) and the
fictionalized screenwriter father of Nora and Delia Ephron in
``Hanging Up'' (2000). Although his crochetyness precluded begging
for audience approval, Matthau will be remembered as a beloved
actor. Everyone has a favorite Matthau movie. Mine is ``A New
Leaf'' (1970). He plays a dissolute playboy of impeccable taste who
marries Elaine May's mess of a millionairess, planning to murder
her for her money. Comedy is timing. Matthau made me laugh every
time he'd wait an extra beat, staring in cold, deadpan disgust at
May's newest escalation of disarray, convincing us he was wondering
if even the prospect of a fat inheritance was worth enduring her.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1693 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-HANGUP-BOS &LR;      07-03 1716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-HANGUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY: THE LAST GREAT HANG-UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Nothing messes with a person's mind quite like money.
</P>
<P>
   Too much of it, not enough, fear of losing it, the compulsion to
squander it, the dread of being hated for having it, negative
parental messages about managing it _ or not managing it _ and a
thousand other psychological pitfalls have been trapping man since
he invented a monetary system.
</P>
<P>
   That mental turbulence is usually coupled with another kind of
angst _ shame because of the cultural taboo against talking about
these problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK at a cocktail party to say how much you made on XYZ
stock, but it's not OK to say how much you lost, and it's not OK to
talk about your personal finances,'' says Richard Geist, president
of the Institute of Psychology and Investing in Waban, Mass. and a
pyschologist at Harvard Medical School. He counsels individuals on
their money troubles and works with investment firms on the
psychology of risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is emotional,'' he says. ``It's power, self-esteem,
control, authority. The family that never talks about money makes
it secretive and negative. People grow up with these emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Geist and a growing number of psychologists and financial
planners are helping people draw out those emotions while also
helping them draw up a budget. They are trying to close the gap
between the spiritual and the monetary, teaching people to see
money as not merely ``the day job'' or the accumulating pension
that will lead to fulfillment in retirement, but as a tool for
doing what's meaningful to them now.
</P>
<P>
   The field has been coming into its own since the mid-'90s,
expanding along with the economic boom and the mounting pressures
people feel to be smart about money. A survey last year by the
Certified Financial Board of Standards _ the professional
organization that sets standards for the financial planning
industry _ found that 42 percent of American consumers are worriers
who fret over their financial decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking `What is your life about? What do you need to be
fulfilled?' '' explains George Kinder, a guru of the movement and
author of the book ``The Seven Stages of Money Maturity.'' He
teaches Buddhism and is cofounder of the Nazrudin Project, a
national organization of 150 financial planners that takes its name
from a character in the teaching stories of the Sufis, the mystic
branch of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Kinder gets down to the basics quickly, asking clients three
questions: 1. If you had all the money you'd ever need, how would
you live? 2. If you had five to 10 years left to live, what would
you do with your life? 3. If you had 24 hours to live, what would
you regret not having done?
</P>
<P>
   Then he probes the reasons why people aren't following their
hearts' desires, or why they may be unconsciously sabotaging it _
buying a convertible, say, as a reward for sticking with a
well-paying but frustrating job when what they really want to do is
paint or sing or run an inn.
</P>
<P>
   His ``seven stages'' begin with exploring belief systems
instilled in childhood, working through the pain of trying to hang
on to those beliefs, and then moving onto knowledge, understanding,
``vigor'' _ achieving one's goals _ vision, and ``aloha,'' or
kindess shown to one's fellow man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like peeling back the layers of a psychological onion,''
says Gayle Colman, a Nazrudin member, who runs a financial planning
business with her husband, Richard.
</P>
<P>
   They are working with one client who grew up in what Colman
describes as a ``feast or famine atmosphere'' because the family
squandered whatever money came in. ``Consequently my client lives
an incredibly frugal life,'' Colman explains. ``He is paralyzed by
fear that he may have to live in an impoverished state.
Intellectually he hears what I'm saying but emotionally he's
feeling great fear. So we have to go back and relive those
emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   For one married couple seeing the Colmans, the issue was facing
reality. They were blowing through a trust fund as if it were water
and avoiding the obviously sinking bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   The financial problem was that they had left high-paying jobs to
start a sporting goods business but were keeping up the lifestyle
of a two-career couple.
</P>
<P>
   The psychological problem behind the behavior was that the
husband had grown up in a wealthy family and never learned to
manage money, while the wife grew up watching every penny. So he
assumed money would always be there no matter what he did, while
she felt entitled to spend freely after all those years of
skimping. The combination nearly drained a $650,000 fund, as they
bought a $400,000 home, paid for the wife's graduate education at
Harvard, and enrolled the children in private school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another six months and it would have been gone,'' says the
wife, 39. She and her husband are now on a strict budget, giving
themselves each a $50 weekly personal spending allowance. They
balance the checkbook every month _ something they never used to do
_ and are letting the trust fund accumulate for their retirement
and their children's college education. They moved out of the
$400,000 house, downsizing to one costing $100,000 in a nearby
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stopped the train before the train wreck,'' says the wife.
``We learned a lot about ourselves and what's important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   A computer company manager, 35, felt ``like a piece of raw meat
in a pool of piranhas'' when the high-tech firm he worked for sold
for $70 million and he instantly became a multimillionaire. ``I
needed financial advice but didn't know who to trust.'' He and his
wife found the Colmans through a friend and thought the
psychological approach ``felt right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that there is a link between money and psychology was
new to me,'' he explains, noting that George Kinder's book opened
the door to Eastern religions and meditation. ``I had subscribed to
all the money magazines, but nothing really talks about the
holistic approach: 99.99 percent of the noise about money today is
about the mechanics.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife are learning that she has a distrust of people
with money _ her father, a construction worker, always said rich
people never broke a sweat or earned a dime. The couple is working
through the possibilities of setting up a foundation, supporting
existing charities, or doing something else profound with the money
that has changed their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money can enable you to follow a higher purpose,'' he says.
``But it's a daunting task trying to figure out what the hell that
is.''
</P>
<P>
   When Christopher Mogil inherited a family fortune, he formed a
support group in Philadelphia. He now runs another called More Than
Money in Arlington, Mass. The organization helps people network and
explore philanthropic projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody will be sympathetic to the problems you experience if
you have money,'' says Mogil. ``You're in a society that judges you
by the work you do and you're not working. Dating can be difficult.
Is the person interested in me or my money? It does change
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Mogil has plumbed the messages he got about money when growing
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was from a family where my father's side struggled and my
mother's side was flush. My father's side always judged the other
side as selfish. My mother's side always blamed my father's side
for not having money. And both sides were trying to be middle class
when they weren't _ they were wealthy and working class.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he has learned to be ``honest and upfront with people
and not hide who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Pearne, a clinical psychologist who has been a wealth
counselor for 20 years and also deals with people of moderate
means, says: ``This is the decade we will learn to talk about
money.'' The reasons: the economy, the need for people to be smart
about retirement planning as companies and the government do less,
and the amount of wealth that will change hands in the next 10 to
15 years _ more than $10 million will be inherited by the baby boom
generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is the last taboo,'' he says. ``In the '60s and '70s we
learned to talk about sex. In the '80s and '90s we learned to talk
about death. Now it's money. That which is not talked about gains
power within us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sudden wealth, he says, can ``destroy lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your feelings toward the person who bequeathed you the money
shape how you handle it. If you are angry at your parents you may
go on binge spending, act out, or develop a cocaine addiction.
Money represents parental control.''
</P>
<P>
   He has seen people so afraid they are going to lose their money
or make a bad investment decision that they put it into a CD or
savings account for years, and they consequently do lose a fortune
in potential stock earnings or interest.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, he has seen ``the stock-market obsessed,'' who check
their holdings every hour. ``It's like a video-game addiction,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Carter, who runs MoneySense, a financial counseling
service in Newburyport, Mass., defines five types of personalities:
money-mindless, money-deserving, money-balanced, money-fearful, and
money-obsessed. The first forgets to pay bills, doesn't remember
what lunch cost, and usually has been raised to feel he or she
(often she) shouldn't have to deal with all that.
</P>
<P>
   The money-deserving person feels entitled and can be either
financially savvy or a spendthrift. Carter describes one such
client as ``a 3-year-old in the room screaming for a lollipop.''
The balanced person has perspective on dollar signs, while the
fearful person thinks about money all the time, and the obsessed
can't function because of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is connected to our worth, to what we think we deserve,
and to how much we are loved,'' says Carter. ``It's convoluted
between need and want, and consequently piques all the emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter notes how a woman had called that day to say she left two
of her children out of her will. The woman has seven children and
is leaving her estate only to five. ``Now, what does
(itals)that(unitals) say?'' Carter asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to make money sane,'' she says. ``You've got to look at
your own demons and then try to move into balance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
