<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1694 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-YANKEE-FRUGALITY-ART-     07-03 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKEE-FRUGALITY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 EVEN HIGH ROLLERS LIKE TO SAVE A BUCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's affluent enough to live in a Weston neighborhood where the
houses cost at least $1 million, but Dennis Saylor couldn't bear to
fork over $30 to hire someone to haul his old refrigerator to the
basement.
</P>
<P>
   So the 44-year-old lawyer rented a dolly for $20, spent three
hours on the job, and ultimately bruised his cheekbone and arms
when the appliance nearly toppled onto him. Still, the refrigerator
got to the basement, and Saylor has no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I earned as much as Bill Gates, there was no way I was
going to pay to have someone move that refrigerator,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Economists might label Saylor's refrigerator ordeal a ``mental
accounting error,'' a bad choice in the persistent
time-versus-money calculation. Psychologists could say he was
reflecting deep ambivalence about the signs of wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Others would call him just plain cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause, more and more Americans these days cling to
certain frugal habits, even as they enjoy a creeping sense of
affluence in this prosperous economy. While they indulge in
luxuries in many areas of their life, many skimp in others, often
irrationally pursuing metered parking spots in downtown Boston
while driving a new Lexus.
</P>
<P>
   What motivates them?
</P>
<P>
   These selective tightwads say it's partly about money and partly
about personal identity. For them, it's refusing to jump full force
into this society's materialistic mania, especially if they have
impressionable children. It's a yearning to retain some
penny-pinching ways, such as changing the oil in a car, sewing on a
button, or fighting, on principle, a $2 overcharge on a bill.
</P>
<P>
   It's also about clinging to old habits, often inherited from
their parents, that are rooted in the belief that self-sufficiency
and thriftiness are virtues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my frugality I inherited from my upbringing,'' said
Scott Schoen, 42, who insists on mowing his own large lawn in
Franklin, Mass., even as his wife pleads with him to hire someone.
``I grew up with five boys in the family, and we cut our own lawn.
My father would have thought it was horrible to pay someone to cut
your lawn.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoen acknowledges that it makes little economic sense to chain
himself to his lawn mower most Saturdays. As a dual-income couple
(he's a downtown lawyer with a six-figure salary; she's a full-time
teacher), the Schoens could easily afford whatever it costs to hire
a local teenager for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Just how many people fall into this category is hard to
determine. Not wanting to look like tightwads, they are often
quiet, even secretive, about where they draw the line. And national
studies on frugality are often unreliable, as Americans like to
report being frugal, even when they really don't act that way.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 percent of Americans report that they are frugal,
according to a study by Arizona State University marketing
professor John Lastovicka.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just wishful thinking, Lastovicks said. After all,
the nation's credit card debt is at an all-time high, and the
national savings rates often dropped into negative numbers last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, researchers who study American spending say there always
has been a sizable minority of people who retain some frugal
habits, no matter how their incomes grow, and it's a group that
sticks out when times are good.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are holding back in a general environment of
upscaling,'' said Juliet Schor, a Harvard economist and author of
``The Overspent American.'' ``Their spending habits are part of
their personal identity. It's unsettling to change everything. By
retaining certain habits, it gives them a sense of continuity about
who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Ryan, a psychology professor at the University of
Rochester, N.Y., said he knows men who insist on repairing their
cars or drinking cheap beer because it reminds them of ``their
buddies from high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Therapists say people who are frugal tend to share traits such
as an upbringing in which their parents associated money with
security and independence, rather than pleasure. (Of course, some
people react against their parents, so frugal parents can raise
free-spending children.)
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists say children as young as 4 are influenced by their
parents' tight or loose approaches to money.
</P>
<P>
   Many people regard frugality as a sign of intelligence, and they
are particularly galled when they feel cheated, no matter what the
amount.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Brown, a prosperous apartment landlord with a reputation
for thriftiness, said he recently complained to a waitress at a
pancake house about being charged an extra $1.75 for Vermont maple
syrup. He was never told about the charge in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're overcharged, it's like an invasion of your common
sense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated areas of frugality may seem chintzy or charming, but
they can also be illogical. Richard Thaler, a University of Chicago
economist, said he once conducted a survey showing that when buyers
of a $35 clock radio were told that they could save $10 by driving
10 minutes to another store, most took the trip. But when buyers of
an $800 television were told they could buy the same set for $790
at a store 10 minutes away, they declined the cost-saving trip.
</P>
<P>
   That decision reflects an irrational choice, a ``mental
accounting error,'' Thaler said. He said people should have
determined whether ``10 minutes of time was worth $10 or not,'' as
opposed to making a decision on the percentage savings on the total
price.
</P>
<P>
   Any calculation of such modest sums is unseemly to some people.
While puritanical America used to regard frugality as a good trait,
it turned into a negative one beginning in the 1950s, said Sheldon
Garon, a Princeton University historian who is writing a book about
frugality.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the '50s that this country began economic policies
encouraging consumer spending, with cheap imports, easy credit, and
loans, Garon said. The spendthrift was portrayed as more glamorous,
more fun.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he maintains, there's a minority who continue in the
Puritan tradition of associating frugality with sound moral values.
That tradition may also fuel the voluntary simplicity movement, in
which Americans cut back their incomes and spending. Several
national surveys show that 10 to 25 percent of Americans are taking
some steps to cut back both earning and spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way of showing that you have more virtue than others,''
Garon said.
</P>
<P>
   Jodi Hartley, a real estate executive and a grandmother, said
she enjoys her thriving income, but believes that frugality is a
way of showing that money can't be taken for granted. She said she
remembers when money was tight.
</P>
<P>
   Hartley still goes out of her way to avoid downtown parking
fees, and she plans to make a special trip to Bloomingdale's to
return a $66 pocketbook she said fell apart shortly after she
bought it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't get my money easily,'' she said. ``I earned it.''
</P>
<P>
   Frugality can be taken to the extreme. Many psychologists cite
those who treat bargain-hunting like an obsession or even see
superstitious signs of good luck when they get a good buy. Philip
Levendusky, a McLean Hospital psychologist, said he thinks some
people play out their hard-wired aggressive instincts in the new
jungle of shopping malls.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they get a good deal, it's as if they won the battle,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   When does frugality become excessive? People who are selectively
frugal don't usually go to self-depriving extremes, but
psychologists say it could happen, particularly if cost-cutting is
used as a way to curb excessive guilt or anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists acknowledge, however, that they know a lot more
about obsessive spenders than obsessive savers. The reasons are
pretty obvious, said Cheryl Fellows, a clinical psychologist and
author of ``Dollars and Sense: The Psychology of Money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing that frugal people do is see a private
therapist,'' she said. ``It's expensive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
