<HEADER>
A1698 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-03 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITEM PRICING GATHERS DUST FOR SOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you ever noticed the different retail philosophies of Home
Depot and CVS?
</P>
<P>
   When you go into a CVS to buy shaving cream, you find the price
marked on the can as well as on the shelf under the can. But when
you go into Home Depot to buy a package of light bulbs, the price
is only on the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   By stamping prices on individual items in its stores, CVS is
complying with a regulation of the Massachusetts attorney general
that carries the force of law. Home Depot, which says the
regulation is too costly to implement and too prone to errors, is
flouting that law.
</P>
<P>
   CVS's approach is definitely more consumer friendly. It lets
shoppers identify prices more easily, compare prices away from the
shelf, and spot scanner errors right at the register. But it's one
of those things most consumers don't pay attention to unless
there's a problem. (I had a problem last week at Home Depot when I
bought a drain spout that had no price anywhere.)
</P>
<P>
   I've been agonizing about item-pricing lately because my sense
is that Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly's support for
item-pricing is wavering in the face of retail opposition.
Nationally, item-pricing's popularity seems to be waning, with only
a handful of states and municipalities still requiring prices on
individual store items. The question facing Massachusetts consumers
is whether we should join the national trend or buck it.
</P>
<P>
   We can thank Colman Herman for bringing the issue to the
public's attention. A frequent shopper at the Home Depot in Quincy,
Mass., he became annoyed at the company's disregard for the
item-pricing regulation and decided to do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   He first asked Reilly's office to enforce its own regulation,
but no one there would listen to him. Reilly has never enforced the
regulation. His aides say they receive few complaints about it and
consider it a low priority.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Herman last September filed a complaint against Home
Depot's Quincy store in small claims court. He won, but Home Depot
shrugged off the $25 fine. So Herman filed another complaint this
year and when the case was transferred to Quincy District Court he
scored another victory.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Mark S. Coven has ordered Home Depot's Quincy store to
start item pricing by Aug. 16. Home Depot is appealing. The
retailer is not claiming it is in compliance with the law, rather
that Herman was improperly acting as a private attorney general and
Coven was exceeding his authority. The retailer has made no secret
of the fact that it hopes to win on appeal before it has to start
item pricing.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Home Depot's attorney pressed Coven for a stay of his
compliance order, arguing Herman would not be injured by waiting
until the appeal is heard. ``That's because you don't believe in
the validity of this regulation,'' a testy Coven snapped back,
denying the request.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed by Herman's success, Timothy J. Shea, chief of
Reilly's public protection bureau, sent a letter to Home Depot in
late May saying the attorney general would support Herman on
appeal. He also directed the chain to bring all of its
Massachusetts stores into compliance, a request Home Depot has
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Shea's letter didn't sound like he was wedded to item pricing.
He said the regulation is the law until it's changed and invited
Home Depot to suggest changes. Home Depot declined comment last
week, but the Retail Association of Massachusetts says it is
working on a proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate that we have an attorney general here that
recognizes that there are some antiquated laws that need to be
updated,'' said Jon Hurst, president of the retail association.
</P>
<P>
   Hurst said item pricing was enacted in Massachusetts in the
early 1970s, a time when there were no scanners and check-out
personnel needed help keeping track of prices. Today, Hurst said,
marking prices on individual items only increases the potential for
pricing errors. And he said item pricing takes personnel away from
customer service functions and drives up retail costs as well as
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Downey, district manager for Home Depot, said in an
affidavit it would cost the chain $250,000 a year per store to
comply with the item-pricing regulation and deplete an already
understaffed sales force. ``Eventually this will harm Home Depot's
customers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Reilly, Herman says he is amenable to changes in the
item-pricing regulation as long as consumers are protected.
``Consumers have to have an easy, effective means when they're
checking out to make sure what they're being charged is what the
item is priced at,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Reilly will adopt that same view is unclear. What is
clear is that Reilly is not as big a fan of item pricing as
Attorney General Jennifer M. Granholm of Michigan, who not only
supports that state's item-pricing law but aggressively enforces
it.
</P>
<P>
   She and her predecessor have sued such retailers as Kmart, Sears
&AMP; Roebuck, Staples, Wal-Mart and, yes, even Home Depot for failing
to comply with the state's item-pricing law.
</P>
<P>
   Chris DeWitt, spokesman for Granholm, said Michigan residents
love the item-pricing law. He said it allows consumers to determine
whether they were overcharged, which surveys indicate is fairly
common.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've brought a lot of public attention to this issue,''
DeWitt said. ``This is one of the most, if not the most, popular
consumer laws in Michigan.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Long-distance options
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reader reaction to last week's column on long-distance
alternatives was heavy. Some didn't like my attitude, others did,
and many sent in their own long-distance suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Several people said they did not like BigZoo.com as much as
Marianne Stevenson, who I quoted. Their chief complaint was busy
signals getting through to the toll-free number for the
3.9-cents-a-minute prepaid service. ``The phone calls might as well
be free if you can't make them when you want to,'' said James
Pringle.
</P>
<P>
   Other readers offered some very promising long-distance
suggestions. Jock Gill, for example, suggested www.erbia.com, which
is charging 5.9 cents a minute plus a 3 percent universal access
fee and what it calls a $1 Federal Communications Commission
charge. Sign up online or at 877-549-6001.
</P>
<P>
   John Strom suggested GTC Telecom, which he said charges 5 cents
a minute plus a universal service fee and other government charges.
GTC can be reached online at gtctelecom.com or at 800-486-4030.
</P>
<P>
   Elyse Greenberg likes USA Datanet, a long-distance service you
use by dialing a local-access number. It charges 10 cents a minute
but no more than 99 cents a call. It also has a 4.9-cent flat-rate
plan. USA Datanet can be reached at usadatanet.com or by calling
877-532-8263.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Waters sent me an e-mail suggesting several ways to get free
long-distance service. His Web site, www.1888usa.com, is worth
checking out. It offers ways to make cheap calls using a computer
as well as just a plain old phone.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Mohl is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached at
617-474-2510, by e-mail at mohl(at)globe.com, or at The Boston
Globe, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1700 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FUNDS-QUARTER-BOS &LR;      07-03 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-QUARTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR INVESTORS, A TRIP TO NOWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not since Geraldo ripped open Al Capone's vault have so many
been so worked up about so little.
</P>
<P>
   When mutual fund investors get their midyear statements over the
next few weeks, millions will notice an interesting thing: Not much
has happened. Lost amid the Wall Street histrionics is the fact
that a whole lot of people have portfolios that are worth about as
much now as they were New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a few funds gained 7 percent in the first quarter, then
lost 6 percent in the second,'' said Kevin Parke, chief equity
officer for the Boston-based MFS fund family. ``Investors who owned
individual stocks might be down 50 or 60 percent, but the
volatility has been more of a wash for fund investors.''
</P>
<P>
   But, oh, what a trip to nowhere it's been.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first six months of 2000, the Nasdaq Composite index
has moved at least 2 percent in a single day more times than it did
in all of 1999. The technology-driven index has jumped or slumped
at least that much on more occasions this year, in fact, than it
did in the six combined years between 1992 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As a group, technology funds gained 27.2 percent in February to
post their second-best month since researcher Morningstar Inc.
began tracking the sector 52 years ago. (The only better month came
in February 1968, when the ``sector'' consisted of two funds.)
</P>
<P>
   The new-economy funds gave it back in April and May, losing 13
percent each month, before rebounding in the latter half of June.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lipper Inc., science and technology funds ended the
second quarter on the upside by about 2.4 percent year to date.
</P>
<P>
   But go-go technology funds weren't the only ones to take
shareholders on a wild ride.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications funds gained an average of 12.7 percent in
the first quarter, then lost an average of 15.8 percent in the
second. Even diversified US growth funds rose 13.4 percent through
March 31, and fell 7.3 percent between then and June 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that a significant percentage of investors are
chasing performance, cycling in and out of funds and sectors every
time they hear a new tip,'' said Burt Greenwald, a fund industry
consultant in Philadelphia. ``Investor attention spans haven't been
reduced, they've collapsed.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but not every fund or sector has spent six months
treading water.
</P>
<P>
   Some performed fairly well in the first half of the year, though
the numbers don't necessarily sparkle next to the gargantuan
returns a handful of funds posted in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The year's best peformer so far? Health and biotechnology funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That in spite of the election year, which is traditionally bad
for health-care stocks,'' said John Hancock investment strategist
Barry Evans, referring to politicians' quadrennial promises to
tinker with the system.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago at this point, the typical health-care fund was under
water by about 1 percent. This time around, the sector has crested
38.1 percent higher at mid-year than it began.
</P>
<P>
   Managers of natural resources funds, too, have been among the
few happy to see soaring prices for gasoline and natural gas. As
prices moved north, investment returns went with them.
</P>
<P>
   Funds in the sector have returned, on average, 14.4 percent so
far this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the kind of year in which everybody is going to be
thrilled when they open those statements,'' said Jim Weiss, chief
stock strategist at State Street Research in Boston. ``In the
second quarter, especially, there were very few places to hide in
terms of getting positive results.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those places was State Street's own Global Resource fund,
which was the quarter's best performer, according to Lipper. The
fund, which focuses on small- and mid-cap energy companies around
the world, gained 28.3 percent in the second quarter and 45.2
percent during the first six months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Dan Rice takes big risks to get those returns, though.
Global Resource topped the Lipper charts in 1997, returning more
than 70 percent, and slipped virtually to the bottom a year later,
shedding half its value.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very interesting quarter for Dan,'' Weiss said.
``Overall, however, the second quarter probably marked the first
time in a while that diversification paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts agree. After two years in which aggressive growth
and technology funds ruled the roost to the virtual exclusion of
all others, bond funds, value funds, and international funds showed
signs of life in the past three months. The only surprise is that
the laggards didn't come on stronger as investors mowed down growth
and technology funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was inevitable that at some point the pendulum would swing
differently,'' Greenwald said. ``I think the move back has started,
albeit slowly, and diversification will pay more and more going
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The consensus among managers interviewed by the Globe is that
the second half of the year will see the market stay at current
levels or move slightly higher, but with quite a bit of volatility.
Most also expect trading volume to remain relatively light, as many
investors stay on the sidelines waiting for a sign of things to
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``The term mutual fund people use when there are no clear trends
is that it's a stock-picker's market,'' joked Evans, of John
Hancock. ``This market is going to muddle along for a while yet, so
you can expect to hear that term batted around a lot in the next
few weeks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
