<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1703 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-STOCKS-BOS &LR;      07-03 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-STOCKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE AFFAIR WITH TECH STOCKS HAS COOLED, BUT IT'S FAR FROM OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're back _ at least part of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Left for dead a month ago, technology stocks have come back to
life faster than anyone imagined. The tech-heavy Nasdaq Composite
Index, at about 3900, is far below its peak of over 5000. But it is
well above the low point of 3200 it reached in late May.
</P>
<P>
   More impressive is the fact that some of the blue-chip names in
technology, like EMC Corp., are trading at or near their all-time
highs. For investors in these stocks, it's as if the nasty 40
percent slide in the Nasdaq never happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in awe,'' of the rebound, said Ned Riley, chief investment
strategist at State Street Global Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   But the world has changed since March, when tech stocks first
began to tumble. Before March, tech stocks were like the children
in Lake Wobegon: They were all above average. As we enter the
second half of the year, investors are making sharp distinctions
between the best and the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about all the stocks with good earnings stories have come
back nicely,'' said Richard Skaggs, a portfolio manager with Loomis
Sayles. Among those that have held up reasonably well are household
names such as Cisco Systems, Oracle, and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   Others that have survived more or less intact include some of
the hot new names in the infrastructure space _ companies like
Sycamore Networks or Juniper Networks or JDS Uniphase. These
companies don't necessarily make money, but they are growing fast
and investors have some confidence that they will be profitable in
the not too distant future.
</P>
<P>
   Before March, investors were willing to believe in any company
with a good story. Now they either want to see the money or have a
solid assurance that the money is coming.
</P>
<P>
   For more speculative companies, especially Internet companies,
that hard-nosed attitude has proved devastating. Consider the fate
of CMGI, the Andover company that has invested in dozens of
Internet start-ups. Since January, CMGI has lost 70 percent of it
value. The stock price of one of its subsidiaries, Engage, a young
online marketing company, is down 85 percent just since March.
</P>
<P>
   The well-publicized failure of some dot-coms, and the troubles
of big name companies like Amazon.com, have made investors
suspicious of money-losing Internet plays. Even the profitable
Internet companies such as Yahoo and AOL have been hurt by the
general fear that the retail side of the Internet may not be all it
was cracked up to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are reluctant to give big valuations to companies
with no earnings that may run into cash problems,'' said Steve
Demirjian, who manages money for Westfield Capital.
</P>
<P>
   But earnings or the lack of them don't fully explain the zigs
and zags in the technology market this year. The economic outlook
has played a role as well. In March, when the Nasdaq started to
fall, the US economy was growing like gangbusters and the Federal
Reserve clearly announced its intention to raise interest rates to
slow the economy down.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates are bad for all stocks, but they can be
particularly lethal for stocks with very high price/earnings
ratios, a description that covers most technology stocks. The
reason: Higher rates make future earnings less valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the worries was the government's decision to push for
the breakup of Microsoft. The move had no immediate implications
for technology companies. But nervous investors reasoned that if
Microsoft could be a target, other successful technology companies
could be as well.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was the issue of valuations. The price of
technology stocks had reached record levels by March _ the Nasdaq
rose 86 percent in 1999 and another 24 percent in the first part of
this year. After a runup like that, some kind of correction was
probably inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   In late May, surveying the incredible rise and then fall in
technology stocks, Thomas O'Neill, chief investment officer at
FleetBoston Financial, said: ``I don't think in my lifetime we will
ever again see the level of speculation we have just seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the speculative excesses may have been washed out of the
market, but the love affair with tech stocks is far from over.
Mutual fund investors continue to put money into tech funds and
money managers continue to recommend tech stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Where does the bullishness come from?
</P>
<P>
   Tech fans point to a few things. First and foremost, the
eocnomic picture has changed, at least a little. The US economy is
showing some signs of slowing, and the Federal Reserve last
Wednesday decided not to boost rates at its June meeting. The Fed
may yet raise rates again this year, but for the moment the
pressure is off.
</P>
<P>
   If the economy does slow, say analysts, old economy companies
are likely to feel the pinch as consumers cut back on purchases of
cars and houses. But the best new economy companies _ those
supplying the tools that will make corporate America more
productive _ will continue to do reasonably well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamentals in technology remain pretty darn good,'' said
Brian Grove, who manages money for Vaughan Nelson in Houston. Grove
isn't the only one who thinks so. If you had a nickel for every
analyst who is crowing about the fundamentals in technology, you
would be rich already.
</P>
<P>
   The tech bulls point out that, despite the ups and downs of the
stock market this year, the basic story in technology is
essentially unchanged: demand continues to be strong for
semiconductors, telecom equipment, wireless technology, and storage
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The best companies in those areas should grow rapidly in the
coming year, according to Rob Joseph, a technology specialist with
State Street Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growth prospects for many companies look astonishingly
good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For a number of years recently, the fourth quarter has been a
strong one for tech stocks, in part because new products are
announced then. No one knows whether 2000 will see a repeat of that
pattern, but some money managers say there is plenty of cash
sitting on the sidelines ready to come in if a late year rally
breaks out.
</P>
<P>
   So what's not to like?
</P>
<P>
   A few things, say those who remain skeptical about the quick
rebound in technology stocks. At the top of the list is the Federal
Reserve. The Fed took no action last week, but said it would raise
rates again if the slowdown proves illusory.
</P>
<P>
   If rate hikes were a problem in the spring, is there a reason to
think they won't be a problem in the fall?
</P>
<P>
   A second potential problem is the dot-com failures. So far the
stock market is treating the dot-coms and the infrastructure
companies as if they come from two separate universes. In reality,
of course, the two are tightly interwoven. The dot-com companies
have been voracious customers of hardware, software, storage, and
consulting services.
</P>
<P>
   If the dot-coms get into trouble, won't their appetite for some
of those other products and services drop off?
</P>
<P>
   Fears of such a chain reaction hit Scient Corp. last week. The
San Francisco-based e-consulting firm said one of its dot-com
clients had filed for bankruptcy, an event that forced Scient to
set up a reserve to cover possible losses. Scient stock fell 20
percent in a day.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the valuation question. Technology stocks are
never cheap. But at this point, the blue chip names in technology _
Oracle, EMC, Cisco _ sell for price/earnings ratios of anywhere
from 90 to 120. The stock market as a whole has a price/earnings
ratio of 24. The higher the multiple, the greater the expectation
of future growth.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's O'Neill says some of the prices on tech stocks are
approaching nosebleed territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, if you've had to pay 100 times earnings for a
company, it has been difficult to make good returns over time,''
said O'Neill. ``And God forbid, one of these companies should have
a major disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill is not surprised the Nasdaq has bounced off its low, but
he cautions against reading too much into the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there another low coming?'' he said. ``Very likely there
is.''
</P>
<P>
   So there you have it: Tech stocks are either wildly overvalued
or appropriately priced, a safe haven in an uncertain world or a
risky place to be.
</P>
<P>
   Don't you just love Wall Street?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
