u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      07-03 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO AVOIDING UNCERTAINTIES   PLANNING FOR RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. I have a question about the assumptions you use on spending
after retirement. When estimating retirement income, do you assume
that the reader wants to have enough money to pay his or her bills,
not be a burden to others, and die broke? Or do you assume the
reader wants to have enough money to establish an estate at least
the size of the principal available at retirement? Or something in
between? My wife and I have put one son through college at no
expense to him, and we are doing the same for the second. Our goal
is to have enough so that our sons will not have to support us, but
we are not specifically planning to set aside funds for an
inheritance. We expect in retirement that we will be spending not
only the interest earned, but a judicious amount of principal in
most years. Is my view consistent with your assumptions?
</P>
<P>
   B.K., Burlington, Vt. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If most of the people I have addressed on the subject of
retirement planning followed my suggestions, they would likely
leave fairly substantial estates. But this is not because of any
feeling that the next generation is likely to need a helping hand,
but rather because of the vast uncertainties involved in retirement
planning.
</P>
<P>
   The first, of course, is that nobody knows how long he will
live. Relying on life expectancy tables _ such as those used by the
IRS _ could land you in the soup. Suppose you carefully outline a
plan that would serve you until your mid-80s, and then lived
another decade? The financial implications could be painful.
</P>
<P>
   The second uncertainty is investment results. I try to be
realistic and conservative, but I have to remain aware that results
might be considerably lower than projected. (Remember the stock
market decade from 1968 to 1978? People who counted on a stock
market return of the go-go years of the mid-1960s were in tough
shape during those years.)
</P>
<P>
   Next, there's always the chance the future might bring
higher-than-anticipated levels of inflation. I have recently been
using a 3.5 percent figure _ a little higher than the 3 percent
suggested at the Merrill Lynch Web site where I go for these
calculations. But it is certainly far from unthinkable that
inflation might return to higher levels and perhaps stay there for
a long time. Even a small change can work out to big differences.
At 3.5 percent inflation, in 20 years you would need $99,489 to buy
what $50,000 buys today; crank the inflation-rate assumption up to
4 percent and you would need $109,556.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, for many people, one of the biggest expenses in life
comes near the end _ high medical costs.
</P>
<P>
   All of these factors lead me to seek a retirement plan that will
allow the retiree a certain amount of sponge _ and which will leave
his heirs a nice inheritance if everything goes better than it
might.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, my advice for someone who is seeking to leave the world
precisely as broke as when he entered it would be to make his
calculations by projecting a very long life and by setting aside
significant financial pools to deal with lower-than-expected
investment returns, higher-than-anticipated inflation levels, and
substantial unexpected expenses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will reach age 70 1/2 in September and take my first
required distribution in December, so as to minimize the tax
burden. Our home and autos are paid for, and my pension and Social
Security provide enough income, so we don't need the additional
funds at this time. My original thought for the IRA distributions
was to establish a taxable account in each of the funds I am
currently using. But I have some concern with the funds,
particularly Washington Mutual.
</P>
<P>
   J.M., Orange, Calif. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think your plan is solid and would suggest you take a
longer view of the results of Washington Mutual Investors.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of your projected distribution is correct. Although
you could delay your first mandatory withdrawal into the tax year
2001, it would remain the distribution for tax year 2000 _ and then
you would have to take a second distribution for tax year 2001 in
the same year. Taking two distributions in one year would have
unpleasant tax consequences for most people.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Mutual Investors is doing just what it has been doing
for years _ investing in large-cap value-oriented stocks, sticking
with its bets, and producing low turnover. Its current
price-to-earnings ratio is 22.6, and its portfolio shows an average
price-to-book value ratio of 5.4. While its payout level is only
1.79 percent, that is more a function of a stock market that has
sent prices so high that most stock portfolio yields have become
negligible.
</P>
<P>
   What has been happening is simply that value investment is
thoroughly out of fashion. Washington Mutual's results have
reflected those of most value funds. When you look at its 1.8
percent year-to-date loss entering last week, you'll find it in
line with the median 1.7 percent loss for its peer funds in the
large-cap value group. Despite a one-year return of a negative 8.2
percent (compared to a 4 percent loss as the median for its peers),
the fund's three-year record of 10.4 percent average annual return
compares nicely to the 8.8 percent for its peer group.
</P>
<P>
   I can understand the frustration of value investors looking at
the greener grass over in the growth pasture where the bulls have
been grazing. I am one of those value investors. But market
fashions always change, and when I consider the 35.5
price-to-earnings ratio of the Standard and Poor's 500 Index, and
the yields of the funds that track that index only slightly better
than 1 percent, the value territory looks mighty good to me. I
suggest you stick with Washington Mutual Investors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We hold some stocks that have dividend reinvestment plans. So
far, I have not subscribed because I felt it was unwise to have
fractions of stocks. Mostly I have 100, 200, 300, or 400 shares of
a company. What problems might I encounter by owning fractional
shares?
</P>
<P>
   O.B., El Cajon, Calif. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't see any real problem. Dividend reinvestment plans, or
DRIPs, do indeed allow participants to hold fractional shares. Many
people allow shares to build up in a DRIP until they have more than
100 shares in the plan, then ask that they be sent a certificate
for a 100-share round lot of the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, some plans have added a feature that allows
stockholders to mail their certificates to the institutions
managing the DRIP, thus putting all of their holdings in the DRIP.
This not only solves problems of safe storage of the certificates,
but gives the owner the ability to sell the shares either without
paying a brokerage commission or at a cost that's lower than a
broker's fee might be. (Though it's only fair to add that when you
sell DRIP shares, you can't be sure what price they will bring at
the date at which the DRIP managers make their purchases and
sales.)
</P>
<P>
   If you hold fractional shares in a DRIP and decide to withdraw
from the plan, you can either instruct the DRIP to sell the stock
or issue you a certificate for the number of full shares you own.
They will then sell any fractional shares you own and send you a
check for the value of the fractional share.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the uncertainty of a sale price, the only
disadvantages I can see to using DRIPs are minor for most
investors. One is that you cannot use the stock in the account as
security for a loan, as you can do with shares for which you hold
the certificates. Another is that if you borrow money from your
broker to buy stocks, the larger the value of the stocks being held
in your account by your broker, the smaller the chance you might
face a margin call if one of the stocks bought on margin runs into
trouble. For conservative long-term investors, these disadvantages
should loom very small.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
