<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDS REDEFINED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the 20th century, a woman who wanted diamonds usually
had to find a man first. Today, she just looks for a good jeweler.
</P>
<P>
   Not as romantic, but, then, what is in this can-do, no-nonsense
techno-millennium?
</P>
<P>
   The rock purchased solo supposedly still makes the heart sing,
and that song still echoes Marilyn's classic number in ``Gentlemen
Prefer Blondes'' _ but today she's singing it in a business suit
while hefting a briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   She's a dot-comer, banker, executive, doctor, or professor, and
the jewelry trade refers to her as a ``self-purchaser'' _ the
hottest trend breathing on the glass cases across America.
</P>
<P>
   ``A diamond has traditionally been associated with getting
hitched,'' says a single, 49-year-old Boston woman who owns her own
business and purchased two sets of diamond earrings at Shreve,
Crump &AMP; Low _ one for $3,000 and one for $5,000. ``There's a sense
of power, money, and validation attached to the diamond, and in
today's world we women validate ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg DiStefano, manager of the Diamond Information Center in New
York, reports that the US self-purchase market was $3.75 billion
last year, representing 6.7 million pieces of diamond jewelry sold
to women, a 41 percent increase over 1998. According to a national
survey, women spent an average of $585 on diamond jewelry for
themselves last year, up from $430 the year before.
</P>
<P>
   He says nearly 40 percent of the self-purchase market is diamond
rings for the right hand, and that mostly married women are buying
them. Single women are leaning more toward tennis bracelets and
earrings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have more money at their disposal than they used to,''
says DiStefano, adding that the diamond has moved beyond the heavy
symbolism of a love relationship to become ``a hot fashion item''
featured on couture runways and magazine spreads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women in my generation were so reticent about everything,''
says Phyllis Godwin, owner of Granite City Electric in Quincy,
Mass., who inherited most of her fine jewelry from her mother but
who enjoys making the occasional purchase of a new piece.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years ago, when she wanted diamond stud earrings, she felt
she had to wait for her husband to buy them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were too small, and I took them back,'' she says.
``That's how women got what they wanted back then _ by exchanging
what the man picked out. Today, if you're a young woman with
financial capability you march right into Tiffany's and buy
whatever you damn please. There's a sense of instant
gratification.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lebowitz, diamond buyer at Shreve, Crump &AMP; Low,
understands gratification. He leans on the case containing a
$22,500 diamond ring and smiles. ``The woman customer wants to be
wooed and schmoozed. She wants the experience. She wants to be
admired, fussed over.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like she might be a little wistful for the old days when
she came in with a guy. Could it be that all the independent
purchasing is a little like bowling alone? Or is that heresy this
deep into feminism?
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are showing men how powerful they are as managers,''
Lebowitz continues, pointing to the store's popular precious stone
rings _ rubies, emeralds, and sapphires set with diamonds and
selling for $5,000 to just under $40,000. ``Buying diamonds shows
how powerful women are as consumers. It says to business and
personal relations: `I've made it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but are they happy? And what is happiness?
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought the fur coat, the house, and the car,'' says the
Boston businesswoman with two pairs of diamond earrings. ``What's
left? The diamond.''
</P>
<P>
   How do the earrings make her feel? ``Put together,'' she says.
``I can wear them with jeans or a full-length gown. You feel like
you've arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   But for how long? And is a diamond really forever, or is it
another temporary gratification? What, as the man said, do women
really want?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Susan Trausch is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
