   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE (Albany, N.Y.) _ On the campaign trail, both Senate
candidates in New York _ Democrat Hillary Rodham Clinton and
Republican Rep. Rick Lazio _ support reforms to the campaign
finance system. Yet both will likely accept millions of dollars in
legal but unregulated and unrestricted back-door donations in a
race in which the level of soft money is on pace to dwarf past
statewide elections. By LARA JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLICS-HISPANICS (San Antonio) _ Catholic parishes need huge
numbers of Hispanic lay leaders and youth ministers, and they need
them now, a nationwide study has found. The National Conference of
Catholic Bishops commissioned the study, called ``Hispanic Ministry
at the Turn of the New Millennium,'' to help the clerics prepare
for a four-day gathering that begins Thursday in Los Angeles. By J.
MICHAEL PARKER.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-VISITS (San Quentin, Calif.) _ The small, Spartan room
within the fortress of San Quentin State Prison has served as a
lifeline for nearly 20 years, not only for those incarcerated
inside but for myriad outside visitors hungry for contact with the
denim-clad men of California's death row. But a recent fight in the
room is threatening the long and largely safe tradition of the
visits for California's condemned inmates. By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPY-SOFTWARE (San Francisco) _ ``Husband cheating online? Catch
him with this.'' With those words, software developer Doug Fowler
hit the jackpot. He posted the words in an eBay auction
solicitation, posted in July 1999, advertising Internet
surveillance software that could help you nab that straying spouse.
Within four hours, 500 people had clicked on the posting. Within a
week, the number hit 5,000. Sales tripled in the weeks following
the auction, and Fowler's company is growing at a healthy clip of
15 to 25 percent per month. By ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   DOT-COM-SURVIVAL (San Francisco) _ Sink, swim or change
direction. That is what some Internet companies are doing, making
changes to their product, business plans and even their raison
d'etre as the market shakeout eliminates or consolidates weaker
dot-coms. By VANESSA HUA.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-VOLVO (Undated) _ Wagons may be on the verge of extinction,
having been mostly replaced first by the minivan in the 1980s and
then the sport-utility vehicle in the 1990s. But Volvo's new V70
Cross Country, featuring a bigger body and tires, is ready to take
on sport-utility vehicles. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-NAVIGATOR (Undated) _ For years, the luxury-car lines of
Ford and General Motors have struggled to draw flush-with-cash baby
boomers into their dealers' showrooms. But that is changing.
Lincoln Mercury showrooms are busy places these days, thanks to
boomers' love affair with sport utility vehicles. By G. CHAMBERS
WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-TUCKER (San Antonio) _ A Green Bay, Wis., collector
recently took one of the few 1940s Tucker luxury cars ever produced
to San Antonio for the annual convention of the Tucker Automobile
Club. Preston Tucker, for whom the car was named, started his car
company in 1947, and it produced only 51 of these giant, oddball,
rear-engine luxury cars before going belly-up in 1948. By G.
CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-GIZMOS (San Francisco) _ Has a more useful, versatile,
perfect tool ever been invented than the Swiss Army knife? A couple
of years ago I asked readers to reveal the gizmos they find
essential while on the road, and the one item that showed up on
virtually everyone's list was a Swiss Army knife. By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RESTAURANT-TIPS (Undated) _ With diners eating out more often
and paying more for the privilege, it's no wonder restaurant
critics are as thick as nuts on a Texas sheet cake these days. But
often the things critics want to say are not said. Here is a list
of pet peeves _ and suggestions _ restaurateurs should take note
of. By BONNIE WALKER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JIMMY-PEDRO (Undated) _Please forgive Jimmy Pedro if he sounds
just a little annoyed at the major to-do about the U.S. Olympic
basketball ``Dream Team.'' He has his own dream, thank you. For
more than a decade, Pedro has been one of the best Americans in a
sport _ judo _ that may not even wind up on the 100-plus hours of
``minor'' television coverage of this year's Summer Olympics from
Sydney, Australia. By DAVID KING.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-HALFWAY (Undated) _ With all due respect to the All-Star
break, baseball's halfway point is actually the Fourth of July, and
not just because of the 15 scheduled pyro-spectaculars on the card.
By RAY RATTO.
</P>
