<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0704-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    And now for the news
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Well, folks, there's some good news and some
bad news. You'll have to decide for yourself which is which.
</P>
<P>
   Elian has gone home...but...the auto-hysterical cousin
Marisleysis is still shedding public tears. Lincoln-Marti, the
private school Elian attended while he was in Miami has hung a
plaque in his old classroom and intends to have an Elian museum in
place by August to display the work he did during the estimated 100
days he was enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Braves big-mouth pitcher, John Rocker, split open a
callous on his thumb and had to watch from the bullpen as the Mets
stomped all over his team. It could have been worse...he could have
had to take the 7 train to the ballpark and sit next to some of
those folks he's been trashing lately.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Mayor Rudy has asked the natives not to attack.
</P>
<P>
   Mars is looking wetter all the time and the guys with the
satellites and telescopes are telling us that maybe there's some
water frozen under there, and maybe there's life on the red planet
after all.
</P>
<P>
   And MAYBE Orson Welles was right.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles, heir to the British throne, and his long-time
lady love, Camilla Parker Bowles, have finally appeared together at
an official function. They hosted a fundraiser for the Prince's
Foundation, the group that oversees Charles's environmental and
architectural projects. Their recent photo in U.S.News &AMP; World
Report showed them all dressed up and, for a change, with somewhere
to go.
</P>
<P>
   His Highness was in black tie, Camilla wore Versace _ but it was
nothing like the oddity of the same label almost worn by Jennifer
Lopez to the Grammy awards. Ms. Parker Bowles's gown was palest
pink and covered the fair lady's charms nicely. And she didn't look
one bit like a Rottweiler.
</P>
<P>
   This whole romance thing between Charles and Camilla has had
little impact on my life. The way I see it, they've been at it a
long time and should by now, know what they want, in spite of
Charles's mum's objections. Rumor has it though that the Queen is
coming around a bit and the ladies have done ng beauty. Without
royal trappings, they just look comfortable together, the way a
middle-age couple should. After all, that's what they are.
</P>
<P>
   Charles's princely face is etched by squint lines _ some put
there by his years in the cockpit, and others no doubt, by
wondering when his mama is going to hand him the scepter and orb
and say, ``Have at it son; the country's all yours.'' Nor is
Camilla's countenance free of wear and tear.
</P>
<P>
   Charles is not tall, but that's okay. And Camilla isn't skinny.
HOORAY!
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ms. Parker Bowles's shape is considerably less than
perfect by today's standards. She has a chest just like a real
woman's and, forgive me for noticing, it's long past perky. And
even a Versace cannot disguise the amplitude of the lady's
midsection _ referred to by us commoners as a spare tire.
</P>
<P>
   But you know what? It looks good. It looks natural. And it
surely makes me feel a whole lot better about what I'm seeing in
the mirror every day.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, her Prince still loves her.
</P>
<P>
   Good news? Bad news? I dunno. It's your call.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
