<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1736 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NETWATCH0704-COX     07-03 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH0704-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOL tunes up downloadable music
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Want to see the future of the Internet? Keep an eye on
Bob Pittman, America Online's president and chief operating
officer.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of the AOL/Time Warner merger vote, Pittman, 46,
has become one of the most influential figures in both old and new
media. The decisions he'll make at America Online will have an
impact on nearly everyone who picks up a magazine, watches TV, goes
to a movie or logs on to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Media insiders will remember Pittman as the man who helped
develop MTV and VH1, the wildly popular cable music channels.
</P>
<P>
   He joined AOL in 1996 with a plan to use his knowledge of TV
programming to create channels and ``programming'' for the online
service.
</P>
<P>
   Pittman also came to AOL to transform the online service's
business model. Ripping another page from his television
background, he moved AOL from a subscription-based business model
to one that included advertising, marketing and electronic
commerce. The combination was and still is so successful that
almost all other Internet service providers _ including the No. 2
ISP, Atlanta-based EarthLink _ now consider it a key component of
their business strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Pittman has expanded his vision to include delivering AOL on any
device from the traditional PC to pagers and television. He also
sees a world where AOL users can watch movies and download music
right on the service.
</P>
<P>
   Charging for digital music downloads could be the one place
where Pittman will make his biggest impression on the Internet
economy. Last week, AOL took its first step toward selling music
online, making a deal with InterTrust Technologies that will let
AOL members download digital music for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of trying to figure out how to
commercialize digital downloading,'' said AOL spokeswoman Wendy
Goldberg. The technology will be included in AOL version 6.0 due
out this year.
</P>
<P>
   However, the billion-dollar question that artists, record
companies and Internet companies dearly want to answer is whether
AOL customers will be willing to purchase music online _ no matter
how easy it is to do.
</P>
<P>
   Talal Shamoon, senior vice president for media at InterTrust,
said America Online's 22 million-plus subscriber base would be the
ideal setting to launch a secure version of Napster, the widely
used system for swapping music files.
</P>
<P>
   AOL, through its various partners and the seemingly limitless
resources of the Time Warner family of media products, could offer
a stunning range of incentives that could include everything from
concert tickets to a free month of HBO.
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities are limitless, and if anyone can figure out a
way to persuade listeners to pay for music on the Net, the odds are
pretty good it's Pittman. After all, who would have thought back in
1981 that people would be willing to sit and watch a channel that
then consisted of nothing but music videos 24 hours a day?
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be at the threshold of something very big,'' Shamoon
told The Wall Street Journal. ``A robust electronic community of
people exchanging content in a safe way, where rights holders get
paid and consumers feel good about the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether that ``something very big'' actually materializes is
entirely up to Pittman, and it's hard to find a pundit who doesn't
believe Pittman is this century's P.T. Barnum _ the kind of
businessman who instead of selling things you don't want, persuades
you to buy things you had absolutely no idea you wanted.
</P>
<P>
   His business skills Hollywood media connections and marketing
genius create a rare set of talents, combining ``old economy''
horse trading with ``new economy'' innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Mark Stavish, head of personnel for AOL, put it best when
he told the Sunday Times of London, ``People say AOL exists because
of Steve (Case, AOL's founder and chief executive), but it works
because of Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
