computer the fun part of computing is almost always instantly
apparent. ``Students at the end of the first lesson are reluctant
to leave the Solitaire game that is scheduled for the last 15
minutes of the session to practice mouse usage.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you're online and looking for a jump start to the Web,
there are plenty of guides to help you find interesting Web sites
geared to your interests. ``The Internet Cool Guide'' and ``The
Internet Cool Guide to Online Shopping'' are two small,
easy-to-read guides to some of the best-known Web sites. Even if
you're not online yet, browsinww.digitaldiva.com) must have felt
when she went to work in Microsoft's marketing department three and
a half years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know the difference between hardware and software,''
she says. ``That's a pretty big problem when you work at Microsoft.
I'd sit in these meetings and hear all this technology talk and I
was just overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   She spent most of her time in meetings scribbling down strange
acronyms and techno-speak that sounded like something Captain
Picard would utter in an average episode of ``Star Trek,'' then
hurry back to her office and try to look everything up.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, like a lot of women new to technology, was afraid to
ask questions of her Microsoft colleagues because she didn't want
to appear ignorant. However, she soon discovered that many of her
friends who didn't work for high-technology companies like
Microsoft were just as confused and intimidated as she was.
</P>
<P>
   The Digital Diva's traveling road show takes her all over the
country with the Microsoft team, demonstrating products and
spreading the word that technology is accessible. She has a ``try
it, you'll like it'' attitude about technology that resonates with
women who are interested but slightly nervous around computers,
software, hand-held devices and other high-tech gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent show-and-tell engagement at the Atlanta Civic
Center, women stopped to look over and ``test drive'' everything
from money management software programs to electronic organizers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to open our eyes and see what's happening,'' said
Jody Gold, a visitor from Maryland who stopped by the technology
display to test out a hand-held electronic organizer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we really want to get involved in and not shy
away from,'' added her friend Beth Kwiateck. They both said that
being able to play around with various software and computer
devices in a low-stress atmosphere (none of the products
demonstrated was available for purchase on-site) made them more
willing to ask questions and try the products out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only use the computer at home,'' said Beth Kearney, ``but my
daughter just got a high-tech job and she wants to tell me about
all this stuff and I want to find out what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
