<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barbecuer's deck hand
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Does your grill drool grease or sputter sparks?
At one time or another most grills become the source of a deck-top
mess. Instead of pressure washing wood or stone after every
cookout, why not buy a bib for the barbie? The ``Original'' Grill
Pad ($25 to $40 depending on size; www.diversitech.com) is little
more than a pad of thick, feltlike material coated in colored
concrete. But it's big enough (30-by-42-inch rectangles or 30-inch
rounds) to protect the deck and can be cleaned off with a shot from
the garden hose.
</P>
<P>
   IF ONLY IT POPPED CORN
</P>
<P>
   At first our home TVs and radios pumped their sound through a
single speaker. The speaker count jumped to two for stereo, then
four, and for the past couple years it's been six speakers for 5.1
channel Dolby Digital. Now the latest is Dolby Digital 6.1 Extended
Surround, which requires seven speakers to bring the movie theater
experience home. Sherwood America, a California-based home and car
audio specialist, won an Innovation Award at the International
Consumer Electronics Show in January for its design of the
Newcastle R-956 Receiver ($1,500; www.sherwoodamerica.com), which
is capable of reproducing the 6.1 channel movie theater sound
environment at home. The R-956 has six 120-watt-per-channel
discrete amplifiers to drive its speakers. The receiver also
features an on-screen display, a dedicated audiovisual output to
send signals to a home theater in a second room and digital outputs
for a compact disc or mini disc recorder.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
