<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A dud named 'Sue'
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ What a disappointment. The most complete
Tyrannosaurus rex ever discovered gets the most shallow treatment
ever burned onto a CD-ROM in Simon &AMP; Schuster Interactive's I See
Sue . . . the T.rex. ($20; www.simonandschuster.com; for Windows
and Mac). The sad truth is that you'll get relatively few glimpses
of the magnificent creature's bones alongside a mind-numbingly
simple, simulated board game in which you collect and discard
tiles, go-fish style, to complete a dinosaur and move across a
badly-drawn playing field. The game takes about as long to master
as tic-tac-toe, and the frustratingly random jump-aheads and
fall-backs on the game board remove even that classic paper and
pencil game's strategy factor. Annoying Nickelodeon child star
Danny Tamberelli (''Pete and Pete,'' ``Figure it Out,'' ``All
That'') provides repetitive, bothersome rhyming commentary with
only the most cursory level of information. Skip the CD-ROM and go
straight to the wonderful Web site, www.iseesue.com, for a far more
in-depth look at Sue's discovery and reconstruction with puzzles to
print and complete. Yeah, T.rex is supposed to be bad, just not
like this. (Ages 4-7).
</P>
<P>
   NOW THIS GAME'S GOT BITE
</P>
<P>
   Disney's Dinosaur Activity Center ($30;
www.disneyinteractive.com; for Windows and Mac) is everything ``I
See Sue'' isn't . . . that's the good news and the bad news.
Whereas ``Sue'' is a clunker built around a real creature,
``Dinosaur'' is a fantastic, personality-filled CD-ROM based on
those fictional, Disnified creatures-with-human-faces from the hit
movie of the same name. Of the three great arcade and logic
strategy games here (not including the silly Lemur Love Match),
Colossal Fossil Face Off is the best. It's a simplified chess-type
game of dino vs. dino, where each player's beasts have their own
special moves. The object is to discover which of your opponent's
creatures is hiding the dinosaur egg. There's a fun dinosaur puzzle
maker, which lets kids mix and match dino parts and record their
own voice-over roars, and, with an Internet connection, the
dinosaur creations can be e-mailed to friends. Children won't learn
much about real dinosaurs here, but they won't be bored to tears
after five minutes, and they'll pick up some logic and strategy
skills along the way. (Ages 5 and up).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
