</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SIDE0704-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Digital Diva' Stacy Elliott's Tips
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Elliott, Microsoft's ``Digital Diva,'' offers this advice
for newcomers to computers and the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   1. Figure out what you want to do. Focus on what you want to do
rather than on the technology itself. From there you can decide
what products you need. If you just want to send e-mail and surf
the Web, your needs will be simple. But if you want to send digital
pictures, you need a camera and a scanner.
</P>
<P>
   2. Grab a friend and go to the computer store. It's good to take
a friend along with you. Store personnel are great, but they don't
know you and your skill level. The best way to learn about
technology is to have somebody you know help.
</P>
<P>
   3. If you belong to a club, have a ``Tech Night.'' ``Many people
are involved in clubs or organizations, like gardening clubs or
book clubs,'' Elliott says. Pick a night to talk about technology.
Ask everyone to bring a gadget and demonstrate how it works, or
have the meeting at a home where everyone can try the computer.
``All of a sudden, you'll have new ideas about what technology can
do,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   4. Do a little bit every day. Don't try to do everything all in
one day. Play with it, practice with it and explore. Learn one
thing, then you can go onto something else.
</P>
<P>
   5. Read up. Don't skip over the technology articles in magazines
like Family PC _ if you are connected to the Internet you can go
out onto the Web and look for more tips and tricks. Elliott
suggests flipping through books at the local bookstore to find the
right one for you. Make sure you don't buy any book that uses
language you don't understand. One book she recommends is ``The
Grown-Up's Guide to Computing'' by Mary S. Furlong and Stefan B.
Lipson from the Microsoft Press, but there are many good ones to
chose from.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
