r a BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0704-COX     07-03 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0704-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _Q: Regarding your reply to the person who asked
about mountain vs. hill _ I've noticed other tricky pairs like
that. For example, when does a pond become a lake or a creek become
a river?
</P>
<P>
   _ Charles Wukasch
</P>
<P>
   A: Naming of ponds, lakes, streams and rivers is by local
convention. Cartographic researcher Beth Gorman of the United
States Geological Survey Earth Science Information Center reports
no volume amount defines these terms. Technically, all flowing
bodies of water are called streams (the Mississippi Stream?!).
Generally, local convention dictates creeks are smaller than
streams and rivers are larger. Q: Over the weekend my husband and I
were having a discussion of where all the cabooses are. Could you
help, please?
</P>
<P>
   _ Jennie Koch
</P>
<P>
   A: A few are still in operation, reports Robert Crossman of
Austin &AMP; Texas Central Railroad. This car also often contained crew
sleeping and eating quarters. Cabooses (caboosi?) and their crew
monitored the rear of the train and put the air brakes on if
necessary. These functions are now performed by FRED, or flashing
rear end device. Many cabooses ended up in scrap yards; some have
more interesting second careers as lake houses or diners.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do we get a question to the team that made ``The Sixth
Sense''? Almost everyone I've asked agrees that Cole knows
(senses?) the doctor is ``not quite himself'' from the beginning.
Was this intended? _ F. Dacic
</P>
<P>
   A: How about the opinion of Thomas Schatz, chair of the
University of Texas' radio, television and film department? If you
have not seen this movie, stop reading here. Logic tells the
audience that Cole knows Bruce Willis' character is dead although
his performance cannot blatantly reveal this fact. Cole is always
``in a state'' when he sees Dr. Crowe. The audience never sees
Crowe's wounds; however, most of the film is through Crowe's, not
Cole's, eyes. Schatz concludes Cole definitely knew. Q: My dear
friend who lives in Bullhead City, Ariz., wants a thermometer that
registers more than 120 degrees. It does get hot there. Do they
make such a thing?
</P>
<P>
   _ Jean Neece
</P>
<P>
   A: How about up to 158 degrees? That's very hot. Call Life With
Ease at (800) 966-5119 to order a talking indoor/outdoor
thermometer ($22.95 plus shipping). The National Climatic Data
Center reports the highest temperature recorded in the United
States is 134 degrees (ouch!) on July 10, 1913, in Greenland Ranch,
Calif. Arizona's record is 128 degrees on June 29, 1994, in Lake
Havasu City (not far from Bullhead). And the Lone Star State? 120
degrees on Aug. 12, 1936, in Seymour.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a 1943 Abraham Lincoln penny. I read an advertisement
that told me the coin was worth about $3,000, but the address on
the advertisement was fishy. It was only a P.O. box in the New York
area. I wanted to know if I could get the coin evaluated here in
Austin. Are there old coins that are worth $3,000 as claimed in the
advertisement?
</P>
<P>
   _ Mohammed Suhail
</P>
<P>
   A: Before you respond to this or any other penny-worth-a-fortune
ad, grab a magnet. If the penny is attracted to the magnet, it may
be worth 10 cents. Rare coin dealer Larry Spence (454-3003) says
that during World War II, copper was needed for the war effort, so
1943 pennies were made of steel. A few 1943 pennies (blank, S or D)
were made of copper. These copper ones are valuable, but few have
been found. Some 1943 steel pennies have turned black, so owners
believe they are copper. Counterfeiters occasionally plate 1943
steel pennies with copper and try to pass them off as rare. If your
penny passes the magnet test, take it to a reputable dealer, who
will have it authenticated by the American Numismatic Association.
While you are sorting through change, look for a mint error dollar
coin (Sacagawea on the reverse and a Washington quarter on the
obverse). Interest has been high since an Arkansas newsman stumbled
on it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a handmade beautiful quilt that I have been using for
a bedspread for five or six years. It is in desperate need of a
good washing and I am afraid I will ruin it. I have heard it is not
a good idea to have a quilt dry-cleaned. Could you please tell me
how to do this properly and what soap to use?
</P>
<P>
   _ Joyce Fraser
</P>
<P>
   A: Washing by hand is the kindest thing you can do to a quilt.
Test for colorfastness first. Then select a pure soap such as
Ivory, Castile or quilt soap. Quilt soap is formulated with orvus
paste _ a soap gentle enough to use on animals. Wash the quilt in
the bathtub and dry on a rack or even over the shower curtain rod.
(Place a towel or sheet between the quilt and the metal rod.) Q: I
just bought a wading pool for my little girl. It's rather large, so
I feel wasteful filling and emptying it every day. If it had a
screen over it to keep out debris and mosquitoes, how long is the
water good?
</P>
<P>
   _ Cindy Bogard
</P>
<P>
   A: As I recall, the composition of my children's wading pool on
a summer afternoon was part melted Popsicle, part unidentified
liquid and two parts very warm water. I'd dump it. ``Not a good
idea to keep water in a fill-and-draw pool,'' says Mark Parsons of
the Austin/Travis County Health and Human Services department. The
pool needs chlorine and circulation. Children are not that
particular about personal hygiene, he added delicately. Nothing
dangerous to your child's health may grow in this water overnight,
but then again, nothing dies either.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My neighbor is looking for Lip Life lipstick. She used to buy
it at a store named Leon's. Secondly, she'd like to find an ostrich
feather duster that has a long enough handle to reach regular
ceiling height.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Calton
</P>
<P>
   A: Sorry, Lip Life by Neutrogena has not been made for four
years. Telescoping feather dusters (what is it about ostriches that
make their feathers sooooo attractive to dust?) may be ordered from
Gardener's Supply Co. at (888) 833-1412. This arm extends 72 inches
and may be detached for daily use. Gardener's boasts these feathers
were humanely harvested. Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670,
Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or
fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
