<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _Q: Regarding your reply to the person who asked
about mountain vs. hill _ I've noticed other tricky pairs like
that. For example, when does a pond become a lake or a creek become
a river?
</P>
<P>
   _ Charles Wukasch
</P>
<P>
   A: Naming of ponds, lakes, streams and rivers is by local
convention. Cartographic researcher Beth Gorman of the United
States Geological Survey Earth Science Information Center reports
no volume amount defines these terms. Technically, all flowing
bodies of water are called streams (the Mississippi Stream?!).
Generally, local convention dictates creeks are smaller than
streams and rivers are larger. Q: Over the weekend my husband and I
were having a discussion of where all the cabooses are. Could you
help, please?
</P>
<P>
   _ Jennie Koch
</P>
<P>
   A: A few are still in operation, reports Robert Crossman of
