<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-COLUMN0704-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reality tv just got more realBy Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ CBS, the network that prides itself on devotion
to hard news, is loaning its morning news anchor to the latest
edition of the peeping Tom wave.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Big Brother'' debuts Wednesday at 8 p.m., the live hour
of this multi-night reality series will be hosted by Julie Chen,
who anchors the news segments on CBS's ``The Early Show.'' Not a
peep of protest has been heard, which presumably means that no one
cares that the once-blurred line between news and entertainment is
now invisible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm totally comfortable with doing it,'' Chen told USA Today.
``I look at it as an extension of my job on
</P>
<P>
   'The Early Show.' ``
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother'' is an extension of news? That thumping noise you
hear is Edward R. Murrow rolling over in his grave. People aren't
squawking about this, but they should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ill-advised, because it undermines the credibility of the
person delivering information,'' says Stephen D. Reese, chairman of
the journalism department at the University of Texas. ``Maybe it's
not something the audience is immediately aware of, but over time
the message sent is that there's no discernible difference between
entertainment and news.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' for the blissfully unaware, is the new
voyeuristic series, inspired by George Orwell's ``1984,'' that
hopes to latch on to the coattails of the blockbuster ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   The program will air in half-hour installments Monday, Tuesday
and Friday, a live hour Thursday and an hour-long recap on Saturday
throughout July. On the live editions, the 10 residents who have
been locked away in a house with 28 hidden cameras and 60
microphones will nominate two people to be evicted. Viewers will
phone in their votes for the unlucky resident. The last person left
receives $500,000 _ a pittance compared with the $1 million
awaiting the final ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen will interview the rejected ones, which is perhaps no
different from the weekly interviews ``The Morning Show'' does with
the rejects from ``Survivor'' or the ``Good Morning America'' chats
with ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire?'' winners. Except that Chen
will be out of her normal news context. Maybe that's an important
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually two sides of the same coin,'' Reese says.
``They're just using the programs to mutually reinforce each other.
There's no news there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother'' was a hit in the Netherlands, Germany and Spain
and is expected to catch fire here. Adding to the overall
creepiness is the fact that people can peek in on the house guests
24 hours a day, seven days a week via video streaming on the Web at
www.bigbrother2000.com.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY NIGHT WITH MILLER
</P>
<P>
   ABC's decision to sign politically inclined comedian Dennis
Miller to ``Monday Night Football'' is destined to be an overtime,
Super Bowl touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   It's an inspired idea that could spark a much-needed trend
toward crackling commentary in otherwise dull events. I'm thinking
Billy Graham on heavyweight boxing and Meatloaf at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Sports purists are howling that Miller will detract from the
hallowed game of football with his acid wisecracks, but ``Monday
Night Football'' is entertainment first, sports second. Just ask
the Nielsen surveyors, who say the audience on Monday nights
includes lots of viewers just looking for a good time, a miniature
demographic of the Super Bowl. Hard-core football fans are the ones
watching three games on Sunday afternoon. Maybe those games need
``serious'' announcers.
</P>
<P>
   The last time there was any spice to the commentary on ``MNF''
was when Don Meredith and Howard Cosell traded insults in the
1970s. And when Dandy Don sang ``Turn Out the Lights'' at half-time
of the lopsided games. That team disbanded in 1983 and was followed
by a string of flops that included O.J. Simpson, Joe Namath, Fran
Tarkenton, Alex Karras and Boomer Esiason.
</P>
<P>
   Placing someone totally out of context on the ``MNF'' team may
well prove to be a stroke of genius with far-reaching
repercussions. Just think of the possibilities . . .
</P>
<P>
   Eminem at the Republican National Convention. This controversial
rapper would do a fabulous job analyzing the prospects of George W.
Bush. CNN might have to bleep Em from time to time, but that would
add sparks to what might otherwise be a major snoozer. Paired with
stodgy Bernard Shaw, Eminem would provide the much-needed chemistry
to attract an audience.
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas at the Democratic National
Convention. This works on many levels. Supreme Court justices are
mysterious because they rarely speak to the media and they aren't
supposed to be political. Pair Thomas with Ted Kennedy, and you've
got a blockbuster. It wouldn't make a whit of difference if Al Gore
is stiff and boring. The commentary would be spellbinding.
</P>
<P>
   Meatloaf, commentator at large, for the Summer Olympics. Can't
you just imagine Meatloaf popping off about tiny gymnasts and
platform divers? Could he even react quickly enough to comment on
gold-medal sprinter Michael Johnson? Just parading him around in a
Peacock polo shirt would draw a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ruth and Dan Rather at the Oscars. Admit it, you've always
wanted to see these two together. Dr. Ruth may be the same size as
the statuettes, but she's got a keenly ribald sense of humor and an
oddly compelling voice. Gunga Dan, of course, spouts folksy sayings
(``Ooooo boy! That guy is all hat and no cattle!'') and sings a
mean train song. Billy Crystal would be a faded memory within
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
