<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cuban boy goes home
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Six-year-old Elian Gonzalez returned to Cuba last week
with his father after the U.S. Supreme Court cleared the way for
him to go. The court rejected the case of Elian's Miami relatives,
who wanted him to stay in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Elian and his family will stay in a government guesthouse in
Havana for a while, then return to his hometown of Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months ago, Elian's mother drowned while trying to bring
him to the United States. The boy was rescued by fishermen. He then
was caught in a battle that pitted his Cuban father, who wanted to
take him home to Cuba, against his uncle and cousins in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The situation made many Americans question which was worse _ a
boy facing life without his father or a boy facing life in
Communist Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   READING THE `BOOK OF LIFE'
</P>
<P>
   Scientists last week announced that they had cracked 99 percent
of the human genetic code and should complete the ``book of life''
within the next couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has thousands of genes that dictate how their bodies
function and even what diseases they may get. In essence, our genes
are the instruction booklets for our lives.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists hope that understanding the genetic code will lead to
cures or new treatments for illnesses such as diabetes, Alzheimer's
disease and cancer. But it may take decades for scientists to
figure out just how to use everything they've learned.
</P>
<P>
   ROCKER RETURNS TO N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Braves pitcher John Rocker (above) faced a roar of boos
and dodged a few thrown objects as he raced onto the field at Shea
Stadium last week to face the New York Mets on their home turf. The
Braves had not played in New York since Rocker months ago made ugly
statements about New Yorkers, minorities, foreigners and
homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker quieted the crowd a little by pitching well. Before
Thursday's game, the left-hander apologized again for what he had
said.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case, though, the New York Police Department sent about
700 officers to the game to keep the crowd from getting too unruly.
</P>
<P>
   BYE-BYE, PLAIN M&AMP;MS
</P>
<P>
   The M&AMP;M/Mars candy company has decided that the name ``Plain''
just doesn't do justice to their original M&AMP;Ms. So the little round
chocolate treats are getting a new name: ``Milk Chocolate'' M&AMP;Ms.
</P>
<P>
   The company has begun putting packages with the new name in
stores. It also is airing TV ads featuring a plain red M&AMP;M calling
itself a ``Milk Chocolate'' M&AMP;M.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
