r k BC-COMMENTARY-BJT04-COX     07-03 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENTARY-BJT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday, July 4 and Wednesday, July 5,
2000 are moving today to clients of the New York Times News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN04 _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Well, folks, there's some
good news and some bad news. You'll have to decide for yourself
which is which. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED FOR TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ A year ago, we were a state
full of dumb kids and bad schools.
</P>
<P>
   No more. Florida has become one big Lake Wobegone, a place where
all the children and their schools are above average. How did our
kids get so smart so fast? (And if they did, how come they still
look like that?) Are their classes smaller? Are their teachers
better paid and trained? Is their curriculum more meaningful? Are
kids getting more individual attention? Did everyone get books they
could take home? Of course not, silly. (Lane, Daytona Beach
News-Journal) MOVED FOR TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ The story of the new guy and Mangy Bill just
goes to show that boys will be boys _ and that's not always
easy.The story of the new guy and Mangy Bill just goes to show that
boys will be boys _ and that's not always easy. (JoeMurray, Cox
News Service). MOVED FOR TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Tom Teepen says that third-party candidate Ralph
Nader's contention that there is no difference between the two
major parties is likely to have the negative effect of increasing
voter apathy. (Teepen, Cox News Service.) MOVED MONDAY FOR
WEDNESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Its natural resources diminished, its economy
bankrupt, its politics clouded and its people impoverished, Haiti
has become an easy conduit for the Colombian drug trade.
Transferring drugs might just be the country's leading industry.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED MONDAY FOR WEDNESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN05 _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ For one brief and shining
Camelot moment, before the numbness of sleep has washed from my
awareness, all's right in a perfect world. ``Mee-owww,'' a small
voice calls from the doorway to my porch. I roll over for a look.
Biddy, my 11-year-old Siamese sits daintily on the threshold
awaiting our morning chat _ lopsided though it may be. I tell her
I'll be there in a minute and invite her into the hammock for a
snuggle. She refuses and chatters on.(Schuett, Cox News Service)
EMBARGOED FOR WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ John Young is on vacation. His column will resume
shortly.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS, LAYOUTS and GRAPHICS CoxNet layouts are for sale over
the web, through the New York Times News Service's PageExpress
service, at http://nytsyn.com/syndicate/pageex.
</P>
<P>
   If a budget line or story is marked with photos or graphics,
those are available from the New York Times News Service at
212-556-4204. Or call CoxNet for more information at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO REACH US
</P>
<P>
   Questions should be directed to CoxNet, the Cox News Service, in
Atlanta at 404-526-5456. We are staffed 8 a.m. to 10 p.m.
Monday-Friday, and 1-10 p.m. on weekends and holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The day news editor is Tom Oder, 404-526-5887,
toder(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   The night news editor is Todd C. Duncan, 404-582-7282,
tduncan(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338, artd(at)coxnews.com
</P>
