<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1800 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-GENOME-CHEERS'N'FEARS     07-03 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOME-CHEERS'N'FEARS-ECONOMIST-650&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD SCIENCE, EVIL MEN: GENOME TRIUMPH CALLS FOR CAUTION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE 2 trims, 325 wds; 1,275 uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 950-word (trimmed) material from The
New York Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (NOTE: TWO OPTIONAL TRIMS, TOTALING 325 WORDS; 1,275 WORDS UNCUT)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   One of Alice's adventures in Wonderland takes the form of a
race. When it is over, she asks who has won. ``Everybody has won,''
the judge, a dodo, replies, ``and all must have prizes.''
</P>
<P>
   The race to sequence the human genome _ or, rather, to claim the
credit for sequencing it _ is now over. It is time to declare
victory and get back to work.
</P>
<P>
   So the White House's dodo-in-chief, Bill Clinton, has duly
awarded prizes to everybody. There are prizes for the leaders of
the Human Genome Project, the publicly-funded entry in the race.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a prize for Craig Venter, the entrepreneurial
scientist who fired the shot that turned what had been a leisurely
stroll into a contest in the first place, by founding a company
called Celera Genomics to do the whole thing with private money.
</P>
<P>
   The prizes to the public project's scientists are the pretense
that the race was actually a tie, and that a commercial upstart
that is barely two years old did not really beat them to it.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Venter's prize is the officially sanctioned respectability
that should give him a place on the invitation list (traditionally
limited to three people) to receive a Nobel award for medicine from
the hands of the King of Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Undeniably, the unravelling of the full sequence of the human
genome _ a list, in order, of the chemical bases that encode the
information needed to assemble and run a human body _ is a
scientific wonder.
</P>
<P>
   It is not diminished by the fact that what have been announced
are ``draft'' sequences, and that dotting every genetic ``i'' and
crossing every ``t'' will actually take years.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it diminished by the fact that this particular race was
not to the finishing-post, but to the starting-line. Knowing the
sequence is really just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The actual benefits will come from the hard graft of
interpreting the data and coming up with uses for them. Those
benefits will be real, and may be spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Genomic knowledge, of humans and other species, will transform
medicine by introducing side-effect-free drugs that work first
time, expanding the range of diseases that are treatable and
refining diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   If allowed, it could transform agriculture by increasing the
nutritional value of crops and making them easier to grow. Even
industry should benefit, as microbes are harnessed to produce
chemicals that are currently either impossible, or too costly, to
make.
</P>
<P>
   And at a more elevated level, the biological knowledge generated
will enhance understanding of what, exactly, it means to be human.
</P>
<P>
   When triumphalism is in the air, however, it is always wise to
pause. These new technologies create extraordinary possibilities
that people find disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   Many such fears, perhaps most, will prove unwarranted; and the
astounding benefits that this new technology is capable of
delivering are not to be cast away without good reason. But caution
is appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   The genome revolution will move the world into places that are
ethically, as well as scientifically, uncharted. That people are
nervous about genomic technology is obvious from the reaction in
Europe, and increasingly in America, to genetically modified crops.
</P>
<P>
   All the scientific evidence suggests that these are harmless to
people and no more harmful to the environment than more traditional
methods of farming. Yet a few uses of the ``F'' word
(``Frankenstein,'' not the other one) in newspaper headlines have
supermarkets clearing their shelves and activists clearing fields.
</P>
<P>
   If that sort of reaction greets the idea of plants that have had
single genes for things such as herbicide resistance transferred
into them, what will be the response to more heavily engineered
plants and animals?
</P>
<P>
   Quite apart from fears about health, which will probably
diminish if research continues to show them to be unfounded, there
is the question of what happens if something runs wild. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 150 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 650) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The risk that this may happen needs to be faced _ provided it is
also remembered that no technology is entirely safe and that the
most it makes sense to demand is that the risks are understood and
kept low.
</P>
<P>
   Any new organism will be designed for the cosseted environment
of farm or fermentation tank, not the big, bad world where
everything is trying to eat you or steal your food. But things can
go wrong, as with the spread of prickly pear in Australia early
last century or zebra mussels in the North American Great Lakes at
the moment.
</P>
<P>
   A sensible risk assessment therefore needs to ask, in each case,
how bad could things be if the worst happens?
</P>
<P>
   More dangerous, however, than the inadvertent spread of
genetically engineered species is the risk that somebody will use
the technology to do deliberate harm _ by building better
pathogens, for example. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Those who worry about Saddam Hussein cloning himself using the
new technology should probably worry more about what he is cloning
in his country's germ-warfare laboratories. That is because knowing
the human genome, and knowing the genomes of numerous pathogens, it
might be possible to re-engineer the latter so that the former
cannot resist.
</P>
<P>
   Against this threat there are only two defenses. One is the
eternal vigilance of the intelligence services of civilized
governments. The second is the creation of laboratories that could
analyze a threat rapidly and respond to it with a treatment using
the same technological nous that created the threat in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   For many, though, the real ``F'' nightmare is tinkering with
human genes in egg and sperm cells, or in recently fertilized eggs.
</P>
<P>
   This might be done for the best of motives _ to prevent disease.
But it might also be done for motives that some people, at least,
would regard as more suspect, such as slowing the process of aging;
or for motives that make most people, at present, very
uncomfortable, such as making your child more intelligent, or
better-looking, or more sociable.
</P>
<P>
   Quite possibly, parents will one day be able to equip their
children with capacities that are currently inhuman.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing lines across this squirming territory is going to be
difficult. What is ``natural'' is no guide. Man has already left
nature far behind, thank heaven: open-heart surgery is
``unnatural.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 175 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 1,050) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Morally, it is straightforward to put state-sponsored eugenics,
at least, utterly beyond the pale. At the moment, however, many
governments extend sweeping prohibition of genetic interventions to
individual parents, as well.
</P>
<P>
   For now, that seems sensible and cautious. But if the technology
proves reliable in other animals, pressure will grow for the bans
to be relaxed _ and it might then be wise to relax them, at least
in part.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, it might be right to shift the burden of proof from
individuals who wish to use these technologies to governments that
wish to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   It is at least imaginable that, in a liberal regime, the sum of
individual parental decisions might, for example, reduce genetic
diversity in undesirable ways. And governments, which rightly act
against child abuse, would be right to act against ``genetic''
child abuse in the unlikely event that perverse parents began
adding damaging genes to their children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,275) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, though, if human genetic engineering looks safe
for the humans who are engineered, a light hand of regulation will
in the end be most appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Nanny may sometimes know best. Big Brother rarely does. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
