r k BC-GREEN-PARTYANIMALS-EC     07-03 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREEN-PARTYANIMALS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED, WHITE AND GREEN: TEAMSTERS AND TURTLES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 500-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   DENVER, COLO. _ Thank God for Greens. Amid the general po-faced
seriousness of American politics, here is a party that doesn't dare
to be dull.
</P>
<P>
   One pony-tailed would-be presidential candidate from Tennessee
says that he hasn't smoked pot with Al Gore for a long time.
Another, Jello Biafra, wants a maximum wage _ around $200,000, he
thought, should suffice _ and the abolition of both the CIA and
sports-utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates in formal evening wear carried placards saying
``Billionaires for Bush and Gore. We bought the election so you
don't have to.''
</P>
<P>
   And, turning to serious business, the platform calls for a
30-hour working week, the decriminalization of marijuana and
proportional representation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Greens had 43 elected officials in 13 states. This
year, the figure is 78 in 19 states. California's Green Party has
over 100,000 members, the largest single green party (they claim)
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Blithely ignoring the petty detail that he is not actually a
member of their party, the Greens' presidential candidate is Ralph
Nader, the celebrated consumer advocate, protectionist and
Economist contributor. (Yes, he once wrote a series of articles for
us on car safety but he has since grown up and condemns capitalism
utterly.)
</P>
<P>
   After the WTO rumpus in Seattle and the McCain insurgency, the
timing might be ripe for an anti-globalization independent. But
third-party surges have a way of looking good in June and petering
out in November.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ross Perot's 19 percent of the vote in the 1992 election
was disappointing compared with what might have been: in June he
had been leading the polls. And this time Pat Buchanan's Reform
Party is also competing for independents.
</P>
<P>
   For the Greens, electoral success means getting 5 percent of the
vote, enough to secure federal funding next time around. Their best
cards are Nader's name and the notion of a ``blue-green'' alliance
between blue-collar workers worried about competition from cheap
labor abroad and environmentalists worried about trees.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance of Teamsters and Turtles can work. The leader of
the Green Party of Gary, Indiana (one of America's biggest steel
towns) runs it from the offices of the local steelworkers' union.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Green Party was founded last year in the Houston
headquarters of the AFL-CIO after the two sides had teamed up
against a firm that had offended Greens by felling redwoods and the
union by locking out aluminium workers.
</P>
<P>
   And much of the Green platform, with its support for union
rights and a more generous social safety net, looks close to that
of a European socialist party.
</P>
<P>
   What about the idea that the unions are only supporting his
turquoise alliance to discipline Gore? Nader replies that he will
attract voters away from George W. Bush as well.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he will mobilize the 50 percent of Americans who do not
vote at all. If so, that would be a miracle. But nothing else has
got them to the polls. Perhaps some populist business-bashing
will. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
