r k BC-BUSHGORE-SUPREMECOURT     07-03 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSHGORE-SUPREMECOURT-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW WILL NEXT PRESIDENT IMPACT SUPREME COURT?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 875-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The nine justices of the Supreme Court are famously
shy of the limelight, yet their dramatic timing is impeccable.
</P>
<P>
   They like to announce their most politically contentious
decisions on the very last day of their nine-month term and then go
off on vacation, leaving a swirl of controversy behind them.
</P>
<P>
   This year, they turned in a vintage performance. On June 28, in
four split rulings, the court overturned a Nebraska law banning
so-called ``partial-birth'' abortions, upheld a law restricting
anti-abortion protests, allowed taxpayers' money to be used to buy
computers for religious schools, and ruled that the Boy Scouts can
exclude gays.
</P>
<P>
   Two days earlier, it had upheld the famous Miranda warning to
criminal suspects (``You have the right to remain silent...''),
overturned a referendum result allowing voters in California to
cast a vote in any political party's primary, and knocked down a
New Jersey hate-crime law which gave too much sentencing power to
judges rather than juries.
</P>
<P>
   This week's judicial fireworks capped a term littered with
attention-grabbing cases. It coincided with a presidential election
year.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, this has highlighted the question: how much impact
can the next president have on the direction of the court? A lot,
is the most widely held view.
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Tribe, a professor at Harvard Law School, points out
that both candidates have promised to add more conservative and
liberal justices respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The most vulnerable ruling could be Roe v Wade, the
controversial 1973 decision which guaranteed American women the
right to an abortion. ``It might take three appointments to
overturn Roe, but even just one could undermine it,'' says Tribe.
</P>
<P>
   A great deal, then, seems to depend on how many justices (and
which ones) retire in the next four years. No one has retired since
1994, and several justices have had serious health problems,
including Chief Justice William Rehnquist, 75.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the nine are Republican appointees, and so might be
less willing to be replaced by Al Gore than by George W. Bush. But
with eight justices over 60, nature may intervene anyway.
</P>
<P>
   And yet there are reasons to doubt that appointments by the next
president, whoever he is, will matter as much as people suppose.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is the current character of the court. The Rehnquist
court is often described as sharply divided, with a narrow
conservative majority, largely because of a series of 5-4 votes on
federalism, affirmative action, religion and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The inflammatory language of dissenting opinions written by
justices in the minority has often bolstered this impression. In a
scathing dissent from the Miranda decision, Justice Antonin Scalia
seemed to threaten civil disobedience by continuing to apply the
law the court had just knocked down.
</P>
<P>
   And yet such overheated rhetoric is somewhat misleading. Most
closely contested cases have been over relatively narrow
differences of opinion about how to apply earlier court precedents
to new situations.
</P>
<P>
   The Rehnquist court has not overturned major laws or signalled a
sharp change of direction for the nation, as the 1960s Warren court
did. It was not supposed to be this way.
</P>
<P>
   In their five appointments, Presidents Ronald Reagan and George
Bush consciously set out to make the court more conservative. But
three of their appointees, Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony Kennedy and
David Souter, have proved to be fairly moderate.
</P>
<P>
   The court's most consistent line of decisions has aimed at
restricting federal power in favor of states' rights, and it has
chipped away some of the civil-liberties protections. But it has
moved with comparative caution even in doing this.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone applauds the court's pragmatism. Douglas Kmiec, a
law professor at Pepperdine University in California and a former
Reagan administration official, complains that the court has once
again ``delivered the expected, common-sensical outcomes without
paying attention to the demands of the Constitution or its
history.''
</P>
<P>
   This may suit most Americans, but it turns the court into a
third legislative chamber. ``If arguments are not anchored in
constitutional argument, it becomes almost a lawless process,'' he
argues.
</P>
<P>
   In his view conservative justices such as Scalia, who claim to
adhere strictly to the text of the Constitution, are as guilty of
ad hoc rationales as the ``liberal'' justices. The result has made
the court's decisions difficult to predict.
</P>
<P>
   This term, for example, has seen Stephen Breyer, a
Clinton-appointee, lecturing Justice Kennedy, a Reagan-appointee,
on why soft-core pornography should not be delivered unfiltered
into homes via cable-television.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice Rehnquist, long a fierce critic of the Miranda
decision, wrote this week's opinion upholding it.
</P>
<P>
   And Justice Scalia, a strong supporter of the court's
states-rights agenda, wrote the opinion knocking down California's
primary system which many _ including the two dissenting justices
who have consistently opposed expanding states' rights _ thought
was preeminently a matter for the states.
</P>
<P>
   The intellectual incoherence, as well as political moderation,
of the court could make it more difficult for the next president to
push it sharply in any one direction, at least with only one or two
appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, given their centrist positions, neither Bush nor Gore
may want to risk a bruising confirmation battle for a controversial
appointee. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
