<HEADER>
A1807 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-DOT.COM-DEMOCRACY-ECO     07-03 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOT.COM-DEMOCRACY-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALAS, POLITICIANS CAN'T PRESS THE FLESH IN CYBERSPACE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 1,100-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Politics has few rules, especially in an election
year. But here is one: it generally lags commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 19th century, party bosses paid the ultimate
compliment to the brand-new system of industrial mass-production by
inventing ``machine politics.'' Now that commercial America is in
love with the Internet, when will that, too, turn politics upside
down?
</P>
<P>
   The arguments for sooner rather than later are not difficult to
make. The proportion of the voting-age population with Internet
access will hit 70 percent by election day.
</P>
<P>
   This wired world includes the vast majority of the people that
politicians drool over _ those with a high propensity not just to
vote but also to volunteer time and money.
</P>
<P>
   A traditional direct-mail pitch costs 30 to 40 cents per address
and yields a response rate of 1 percent to 1.5 percent. Targeted
banner ads on the Web have a similar yield for a dime or less. And
it is generally easier to get the people you want.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the old mailshots which ask raving right-wing
libertarians to give generously to Hillary Rodham Clinton. (``I'll
fight my heart out for the values you and I share.'')
</P>
<P>
   Now computers allow politicians to talk only to people who are
reasonably susceptible to their blandishments.
</P>
<P>
   Wistful politicians talk of reinventing the old face-to-face
politics of wards and precincts on a new basis: not the accident of
geography, but the glue of common interests and aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet gold rush is spreading to politics. All you need is
a moderately catchy name (vote.com, voter.com, speakout.com); a
moderately well-known political figure (Susan Molinari, Randy Tate
and Michael Deaver have all been recruited by start-ups on the
grounds that somebody, somewhere knows who they are); and a
moderately clever gimmick (attracting visitors to Web sites that
specialize in politics and then selling their names to candidates,
or selling ``campaign starter-kits'').
</P>
<P>
   Then you too can turn democracy into a money-spinner. But before
you rush to buy shares in one of these start-ups, it is worth
remembering one awkward fact.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's presidential race, the people who have made the
biggest fuss about the Internet have all got one thing in common:
they're losers.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes predicated his entire campaign on the assumption
that the Internet would redefine politics in much the same way that
television did in the 1950s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   He launched his campaign on the Internet, employed five
full-time staffers to work on his Web site, invented something
called the ``e-Precinct,'' which encouraged supporters to enroll
friends in ``e-Blocks'' and ``e-Neighborhoods,'' and even held
virtual fund-raisers, featuring private e-chats with the man
himself.
</P>
<P>
   He got just two delegates. John Kasich, another Republican,
styled himself as the ``JFK of the information age'' and maintained
such a sophisticated Web site that voters from Iowa, New Hampshire
and Ohio got different pages when they logged on. They didn't vote
for him, though.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley and John McCain had, by common consent, much better
Internet operations than the party machines that crushed them.
</P>
<P>
   The party that is currently making the most fuss about the
Internet is the Reform Party. Its members will be able to vote for
their presidential candidates online (which might save the world a
few punch-ups).
</P>
<P>
   One of the candidates for the job, John Hagelin of the Natural
Law Party, assures the world that the Internet will break the mold
of traditional politics. The establishment candidates are far more
cautious.
</P>
<P>
   With George W. Bush, this might be expected. But Al Gore, a man
whose idea of bliss is reading position papers on ``government in a
networked world,'' runs a Web site that is less professional than
his rival's.
</P>
<P>
   They have dabbled in ``electronic town halls.'' They have even
engaged in (rather tame) e-mail wars.
</P>
<P>
   In general, they have used the Internet as a means of speeding
up old-fashioned political combat rather than a means of changing
the rules of engagement. Thus they post plenty of useful
information. (It is particularly nice to be able to search position
papers and, in Bush's case, get up-to-date lists of donors.)
</P>
<P>
   They get volunteers to sign up (100,000 for Bush). But they shy
away from driving the political debate. Which is exactly as it
should be.
</P>
<P>
   For both candidates have grasped what eluded the cerebral
Forbes: that even in a country as big and wired as the United
States, politics is still about pressing the flesh rather than
personalized e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   As Joe Klein put it in his 1992 political novel, ``Primary
Colors'': ``The handshake is the threshold act, the beginning of
politics... He (i.e., President Bill Clinton) is interested in you.
He is honored to meet you... He'll flash that famous misty look of
his. And he will mean it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no substitute for the personal touch if you are going
to convert people to your cause. Presidents Kennedy and Reagan
moved hearts with the force of their rhetoric. Bill Clinton seduced
normally cynical journalists into becoming shameless apologists.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's success in raising more than $6 million online is
certainly impressive. But what really made his campaign was the
months he spent talking to ordinary voters in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   There is also no substitute for the personal touch when it comes
to mobilizing your political base.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Gore have raised about $1.6 million online _ a
paltry sum compared with the $21.3 million that Bush raised at a
dinner in Washington on April 26, or the $26.5 million that Clinton
and Gore raised at a blue-jeans rally there a month later.
</P>
<P>
   The very least you want if you are going to part with serious
money is a good dinner. That is not to say that the Internet is a
mere irrelevance. As the television and the computer merge, more
personality will be able to seep into the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Internet is wonderful at giving a vent to the angry
or a voice to the powerless. In 1998, with barely any effort, a
California couple accumulated $13 million and 500,000 signatures
when they pledged to stop Clinton's impeachment. Zack Exley's spoof
Web site, www.gwbush.com, has infuriated the governor as much as
anything else in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One day, as the technology improves, it may even produce the
fabled world of electronic wards and precincts. But for the time
being, at least, the handshake is still far more potent than the
Web page. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
