<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-JITTERS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NERVOUS NAIL-BITING GRIPS MEXICAN VOTERS, MARKETS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for Mexico's JULY 2 Election)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 450-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The last four presidential terms have ended in
economic turbulence, but this time it is going to be different. So
Mexican officials have sworn and, until recently, investors had
believed them.
</P>
<P>
   But a bout of nerves that began last month seems to be
worsening. This week the peso fell, briefly, to its lowest since
February 1999, and the central bank, worried about inflation,
tightened monetary policy slightly.
</P>
<P>
   The jitters were ostensibly triggered by worries that the result
of the presidential election on July 2 will be both close and
disputed. But investors have been uneasy for a while.
</P>
<P>
   When Moody's, a credit-rating agency, announced in March that it
was awarding investment-grade status to Mexican bonds, the premium
these yield over United States Treasury bonds fell for only a few
days before rising again.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just political uncertainty that is to blame. Investors
are worried about the effect on Mexico of a hard landing in the
United States, which takes 90 percent of its exports.
</P>
<P>
   And Mexico's economy is showing signs of overheating: GDP grew
at an annual rate of 7.9 percent in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Officials point out that this is partly because of strong
American demand for Mexico's exports. But cynics detect a typical
pre-election boom, engineered partly by higher government spending:
buoyed by higher oil revenues, this increased by 15 percent in real
terms in the first quarter compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales are racing ahead, too, boosted by higher real
wages. All that points to a slowdown after the election.
</P>
<P>
   But the odds are still against a 1994-style crash. The peso's
fall is not yet alarming: indeed, it was (and perhaps still is)
overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the economy President Ernesto Zedillo will bequeath
to his successor on Dec. 1 is far sounder than the one he
inherited: the current-account deficit is much smaller, there is
almost no short-term foreign debt, the floating peso gives
flexibility, and management is more open.
</P>
<P>
   Officials expect growth to slow to 5-6 percent for the year as a
whole. But that slowdown could still be bruising, if, say, Mexico
was unlucky enough to suffer post-election political turmoil, a
crash in oil revenue, and a sudden cooling in American demand.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the handover of power from one president to the
next, rather than the election itself, has been the trigger for
Mexico's economic eruptions. But this year, for the first time, the
election result is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   History is not doomed to repeat itself in Mexico, but officials
and investors alike will need to remain vigilant for the next few
months. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
