<HEADLINE>
EPIC `BATTLE FOR ELIAN' ENDS. NOW, ABOUT THAT EMBARGO...  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 600-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   HAVANA _ Fidel Castro might have won his Battle for Elian, the
six-year-old boy shipwrecked off Florida last November, who finally
returned to Cuba with his father on June 28. But his hopes that
this victory would prompt bigger changes in American policy towards
Cuba seem premature.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in the United States' House of
Representatives agreed this week to a plan that would allow sales
of food and medicine to Cuba. But this apparent easing of America's
trade embargo comes with so many conditions attached that Castro's
officials dismissed it as ``a great joke which would in practice
change nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   How quickly the proposal will become law is not clear. On paper,
it is the biggest change in the embargo since it was imposed in
1960. Some supporters of the measure believe it heralds the further
gradual easing of American policy towards Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But under the new proposal, Cuba will not have access to private
or public credit from the United States to finance any purchases;
and barter, a common Cuban trading method, will not be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Transport will be difficult and expensive, since any ships
visiting the island will still be banned from putting into a United
States' port during the following six months.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also bans the purchase of any Cuban goods by
American firms, and potentially stiffens the ban on United States'
citizens visiting Cuba by turning this from an administrative
ruling into a law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only does it not soften the blockade, in some aspects it
makes it worse,'' said Ricardo Alarcon, the president of Cuba's
National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Since Cuba is desperately short of hard currency, it is unlikely
to be able to buy much food or medicine on the proposed terms
(although American firms may eventually find ways around this).
</P>
<P>
   Any strengthening of the travel ban, however, could hurt Cuba's
economy. Tourism is now the island's biggest industry, and tens of
thousands of Americans have visited the country illegally over the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   Only a month ago, Cuban officials were speculating that the
fight over Elian would herald a real easing of the trade embargo,
and perhaps the lifting of the travel ban.
</P>
<P>
   That was because it seemed to show that the leaders of Miami's
exile community, who pushed for the boy to stay, were out of touch
with mainstream American opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the congressional deal shows that the Cuban-American lobby
still has political weight. In effect, the Cuban-Americans have
blocked a push by business lobbies for more open trade with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Many businessmen argue that the embargo has been ineffective at
toppling Castro, but effective at excluding them from a market
dominated, as a result, by European and Canadian rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Now that America has agreed to normal trading relations with
China, the United States Chamber of Commerce is to make eliminating
the Cuba embargo its top priority, said Craig Johnstone, its
vice-president, during a visit to Havana last month.
</P>
<P>
   But neither George W. Bush nor Al Gore seem to agree: to
Castro's annoyance, both candidates have sided with Miami over both
Elian and the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   For the past four decades, Castro's main objective has been
political survival. The fact that Congress and the Clinton
administration are at last discussing the embargo is being
portrayed in his government's propaganda as evidence of Cuba's
``power of resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   But the upshot of that discussion suggests that Congress is only
slightly more likely than Castro to start blinking. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
