<SLUG> BC-WORLDCOM-DISCONNECT-ECONOMIST-700&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I'M SORRY, WE'RE UNABLE TO CONNECT YOUR MERGER. PLEASE DON'T TRY
AGAIN'  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (NOTE: Story can stand in 700; 1,050 words uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 700-word (trimmed) material from The
New York Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (NOTE: STORY CAN STAND ALONE IN 700 WORDS; TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,050.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Live by the sword, die by the sword.
</P>
<P>
   In less than two decades, Bernie Ebbers made his way from
small-time motels to big-time telecoms, eventually controlling a
third of America's long-distance calling and nearly as much of its
Internet traffic.
</P>
<P>
   He built this empire with a classic new economy strategy of
buying real assets with virtual money, in this case shares pumped
high by stock market enthusiasm for his company, WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   Last year he crowned his run with a deal that was then the
biggest in history: a $115 billion bid for Sprint, America's
third-largest long-distance carrier and perhaps its best wireless
firm.
</P>
<P>
   But, on June 27, the streak ended: Sprint was one acquisition
too many. Both America's Department of Justice (DOJ) and the
European Union's regulatory authorities moved to block the deal on
competition grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Although both Sprint and WorldCom are officially keeping their
options open, the merger is dead.
</P>
<P>
   For the DOJ, the problem boiled down to simple arithmetic: it
reckoned that it was bad for competition to move from three big
long-distance firms to two.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, the stated objection was to the unhealthy
concentration that would arise from combining the Internet
operations of WorldCom and Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the European regulators may have been reacting more to
the shabby way WorldCom behaved in acquiring MCI.
</P>
<P>
   It first promised to spin off some MCI Internet holdings to
Cable &AMP; Wireless to satisfy regulatory concerns, and then did so in
such a halfhearted way (it stole back employees and kept customers)
that the British firm had to take it to court (C&AMP;W settled for $200
million).
</P>
<P>
   Big companies on buying sprees run into antitrust issues all the
time. But this is different. Ebbers is a serial buyer like no
other.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade he has bought nearly 70 companies,
including several larger than his own. MCI, then America's
second-largest long-distance firm, was three times WorldCom's size
when the upstart bought it with stock in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   From its base in Clinton, Miss., WorldCom snapped up fiber-optic
networks, Internet infrastructure, data services, calling-card
firms and local telecom carriers, emerging as one of the world's
leading Internet carriers and business telecoms suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Not for nothing did Ebbers call his first yacht ``Aquasitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebbers argued (as he would, of course) that the deal was good
for competition. Certainly, in a business where the price of
long-distance calling may soon reach zero (in part because of a
swarm of smaller competitors, including free Internet calling
services), the harm to consumers of reducing big long-distance
firms from three to two may be limited.
</P>
<P>
   Upstarts, such as Qwest, are well capitalized, while the
remaining Baby Bells should soon be entering the market in force.
Bell Atlantic already has nearly 1 million long-distance customers
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   There is also plenty of competition (and money to create new
competition) in Internet infrastructure, the area that worried the
EU.
</P>
<P>
   But the regulators' real concerns went deeper. After MCI,
regulators on both sides of the Atlantic had simply seen enough
megamergers for now, especially from the cowboy from Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't come back soon with another big one like this,'' one had
reportedly warned Ebbers in the wake of the MCI deal. Yet a year
later he did exactly that with Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the regulators saw in the WorldCom-MCI
deal echoes of a reanimated Ma Bell, the end-to-end monopolist that
they had broken up in 1984 after years of painful litigation. In
Europe, too, WorldCom was simply seen as an untrustworthy predator.
</P>
<P>
   Although both sets of regulators highlighted aspects of the deal
that they disliked, the list of parts that WorldCom would have had
to spin off (at less than preferential terms, given such a forced
sale) was impracticably long.
</P>
<P>
   Until the last days there was talk of wholesale divestitures,
from long distance to local networks, to allow the deal through.
But WorldCom decided that they would have undermined the merger's
financial logic and left the table. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 700, OR CONTINUE TO 1,050) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT NEXT FOR WORLDCOM? &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom's core competence is buying other companies and making
more of their assets than their previous owners did. Now, it can no
longer simply buy its way to the top. It needs a new strategy. But
what?
</P>
<P>
   For a start, Ebbers could still buy other firms, provided they
were smaller and did not overlap much with its existing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom still needs wireless; Sprint's digital PCS network had
been that company's main attraction. Other wireless firms, such as
Nextel and Voicetel, are still available. But WorldCom decided last
year that Nextel was too expensive; since then Nextel's market
value has doubled while WorldCom's has shrunk, making it dearer
still.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, WorldCom could expand more abroad, especially in
markets and businesses where it is not yet strong. Or it could
change tack, seeking to increase revenues more from its operations
than from acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom has always been a better operating company than it was
given credit for; some of its acquisitions, especially MCI's
consumer business, were actually a drag on earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom now talks of shedding its consumer long-distance
business, which is both slower-growing than the rest of its
operations and an antitrust obstacle, and focusing on the more
lucrative business market.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point every company has to be about execution instead
of just acquisition,'' says Richard Klugman, an analyst with
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, an investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it could turn from predator to prey. There are plenty
of potential buyers, including European firms such as Deutsche
Telekom, France Telecom and BT.
</P>
<P>
   This week Deutsche Telekom, which has previously expressed an
interest in WorldCom, completed a bond issue that raised $14.5
billion; it also recently won shareholder approval to use shares
valued at $100 billion for acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   It is more likely, however, that the German firm, which believes
it needs to do a big deal in America, will now go for Sprint. It
already has a 10 percent stake and knows the company well from the
recently dissolved Global One alliance that included France
Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   None of which is likely to make life any easier for Ebbers or
his company. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
