<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEOWNERS-CLINIC-POPMECH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMEOWNERS CLINIC Q&AMP;A 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 By NORMAN BECKER, P.E. 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COVERING OLD VINYL FLOORING
</P>
<P>
   Q: The house I bought has two bathrooms, and I want to put new
vinyl flooring in them. I'm not sure if the old vinyl has asbestos,
or even whether that matters, but in any case I would like to know
how to go over the top of the old vinyl.
</P>
<P>
   _ Martin Cleary, Lewes, Del.
</P>
<P>
   A: As long as you cover the existing vinyl, it doesn't matter if
it contains asbestos. However, manufacturers don't recommend
covering over more than one layer of vinyl flooring. In that case,
manufacturers recommend removal. Then the presence of asbestos
becomes a concern. Unless you're certain that the vinyl flooring
does not contain asbestos, for safety's sake you should assume that
it does.
</P>
<P>
   Asbestos in vinyl products is non-friable (that is, when it is
dry, it cannot be crumbled, pulverized or reduced to powder by hand
pressure). But some removal practices like grinding or sanding can
cause the particles to become airborne.
</P>
<P>
   If you have to remove the floor, get a copy of a booklet
published by the Resilient Flooring Institute, ``Recommended Work
Practices For Removal Of Resilient Floor Coverings.'' Write the
Institute at 401 E. Jefferson St., Suite 102, Rockville, Md.,
20850. You can also request it by sending a fax to 301-340-7283,
but please don't call with your request.
</P>
<P>
   If the existing vinyl flooring consists of a single layer, you
can cover over it as long as it is well bonded. The vinyl should be
cleaned, and any surface finish such as wax must be removed by wet
stripping only. If the vinyl is textured or embossed, you should
use an embossing leveler to fill in and smooth out the surface.
Another option is to cover the floor with quarter-inch-thick
plywood, and then apply the flooring.
</P>
<P>
   TREATING SOUTHERN PINE
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to stain my new Southern yellow pine deck. Should I
first apply a water-repellent preservative?
</P>
<P>
   _ Joann Crews, Thomasville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: You can apply a water-repellent preservative, often referred
to as WRP, or a semitransparent stain, but you should not apply
both because an application of WRP will inhibit the absorption of
the stain. Besides, many semitransparent deck stains are
water-repellent preservatives with a small amount of pigment added
to give them color. These products will be absorbed by the deck,
and will inhibit mildew growth and prevent water from soaking into
the deck.
</P>
<P>
   It's important not to apply a stain that is more heavily tinted
than a semitransparent type. However, you can apply heavily
pigmented stains on vertical surfaces, such as handrail balusters.
People apply solid stains to their decks but are usually
disappointed when the finish performs poorly. Research by wood
technologists and finish chemists indicates that heavily pigmented
stains don't perform well on horizontal wood surfaces that are
exposed to the weather.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW: BACKUP POWER INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   Many homeowners are left in the dark when electricity is
disrupted because they feel owning a generator is a hassle they can
do without. They'd rather take their chances or tough it out when
the lights go out.
</P>
<P>
   There is a backup power alternative to generators: A bank of
12-volt batteries that supply current through an inverter/charger.
When the system supplies current, the inverter converts the
batteries' direct current into 120 volts of alternating current.
When the system is operating in standby mode, the charger maintains
the batteries.
</P>
<P>
   These systems are designed to come on automatically and quickly
enough to prevent the loss of computer data. Incidentally, it's not
some weird idea cooked up by the battery companies. Various forms
of the method have been used for years.
</P>
<P>
   Trace Engineering offers literature that explains how its
systems provide low-maintenance backup power from an
inverter/charger-battery system. Generally speaking, you would use
this system to power a computer, lights, a refrigerator, a water
pump, and gas or oil-fired heating systems. Appliances that need
more current require a backup generator.
</P>
<P>
   Trace designs its systems so that generators can be integrated
into them. We were surprised to learn, however, that even without a
generator, some of these systems are capable of producing thousands
of watts for hours at a time.
</P>
<P>
   To get an information packet, write Trace Engineering, 5916
195th St. N.E., Arlington, Wash., 98223, or visit the company's Web
site at www.traceengineering.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Roy Berendsohn.
</P>
