<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: An illustration of diesel-powered electric generator, an
illustration of an early primate and a photo of seedlings in a gene
splicing lab are available by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.)
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHARKS REALLY DO GET CANCER
</P>
<P>
   The foundation of the ``cartilage pill'' industry, the notion
that sharks don't get cancer, has been shaken by a new study
presented at a recent meeting of the American Association for
Cancer Research.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting on recent research, Gary Ostrander, of Johns Hopkins
University, said that sharks, skates and rays really do get the
disease. ``People are out there taking shark cartilage pills based
on very faulty data and no preventative studies to show that it
works,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   HARVESTING ELECTRICITY FROM DIESEL FUEL
</P>
<P>
   A device that makes electricity from burning diesel fuel is
being perfected by Brookhaven National Laboratory in New York and
Edtek of Kent, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   A low-pressure air-atomizing nozzle sprays fuel into a
combustion chamber. Infrared emissions from the flame are converted
to electricity by a converter that consists of a mesh filter and a
gallium antimonide photovoltaic cell. The filter reflects away
low-frequency energy that produces heat, but allows sufficiently
energetic photons to pass and stimulate a flow of electrons in the
photo cell.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the program is to develop a portable
thermophotovoltaic generator that produces 500 watts of 24-volt
direct current, while burning about 0.07 gallons of diesel fuel an
hour. A prototype operates at 10 percent efficiency. Researchers
say efficiencies could reach 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE EYES IDENTIFY CHEMICALS
</P>
<P>
   Recently declassified technology from heatseeking missiles is
being used to quickly identify chemicals. In some cases it works
5,000 times faster than conventional methods, says Purdue
University professor Jochen Lauterbach. The instrument bathes the
sample in invisible infrared light, and then looks at the resulting
unique molecular signature. Early applications will include finding
more efficient catalysts for pollution-control systems.
</P>
<P>
   MEET YOUR NEW RELATIVE
</P>
<P>
   Chinese and American scientists say they have found bones that
bridge the anatomical gap between lower and higher primates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to use the term missing link, but these fossils really
do fill a wide gap that previously separated higher primates from
their relatives,'' says Christopher Beard of Carnegie Museum of
Natural History in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   He coordinated the American side of an expedition that found 45
million-year-old fossils of an Eosimias centennicus in a limestone
quarry 350 miles southeast of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The find clarifies the family link among monkeys, apes and
humans, the researcher says.
</P>
<P>
   PHONE PAD LETS DEAF CALL 911
</P>
<P>
   A new way of arranging letters on a telephone will give the deaf
access to 911 emergency service, even from pay phones. The ability
to send words over phone lines is hampered by the lack of a Q,
space or Z on keypads.
</P>
<P>
   Placing the missing characters over the number 1 lets you send
the entire alphabet, says James Burrell. His company, AM Research
of Union, N.J., (www.8key.com) won a patent for the idea. He says
he will license it to 911 centers for a dollar a month. AM has a
similar system for use as a one-hand keyboard that helps to prevent
carpal tunnel syndrome by reducing hand motion.
</P>
<P>
   GENE SPLICING IN SPACE LAB
</P>
<P>
   Gene splicing appears to work 10 times better in space than on
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, NASA conducted a DNA transfer experiment with soybeans
aboard the space shuttle. Of these seedlings, 9 percent exhibited a
genetically inserted trait, compared to 1 percent in the control
group on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't even know if you could do gene transfer in space,''
says Richard Vierling, the Purdue University researcher who
designed the experiment.
</P>
<P>
   He theorizes that low gravity makes it somehow easier for
bacteria carrying altered genetic material to enter cells.
</P>
<P>
   A followup study will fly on a future space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
