<SLUG> BC-BREAKTHROUGH-BRIEFS-DISCOVER-$ADV27-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKTHROUGH BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tue., June 27, 2000, or anytime thereafter.) 
 &HT;    
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color art is available.) 
 By THE EDITORS OF DISCOVER MAGAZINE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 UNDER T.REX'S TOES  
 &HT;    Stephen Hasiotis was clambering around near Lake Powell, Utah,
in 1996 when he spied striking white structures jutting out of the
purple clay.
 &HT;    In the years since, he and his colleague Robert Wellner have
uncovered 100 more of the formations and identified them as
fossilized burrows dug by some of our mammalian ancestors 150
million years ago.
 &HT;    Back then, mammals had to compete against much larger dinosaurs.
 &HT;    ``If you were on the ground, you could be eaten or squashed. The
trees probably weren't very safe either. So, our best bet was
probably in the ground,'' says Hasiotis, a biogeologist at Indiana
State University.
 &HT;    The burrows have complex forms similar to today's mammal
hideouts. Each has several openings, spiral ramps, and three or
four chambers that may have served as living room, pantry, birthing
room and bathroom.
 &HT;    Based on the burrows' shapes, Hasiotis suspects the animals
looked like prairie dogs but with longer tails and extended snouts
for hunting insects.
 &HT;    So far, the researchers haven't found any fossils of the mammals
themselves, but Hasiotis plans to hunt for them this summer. To
uncover bones or teeth, he'll use hydrochloric acid to dissolve the
calcium carbonate deposits that have filled the once-empty burrows.
 &HT;    Soon, he predicts, we'll be looking at the actual remains of the
timid diggers who eventually took over from the dinosaurs.
 &HT;    
 HOMO INTOXICATUS  
 &HT;    Getting sloshed on a Saturday night may seem a uniquely human
tradition, but not if physiologist Robert Dudley is to be believed.
 &HT;    Dudley, a biologist at the University of Texas at Austin, claims
the taste for alcohol runs deep in animal evolution and is shared
with our close primate relatives: chimps, gorillas, and orangutans,
which have a known weakness for overripe fruit.
 &HT;    Ripe or rotting rain-forest fruits contain alcohol
concentrations as high as 5 percent, Dudley says. The odor attracts
birds, bats, butterflies and elephants.
 &HT;    Chimps and gorillas _ from which our hominid ancestors split
between 5 million and 7 million years ago _ will roam for miles
through tangled trees and creepers in search of fermenting fruit.
Sugar and alcohol provide primates with precious calories, and the
fruit in turn spreads its seeds far and wide.
 &HT;    Genes for alcohol addiction may have persisted in the human line
for the same reason that those for fat accumulation have, according
to Dudley's theory.
 &HT;    Modest amounts of alcohol are known to decrease heart disease
risk and may lengthen life. Animals predisposed to a little nip
would be better survivors, more likely to pass their DNA to the
next generation. That genetic heritage may no longer be helpful now
that alcohol, like high-fat food, is available on every corner.
 &HT;    ``Alcoholism is not just another addiction,'' Dudley says. ``It
is a by-product of our ancestral nutritional physiology. Once we
better understand the mechanism, we'll have a better shot at a
cure.
 &HT;    -----
 FRESH-SQUEEZED  
 &HT;    The blandness of canned orange juice is an unfortunate side
effect of the high heat and chemical preservatives needed to
prevent food poisoning. Now microbiologist Martin Cole of Food
Science Australia and others have developed a way to kill germs
without killing flavor.
 &HT;    Cole applies pressures of up to 100,000 pounds per square inch
