<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: READERS WRITE ... AND WRITE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 PLEASE NOTE: Optional trim indicators have been included in this
feature to make shortening the piece an easier task.) 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By ADELE MALOTT 
 Condensed from The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 CORRECTION  
 &HT;    A recent Mature Traveler column reported that Hilton's Senior
HHonors program has been extended to include Doubletree, Hampton,
Homewood Suites and Embassy Suites. This is incorrect. The Senior
HHonors membership program for those ages 60 and older is valid
only at Hiltons and Conrad International Hotels. For more details,
call (800) 432-3600, or visit www.hilton.com on the Web.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    I love to hear from readers _ especially when their questions
are ones that will benefit many mature travelers.
 &HT;    Here's a selection of questions that recently crossed my desk.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     DEAR TMT:  
 &HT;    Your book, ``The Mature Traveler's Book of Deals,'' refers to
the French Carte Vermeil railroad pass, but I can't find any other
references to it. What can you tell me about it? _ Tom Lowell, San
Antonio, Texas
 &HT;    
 &HT;    DEAR MR. LOWELL:  
 &HT;    It's probably a bit hard to find since it has a new name, Carte
Senior, and it replaces the two earlier Carte Vermeil travel cards.
Travelers ages 60 and older can buy a Carte Senior for 290 francs _
the equivalent of about $42 U.S. _ at a French railway station to
get reductions of up to 50 percent off standard rail prices. The
pass is good for a year.
 &HT;    Carte Senior holders also are entitled to 30 percent off the
standard price for all train trips in 23 European countries that
use the Rail Europe Senior plan.
 &HT;    You will need to bring an identity photo in addition to your
passport when applying for a Carte Senior pass at the ticket
office. The Web site www.sncf.fr gives some background but does not
reveal a ticket price until you have made a reservation.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     DEAR TMT:  
 &HT;    I am planning a round-trip train ride to San Diego, Calif., in
August. Please help me with information about train travel. _ Tom
Ladner, Levittown, Penn.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     DEAR MR. LEVITTOWN  
 &HT;    First, call Amtrak, (800) 872-7245, to see about travel dates
and fares. Amtrak discounts its railfares by 15 percent for those
ages 62 or older. However, the fare you pay depends on how full the
train is.
 &HT;    For example, when I recently checked with Amtrak, senior fares
for a chair ticket from your area to San Diego ranged from $356.50
to $898 _ and the latter price was for a nearly full train. Of
course, a compartment costs more.
 &HT;    Here are two possible routes:
 &HT;    Take the Amtrak Three Rivers from Trenton, N.J., to Chicago,
where you will transfer to the California Zephyr, which will take
you via Denver to Oakland. There you will board the Coast Starlight
to travel along the California coast to Los Angeles, where you will
get on the San Diegan for the last leg of the trip.
 &HT;    Or, take the Nutmeg to New York, where you will transfer to the
Three Rivers to go to Chicago. In Chicago, you will board the
Southwest Chief, which travels cross country via Albuquerque, N.M.,
to Fullerton, a Los Angeles suburb, where you will board the San
Diegan.
 &HT;    For more information, call the San Diego Convention and Visitors
Bureau at (619) 232-3101.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     DEAR TMT: 
 &HT;    My wife and I have some travel questions that we hope you can
answer:
 &HT;    1) Whom should we contact to arrange traveling between England
and France by train?
 &HT;    2) What is the procedure for obtaining a National Parks Golden
Age Passport?
 &HT;    _ A.E. Lockert, Jr. Nashville, Tenn.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     DEAR MR. LOCKERT:  
 &HT;    1) To book travel on Eurostar (under the English Channel),
contact your travel agent or Rail Europe, which is the North
American supplier of European rail products. Call (800) 438-7245,
or www.raileurope.com on the Web.
 &HT;    2) If you are 62 or older you can buy a lifetime Golden Age
Passport for $10. Passports are available at any national park, or
you can contact the National Park Service, P.O. Box 37127,
Washington, D.C. 20013; www.nps.gov.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;     DEAR TMT:  
 &HT;    To whom should I write to get a travel itinerary for Helen, Ga.?
Your help is greatly appreciated.
 &HT;    _ Ethel Spade, West Palm Beach, Fla.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     DEAR MRS. SPADE:  
 &HT;    First call your travel agent and ask about motorcoach companies
that plan trips to Helen. Or ask the agent if he/she knows a travel
club or church group going to Helen that you could call.
 &HT;    If the travel agent can't help, I would contact information
centers and ask which motorcoach companies include a Helen
itinerary.
 &HT;    Try contacting:
 &HT;    _ Alpine Helen-White County Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau, P.O.
Box 730, Helen, Ga. 30545; (706) 878-2181.
 &HT;    _ Helen Welcome Center, City Hall - Chattahoochee St., Helen,
Ga. 30545; (706) 878-2521.
 &HT;    _ The Georgia Tourist Division, (404) 656-3595.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;     DEAR TMT: 
 &HT;    I read your column every Sunday and enjoy it very much. But I
have a suggestion: In future articles, could you give the distances
from major airports to town centers and include if public transport
is available? Many of us prefer not to rent cars.
 &HT;    One of your columns reads, ``Banff is easily accessible via
90-minute drive from Calgary airport!'' A 20-minute trip by cab,
bus or shuttle is a more reasonable distance. _ John Lancaster,
Doylestown, PA.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     DEAR MR. LANCASTER:  
 &HT;    I will be happy to work airport/city center information into
future articles when it is appropriate. The handy reference book
``Salk International's Airport Transit Guide'' is also a great
help. For a current copy of the book, call Magellan's at (800)
962-4943. The price is $9.95 and includes shipping and handling.
 &HT;    The guide gives the kind of information you want and includes
average prices for shuttles and cabs as well as where to get them
and which routes are recommended.
 &HT;    Regarding the Banff to Calgary transfer: There are shuttles that
run regularly between the two points, giving you a chance to relax
and enjoy the scenery.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     DEAR TMT:  
 &HT;    My sister and I are planning a trip to New York to visit Ellis
Island to see our parents' names are on the immigrants' wall. We
want an escorted tour that lasts about three days. We'd like to be
escorted from the airport to our hotel and then to Battery Park,
etc. The only travel company I have located includes four extra
days in New York. Do you know of any of short length? _ Eileen
Wozneski, Palm City, Fla.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     DEAR MS. WOZNESKI: 
 &HT;    I recommend that you work with Gray Line of New York, (800)
669-0051. Gray Line does offer airport transfers from each airport
to most hotels in Manhattan for rates ranging from $16 to $19 per
person.
 &HT;    And Gray Line has a number of escorted tours within the city.
Several incorporate visits to the Statue of Liberty and Ellis
Island with other attractions.
 &HT;    For senior travelers, I always recommend the Big Apple Greeters,
(212) 669-2896. It's not a tour, but is made up of local volunteers
who showcase those parts of New York they know best.
 &HT;    The Greeters prefer to be contacted a minimum of 10 days before
any planned trip so they can match your needs with the available
volunteers' specialities.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Adele
Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St., 14th
Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send Adele a postcard from your trip
with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you find for
seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to Adele by electronic mail. The
address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on your
keyboard.)
 &HT;    Adele Malott is the publisher of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
 &HT;    
 c.2000 The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
