<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING AROUND: PLANNING FAMILY TRAVEL ON THE WEB  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Still haven't planned a summer family getaway?
 &HT;    Then get on the Web. There are some great sites out there that
are fast, efficient and can help save money. Some can help reveal a
cheaper airfare or car-rental deal. Others can aid in unearthing
the perfect hotel or inn. So take these steps to get the best
vacation value this summer.
 &HT;    For those who can't decide between a cottage by shore, a
national park visit, or a trip to Florida, do a little research.
Disney's site, Family.com (www.family.com), has vacation advice of
all kinds, helping travelers plan trips by location and by type.
 &HT;    Anyone looking for an inexpensive family restaurant in
Yellowstone National Park, a bed &AMP; breakfast in Vermont or a hotel
in Chicago that will accept the family dog should go to Fodor's
(www.fodors.com), the Web site of the famed guidebooks. It's
well-organized, detailed and opinionated.
 &HT;    Also have a look at Arthur Frommer's Budget Travel
(www.frommers.com), where there is loads of information about
underrated and inexpensive places such as Portugal and Greece.
 &HT;    Frommer and his staff seek out low-cost ways to take vacations
that just seem expensive, like beach holidays. They also look for
unusual and cost-saving options, such as volunteer vacations with
the Sierra Club.
 &HT;    Fodors travel guides are connected to Concierge.com
(www.concierge.com), the Web site of Conde Nast publications, a
good resource for bed &AMP; breakfasts, resort hotels and lakeside
retreats. For those who want a peek at more luxurious vacations,
``Travel + Leisure''s Web site (www.pathfinder.com/travel/TL) has
the current issue and back issues available through a good search
engine.
 &HT;    If a vacation paradise must include sand and palm trees,
Pleasant Hawaiian Holidays (www.pleasanthawaian.com) are
discounters who can put together a range of well-priced
air/hotel/transfer deals to the islands, utilizing a large stock of
hotels and condos. Their sister company, Pleasant Mexico Holidays,
can do the same south of the border.
 &HT;    For the world beyond, check out Time Out (www.timeout.com),
which is like going online with an English accent. This site takes
the best of Time Out's city guides and city listing magazines and
puts them on the web.
 &HT;    Rough Guides (http://travel.roughguides.com) are written with
the independent traveler in mind and Lonely Planet
(www.lonelyplanet.com) set the standards for such travel. Then look
at BootsnAll.com (http://216.110.36.72/cgi-bin/gt/index.shtml),
which refers to itself as ``The Ultimate Resource for the
Independent Traveller,'' with a host of first-person stories by
young people traveling cheaply around the world.
 &HT;    The Europe-bound should head to Rail Europe's site
(www.raileurope.com), a godsend for anyone who has tried to plan a
rail journey through Europe. This site has schedules and fares for
point-to-point train fares, Eurailpasses, multi-country passes,
single country passes and rail 'n' drive passes. They also offer
Eurostar tickets from London to Brussels or Paris.
 &HT;    For getaways to American cities, check out discount hotel
brokers like Quikbook (www.quikbook.com) and Hotel Reservations
Network (www.180096hotel.com). Figure on discounts from 15 percent
to 40 percent off published rates in major city hotels, based on
availability, of course.
 &HT;    Once the hotel is booked, have a look at CultureFinder.com
(www.culturefinder.com), which has thousands of listings for opera,
ballet or theater performances in dozens of cities around the
country. In some cases, event tickets can be ordered online. Both
Digitalcity (www.digitalcity.com) and Citysearch.com
(www.citysearch.com) have a city-by-city list of restaurants and
shops, as well as sightseeing, arts and other entertainment. These
sites can make a visitor feel like local.
 &HT;    Biking, hiking and multisport vacations with the family are a
terrific way to spend a week or two outdoors with like-minded
families. But it can be daunting to sort through and evaluate
hundreds of similar-sounding adventure companies. So visit G.O.R.P.
(www.gorp.com), an acronym for the Great Outdoor Recreation Pages,
which has adventure travel stories and links to dozens of
outfitters who offer hiking, biking, kayaking and white water
rafting trips.
 &HT;    For those who have to fly, check out upcoming deals and sales on
the Web sites of American Airlines (www.aa.com), Continental
(www.flycontinental.com), United Airlines (www.ual.com), Delta
(www.delta-air.com), TWA (www.twa.com), USAirways
(www.usairways.com) and Northwest (www.flynwa.com).
 &HT;    Both Expedia.com (www.expedia.com) and Travelocity
(www.travelocity.com) have fast and sophisticated fare-finders.
They also offer short-term deals, sale fares and specials. It's
relatively quick and easy to book an entire vacation on these
sites, from airline seats to hotel rooms and car rentals. But
price-sensitive shoppers should also take a look at Lowestfare.com
(www.lowestfare.com), 1Travel.com (www.onetravel.com) and
Cheaptickets.com (www.cheaptickets.com).
 &HT;    As for specialized tickets, such as around-the-world tickets and
discounted business class tickets, look at TicketPlanet.com
(www.ticketplanet.com). Finally, for those with a yen to go cheaply
to Japan, China or other Asian destinations, Chisholm Travel
(www.chisholmair.net) is the best source.
 ---- 
 c.2000 Everett Potter 
