<HEADER>
A1859 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-SIGHTSEEING-SAO-PAULO     07-03 2121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIGHTSEEING-SAO-PAULO-TRAVEL-DOING-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN SAO PAULO  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slides and B&AMP;W map available.) 
 FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES 
 By LARRY ROHTER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Superlatives come quickly to mind when talking about Sao Paulo.
With 18 million people in its metropolitan area, this is the
largest city in Brazil, the largest in South America, indeed the
largest in the Southern Hemisphere.
 &HT;    It boasts of having the largest population of Japanese descent
of any city outside Japan, the largest of Lebanese descent of any
city outside the Middle East, the largest of Italian descent of any
city outside Italy, and more wealth than any city in what used to
be called the third world.
 &HT;    Paulistanos, as residents of the city are known, have always
taken pride in the cosmopolitan environment they have constructed
around them during the past century, but rarely more so than now.
 &HT;    All year long, Brazil is marking the 500th anniversary of the
arrival of the first Portuguese expedition to the New World, and
Sao Paulo, with a melting-pot population that personifies the
Brazilian ideal of racial democracy, is a focal point of the
commemorations.
 &HT;    Those who come to Sao Paulo expecting to find a laid-back
seaside tropical resort in the style of Rio de Janeiro or Salvador
are in for a shock. Sao Paulo is a very different kind of Brazil:
aggressive, sprawling and resourceful, with a different climate,
including temperatures that can drop to near-freezing at night
during the Southern Hemisphere winter (June through September).
 &HT;    Instead, Sao Paulo's charms are distinctly urban: restaurants,
museums, concerts, nightclubs, parks and window shopping along
Avenida Paulista, the main commercial boulevard. So are the
problems the city confronts, including poverty, crime and police
brutality. But even a confirmed Tropicalist like the pop singer
Caetano Veloso was forced to confess that, as he wrote in a homage
to the busiest intersection in Brazil's busiest city, ``Something
happens in my heart every time I turn the corner of Ipiranga and
Sao Joao.''
 EVENTS  
 &HT;    The magnificent exhibition known as ``Brazil+500'' is the
largest show of Brazilian art ever assembled, spread over an area
larger than the Louvre in four separate buildings. With some 15,000
pieces on display, it is hard to talk about highlights, but the
sections focusing on Indian, folk and Afro-Brazilian art have drawn
especially lavish praise from local and international critics.
Admission is $5.75 on weekdays and $8.50 on weekends, at 1.8 real
to the dollar. Telephone (55-11) 573-6073. Until Sept. 7 at
Ibirapuera Park.
 &HT;    To mark the 500th anniversary of the Portuguese arrival, leading
Brazilian and Portuguese pop musicians are offering a monthly
series of free joint concerts at Ibirapuera Park. On July 30,
Gilberto Gil, Maria Joao and Mario Laginha will perform together,
with Ney Matogrosso and Marta Dias scheduled for Aug. 13 and Gal
Costa and Madredeus closing the series on Sept. 9.
 &HT;    Sao Paulo has numerous music halls featuring Brazil's top
artists, with performance schedules published in newspapers and
monthly English-language tourist guides. One winter highlight
promises to be a number of shows by the brilliant pop singer Marisa
Monte at the Palace, Avenida dos Jamaris 213 in Moema. She will be
performing weekends from July 27 through Sept. 9, with tickets $10
and up; (55-11) 5643-2569.
 &HT;    No rivalry in international soccer is more intense than that
between Brazil, which has captured the World Cup four times, and
Argentina, which has won it twice. The national teams of the two
countries will play each other on July 26 at the 80,000-seat
Morumbi Stadium, Sao Paulo's largest, at Praca Roberto Gomes
Pedrosa 1, Jardim Leonor, as part of the qualifying round for the
2002 World Cup. Call (55-11) 3749-8000 for information about
tickets (prices to be announced shortly before the match).
 SIGHTSEEING  
 &HT;    Ibirapuera Park is to Sao Paulo what Central Park is to New York
City: an island of green and calm amid traffic and skyscrapers. It
has numerous museums and pavilions, many of them designed by the
renowned Brazilian architect Oscar Niemeyer, and open spaces that
include lakes and playgrounds, which draw large crowds of families
on weekends. The planetarium, $2.85, is especially interesting
because it displays the constellations of the Southern Hemisphere.
The park is open daily, 6 a.m. to 8 p.m.; (55-11) 574-5177.
 &HT;    Exhibitions in which venom is extracted from snakes are no
longer offered to the public, but the Instituto Butantan, Avenida
Vital Brasil 1500 in the Butanta area, remains perhaps the city's
most popular tourist attraction.
 &HT;    One of the world's leading reptile research centers, it has a
collection of more than 60,000 animals, and its small museum
features live spiders and scorpions as well as poisonous snakes
with exotic names like jararaca and mussurana. Open Tuesday through
Sunday, 9 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Admission is 85 cents; 55 cents for
children; (55-11) 813-7222.
 &HT;    The Memorial to the Immigrant, at Rua Visconde de Parnaiba 1316
in Bras, is the Brazilian equivalent of Ellis Island. Nearly three
million people from 60 different countries, including the United
States, came through this processing center during the 91 years it
operated before closing in 1978, and their contributions to
Brazilian society are honored in thorough, fascinating exhibits in
a somewhat nondescript complex of brick buildings done in
neo-Classical style. Open Tuesday through Sunday, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.
Admission $1.15, half price for children; (55-11) 6693-0917.
 &HT;    Installed in one of the city's uglier buildings is its best
museum, known as the MASP, or Museu de Arte de Sao Paulo. The
collection here is said to be the largest and most impressive in
Latin America, with European masters like Rembrandt, van Gogh,
Goya, El Greco and Monet as well as leading Brazilian artists such
as Portinari, Anita Malfatti and Tarsila do Amaral. On Sunday an
antiques and arts and crafts fair is held on the square outside the
museum. Open Tuesday through Sunday, 11 a.m. to 6 p.m.; admission
$5.75. Avenida Paulista 1578; (55-11) 251-5644.
 &HT;    Also on Sundays, the ``Discover Sao Paulo'' program offers three
bus tours departing from the Praca da Republica downtown. The Green
route shows visitors parks and gardens, the Cultural itinerary
visits the principal museums, and the Historic tour stops at old
homes and monuments. Tickets _ $2.85; $1.15 for children _ are sold
at tourist offices or through (55-11) 6971-5000.
 WHERE TO STAY  
 &HT;    By Brazilian standards, Sao Paulo hotels can be absurdly
overpriced. Rates mimic those of New York, with service and
amenities that cost half as much in Rio de Janeiro or Salvador. But
on weekends, when business travelers leave, rates at major hotels
can drop by 30 percent.
 &HT;    Few of Sao Paulo's hotels are more reliable or convenient than
the Crowne Plaza, just off Avenida Paulista at Rua Frei Caneca 1360
in Cerqueira Cesar. Remodeled not long ago, it has 220 rooms and
large beds and bathtubs in which to sink at the end of a long day.
A standard double starts at $198 a night through the chain's
``Summer Options'' program. Telephone (55-11) 253-2244 or (800)
227-6963; fax (55-11) 251-3121.
 &HT;    In the 1970s, the Grand Hotel Ca D'Oro, Rua Augusta 129 in
Consolacao, was the most elegant place to stay in Sao Paulo. The
neighborhood has fallen on hard times, but the 265 rooms, most
still decorated in the same style as they were back then, are
large, and the Italian restaurant on the ground floor is one of the
best in town. Doubles are $150, breakfast included; (55-11)
236-4300, fax (55-11) 236-4311.
 &HT;    Budget: Sao Paulo is awash in what are known as ``flats,''
apartment hotels aimed primarily at the long-term business visitor
but also available to the tourist. One especially good option is
the Parthenon chain, which operates a score of these residential
hotels. Rooms at some, such as the Parthenon St. Germain on Rua
Padre Joao Manuel 202 in Cerqueira Cesar, start at $60, with
breakfast. The top price at this chain is $100. Call (800) 111790
for reservations; fax (55-11) 883-2476.
 &HT;    The Best Western Porto do Sol, Rua Tutoia 77 in Cerqueira Cesar,
is halfway between Avenida Paulista and Ibirapuera Park and
convenient to many good restaurants. Its 198 rooms, while simple,
are as clean and attractive as those of its much more expensive
neighbors. A double starts at $100, with an ample breakfast buffet
of tropical fruits and juices; (55-11) 3059-5000, fax (55-11)
3059-5193.
 &HT;    Luxury: Big, swaggering, always crowded and boasting such
curiosities as a restaurant specializing in Danish cuisine, the
Maksoud Plaza Hotel, Alameda Campinas 150 in Bela Vista, has become
something of a landmark since it opened 20 years ago. But the
imposing atrium and 415 rooms are starting to show their age, and
there is a certain air of snobbery that can be disconcerting.
Doubles from $350; (55-11) 253-4411, fax (55-11) 253-4544.
 &HT;    On the other side of Avenida Paulista, at Alameda Santos 1123,
sits the Inter-Continental Sao Paulo. The 193 rooms here are larger
than those at several other luxury hotels, the atmosphere is one of
cool efficiency, and there are many good places to eat within
walking distance. Doubles are normally $400, but some are available
through Sept. 15 at the ``Summer Options'' price of $200. Telephone
(55-11) 3179-2600 or (800) 327-0200; fax (55-11) 3179-2669.
 WHERE TO EAT  
 &HT;    Year after year, Baby-Beef Rubaiyat is the runaway winner in
every survey of Sao Paulo's best churrascarias, restaurants
specializing in grilled meat. The cuts may seem unfamiliar to the
American palate, but the meat here is extraordinarily tender and
lean, perhaps because the restaurant has its own ranch where it
raises cattle, hogs, sheep and chicken. Of the two branches, the
more convenient is at Alameda Santos 86 in Paraiso. Dinner for two
with beer, about $65; (55-11) 289-6366.
 &HT;    In theory, Antiquarius, Alameda Lorena 1884 in Cerqueira Cesar,
specializes solely in Portuguese cuisine. But one of its signature
dishes is a singular mixture of Lusitanian and Brazilian
ingredients: a startlingly delicate codfish moqueca, or stew, laced
with coconut milk. The atmosphere is charmingly rustic. Dinner for
two with a bottle of sparkling Portuguese vinho verde: about $125;
(55-11) 282-3015
 &HT;    The menu at Amadeus, Rua Haddock Lobo 807 in Cerqueira Cesar, is
devoted to seafood in all its forms, freshly caught just off the
coast less than 50 miles away. Traditional Brazilian sauces, which
make liberal use of coconut milk, palm oil, onions, tomato and
peppers, are the main feature, but a terrific shrimp curry is also
on the menu. Dinner for two with a bottle of Brazilian wine is
about $110; (55-11) 3061-2859.
 &HT;    In a city blessed with dozens of excellent Italian restaurants
and cantinas, Massimo, at Alameda Santos 1826 in Cerqueira Cesar,
stands at the head of the class. The osso buco is so tender it
almost melts off the bone, and the cheeses, eggplant, peppers and
olives used in the antipasto are extraordinarily fresh. Dinner for
two is about $125 (no credit cards accepted); (55-11) 284-3011.
 &HT;    For cheap, appetizing eating, Paulistanos often turn to
restaurants offering food by the kilogram, most of which charge
$4.50 to $5.50 a pound. There is a large concentration of these
self-service buffet-style cafeterias in Rua Augusta. One that
stands out for its varied menu and mouth-watering desserts is the
Parque Avenida Grill, Avenida Paulista 1776; (55-11) 283-0201. 
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Larry Rohter is chief of the Rio de Janeiro bureau of The
Times.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Larry Rohter 
