<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-NAVIGATOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LINCOLN SHEDS ITS FOGYISH IMAGE WITH THE NAVIGATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, the luxury-car lines of Ford and General Motors have
struggled to draw flush-with-cash baby boomers into their dealers'
showrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Middle-aged consumers have tended to associate Lincoln and
Cadillac products with their parents and have generally left the
cars those divisions produce to the older generation.
</P>
<P>
   But that is changing now. Lincoln Mercury showrooms are busy
places these days, thanks to boomers' love affair with sport
utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The Navigator is an upscale version of the popular full-size
Ford Expedition SUV.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced for the 1998 model year, the Navigator takes the
Expedition to a higher level with a revised exterior that includes
lots of chrome, an interior flush with leather and wood trim, and a
$42,000-plus base price with two-wheel drive or $46,000-plus with
four-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle, about 15 inches shorter than the Chevrolet/GMC
Suburban, is priced to compete against the other large, upscale
SUVs: the Toyota Land Cruiser and its clone, the Lexus LX 470; the
Range Rover; the Mercedes-Benz ML55; and the BMW X5. All of these
vehicles list for $50,000 or more when equipped the way most people
would buy them, but the Navigator is the least expensive of the
bunch.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean it's any less of a luxury SUV, however.
</P>
<P>
   The Navigator has a giant plus in its favor: Underneath, it's
really a Ford F-150 pickup, which is the nation's best-selling
vehicle and has a well-deserved reputation for toughness,
reliability and longevity.
</P>
<P>
   There is a down side to that, though. Being an F-150 underneath,
the Navigator is a truck, not a car. The ride, therefore, is not as
smooth as you would expect from a Town Car or Continental, or even
the new Jaguar-based Lincoln LS.
</P>
<P>
   It's not bad, though, thanks in part to the standard
load-leveling air suspension. But if your bones are already getting
somewhat creaky, you might want to go with a plush sedan instead.
</P>
<P>
   Even with creaky bones, though, a sport utility such as the
Navigator is just fine for me, and this is one of the best on the
market. You could save $6,000 to $12,000 by choosing a less cushy
and less well-equipped Expedition, of course, but if you can afford
the extra fare, the Navigator offers just about everything you
could want in a luxury SUV.
</P>
<P>
   It's powered by Ford's 300-horsepower, 5.4-liter, 32-valve V-8
engine, connected to a smooth-shifting four-speed automatic
transmission. There is plenty of power to push this 5,700-pound
vehicle along. The engine cranks out 355 foot-pounds of torque at
2,750 rpm, enough to move the Navigator off the starting line with
the rest of the SUV pack.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you're used to a similar V-8 engine powering a
sedan that is 1,500 pounds lighter, you might be a bit
disappointed. But those of you used to driving trucks and SUVs will
be pleased with the Navigator's power.
</P>
<P>
   Handling is what you'd expect from a large vehicle like this;
it's not really nimble, but it's not as clunky as some other
truck-based SUVs, such as the previous-generation Suburban. And it
will fit in the standard garage and downtown parallel parking
space, unlike the Suburban and Ford's even-bigger SUV, the
gargantuan Excursion.
</P>
<P>
   The interior is plush with leather, with nice burled-walnut trim
in the dashboard and thick pile carpeting throughout. There are
consoles in the floor and overhead, and the lower one, between the
two front occupants, has two large cup holders.
</P>
<P>
   Standard seating includes bucket seats up front and in the
second row; a bench seat is in the third row, seating an additional
three people for a total of seven. The bucket seats in the center
row are separated by a console with cup holders.
</P>
<P>
   My only real complaint with our test vehicle is the two bucket
seats in the center row, which made it essentially a four-passenger
vehicle, unless someone wanted to climb into the rear to access the
third seating row. Adults don't like doing this, I found out, and
since we had two child seats hooked up in the middle-row bucket
seats, anyone else riding with us, other than up front, had to
crawl into the rear.
</P>
<P>
   If I were ordering a Navigator, I would choose the optional
three-passenger bench seat for the middle.
</P>
<P>
   With the third seat in place for passengers, there is not much
luggage space either. That's where the Navigator comes up short
compared with the Suburban; that extra 15 inches in the Suburban is
tacked onto the cargo area. The Navigator's third seat can,
however, be folded down easily to increase luggage space if you
don't need the seat for people.
</P>
<P>
   Loading is easy; you can open the whole tailgate by lifting it
up, or open just the tailgate window to sling grocery bags into the
back.
</P>
<P>
   Our test vehicle came with the full-time four-wheel-drive system
and carried a base price of $46,410 (plus $690 transportation). The
two-wheel-drive model carries a base price of $42,660 (plus
transportation).
</P>
<P>
   For my money, I would go with the four-wheel drive. I have
tested the two-wheel-drive version, and I found the tail end
slipping and sliding on wet pavement and losing traction in turns.
</P>
<P>
   Those problems were completely gone in our four-wheel-drive test
vehicle. This system can be set in automatic mode to bring the
front wheels on line when rear-wheel slippage is detected. Besides,
why buy half a truck when you can get a whole one for $4,000 more?
</P>
<P>
   Although this really is an Expedition underneath, it looks like
a Lincoln, thanks to the chrome-edged, turbine-vane signature
grille.
</P>
<P>
   Safety equipment includes power four-wheel disc antilock brakes,
second-generation (depowered) driver and front-passenger air bags,
side-door protection beams, and rear-door child-safety locks.
</P>
<P>
   Automatic climate control is standard; our vehicle came with the
optional rear air-conditioning/heating unit ($715) to keep even the
rearmost passengers comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Navigator is a truck, sound-deadening materials
have made the interior nearly as quiet as that of a luxury sedan.
That makes it easy to carry on a conversation or enjoy the nice
AM/FM/cassette stereo with the optional six-disc remote
compact-disc changer ($595).
</P>
<P>
   Other standard features on ours included cruise control, 17-inch
aluminum wheels, dual six-way power seats, digital clock, dual
power mirrors, fog lights, power door locks with remote control,
leather-wrapped tilt steering, power windows, rear privacy glass,
rear defroster, 3.73-ratio limited-slip rear axle, luggage rack and
a trailer-towing package.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the CD changer and rear climate control, options on our
vehicle included the reverse-parking aid ($255), which warns the
driver when the vehicle is approaching an object while backing up;
the GPS satellite navigation system ($1,995); and
climate-controlled front seats ($595).
</P>
<P>
   Total price for our test vehicle was $51,255, including
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings are 12 mpg in the city and 17 mpg on
the highway. The tank holds 30 gallons of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
