<HEADER>
A1866 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-TUCKER-HNS &LR;      07-03 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-TUCKER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SHORT-LIVED TUCKER DRAWS OGLING CROWDS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ There was a Tucker in town recently.
</P>
<P>
   The car was brought here by its owner, Francis ``Fuzzy'' Fruzyna
of Green Bay, Wis., and the occasion was the annual convention of
the National Tucker Automobile Club. This, however, was the only
Tucker that made it to the event.
</P>
<P>
   Preston Tucker, for whom the car was named, started his car
company in 1947, and it produced only 51 of these giant, oddball,
rear-engine luxury cars before going belly-up in 1948. All of them
are 1948 models, and of them, 47 are still accounted for, according
to the club, whose total membership numbers more than 800.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we don't all own Tuckers, because there aren't
enough to go around,'' said member Bob Niles, also of Green Bay,
who was baby-sitting Fruzyna's Tucker in the parking garage at the
downtown Menger Hotel the weekend of June 24-25 as hordes of people
stopped by to look it over. ``Most of us couldn't afford one
anyway; the last one that was sold, about a year ago, went for
$425,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The dark green Tucker made quite a splash during its visit here.
</P>
<P>
   ``One family came by and said they had been walking all over San
Antonio all morning, had been to the Alamo and everything else
downtown, but that this was the most exciting thing they had
seen,'' Niles said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 47 Tuckers still around, most are in museums where they
have been on display for years and are not considered to be in
running condition, club members said. But there are about 15 of the
cars that are still running, including Fruzyna's.
</P>
<P>
   And it will run, Fruzyna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put about 1,500 miles on it in the six years I've owned
it, so it now has a total of about 7,800 miles on the odometer,''
he said. ``I drove it as fast as 97 mph once, but was afraid I
would get a ticket if I went any faster. Top speed is supposed to
be 130.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Willeford, a tour guide at the Alamo who dropped by the
Menger to check out the Tucker, said he was impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really something else,'' he said. ``I saw the Tucker in
the film, but never had seen one up close. This is just amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The film he was referring to was the 1988 Francis Ford Coppola
flick, ``Tucker: The Man and His Dream'' starring Jeff Bridges as
Preston Tucker. (Tucker died in 1956 at age 53.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Preston Tucker was a car-crazy kid who hung around auto
speedways and grew up to create an automobile _ the Tucker _ that
was years ahead of its time,'' said the cover of the book ``The
Indomitable Tin Goose'' by Charles T. Pearson. ``He was a man of
pioneering spirit, ingenuity, and daring, who revolutionized
Detroit in the 1940s with his stunning car of tomorrow. It was
streamlined, futuristic, and fast _ the car every American dreamed
of owning, at a price most people could afford.''
</P>
<P>
   That assessment isn't fully based on fact; the car's styling was
controversial, and the sticker price, $2,450, was a lot of money
for a car in those days. Of course, if you had bought one then and
held onto it, you would have quite an investment on your hands.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Dorsey of San Antonio visited the Tucker and said he
couldn't believe his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real classic, for sure,'' he said, walking around the
car and stopping here and there for a closer look. ``They ought to
still be making cars like this. I certainly like its looks, and I
would be proud to drive it down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The insurance would put a crimp in anyone's budget, though, with
the car's value approaching $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   On hand to talk about the Tucker with visitors was Bill Whipple,
79, of Seattle, one of the last surviving employees of the Tucker
Automobile Co.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple said he was a mechanic millwright who helped convert the
Tucker factory in Chicago from a World War II bomb-making plant to
an automobile plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had stayed in business, I was on the list to get the
148th car built,'' he said. ``But obviously I never got mine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whipple has been on national TV as a former Tucker employee and
even has his paycheck stubs and plant employee badge to show
people, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the car itself, ``she rides and drives good,'' Fruzyna
said. ``I think I'll keep her for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Tucker club, here are the answers to the most
frequently asked questions about the car:
</P>
<P>
   _ This ``Car of Tomorrow'' was the vision of Preston Thomas
Tucker (1903-1956) of Ypsilanti, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fifty-one were built, of which 47 survive now (and many are on
display to the public).
</P>
<P>
   _ This fastback sedan was styled by Alex S. Tremulis. The car
was put together by chief mechanic John Eddie Offutt, who had
worked with Tucker and Harry Miller at the Indianapolis Speedway.
Offutt's cars won twice at Indy.
</P>
<P>
   _ The car is called the Tucker 48 (for its model year). It was
called the Tucker Torpedo as it was being designed and promoted.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Tucker 48 was designed in Michigan and built in Chicago in
a vast factory that is now the site of the ``Ford City Mall'' on
Cicero Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Tucker 48 pioneered automotive features and ideas that
became standard later.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fiberglass replica bodies are available for building Tucker
replicas, which use Cadillac chassis and Northstar engines.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tucker 48 specifications: engine, horizontally opposed
six-cylinder, 335 cubic inches, 166 horsepower, 372 foot-pounds of
torque; size, 128-inch wheelbase, 219-inch overall length, 60-inch
height, 79-inch width; weight, 4,200 pounds; performance, 0-60 mph
in 10 seconds, estimated top speed 120 mph.
</P>
<P>
   _ Original price, $2,450; current value: from about $250,000 to
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it could go into reverse. (The prototype, with a Cord
automatic transmission, did not have a reverse gear.)
</P>
<P>
   For more information about the Tucker and the car club, check
out the Web site www.tuckerclub.org.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
