<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1867 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-VOLVO-HNS &LR;      07-03 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-VOLVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BEEFED-UP VOLVO CROSS COUNTRY TAKES AIM AT SUV MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wagons may be on the verge of extinction, having been mostly
replaced first by the minivan in the 1980s and then the
sport-utility vehicle in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. There may be new life in these vehicles, thanks to
some smoke and mirrors and a crafty marketing strategy created by
automakers such as Volvo that are not fortunate enough to have
minivans and SUVs in their lineups.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the idea: Suppose we take a station wagon, beef it up a
bit, add four-wheel drive, then call it a sport-utility vehicle or
at least promote it as a vehicle that is every bit as good as, if
not better than, the typical truck-based SUV.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's not really such a bad idea. Why not take an existing
product and modify it, rather than spend a billion dollars or more
to develop a whole new truck product to satisfy the consumers' need
for sport-utilities?
</P>
<P>
   There is precedent for this.
</P>
<P>
   Subaru has gotten away with it for several years. In fact, it
hasn't only gotten away with such a strategy; it has been wildly
successful at it _ with such popular products as the midsize Legacy
Outback Wagon and Sedan, compact Impreza Outback Wagon, and the
Forester, a beefier version of the Impreza Outback, all of which
come with full-time all-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   Even Honda and Toyota have taken existing car platforms and
turned them into SUV-like products. For Honda, it is the CR-V,
based on the compact Civic; for Toyota, it is the RAV4, built on
the chassis of the previous-generation Celica hatchback.
</P>
<P>
   Pontiac, also hungry for an SUV but with only a minivan in the
truck category, has turned its former Trans Sport minivan into a
sport-utility of sorts, called the Montana. Unlike the others,
though, the Montana has no all-wheel-drive option. But that doesn't
stop Pontiac from pushing the vehicle as a sport-utility, even
though Chevrolet still sells the same vehicle as the Venture
minivan, and Oldsmobile as the Silhouette. All of those TV
commercials showing grizzled cowpokes driving the Montana as though
it were a sport-utility have made it into an SUV at least in some
consumers' minds.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not so outlandish that Volvo, that Swedish builder of
premium sedans and station wagons, would presume to turn one of its
wagons into an SUV-like product.
</P>
<P>
   That's old news, of course, to you who know Volvo products. The
company, now a subsidiary of Ford Motor Co., introduced the V70
Cross Country Wagon, with all-wheel drive, nearly three years ago,
and has enjoyed sales success while marketing this vehicle as at
least an alternative to the traditional truck-based SUV. The
company sold 17,500 of these wagons last year, a vehicle that Volvo
marketing executives call a ``premium car-based crossover
vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   This vehicle, which began as a 1998 model and continues as a
2000, is based on the Volvo 850 wagon, renamed the V70 in the
mid-90s.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Volvo is taking the V70 Cross Country to an
entirely new level with the 2001 model, which goes on sale this
fall at U.S. dealerships, and later in the year in other world
markets.
</P>
<P>
   This all-new version of the Cross Country is based on the
chassis platform of Volvo's newest and best luxury sedan, the S80,
introduced two years ago. Quite unlike any Volvo ever before, the
S80 is a fine European luxury sedan on par with vehicles such as
the Audi A6, Mercedes-Benz E-class and BMW 5-series, as well as the
Lexus GS 300 and Acura RL.
</P>
<P>
   As a wagon-turned-SUV, the new V70 Cross Country puts carlike
comfort and road handling in a package that rivals some of the most
popular sport-utilities, such as the Mercedes-Benz M-class, Lexus
RX 300 and Jeep Grand Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the all-wheel-drive system won't take this vehicle into
the deep woods like that of the Grand Cherokee, because it doesn't
have the low-range gearing that Jeep and many other SUVs offer for
serious off-roading. But some of the other premium SUVs _ such as
the RX 300, Oldsmobile Bravada and Mercury Mountaineer _ don't have
such low-range gearing either, which limits their off-road
capabilities. In comparison with those, the new V70 Cross Country
appears to be every bit as much of an SUV, with more creature
comfort (thanks to its smoother-riding car-based chassis).
</P>
<P>
   What about ground clearance? It's a whopping 8.2 inches in the
2001 V70 Cross Country, as much or more than most popular SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo designed the new Cross Country from the ground up as an
SUV contender, taking the best features of popular sport-utilities
and combining them with the best attributes of the utterly
fantastic S80 sedan. From the side, the V70 Cross Country even
looks like an SUV; it's similar in appearance to the new Jeep Grand
Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   What this all means is that even automakers that don't build
trucks can play in the SUV market, as the lines between sedans and
SUVs, wagons and SUVs, and minivans and SUVs continue to get
blurred.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent media rollout for the new V70 Cross Country, Mark
LaNeve, Volvo's North American marketing chief, declared that the
vehicle was creating its own special market segment, ``combining
the European premium-car experience with the function and
capability of an SUV,'' along with ``Volvoness, which includes
safety and environmental values.''
</P>
<P>
   The starting price will be $34,900. But well-equipped _
including leather interior _ the car will list for $36,900, which
is $1,400 less than the average transaction price of the current
V70 Cross Country. It's also virtually the same price as many
competing premium SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo anticipates selling 20,000 of the new Cross County in the
United States in the first full year. The typical buyer will be age
35-45, married, and college-educated, with a median household
income of $175,000 annually, Volvo says. Those buyers will have
active lifestyles that include such pastimes as hiking and biking,
LaNeve said.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo acknowledges that it went after the Grand Cherokee in
designing the new Cross Country.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get the Jeep look, we needed very Jeepy wheels, so we went
up two sizes over the current Cross Country,'' said Lars Erik
Lundin, Volvo's vice president for the Cross Country project.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle is beefier than before, too. It is two inches
longer, four inches wider and two inches higher. And its wheel base
is four inches longer.
</P>
<P>
   The new Cross Country is powered by a 197-horsepower, 2.4-liter,
light-turbo inline five-cylinder aluminum engine, and comes with
either a five-speed manual or five-speed automatic transmission. It
will go from zero to 60 mph in 8.4 seconds with the automatic, or 8
seconds even with the manual. Top speed is 130 mph.
</P>
<P>
   It is fuel-efficient, too, especially when compared with the
current crop of competing SUVs. EPA ratings are 20 miles per gallon
in the city and 25 mpg on the highway, according to preliminary
figures.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
