<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1891 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-BOS &LR;      07-03 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO-DONE-ITS STEEPED IN BELIEVEABLE DETAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN W. WINKS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is, to my mind, an important difference between local
color and a sense of place. The first is an artificial pigment
applied, often too heavily, by a writer who is a bit insecure about
how to create a compelling story and who thinks an infinitude of
details, relevant or not, will carry the reader over some rough
patches; the result is often that the local color, however
interesting it may all be in the abstract, proves an annoyance. The
second grows out of a sense of confidence, and is provided by a
writer who truly understands the environment in which a book is
set. In the case of mystery and detective fiction, this means that
the locale (and the details used to bring the reader into that
locale) provides a reason rather than merely a setting for the
plot. I can't claim this distinction entirely escapes triteness,
but it served as the subject of rumination this month as I read a
number of new novels that seemed to me to prove my point.
</P>
<P>
   A fine example is ``Brigham's Day'' by John Gates (Walker,
$23.95). This first novel is one of the best debuts I have read in
a long time. The title refers in part to the protagonist, Brigham
Bybee, a lawyer who is brought to the small southern-Utah town of
Kanab to be second counsel in what local authorities hope will be
an open-and-shut case. Bybee has made a mess of his life by
bringing a leader of the Mormon Church to trial on charges of rape
and assault and then failing to get a conviction, thanks to
arrogance and too much alcohol, losing his wife and children in the
process. But the title also refers to Brigham Young, the Mormon
leader who may, Gates suggests, have ordered the killing of 120
California-bound settlers in 1857. Known as the Mountain Meadows
massacre, this event is marked by a small monument in southwest
Utah, and it is the focus of much controversy among Mormons and
those who dislike them for one reason or another. Bybee is a ``Jack
Mormon,'' a man who has left the church but still understands the
language, and he begins to believe that his client is innocent and
that the murder with which he is charged had to do with a document
that would reveal the truth about the events of 1857. Gates handles
the air of suspicion extremely well, and he plays against
stereotypes. Bybee is by no means a whole person; the fat and
sloppy (and certainly unethical) lawyer he is to back up proves to
be a far better investigator than one might imagine; and the
villains in the piece are often complex beneath simplistic
surfaces. Gates is a lawyer himself, and he uses his professional
and local knowledge (he was raised in Kanab) to tell a persistently
compelling story.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McGarrity does not write so well as Gates, but he too
tells a taut and convincing story in ``The Judas Judge'' (Dutton,
$23.95). The setting is the mountains of southern New Mexico,
between Carrizozo and Alamagordo, and the high desert is used to
great effect. McGarrity's series figure, police chief Kevin Kerney,
must deal with the apparently random murder of six individuals in
the campgrounds of this mountainous region; one of them is a
powerful local judge. Kerney kills a fellow officer early in the
action, which turns several members of the police against him.
McGarrity never lets the reader forget this high, dry, dramatic
land, or the Mescalero Apaches who live on it, or the nature of
life in communities that are taken for cities in their region
though they are, in fact, small towns. I read this one in a single
sitting, even forgiving the author for locating Creede, Colo.,
northeast of Alamosa, when it is well to the northwest (they are
two towns I know and care about from a previous age, when all that
mattered to me was beating them in high school football).
</P>
<P>
   Brent Monahan moves us to a far richer and more complicated
society in ``The Jekyl Island Club'' (Minotaur, $23.95), set on
that once idyllic Georgia coast that so attracted the rich at the
turn of the last century. A member of the club dies in a hunting
accident; the local sheriff must take on the members of a club who,
in 1899, controlled one-sixth of the nation's wealth. J. P. Morgan
and Joseph Pulitzer, President McKinley, and other top politicians
all figure in the action, and behavior, speech, and place are
lovingly presented.
</P>
<P>
   I also like ``Poison Apples'' by Nancy Means Wright (Minotaur,
$24.95), set in a wonderfully observed Vermont. Moira and Stan
Earthrowl are having a hard time of it, as their apple orchard (and
source of income) is going down the tubes. When poisoned fruit
kills a Jamaican picker, Moira has to call in help, in the form of
Vermont farmer Ruth Willmarth. Theme and setting could be cutesy,
folksy, or local-colored to death, but Wright doesn't put a foot
wrong in this well-wrought mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is ``Escape from Kathmandu'' by Kim Stanley
Robinson (Tor Books, $13.95 paperback), which is a delight. I have
never encountered Robinson before, despite a long list of credits
(mainly in science fiction, which I do not like). But I am an
instant convert. This is a straightforward adventure novel based on
the premise that in the high mountain valleys of Nepal the yeti, or
Abominable Snowman, actually exists. Nepal is a home away from home
to scores of American and British climbers, aging hippies,
occasional businessmen, and scientists who simply love the
Himalayas. Two of them link up to rescue a captured yeti and return
it to the wild. Former President Carter, any number of intriguing
Buddhists, and the yeti itself figure in the kind of romp that, a
century ago, might have been written by John Buchan or H. Rider
Haggard. In this century, Robinson is a terrific storyteller who
knows why shaggy-dog yarns survive, and the tale he tells could not
happen anywhere else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
