<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1892 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-BROTHER-BOS &LR;      07-03 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BROTHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE YOU WATCHING `BIG BROTHER' WATCH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It began to snowball last August with ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' and gained renewed force last month with another
summer phenomenon, CBS's ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with ``Big Brother,'' CBS is poised to turn another group
of previously anonymous Americans into TV stars while capitalizing
on the tube's hottest trend of the moment: ``reality'' programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The face of television has changed drastically in the last 12
months,'' said CBS Television president Leslie Moonves. ``And it
will continue to change.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, after weeks of relentless promotion, CBS
will unveil ``Big Brother.'' Slated to air five nights a week for
three months, it will showcase 10 contestants ranging in age from
early 20s to mid-40s, leaving behind their normal lives to be
cooped up together in a two-bedroom house built on a studio lot. As
they interact, 28 cameras and 60 microphones will record every move
they make and every word they utter.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they are denied access to newspapers, television,
phones, or the outside world, they will be subjects of what CBS and
partner America Online hope will be a multimedia event. Apart from
the nightly televised dose of ``Big Brother,'' AOL will allow
Internet users to monitor the goings-on in the house via streaming
video. Every two weeks, viewers will vote by telephone to expel one
person from the house. (AOL plans to offer live chats with each
contestant as he or she leaves the house). On the next to last
episode, viewers will choose a winner from the three remaining
housemates. And on Sept. 30, that winner will receive a check for
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never done a show remotely like this before,'' said
Moonves. ``We're treading in uncharted territory for an American
network. . . . It's exciting and scary at the same time because of
the newness of it all.''
</P>
<P>
   John de Mol, cocreator of the ``Big Brother'' series in Holland
and Germany, predicted that viewers of the US version ``will get
involved and intrigued with the people in the house and the
situations they are in.'' The contestants, he added, are ``people
you will mostly love and sometimes hate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dog-eat-rat view
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But programs like ``Big Brother'' and ``Survivor'' have kindled
concerns about the invasion of privacy they seem to encourage.
Critics say the shows, with their arrangements designed to induce
tensions, appeal to a dog-eat-dog view of human nature. Moreover,
some say, the reality programs encourage the basest kind of
voyeurism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it is voyeuristic TV,'' conceded Moonves. But he said,
``I don't think it's necessarily bad. People are interested in what
other people will do in this situation. . . . There are 500
channels. You don't like it, change the channel.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, CBS is hoping that viewers don't touch that remote.
Moonves says ``Big Brother'' could be ``an even bigger event'' than
``Survivor,'' which is saying something. In its third episode, for
instance, ``Survivor'' drew an average of 23 million viewers, more
than the other five broadcast networks combined. Long known as the
broadcast home of older viewers, CBS has been ``totally
transformed'' by the blockbuster ratings and appeal to young
viewers of ``Survivor,'' according to Moonves.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first network to be transformed by a single show.
Last season, ``Millionaire'' revived the quiz-show genre _ which,
while different from ``reality'' programs, also relies on average
citizens as its stars _ and single-handedly propelled ABC from
third to first place in the ratings. ``Survivor'' and ``Big
Brother'' might reap similar dividends for CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Big Brother,'' ``Survivor'' and ``Millionaire'' were
imported from Europe. So, inevitably, ABC recently announced that
it will produce an American version of ``The Mole,'' a reality
series from Belgium that follows a group of contestants assigned to
complete difficult tasks while unaware of a saboteur in their
midst.
</P>
<P>
   ``The eyes of America were opened when `Millionaire' started the
trend,'' said Moonves. ``We were a little closed-minded. Americans
always assumed we were the exporters, not the importers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joining the club
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The race for reality programs promises to become even more
heated. NBC president Robert Wright, irked that the Peacock Network
is being left out of the trend while ratings for its dramas and
sitcoms dip, has reportedly ordered NBC programmers to come up with
a reality series, and soon. At CBS, Moonves does not rule out
airing ``Big Brother'' six nights a week, though five nights a week
is the planned schedule. De Mol, the chairman of Endemol
Entertainment, says the ``Big Brother'' format will expand to 25
countries in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the States, Moonves said, ``people are beating
down our doors with the most ridiculous rip-offs of `Big Brother'
and `Survivor' you've ever heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Although you'd never know it from the suggestive commercials CBS
has been running, Moonves and De Mol say there will be no nudity or
profanity in ``Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10 contestants will share two small bedrooms and one
bathroom in a one-level house. They will do mundane chores _
maintain a vegetable garden, prepare dinner, do laundry _ and must
also fulfill a weekly ``challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, De Mol said, in Dutch and German versions of ``Big
Brother'' contestants were required to keep a fire burning in a
fire pit for a full week, to ride a stationary bicycle for hours at
a time, and to collaborate in the construction of a 3,000-piece
jigsaw puzzle that forms a picture of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, however, ``Big Brother'' will listen in as the
contestants pour out their hearts to each other. ``There will be a
lot of conversation,'' said De Mol. ``If you picture a normal soap,
like `The Bold and the Beautiful,' it's all conversation. But this
is real.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
