<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1894 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-03 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSISTING AFRICA'S DILEMMA MEANS ACKNOWLEDGING IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What if tomorrow the news media reported that 20 percent of the
United States' population is infected with HIV, the AIDS virus?
Outraged, panicky, and scared Americans from California to
Massachusetts would be up in arms, demanding that the government
take immediate steps to combat this epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   Then suppose that, the next day, the media reported that more
than 50 percent of America's 15-year-olds would die from AIDS. The
result would likely be a quickly organized march of millions of
panic-stricken and angry citizens on Washington, demanding that our
leaders do something to reverse the deadly trend.
</P>
<P>
   The panic and anger in the United States would spread if, on the
third day, the media reported that in neighborhing Canada and
Mexico, one-fifth of the populace was infected with HIV _ as was
more than one-third of the population in nearby Puerto Rico. Or
that in Texas, 2,000 people were dying each week from AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   This nightmare scenario is, of course, just that, and is not
true in this part of the world. But it is very real in South
Africa, where 20 percent of the population, or 4.2 million people,
are HIV positive; and in Botswana, where one in three adults is
infected with HIV; and in Zimbabwe, where 2,000 people are dying of
AIDS each week.
</P>
<P>
   Africa's sad story spreads even farther: to 16 sub-Saharan
African nations, where more than one-tenth of the population
between the ages of 15-49 has HIV, and where in seven countries, 20
percent of the population is infected.
</P>
<P>
   Apply Botswana's HIV infection rate to the United States, and it
would mean that 90 million of our 270 million would be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite the staggering enormity of the epidemic in Africa,
the world has not shown anywhere near the the anger, the outrage _
or even just the concern _ that would have been registered if the
statistics applied to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   When other tragedies befall Africa _ such as when innocents are
slaughtered at the hands of warring rebels and troops _ the media
at least takes note, or raises questions about the motive. But
reports of a scourge as devastating as the Black Plague that ripped
across Europe and Asia in the 14th century don't seem to spark even
a moderate level of interest in the United States and other Western
nations.
</P>
<P>
   True, this country has its own HIV and AIDS problem to deal
with. And despite making some progress in this area, we seem to be
backsliding. A sharp decline in the AIDS death rate here _ it
dropped 42 percent from 1996 to 1997 _ has since slowed to half
that rate, according to the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta.
In real numbers, AIDS killed more than 17,000 people in the United
States last year.
</P>
<P>
   The decline has leveled off in part because AIDS drugs have
apparently lost much of their effectiveness. And, as one doctor
noted, ``AIDS drugs don't work for everyone, and are not a cure for
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The 17,000 Americans killed by AIDS last year were
disproportionately African-American, according to the CDC. While
blacks make up 13 percent of the US population, they accounted for
49 percent of AIDS deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Helen Gayle, director of HIV prevention at the CDC, made an
important point during a recent MSNBC interview. ``In many ways,''
she said, ``the story of how well we do in HIV and AIDS will be
told by how well we do with the African-American population.''
</P>
<P>
   It could also be said that how well we do with HIV and AIDS will
be told by how well the United States and other Western nations do
with the AIDS epidemic in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
   UN representatives attribute the explosion of HIV and AIDS in
southern Africa to the legacy of apartheid, the racially segregated
system that separated men from their families in rural areas and
sent them to work in towns where prostitutes also worked.
</P>
<P>
   But they also blame the governments for ignoring the problem for
far too long. What has happened in southern African, they add,
should be a lesson for other regions, including Asia, Eastern
Europe and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also important that the United States, Canada, and
other nations in the world pool their financial and educational
resources to combat this still-growing epidemic. Thus far, AIDS has
killed 19 million people worldwide, and orphaned 13 million
children. Another 34 million are HIV-infected.
</P>
<P>
   As parts of the world once needed the Marshall Plan to keep
millions of people in Europe from starving, the nations infected
with the HIV/AIDS epidemic need a massive plan to keep millions of
adults and children from dying.
</P>
<P>
   They had best begin now, or the news media may someday be
reporting on how HIV and AIDS is destroying the US population as
fast as destroyed the people of southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
