u k BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-03 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING HOME HEALTH CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON &UR;  &LR; _ In the language of government programs, they
call it home health care.
</P>
<P>
   To Senator Susan Collins in Maine, it has human faces that mock
the dry terminology _ a couple in their 80s up in Caribou, the area
in northern Maine she comes from, who have been married more than
50 years and only want to be together in their home in their final
years. A professional who visits them to provide care makes that
life possible.
</P>
<P>
   But for 7,000 of the Republican senator's elderly and disabled
constituents, that simple yearning is no longer possible, the
result of a government goof of colossal proportions that now
borders on the intentional because it has been allowed to go
uncorrected for three years. In addition, there has been a 30
percent drop in actual visits to homes by professionals and a 26
percent plunge in Medicare payments to the state's home health
agencies. None of it is justified.
</P>
<P>
   To Representative Jim McGovern in Massachusetts, home health
care means another retired couple in his native Worcester living in
an apartment nowhere near public transportation. The husband is
ailing but can be treated less expensively by a visiting
professional in their home than in a nursing home. They are facing
the loss of this care, which is likely to send the husband to that
nursing home and make Herculean his wife's task simply to visit
him.
</P>
<P>
   It also makes the Democratic congressman think of a guy in
Upton, a multiple sclerosis patient who can still get by with home
treatment. All it will take is staff reductions at the outfit
serving him (a distinct likelihood) to leave him with no
alternative to institutional care.
</P>
<P>
   For national perspective on this mess, Senator John Kerry says
that since the government goof in 1997, more than 2,500 agencies
delivering health care to people's homes have had to close, robbing
more than a half-million people of services that are the threads in
their safety net. The cause is direct: Three years ago the federal
government was spending $17.5 billion on home health care; since
then the figure has been slashed more or less in half. The
Congressional Budget Office estimates that between 1998 and 2002,
some $69 billion will have been taken away from a system that was
working.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're losing the industry,'' he told me. ``We're losing a
vital component of the health care community; the plugs are getting
yanked out of this system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't stand it when government directly creates harm,''
Collins says with refreshing anger.
</P>
<P>
   Three New England legislators are leading the effort in Congress
to replace the Clinton administration's Band-Aids for providers of
Medicare and Medicaid services with a full restoration of home
health care's status. Collins is a moderate Republican, McGovern a
liberal Democrat, and Kerry a New Democrat _ the natural coalition
supporting this cause is that broad.
</P>
<P>
   Collins and Kerry in the Senate and McGovern in the House late
last month joined forces to push for an end to the cutbacks, which
began with the balanced budget agreement of 1997. Collins is
leading an effort to forestall an additional reduction of 15
percent for home health care as of late next year. So far, 52
senators agree with her.
</P>
<P>
   New England, along with the Midwest, is the jewel in the home
health care system, with strong traditions of well-run, nonprofit
service providers. Cases of excessive payments to fast-buck artists
have been concentrated elsewhere, especially in the South. What
happened three years ago was a classic case of babies and
bathwater.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare went on the table in the final stages of the budget
talks. What was portrayed as an easily absorbable nick in payments
to Medicare's providers _ home health care agencies, teaching
hospitals, and nursing homes _ turned out to be something else
again. The estimate of savings in the payment system for home
health care providers was about $16 billion; the last time anyone
checked, the actual reduction was at least four times that.
</P>
<P>
   That's ridiculous. Clinton last month proposed that some
additional money go to providers next year. Something similar
happened a year ago with the huge pot of desperately needed funds
lost by teaching hospitals. But the president's approach is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot stopgap this thing,'' Kerry told me. ``It's worse
than Band-Aids; it's triage.''
</P>
<P>
   Ours is population that is aging rapidly. It is simply nuts to
eviscerate the basic infrastructure for the services seniors and
the disabled depend on through Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, to take the last steps to a balanced budget,
Clinton and Congress made a colossal mistake. Collins, Kerry, and
McGovern are right: The time has come to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
