u a BC-SCI-ROCKET-BOS &LR;      07-03 1574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ROCKET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS FIRE AT NEW NASA ROCKET EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASA is about to embark on its biggest new program since the
high-priced and perpetually delayed space station. But hardly
anyone seems to have noticed it, except some critics who say the
program could actually stall attempts to develop the space
frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Yet analysts expect Congress to approve the five-year, $4.4
billion plan within the next few weeks, virtually without debate.
</P>
<P>
   It is called the Space Launch Initiative, aimed at developing
new rockets that could eventually replace the aging space shuttle.
The five-year program is just the first stage of a 40-year plan the
agency has mapped out. Though it is the largest program the agency
has initiated since it began working on the $60-billion-and-growing
space station project in 1982, it remains virtually unknown to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration, which
announced the plan in February, says it is intended to bring
together various plans within the agency aimed at improving the
safety, reliability, and affordability of launch vehicles. The
program focuses on development of a ``second generation'' reusable
launch vehicle that would eventually replace the fleet of space
shuttles, with a goal of increasing safety a hundredfold and
slashing costs by 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It also includes smaller projects to develop rockets that could
help ferry supplies to the International Space Station, and to test
concepts for new technology.
</P>
<P>
   And, the agency says, its aim is to foster the commercialization
of the space launch business and to encourage competition. Toward
that end, it intends to provide contracts to multiple companies,
leading to perhaps a whole family of piloted and unpiloted
configurations for the replacement shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   But critics are skeptical, contending that while NASA is saying
the right things in public, the documents spelling out the details
of the plan suggest that its effect could be to impede the very
competition it purports to promote.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is NASA's next giant mistake,'' said Robert Zubrin, an
aerospace engineer and president of the Mars Society, an advocacy
group for space exploration. ``The first was the shuttle, and
abandoning all the Apollo-era hardware. The second was the space
station. This is the next, and it is a program to basically
replicate capabilities we already have.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many advocates for increased exploration, Zubrin thinks the
shuttle and space station programs have devoured most of NASA's
budget and thus precluded more ambitious programs with the
potential to generate both important scientific data and public
enthusiasm, such as human missions to Mars. Others suggest the
priority should be on fostering the development of low-cost ways to
reach orbit, enabling a gold rush of space-related businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while the space station project generated intense debate and
annual attempts by Congress to kill it, so far there has been
virtually no political or public opposition to the new initiative,
which NASA describes as its third-highest priority (after the
shuttle and space station).
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, say critics, is that any person or company
involved in the aerospace business is so dependent on NASA that few
are willing to criticize the agency's plan in public. But, they
say, concerns about the new plan run deep when aerospace people
talk in private.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably get fired'' for talking about it, said Tim
Kyger, a Washington lobbyist for Universal Space Lines, during an
interview with the Globe. But, he said, the plan is so threatening
to the prospects for a new generation of low-cost, reusable space
vehicles that he felt compelled to take the risk.
</P>
<P>
   While touted as a means to foster the development of a new
generation of rockets, the plan will actually stifle it, Kyger
said. For one thing, NASA is insisting that any vehicles developed
under the plan be 15 percent larger in payload capacity than the
shuttle _ a size most analysts think precludes most possible
private, commercial uses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's forward into the past,'' Kyger said. Under the plan, he
said, ``we will keep doing the same thing we have been doing.'' And
the plan could take on a life of its own and dominate the space
agency's budget for decades, he said. ``It literally sets up a plan
which they have sketched out through 2040. . . . What it will
produce is another shuttle or station program that goes on and on
forever, and sucks up all the agency's resources.''
</P>
<P>
   One major concern is that by spelling out a plan under which it
would take NASA 10 to 15 years to begin producing a new, reusable
launch vehicle, the agency will cast a pall on any financing
prospects for the several companies trying to develop low-cost
launchers much faster than that. But others caution that much
depends on the details, and the plan could end up being of some
help to some of the companies if it provides small launch contracts
to them, as is envisaged under part of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Smith, NASA's deputy director of space transportation at
Marshall Space Flight Center, defends the program and says it is
intended to foster just the kind of commercialization and
competition for launch vehicle companies that the critics advocate.
He said in an interview that the program was developed with
extensive consultation with representatives from industry, and that
in defining requirements for vehicles developed under the program
NASA intends to ``make sure they are as applicable to commercial
needs as to NASA's needs.''
</P>
<P>
   But the plan is ``fatally flawed'' and based on ``fundamentally
wrong assumptions,'' according to an analysis by the Space Access
Society, an advocacy group that has been calling for investment in
research aimed at ``cheap access to space.''
</P>
<P>
   The society, along with many independent aerospace engineers and
about a dozen small startup companies, believes that it is possible
within just a few years to produce rockets that could slash the
cost of launching hardware into space by 90 percent, and that even
reductions to as little as one one-100th of present costs are
ultimately feasible. When that happens, they say, whole new
industries will rise up to take advantage of that access, including
same-day package delivery to anyplace on Earth, manufacturing of
high-value products such as pharmaceuticals and microelectronics,
and even space tourism.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts say that regardless of what NASA does or
doesn't do, the efforts of small companies to create a new
generation of launch vehicles using private financing are doomed.
``Stepping aside and waiting for the private sector is not going to
work,'' said John Logsdon, director of the Space Policy Institute
at George Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no investment money for these little innovative
companies,'' Logsdon said. This is not NASA's fault, he says, but
rather a result of the general Wall Street aversion to risk, and
recent space-related business failures such as the Motorola-backed
Iridium global satellite cell-phone system, which declared
bankruptcy earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That market has kind of collapsed,'' Logsdon said.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's Smith agreed, saying that market projections for the
launch business ``have changed dramatically'' in the last few
years, and are ``nowhere near what they were,'' requiring NASA now
to take a more active role in supporting the development of
next-generation rockets.
</P>
<P>
   The critics counter that NASA itself has helped to chill the
investment climate, partly by choosing the riskiest of three
contenders for its X-33 project to develop a reusable demonstration
rocket.
</P>
<P>
   As many engineers predicted, that project has been plagued with
problems, is behind schedule and over budget, and has had serious
problems with the development of advanced composite-materials tanks
for liquid oxygen. Originally scheduled to fly this year, the
vehicle has been postponed indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's long-range plan, said aerospace engineer and consultant
Charles Lurio, a longtime advocate of the development of
inexpensive rockets, ``is a sequence of 10-year programs with the
proclaimed goal of slashing launch cost each decade, yet showing
every sign of building ever-higher the barriers'' to such cost
reduction. With its inclusion of far-flung technologies like
antimatter propulsion and long electromagnetic catapults, he said,
the plan is ``like saying in 1930 that we need a supersonic
transport before we start carrying passengers through the air at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   What is needed instead, many engineers think, is a
less-expensive, faster, but less-glamorous series of small research
vehicles and ground-based tests to establish basic, reliable
technology, such as simple, long-lived rocket engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they need is boring research and development to make
robust technology,'' Lurio said.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is accusing the space agency of deliberately thwarting
progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think they're doing the right thing, they really do,''
said Kyger. But ``they don't see the unintended consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   And in this case, he said, the consequence could be disastrous
for the many startup companies hoping to build inexpensive reusable
rockets. ``What SLI will do,'' he said, ``is make sure all the new
guys don't get to build anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
