<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SUNGLASSES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 SUMMER EYEWEAR IS VARIED, VERSATILE, AND TINTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rose-colored glasses too cliche? Try yellow, green, purple, or
blue in oversized aviators, retro styles, or futuristic frames for
eyeshade chic this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But fashion shouldn't be the only guide when choosing a tint.
Think neutral-colored lenses, such as gray or green, for the most
versatile protection and comfort. For driving cars (or golf balls),
try brown because it offers definition, the easier to find that
Titleist in the rough. Yellow and amber lenses work best where
depth perception is important _ and if you insist on wearing your
shades when the light is low.
</P>
<P>
   As for the season's trendiest tones, pink and blue, they distort
color. However, the sales pitch goes, the former can be pretty on
certain skin tones and blue can soothe.
</P>
<P>
   Polarized coatings block normal and horizontal rays that hit the
eye from reflected surfaces, making these lenses among the most
comforting to the eyes, especially when on the beach or in a boat.
</P>
<P>
   Keep those mirrored lenses around next winter for the ski slopes
because they block additional light.
</P>
<P>
   There's a common myth that darker lenses offer the most
protection _ from the sun or being recognized. But if the tint's
too dark, it can impair vision.
</P>
<P>
   That sorted, what's the difference between a $10 pair of
sunglasses and a $400 pair? It's not as simple as KMart or Gucci.
After all, you can find sunglasses with 100 percent protection
against ultraviolet rays _ which can cause cataracts and wrinkles
around the eyes _ even in some of the least pricey models. And all
glasses must meet the same government standard for shatter
resistance and lens retention.
</P>
<P>
   Some plastic designer glasses are handmade of cellulose acetate,
which is more likely to lose its shape if left on the dashboard of
a hot car, says Foster Grant's Mark Flanagan. And glass lenses,
heavier and costlier, are not as shatter-proof as plastic, although
they provide the clearest view and can reduce the likelihood of
headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, high-end retailers insist design detail, lens
quality, fit, frame material and overall durability can be worth
the extra expense. To say nothing of the logo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
