<HEADER>
A1903 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-DRAGONFLY-BOS &LR;      07-03 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DRAGONFLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARING NOVEL OF A WEST INDIAN GIRL'S STRUGGLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
MAMZELLE DRAGONFLY 
By Raphael Confiant (translated, from the French, by Linda
Coverdale) 
Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, 169 pp., $22 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the tree, Adelise tells her secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the far end of her mother's garden, the flowering
mangrove tree is her confidant, her soul mate. For hours at a time,
Adelise wraps her arms around its trunk, her heart pounding against
its bark, her feet planted near the roots where her mother buried
her umbilical cord. Such is their bond that each new dawn, Adelise
even eats some of the tree's small white blossoms.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother chastises her preoccupation with the tree, accusing
Adelise of being oblivious to reality, of breezing through life
``like dragonflies fluttering over waterlilies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You must learn every evening to think on all the things you
promised yourself to accomplish during the day, and if you happened
to succeed perfectly with a single one, then you can give into
contentment,'' her mother says. ``That's the lesson life teaches
us, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyrical yet unsentimental, Raphael Confiant's ``Mamzelle
Dragonfly'' tells of the harsh lessons life teaches Adelise, a girl
on the tenuous edge of womanhood. Set amid the social and political
restlessness of a 1950s Martinique clamoring for independence from
France, this is a novel of hardship endured, and about how a girl
learns to separate her mind and body from the circumstances and
people who threaten to tear her apart.
</P>
<P>
   Adelise is only 14 when she first goes to work for the
blanc-pays _ rich white landowners on her West Indian island. ``In
the middle of the sun's fierce dance,'' she would toil with the
other children _ ``the li'l gangs'' _ tying together bundles of
sugar cane felled by the relentless cutlasses of the men. Though
her mother warns Adelise about the boys, it is the adult field
commanders who pose the biggest threat to the girls, raping them
repeatedly in the rough grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I wondered why Rosalie claimed that making love was
a thing as sweet as honey-dipped sugar. I didn't understand because
I felt absolutely nothing. Nothing at all,'' Adelise says. ``I'd be
lying on the bare ground, watching the men's eyeballs roll back,
listening to their chuffing in their throats, while their hands
stroked all over my skin and their loins thrust roughly into mine.
What pleasure could they possibly take in that?''
</P>
<P>
   Here, Adelise learns to escape her own body, to become ``harder
and harder, hard as iron.'' It is an ability that serves her well
when she is sent from her tiny hamlet to Fort-de-France, a mean,
teeming city, to live with her aunt Philomene. Though Adelise's
mother is the younger sister, Philomene is everything Adelise's
mother is not. She is chatty and bawdy, full of stories and advice
for Adelise.
</P>
<P>
   Philomene is also a prostitute. She tells her niece, ``just
because I'm a whore doesn't mean you have to become one too. I
didn't choose this trade, I was dragged into it by poverty and bad
luck _ they're what brought me to the life.'' But within a year,
Adelise, now 17, is turning tricks as well because, as Philomene
tells her, ``It's not pretty, but what can I say? When you're born
hard up, there's stuff you've got to do to survive.'' There's much
money a ``little black virgin'' can make among ``the big
bourgeois,'' Philomene says to Adelise.
</P>
<P>
   And so Adelise detaches herself, allowing men time and again to
take her body, while she keeps her spirit pure and whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dolled myself up in elegant dresses, cancan petticoats,
streetwalker kicks, colliers-chou, and all kinds of fancy
fripperies, but they didn't matter to me,'' Adelise says. ``Not a
snap. My body did not belong to me, I'd lost it with the passing
days, only my heart remained mine, and what brooded there was
heartache beyond measure for my tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Confiant's searing writing recalls the work of Edwidge Danticat,
the acclaimed young Haitian-American author of ``Krik? Krak!'' and
``The Farming of Bones.'' There is a similar wonder and beauty
here, one that never quite softens his most difficult passages, but
wraps them in the sad, lovely poetry of a wounded yet resilient
soul.
</P>
<P>
   In his native Martinique, Confiant has published several
award-winning novels, and is considered an important figure in
French literarature. With ``Mamzelle Dragonfly,'' Confiant's first
novel translated into English, the rest of the world may soon
understand why.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
