A1906 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-HENIG-BOS &LR;      07-03 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HENIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENES, AT THE START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE MONK IN THE GARDEN 
The Lost and Found Genius of Gregor Mendel, the Father of
Genetics. 
By Robin Marantz Henig. Houghton Mifflin. 292 pp. $24. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The race to map the human genome reached fruition last week,
with promises of a revolution in medicine spurred by reading out
the genetic scripts in our own DNA.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Genome Project has been the epitome of Big Science:
scientific teams collaborating across vast distances, costly
supercomputers and robot gene-readers, published papers with dozens
of authors' names.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes the timing of Robin Marantz Henig's excellent book
about the ``father of genetics'' just about perfect. The work of
Gregor Mendel, who lived from 1822 to 1884, was rediscovered just a
century ago this year: It had lain ignored for 35 years after he
reported his revelations about heredity, which ultimately
galvanized a new generation of biologists who went on to discover
genes, chromosomes, and DNA _ all unknown to Mendel.
</P>
<P>
   Mendel's story, as delightfully told in ``The Monk in the
Garden,'' is miles away from Big Science. It's the tale of a
solitary researcher, a rotund, cigar-loving (as many as 20 a day)
cleric who carried out his experiments while leading a simple life
in a monastery. He had, and needed, little equipment except pen and
paper, seeds and a sunny garden, and penetrating intelligence _ as
well as immense patience.
</P>
<P>
   Mendel's historic work was carried out in the St. Thomas
monastery in Brno, in what is now the Czech Republic. In tediously
systematic breeding experiments between 1857 and 1863, Mendel
examined more than 28,000 pea plants in an effort to understand how
individual traits _ like height, seed shape, seed pod color, and so
forth _ were passed along from one generation to another.
</P>
<P>
   The question was of more than academic interest. Agricultural
improvement was a hot topic, but scientists could not yet predict
what succeeding generations of sheep or fruit trees, for example,
would look like. It was mainly a trial-and-error process.
</P>
<P>
   The going theory was that if you crossed (bred) strains of
plants or animals with differing traits, the offspring would
display ``blended'' or intermediate traits: tall plants crossed
with short ones would yield medium-sized offspring, contrasting
colors would converge toward an in-between hue.
</P>
<P>
   Mendel disproved this. His hard-won insights, which would point
the way toward the discovery of chromosomes and genes in the traits
are inherited as pure units _ not blended _ and the traits reappear
in successive generations in mathematically predictable ratios.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, said Mendel, the two units of each trait, one from
the father and one from the mother, are passed randomly to the
offspring. That is, any offspring can have any combination of
paternal and maternal traits. He showed that some ``factors'' _
what we now call genes _ are dominant and determine the offsprings'
appearance, even though recessive factors persist and will show up
in future generations.
</P>
<P>
   But his work, conveyed in two reports to a local society and in
a few letters, was virtually ignored until 35 years later. As one
contemporary put it, ``not a soul believed his experiments were
anything more than a pastime, and his theories anything more than
the maunderings of a harmless putterer.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1900, three researchers independently made similar findings
and discovered they had been beaten to them by Mendel.
</P>
<P>
   Henig's account of Mendel and the conflicting scientific
currents of his time is rich, clear, and filled with wonderful
evocations of Mendel's world. In her research, she gleaned so many
details of place, weather, sounds, and sights that the book has an
unexpectedly sensual texture making it as pleasurable to read as a
superbly written travelogue.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is she afraid to speculate about the many unresolved issues
surrounding Mendel, most of whose papers were burned. What did he
think he was pursuing in his experiments? Did he believe in
evolution? Did he fudge his data or perhaps even do all his
experiments on paper, not bothering to crossbreed the plants?
</P>
<P>
   Some of the questions are unanswerable, yet arguing and
speculation continue to this day, reflecting the fascination that
still surrounds Mendel, whom Henig calls, ``a gentle
revolutionary'' born a generation too soon to be understood in his
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
