<HEADLINE>
THE KID WIZARD GEETS EVEN BIGGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (e and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harry Potter, meet Bugs Bunny. Bugs, meet Harry.
</P>
<P>
   When the fourth Harry Potter novel is released this Saturday
amid a feeding frenzy of young and not-so-young fans, it will mark
the fourth chapter of the astounding tale of a once-obscure author
who has sold some 20 million books in the United States in less
than two years. But the feverish midnight unveiling will not begin
to equal the carefully planned, long-term campaign of Potterabilia
that will eventually put Scottish author J. K. Rowling's kid wizard
on everything from the silver screen to boxer shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros., the company that brings us Looney Tunes and Batman
among others, has not merely cut a deal for the movie rights to the
first of four of what Rowling says will eventually be seven Potter
tomes. One of the company's divisions, Warner Bros. Worldwide
Consumer Products, has licensed more than 45 companies _ including
toymaking giants Hasbro Inc. and Mattel Inc. _ to produce Harry
Potter paraphernalia aimed largely at 8- to 13-year-olds. Thus the
day isn't far away when they can eat Harry Potter candy, slip into
Harry Potter socks, sit on Harry Potter furniture, drink from Harry
Potter mugs, peer through Harry Potter sunglasses, and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a big one,'' said James Mammarella, editor
and associate publisher of License!, a trade magazine. A few
moments later, Mammarella bestowed perhaps an even higher
compliment upon Warner Bros.' new franchise: ``It's toyetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Toyetic?
</P>
<P>
   ``It translates well into toys and games,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, people are already wild about the untoyetic Harry.
About 21 million copies of J. K. (for Joanne Kathleen) Rowling's
trio of yarns about the boy who wears owlish glasses and attends
the Hogwarts School for Witchcraft and Wizardry have been printed
in the United States. Scholastic Press has ordered an initial run
of 3.8 million copies of the upcoming, 752-page ``Harry Potter and
the Goblet of Fire,'' making it what the company says is the
largest first printing in the history of domestic book publishing.
And Rowling, an unpublished author when she wrote the beginnings of
the first Potter book on scraps of paper in an Edinburgh cafe, has
become an international literary cult figure.
</P>
<P>
   But reviews of the selling of Harry Potter _ the movies, the
T-shirts, the coffee mugs, and so forth _ are mixed. At the East
Boston branch of the Boston Public Library, children's librarian
Anne Kelly says she worries that the November 2001 release of the
movie ``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone'' will rob young
readers of their own inventiveness. ``Now kids will be shown what
Harry looks like instead of imagining him,'' Kelly lamented. ``And
nobody knows what he really sounds like. But now they will.''
</P>
<P>
   But although Kelly says she finds the array of upcoming Potter
products ``cheapening,'' she doesn't think they will drive young
readers away from the books. ``Kids are just so used to everything
arriving in an integrated package,'' she said. ``Besides, someday
the merchandise will die away, and the kids will just have the
books. And they'll read them.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be good news to Lisa Burkin, advertising and
promotions manager at WordsWorth Books in Cambridge, Mass. Burkin,
who has seen merchandise effectively promote such children's
literary characters as the mischievous monkey Curious George and
the young sleuth Tintin, cautions that Potter could conceivably die
from overkill. ``If they dump everything into the market all at
once, I don't think that would be great for the books,'' she said.
``Too much of a good thing kills the golden goose. And whatever
they merchandise should be smart and attractive. It should fit with
the ambience and the mood of the book.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Rowling has said she did not want her books and
their characters to be overwhelmed by related merchandise. This
week she declined, through the office of her London agent,
Christopher Little, to discuss upcoming Potter-related products and
movies, as did Little himself. Scholastic Press, meanwhile, played
down the notion that the literary Potter will be lost in the wake
of the toyetic Potter. ``The books are so unique and distinct that
we're confident they'll last forever,'' said Chris Moran, a company
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Warner Bros. is describing a slow-build,
three-wave campaign to bring Harry Potter merchandise into American
homes. Since acquiring the rights to all things Potter in mid-1998,
about a year after the first volume was released in England but
about three months before it was published in the United States,
the company has bided its time waiting until its movie is on the
horizon. The first wave will arrive in August with items connected
to the first book (a.k.a. ``the literary property'') being sold in
the 140 Warner Bros. Studio Stores. The next wave involves selling
similar items in upscale specialty and department stores beginning
in October. And, finally, Wave III: As release of the movie version
of the first book (``the film property'') approaches next year, a
batch of new items will be released in mass-market stores.
</P>
<P>
   (Those who can't wait are already bidding on Internet auction
sites for Warner Bros. and Scholastic Press trade promotion items
such as baseball caps, tote bags, and candy.)
</P>
<P>
   All this may seem to add up to a tidal wave, but George Jones,
president of worldwide licensing and Warner Bros. Studio Stores,
calls the plan ``judicious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've turned down tons and tons of proposals and products that
weren't true to the book,'' Jones said. ``A Harry Potter potty seat
was actually proposed, for example. But we want to be true to the
audience that loves this book. And in certain key categories,
within our licensing arrangements, we've put limitations in our
contracts on the numbers of units that can be shipped. That assures
us we won't have overkill.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. contends that Rowling has a significant role in the
oncoming stream of Potterabilia. ``She is a creative and business
partner in every aspect of the project,'' said Barbara Brogliatti,
the company's vice president of corporate communications. ``She's
involved in everything. It's a unique Hollywood partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   The first Potter movie will begin filming in England in October
and is budgeted at between $90 million and $100 million. It will be
directed by Christopher Columbus, who directed ``Home Alone'' and
``Mrs. Doubtfire.'' Steve Kloves, who wrote ``The Fabulous Baker
Boys,'' will adapt the book to the screen. Despite rumors, Warner
Bros. says no stars have been signed for the movie, not even the
thousands of applicants who have responded to the company's
Internet casting call. ``We are looking for British children,
between the ages of 9 and 11,who look like Harry Potter, Ron
Weasley or Hermione Granger,'' the studio's Harry Potter Web site
declares, referring to the book's main characters. ``You can become
a Junior Talent Scout by urging them to send a recent picture and
videotape to us!''
</P>
<P>
   The acknowledged measure of a successful merchandising push such
as the one being planned for young Harry Potter is $1 billion in
revenues. According to Sandie Hatch, executive vice president of
the Licensing Industry Merchandisers Association, the boy wizard is
considered a good bet to achieve this benchmark, and has earned a
new name in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the trade,'' said Hatch, ``they're already calling him a
billion-dollar boy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
