<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !!! &LR;  ``The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle'' Another TV
cartoon makes it to the big screen. Jay Ward's flying squirrel and
moose pal have been reinvented, via computer, in color and 3-D.
They play against real actors Jason Alexander and Rene Russo as
Boris and Natasha, still henchmen to their old boss turned
capitalist, Robert De Niro. Sunny, funny and fresh, it revels in
its airhead buoyancy. (PG) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! &LR;  ``The Patriot'' Mel Gibson makes all the difference in the
American Revolution. Loosely modeled on Francis Marion, the
so-called Swamp Fox who mired the Redcoats in guerrilla warfare,
he's a South Carolina widower farmer with seven children who hangs
back as the war begins, but gets involved when his idealistic sons
do. The heroics are sheer Hollywood cornball, the combat scenes
often bloody _ but the film works rousingly. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! &LR;  1/2 ``The Perfect Storm'' The working-class ``Titanic'' _ and
then some. Closely following Sebastian Junger's bestseller about
what happened to a boatful of Gloucester fishermen when three storm
systems collided in the North Atlantic in 1991, it unleashes a
spectacular screenful of storm effects. But what makes it special
is the determination of the cast, headed by George Clooney and Mark
Wahlberg, to depict the fishermen and their world with veracity and
respect. (PG-13)
</P>
</TEXT>
