<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ECON (Mexico City) _ On how the market and the currency
reacted Monday to the election results. (Staff byline to come)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Chechen guerrillas killed at least 36
Russian soldiers and wounded scores in five suicide bomb attacks on
Russian security force bases over a 24-hour period, Russian
authorities said on Monday. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIANS-STATEHOOD (Jerusalem) _ Perhaps averting a crisis
in September, the Palestinian Authority was expected to vote Monday
to defer its declaration of statehood from September to the end of
the year. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-AUSTRIA (Paris) _ Austria's far-right political leader
Joerg Haider said on Monday that his country would block reforms to
European Union institutions due to be agreed upon later this year
unless bilateral political sanctions on Vienna were lifted. By
Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-GAY-PRIDE (Rome) _ The latest World Gay Pride vs. the
Vatican dust-up: The pope on Sunday instructed a French bishop not
to take part in a symposium on religion and homosexuality. He
obeyed and didnt speak at the conference, but spoke his mind to
reporters outside the room. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-IMMIG (Beijing) _ The head of the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service and other INS officials met Monday with
Chinese officials to try to stem illegal immigration. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-PRESCRIPTIONS (Undated) _ Vice President Al Gore, fresh
from an attack on big oil, is toughening his assault on drug
manufacturers by blaming ``drug company price-gouging'' for the
soaring cost of prescriptions. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-MEMORIAL (Washington) _ Thousands of Vietnam veterans
whose names were not included on the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in
Washington because they did not die from battle-related injuries or
accidents will now be honored there. Under legislation signed by
President Clinton last month, a plaque will soon be erected to
honor veterans who died from exposure to Agent Orange,
post-traumatic stress disorder and other causes not directly
related to combat wounds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SYPHILIS-ERADICATE (Nashville, Tenn.) _ The new jail inmate had
intimidating arms, thick as thighs. But he extended one meekly when
a nurse, Jean Graves, told him: ``I have to give you a tuberculosis
skin test. I also have to draw blood for syphilis, O.K.?'' As she
slid the needle into his skin, Nashville took one more small step
in a sweeping national program: a push by health authorities to rid
the country of the ancient scourge of syphilis, spirochete
bacterium by spirochete, chancre sore by chancre, once and for all.
Even here, where the syphilis rate is second-highest in the country
among major cities, topped only by Indianapolis, the numbers are
less than staggering: Only 250 cases of new _ and thus still
infectious _ syphilis turned up last year. Nationwide, they dropped
below 7,000, down from the most recent peak of 50,000 in 1990. But
that is the very point, health officials say. Now, when new cases
are at an all-time low and so concentrated that about half of them
come from just 25 of the country's 3,100 counties, is the time to
try to wipe it out altogether. They are prosecuting a multipronged
attack that includes heavy reliance on community activism and
stepped-up detective work to track down carriers and those at risk,
as well as expanded clinical and laboratory services. By Carey
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-BUSINESS (Undated) _ In the world of Internet startups,
where a typical chief executive is 30 and a labor shortage
continues even as some Web companies fail, dot-commers are
recruiting their own parents. This curious form of nepotism is
upending traditional notions about family businesses. By Katie
Hafner.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT20,21, sent on June 20.
</P>
<P>
   ENERGY-PRICES (Undated) _ After a summer of high gasoline
prices, a winter of surging heating oil and natural gas prices
already looms. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-FIREWORKS (Shanghai) _ The United States celebrates
its freedom on July 4 by blowing up tons of ornamental ordnance put
together by the world's last major Communist power. But with every
oooh and aaah Americans utter Tuesday night, the trade deficit will
expand by another couple hundred dollars. Even many of the little
U.S. flags that people wave at parades are made in China. By Craig
S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ In a session shortened in anticipation of
the July 4 holiday, stocks closed higher: The Dow Jones industrial
average closed up 112 points, the S&AMP;P 500 up 14 points and the
Nasdaq composite up 25 points. By Danny Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   Editors, because U.S. markets will be closed July 4, there will
be no MARKETPLACE column.
</P>
<P>
   HONG-KONG-TELECOM (Hong Kong) _ Having won the largest takeover
battle in Asian corporate history, Richard Li, the thirty-something
tycoon whose deal-making has riveted Hong Kong, must now
demonstrate that he can run an empire as effectively as he acquired
it. Minority shareholders of Cable and Wireless HKT voted
overwhelmingly Monday to be acquired by Li's Internet company,
Pacific Century Cyberworks. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-INFLATION (Moscow) _ President Vladimir Putin gave an
unusually blunt warning Monday about rising inflation after
consumer prices in June rose 2.5 percent above May levels. Such a
rise would indicate that the booming Russian economy is beginning
to overheat. By Sabrina Tavernise.
</P>
<P>
