<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASSWORD-OVERLOAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MANY PASSWORDS, TOO LITTLE (HUMAN) MEMORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Password'' was a 1960s TV game show in which contestants
guessed at a hidden word while their partners fed them clues.
Imagine the show retooled for today's numerically overloaded world:
Win cash for reciting your computer passwords, ATM PINs, calling
card numbers, and home-security codes in 60 seconds or less.
</P>
<P>
   No clues. No crib sheets. Final answer?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even remember my own cell phone number,'' moans Art
Jahnke. ``Two of my computer passwords are kept in an online
repository, but I forget the password to that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Jahnke, Web editorial director for CIO.com, counts five computer
passwords to go along with his bank PIN, his wife's phone and fax
numbers, and a home alarm system whose entry code he can't
remember, either. He mostly picks names of dependents, Jahnke says,
but even that strategy has its limits. Because he keeps blanking on
how to access his online Wall Street Journal account, he
re-registers under new user IDs _ to the point that he would now
need octuplets to keep up with the Dow Joneses.
</P>
<P>
   Others favor the unrequited-love angle to password mnemonics.
For her bank PIN, says consultant Gina Addis of ML Strategies, ``I
use my old boyfriend's phone number at a Bar Harbor, Maine, bar
where he worked in 1983. I remember it because the guy was such a
louse that I was always trying to chase him down.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston TV investigative reporter Hank Phillippi Ryan relies on a
popular device frowned on by most computer security experts: the
one-key-fits-all approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I can manage the password problem is to just
flatly make them all the same,'' says Ryan. ``Without
standardization, I'd be lost.''
</P>
<P>
   For her computer, Ryan settled on the name of a childhood pet.
When most passwords grew longer than four letters, ``I'd add
something like NYT for my New York Times account,'' she says.
``Since I kept forgetting those, now I just use the pet's name
twice.''
</P>
<P>
   If all this PIN-dropping makes you feel as if you're retaking a
high school trigonometry final, take heart. Professional organizer
Elaine Bloom of Maplewood, N.J., says even pros like her are
singing the Password Overload Blues these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't figured out any good way of dealing with the problem
either for myself or my clients,'' Bloom admits. ``I tend to make
them all similar types of things, but I know experts say that's not
the smartest thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Arnold of Passlogix suggests a service like his company's
free download system (www.passlogix .com). One password leads you
to a customized icon that opens all online accounts, says Arnold,
who cofounded the company three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stood in the parking lot of a CompUSA store for three days,
asking people how many passwords they had,'' says Arnold. ``The
average person had seven or more, so clearly there was a problem
there.''
</P>
<P>
   There's more good news. Several companies are working on
fingerprint, face-, and voice-recognition technology that could
soon make passwords obsolete. Also, the IRS has begun issuing
5-digit PINs for online filing. Should you forget the number,
agents will track down that ex-boyfriend for you, so you won't have
to file late. As for the garage-door code, IRS officials say,
you're on your own.
</P>
</TEXT>
