<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1926 &Cx1f; sci-z
u v BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     07-03 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, July 4:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GREEK-FOSSILS (Undated) _ A classical folklorist and
independent scholar has dug deep into the past and found literary
and artistic clues _ and not a few huge fossils _ that seem to
explain the inspiration for many of the giants, monsters and other
strange creatures in the mythology of antiquity. Greeks'
perceptions about fossils, she discovered, were quite amazing for
prescientific people. Her years of research thus challenge the
widely held view that natural historians in classical Greece and
Rome lacked the knowledge to interpret large vertebrate fossils as
organic remains of the past. By John Noble Wilford. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT5.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PROTEIN-SHAPES (San Diego) _ With the human genome sequence
nearly complete, scientists are gearing up for a follow-on project
that some say could be every bit as ambitious. The endeavor is
known as structural genomics and involves trying to determine the
three-dimensional shapes of thousands upon thousands of proteins,
much as genomics determined the sequences of genes en masse.
Knowing the shape of the protein lock could make it easier to
design drugs that act as keys, binding to some particular protein
and turning it on or off. By Andrew Pollack. (2100 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PROTEIN-XRAY (Undated) _ Protein shapes are usually
discerned by X-ray crystallography, a process that in some ways
resembles a CAT scan. An X-ray is taken from multiple angles and a
computer uses that data to calculate a three-dimensional image. By
Andrw Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SAGE-GROUSE (Undated) _ A new species of bird has emerged
from research in the sagebrush ecosystem of western Colorado and
eastern Utah, according to scientists working there. The bird, the
Gunnison sage grouse, named for the area of Colorado where it was
discovered, has been in plain view all along _ seen, hunted as a
game bird and, most spectacularly, heard at sunrise every spring as
part of one of the avian world's oddest courtship rituals. But it
had long been assumed to be the same species as the related
northern sage grouse, even though the two differ starkly in size,
appearance, behavior. By Jon Luoma. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ENVIRON-RIVETS () _ In trying to illuminate what humans are
doing to the natural environment, scientists and conservationists
over the years have come up with a number of descriptive images.
One of the best known is the metaphor of the rivets. In this
formulation, an ecosystem is likened to an airplane: each act of
environmental destruction _ the extinction of a species of plant or
animal, for instance _ is akin to removing a rivet from the plane.
At first, the losses make little difference, because there are lots
of rivets. But if enough are removed or a few are taken away at
crucial spots, the plane will crash. An essay by William K.
Stevens. (1370 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-YOUNG-FISH () _ The typical saltwater fish's childhood is
something of a lost time, at least for scientists trying to study
it. Not much is known about what happens during most fishes' larval
stages, when they are tiny and floating in the plankton in the
swirling waters. And that has led to a great question in marine
ecology: are fish populations open, with young fish shuttling in
and out across great distances, or closed, with juveniles largely
settling back where they were born? By Henry Fountain. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on meteor
flashes, using balloons to get equipment to the edge of space and
using fruit flies to study malaria. By Henry Fountain. (675 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VIRTUAL-MEDICINE (Seattle) _ Virtual reality now is being
used in medicine: it's helping distract burn patients so they feel
less pain, it's being used to alleviate phobias and it's even
helping people to relax and unclog blood vessels. By Jim Robbins.
(1560 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LOCAL-ANESTHESIA (Undated) _ Doctors recently performed a
heart bypass on a patient using only a local anesthesia. It was
believed to be the first such operation in the United States, but
some doctors are optimistic that many more now can be done, at
least in certain circumstances, like a single bypass. By Denise
Grady. (1075 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PSYCHIATRY (Undated) _ A complex but pervasive problem in
psychiatry. It can be frustrating and, at times, nigh impossible,
to sort out where ``reality'' lies in the no man's land between the
patient's preconceptions and distortions of reality and those of
the therapist. In the strange, delicate, dyadic relationship
between patient and therapist, the events of the outside world can
become surprisingly elusive. The case of a patient claiming to be a
famous European artist illustrates the point. By Anna Fels, M.D.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal health column: Hiking
has loads of health benefits, but veterans and beginners alike
should prepare to avoid catastrophes, pain and inconveniences. By
Jane E. Brody. (1225 words0
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER-BOOK (Undated) _ Books on Health: With thousands of
cancer patients seeking alternative and complementary medicine,
``The Journey Through Cancer'' by Dr. Jeremy Geffen seems a timely
addition to the medical bookshelf. By Laurie Tarkan. (420 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MEDICINE-SUPERSTITION (Undated) _ Don't take the scientist's
objective observation for granted, cautions Dr. Sherwin B. Nuland
in ``The Mysteries Within.'' Until the 19th century, the greatest
thinkers in medicine (Hippocrates, Galen, Paracelsus) turned to
supernatural powers, superstition, fanciful spirits and energies to
fill the holes in their medical theories. By Laurie Tarkan. (420
words)
</P>
<P>
   VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ A new study shows that the blood vessels of vigorous older
people functioned as well as those of athletes less than half their
age. (190 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A hormone produced in pregnancy has been found to reduce
symptoms of scleroderma, a debilitating skin disease that has
previously been considered untreatable, a study says. (335 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ The chickenpox vaccine is working on both children who take
and on those who don't. Rates are way down for the contagious
disease in Los Angeles. (250 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Migraine headaches strike teenagers most commonly on Mondays
and most rarely on Saturdays, according to a study presented in
June. But researchers do not think that malingering is the reason:
instead, it probably is stress, anxiety or changing sleep patterns.
(190 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ The most detailed study to date of the acute respiratory
attacks suffered by sickle-cell anemia patients has led researchers
to call for more aggressive tactics in diagnosis and treatment.
(260 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: Is a third
whale involved in whale mating? By C. Claiborne Ray. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Some ScienceTimes stories are available to international clients
only by special arrangement, and are so marked. Asian and European
points: contact Karl Horwitz in Paris for details and prices
(Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX: 47-42-80-44). Latin American points:
contact Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX:
310-996-0089).
</P>
