<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JULY4-CONSUMERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    July 4 the ideal time to promote individual independence
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - What better day to promote independence than July
4?
</P>
<P>
   The steps we take toward our own independence are significant _
whether we're an infant rolling over for the first time, a teen
coping with disability or a widow or widower rebuilding a life
after the loss of a spouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Independence is a Western value, not a universally held
value,'' explains clinical psychologist Judith Schwartzman. ``In
other cultures around the world, the emphasis is on the well-being
of the group, the family, society as a whole rather than the
well-being of any one individual.''
</P>
<P>
   But the United States, she says, was built on a platform of
individual liberty. ``It was a value of the individuals who founded
and shaped this nation and it is strongly ingrained our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there are products and services designed to foster
independence at every age and every stage of our lives. We've
assembled a few in honor of the holiday:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  It isn't just E.T. who should know how to phone home. Kids
need to know as well. The Teaching Telephone from Pretend &AMP; Play is
a programmable telephone on which little ones can practice dialing
911 as well as their own home phone ($39.99 at Zany Brainy).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Taking a course at a college or community center can teach
skills that will help us stand on our two feet. Colleges offer
courses ranging from home car repair to PC keyboarding and from
Internet skills to career planning.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Learning to read is a terrific way to promote independence,
and summer is the perfect time to pick up a book. Kids can sign up
for one of the reading clubs at bookstores and libraries where
specially themed programs and incentives are offered.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of terrific books and products to help someone
learn to read. Among them: the Bob Books for beginning readers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Swimming is fun, great exercise and may even save a life.
Check out lessons at local YMCA's, private clubs and community
centers. If you're an adult who's afraid of the water, private
classes can be arranged.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Author John Cassidy has come up with an innovative way to
teach kids how to tell time in The Time Book (Klutz, $12.95).
Attached to the book is a battery-included kid's watch. The sturdy
wire-bound book is cleverly illustrated by Roger Bollen and
includes lots of interesting ``Time Factoids''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The inventive mind behind ``Arthritically Correct'' belongs to
Frank Halstead, a California entrepreneur who has come up with a
group of products for those who need a helping hand. Items, priced
from $2 to $7 each, range from Comfort Clips (small
elastic-and-nylon clips that replace shoelaces) to the EZ-KEY, a
key-turning device that eliminates the pain involved in turning a
key in a balky or sticky lock. Halstead also makes citrus peelers,
a patented handle and more. Check out his website at
www.arthritisstoreusa.com. or call toll-free (888) 511-7367.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Potty training is an important step on the road to
independence. In addition to the little seats, there are videos and
books designed to make the job easier. At Toys R Us, check out
his-and-hers versions of ``Once Upon a Potty'' in either book and
video form. The video is $13.99, the book sells for about $6. The
Duke Family Series''''It's Potty Time'' video is approved by Duke
University Medical Center ($13.99).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``WE'' magazine is a terrific resource for people with
disabilities and their families. The upbeat glossy magazine
features lifestyle articles on subjects ranging from sports and
travel to fashion and the arts, and profiles individuals with
disabilities, including Michael J. Fox, Muhammad Ali and Itzhak
Perlman. The bimonthly magazine is available at bookstores; you can
also call (800) 936-2426. A subscription is $12.95 a year. Check
out the Web site at www.wemedia.com. The company will launch a
shopping mall soon with products ranging from clothes and books to
wheelchairs and adaptive equipment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A lot of our books are written in such a way that children
are able to complete the crafts and activities with little or no
help from adults,'' says Kellie Cullihall of Kids Can Press in New
York. In `` kids learn to grow tomatoes, build a composter, make a
scarecrow, plan a peace garden or build a sunflower fort. In ``The
Kids Can Press Jumbo Cookbook,'' they learn to whip up tacos,
pizza, lasagna roll-ups, vegetable curry or brownies ($14.95 each).
The company also publishes a Kids Can Do It craft series, a Kids
Can Easy Craft series and a Starting With Science Series.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``An important part of the learning process is for children to
learn to do things on their own,'' says Rochelle Hartigan, general
manager of a Zany Brainy.
</P>
<P>
   One example: Taking those first steps is fun with V-Tech's First
Steps Plus. The activity walker is designed for children ages 6 to
36 months. After they are walking, the activity board can be
detached; it includes letters, numbers, a phone and more ($49.99 at
Zany Brainy).
</P>
<P>
   Another toy that promotes walking: Elmo's Bubble Tunes from
Fisher Price. The push-along bubble maker is ideal for backyard
fun. Kids push Elmo in his ice-cream truck and bubbles come out
while music plays. For children 18 months and older; available at
toy stores ($19.99).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
