<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1948 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-POPE-GAY-PRIDE-(TRIM)     07-03 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-GAY-PRIDE-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOP BARRED BY POPE FROM GAY PRIDE EVENT SPEAKS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Skirting a Vatican order to withdraw from a gay pride
seminar on religion and homosexuality, Bishop Jacques Gaillot sat
on a couch outside a hotel conference room Monday and explained
where he thinks the Roman Catholic Church has erred.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church should not have second-class citizens,'' said
Gaillot of France. ``Homosexuals have the same right to tolerance
and dignity as any other group.'' He explained that he was called
on Sunday by his French superiors and told that the pope had asked
that he not participate in the event, part of the seven-day gay
pride festival called World Pride Roma 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am being loyal and obedient to the pope,'' said Gaillot, who
skipped the seminar but instead discussed the order with the press.
``But the pope has done me a great service in creating an event out
of me.'' Gaillot, who was removed from his diocese in Evreux in
1995 for his leftist views, added, ``Nobody would be asking me for
interviews had it not been for the pope's intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   World Pride Roma 2000, which opened on Saturday, was timed to
coincide with a Holy Year of the Roman Catholic Church. Vatican
opposition elevated the Roman event into a tense political
battleground, pitting church leaders and many right-wing groups
against organizers and defenders of gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican's efforts to postpone the festival, and most
recently, its effort to silence a bishop whose views do not reflect
the Vatican's, has focused attention less on gay pride than on the
state of tolerance inside the Holy See.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a big difference in how the Vatican and American
church leaders approach homosexuality,'' said Francis De Bernardo,
a member of New Ways ministry, a religious association for gay
Catholics. ``U.S. bishops want outreach.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was not surprised by Rome's cold shoulder, citing the
Vatican's efforts to silence Jeannine Gramick and Robert Nugent, a
nun and priest who were ordered to end their ministry to gay men
and lesbians in 1999. ``But this thing with Bishop Gaillot is
disturbing. It shows there is not going to be even the hint of a
conversation between the church and the gays gathering here.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, there has mainly been conflict between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, as the Italian movie star Maria Grazia Cucinotta
cut a rainbow-colored ribbon, alongside Vladimir Luxuria, Italy's
best known drag queen, at the opening ceremony in the garden of the
Philharmonic Academy in Rome, about 700 demonstrators marched
trough central Rome with the neofascist group Forza Nuova. As riot
police looked on, the group paraded noisily, with fascist salutes
and banners that read, ``No Gay Pride.''
</P>
<P>
   A Catholic association, Centro Culturale Lepando, and a
right-wing party, National Alliance, organized a torchlit
seven-mile walk by 1,000 people to offer ``penance'' for the gay
pride event.
</P>
<P>
   At the Church of Santa Teresa d'Avila in Rome, a small group of
believers organized by the Committee for a Christian Rome recited a
rosary to atone for the city's decision to allow the gay pride
event.
</P>
<P>
   Riot police and bomb squads on Monday lined the entrance of the
Hotel Cicerone, near the Vatican, where gay pride meetings were
being held.
</P>
<P>
   The event, which organizers expect to draw more than 200,000 gay
men and women to Rome, was planned three years ago and initially
won the support of the city. But after the Vatican protested
earlier this year, Mayor Francesco Rutelli tried to persuade World
Pride organizers to postpone the event for a week. He contended
that its schedule _ which includes conferences, drag fashion shows
and a parade through Rome on Saturday _ could disturb the church's
events for this special jubilee year.
</P>
<P>
   When the organizers refused, Rutelli said the events would go on
as planned, but he withdrew the city's endorsement and its logo
from the banners. Prime Minister Giuliano Amato broke with many
leaders of his own center-left coalition by stating that the timing
of the gay pride festival during a Holy Year was ``inopportune.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic Church does not teach that homosexuality is a
sin, but that homosexual acts, as with adultery, are sinful. And
the Vatican views the timing of the gay pride event as an offense
to the church and to family values _ as well as a political cudgel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pains me to see that young people are being told that the
church is their enemy,'' said Cardinal Ersilio Tonini, an emeritus
archbishop who was one of the few church officials to address the
issue on television over the weekend. ``For us, they are always our
brothers and sons. But shouting about pride in this public event is
not right. The church has to tell the truth, even if that truth is
not fashionable.''
</P>
<P>
   The event expected to draw the most protest is Saturday's gay
pride parade, and the Coliseum has become the focus for the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say they will march to the Coliseum and form a ring
around it in defiance of the city, which refused to approve the
streets around it as part of the parade route.
</P>
<P>
   Right wing groups have said they will block marchers from
surrounding the structure, which they view as a shrine to Christian
martyrs. The Coliseum also has been adopted this year by human
rights groups and the Catholic Church as their symbol in their
fight against the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Historians say that no early Christians were actually fed to the
lions in the Coliseum, but church lore and Hollywood movies have
kept the legend alive. At Saturday's neofascist counter
demonstration, protesters held up banners that read, ``Gays at the
Coliseum? Only with Lions!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
