<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1952 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-DOT-COM-SURVIVAL-HNS &LR;      07-03 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOT-COM-SURVIVAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     UPSTART INTERNET COMPANIES GET A DOSE OF REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VANESSA HUA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sink, swim or change direction.
</P>
<P>
   That is what some Internet companies are doing, making changes
to their product, business plans and even their raison d'etre as
the market shakeout eliminates or consolidates weaker dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   After 18 months, for example, the founder of portal
Myownempire.com was forced to admit his nascent kingdom was
crumbling.
</P>
<P>
   His $500,000 in funding, given on faith from friends, family and
investors, was nearly gone in January, said founder Bob Haya, who
carried the job title ``king'' at the Redwood City-based company.
</P>
<P>
   Though he paid some of the workers in stock only, he had to pare
back his staff. The site, which promised shares of the company as
an incentive to users, wasn't attracting visitors fast enough, Haya
said. A meta-portal, Myownempire.com allowed users to search
multiple job, portals, and auction sites all at once, but it
suffered from a false perception that his on-line stock giveaways
were fraudulent.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than stick to the original concept, though, Haya salvaged
the parts that worked and transformed the company into an
information software developer, Coportal.com. From its high of 20
staffers and contractors, six stayed on. Soon after Haya's company
changed course, incubator CreateLabs in San Francisco bought the
personalization, rules-based software company.
</P>
<P>
   Haya considered seven different directions, including
application service provider, business tools maker and private
portal developer, before settling on his newest plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some neat stuff we didn't know we were sitting on, used
in the making of the site itself,'' said Haya, who brainstormed
with his workers on what to save. ``What a shame it would have been
to let that go to waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies who launched in new directions include San
Francisco-based Vergesoft.com, an information software company that
turned into Xmarksthespot.com, an on-line marketing company; Santa
Clara-based Beyond.com, a computer software e-tailer that now
develops software to build online stores; and Menlo Park-based
Mambo.com, a Net invitation site that spun off PayPlace.com, an
electronic payment site in April.
</P>
<P>
   In reinventing themselves, the companies may avoid the fate of
upscale e-tailers such as the British Boo.com and Foofoo.com,
on-line video merchant Reel.com in Emeryville and the Viacom-owned
toy store Redrocket.com, which shut down, sold off or licensed
their expensively developed technology and brand name at fire sale
prices.
</P>
<P>
   The rising dot-com body count _ driven by increased pressure for
profits, rabid competition and the lure of better prospects _ is
propelling the change, industry watchers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entrepreneurs and investors assumed that they would get it
right the first time and grow in record time on Internet models not
proven or known,'' said Robert LaBatt of the Gartner Group, a
technology market research firm. ``But that hasn't happened, by and
large.''
</P>
<P>
   Change is part of the nature of startups. Yet the rise and fall
of Internet companies happens more quickly and dramatically when
compared with other industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditional companies have time and space to grow slowly and
manage their growth, but lots of dot-coms felt they had no choice
but to have big-bang growth,'' said Andrew Bartels, an analyst at
Giga Information Group, a technology research firm. ``They're
playing with a lot more money, which requires them to adapt more
rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the need for change reflects the consequences of
too-easy funding for underdeveloped business plans, especially
during last year's glut of initial public stock offerings and
venture capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lazy capital funded companies it shouldn't have been
funding,'' said Dan Beldy, partner at Hummer Winblad, a San
Francisco venture capital outfit. ``When push came to shove, those
companies were faced with reality.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how detailed their projections, how thorough their
research, companies often may falter, or may stumble upon an
unforeseen opportunity even greater than the original, once they go
live.
</P>
<P>
   The key is to stay focused on building a business but still
adapt to roiling market conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those realizations don't happen until you go out and start
talking to customers and learn what the environment is about,''
said Neil Cohen, co-founder and chief marketing officer of Campsix,
a business incubator in San Francisco. ``Changing a business model
can help turn around an average or mediocre concept. It's a good
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and other analysts point to the success of companies that
reworked their business plans, such as the former Netscape
Communications, where revenues first came from selling its
browsers, then its servers and then as a portal.
</P>
<P>
   They also point to its acquirer, America Online, the Internet
service provider where revenue came initially from subscribers'
monthly charges. Since then it has added income from advertising
and from fees that other businesses pay to be featured on the
portal. The latest round of rebirths comes at a time of intense
scrutiny on Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to show profitability. Everyone has an eye on the
bottom line, whether an investor or analyst or a CEO,'' said
Merideth Medland, analyst at Jupiter Communications, an Internet
research firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
