<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1967 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-PHILLY-TECH-NYTS     07-03 1478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-PHILLY-TECH-NYTSF-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROTHERLY LOVE IT'S GOT, AND NOW THERE'S A TOUCH OF ENVY, TOO  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 &HT;    
 By DAVID J. WALLACE  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Like a character actor who takes roles as a
serial killer after years of playing the kindly uncle, civic
boosters here are trying to shed the cardigan sweater and the
sensible shoes. There is a palpable desire to be a technology hot
spot.
</P>
<P>
   But how? Over the last couple of years, Technophilly,
SiliconPhilly, Silicon ValleyForge, (at)Philly and Philacon Valley
have been floated in efforts to raise the region's brand awareness,
on the theory that recognition and corporate dollars would follow.
Some names have Web sites or printed materials behind them, but not
one of the monikers has stuck.
</P>
<P>
   As any athlete knows, nicknames are given, not manufactured.
Philadelphia is not as complacent and dowdy as its critics say. It
has its power lunchers, its venture capitalists who chat casually
about jaw-dropping sums. But it is not the technology mecca
envisioned by its boosters.
</P>
<P>
   And when the city was omitted from a Wall Street Journal list of
the top 20 technology areas last November, the slight touched off a
quest for attention that would have made the region's Quaker
settlers twitch uncomfortably.
</P>
<P>
   Civic leaders want an e-business scene, just as earlier civic
efforts tried to recognize the city's movie, restaurant and film
notables.
</P>
<P>
   The actor Will Smith, Ben Vaughn, a rocker, and the rap group
The Roots are hometown heroes, but the enduring reputation is ``The
Sound of Philadelphia,'' soul and pop music created by Kenny Gamble
and Leon Huff two decades ago. Movies recently filmed here include
the creepy ``Twelve Monkeys'' and ``The Sixth Sense,'' hardly the
stuff shown by the chamber of commerce to foster corporate
relocation.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia has long had an identity crisis, flanked on the
north by New York's financial and media capital and on the south by
the political capital, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Defining the region is exasperating because of its diversity,
said David Thornburgh, the executive director of the Pennsylvania
Economy League, a public policy and research organization. The
region encompasses some of the former steel towns of Pennsylvania
and the shore resorts of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Las Vegas or Detroit, where tourism or automotive
industries serve as bellwethers, Philadelphia companies enjoy a
strong reputation in credit, finance, insurance, medical education
and care, biotechnology and pharmaceutical research, among other
industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been no image defined in the public psyche since
`Rocky,''' Thornburgh said. ``But we could become the buckle on the
East Coast's money belt because of our location. And our strength
is in putting things together as an integrator.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as in San Francisco or Boston, there is no single
technology epicenter in the city. Philadelphia's downtown lofts and
19th-century storefronts now house computer graphics or e-business
start-ups and electronic-art galleries.
</P>
<P>
   That streetscape contrasts with acres of suburban office parks
where companies vie for room to grow alongside countless
consultants, training firms and support-service providers. Devon
Consulting, in the Main Line borough of Wayne, uses the parking lot
for advertising. A Plymouth Prowler sporting the company's logo
reminds clients that a successful referral may bring a week's use
of the car.
</P>
<P>
   Many argue that the region's reputation as a technology center
will grow as more companies migrate to the Internet. There are now
companies that excel in particular applications, among them SEI
Investments in Oaks, Pa., which provides technology services and
asset management for banks and investment companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we've never been able to birth a megacompany
like AOL, Microsoft or Sun Microsystems,'' said Howard Ross, an
adviser to emerging companies since the 1980s and a principal in
LLR Equity Partners, a new venture fund. ``But this area could wake
up and surprise itself.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for Ross' optimism is his argument that Boston and
San Jose, Calif., had the first significant concentrations of
venture capital, but the capital that creates companies is now
flowing into other areas.
</P>
<P>
   In just the last three years, more than $50 billion in wealth
was created on paper by three local companies. The charge has been
led by the Safeguard Scientifics Corp. of Wayne, Pa., a publicly
traded venture-capital investor, which backed two of the most
successful public offerings in 1999, Internet Capital Group and
VerticalNet.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the e-commerce activity is in the business-to-business
market, where less glamorous companies make the consumer dot-coms
look good by providing the systems and fulfillment processes that
power consumer Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Major corporations based here include QVC Network Inc., the
Comcast Corp., SAP Americas Inc. and Aetna U.S. Healthcare. Yet
there are several obstacles to growth, said Stephen Mullin, a
former commerce director for the City of Philadelphia who teaches
college courses on e-commerce and is a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   He points to a city tax structure that punishes companies by
taxing both wages and net profits as one explanation as to why most
of the expansion has been in the suburbs instead of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to distinguish itself, a study found that Philadelphia's
cost of living, relative to a technology professional's salary,
ranked third lowest, behind Dallas and Chicago, among 15 cities.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hollebeek, a data-mining expert, found the region was in
a top spot in the number and density of colleges and universities.
The residents of those 88 institutions, however, are transient,
with one-quarter of the population coming and going each year, many
taking business plans with them.
</P>
<P>
   Innovative start-up ideas are being exported from Temple,
Villanova and Drexel universities and the University of
Pennsylvania, where the first electronic computer was created, in
1946.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, it was announced that eTechtransfer.com, a
business-to-business marketplace for the life-sciences industry,
won the 2000 Wharton Business Plan competition. The prize was
$15,000 cash and a $10,000 investment from Safeguard Scientifics.
The 1999 winner, Paymybills.com, got snapped up by a California
incubator, which disappointed local technology leaders.
</P>
<P>
   To help stem the talent flight, the Eastern Technology Council,
a regional industry group, has supported a program of scholarships,
financing assistance for start-ups and using mentoring efforts to
keep students here after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philadelphia's business plans are farther along than other
cities', but the ideas that emerge here are going other places,''
said George Boyajian, a managing director of RoundTable Partners,
which advises emerging companies. ``As more `smart money' comes
into the area, more deals are getting done. But the traditional
Quaker banking, insurance and real estate money is remarkably risk
averse.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the buzz of entrepreneurship is growing louder. At a
student-entrepreneur forum organized by Boyajian at the University
of Pennsylvania, 40 of the 60 undergraduates there said they had
started a company.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the search for a glamour tag continues. One local
entrepreneur has tried out the idea that the area could be billed
as being twice as important as Silicon Valley, whose technology
companies are clustered around Route 101. Philadelphia's straddle
Route 202.
</P>
<P>
   (David J. Wallace, a business and technology writer, has moved
to Boston from the Philadelphia area.)
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
