</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Rakuten has been profitable, earning $1 million
on sales of $5.6 million last year. That's an impressive 17.8
percent profit margin, largely unheard of in e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Mikitani had the advantage of studying the business models of
Amazon.com and eBay, and quickly decided that Rakuten would be much
better off as a hybrid, leaning more toward the eBay model than
toward Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he is unimpressed with Amazon.com. He just wants to
avoid the costs and liabilities of inventory and distribution. And
Rakuten has never advertised.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not really a retail company,'' Mikitani said. ``We sell
retailers the use of our servers, and there's a big difference.''
(In addition to the monthly membership fees, which provide 80
percent of Rakuten's revenue, 10 percent of the revenue comes from
advertising and the rest comes from auction.)
</P>
<P>
   Mikitani has limited Rakuten's risk by assuming the least
liability possible for the business conducted on the site, but he
pays attention to customer service. Shops are carefully monitored,
and a few have been asked to leave Rakuten for business practices
that were considered shady.
</P>
<P>
   Mikitani contends that Japan will be a better market for
e-commerce than the United States, mostly because of the medium's
ability to spark a consumer revolution in a country known for its
high prices.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Internet allows merchants to circumvent the many
layers of middlemen who clog this country's distribution system,
adding costs every time merchandise changes hands.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you buy an obi, the sash worn with a kimono, at
the retailer Kyoto Kimono Ichiba, it will cost 138,000 yen, or
about $1,300. Buy it from Kyoto Kimono's shop on Rakuten, and it
costs 13,800 yen, or an affordable $130.
</P>
<P>
   Or think of it this way, which is Mikitani's favorite
illustration of the power of the Internet here: Buy a share of
Rakuten through a traditional Japanese stockbroker, and pay
commissions equal to 3 percent of the share's value, which is about
1,065,000 yen at current prices, or $10,000. Buy it online from
Monex, a securities broker here, and pay a $10 commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the U.S., you use Schwab's online brokerage and you get a
price break for sure,'' Mikitani said. ``But it's not anything like
the savings you get in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Mikitani predicted, the Internet ``is going to
completely rebuild the Japanese economic system, much more so than
in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   He also thinks that Japan's more homogeneous population, with
its flatter distribution of wealth and stronger sense of community
than in the United States, provides the country with e-commerce
advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japanese people like to communicate with each other, and it's
much easier to do that on the Net,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Hitotsubashi University in Tokyo, Mikitani
became a banker at the Industrial Bank of Japan, one of the
country's most blue-blooded financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   He took a break from banking to go to Harvard Business School,
returning to the bank in 1993 with a master's of business
administration and a newfound respect for entrepreneurship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I went to business school, I thought my choices were to
either work my way up Japanese style to become a director of the
bank, or to go into investment banking at a Western firm and make a
lot of money,'' Mikitani said.
</P>
<P>
   But he opted for a third approach, striking out on his own to
become a consultant, which led to his foray into e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Mikitani toyed with selling educational services, financial
advisory services and other things online but chose Rakuten
``because it was scalable,'' which he defined as requiring lots of
technology and relatively little human input.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I could service 2,800 customers with Rakuten,'' he
said. ``Giving 2,800 people financial advice would have been
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Rakuten has had no marketing costs so far, although it plans to
use some of the $430 million it raised in its stock offering to do
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky,'' Mikitani said. ``We got famous fast. The
first mover always has an advantage, and we were the first mover.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that others are not moving fast. Curio City,
another virtual mall that Mitsui &AMP; Co. started about the same time
that Rakuten opened, has said it plans to increase the number of
stores affiliated with its site to 10,000 from the current 800 by
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   But out-Rakutening Rakuten is not easy. WomenJapan.com, which
offers a forum in which Japanese women can seek out and exchange
information and advice about careers, finance, health,
entertainment and family issues, experimented with the online
bazaar concept at Christmastime.
</P>
<P>
   The site featured two shops, one selling pashmina wraps and
other items, and the other selling wine. Neither vendor was an
actual store, and WomenJapan.com found the logistics of
distribution and inventory management cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   The result? ``E-commerce in Japan is still a big question mark
in my mind,'' said Grace Fromm, the chief marketing officer at
WomenJapan.com.
</P>
<P>
   But WomenJapan.com has not given up on e-commerce. Rather, it
took a page from Rakuten's book, signing up two vendors for
Mother's Day _ Tower Records and Hibiya Kadan, a well-known Tokyo
florist _ that could handle orders on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Mikitani's success has made him something of a celebrity, and
government officials and politicians seek his advice about
e-commerce, although some people worry that the government is more
interested in regulating the Internet than in encouraging it.
</P>
<P>
   It is worth remembering that free and unfettered markets have
been the exception in Japan, not the rule. Nobunaga Oda, after all,
committed ritual suicide under threat of assassination by a vassal
turned enemy.
</P>
<P>
   But Mikitani is not afraid. ``What can they do? Shut down a
server?'' he asked. ``All you have to do is move the server to the
U.S., and you're back in business.''
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
