</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONG-KONG-TELECOM-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET COMPANY CONCLUDES LARGEST TAKEOVER BATTLE IN ASIAN
CORPORATE HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ For Richard Li, the thirty-something tycoon whose
deal-making has riveted Hong Kong, Act One ended Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Minority shareholders of Cable and Wireless HKT voted
overwhelmingly to be acquired by Li's Internet company, Pacific
Century Cyberworks. The deal must be ratified by a judge on July
25, but analysts say Monday's vote guarantees that Li, 33, will
soon own Hong Kong's flagship telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Act Two.
</P>
<P>
   Having won the largest takeover battle in Asian corporate
history, Li must demonstrate that he can run an empire as
effectively as he acquired it. On Friday, at an
uncharacteristically modest news conference in London, Pacific
Century introduced its new television and online service. Known as
Network of the World, it is the centerpiece of Li's effort to
combine broadcasting with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the first product from Pacific Century, which has
become one of the most celebrated Internet companies in Asia
largely on the reputation of its brash founder. Analysts say they
will now evaluate Li's company on the performance of the new
service, which will be rolled out over the next 18 months to a
potential audience of 136 million households in Asia. It will later
expand elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to succeed at rolling out the broadband service, and
the economics of that haven't been illustrated yet,'' said Greg
Feldberg, a communications analyst at Indosuez W.I. Carr Securities
here.
</P>
<P>
   Feldberg recently lowered his rating on Pacific Century to a
hold from a buy because he believes the company's assets _ even
after the acquisition of Cable and Wireless HKT _ do not justify
its market value of $20.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are struggling to assess Network of the World because
its ambitions are so vast and its starting point is so modest.
Pacific Century, which owns no programming and has only a handful
of licenses for sporting events like Indian cricket, plans to
develop a service that, it declares, will be a ``revolutionary new
medium for the new generation of consumers in the digital age.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, however, Network of the World, or NOW, consists
of four hours of original programming a day on a single television
channel, beamed via satellite to Asia and the Middle East. The
companion Web site (www.now.com) contains information that builds
on the video programming.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one program features computer-game players squaring
off against each other as a host offers play-by-play commentary.
Viewers can apply to be contestants by going to a the web site,
where they will be interviewed by one of the show's ``virtual''
producers. If they prefer to sit on the sidelines, they can create
an electronic persona to be inserted in an audience.
</P>
<P>
   The network's top producer, who works in a slickly designed
studio in London, acknowledges that such programming ideas may seem
oddball. But he is confident that young viewers will respond in
droves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people watch TV and surf the Internet at the same
time,'' said the executive creative director, Michael Johnson.
``This is a very comfortable space for the computer literate, and
it is completely incomprehensible to older viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   As the network's shaky debut illustrates, however, even
traditional television programming is challenging. NOW had hoped to
roll out the service last weekend with simultaneous TV and Internet
coverage of the Wimbledon tennis championships. But Johnson said
the network canceled the plan at the last minute because it feared
problems with the production quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be there next year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century plans to invest $1.5 billion in Network of the
World over the next five years. Some of that will go to opening
programming studios in Tokyo, Hong Kong and Bombay. The rest will
go to securing distribution. Li plans to beam Network of the World
to cable operators in China, India and other Asian countries.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In building an interactive service, Pacific Century is trying to
succeed where other, much larger companies, have failed. Time
Warner shut down its vaunted cable service in Orlando, Fla., in
1997, after spending millions of dollars and signing up less than
10,000 customers. Several regional Bell telephone companies teamed
up to start interactive media companies _ only to abandon them a
few years later.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts contend that NOW will fall to the same weaknesses
that doomed those ventures: inadequate technology and programming
that does not beguile viewers. The service's Web site, for example,
currently cannot be accessed by an Apple computer or with a
Netscape browser.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people want are reliable, high-capacity networks for
accessing existing content,'' said Joseph Sweeney, the research
director of Gartner Group of Hong Kong, a research firm. ``The NOW
network is probably ahead of its time. It's very hard to see how it
is going to make money.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a longtime television producer who helped start the
Star TV cable network for Li, rejects those comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Time Warner TV project really focused on technology,'' he
said, ``and the attempt to push movies down phone lines was done by
phone companies, which are not famous for knowing audiences.''
</P>
</TEXT>
