<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1980 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-GIZMOS-HNS &LR;      07-03 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-GIZMOS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SWISS ARMY KNIFE: NEVER LEAVE HOME WITHOUT ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN FLINN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A desperate call came over the intercom on a
USAir flight to Memphis a few years ago: An elderly passenger was
choking to death on a piece of steak. Was there a doctor on board?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Plotkin, an anesthesiologist from North Carolina,
rushed to the man's seat, opened his trusty Swiss Army knife and
tried to perform an emergency tracheotomy. Alas, the 1 1/2-inch
blade on the physician's Classic model wasn't long enough for the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Another call for help went out: Did anyone on the plane have a
knife with a longer blade? Half a dozen passengers rushed forward,
each offering their own Swiss Army knives. Using the 2 1/2-inch
blade on a Camper model, Plotkin cut a breathing hole in the
choking man's neck and saved his life.
</P>
<P>
   What Plotkin didn't know at the time was that Victorinox Cutlery
Corp. makes a Swiss Army knife model with a curved, surgical blade
specifically designed for emergency tracheotomies.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a travel emergency that cannot be remedied with a Swiss
Army knife? Has a more useful, versatile, perfect tool ever been
invented? Is there a self-respecting traveler who doesn't carry
one?
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago I asked readers to reveal the little
knickknacks and gizmos they find essential while on the road, and
the one item that showed up on virtually everyone's list was a
Swiss Army knife.
</P>
<P>
   I've used my Climber model to carve apples and Emmental cheese
next to a Swiss glacier, to change camera batteries in the Masai
Mara, to cut moleskin for blisters in the shadow of Mount Everest
and to uncork a bottle of Cotes du Rhone in Provence. Its tweezers
have extracted thorns picked up in the Australian bush; its leather
punch amended my belt in Russia when a bout of the Trotskies made
me skinnier than I've been since high school.
</P>
<P>
   Every U.S. president since LBJ has ordered a batch engraved with
the presidential seal to be distributed as White House souvenirs.
NASA issues the 17-tool Master Craftman model to all astronauts,
who routinely use them to make zero-gravity repairs to the space
shuttle. Swiss Army knives have been to both poles and the summit
of Everest. When Gary Powers was shot down over the USSR in his U-2
spy plane in 1960, the Soviets exhibited his knife as ``CIA
equipment.'' There's a 33-tool Swiss Champ model on permanent
display in the New York Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   All this from such humble beginnings. The original knife, with
six blades and a red handle to make it easier to spot if dropped in
a snowbank, was patented by Swiss cutlerly maker Cark Elsener in
1897. At first Elsener made just two models: one with a corkscrew
for Swiss Army officers, one without for enlisted men. The company
Elsener founded, Victorinox, is today run by his grandchildren in
the Swiss town of Ibach, a small village an hour's drive south of
Zurich, in the German-speaking part of Switzerland. The Victorinox
factory turns out 34,000 knives a day on average.
</P>
<P>
   In 1908, Wenger S.A., a rival cutlery firm in Delmont, in the
French-speaking part of Switzerland, began manufacturing an almost
identical knife. The Swiss being, well, Swiss, adopted a policy of
strict neutrality, and to this day the army buys exactly half its
stock from Victorinox and half from Wenger. (Actually, the Swiss
army isn't buying knives from either company this year. Downsizing
as left them with a surplus, and they don't expect to purchase any
new ones until 2002.)
</P>
<P>
   A practiced eye can spot the difference between the two brands:
a different shield around the Helvetica cross on the case.
Victorinox bills itself as the ``original'' Swiss Army knife,
Wenger as the ``genuine'' Swiss Army knife. Victorinox controls
about 80 percent of the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the brand, the knives have achieved almost a cult
status among travelers and outdoorspeople.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an aura of cleverness and resourcefulness about the
Swiss Army knife,'' said Rick Wall, a San Diego teacher and founder
of the now-defunct Swiss Army Knife Society. ``There may be more
practical tools, but nothing with the panache of the Swiss Army
knife.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For years Wall published a newsletter, the ``Crimson Cutter,''
filled with folksy testimonials from Swiss Army knife fans around
the world. One grateful owner used his to fix a broken toilet on a
train from Moscow to Leningrad, another to slice blueberry pie in
Vermont. A letter carrier in the San Francisco area repaired the
window crank in his mail truck; a British man spliced a ruptured
fuel line in his Rover.
</P>
<P>
   Wall compiled much of this lore in a book, ``The Swiss Army
Knife Companion,'' which is now out of print but available on line
from www.borders.com.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are more than 400 varieties of Swiss Army knife in
circulation. There's a model for golfers, with a tool for replacing
divots; one for equestrians, with a blade for removing stones from
horses' hooves; one for speakers, with a laser pointer. A model for
auto mechanics comes with a tiny flashlight, tire pressure gauge
and fuse-puller. There's even a new $75, 34-function Cyber Tool
model for computer users, with a device for prying open the cases
of laptops and a ``DIP switch setter.'' Whatever that is.
</P>
<P>
   What model to buy? I can vouch for the $35 Climber, with a large
blade, small blade, can opener, screwdriver, bottle opener,
scissors, leather punch, toothpick, tweezers and corkscrew. (But,
alas, no tracheotomy blade.) It sounds like a lot of tools, but
it's roughly in the middle of the size spectrum. The one blade I
miss is a serrated knife for cutting tomatoes and bread.
</P>
<P>
   It's important, say Wall and other experts, to avoid being
seduced by tool-chest models bristling with divot removers, cigar
cutters, fish scalers, wire strippers, socket wrenches and other
impedimenta if you're unlikely to use them. Buy the smallest model
that has the tools you absolutely need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything more than that,'' says Wall, ``and you're just
showing off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
