<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2004 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-03 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHAT? NO SECOND BANANA? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As speculation mounts about potential running mates
for Al Gore and George W. Bush, a contrarian view is now offered:
Who needs a vice president anyway? Let's get rid of that useless
appendage!
</P>
<P>
   There's a small constitutional problem with this suggestion, but
what the heck. Nothing ventured, nothing gained.
</P>
<P>
   The author of this revolutionary idea is former Minnesota Sen.
Eugene McCarthy, a Democratic presidential candidate in the
tumultuous Vietnam-era year of 1968. He lost, of course, but for a
time he was the center of excitement, defying incumbent President
Lyndon Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy's year of fame having long passed, we haven't heard
much from the 84-year-old politician lately. He's been writing
books and thinking. But with McCarthy, known for a wicked wit and
an impish intellect, thinking can be dangerous to the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   His latest brainstorm is perfectly in character. McCarthy has
always danced to a different drummer.
</P>
<P>
   The way he outlines his idea, eliminating the post of vice
president almost sounds like a sensible move. Can he really be
serious?
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy was once in the running for the job himself. In 1964,
Johnson made a public fuss over McCarthy and hinted that a
Minnesota senator would be perfect as his running mate. Then he
picked Minnesota's other senator, Hubert Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy muses wryly that ``I lost by one vote'' _ Johnson's.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy surfaced last week at a media luncheon to try out his
idea and promote his new book, ``American Beastiary,'' which
equates politicians with animals in a light-hearted way.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of leaving a president veep-less, with nobody of
high rank to cover his behind or do his bidding and his dirty work,
is pretty hard going. We are accustomed to a Constitution that
clearly calls for the election of a vice president who is to
succeed any president too disabled to continue his executive
duties.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution originally provided that the person who
received the second-largest number of votes in the presidential
election should be named vice president. After this proved
politically awkward, the provision was amended in 1804 to provide
that presidential and vice presidential candidates be named
separately on the same ballot.
</P>
<P>
   But McCarthy has never been intimidated by tradition. ``On every
ground the job is a nuisance,'' he says. Since the everyday duties
and responsibilities are not defined, most vice presidents have
wound up underappreciated, underemployed and unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore has been luckier than his predecessors.
President Clinton has not only given Gore specific, substantive
tasks but allowed him considerable influence in policymaking across
the board. Gore's role may not set a permanent precedent, however.
It is strictly up to the next president to decide how much access
and authority to give his second banana.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy also grumbles that however wasteful the post, it puts
the holder first in line to be the next president. Sometimes the
veep is chosen for the wrong reason, such as his ability to deliver
a specific state, and isn't up to running a country. Dan Quayle, a
foolish choice by George Bush, comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   That second name on the ballot just ``clutters up the
campaign,'' McCarthy observes. Nobody knows what vice presidents do
anyway, except to wait around for the president to fall ill. So
what to do in such a disaster if there's no fall-back person? Throw
it to the Electoral College, says McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   The qualities of a good second banana _ discretion, patience,
loyalty and playing second fiddle to the boss _ are not those that
matter most in a good presidential candidate. ``What a vice
president does as vice president doesn't count in a presidential
race,'' McCarthy says. That is part of Gore's problem and why he
has been constantly trying to re-invent himself.
</P>
<P>
   After all these years he has spent at Clinton's side, many
voters still don't know who he is or what he has done.
</P>
<P>
   Given McCarthy's fey sense of humor, you can never be sure when
he is pulling your leg or whether he has really had a political
epiphany.
</P>
<P>
   But watching the current presidential candidates wrestle with
lists of possible veeps that contain no stars and no obvious
choices, you have to wonder if they wouldn't be better off making
their race alone. The basic rule about picking running mates is
that the person shouldn't hurt the ticket. If he or she is of some
help that's a plus, but it's not guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy would spare them the agony of that choice. It might not
be such a bad idea after all.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
