<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2010 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-LOST-AMENDMENTS-950&AMP;A     07-03 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOST-AMENDMENTS-950&AMP;ADD-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOST 13TH AMENDMENT WAS ACTUALLY RATIFIED, SOME HISTORIANS ARGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Monday, July 3, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For information
about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of The New York
Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697; e-mail:
weyded nytimes.com.) 
 &HT;    
 By DRU SEFTON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a constitutional amendment that bars federal officials
from receiving money or favors from foreign interests, under
penalty of loss of citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might just be that the American people would really support
such a thing,'' said Michael Paulsen, law professor at University
of Minnesota. ``If so, there is nothing to keep this amendment from
being ratified.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because it already was submitted to Congress and
approved, as the 13th Amendment, in 1810. Back then, as now,
amendments first pass through the House and Senate and then proceed
to the states for their approval, or ratification. Three-quarters
of the states must ratify for an amendment to become part of the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   No one argues that the House and Senate failed to approve the
13th Amendment, also known as the Titles of Nobility Amendment. The
controversy arises over the ratification.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government recorded 12 states that ratified, four
states that rejected, and Virginia as a ``no reply.'' And so an
amendment forbidding slavery went on to be ratified as the current
13th Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia's reply may have been lost during difficulties in
communication during the War of 1812, scholars say.
</P>
<P>
   But now a group of advocates, calling themselves Project 13,
insist they have evidence that the original 13th was ratified.
</P>
<P>
   It's but one of several ``failed amendments,'' concerning
everything from states' rights to women's rights, that supporters
and constitutional scholars say are still alive. These are
amendments that were approved by the House and Senate, didn't get
enough states to ratify and -- this is key -- have no time limits
on ratification.
</P>
<P>
   That original 13th Amendment is eerily appropriate now, with the
Senate Judiciary Committee examining foreign influences in the 1996
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a dead letter,'' said Paulsen, who has written about
time limits and the amendment process. ``It's still out there,
kicking.''
</P>
<P>
   The last amendment to the Constitution, named for its author,
James Madison, proved that ``lost'' amendments can be ``found,'' as
it were. Concerning the timing of congressional pay raises, the
Madison Amendment was ratified as the 27th Amendment in 1992 --
more than 200 years after it was first submitted.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   That means the Equal Rights Amendment is still alive, its
backers say. They've used Madison's success to push the ERA in the
Missouri General Assembly, where it's nearing a vote. Were the
effort to succeed, the ERA theoretically would need only two more
states for ratification.
</P>
<P>
   (ERA advocates must also overcome the argument that the proposed
amendment expired, after a congressional extension, in 1982.
Backers say that because the date appears in the proposing clause,
not in the text of the amendment itself, it does not apply.)
</P>
<P>
   Some of the failed amendments are now unnecessary. Regulation of
child labor, the subject of a 1924 proposed amendment, now is
handled through federal laws. And a proposed amendment from 1789
concerning the size of the House of Representatives would be moot,
as that number of members -- 200 -- already has been exceeded.
(There are 435 seats in the House.)
</P>
<P>
   Another proposed amendment, barring any law interfering with the
``domestic institutions'' of states, including slavery, is cited in
literature from the League of the South, which champions states'
rights. Some scholars say that although that proposal remains
technically viable, its main thrust was nullified by a later one
(the current 13th) that outlawed slavery.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   The Titles of Nobility Amendment, fans say, is not only still
viable, but necessary and important.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Dunn, a former Baltimore police officer now retired in
Albion, Maine, has spent the last 20 years researching it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at it from a historical perspective,'' Dunn said,
``it's an internal Monroe Doctrine, where foreign influence is not
only checked but the persons involved lose their positions in
government and their citizenship.'' The Monroe Doctrine, enacted in
1823, forbade European nations to interfere with American affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The Titles of Nobility Amendment was indeed similar in intent.
It was submitted at a time when there was great concern over
American citizens accepting foreign titles. One example was
Napoleon Bonaparte's younger brother, Jerome Bonaparte, and his
wife, Baltimore socialite Elizabeth Patterson. They made Congress
especially nervous, as rumors were rife that France was considering
granting them titles -- and, thus, power.
</P>
<P>
   The text of the Titles of Nobility Amendment reads as follows:
</P>
<P>
   ``If any citizen of the United States shall accept, claim,
receive or retain any title of nobility or honor, or shall, without
the consent of Congress, accept and retain any present, pension,
office or emolument of any kind whatever, from any emperor, king,
prince or foreign power, such person shall cease to be a citizen of
the United States, and shall be incapable of holding any office of
trust or profit under them, or either of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn has visited libraries across the country, poring over
thousands of books, law dictionaries, encyclopedias and documents.
He is convinced that the Titles of Nobility Amendment was indeed
ratified and should be recognized as part of the Constitution.
Along the way he's met other researchers with his same passion;
they all formed Project 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a subterranean type of movement,'' Dunn said. ``We've
never received that much publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   One piece of their evidence is a letter from John Quincy Adams
in the early 1800s to a citizen who wanted to assist the German
government. ``Adams specifically mentioned the 13th amendment'' as
forbidding him to do so, Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said he's also found the amendment listed in many books.
</P>
<P>
   John Vile, however, is dubious.
</P>
<P>
   Vile, head of the political science department at Middle
Tennessee State University in Murfreesboro, is the author of
several books on the amending process, including ``Encyclopedia of
Constitutional Amendments, Proposed Amendments, and Amending
Issues, 1789-1995.''
</P>
<P>
   Just because it's in books, Vile said, does not mean the
original 13th was ratified. ``Communications were a lot different
then,'' Vile said; perhaps the publisher simply assumed the
amendment would be ratified before it was. ``The best scholarship
suggests it was not adopted.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes numerous law-journal papers, such as one titled
``The Missing 13th Amendment: Constitutional Nonsense and Titles of
Nobility'' in a recent Southern California Interdisciplinary Law
Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn and his colleagues remain undaunted. They've launched a Web
site (www.13th-amendment.org) to publicize the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   And what does Congress have to say about all these amendments?
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., submitted a resolution that
all the failed amendments ``are hereby declared to have lapsed''
and were no longer subject to ratification.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed the resolution unanimously, 99-0, and referred
it to the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   It was never heard from again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1539EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0199 </DOCNO>
