 ATTENTION EDITORS: This advisory describes the top offerings from
NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for Monday, July 3. For information about
purchasing articles as a ``separate-buy,'' contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OUR TOP OFFERING:
</P>
<P>
   LOST 13TH AMENDMENT WAS ACTUALLY RATIFIED, PROPONENTS SAY
</P>
<P>
   LOST-AMENDMENTS (UNDATED) _ Imagine a Constitutional amendment
that bars federal officials from receiving money or favors from
foreign interests, under penalty of loss of citizenship. The Titles
of Nobility Amendment, does just that. It was approved by the House
and Senate, and, some historians say, was even ratified by a
sufficient number of states to become the 13th Amendment. And it's
eerily appropriate now, with the Senate Judiciary Committee
examining foreign influences in the 1996 presidential election. By
Dru Sefton. With a graphic. About 1,000 (``a'' and ``w''
categories.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1540EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2016 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-SPY-SOFTWARE-HNS &LR;      07-03 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPY-SOFTWARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `SPY' SOFTWARE A BOOMING BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``Husband cheating on line? Catch him with
this.''
</P>
<P>
   With those seven words, software developer Doug Fowler hit the
jackpot. He posted the words in an eBay auction solicitation, in
July 1999, advertising Internet surveillance software that could
help you nab that straying spouse.
</P>
<P>
   Within four hours, 500 people had clicked on the posting. Within
a week, 5,000 had perused the offer. Sales tripled in the weeks
following the auction, and Fowler's company is now growing at a
healthy clip of 15 to 25 percent per month.
</P>
<P>
   With those seven salacious words, a software star was born. And
like many stories of overnight success, the breakthrough was
accidental.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler, a software developer in Vero Beach, Fla., was trying to
pump up the sagging sales of his Spector software, which records
computer and Internet activity, much like a camcorder, and lets
users play back the recorded information.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the ``husband'' posting, Fowler had targeted two
primary fields: parents monitoring children and employers
monitoring employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We originally thought parents and employers would be our
original markets, and marketed to them exclusively for about 6
months,'' said Fowler, who is president of SpectorSoft Inc. ``Then
we got a letter from a woman who caught her fiance meeting several
women a day on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a fringe use at first, until a couple of
months later when we got more letters. That's when we ran the
auction. Essentially, sales tripled over night after the eBay
auction.''
</P>
<P>
   Spector's spying software can be installed in ``stealth mode,''
masking it from a child, an employee or spouse. The software acts
like an invisible video recorder pointed at the computer monitor,
secretly taking snapshots as frequently as once per second, or as
sporadically as one per half hour.
</P>
<P>
   Spector retails for $49.95.
</P>
<P>
   Because it can take pictures so frequently, Spector can capture
all chat conversations, instant messages, e-mails sent and
received, all Web sites visited, all documents, all keystrokes
typed.
</P>
<P>
   The original user accesses the results by typing in a four-key
access code, as well as a password.
</P>
<P>
   And as you can well imagine, those results can be explosive.
</P>
<P>
   According to Fowler, one SpectorSoft customer believed his wife
was having an affair. Within a few days of using the software, he
not only confirmed his suspicions, but also discovered that his
wife and boyfriend were plotting to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard a lot of stories about what people have found out,
but that is certainly the most chilling one,'' Fowler said.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Pierce, a lawyer for the Electronic Frontier Foundation
in San Francisco, said SpectorSoft reveals some pretty serious
societal issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are trust issues here,'' said Pierce, whose nonprofit
organization champions privacy and free speech rights in relation
to technology. ``Obviously people are not trusting their kids,
spouses or employees. To not tell someone they're being monitored
can be very detrimental to any relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Fowler said people who have privacy concerns should not use his
software.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that some people may interpret this as an
invasion of privacy,'' he said, ``but, generally, people are in a
situation that they suspect something is going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone would argue with parents or employers
(using Spector). As far as the spousal situation, it comes down to
a question of whether it's better to have the knowledge of someone
cheating on you ... or whether it's better to protect someone's
privacy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1541EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2017 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-LILEKS-GORE-NNS &LR;      07-03 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILEKS-GORE-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REINVENTING THE SPIEL 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Monday, July 3, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For information
about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of The New York
Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697; e-mail:
weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By JAMES LILEKS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore has a new theme, ``Prosperity and Progress.'' Thus he
distinguishes himself from the candidates running on widespread
penury and decline. The retooling of Gore is intended to capitalize
on all those bounteous budget surpluses. His advisers are recasting
Al as the symbol of fiscal fecundity, the Gorenucopia from which
all bounty flows.
</P>
<P>
   Or, to put it another way: Vote for Gore, and he guarantees to
tax you more than it takes to run the government.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic strategists wonder why Gore doesn't get credit for
this booming economy. Simple: Americans obviously don't think he
had anything to do with it. Ditto Bill Clinton. It's what they
didn't do. Didn't nationalize any industries. Didn't put laughing
powder in Alan Greenspan's drink, making him giggle uncontrollably
and squirt milk out his nose while discussing ``irrational
exuberance,'' thereby reducing confidence in his stewardship.
Didn't establish the Department of Triplicate to oversee the newly
created Office of Duplication. Didn't come clean on Monica, which
resulted in the impeachment drama, also known as the Lawyer and
Pundit Full Employment Act of 1998. Didn't invade too many
countries and kill too many people.
</P>
<P>
   They did, however, push that little health care proposal. It
gave so many people bone-deep heebie-jeebies that they voted in the
GOP Congress in '94 and forever changed the character of Clinton's
tenure. Ever after he dressed on the right and contented himself
with a small scrap of socialism over here, an offstage war there.
Having done nothing, he leaves Gore unable to claim any role in the
prosperity -- unless Gore wants to insist he was right by Clinton's
side when the president declined to tax e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's latest makeover might be the dullest yet, and it might be
DOA like the others. Retooling doesn't work. In 1996, for example,
handlers tried to turn Bob Dole into -- well, it's hard to say; the
entire campaign was one long senior moment. But they tried to make
him Ronald Reagan's long-lost half-brother -- a war hero, a tax
cutter, a moral bulwark. They played down Dole's snarky wit and
played up his gravitas, hoping it would make Clinton look like a
callow playboy. But people already saw Clinton as a callow playboy.
They weren't in the mood to elect Dad -- no matter how the handlers
remade him.
</P>
<P>
   Whether voters want to elect Frat Brother remains to be seen.
Supposedly voters will turn to Gore once they learn the details of
George W. Bush's proposals, but this presumes the voters have any
interest in details. They don't. Gore people say: ``Sure, on
defense issues Bush has a 40-point lead among men ages 11-92. But
once voters realize that Bush favors a 14 percent reduction in
average boot-heel density and a repainting of all ships in a
slightly duller shade of gray, we feel that his numbers will drop
off considerably.'' Sorry. Doesn't work that way. If all your
details dovetail perfectly with the desires of the electorate but
the polling data show that you ``strongly remind people of runny
cheese,'' you aren't going to win.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean Gore is dead. Anything can happen. But Bush is
popular enough to have a three-gaffe margin. If he says something
really stupid (``I'm looking forward to meeting the king of
Canada''), his supporters will think, well, everyone makes a
mistake. Gaffe No. 2 (``Well, your right to swing your fist ends at
my right to say `Fire' in a crowded theater''), people will think
the press is picking on him. Gaffe No. 3, voters will think: What's
up with this idiot, anyway? But Bush is too tightly run and too
well spun to make bright, screaming mistakes. We'll get the crinkly
grin and the fractured banter, all upbeat and positive -- except
for a sad tug at the corner of his mouth when Al goes negative.
</P>
<P>
   This absolutely has to drive Gore nuts. He knows the cheat sheet
for Gore jokes: ``Love Story,'' Love Canal, invented Internet,
slumlord, world's first wooden robot. And what's the cliche for
Bush? Stooopid. And he's leading. It's ... just ... wrong. Gore is
knowledge. Gore is details. He is RoboWonk. Smarter than Bush? No
doubt. Democrats always nominate smarter guys. And they lose to the
charming guys. And then fume like chess club presidents who can't
understand why Cindy Lou went to the prom with the quarterback
instead of choosing her intellectual superior.
</P>
<P>
   Reinvention is a doomed enterprise. If you have to reinvent,
they're already on to you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
