<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2021 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV09-NY     07-03 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANGUAGE BOOKS TO SCHLEP ALONG ON VACATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 9)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You're on vacation. Your stress is disappearing but your brain
is vegetating. You long for intellectual meat with a spicy sauce.
Try a language book.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've Got Ketchup on Your Muumuu,'' by Eugene Ehrlich (Henry
Holt, $24), is an etymologist's breezy look at foreign words that
have been gulped down by English speakers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ketchup &LR; , to begin: This word, meaning ``a condiment of pureed
tomatoes, onions, vinegar, etc.,'' is from the Chinese  &UR; kejap &LR;  or
 &UR; ke-tsiap &LR; , ``fish sauce,'' made of brine of pickled fish. The
author notes the variant spelling,  &UR; catsup &LR; , which is what Del
Monte labels used to say; my own research shows that since 1988 the
Del Monte marketers have fallen into step with Heinz and Hunt's in
calling their thick, red stuff  &UR; ketchup &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Muumuu &LR;  was adopted into English from the Hawaiian in the 1920s
and is ``the name of a dress, literally, a `cutoff,' so-called
because it has no yoke, the usual top section from which the rest
of the dress hangs.'' That fashion definition leaves me a little
confused (it's a colorful, loose-fitting variation of the
missionaries' Mother Hubbard dress), and I would not hyphenate  &UR; so
called  &LR; because it is not used here as a compound adjective, but
Ehrlich's etymology is sound.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the borrowings are familiar: the Tagalog  &UR; boondocks &LR; ,
the Sanskrit  &UR; guru &LR; , the Chinook  &UR; high muck-a-muck &LR; . The German
 &UR; Pickelhaube &LR; , however, was new to me.  &UR; Haube &LR;  is ``helmet,'' and
 &UR; Pickel &LR;  has a sense of ``pick ax''; a  &UR; Pickelhaube &LR;  is ``a German
army spiked helmet of a type worn before and during World War I.''
There's a word to spring on some unsuspecting historian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Word Court,'' by Barbara Wallraff (Harcourt, $24, and whatever
became of Brace? I'd like to see a firm of castaway founders, like
Brace, Roebuck, Pearce, Fenner &AMP; Beane.): Here is a usage guide in
question-answer form by the Atlantic magazine columnist and
longtime line editor. (A ``line editor'' is a copy editor with a
lust to rewrite. Most writers resent line editors because they show
us to be sloppy and lazy.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Try and &LR;  or  &UR; try to &LR; ? Wallraff advises against the colloquial
 &UR; try and &LR;  in formal writing and goes on to explain the informal
variant as an example of  &UR; hendiadys &LR; , ``a device used as a poetic
ornament in Greek and Latin.'' An example is  &UR; nice and warm &LR;  to
express  &UR; nicely warm &LR; . Try to keep that straight.
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR; Gravitas &LR;  is a word that pundits such as William Safire and
William F. Buckley love to use,'' notes a questioner irritated by
his inability to find this weighty word for ``solemnity, high
seriousness'' in his limited dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   Wallraff responds: ``You're quite right that it is unkind of
authors to use unfamiliar words that leave their readers guessing.
But aren't you glad that it's not only people with rings in their
bellybuttons and skateboards under their toes who are giving us
words for the dictionary makers to include in their next
editions?'' (Yes, some dictionaries treat  &UR; bellybutton &LR;  as one
word, but  &UR; belly laugh &LR; ,  &UR; belly flop &LR;  and  &UR; belly dance &LR;  as two. I
prefer to keep them all separate until Big Bellyup Day, when we
will squeeze them all together at once.)
</P>
<P>
   For linguistic heavy hitters, MIT Press offers ``Lingua ex
Machina,'' subtitled ``Reconciling Darwin and Chomsky with the
Human Brain,'' a cross-discipline debate by the neurophysiologist
William Calvin and the linguist Derek Bickerton ($26.95).
</P>
<P>
   They try to (not  &UR; try and &LR; ) resolve ``the apparent paradox that
has  &UR; hag-ridden &LR;  the human sciences for centuries: that we were
produced by the same forces as other species, yet behave so
differently from other species.'' Great archaic word,  &UR; hag-ridden &LR; ;
means ``afflicted by nightmares.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Barzun's ``From Dawn to Decadence: 500 Years of Western
Cultural Life'' (HarperCollins, $36) is cultural history with an
attitude: My nonagenarian mentor condemns the severe effects of
anything-goes linguistics on education and derides the
loosey-goosey notion that ``no native speaker can ever make a
mistake.'' The legendary Columbia professor emeritus has turned out
a  &UR; tour d'horizon &LR;  that is at once a  &UR; tour de force &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Euphemism Watch
</P>
<P>
   In Shakespeare's time, they were called  &UR; gravediggers &LR; . Then
they got organized, raised prices and named themselves
 &UR; undertakers &LR; . When that acquired a too-gloomy connotation, they
changed it to  &UR; morticians &LR; . But now that caretakers have given way
to caregivers, and even  &UR; sharing &LR;  has been overtaken by  &UR; caring &LR;  as
the most pious participle, we have _ trumpeted in a reverential,
hushed ta-dah! _ the  &UR; deathcare industry &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The other major euphemism to burst forth this year is the
diplomatic replacement for  &UR; rogue state &LR; . The earliest use I can
find of this phrase was in a 1983 Wall Street Journal story noting
that smokestack industries have ``won Ohio a largely deserved
reputation as a  &UR; rogue state &LR;  on the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the columnist William Pfaff first applied it in
its current sense: ``The Soviet Union had deliberately isolated
itself. Its role was that of a  &UR; rogue state &LR; , a revolutionary power
that challenged all the others.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the phrase has been applied to states like
Libya, Iran, Iraq, Serbia, Sudan, Syria and North Korea that
supported or condoned the presence of terrorists. Last month,
however, on National Public Radio's ``Diane Rehm Show,'' Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright revealed an official smoothing-over:
``We are now calling these states  &UR; states of concern &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about this new locution, state spokesman Richard Boucher
said of Iraq, a hard-core  &UR; rogue state &LR;  in the earlier formulation,
that it had become ``a state previously known as rogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Problem solved; worry removed. Of course, if one of those
 &UR; states of concern &LR;  gets hold of a nuclear or biological missile,
it could be a bonanza for the  &UR; deathcare industry &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
