<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2023 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-$ADV05-H     07-03 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-$ADV05-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BOY SCOUT VALUES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his dissent from the Supreme Court ruling that
the Boy Scouts may bar gays as members, Justice John Paul Stevens
quotes the legendary Justice Louis Brandeis: ``We must be ever on
our guard, lest we erect our prejudices into legal principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William Rehnquist, writing for the 5-4 majority
that found the Scouts had a right to accept only members they
wanted, countered by pointing out that the great Brandeis was also
a champion of free speech. The majority viewed this case as turning
on the First Amendment right of freedom of expressive association,
not on discrimination on the basis of sexual preference.
</P>
<P>
   And there you have it. This was a classic case of conflicting
rights, each legitimate, each at loggerheads with the other.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court of New Jersey, where the case originated, had
declared the Scouts to be a sufficiently public organization to be
subject to the state's anti-discrimination law. But the U.S.
Supreme Court majority simply declared the organization to be a
private institution under federal law despite its use of
taxpayer-financed facilities in some places, frequent reliance on
public support for troop sponsorship and participation in
government-sanctioned charity drives.
</P>
<P>
   The high bench put great weight on the Boy Scouts' claim to
being dedicated to shaping young males into models of moral purity,
which to the Scouts included the rejection of a homosexual
lifestyle. There was not a lot of evidence pointing to a specific
anti-gay policy, except that Scouts were required to be ``morally
straight'' and ``clean.''
</P>
<P>
   The Scoutmaster Handbook does not mention sexuality. The
attitude of the Scout leadership, however, is to encourage boys to
be boys, with all the well-known implications, good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   But to justify its decision the court's majority had to find in
Scout doctrine a basic message that would be not just blurred but
definitely harmed by the admission of a gay scoutmaster. It was not
enough that a gay be present. There must be an unwanted message
about gay pride involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state interests (in forbidding discrimination) do not
justify such a severe intrusion on the freedom of expressive
association,'' Rehnquist wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The chief justice worried that the public presence of a gay
Scout leader would ``force the organization to send a message, both
to the youth members and the world, that the Boy Scouts accept
homosexual conduct as a legitimate form of behavior.'' That message
might also have been one of tolerance of diversity, but Rehnquist
and his four colleagues didn't get that one.
</P>
<P>
   Only ``severe intrusion'' would do to trump legally sanctioned
bigotry. So the court, by golly, found it.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, legitimate reasons for people to want to
associate with other people who share their thinking, their
background, their common goals. But that is appropriate only in
private groups, which do not seek the backing of public,
taxpayer-supported organizations for support.
</P>
<P>
   You want to build a tree house in your backyard and exclude
girls, okay. You pay for its construction and you sit there alone.
Your loss.
</P>
<P>
   But the Boy Scouts are not strictly private. If you have
children in school, the Scouts are constantly in your face,
recruiting youngsters under the banner of teaching good citizenship
and good fellowship. They go into the community to raise money.
They wear uniforms so they can be identified. They use churches,
schools and other public places in which to meet. Their
convocations are held in public parks with speeches by politicians,
bands and other attendant symbols of public support.
</P>
<P>
   The high bench, as it so often does, saw what it wanted to see.
It gave the Boy Scouts a green light to become a crusty, exclusive
organization isolated from a changing society.
</P>
<P>
   The Scouts can react to this sensibly or arrogantly. If they
conclude that a ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy might work and
relax their fears of sexual subversion, all may yet be well. But if
not, they will become just another young boys' club in a world of
more interesting clubs. Stuffy doesn't cut it any more _ for any
age.
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1602EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
