<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2025 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-SMITH-COLUMN-TEX     07-03 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL SCOUTS LOSE SUPPORT BECAUSE OF STANCE ON GAYS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK Z. SMITH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, the Supreme Court ruled that the Boy Scouts of
America can legally ban homosexuals from serving as troop leaders.
The decision also strongly implied that the organization has a
right to exclude gay boys as members.
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-4 decision, the court concluded that the BSA, as a
private organization, has the right to discriminate in choosing who
is permitted within its ranks.
</P>
<P>
   BSA officials proclaimed a great victory. But the decision could
backfire on the Irving, Texas-based organization in at least one
significant way.
</P>
<P>
   It could cause the growing numbers of corporations,
organizations and individuals who oppose discrimination against
gays to have second thoughts about contributing financially to the
Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations such as the United Way, which solicit donations
that support an array of organizations including the Boy Scouts,
could face pressure in some cities to remove local Scout councils
from their list of beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Some who contribute annually to the United Way through their
employers might also specify that they don't want their money going
to the Boy Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   I'll be taking that route because I don't believe in
discriminating against gays. I cannot in good conscience give money
to an organization that does.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, cities, corporations, universities and other
institutions are formally adopting enlightened regulations that
specifically ban discrimination against gays, such as in hiring and
benefits policies.
</P>
<P>
   Will many of these entities continue contributing to the Boy
Scouts if they have done so in the past? It would be inconsistent
and hypocritical to do so if they truly oppose discrimination
against gays.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, the BSA should re-examine its position and voluntarily
end its policy of barring gays. But that's unlikely to happen any
time soon.
</P>
<P>
   It's a safe bet that many gay boys will feel the lure of
Scouting and continue to join, just as they always have. They'll
probably be discreet about their sexual orientation _ if, indeed,
they already have a clearly established orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The BSA is, in most ways, a splendid organization. I have fond
memories of being a Scout in the early to mid-1960s in my small
hometown in northeast Texas. Camping out, playing basketball in a
school gym on Saturday mornings, taking a rigorous 20-mile hike
through the countryside and working on merit badges are activities
that I greatly enjoyed. I proudly wore my uniform and recited the
Scout Oath.
</P>
<P>
   BSA officials say that the organization snubs homosexuals
because they do not comply with the oath's pledge to be ``morally
straight.''
</P>
<P>
   When I was a Scout, I felt that ``morally straight'' meant being
honest, sincere, responsible and following the Golden Rule in
treating others as I would want to be treated. It never occurred to
me that the phrase might refer to sexual orientation, nor did I
ever give a moment's thought to whether anybody in our troop might
be gay.
</P>
<P>
   As a heterosexual, I don't fully know what it means to be gay.
But I know gay co-workers and community leaders whom I like,
respect and feel comfortable around.
</P>
<P>
   I have a gay relative who is one of the finest human beings I
know. He's intelligent, compassionate, hard-working, unselfish,
honest to a fault, and caring to friends and family. I consider him
more ``morally straight'' than 95 percent of the people I know.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, someday, the Boy Scouts will come to realize that there
are more important factors than sexual orientation in judging a
person's character, morality and fitness for membership in their
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Until they do, they'll lose support from increasing numbers of
Americans, myself included, who don't view homophobia as an
admirable personal or institutional trait.
</P>
<P>
   (Jack Z. Smith is an editorial writer and columnist for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. He can be reached at (817) 390-7724 or
jzsmith(at0star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
