<SLUG> BC-SCI-YOUNG-FISH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDIES FIND YOUNG SALTWATER FISH RETURN TO THE FOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla. , Calif., Australia)   (The Science Times)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The typical saltwater fish's childhood is something of a lost
time, at least for scientists trying to study it. Not much is known
about what happens during most fishes' larval stages, when they are
tiny and floating in the plankton in the swirling waters. That has
led to a great question in marine ecology: are fish populations
open, with young fish shuttling in and out across great distances,
or closed, with juveniles largely settling back where they were
born?
</P>
<P>
   Now, research offers the first solid evidence that larvae can,
and do, go home again, that a population of fish retains a lot of
its offspring. The findings have great implications for managing
ocean fish stocks and developing marine reserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the results are incredibly surprising,'' said Stephen
Swearer, a researcher at the University of California at Santa
Barbara and the lead author of a study of reef fish on the
Caribbean island of St. Croix. ``The paradigm was that marine
populations were open. But it seemed to me more logical that this
is what larvae were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The St. Croix study and a study of fish on the Great Barrier
Reef by scientists at James Cook University in Townsville,
Australia, shed light on what happens to the larvae during the
pelagic phase, when they are out in the plankton amid the currents.
It is like finding out what happens to a needle in a haystack swept
up in a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers in both studies made use of a tiny ear bone
found in fish larvae to help trace their whereabouts. The bone,
called the otolith, is no larger than a grain of sand and adds
layers of calcium carbonate as the larvae develop, like a daily
version of a tree ring.
</P>
<P>
   But the two groups' approaches were vastly different. The
Australian scientists used brute force, tagging some 10 million
damselfish embryos collected around one island by soaking them in a
tetracyline solution. Fifteen of 5,000 juvenile fish collected over
the ensuing weeks had the tetracycline marker, which shows up as a
fluorescent stain under a microscope.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't seem like a lot,'' said Dr. Geoffrey Jones, the
Australian team's lead researcher. But since only a tiny fraction
of the embryos around the island were tagged _ less than 2 percent
by the researchers' estimate _ the numbers mean that 15 to 60
percent of juveniles may be returning to the island. ``It tends to
suggest that these larvae have some sort of mechanism for staying
in the same area,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Barbara team, by contrast, ``tried to let nature do
the tagging for us,'' Swearer said.
</P>
<P>
   Using extremely sensitive mass spectrometry techniques, he
analyzed otoliths of bluehead wrasse fish for trace-metal content.
Coastal waters tend to be rich in trace metals _ from erosion and
pollution, among other things _ while the open ocean tends to be
depleted of such elements. So the trace-metal content of an otolith
tells a tale something like a flight recorder, showing in what
waters the larvae developed.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Croix results showed that many of the fish spent their
time in coastal waters, meaning that the larvae were retained
locally and did not cross the open ocean from somewhere else. ``We
found that retention is much more prevalent,'' Swearer said.
</P>
<P>
   The two studies, published in the journal Nature, ``were
essentially the first empirical evidence that fish with pelagic
larvae come back to natal areas,'' said Dr. Robert R. Warner, a
professor at Santa Barbara who worked on the St. Croix research.
</P>
<P>
   Warner has formed a group to study the issue, particularly the
question of how a fish larva, often thought of as a passive lump,
accomplishes the feat of returning home.
</P>
<P>
   One scientist studying the behavior of fish larvae is Dr. Robert
K. Cowen, a biologist at the University of Miami. In a recent paper
in Science, he argued that after they develop swimming ability,
some larvae can adjust their depth, avoiding strong offshore
currents and drifting in deeper water headed toward shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small larvae aren't going to have much effect trying to swim
against a strong current,'' Cowen said. ``But by going 10, 20,
maybe 30 meters in the vertical, they can end up in a current going
in a different direction. It doesn't take much behavior of the
larvae to get in that onshore flow.''
</P>
<P>
   How do they know which direction is toward shore, toward where
they were spawned? Cowen said that sense of hearing might play a
role. ``Reefs are very noisy places, with waves, snapping shrimp
and bubbles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The larvae might also be able to smell the reef through the
water. ``They might have the ability to pick up relatively small
gradients in these cues to be capable of finding where they want to
go from some distance away,'' Cowen said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how larvae do it, the evidence that they are
retained locally may result in a rethinking of how to manage fish
stocks and design preserves, said Dr. James Bohnsack, a research
biologist with the National Marine Fisheries Service in South
Florida. In the past, a fish spawning area might have been thought
of as helping to populate areas far away. But if a spawning reef is
largely repopulating itself, there may be a need for more
preserves.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bohnsack said, the new research is already being used
to formulate a fish conservation plan for the Tortugas area west of
the Florida Keys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to take the science and apply it to practical
problems,'' Bohnsack said. ``Now we understand a little bit more
about it, so hopefully we can do a little bit more about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
