<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PSYCHIATRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORTING OUT DELUSIONS IN THERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By ANNA FELS, M.D.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When I spotted my new patient in the psychiatry ward
in the small hours of the morning, she was in the custody of two
police officers and was naked except for a toga made of brightly
flowered sheets.
</P>
<P>
   I instantly knew the diagnosis. When the patient informed me
irritably that she was a famous European artist, I thought to
myself, ``Right, and I'm Georgia O'Keeffe doing my night job.'' I
completed a perfunctory history and physical, gave the orders for
medication, and wrote up my summary: mania characterized by
delusions of grandiosity, impaired judgment, sleeplessness,
irritability. Then I went to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours later, I found my new patient angrily snapping
photos with a disposable camera given to her by the occupational
therapist. She was clicking away at us through the glass partition
of the nurses' station and shouting at us to call her agent. The
head nurse rolled her eyes as we proceeded with morning rounds.
</P>
<P>
   At 9 a.m., however, the daily routine came to a grinding halt.
The phone lines in the nurses' station all lit up simultaneously
and my beeper went into its equivalent of intractable seizure
activity. An ambassador, two lawyers (one on each side of the
Atlantic), the agent and a non-English-speaking psychiatrist all
urgently needed to talk to me, the admitting psychiatrist, about
the care of the new patient.
</P>
<P>
   It quickly emerged that the patient was, in fact, a famous
artist. Her ``grandiose'' version of her life was correct and my
scribbled version of her story had been, in part, wrong. She was
manic and in need of hospitalization and medication. She was not,
however, psychotic and delusional.
</P>
<P>
   For me, it was an early lesson in a complex but pervasive
problem in psychiatry. It can be frustrating and, at times, nigh
impossible, to sort out where ``reality'' lies in the no man's land
between the patient's preconceptions and distortions of reality and
those of the therapist. In the strange, delicate, dyadic
relationship between patient and therapist, the events of the
outside world can become surprisingly elusive.
</P>
<P>
   In some contexts, distortions are an inevitable and even
productive part of the therapeutic process. There are areas of
insight-oriented therapy, for example, where exact historical truth
is neither attainable nor necessary. It has become widely accepted
by psychotherapists that a patient's narrative of her past is
constructed in the present and therefore necessarily influenced by
it. The remembered past is in constant flux.
</P>
<P>
   In many situations, however, an accurate assessment of the
patient's life is crucial for both diagnosis and treatment. With
the manic artist, outside sources of information were all too
abundant. By the end of her first day in the ward, the place was a
circus. The horde of visitors had supplied us with ample
information about her life.
</P>
<P>
   But with many patients such crucial data are in short supply.
The situation is particularly perilous for the therapist when
information is not just distorted, but omitted. Patients may
consciously wish to deny or hide aspects of their lives. More
commonly, they simply do not see the elided area as important or
problematic.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most common and worrisome omission in psychotherapy
is information about alcohol abuse. I learned this the hard way
when I first began my practice. An internist called to ask me how I
was handling the severe alcohol abuse of the patient he had
referred to me. Three months into therapy, the patient was happily
exploring memories of her narcissistic father, and I had no notion
that he was an alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   For the patient as well as for the therapist, bringing outside
sources of information into the therapeutic dialogue can add useful
new vantage points and can often overturn prior assumptions and
beliefs. It can be information from family members or physicians;
it can be patients' year-end work evaluations, or even their old
report cards.
</P>
<P>
   After the artist was discharged, she provided the hospital staff
with just such a new, outside vantage, but it was one from which to
view our own therapeutic world. She sent a photo to hang in the
ward.
</P>
<P>
   The image is one that I often recall when I am forcibly brought
up against the limits of psychotherapy. In the picture, the ward
staff sits huddled over a table surrounded by the plexiglass bubble
of the nurse's station. A pale reflection of the patient stares
back from the surface of the glass.
</P>
</TEXT>
