<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SAGE-GROUSE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A LIFE IN THE SHADOWS, A BIRD GAINS STATUS AS A SPECIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo., Ore.)   (The Science Times)  
 By JON LUOMA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a new image suddenly materializing on a tapestry, a new
species of bird has emerged from research in the sagebrush
ecosystem of western Colorado and eastern Utah, according to
scientists working there.
</P>
<P>
   The bird, the Gunnison sage grouse, named for the area of
Colorado where it was discovered, has been in plain view all along
_ seen, hunted as a game bird and, most spectacularly, heard at
sunrise every spring as part of one of the avian world's oddest
courtship rituals.
</P>
<P>
   The Gunnison sage grouse had long been assumed to be the same
species as the related northern sage grouse, even though the two
differ starkly in size, appearance, behavior, and now, it turns
out, DNA.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery is rare news in the world of avian taxonomy. This
appears to be the first instance in decades that a wholly new
species of bird has been described in the continental United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Banks, an ornithologist with the Biological
Resources Division of the U.G. Survey, said, ``People find new
species from time to time in South America, for example, on an
isolated mountaintop no one's been to before. But reporting a new
species in the U.S. is extremely unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks, who manages the official catalog of bird species for the
American Ornithological Union, said that no such event had occurred
in his career, and might well reach back to the end of the 19th
century.
</P>
<P>
   It is no small matter for bird-watchers seeking to add new
species to lists of species viewed. A few of the most savvy have
already begun pilgrimages to Colorado's Gunnison Basin in hope of
being among the first to add a new species to their life lists.
That trickle could turn into a flood after the bird is officially
listed as a new species by the American Ornithological Union in its
journal, The Auk, later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Word has only barely gotten out,'' Banks said. ``It really
hasn't been publicized very much in public or in the popular
journals that get to the bird-watchers _ that will happen in very
short order, and people will be going en masse to add the bird to
their lists.''
</P>
<P>
   Eager bird-watchers may not want to wait too long. Even before
its status as a new species becomes official, scientists studying
the species say it has suffered sharp declines in this century, and
some environmentalists are already calling for the Gunnison sage
grouse to be listed as an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   Taxonomists acknowledge that the very process of deciding when a
form constitutes a separate species can sometimes be a judgment
call. In the past, physically distinct but closely related forms
have either been ``lumped'' into one species, with each form
classified as a subspecies, or ``split'' into two species.
</P>
<P>
   A scientific committee of the American Ornithological Union
performs such hairsplitting based not only on differences in
physical appearance, but on evidence of free interbreeding between
two groups. Two groups that are not freely interbreeding are
presumed to be on separate evolutionary paths.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, the Gunnison sage grouse was never even considered a
subspecies of the more widely distributing northern sage grouse.
There now appears to be little room for doubt that it is, in fact,
a wholly distinct species. The creature not only does not
interbreed with the northern sage grouse, the two are so strikingly
different in both appearance and behavior that it seems almost a
wonder that they could have ever been considered birds of the same
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, even more definitive evidence piled up, when detailed
studies of the two groups' DNA showed that they were far too
distantly related to be considered the same species. The findings
were reported by Dr. Tom Quinn and Dr. Sara Oyler-McCance of Denver
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the strongest cases that's ever been,'' says Dr.
Jessica Young, a biologist at Colorado's Western State College,
whose studies have been crucial to defining the species.
</P>
<P>
   Both the more common northern sage grouse and the Gunnison
species indulge in one of the animal world's most peculiar mating
routines. Male sage grouse are equipped with air sacs on their
breasts, which they use in the early predawn hours each spring,
making a racket as they congregate in large groups, called leks, or
strutting grounds. Their mating call, audible a mile or more away,
has been compared to the sound of bubbles, or gulps, underwater.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the most dominant and aggressive males position
themselves in the center of the lek, fending off all pretenders to
this throne. One by one, females visit the lek, choosing a mate
based, as nearly as biologists can tell, on the quality of his
bubbly noise-making and vigor and quality of a rapid head-shaking,
strutting dance that accompanies it. The winner, almost always,
turns out to be one of the most dominant males at the center of the
lek, with one or two males often fathering almost all of the chicks
born in a given year.
</P>
<P>
   It was sound from the strutting grounds that provided some of
the first strong hints that the two groups might in fact be
separate species. As an undergraduate at the University of
California at San Diego in the 1980s, Young had found herself
listening to and trying to analyze hundreds of tapes of northern
sage grouse as part of a biology project. When some new tapes of
sage grouse arrived from the Gunnison Basin, Young was startled at
the differences in vocal patterns. While northern sage grouse
consistently pop their air sacs twice in each of the many brief
strut displays they perform, the Gunnison birds pop their air sacs
nine times, and the sounds they produced are notably deeper.
</P>
<P>
   Young said that once she heard the tapes, she rounded up video
and audio recorders, a mini-van, a portable bird blind, and her
mother, who drove with her directly to Colorado to make more
recordings. That outing turned into a career.
</P>
<P>
   Young continued to specialize in studies of the Gunnison grouse
while receiving a doctorate at Purdue and, later, after being named
to the faculty at Western State, which is in Gunnison.
</P>
<P>
   Her chief collaborator, Dr. Clait Braun, recently retired as
avian research program manager for Colorado Division of Wildlife,
says he began to suspect that the Gunnison grouse were a separate
subspecies, but not a full species, as early as the late 1970s,
when his surveys of sage grouse wings turned in by hunters proved
that grouse in the Gunnison Basin were remarkably smaller than sage
grouse shot elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But Braun says he was ``too conservative'' to come to the
extraordinary conclusion that the Gunnison grouse was a separate
species. He says Young, in time, simply compiled too much evidence,
including ``exquisite behavioral findings,'' to conclude otherwise.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Physically, aside from the differences in size, the Gunnison
grouse have different coloration and patterns in their feathers,
including white bands on their tail feathers. Beyond the
differences in vocal performances, the Gunnison males perform a
different sort of strut, tossing their elaborate neck feathers, or
filoplume, over their heads like pony tails, and wagging their tail
feathers at the end of the display. When Young tried to play
Gunnison grouse sounds in the territories of northern sage grouse,
the northern females actively shunned the area, repelled. The same
occurred when she tried to romance Gunnison females with the sounds
of northern sage grouse males.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really made the case that under all the concepts of what
makes a species, these birds were really different,'' Braun said.
``Her case eventually became overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   But the two researchers also found that the species they had
just discovered was in serious peril. ``At the same time we
realized we had a distinct species, we also realized we had fewer
than 5,000 of them left,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the bird's survival problems preceded even its formal
designation as a species. In January, American Lands, an
environmental group in Portland, Ore., petitioned the United States
Fish and Wildlife Service for an emergency listing of the Gunnison
sage grouse as an endangered species, and that agency has begun a
review of the petition.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Randy Webb, a consulting biologist and lawyer in Eugene,
Ore., who prepared the petition for the environmental group, said
he was shocked at the state of sage grouse in general when the
group first asked him to look at the bird's status. Webb said
historical accounts suggested that across the great sweep of the
arid intermountain West, sage grouse were once extremely abundant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are stories about them blackening the skies,'' he said.
``Of kids going out with a stick to round up grouse for dinner, and
of market hunters loading them up by the wagonload. This is a
species that in its ecosystem used to be an ecological dominant,
like buffalo or salmon.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb estimates that numbers of the more abundant northern sage
grouse have decreased by 90 percent or more, from somewhere beyond
one million birds in the West to perhaps 100,000. But the status of
the Gunnison sage grouse, he said, ``is much, much worse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
