<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investors shake up the market value rankings
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Investors vote for and against companies by buying or
selling their shares, making market value _ share price times
shares outstanding _ the chief barometer of the public's perception
of a company's worth.
</P>
<P>
   Consider how those perceptions have changed for a pair of
heavyweight in the latest - July 10 - Business Week ranking of
global corporate giants.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which topped the list of 100 biggest companies in
1999, dropped to fourth place this year after taking a drubbing in
a federal antitrust lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Coca-Cola, whose troubles led to a top-level
management turnover, fell to 26th place this year from 11th a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Atlanta-based companies also moved in the rankings.
Home improvement retailer Home Depot moved up to 34th from 41st,
while BellSouth, the phone company, dropped to 49th from 36th.
</P>
<P>
   No home field advantage
</P>
<P>
   Corporations may get ego satisfaction by putting their names on
sports stadiums and arenas, but it can be hazardous to their stock,
says the July 3 Barron's. A notable exception is Philips, as in
Atlanta's Philips Arena, whose shareholders have done well.
</P>
<P>
   But the shares of 17 of the 47 firms that have slapped their
names on sports facilities in recent years have declined since the
openings. The worst showing was by Fruit of the Loom, whose Pro
Player sports apparel division paid to put its name on the home
field of the Miami Dolphins and the Florida Marlins. Fruit of the
Loom's stock plunged 99 percent and the company filed for
bankruptcy, Barron's notes.
</P>
<P>
   Conseco and Staples have also declined since the opening of
Conseco Fieldhouse, home of the Indiana Pacers, and Staples Arena,
home court of the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But Qualcomm, which put its name to Jack Murphy stadium in San
Diego in 1997, has seen its shares rise more than ninefold.
</P>
<P>
   In second place among winners is Philips Arena, home of the
Atlanta Hawks basketball and Thrashers hockey teams. Shares of the
Royal Philips Electronics have posted an annualized return of 98.6
percent since the Netherlands company bought naming rights last
year from Turner Broadcasting System, a Time Warner subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning
</P>
<P>
   Red Herring (July) says April's technology sell-off shook the
venture capital industry ``to its foundations,'' but that it may be
a good thing by forcing lenders and investors back to basics.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune (July 17) says the federal court ruling to cut Microsoft
in half hasn't stopped the software giant from launching a daring
bid ``to rekindle growth by reinventing the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Playboy was one of the first magazines to grasp the Internet's
impact, going on the Web in 1994. But that has been a money-losing
venture, says eCompany Now (July), which is why Playboy Enterprises
expects to spin off 15 percent to 20 percent of Playboy.com as a
public company. Christie Hefner, daughter of founder Hugh Hefner,
anticipates $50 million in new working capital.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
