<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2042 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-NADER-SPOILER-HNS &LR;      07-03 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NADER-SPOILER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NADER, ATTACKING FROM THE LEFT, DENIES HE'S HURTING GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GARY MARTIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Green Party candidate Ralph Nader is mounting a
serious presidential campaign that political observers say may
divert critical support from Vice President Al Gore and possibly
throw the November general election to Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Without the votes to win, Nader could play the role of spoiler,
a role he is quick to reject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't view myself as a spoiler, but as a reformer,'' Nader
told a breakfast gathering of newspaper reporters last week.
</P>
<P>
   The spoiler scenario has been a recurring theme during the 2000
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan, who failed to generate much support with
Republicans, switched to the Reform Party, taking along some ardent
social conservatives and threatening to siphon votes away from
Bush, the Republican presidential hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., emerged in New Hampshire as a serious
threat to Bush in the primaries. After his hard-charging campaign
against Bush fell short, McCain rejected numerous invitations to
mount a third-party challenge that could have undermined Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Now the focus is on Nader, 66, a consumer activist whose rise is
supported by an eclectic following of environmentalists, unions and
the politically disaffected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest surprise of the year has not been McCain's
showing, it's been Nader,'' said Larry Sabato, a University of
Virginia professor and an expert on campaigns and elections.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans blame Ross Perot's surprisingly strong independent
bid for the presidency in 1992 for drawing some Republican and
independent voters away from President George Bush in 1992, handing
the election to Bill Clinton, who himself won with less than 50
percent of the vote. At this point in the 2000 election, it appears
that Nader poses a bigger threat to siphoning liberal Democrats and
labor unionists away from Gore than Buchanan does drawing
arch-conservatives from Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the year, we thought Buchanan might grab
the presidency from George Bush. Now at midyear, it's looking like
Nader might grab the presidency from Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what it will look like in November, but Nader
is doing well enough that the Gore people have to be concerned,''
Sabato said.
</P>
<P>
   Recent national opinion polls show Nader favored by 6 percent of
those surveyed, well ahead of Buchanan at 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A Gore spokesman downplayed the Nader threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This November, people who are serious about protecting the
environment, and want someone to fight for them, know the smart
vote is for Al Gore,'' said spokesman Jano Cabrera at the Gore
campaign headquarters in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, third-party candidates who rise in popularity
emerge in times when voters feel alienated by the major parties,
the candidates or the political process.
</P>
<P>
   Perot, the Dallas billionaire, drew support from people who said
President Bush was complacent but who also lacked interest in
Clinton, the moderate Democratic governor from Arkansas. Perot won
19 percent of the vote with his straight talk about the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The same political dynamic is in place now, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the people who are most alienated who will vote for
Nader,'' said Richard Winger, editor of Ballot Access News in San
Francisco, a nonpartisan newspaper that tracks election results for
minor political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people respond to an honest person, and Nader seems
honest,'' Winger said.
</P>
<P>
   Nader is best known for having taken on corporate powers and
championing such causes as auto safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I combine opportunity with alienation. There's a lot of
alienation around the country. The two parties are rapidly
converging, with the big corporation running the show,'' Nader
said.
</P>
<P>
   Polls also show that some of Nader's support comes from a lack
of interest in the major party presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Nader called Gore a ``gee-whiz, techno twit,'' a hypocrite and a
``plastic person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great environmental impostor,'' Nader said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, according to Nader, is ``beyond satire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His motto is: If polluters give to my campaign, they can
regulate themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Worthey, a San Antonio landscaper, said the public's blase
attitude toward the ``status-quo'' candidates has spurred interest
in Nader's presidential campaign and the fledgling Green Party in
that South Texas city.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are attracted to Nader for the same reason
they were attracted to John McCain,'' explained Worthey, 53.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see Nader as someone who has integrity. He is not bought
and paid for. A lot of people are concerned that people in politics
are owned by big money.''
</P>
<P>
   Worthey, like a other Green Party members, voted as a Democrat
in recent elections. He voted for Clinton in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Nader received 1 percent of the vote in 1996 as a Green Party
candidate. In Texas, he was a write-in candidate.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Nader will spend $5 million to get on the ballot in
Texas and 47 other states.
</P>
<P>
   To boost his candidacy, Nader has received donations from
celebrities such as singers Jackson Browne and Bonnie Raitt, actors
Paul Newman and Warren Beatty, and ice cream purveyors Ben Cohen
and Jerry Greenfield of Ben and Jerry's Homemade, Federal Election
Commission records show.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hightower, a radio personality and former Texas agriculture
commissioner, has signed up to ramrod the Green Party presidential
campaign in Texas. In a television interview, Hightower said Nader
is generating a buzz ``hotter than high-school love.''
</P>
<P>
   If Nader wins 5 percent of the vote in November, the Green Party
will receive federal funding for the 2004 election. The Reform
Party will receive $12 million in federal funds this year for its
presidential nominee, based on Perot's 8 percent showing in the
1996 general election.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Green Party officials say Nader needs to be included in the
presidential debates this fall to build on his support and poll
numbers, but the candidate faces a Catch-22.
</P>
<P>
   According to the rules established by the Commission on
Presidential Debates, a candidate must have a 15-percent standing
in the polls to be included in the televised presidential forum.
</P>
<P>
   To force his way in, Nader has sued to block corporate
sponsorship of presidential debates that exclude minor political
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan and the Libertarian Party also have sued to be included
in the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Green Party officials believe exposure from the debates could
create a groundswell of support that would move him far past other
minor party candidates and make him a serious contender for the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Nader's rise as a potential challenger is bolstered by
Buchanan's recent decline, some say.
</P>
<P>
   Lingering questions about whether Perot will mount a third
campaign continue to overshadow Buchanan. The Reform Party
presidential nomination will be determined in August.
</P>
<P>
   In his third presidential campaign, Buchanan has failed to rally
supporters in the Reform Party as he did as a Republican candidate
in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are sick of him,'' Sabato said. ``They view him as
offensive and his newly adopted party is falling apart.''
</P>
<P>
   With Buchanan's star diminishing, the disenchanted are looking
at Nader. Many of the disenchanted in the 2000 election are
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of old liberal Democrats who are tired of the
Clinton-Gore new Democrats,'' Sabato suggested. ``They hate welfare
reform. They don't support the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, a Bush spokeswoman, said Nader's rise in the polls
coincides with Gore's failure to unite the various factions within
the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has some serious problems within his base,'' Hughes
said. ``According to the polling, some members of what would be
considered the Democratic Party are not happy with Al Gore as a
candidate and are looking towards Ralph Nader as an alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, says the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bush campaign is trying to distract away from the real
choice in November, and that is between Gore and Bush,'' Cabrera
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between those two candidates is night and
day,'' Cabrera continued, saying that Gore is trying to protect the
environment, while ``Bush has numerous slick ties to big oil
interests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
