<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AHEADOFCURVE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ahead of the curve
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEROKEE
</P>
<P>
   Agency closes on land
</P>
<P>
   for research park
</P>
<P>
   The Cherokee County Development Authority has closed on the
purchase of 629 acres that will become a high-tech research park,
said Kevin Johns, vice president of the development authority.
</P>
<P>
   Canton Textile Mills sold the land. The development authority
purchased the land with funding from Cherokee County. The county
backed $6.5 million in bonds. The land is located on Canton's
northern edge, north of the RiverStone mall, and runs parallel to
I-575.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the land is the 300-acre Hickory Log Creek Reservoir,
being constructed by the city of Canton and the Cobb County Water
Authority. Technology Park Atlanta is to develop the park, which is
expected to bring 15,000 jobs to the county in the next two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   FAYETTE
</P>
<P>
   Developer seeks
</P>
<P>
   annexation of tract
</P>
<P>
   Developer Bob Rolader is requesting that his proposed 454-lot
Deer Pointe subdivision be annexed into the city of Fayetteville so
the houses can hook up to the city's sewer system.
</P>
<P>
   The property is now located just west of the city limits, south
of Lester Road. If the area is annexed, Rolader is offering 215
acres of the 610-acre tract to the city to be used as a park, as
well as access to several small lakes as a water source. If the
annexation is denied, Rolader has stated that he will develop the
tract, make lot sizes smaller and run the subdivision on septic
tanks.
</P>
<P>
   The request will be discussed July 11 at a Fayetteville Planning
and Zoning Commission meeting. City officials have declined to
comment until they review of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   FULTON
</P>
<P>
   New office building
</P>
<P>
   at McGinnis Park
</P>
<P>
   Trammell Crow Co. and Triad Properties Corp. have started
construction on a second office building at their McGinnis Park
development in Alpharetta.
</P>
<P>
   The four-story, 100,200-square-foot building will be completed
in January. Trammell Crow and Triad Properties began the building
after leasing 97 percent of the first building at McGinnis Park.
Tenants include Qwest Communications, Pilsner Urquel and Keebler
Foods Co. The master plan for McGinnis Park calls for three
buildings on 25 acres at Windward Concourse and McGinnis Ferry
Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although Phases I and II were developed according to the
master plan of McGinnis Park, great flexibility exists in the
actual design and size of Phase III,'' said Penny Thompson, senior
associate at Trammell Crow.
</P>
<P>
   The final phase can accommodate the space requirements of a new
tenant or the expansion needs of a tenant in the first or second
building, she said.
</P>
<P>
   County to consider
</P>
<P>
   several projects
</P>
<P>
   The Fulton County Board of Commissioners will consider several
small-to-moderate-sized projects for the north Fulton area this
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the projects on the agenda will include a day care
center for 270 children, a 45-lot subdivision on Jones Bridge Road,
a 175-unit townhouse development on Morris Road and several other
small-to-medium housing projects. To see all the projects that were
considered by the county planning commission and will be heard on
Wednesday, go to www.fultonecd.org/zoning
</P>
<P>
   /current.htm and click on ``planning commission
recommendations.''
</P>
<P>
   At the planning commission meeting June 20, several residents
turned out to ask that a seven-home subdivision proposal on Kimball
Bridge Road be reduced to six and its lots be bigger. When the
commission approved the seven-home plan, one of the angered
residents said ``they're on the take'' as he filed out. A couple of
board members glared angrily but said nothing.
</P>
<P>
   GWINNETT
</P>
<P>
   Multiuse project goes
</P>
<P>
   before Duluth council
</P>
<P>
   The final hurdle for a controversial multiuse development will
head before the Duluth City Council on July 10. Crossroads at
Gwinnett Place is an 80-acre development that combines office,
residential, retail and industrial projects.
</P>
<P>
   The project is estimated to spawn 2,500 jobs and $3 million in
taxes annually.
</P>
<P>
   Developer Steven Gaultney is attempting to move the project from
Gwinnett County into the city of Duluth _ a move that coincided
with a six-month county moratorium on new rezoning requests.
Gaultney said the moratorium wasn't the reason for this move.
Duluth has multipurpose permitting he desired for this project.
</P>
<P>
   The Duluth Planning Commission gave its approval to the project
last month. Many residents, though, are upset with the inclusion of
a road extension on the property _ North Berkeley Parkway _ which
they fear will increase traffic to nearby subdivisions.
</P>
<P>
   The inclusion of 800 new apartments didn't sit well, either.
Gaultney and residents are discussing these concerns before the
final decision.
</P>
<P>
   _Staff writers Tony Wilbert, Dana Tofig, Don Fernandez, Janet
Frankston and Alan Gomez contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
