<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2044 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-DEVAULT01-COX     07-03 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEVAULT01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peppier feel for Mazda's 626
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mazda claims to have made dozens of changes to its
family-oriented 626 sedan for the 2000 model year. The improvements
are striking, more so inside than outside.
</P>
<P>
   Revisions to the front and rear aren't so radical that the 626
stands out in a crowded parking lot. But start it up, and the
170-horsepower V-6 that comes with the LX and test ES versions is
quieter. Take it down the road and the ride, along with overall
driveability, is better.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Guide rates the 626 as a ``best buy,'' while Road &AMP;
Track notes that Mazda has addressed the characteristics that have
caused the enthusiast press to whip on the 626 for not being ``more
of a serious driver's car.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the 2.5-liter V-6 hardly turns the 626 into a performance
sedan, but couple it with the easy-shifting five-speed manual, and
the 3,000-pound sedan has good start-up acceleration. No need to
worry about the 626 leaping out from under you during routine
highway acceleration.
</P>
<P>
   Prices start at $18,245 for the LX and $20,445 for the ES with
Mazda's 130-hp four-cylinder engine. The LX with V-6 is $19,445,
and the ES is $22,445. Basic equipment is reasonably good up and
down the line, with available options including side air bags and
traction control ($950), six-disc CD player ($225) and four-speed
automatic transmission ($800).
</P>
<P>
   One area in which the 626 distinguishes itself is interior
space. Mazda's design folks have made the 626 a compact car on the
outside (overall length is a modest 187.4 inches), but the cabin
has 97.1 cubic feet of room, with seating in the rear that's
generous enough for full-size adults.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touches include the swinging center-dash vents that Mazda
has used for years, just enough chrome inside and out to give the
626 some character without making it garish, and stereo controls
that don't require technical expertise or awkward contortions to
reach and operate.
</P>
<P>
   The ease of operation extends to the major controls, with good
steering and brake feel for a car in the 626's class _ think
Passat, Galant, Alero and Altima. As other reviewers have pointed
out, the 626 is not an attention-grabber, but it does deserve a
second look by family-car shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 2000 Mazda 626 ES front-drive sedan
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $24,070 (base: $22,445, plus $450 delivery)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 2.5-liter V-6 engine with 24 valves (170
horsepower), five-speed manual overdrive transmission
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual front air bags, optional power anti-lock
brakes with traction control and dual front side air bags, $950;
side-impact beams; height-adjustable front shoulder belts
</P>
<P>
   Standard features include: leather-trimmed interior, CD/cassette
players, air conditioning, glass sunroof, power windows and locks,
keyless entry system, cruise control with steering-wheel-mounted
controls, height-adjustable power driver's seat
</P>
<P>
   Other options on test vehicle: six-disc CD changer, $225
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 21 mpg premium unleaded city, 27 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
