<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORA30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tiny valve has big role in smog control
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dynamometer emission testing of older vehicles has been the
key in detecting the main contributor to ground-level ozone, oxides
of nitrogen, commonly referred to as NOx.
</P>
<P>
   This pollutant, produced when engine combustion temperatures
exceed 2,500 degrees, is spewed out of the tailpipe into the air.
When combined with hot, sunny conditions, it sets the stage for
ozone alert days.
</P>
<P>
   One MUMMI _ Miscellaneous Unscheduled Manufacturer's Maintenance
Item _ that has risen from obscurity to star status as a result of
this testing is the exhaust gas recirculation valve.
</P>
<P>
   EGR devices, which began making their appearances on engines in
the early 1970s, were developed for the sole purpose of controlling
NOx. They accomplished this task by cooling down the combustion
chamber during certain driving conditions.
</P>
<P>
   To understand how the EGR process works, you need to know two
basic concepts:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fuel is cool. This means when the proportion of fuel to air is
fuel-rich, the combustion chamber is naturally cooled. While this
would seem to solve the heat problem, there is a downside.
Fuel-rich mixtures produce a much more deadly pollutant than NOx,
carbon monoxide.
</P>
<P>
   With the price of gasoline as high as it is, fuel-rich burning
means worse mileage and higher fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More air, more heat. Much like using a bellows on an open fire
to raise the temperature, the amount of oxygen pushed into the
intake manifold directly relates to the amount of heat produced
during combustion.
</P>
<P>
   The EGR valve does just what its name says. It opens a small
orifice between the engine's fresh air intake and exhaust
manifolds. When this passage is open, it permits a small amount of
exhaust gas to be recycled back into the intake manifold, where it
is mixed with the air and fuel entering the combustion chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Exhaust gas contains very little oxygen because it was used up
during the burning process. It displaces some of the oxygen in the
air/fuel mixture, allowing for a cooler burn inside the combustion
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   This accomplishes two things: It helps control oxides of
nitrogen, and it helps eliminate pinging, also the result of excess
or unplanned heat.
</P>
<P>
   The EGR valve is only effective during certain driving modes. It
should not be open when the engine idles or during acceleration.
Both of these conditions require a disproportionate cool-fuel
mixture, so EGR isn't needed anyway. If exhaust gas is allowed to
recirculate at these times, the lack of oxygen in the air/fuel
mixture will cause rough idle and driveability problems.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, during midrange cruising, the engine's need
for fuel decreases, and combustion chamber temperatures start to
climb. The EGR valve needs to be open.
</P>
<P>
   Externally, an EGR valve can appear to be working normally.
However, the hidden problem occurs between the exhaust and intake
orifices underneath the valve. Exhaust gases contain some carbon,
and over a period of time, the orifices and passages become plugged
with the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The only solution is to remove whatever is necessary for access
and clean out the carbon. Repairing this problem can range from
flushing the passages with a special cleaner to actually having to
burn the accumulation of crud out with a welding torch. Sometimes
the valve can be saved; sometimes it must be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter has 27 years of experience in the auto repair
industry and is an automotive instructor at DeKalb Technical
Institute and an ASE master automobile technician/L1. Write her in
care of Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689,
Atlanta, GA 30302.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
