<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TALK0705-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leasing still a valid option
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The juiciest deals may be gone, but millions of
Americans still choose to lease their new cars.
</P>
<P>
   Why would that many people want to make payments on a big-ticket
item, one they will use every day, when they know that they will
never own it?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is money. The upfront cost is usually cheaper, and
monthly payments can be a lot less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a lot more for a little bit more money,'' said Chris
Consolmagno, a young Atlantan who sold his last car and leased a
Chevrolet S10 pickup truck. ``Besides, I like to have a new car
fairly often.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, leasing was even more attractive. ``Consumers
could get absolutely tremendous leasing deals,'' said David McKay,
a director in J.D. Power and Associates' analysis group.
</P>
<P>
   Ford popularized leasing, then many competitors rushed in.
``Then you got a flood of 2-year-old vehicles coming off lease,''
McKay recalled. Resale values were unexpectedly low, some lessors
took a bath, and leasing terms got less generous.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some consumers dropped out of the leasing market.
Some just didn't understand how the system worked, and some were
unhappy about lease-ending charges that they hadn't noticed before.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 4.4 million Americans leased a car or truck last year.
That means one out of four new vehicles was leased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mainly that's because people want more car for lower monthly
payments,'' said Linda Lee Goldberg. She is president of CarSource,
a car buying service in Larkspur, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Convenience was another motivation. ``Most people like the idea
that they're renting a car and they don't have to do anything but
turn the car back in,'' Goldberg added. ``They can get a new car
every three or four years, and that's especially attractive on
expensive cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Leasing works best for careful shoppers who have predictable
lifestyles and are willing to do their research about how leasing
works, as well as about the car they want.
</P>
<P>
   If you think you might need to trade the car in before the lease
is up, perhaps to accommodate a growing family, leasing is not for
you.
</P>
<P>
   If predictability means owning rather than renting, or driving
the same car for many years and many miles, leasing won't work very
well. Finally, leasing may not be possible if you have a bad credit
record.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some leasing tips from experts:
</P>
<P>
   Read the contract. The paperwork can be confusing, and some
lessors have used that to overcharge customers. That's why the
government now requires a simplified disclosure form.
</P>
<P>
   Check for such things as numbers that don't add up or charges
that have not been made clear. ''It's a contract, and it's your
responsibility to make sure you understand your obligations,''
McKay said.
</P>
<P>
   You can find a sample disclosure form, along with other useful
information, at www.ftc.gov/ftc
</P>
<P>
   /consumer.htm. Click on Automobiles, then on Keys to Vehicle
Leasing.
</P>
<P>
   You can get a similar rundown by writing to Publications
Services, MS-127, Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System,
Washington, D.C. 20551. Ask for a copy of the ``Consumer Guide to
Vehicle Leasing.''
</P>
<P>
   You may want to take a contract home to examine closely before
deciding to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Closed-end leases are the most amenable for consumers. With this
type, you simply return your vehicle at the end of the lease and
have no other responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The leasing company estimates, upfront, what your car will be
worth at the end of the lease. If it's worth less, the company is
responsible for the difference, not you.
</P>
<P>
   With an open-end lease, the consumer takes all the risk and is
responsible for any gap between the anticipated value of the
vehicle, stated in the contract, and what it actually is worth at
the end of the lease.
</P>
<P>
   Open-end leases are used primarily for commercial business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a closed-end lease is what a client should have,''
Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't pay too much. A lease contract gives you the capitalized
cost, which is the price of the vehicle plus some fees. If it's
more than you would pay for buying the car, start over again on
negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   Pay attention to the mileage limit in your contract. Often it
will be 12,000 to 15,000 miles per year. If you go over the limit,
excess mileage charges can add up very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Think seriously about gap insurance. This protects you if a
leased car is stolen or totaled. Some experts consider it a must,
but check the price.
</P>
<P>
   DECISION POINTS
</P>
<P>
   The choice between leasing and finance depends on the buyer's
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Lease if...
</P>
<P>
   _ You like a new car every two to four years.
</P>
<P>
   _ You know you can keep the car for the full term.
</P>
<P>
   _ You're easy on cars.
</P>
<P>
   _ You want a nicer car than you can afford to make payments on.
</P>
<P>
   _ You have good credit.
</P>
<P>
   _ You don't mind payments that don't build equity.
</P>
<P>
   Finance if...
</P>
<P>
   _ You want the same car for many years.
</P>
<P>
   _ You think you might have to give it up earlier.
</P>
<P>
   _ You put a lot of wear and tear on a car.
</P>
<P>
   _ You're on a Chevy budget and can accept a Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   _ You have a poor credit record.
</P>
<P>
   _ You want to own what you pay for.
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet
</P>
<P>
   _ For advice and a good glossary of leasing terms, check out
www.cars.com. Go down the left side to Advice, then click on More
to find leasing information.
</P>
<P>
   _ For negotiating tips and interactive calculators, go to
www.kiplinger.com. and click on Complete Auto Guide, then on Lease
or Buy?
</P>
<P>
   _ Skeptics can find Top 10 Leasing Scams, along with plenty of
advice, at www.leasetips.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ For good advice and good links, go to www.leaseguide.com.
</P>
<P>
   Books
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Leasing Lessons for Smart Shoppers,'' by Mark Eskeldson.
$8.95.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Car Buyer's and Leaser's Negotiating Bible,'' by W. James
Bragg. $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
