<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0705-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The cat's meow
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ This morning dawned cool and clear. The
greens surrounding the treetop aerie where I sleep all summer, are
lush from spring rains, and as I stretch an arm out from under the
comforter to test the air, sounds of
</P>
<P>
   another day's beginning are all around.
</P>
<P>
   Mama bluejay is lecturing her babes on the use and abuse of back
yard feeders; a mourning dove is softly whooping to a friend on a
nearby limb who dutifully answers in kind, and Sheena, queen of the
squirrels, is scampering on
</P>
<P>
   the roof above me, occasionally swinging onto the old half-round
gutters to look in and ask when's breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   For one brief and shining Camelot moment, before the numbness of
sleep has washed from my awareness, all's right in a perfect world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mee-owww,'' a small voice calls from the doorway to my porch.
I roll over for a look. Biddy, my 11-year-old Siamese sits daintily
on the threshold awaiting our morning chat _ lopsided though it may
be. I tell her I'll be there in a minute and invite her into the
hammock for a snuggle. She refuses and chatters on.
</P>
<P>
   Biddy doesn't like my sleeping porch _ usually too chilly for
her heat-seeking Asian blood. Once in a while, though, I catch her
stretched out in a patch of late afternoon sun that has angled its
way onto the old canvas-covered floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``MEE-OWWW!'' Her final warning.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, I roll out and slip into the ragged elephant shirt
that hangs on a hook next to the door. Biddy leads the way
downstairs. I pad along in her wake, cautiously stepping around her
stair-by-stair ballet as she lures me to the kitchen and reminds me
her food dish is perilously low and the water in her big pink bowl
is a night old.
</P>
<P>
   As I scrape and wash, rinse and fill, I think what a perfect
morning it will be for tea and toast on the porch swing. Maybe I'll
ask Biddy to join me if she promises not to dive off the rail after
the first critter who moseys through
</P>
<P>
   the yard. Then I remember _ tea and tranquillity will have to
wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time for our medicine,'' I chant lightly. On the floor I line
up her vitamin drops, an antibiotic prescribed for a tummy upset, a
tube of hairball remedy, and a packet of chicken-flavored
toothpaste. Biddy has gone rigid.
</P>
<P>
   Down on all fours (mine) I go, stuffing the stiff cat's backside
back between my legs and crossing my ankles so she can't back out.
With my left elbow balanced on the floor and the forearm wrapped
around her chest, I reach for the
</P>
<P>
   first dropper.
</P>
<P>
   Biddy shrieks.
</P>
<P>
   An eternity later, woman and cat straggle onto the front porch.
Biddy has pasty antibiotic dribbling down her chin, and we're both
wearing a week's supply of Kitty Vita-Mite. An inch-and-a-half of
hairball remedy is stuck to my leg, and the chicken-flavored
toothpaste is history. I fell on it with my knee and squirted it
all over the butcher block leg.
</P>
<P>
   Biddy sits on a rocker, washing and grumping. I remind her that
I don't like poking stuff between her teeth _ particularly my
finger _ anymore than she does. She turns her back on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey!'' I say stooping beside her chair so we're eyeball to
eyeball. Remember me? I'm the goof who turned down a two-week
cruise in the Bahamas on a friend's boat because you have an upset
tummy.'' She looks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``And don't forget the long holiday weekend I spent alone, with
you, rather than riding bikes and toasting sunsets on Pelee Island
with my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems I've reached her. She turns, flashes those big Siamese
blues at me, and licks a glob of chicken-flavored toothpaste off my
right knee. I pat her head. She purrs. We're friends again.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great day after all.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
