   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Suicide bombers set off a series of
devastating blasts throughout the breakaway republic of Chechnya on
Sunday night, killing more than 40 Russian soldiers and wounding
120, Russian officials said Monday. The truck bombs exploded in
towns and cities ostensibly under Russian control and represented
one of the fiercist rebel counterattacks in the bitter conflict. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-MINORITIES (Los Angeles) _ At some unknown moment between
now and next July 1, if state demographers are right, California
will become the first big state in the nation in which non-Hispanic
whites are officially no longer a majority. Or, to put it another
way, California will become by far the largest proving ground for
what it may eventually be like to live in a United States in which
no one racial or ethnic group predominates. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SYPHILIS-ERADICATE (Nashville, Tenn.) _ The new jail inmate had
intimidating arms, thick as thighs. But he extended one meekly when
a nurse, Jean Graves, told him: ``I have to give you a tuberculosis
skin test. I also have to draw blood for syphilis, OK?'' As she
slid the needle into his skin, Nashville took one more small step
in a sweeping national program: a push by health authorities to rid
the country of the ancient scourge of syphilis, spirochete
bacterium by spirochete, chancre sore by chancre, once and for all.
Even here, where the syphilis rate is second-highest in the country
among major cities, topped only by Indianapolis, the numbers are
less than staggering: Only 250 cases of new _ and thus still
infectious _ syphilis turned up last year. Nationwide, they dropped
below 7,000, down from the most recent peak of 50,000 in 1990. But
that is the very point, health officials say. Now, when new cases
are at an all-time low and so concentrated that about half of them
come from just 25 of the country's 3,100 counties, is the time to
try to wipe it out altogether. They are prosecuting a multipronged
attack that includes heavy reliance on community activism and
stepped-up detective work to track down carriers and those at risk,
as well as expanded clinical and laboratory services. By Carey
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   BROWNSTONE-REVIVAL (Portland, Conn.) _ Brownstone is back. That
somber yet elegant cloak for more than 50,000 row houses, from
Baltimore to Boston, was revered during the so-called Brown Decades
of the mid-nineteeth century, then reviled by the century's turn,
when gleaming white limestone and marble captivated the public. But
preservationists and planners are beginning to see a new future for
the formidable stone. Architects have started using it to give a
touch of historical sobriety to gaudy mansionettes, and
conservators have begun renewing the elegant facades of grand
monuments. But the revival has sparked a debate on whether
brownstone should be used at all. Because the terrible secret is
that brownstone isn't really much good as a building material. The
same quality that gives brownstone its charm, making it easy to
quarry and easy to sculpt, also makes it exquisitely vulnerable to
harsh weather and the passage of time. By Tracie Rohzan.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT8.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Undated) _ Crude oil traders and analysts in Houston
and London said Monday that they expect oil prices to drop if Saudi
Arabia pumps into the market 500,000 barrels a day more oil than
previously agreed to. (Summary from wires) By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
