<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAYMUSICALS-REISSUES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIVAL OF THE FITTEST: CD SERIES POLISHES BROADWAY'S OLD JEWELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Didier C. Deutsch, the recent spate of successful revivals
of classic Broadway musicals signifies an important change on the
Great White Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am much more gratified when I see shows like `Kiss Me Kate'
and `The Music Man'' attracting crowds again,'' he says. ``Perhaps
that might compel writers to go back to the drawing board and
create shows that have tunes that sing. Revivals are doing so well
on Broadway right now because people want to go to the theater,
enjoy themselves and leave the theater humming a tune.''
</P>
<P>
   This is important to Deutsch not only because he personally
prefers the traditional song-and-dance showmanship of old-style
musicals to the more complex storytelling of recent fare, but also
because revivals are his business _ revivals of Broadway musical
soundtracks, that is. Along with producers Darcy M. Proper, Tom
Shepard, Gary Schultz and Thomas Frost, Deutsch, a drama critic and
educator, is responsible for the Columbia Broadway Masterworks, a
series of reissues of classic musicals on CD.
</P>
<P>
   On May 30, five more titles hit the stores, bringing the total
since the series' inception two years ago to 14. The latest
releases are the original cast albums of ``Bye Bye Birdie,''
``Finian's Rainbow,'' ``Kismet'' and ``The Pajama Game,'' and the
1962 studio cast revival of ``Show Boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Previously released titles in the series include ``Girl Crazy,''
``Company, South Pacific,'' ``A Little Night Music,'' ``On the
Town,'' ``Oh, Kay!,'' ``Cinderella,'' ``Flower Drum Song,''
``Gypsy,'' ``Mame,'' ``Sweet Charity'' and ``No, No, Nanette.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you consider so many wonderful shows and a plethora of
hit tunes,'' Deutsch says, ``you realize that there is a richness
there that needs to be exploited and brought to the forefront
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Remastered reissues of musical classics are nothing new. In
fact, these producers had worked on previous reissues of some of
the same titles _ while some had been involved with the original
records.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Columbia Broadway Masterworks unique are the
discs' combination of extras. Most of them have bonus tracks, from
alternate song versions to tracks cut before the show hit the
boards. Some feature behind-the-scenes interviews with the stars
and creators. Many of these were found on the original session
tapes and have been previously unreleased.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the series' release of ``Cabaret'' includes four
songs that did not make the final cut, performed by composer John
Kander and lyricist Fred Ebb.
</P>
<P>
   The booklets for each release include vintage cover art, rare
photographs from the original productions, comprehensive cast
listings, discographical annotations and newly commissioned liner
notes by musical-theater authorities. The ``Sweet Charity'' disc
features an interview with composer Cy Coleman; ``West Side Story''
has a remembrance from an original cast member. Some fans,
interested just in the tunes, might find such behind-the-scenes
details irritating; but for musical-theater aficionados, it's a
rare treat to experience the making of a live show that's long
gone.
</P>
<P>
   Much care is taken to perfect the quality of the original
recording, and in a few cases that evolves into a bit of tinkering
_ such as for the song Love, ``Look Away'' in Rodgers and
Hammerstein's ``Flower Drum Song.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The singer, Arabella Hong, at one point went from a head sound
to a throat sound, and that has always disturbed me,'' Deutsch
says. ``When I produced that reissue, I listened to the session
tapes, and there was another tape in which she did exactly the same
thing, but in reverse. I was able to splice together the two
performances and correct the flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take some liberties with the original recordings, but at
the same time, we give it a more natural feel. We remove some of
the reverb if that's in there. The recording sounds much better
than it ever sounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the titles originally had respectable runs on
Broadway, Deutsch says the committee of producers would consider
reissuing a soundtrack for a show that was not successful if it's
considered an important work, such as Stephen Sondheim's ``Anyone
Can Whistle,'' which had only nine performances in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``certainly a flop, but at least to my mind, it was one
of the most important shows of the early '60s, because it announced
the coming of Stephen Sondheim as a major voice in theater.''
Deutsch says. ``Some of the best elements you find in subsequent
shows by Sondheim are an embryo in `Anyone Can Whistle.'''
</P>
<P>
   Other shows being considered include ``Li'l Abner,'' ``House of
Flowers,'' ``Candide,'' ``Bells Are Ringing'' and Maury Yeston's
Tony-winning ``Nine,'' of which only excerpts were released on
record.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the better-known titles such as ``West Side Story''
and ``South Pacific'' sell better, but Deutsch says the great thing
about soundtracks is that they have longevity. Currently, he says,
12 of the 13 bestselling albums in the Sony Classical catalog are
Broadway cast albums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not forget that titles like these will not sell as well
as, say, rock titles,'' he says. ``But in 10 years these will still
be selling.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
