<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOORSTIN-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: THE PRIZE FOR REALITY IS $1 MILLION. ISN'T THAT
UNREAL? 
</HEADLINE>
   By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  It's a safe guess that few of the millions of young and
middle-aged fans of ``Survivor,'' the smash hit CBS specimen of
``reality television,'' have ever heard of Daniel J. Boorstin. Yet
the show's arrival certifies Boorstin as a prophet in his time.
(Speaking of prophecy, CBS is banking on a second reality series,
``Big Brother,'' which begins Wednesday and continues for five
nights a week, to give a further lift to its ratings.)
  It was in 1961 that Boorstin, then a history professor at the
University of Chicago who had won a Bancroft Prize for ``The
Americans: The Colonial Experience'' (Random House), came out with
a new work. ``The Image: Or What Happened to the American Dream?''
(Atheneum) took aim at the unreality of much that was being
marketed as the real stuff of American life. Although the
indictment was not entirely original, he applied it broadly and
forcefully, in particular to the delivery of ``reality'' in all its
dubious forms by television.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everywhere he looked, he found fake events, planted for the
profit of the planters and the delectation of a mass audience.
</P>
<P>
   But in his direst nightmares, even Boorstin, who would go on to
become the Librarian of Congress, apparently never envisioned a
show quite like ``Survivor,'' which under the guise of delivering
real experience serves up a voyeuristic feast drawn from adventure
tales, game shows, soap opera and anything else, be it bowel
movements or rat-eating, that might titillate the impressionable.
 &UR;  &LR; Where ``Survivor'' placed 16 scantily clad campers on a remote
island in the South China Sea, ``Big Brother'' installs 10 people
in a locked house under constant television scrutiny. Where the
cast members of ``Survivor'' get to choose which of them will be
knocked off the show each week, ``Big Brother'' gives the choice to
the audience. Both series trade in what Boorstin called ``synthetic
novelty.''
 &UR;  &LR; To borrow another of his favorite phrases, ``Survivor'' is a total
``pseudo event.'' Although the merchandise is presented as realism,
the essential criterion is simply whether it will pay off. So,
Boorstin charged in 1961, in a society dominated by television
techniques, authenticity is in short supply and getting shorter.
 &UR;  &LR; The success of ``Survivor'' four decades later is evidence of his
prescience: Millions are relishing, as examples of reality,
concoctions contrived to meet the market's taste. The Boorstin
rule: ``By this new Gresham's law of American public life,
counterfeit happenings tend to drive spontaneous happenings out of
circulation.''
 &UR;  &LR; On CBS, as Bill Carter wrote in The New York Times, the line
between news and entertainment is being further eroded by tacking
on a network news announcer, Julie Chen, to play the role of Big
Brother and to interview psychologists and sociologists who don't
mind lending their credentials to the enterprise.
 &UR;  &LR; ``Why are these people willing to do these things?''asks Susan
Zirinsky, referring to the contestants on the programs. Zirinsky is
the executive producer of the CBS news magazine ``48 Hours,'' which
adds to Wednesday's prime-time takeover by devoting a segment to
the ``Survivor'' participants.
</P>
<P>
   Why is an ostensible news program willing to do these things?
Well, there's the fact that CBS has paid $20 million for ``Big
Brother.'' Boorstin offered another answer: Overnight, the people
on a reality program or a game show or a chat show become the talk
of the tube, media-created creatures who, as Boorstin put it, are
known for their well-knownness.
 &UR;  &LR; The network publicity engines do their job. For a season or more
the audience is entranced by who will win the quiz show. Or, now,
it is enthralled by who will get kicked out of the locked house or
whether the former member of the Navy Seals, suddenly a national
figure by virtue of ``Survivor,'' will survive longer than the
truck driver and maybe end up with $1 million, which seems to be
the going rate for victory these days.
 &UR;  &LR;  Boorstin might have been aiming directly at ``Survivor'' and
``Big Brother'' when he wrote, ``The American citizen thus lives in
a world where fantasy is more real than reality.'' The time and
attention the nation lavishes on television and the popularity of a
series like ``Survivor'' lend weight to his assertion that ``in
American public life today pseudo events tend to drive all other
kinds of events out of our consciousness, or at least to overshadow
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Attributing the blurring of news and pseudo news to a
combination of technical virtuosity and audience democratization,
he wrote: ``The image, more interesting than its original, has
become the original. The shadow has become the substance.''
 &UR;  &LR; Are the many millions tuning into ``Survivor'' able to sort out
what is real from what is flagrantly exploitative? Does anybody
care? The soaring ratings seem to signal something more than just a
diverting hour a week and suggest that Boorstin was not giving way
to hyperbole when he wrote that images, synthetic and simplistic
yet vivid and believable, have become the nation's measure of what
is real.
 &UR;  &LR; In a sentence that the creators of ``Survivor'' and ``Big
Brother'' might borrow to promote their goods, Boorstin wrote: ``By
a diabolical irony the very facsimiles of the world which we make
on purpose to bring it within our grasp, to make it less elusive,
have transported us into a new world of blurs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
