<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-IMMIG-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND CHINESE DISCUSS STEMMING FLOW OF ILLEGAL IMMIGRANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Wash., N.Y.)  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The head of the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization
Service held talks here Monday with Chinese officials, hoping to
get ``a commitment for more international cooperation'' in the
agency's effort to stem the huge flow of illegal Chinese immigrants
into the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   The visit, planned months ago, came just weeks after 58 Chinese
immigrants suffocated while being smuggled into England in the back
of a truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten cooperation, but it's been on a case-by-case
basis,'' said the head of the immigration service, Doris Meissner.
``But we'd like to see better cooperation not just from China but
also from transit countries as well.'' Most illegal Chinese
immigrants arrive in the U.S. via a third country, where they often
obtain fake travel documents.
</P>
<P>
   Meissner said the United States had been ``quite successful'' in
some areas, such as slowing the number of illegal migrants who
arrive by boat. But she added that the international smuggling
rings that help Chinese sneak into the U.S. have been quick to
adapt, often creating new problems. She noted that as boat traffic
had dropped off, the number of illegal migrants arriving by air
with counterfeit documents had increased.
</P>
<P>
   She said that the service estimated it would intercept and send
back 4,000 Chinese arriving illegally at U.S. airports this year,
with many landing in Los Angeles, Seattle and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Meissner's 14-member delegation, which includes top immigration
officials from those cities, will also visit the Fuzhou region of
Fujian Province, the home to the vast majority of Chinese who now
live illegally in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service estimates that tens
of thousands of Chinese are smuggled into the U.S. each year,
although Meissner said, ``We really don't have a good count.''
</P>
<P>
   Many western governments that are trying to thwart the trade say
that international criminal gangs are making huge profits in this
illegal human trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amounts of money that go into this and the level of
organization and the level of criminality and abuse puts Chinese
smuggling in a class by itself,'' Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   Meissner said that one of the most effective weapons against the
illegal trade was the quick return of those who are intercepted.
That is ``the strongest signal that can be sent that taking the
risk and paying the money will not pay off,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But quick repatriation is often not possible in the case of the
Chinese, since many apply for political asylum, and those claims
can take years to work their way through the system.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although Chinese officials have said that the United States'
relatively liberal political asylum process had encouraged poor
Chinese to try their luck at emigration, Meissner said that
complaint had not come up in meetings here.
</P>
<P>
   She said that only about 13 percent of political asylum claims
by Chinese are successful, generally made by people who say that
they will face political or religious persecution if they are
returned to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   But many illegal immigrants disappear into the vast Chinese
networks in place in cities like New York before the asylum process
is complete.
</P>
<P>
   Meissner said Monday's talks were quite general, touching on an
array of cooperative ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to share analytic information, we need to work
together on fraudulent document use, and on public information so
that accurate information is getting into the sending societies and
communities,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
