r a BC-PSYCHOLOGY-LECRONE05-     07-03 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHOLOGY-LECRONE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stress management can cut sports anxiety
 &HT;    By Hap LeCrone
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   His sand wedge descended from its slow, graceful arc and entered
the sand about 2 inches behind the golf ball. With a calculated
explosion of sand, the ball emerged from its resting place and
lifted above the putting surface _ coming to rest a few inches from
the cup. This whole procedure was finely executed in the mind's eye
of the golf professional who was preparing to execute this same
shot moments thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Such golfing greats as Jack Nicholas, Tom Kite and now Tiger
Woods use visual imagery to enhance and improve their proficiency
in a sport that epitomizes the term mind game.
</P>
<P>
   Visual imagery, sometimes referred to as mental rehearsal or
visualization, is the process of creating (visualizing) an
experience in the mind. This technique is used for relearning new
skills, practicing and refining existing skills and even preparing
psychologically for the whole sporting event or match itself.
</P>
<P>
   By lowering anxiety, increasing focus and self-confidence and
enhancing warm-up techniques, visual imagery is one of the many
techniques utilized in the growing area of sports psychology.
</P>
<P>
   This marriage between psychology and golf was spoken in the
1920s by golfing great Bobby Jones, who discussed the ``mental
game'' of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Professionals in golf and other sports such as tennis,
basketball, football and bowling seek out the assistance of
professionally trained sports psychologists to enhance their
skills. Other psychological techniques used by sports psychologists
include relaxation and stress management.
</P>
<P>
   Intense competition, large crowds, television cameras and huge
monetary rewards can all contribute to a great deal of stress and
tension. Athletic performance is often improved by normal increases
in energy and arousal. However, many motor skills, especially those
fine motor skills utilized in activities such as putting, can be
greatly impaired by overarousal.
</P>
<P>
   By utilizing techniques such as self-hypnosis, athletes are able
to reduce tension and guard against overarousal, thereby increasing
their focus on desirable outcomes. Simply closing one's eyes
between shots can assist in focusing on the task at hand and screen
out undesirable external stimuli such as noisy crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Other psychological assistance such as anger management, fear
reduction of intrusive and unrealistic worries, and reframing of
emotions such as nervousness are taught by sports psychologists.
</P>
<P>
   So the next time you go out for your weekend game of ``duffers''
golf, consider taking along the techniques taught by the sports
shrinks. Who knows, you might knock enough strokes off your game to
have something to brag about on the 19th hole.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hap LeCrone is a clinical psychologist. If you have
questions or topics you would like Dr. LeCrone to discuss, write
him at 4555 Lake Shore Drive, Waco 76710 or e-mail him at
hlecrone(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
