<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2070 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PRISON-VISITS-HNS &LR;      07-03 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-VISITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CRACKDOWN ON PRISON VISITATIONS IS CONDEMNED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN QUENTIN, Calif. _ The small, Spartan room within the
fortress of San Quentin State Prison has served as a lifeline for
nearly 20 years, not only for those incarcerated inside but for
myriad outside visitors hungry for contact with the denim-clad men
of California's death row.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the East Block visiting room, the utilitarian room
functions as social hall and as a wedding chapel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't a lot of activities, mostly you just sit and
talk,'' said Charlie Larsen of Fresno, whose stepson is on death
row. ``But I feel safer in that visiting room than on some Fresno
streets at night. Everyone is on their best behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the long, and largely safe, tradition of contact visits for
California's condemned inmates is facing possible termination.
</P>
<P>
   A visiting room fight between two death row prisoners on March
31, the first such clash in the room, triggered a suspension in
``contact'' visits.
</P>
<P>
   The program has been in a declared ``state of emergency'' ever
since, with relatives, friends and attorneys forced to scramble for
one-hour ``noncontact'' visits that take place between glass
partitions over telephones.
</P>
<P>
   The new restrictions are unduly harsh, say relatives and friends
of the condemned men, because they severely limit the number and
length of visits, because the prison's appointment system is a
scheduling nightmare _ previously, appointments were unnecessary,
visitors simply showed up _ and because all inmates are being
punished for the misconduct of two prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state has never made it easy for us to visit, but now it
is more difficult than ever,'' said Donna Doolin-Larsen, a Fresno
resident whose son, Keith Doolin, convicted of two murders and four
attempted murders, has been on death row since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The call-in system is terrible, the line is always busy. You
just sit and redial, redial. It has taken me from 47 minutes to one
hour and 37 minutes to get through to make an appointment. And if
all the slots are full, we don't even know it because they stop
answering the phones. I'm devastated by this. To think I would
never again be able to touch my son . . . is almost too much for me
to bear.''
</P>
<P>
   But that might be the future awaiting her and many others whose
loved ones are under a judgment of death. The warden at San
Quentin, J.S. Woodford, is recommending that the current
restrictions become permanent.
</P>
<P>
   Woodford was appointed on June 8 by Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat,
and must be confirmed by the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unfortunate that the actions of a few have disrupted an
entire program, but the trend toward violence in the visiting room
is alarmingly clear to me,'' Woodford wrote in May. ``It is time
for the department to take a second look at our program and decide
if the benefits outweigh the risks. I believe they do not.''
</P>
<P>
   California is one of only a few states that permit contact
visits for ``Grade A'' death row prisoners, a classification of
good behavior awarded to the majority of San Quentin's death row
dwellers.
</P>
<P>
   The visits were made possible by a federal consent decree 200
years ago that spelled out living conditions for condemned inmates,
including their right to exercise, shower, and eat two hot meals
and a bag lunch daily.
</P>
<P>
   Where before inmates and their visitors were confined to
plexiglass booths, now Grade A condemned men could freely mingle
with families and friends who underwent security checks, to hug and
sit with them in the general visiting room.
</P>
<P>
   Since the consent decree took effect in 1980 (a District Court
has since terminated it and the matter is on appeal), San Quentin's
condemned population soared to 551. The visiting room _ with a
93-person capacity _ had become increasingly packed, particularly
on weekends, since it opened in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Since the new crackdown, a maximum of seven visitors, including
attorneys, are permitted per hour, with a total of 96 slots
available each week.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking publicly for the first time, critics of the
restrictions say they fear an upsurge in prison violence if the
crackdown becomes permanent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the importance of visits on prison life,'' said Charla
Greene of Santa Rosa, a death row visitor for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a prize to prisoners, they are a protection against
violence. If they no longer allow contact visits, there will be
more violence. For families, to not be able to touch their loved
ones and to visit them, is mean-spirited. You are condemning the
families as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The seven-minute altercation that led to the prison crackdown
involved rival factions of the Crips street gang. During the fight,
a 32-year-old inmate attacked a 41-year-old inmate with a
prison-made knife. Guards ordered the two to stop, then subdued
them with pepper spray. The inmates suffered minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Many visitors blame San Quentin for permitting the two inside
the visiting room at the same time. They also fault prison staff
for failing to detect the weapon, for prisoners are strip-searched
before entering the visiting room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officials did not take reasonable precautions,'' said Robert
R. Bryan, a San Francisco capital appeals attorney who represents
several condemned inmates. A death row visitor for nearly two
decades, Bryan has filed a motion in federal court protesting
various aspects of the new restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like putting an explosive device into a room then, when
it goes off, blaming others. One lieutenant later told me he was
very proud of the inmates. The fight did not escalate, they all got
out of the way and protected their loved ones. Those same people
are now being penalized over a situation created by San Quentin's
officials. The behavior in the visiting room has always been
exemplary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
