<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2072 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-HOLLYWOOD-WOMEN-1000(     07-03 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-WOMEN-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BOOK SPARKS DEBATE AMONG HOLLYWOOD WOMEN ABOUT HOW FAR THEY'VE
COME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood's hierarchy used to be easy to understand. Any woman
who wouldn't think of leaving the house in anything less than a
one-of-a-kind Edith Head gown was a force to be reckoned with. All
others were invisible.
</P>
<P>
   Today, you're more likely to see the most powerful women in the
industry _ and not even recognize them.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the biggest movies each year still offer, at best,
a ``girlfriend'' role for a female lead, women offscreen have
larger, more fulfilling roles in Hollywood's boardrooms and
screening rooms. They're directing and producing movies. They're
writing movies. They're even running studios.
</P>
<P>
   Which doesn't necessarily mean Tinseltown is embracing equality
between the sexes as much as it is ``dealing'' with it, say some
insiders.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, after 20 years in the movie business, producer Joan
Hyler thinks there are two eternal truths about Hollywood: ``One,
you can't get a good bagel anywhere, and two, women don't get an
even break.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyler, owner of Hyler Management, a Los Angeles-based
management/production company, and a former senior vice president
of the William Morris Agency, says that ``though there has been
some improvement with women in executive positions, there is still
a lack of parity at every level.''
</P>
<P>
   That imbalance has been highlighted in a new book, ``Is That a
Gun in Your Pocket? Women's Experience of Power in Hollywood''
(Random House, $26.95), by Rachel Abramowitz. A former writer for
Premiere magazine, Abramowitz has ignited fierce debate in
Hollywood about women's roles in the business, and whether their
successes _ as well as the obstacles they continue to face _
reflect society as a whole. Abramowitz notes that less than 10
percent of all major studio films are produced or directed by
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is certainly no surprise,'' says Hyler of the statistic.
``In a few cases, women may have gotten more powerful positions at
the studios, but overall we're still in the same historical
patterns. Men in Hollywood are the ones calling almost all the
shots. I think Rachel's book is very true, a very accurate social
history.''
</P>
<P>
   But not every prominent woman in the film industry agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no easier business for women to advance in than the
movie business,'' says Linda Obst, producer of ``Sleepless in
Seattle,'' ``One Fine Day'' and several other hit films. ``Women
coming out of college have equal opportunity with men for
entry-level jobs. Women have equal opportunity to be promoted.''
</P>
<P>
   Obst, a Fredericksburg, Texas, resident whose book ``Hello, He
Lied: And Other Truths of the Hollywood Trenches,'' was a
bestseller in 1998, believes ``the anecdotes (in Abramowitz's book)
are archaic. Yes, there is a ladder anyone in Hollywood has to
scale, but the rungs are the same for women and men.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate, even among women in Hollywood, doesn't surprise
Abramowitz, who admits that generalizations are tough to make.
Gender, she says, was sometimes the only thing some of the women
she interviewed for the book had in common.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got these incredible contrasts,'' she says. ``Eventually,
I focused most on Sherry Lansing (chairman of the motion pictures
group for Paramount) and Dawn Steel (the late president of Columbia
TriStar Pictures, who died in 1997). Sherry is so feminine, so
sweet. Dawn Steel was tough. But they were the first women to
really make it to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyler and Abramowitz agree that women do have more opportunity
in some aspects of the movie industry than in the past, thanks to
the Lansing/Steel generation that forced its way to the front lines
by combining chutzpah and talent. But as in most industries, women
still have less executive presence, less ``clout,'' than men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big moguls are still guys,'' Hyler says. ``Just name them
_ Diller, Eisner, Murdoch. The couple of women in suits at high
executive levels still have to report to them. The movie industry
mirrors the Fortune 500 business profiles. Traditionally, they may
move up some women into near-the-top rungs, but the top echelon is
male.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Despite her accomplishments, Lansing _ whose elevation to head
of production for Twentieth Century Fox in 1980 was so surprising
and novel that it made the front page of The New York Times _
exemplifies how successful women in Hollywood are still not given
credit for talent, Abramowitz says. In ``Is That a Gun in Your
Pocket?'' she quotes a male colleague snarling after a screening
that, ``Sherry worked the aisles like an airline stewardess,
hugging and kissing everyone she knew.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When is a woman ever judged objectively by her ability?''
Abramowitz asks. ``I have talked to Sherry since the book came out.
She said there were obviously things in it she didn't like, but
mostly she was incredibly complimentary.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   Hyler says she believes the obstacles Hollywood power brokers
place in front of women ``is not particularly intentional,'' and
it's driven as much as anything by the fact that teen boys and
young men have made up the largest and most predictable block of
moviegoers ever since ``Jaws'' and ``Star Wars'' began the
``blockbuster'' era in the mid-'70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's conservatism rather than exclusionism,'' she says. ``When
you're talking about the costs of studio movies starting at maybe
$80 million, then the studios _ the men running the studios _ tend
to rely on what worked for them in the past. It turns into a
chicken-and-the-egg thing. With that much money involved, they
won't hire a woman who doesn't have extensive experience. But if
women don't get hired, they can't get any experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Where women now make their greatest impact on major studio
films, Abramowitz believes, is in pressuring male counterparts to
make movies that will attract female audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the longest time, mostly movies were made by men for men,
with teen-age boys seen as the sort of optimum audience,''
Abramowitz says. ``Gradually, the message has gotten through that
adult women (moviegoers) can make movies successful _ `Ghost' was
that kind of movie. `Pretty Woman' another. `Titanic' finally made
it impossible to ignore. Getting women interested in your movie is
the best way to have a blockbuster now.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that such recent successes have completely broken old
habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laurie McDonald of DreamWorks told me this story,'' Abramowitz
says. ``She's one of their heads of production. They were having a
(story) meeting to plan `Gladiator,' and she told the writer and
director that there had to be an interesting woman character (to
attract female moviegoers). They put one in. Then she got called
away, had to leave the room, and when she got back a short time
later, they'd already killed off the female character.'' (McDonald
resuscitated the character.)
</P>
<P>
   Such experiences aren't just frustrating to the women involved,
says Abramowitz. The impact Hollywood has on culture and society
makes the presence of women in top Hollywood positions especially
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often (female) characters in movies reflect inherent sexism,''
she says. ``It can be a subtle thing, like making the hero's part
bigger while reducing the presence of his love interest. What they
do, essentially, to make him look good, is to dumb her down.''
</P>
<P>
   What's become common is for testosterone-fueled writers to try
to deflect criticism by making their jiggly dumb blondes nominally
intelligent by providing them with Ph.D.'s and impressive-sounding
jobs, even though they're not actually seen doing anything more
taxing than bedding down the male star. One of the more egregious
recent examples is the hot pants-wearing Dr. Christmas Jones played
by Denise Richards in ``The World Is Not Enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When women are actively involved in the production, that's not
as likely to happen,'' says Abramowitz.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Throughout her book, Abramowitz alternates tales of distaff
professional problems with detailed looks at how Hollywood's
professional pressures affect women's personal lives more
powerfully than they do men's. Affairs, divorces and estrangements
between mothers and children are prominent. In one anecdote, author
Larry McMurtry says he based much of the Aurora-Emma
mother/daughter tension in ``Terms of Endearment'' on real-life
problems between production designer Polly Platt and her daughter
Antonia.
</P>
<P>
   Platt _ whose husband, director Peter Bogdanovich, left her for
Cybill Shepherd during the filming of ``The Last Picture Show'' _
admits she found the book's revelations about her personal life
difficult to bear, ``but in reading the book, seeing what sorts of
things had happened to other women, I began to feel less alone,''
she says. ``Women have a harder time succeeding in the (movie)
business. That's true. I told Rachel she should call her book `Few
Women Are Called and Fewer Are Chosen.'''
</P>
<P>
   And those who are called and chosen, Abramowitz says, often have
little tolerance for criticism.
</P>
<P>
   When Barbra Streisand read about herself in ``Is That a Gun in
Your Pocket?,'' she snatched up a telephone and called the author.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of surreal,'' Abramowitz recalls. ``It was a
Saturday night. My husband picked up the phone, said, `Yes, she's
right here,' and handed it to me. Barbra just called herself; she
didn't have a staff member do it. She wanted to blow off steam
about things, like my saying she had talent but had to get past
being `a funny-looking girl' (to succeed in the business). I said,
`Barbra, this book is about women in the movie business and their
flawed humanity. Get past the specific things about you, and look
at the big picture.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720, or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
