<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn:   Colo., Minn., Pa, Ore., Wash., Calif., N.Y. Ga., Ohio,
Fla. ,  Germany, Czech Republic, Italy, Austria)  (For release on Sunday, July 9) 
 By   LUBA VANGELOVA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RENT A MOVIE AT THE AIRPORT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bored airline passengers have a new way to help pass the time
when they find themselves stuck in an airport because of delays or
a long layover. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They can rent a portable DVD player and watch a movie. Frequent
fliers who have seen just about every in-flight movie can watch the
film of their choice, and children can be entertained with movies
appropriate to their ages. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   InMotion Pictures has opened kiosks in seven airports, where for
$10 a day travelers can rent a battery-powered DVD player with
movie, headset and extra battery. Additional movies rent for $4 and
extra headsets are $2.50. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The laptop-size DVD players fall under the same in-flight rules
that apply to other electronic equipment like computers and
cassette players. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One-way rentals are available if the destination airport has an
InMotion kiosk. Multiple-day rentals include additional movies _
one for each day. Travelers with their own portable DVD players or
people whose laptop computers have DVD capability can rent just the
movie disk for $5 and return the disk by prepaid mailer within five
days. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 200 movie titles, including children's films, classics and
new releases, are available at InMotion kiosks at the airports in
Denver; Minneapolis-St. Paul; Philadelphia; Portland, Ore.;
Seattle-Tacoma; San Diego; and San Jose, Calif. The company expects
to open in La Guardia Airport as well as in Atlanta, Cincinnati,
Orlando, San Francisco and Jacksonville, Fla., within the next
several months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Movies can be reserved at (877) 383-8646. More information is
also available at www.inmotionpictures.com.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A FLORENCE ARISTOCRAT WELCOMES GUESTS AGAIN  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Savoy in Florence, Italy has reopened after an
extensive two-year restoration aimed at upgrading its amenities.
</P>
<P>
   In the central Piazza della Repubblica, once part of the city's
Jewish neighborhood, the Savoy was built in 1893 as the offices of
an Israeli banker. Soon after it was completed, it was sold, and
the new owners transformed it into a hotel that quickly became a
favorite of the aristocracy. This is the third time the hotel has
been completely restored; in 1958, a fifth floor was added,
providing panoramic views of nearby monuments, such as the
Cathedral of Santa Maria del Fiore and Giotto's Campanile. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hotel, part of the RF Hotels chain, has 98 rooms and nine
suites, each with air-conditioning, two-line telephones, voice
messaging and interactive satellite television that keeps an
account of your bill day by day and also leaves messages for you.
The room decor is luxurious but simple, employing rich pastel
colored fabrics. Marbles and hand-crafted mosaics decorate the
modern baths. The common rooms, some still with the original
boiserie, retain a fin-de-siecle, Old World elegance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hotel restaurant, L'Incontro, serves traditional Tuscan
cuisine, and in summer tables are set out on the piazza. Doubles
start at $325 and go up to $1,112 for the Repubblica Suite, plus
tax. Breakfast ranges from $15.50 to $22 a person. Contact Hotel
Savoy, Piazza della Repubblica 7, 50123 Florence; telephone
(39-055) 27351, fax (39-055) 273-5888. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE OFFERS A COLD WAR TOUR  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Call it a look behind the Iron Curtain: American Heritage
magazine, inspired by the popularity of its first D-Day tour last
year, will offer its first cold war tour Sept. 20 to 30. It traces
the origins of the cold war with visits to Berlin and Dresden in
Germany, and to Prague. Francis Gary Powers Jr., the son of the U-2
pilot shot down by the Soviets in 1960, will lecture the group. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tour costs $3,899 a person, double occupancy, and includes
air fare from New York. The American Heritage tours are organized
by Historic Tours, a company specializing in World War II trips.
Call (877) 992-8687 or (800) 222-1170. On the Web, it's
www.americanheritage.com; for Historic Tours, www.ww2tours.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PARENTS' NIGHT OUT IN ST. THOMAS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Family vacations are wonderful, but sometimes Mom and Dad want
time alone together. The Bolongo Bay Beach Club and Villas in St.
Thomas offers parents a Date Night, one free night of baby-sitting
for every week's stay. The program, available through Sept. 30,
uses Nannies in Paradise, a company with licensed child-care
professionals. Rates are $145 per room, with up to two children in
the room, including a Continental breakfast. Also, children 12 or
younger eat free in the resort restaurant when their parents dine
there. Call (800) 524-4746. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY AIRPORT GETS DOWNTOWN RAIL LINK  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Sydney can now travel quickly to town from the
Kingsford Smith airport by train. The recently completed domestic
and international terminal rail stations are part of a new route
segment that feeds into the city's extensive CityRail network. The
train ride from the international terminal to Sydney Central, a
main downtown transportation hub, takes 11 minutes and costs $5.35.
Trains will run from about 5 a.m. to midnight daily. At peak hours
they will run every 10 minutes, at off-peak hours, every 15
minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The international terminal's rail station is directly beneath
the northern end of the terminal. The domestic terminal's station
is beneath a nearby parking lot; underground passages connect it to
both Qantas and Ansett baggage-claim areas. The Sydney public
transport InfoLine, when calling within the city, is 131-500; Web
sites are www.sydneytransport.net.au or www.airportlink.com.au. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
