<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2080 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CATHOLICS-HISPANICS-H     07-03 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLICS-HISPANICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CATHOLIC CHURCH STRUGGLES TO RECRUIT, RETAIN HISPANICS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By J. MICHAEL PARKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Catholic parishes need huge numbers of Hispanic
lay leaders and youth ministers, and they need them now, a
nationwide study has found.
</P>
<P>
   That spells a major challenge _ and opportunity _ for San
Antonio Catholic institutions that train such leaders, particularly
the Mexican-American Cultural Center (MACC).
</P>
<P>
   The National Conference of Catholic Bishops commissioned the
study, called ``Hispanic Ministry at the Turn of the New
Millennium,'' to help them prepare for a four-day gathering that
begins Thursday in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Encuentro 2000'' will cover a host of intercultural issues
arising from the church's absorption of new immigrants, including
Asians and Africans. But their increasing numbers in the U.S.
Catholic community make Hispanics the most pressing challenge for
church leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Most immigrants from Latin American are Catholic, but both they
and the church are unprepared for the cultural differences they
face, said the Rev. Jose Gomez of Houston, president of the
National Association of Hispanic Priests.
</P>
<P>
   And if Catholics don't adjust to those differences, there are
plenty of evangelical Protestant churches already attracting
immigrants that are ready to welcome others, church leaders here
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Latin America, nobody registers in parishes, so when they
come to U.S. parishes, they don't register. And immigrants don't
mind if they're a little late for Mass, but priests don't like them
coming at just any old time,'' Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   Too many Catholic parishes are more regulation-oriented than
Gospel-centered, and are not reaching out to nonparishioners, said
the Rev. Virgilio Elizondo, MACC's founder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor Latinos, especially recent immigrants, don't understand
that,'' Elizondo said. ``I see storefront (evangelical Protestant)
churches opening in increasing numbers both in San Antonio and
other cities across the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The study queried bishops and diocesan coordinators of Hispanic
ministry nationwide and surveyed in detail eight dioceses that have
well-established Hispanic ministry offices, including Fort Worth,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Among U.S. dioceses, San Antonio has the fifth largest Hispanic
population (behind Los Angeles, Miami, New York and
Galveston-Houston), and it has grown by more than 23 percent since
1990.
</P>
<P>
   But Hispanics are spreading out in large numbers across the
nation instead of concentrating in Florida, New York, California
and Texas as in the past, said Gilberto Hinojosa, dean of graduate
studies at the University of the Incarnate Word, whose work was
cited in the study.
</P>
<P>
   The five dioceses with the fastest-growing Hispanic populations
are in areas not usually associated with Hispanics: Charlotte,
N.C.; Reno-Las Vegas; Atlanta; Raleigh, N.C.; and Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   In these areas and others, the church must play catch up in
reaching Hispanics, serving their needs, and integrating them into
parish life, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge and very complex problem. In the 19th century
and into the 20th, the worldwide Society for Propagation of the
Faith funded these types of needs. But I don't see anything like
that now,'' Hinojosa said.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found many dioceses, including some with large
Hispanic populations, where lay Hispanics are not sufficiently
trained for ministry leadership. And fewer than one-third of all
dioceses offer youth ministry, lay leadership or retreat programs
geared to Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of dioceses still don't know what to do with Hispanic
ministry. It's a golden opportunity for us to help them focus on
the needs of immigrants,'' said Sister Maria Elena Gonzalez, MACC's
president.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what MACC does in response will be influenced by the Los
Angeles meeting. But Gonzalez said MACC, already a national
resource in multicultural training, could add lay leader and youth
minister training programs by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already trained 30,673 people for Hispanic pastoral
ministry both on and off our campus,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Teams from MACC have worked in 96 U.S. dioceses in the past year
alone, including 24 of the 25 with the fastest-growing Hispanic
populations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Sandoval, a part-time minister at La Iglesia Biblica El
Camino in San Antonio, said it was partly the lack of good Bible
studies that prompted him to leave the Catholic Church in 1990. He
joined El Camino five years ago. About 60 people worship there on
an average Sunday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of members at this church are former Catholics
who had similar experiences,'' he said. ``The Catholic Church
didn't have much in the way of teaching what the Bible says. The
priest would talk a little about it at Mass on Sunday, but that
wasn't nearly enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he studied the Bible from a nondenominational church,
Sandoval said, he began to disagree with Catholic doctrines that
weren't in the Bible or appeared to contradict it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Catholic Church has a lot of good teachings, but I didn't
find much in-depth teaching. I really hungered for God's word,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also knows the conflict that can occur in traditional
Catholic families when members join evangelical Protestant
churches. He said his conversion deeply upset his father, a devout
Catholic, who refused to discuss his son's interpretations of the
Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not familiar enough with it and doesn't feel
comfortable,'' Sandoval said.
</P>
<P>
   MACC founder Elizondo, now the executive producer of Catholic
Television of San Antonio, said the yearning for more systematic
Bible study is a common complaint. He has produced a 13-part video
series on the Bible in Spanish, available at the MACC bookstore,
and the Rev. Juan Alfaro, a teacher at MACC, has been developing a
Bible study course for parish use.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo Cruz, who directs the National Conference of Catholic
Bishops' secretariat for Hispanic affairs, said the church has only
2,005 Hispanic priests serving nationwide, and only 500 Hispanics
are studying for the priesthood.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio is getting a few more Hispanic priests, including
three ordained by Archbishop Patrick Flores this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. David Cruz, who completed his six-year term as rector
of Assumption Seminary this month, said 16 of its last 24 graduates
are Hispanic, though most went to other dioceses. Of 47 seminarians
enrolled in the past year, 24 were Mexican or Mexican-American and
three Colombian. They will be spread among 13 dioceses once
ordained, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gomez said most U.S. seminaries aren't friendly to
Hispanics. And Elizondo noted that ``Protestant storefront churches
call people to ministry very quickly and then keep educating
them,'' a factor that adds to the attraction of those churches for
lay Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Monsignor Lawrence Stuebben, vicar general of the San Antonio
archdiocese, said San Antonio is a natural place to develop
solutions for the multiple challenges of Hispanic ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assumption Seminary is the premier seminary in the country for
Hispanic ministry training, and MACC is a big part of that. That's
why eight religious orders have their formation houses in San
Antonio,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Assumption was a national pioneer in requiring bilingual
seminary education 60 years ago, long before it became common
elsewhere, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
