<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Well, folks, there's some
good news and some bad news. You'll have to decide for yourself
which is which. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ A year ago, we were a state
full of dumb kids and bad schools.
</P>
<P>
   No more. Florida has become one big Lake Wobegone, a place where
all the children and their schools are above average. How did our
kids get so smart so fast? (And if they did, how come they still
look like that?) Are their classes smaller? Are their teachers
better paid and trained? Is their curriculum more meaningful? Are
kids getting more individual attention? Did everyone get books they
could take home? Of course not, silly. (Lane, Daytona Beach
News-Journal) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ The story of the new guy and Mangy Bill just
goes to show that boys will be boys _ and that's not always
easy.The story of the new guy and Mangy Bill just goes to show that
boys will be boys _ and that's not always easy. (JoeMurray, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   PAY-SEXES _ In the war between the sexes, women are starting to
get even. In pay, that is. Latest salary survey from Working Woman
magazine shows that women continue to close the gap in pay in many
industries. But some fields are still behind. FYI, women
journalists on average make $10,000 less than their male
counterparts. (Joyner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CARGO _Atlanta's connections via rail, truck and air cargo.
While big, Atlanta and Georgia seem to be regionally important but
relative lightweight on the national level in terms of cargo. The
biggies: Chicago/Illinois, California, Texas, Ohio, Michigan, i.e.,
autos and intermodal. At least one expert says globalization will
add to Atlanta's role on this front, adding new jobs. Trucks, by
the way, account for 80-plus percent of Georgia cargo both by
weight and value (bad news for atlanta highways). (Grantham,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
