u i BC-AUSTRIA-EUROPE-480&AMP;AD     07-03 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-EUROPE-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRIA THREATENS TO BLOCK EU INTEGRATION IF SANCTIONS CONTINUE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Austria's frustration over European Union sanctions,
which had largely degenerated into a long-distance cat fight
between Austria and France, led over the weekend to threats to
block European expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel of Austria said Monday that the
sanctions would have to be lifted before the 15-member European
Union could admit any new countries. Approval of any of the dozen
countries seeking admission must be unanimous, and other reforms
are planned for December, so Austria could play spoiler if it does
not get its way.
</P>
<P>
   Schuessel's remarks echoed some made earlier Monday by Joerg
Haider, the dominant figure in Austria's rightist Freedom Party,
which is in a coalition government with Schuessel's party.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions were imposed in February, to punish the country
for letting Haider's party into government. The party opposes
immigration, and some charge that it is racist and xenophobic.
Haider, a popular governor of a southern province, is best known
for making several offhand remarks in the past that seemed to
defend the Third Reich.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions have had no serious economic effect on Austria and
amount to a refusal by Cabinet ministers from 14 European countries
to meet publicly with their Austrian counterparts. But the
sanctions rankle with Austrians.
</P>
<P>
   In elections last October, running on an anti-big-government
platform, Haider's Freedom Party got 26.9 percent of the vote,
ending in a virtual tie with Schuessel's People's Party. After
negotiations broke down between Schuessel and the Social Democrats,
which had the largest percentage of votes, he formed a government
with the Freedom Party. Many Austrians are openly infuriated that
other countries, led by France and Belgium, felt they could punish
a fellow country that _ in the eyes of those Austrians _ had done
nothing illegal or anti-democratic.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has been simmering since the sanctions were imposed
five months ago, but flared again over the weekend, when France
took over the rotating presidency of the European Union. Both Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin and President Jacques Chirac, putting aside
their usual snide disagreements with each other, said they did not
expect the sanctions to be lifted this year.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Haider said Monday on Austrian national radio that,
``Now that France has said nothing will change during the French
presidency, we say quite bluntly that nothing will move either.''
And, with his habitually unguarded tongue, he said France, as
president, would find itself ``a noisy giant, like Gulliver, held
in chains by many dwarfs, unable to move.''
</P>
<P>
   The Austrian government is making plans to hold a referendum in
October asking voters how they feel about the sanctions. Schuessel
recently dropped his objection to the idea.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last month, European Union officials suggested a face-saving way
out of the quandary created when the union applied the sanctions
with little warning and virtually no public debate. A group of
``three wise men'' appointed by the European Court of Human Rights
would examine the human rights record of Austria and the Freedom
Party, particularly on immigration matters.
</P>
<P>
   Schuessel said Austria would cooperate. The country has strong
laws against espousing Nazi ideals and virtually no recent history
of racist, anti-Semitic or neo-Nazi violence. It has also, he
contended, accepted more refugees per capita than any other
country.
</P>
<P>
   He did ask that the court's inquiry be finished by September.
Chirac on Monday declined to set a deadline, saying, ``It's up to
them to take the necessary time.''
</P>
<P>
   Haider has complained that submitting his party to an inspection
of its political correctness is insulting.
</P>
<P>
   Other Austrians have pointed out that France has a tarnished
record on its treatment of immigrants and minorities and that it
also has a xenophobic political party. And they say that Germany
and Britain have many more violent neo-Nazi incidents, and that
Austria's immigration policies are in line with policies of other
European Union members even though it is especially vulnerable
because it borders on impoverished Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the other fallout from the squabble, it has
strengthened parties in Britain, Switzerland, Scandinavia and parts
of Eastern Europe that oppose deeper involvement by their own
countries in the European Union.
</P>
</TEXT>
