turning this election into a referendum on which candidate can best
reshape government to meet the challenges of the New Economy. From
health care, to education, to tax cuts to social security, Bush and
Gore are putting before the voters significant questions about how
some of the most fundamental public institutions should be shaped
for a global, digital age that offers the potential for
unprecedented prosperity _ and enormous uncertainty. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT15.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Undated) _ In a move to bring down stubbornly high
oil prices, Saudi Arabia, the world's largest exporter of crude,
announced plans to increase production by 500,000 barrels a day.
The decision will go into effect ``if the price doesn't decrease
... within the next few days,'' according to a written statement
from the Saudi Arabian oil minister. Saudi Arabia will act to raise
output ``in consultation with other producers,'' the statement
said. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BROWNSTONE-REVIVAL (Portland, Conn.) _ Brownstone is back. That
somber yet elegant cloak for more than 50,000 row houses, from
Baltimore to Boston, was revered during the so-called Brown Decades
of the mid-nineteenth century, then reviled by the century's turn,
when gleaming white limestone and marble captivated the public. But
preservationists and planners are beginning to see a new future for
the formidable stone. Architects have started using it to give a
touch of historical sobriety to gaudy mansionettes, and
conservators have begun renewing the elegant facades of grand
monuments. But the revival has sparked a debate on whether
brownstone should be used at all. Because the terrible secret is
that brownstone isn't really much good as a building material. By
Tracie Rohzan.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT8.
</P>
</TEXT>
