u k BC-EDITORIAL-MEXICO-BOS &LR;      07-03 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MEXICO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CHAPTER FOR MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Wednesday, July 05, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vicente Fox Quesada's victory in the Mexican presidential
election marks the defeat of a system of governance that has long
outlived its usefulness. The greatest accomplishment of the
defeated Institutional Revolutionary Party in recent years has been
the opening of the Mexican political system so that an outsider of
Fox's caliber could finally prevail.
</P>
<P>
   This party, known as the PRI from its Spanish initials, was
essential to the evolution of Mexican politics from the warlordism
of the 1910s and 1920s. By the 1980s, its rule had degenerated into
corruption and incompetence, unchecked by a strong opposition. The
party ought to have lost power to an insurgent candidate,
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, in 1988, but PRI control of the vote count
insured that its own candidate prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI had the good sense to gradually open up Mexico at levels
below the national government. Candidates for the Action National
Party, or PAN, took governorships, including in the state of
Guanajuato, won by Fox in 1995. Cardenas, from the leftist Party of
the Democratic Revolution, was elected mayor of Mexico City in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas ran again for president this year, but he was outpaced
by the charismatic Fox and the PRI's Francisco Labastida Ochoa. Fox
promises to increase funding for education and decentralize
government, but there isn't much else to set him apart from
Labastida. Both support foreign investment and free trade.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI has deep roots throughout the country, but it has never
had to exist as a minority. Its greatest challenge now is to
reinvent itself.
</P>
<P>
   Through unions and land redistribution initiatives, the PRI was
supposed to represent the great mass of impoverished Mexicans, but
over the past 20 years it has drifted rightward. Poverty increased
in the 1990s despite growth in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Fox needs to address economic inequities without compromising
his free trade positions. If he does not, he should encounter
strong opposition from the left, perhaps from a reformed PRI. The
new openness in Mexican politics, happily, means that no man or
party will be able to get a lock on power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2095 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-HNS &LR;      07-03 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON AND LAZIO BOTH FACE TOUGH QUESTIONS ON CAMPAIGN
FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LARA JAKES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., voted against the use of
so-called soft money in federal elections and says he would
overhaul the nation's campaign finance system. Yet last month he
accepted such funds to pay for a television in his race for the
U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   His opponent, First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, has her own
campaign finance woes. Sullied by the 1996 White House fund-raising
scandal, although there is no evidence that she acted improperly,
Clinton is the subject of complaints to the Federal Election
Commission about her soft money intake.
</P>
<P>
   On the hustings, both the Democratic first lady and the
four-term congressman from Long Island support reforms to the
campaign finance system. Yet both will likely accept millions of
dollars in soft money, legal but unregulated and unrestricted
back-door donations, in a race in which the level of this funding
is expected to dwarf that in past statewide elections.
</P>
<P>
   The stage was already set when Clinton was facing Republican New
York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, said attorney Don Simon of the
non-partisan watchdog group Common Cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to believe that fund-raising, with Lazio
replacing Giuliani, is going to be anything less than it was
before,'' Simon said. Although Giuliani bowed out May 19 amid
health and marital problems, ``this is still the hottest, most
contested race in the country. ... The candidates seem to be on
track to raise an unlimited amount of soft money. This is a
fund-raising frenzy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has raised $5.1 million since April 1, while Lazio, who
had $3.5 million in his House war chest when he entered the race
May 20, has raised $4.5 million over the last six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It could not be immediately determined how much soft money
Clinton and Lazio received over the last three months. But watchdog
groups predict each one will ultimately rake in millions.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Lazio has not formed a joint fund-raising account with
the National Republican Senatorial Committee, which could pump soft
money into the race _ mostly through TV ``issue'' ads. Such ads,
like the one the Republican Leadership Council (RLC) took out last
month, can advocate for or against a candidate as long as they do
not urge viewers to vote one way or the other.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, top state Republicans say privately that the New York
Republican committee alone could funnel as much as $3 million into
the race against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The latest numbers available show that as of March 31, Clinton
had $3.9 million in her joint account with the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee and the state Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Lazio has begun to follow the soft money trail.
</P>
<P>
   The RLC ad, still airing upstate, features shots of the
grinning, boyish congressman as a voice booms, ``Rick Lazio is a
leader. Call. Tell Rick Lazio to keep fighting for issues important
to us.''
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely the kind of ad that Lazio condemned in two votes
in 1998 and 1999 to ban election propaganda paid for with soft
money. However, his campaign refused to have it pulled off the air,
just as it has not ruled out taking out-of-state donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Condemning the ad wouldn't get it off the air, praising it
wouldn't get it off the air,'' Lazio spokesman Dan McLagan said
when the spot debuted in early June. ``There's nothing we can do to
stop it, change it or move it. And frankly, there's nothing we can
do to stop the millions of dollars that are going to be pouring in
from out-of-state to help Hillary Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Lazio generally voted for campaign finance reforms
_ although he missed one vote this year and flip-flopped on another
to require tax-exempt political organizations known as ``527s'' _
such as the RLC _ to disclose their donor lists. Lazio voted for
disclosure in a third vote last week.
</P>
<P>
   He also voted for requiring political candidates to reimburse
the federal government for any use of official vehicles in
campaigns, and he favors barring contributions from non-citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Those are digs at Clinton, who has traveled on Air Force jets
while campaigning and was accused of indirectly accepting $50,000
from Los Angeles businessman Johnny Chung, who claims he funneled
money from Chinese officials to the Democratic National Committee.
The first lady has denied knowledge of the Chung donation.
</P>
<P>
   Her campaign also claims it paid every bill it received from the
federal government. In February, that total was $34,000, though
Republicans estimate the real value was $180,000. Her campaign
would not provide updated figures.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has called for public disclosure of 527 organization
donor lists and has offered to cap soft money spending in the race
at $1 million _ a challenge both Lazio and Giuliani refused.
Clinton, too, enjoyed the benefit this month of a
soft-money-sponsored ad by the state Democratic Committee _ at an
estimated cost of $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady is also the target of a complaint accusing her of
improperly using soft money. The FEC confirmed it received the
complaint from Common Cause, Democracy 21 and Judicial Watch, but
would not confirm or deny that an investigation is under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strictly abide by all campaign finance laws,'' said Clinton
spokesman Howard Wolfson, noting that the soft money account is
legal. ``We offered to work out an agreement that would limit the
use of soft money, and Congressman Lazio refused. And no one goes
into a ring with one hand tied behind her back.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also inevitably faces being associated with the 1996
White House fund-raising scandal in which donors for President
Clinton's re-election campaign were enticed with sleepovers in the
Lincoln Bedroom and White House coffee klatches. There is no
evidence that the first lady was personally involved and she is not
expected to be investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Simon of Common Cause says, ``She's going to have a hard
time shaking that baggage. She's associated with both the good and
the bad of her husband's administration. And one of the bad things
is the shameful behavior of the Clinton campaign and violating all
of the bounds of fund-raising excess in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect Lazio to have an easier time, Simon said,
especially if he adopts Giuliani's fund-raising tactics, which
pulled in $19 million in direct donations and hundreds of thousands
in soft dollars before he quit. ``Lazio certainly has no profile as
somebody interested in cleaning up the campaign finance schedule,''
Simon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
