 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Customary summer heat will reign from the deserts of the
Southwest to the central and southern Plains to the Southeast and
Middle Atlantic States under the auspice of an upper-air
high-pressure system. Heat will be tempered across parts of
Missouri and middle Mississippi Valleys as thunderstorms erupt in
clusters along the edge of the upper-level ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures will tumble into the 40s over the interior of the
Northwest early Tuesday morning, symptomatic of the cool air mass
over the region. Isolated showers will speckle the Bitterroots of
Idaho, the Cascades of Oregon and Washington and the Klamath
Mountains of Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   A drier air mass will move into the Northeast on the heels of a
cool front. With sunshine returning, the day will be warmer in many
areas than it was Monday.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS:
</P>
<P>
   APHELION
</P>
<P>
   Although this is hottest time of year, Earth reached its
farthest point from the Sun, or aphelion, Monday. But the Northern
Hemisphere is tilted toward the Sun, accounting for the greater
energy that reaches northern latitudes compared with when Earth
makes it closest approach in January. Although in the current era,
Earth is farther from the Sun in the Northern Hemisphere summer,
that is not always the case. Earth wobbles on its axis like a
spinning top. As a result of the slow wobble, 11,000 years from
now, Earth will be closest to the Sun during the northern summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
