<HEADLINE>
GRACE JONES MUST SAY GOODBYE TO THE LAST LITTLE DRESS SHOP IN
TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALADO, Texas _ It's a typical western tale. The crucial
shipment to the small Texas town is hijacked. The loss could amount
to thousands of dollars. The heroine is seen wringing her hands in
dismay. This setback could ruin her business, she could lose the
ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Young rides to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   The heroine is Grace Jones, and she is always at the center of
big events in incongruous places, surrounded by an unlikely cast.
The fact that Loretta Young once came to her rescue when a
planeload of designer evening wear was hijacked is not in the least
bit strange.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is a tiny person who lives large. She's been a pilot, a
model, an ambassador, and most recently, a specialty store owner.
During World War II, she was one of the first WASPS (Women's Air
Service Pilots), who ferried T-38s and C-47s from coast to coast to
free up the male pilots for combat missions. She was a John Robert
Powers model in New York City, and appeared on live television
shows with the likes of Ed Sullivan. She married Lt. Col. Jack
Jones after the war.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, the Joneses retired to Salado. He wanted to ranch. She
wanted to open a dress shop.
</P>
<P>
   Her desire was to have a dress shop the way they used to be. The
kind of place where ladies shopped for fine goods. A place where
the clothes are kept behind closed doors and only a few accessories
are displayed in the public rooms.
</P>
<P>
   She wanted an old-fashioned place where the front room looks
like a parlor with ceiling-to-floor ivory drapes and dainty pieces
of antique furniture grouped in small clusters, where the carpeting
is deep and there is a hush, similar to the kind in funeral
parlors.
</P>
<P>
   There would be saleswomen with deferential airs and the
appraising eyes of Bedouin horse traders, who would inquire if they
can assist. The customer, not a browser or a comparison shopper, is
expected to know what she needs _ a cocktail dress, a day dress,
something casual, an evening gown.
</P>
<P>
   She states her mission, and soon is standing on a small stage in
front of a three-way mirror, in a dressing room the size of a small
bedroom. Here, she is presented with a selection of cocktail frocks
or daytime dresses that are specifically chosen for her size, in
flattering colors and styles that would be suitable.
</P>
<P>
   Tea is served in china cups, drinks in goblets brought in on a
silver tray. If the customer is a regular client, the saleswoman
knows exactly what she bought on previous occasions. The store
keeps a permanent record of your fashion purchases. Can't remember
what you have? Just ask your saleslady.
</P>
<P>
   Saleswomen inquire if the purchase is for a special occasion,
and if it is, the customer is not shown any style that has already
been purchased by someone else for the same event.
</P>
<P>
   Cost might be a consideration, but money is rarely discussed. A
few subtle expressions indicate what is an acceptable price range,
and transactions proceed from there. If a dress is selected, it is
expertly fitted, altered by seamstresses on staff, and then, days
later, arrives in a big box, wrapped in glorious enameled paper and
tied with a moire ribbon.
</P>
<P>
   The bill comes later. In this kind of shop, blouses cost
hundreds, suits thousands and evening gowns tens of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jones wanted that sort of store. She would name it Grace Jones,
and she wanted to carry the very best clothing from New York's best
designers, but that was the extent of her business plan. She took
it to 10 bankers in the Central Texas area. Yes, she realized
Salado was then a town of 250 people. She admitted she had no
previous retail experience. She claimed to have no collateral, but
she had a location _ the empty shell that had been Salado's old
bank and post office. It was nothing but walls of hand-cut
limestone blocks with no roof and years of accumulated rubbish.
</P>
<P>
   To a man, they all turned her down.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who had her own money, didn't need the bankers' help, she
needed their attention. A few months later, after Bryant Reeves, a
Belton-based builder, had refurbished her building, she opened with
a party attended by 10 very curious bankers' wives. What may have
sounded like lunacy to their husbands looked good to their wives,
and they told friends, friends told friends, and soon the
limousines were cruising Salado's gravel streets and Learjets were
landing in the pasture.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Jones paired big Texas names such as Liz
Carpenter, Carolyn Farb and Jane Sibley with labels such as James
Galanos, Christian Dior, Geoffrey Beene and Christian Lacroix. She
became an indefatigable champion of using fashion shows for charity
fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
