<SLUG> BC-CONTACT-LENSES-CHILDREN-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 KIDS CONSIDER CONTACT LENSES FOR COMFORT AND CONVENIENCE
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By IRENE S. LEVINE 
 c.2000 Irene S. Levine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The number of children and adolescents who wear contact lenses
is rapidly growing.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Food and Drug Administration, which began regulating
contact lenses in 1976, estimates that 30 million people in this
country now wear them. Approximately 3 million of these people are
16 years old and younger. While female contact lens wearers
outnumber males two to one, the proportion of males opting for
contacts is also growing.
</P>
<P>
   This news is hardly surprising. Lenses are more comfortable,
easier to wear, easier to care for and more affordable than they
have ever been before.
</P>
<P>
   Between the ages of 11 and 15, nearsightedness (also called
``progressive myopia'') gets worse as children experience a period
of rapid growth. While there are no set rules concerning the age at
which kids are old enough to wear contact lenses, most children who
use contacts begin wearing them in middle school, at the age of 10
or 11.
</P>
<P>
   In large part, a child's motivation, motor skills and maturity
determine readiness. A child may desperately want to wear lenses,
but lack the dexterity and discipline that is necessary to care for
them. One optician quips, ``Your child isn't ready if you still
have to remind them to brush their teeth in the morning!''
</P>
<P>
   Because self-esteem is often related to how they look and how
they are perceived by others, most kids feel better about
themselves when they wear contacts rather than glasses. This is
increasingly true for young boys as well as girls.
</P>
<P>
   Lenses remove the weighty bridge of the eyeglass frame that
rests upon (or alternatively slides up and down) the nose. They
also eliminate the temples (arms) of the eyeglasses that cause
pressure on the ears and obstruct peripheral vision. Kids and their
parents no longer have to worry about glasses that fog up in the
winter or that get wet in the rain. Unlike glasses, contacts are
not likely to get sat on, stepped on, left at school or left at
someone else's house.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of contacts are especially significant for young
athletes. With lenses, soccer players don't need to wear glasses
that can fall off, break or injure them. Hockey players are better
able to see the puck; glasses can't be worn during play because
they fog up under a helmet. Contact lenses remain comfortably
stable in the eyes during cheerleading, dancing, karate, football,
tennis or golf.
</P>
<P>
   There are a variety of eye care professionals that are licensed
to dispense lenses, including ophthalmologists, optometrists and
opticians. Whatever choice is made, it is important to select
someone who is experienced and who routinely sees kids in their
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Mail order is never appropriate for a first pair of lenses. It
is imperative that children or teens receive a complete in-person
examination and fitting.
</P>
<P>
   Because working effectively with kids requires time and
patience, finding someone who specializes in contact lenses may be
a better choice than a practitioner with a busy corrective surgery
practice. Such an individual is generally more willing to solve the
unique fitting problems posed by small eyes and awkward fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Lenses were once exclusively made of hard plastic. Baby-boomers
were the first generation to wear them. Because these little pieces
of hard plastic were relatively new, expensive and difficult to
wear, they were used primarily by vain teen-age girls or young,
single women.
</P>
<P>
   The first major innovation came in the early 1970s when soft
contact lenses were introduced into the market. Rigid gas permeable
lenses came nearly a decade later, greatly increasing comfort and
wearing time by allowing more oxygen to pass through the lens to
the cornea. The market for contacts has now grown to more than 350
different brands, with most adults and children opting for soft
ones. In fact, soft lenses made out of new, more pliable materials
outnumber all other types by four to one.
</P>
<P>
   Soft lenses are easier to wear for a number of reasons. Unlike a
rigid, hard lens, they conform to the shape of the eye and provide
greater comfort. This means that a child who is fitted with soft
lenses can get used to them in a matter of days. Because they are
larger, soft lenses are less likely to pop out than rigid lenses.
</P>
<P>
   There are trade-offs. Rigid lenses are easier to care for and
less likely to rip during handling. Their use is also less likely
to lead to infection.
</P>
<P>
   Because soft lenses act like little sponges, they can attract
irritants such as smoke in the air. Soft lenses are also more
likely to absorb soaps, lotions and other unwanted residues during
handling. Finally, some wearers complain that vision with soft
lenses is less sharp than with rigid ones.
</P>
<P>
   Soft lenses can either be disposable (worn once and thrown away)
or replacement lenses that are replaced according to a schedule
prescribed by the practitioner (generally every two to four weeks).
</P>
<P>
   Among children, the use of daily disposables is becoming
increasingly common. While, over the course of a year, these lenses
are slightly more costly, the additional costs are offset by the
elimination of the need for expensive cleaning and soaking
solutions. Time saved in maintenance and care often makes these
no-fuss lenses attractive to busy kids and their busy moms.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing price, two-week replacement lenses general cost about
$200 per year for the cost of the lenses. The cost of daily
replacement lenses runs slightly higher. A pair of rigid, gas
permeable lenses may run between $140 and $160.
</P>
<P>
   Poor hygiene or improper use of contacts can pose serious safety
risks, such as irritation, infection, corneal ulcers and even
blindness. Therefore, before leaving the practitioner's office, a
child needs to learn the essentials of use and care.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the eye doctor will do this training; in other
cases, a technician takes over. Important information must be
conveyed in a supportive, step-by-step manner that uses
age-appropriate vocabulary that children can understand. A
take-home, written version of the instructions is helpful for
parents who generally will be called upon to troubleshoot at home.
</P>
<P>
   Most eye doctors will follow a patient for at least one or two
visits (which are included in the initial examination and fitting
fee). Because a very small proportion of potential users do not
adapt to contacts for one reason or another, it is useful for
families to ask in advance about the practitioner's refund policy.
</P>
<P>
   Because kids prefer to wear their contacts as long and as often
as possible, parents need to be vigilant to make sure that misuse
or overuse doesn't occur. Sleeping in lenses or wearing them for
too many hours increases the risk of complications. Dr. P. Sarita
Soni of the School of Optometry at Indiana University observes that
adolescents either tend to ``be asymptomatic because they have a
higher discomfort threshold'' or that these teens conceal lens-care
associated problems, so they can continue wearing their lenses at
any cost.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way that new laser vision-correction technology has
revolutionized vision care for adults, surgical options _ even
implants _ may someday replace conventional glasses and contacts
for children. At present, though, these procedures are generally
not appropriate for children whose eyes are still developing and
changing.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to remember that while the use of contact lenses
by kids is more common than ever before, it still may not be the
right choice for every child.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Saviola of the FDA remarks, ``Parents should discuss
all options with an eye care provider they have confidence in to
determine the best option for their child.''
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
