<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETS-BIRDS-LIFEBEAT-420&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 PET BIRDS CAN BE BURDENSOME BUT REWARDING
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo of woman with cocaktoo available in JPEG format by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By TONI GARDNER 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``My birds are infinitely more intelligent than my other pets,''
says Ellen Phillips, managing editor of pet books at Rodale Inc.,
in Emmaus, Pa., and owner of two parrots, a golden retriever and
two cats. ``The older bird taught my new one to speak English in
two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   A bird's intelligence, however, can lead to unforeseeable issues
in its care. Bringing a bird into the family should be well
considered, for birds are complex, intelligent creatures and have
challenging physical and emotional needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest misconception about birds is that they're
'no-maintenance' pets,'' says Dr. Stephen Zawistowski, science
adviser and certified applied animal behaviorist for the ASPCA in
New York City. ``Birds care if you're around, and almost all need
companionship, either from other birds or people.''
</P>
<P>
   Before you invest in a bird as a pet, find an avian veterinarian
who can advise you on the different types of pet birds and put you
in touch with local bird owners and clubs. Be advised: It is
illegal to take a bird from the wild.
</P>
<P>
   After you've chosen from the many pet bird varieties _ gentle
songsters like finches and canaries, friendly parakeets and
cockatiels, or big, bold parrots and cockatoos _ select the
largest-possible cage that your living space can accommodate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever size is recommended, buy larger,'' Zawistowski
stresses. ``And set up the cage according to the type of bird:
Finches need to hop around, for example, while parakeets need to
climb. Vary toys and perch thicknesses.'' And have patience while
your new companion adjusts to its new surroundings and
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts believe that birds can improve our outlook on life
in general. In an animal-assisted therapy program at the Oakwood
Correctional Facility, a short-term mental health facility for
troubled prisoners in Lima, Ohio, male inmates may elect to assume
responsibility for a bird. As activities therapist Karen Bosch
explains, ``The men live with the birds in their cells and form
close bonds with them. They give the birds _ parakeets and
cockatiels _ almost round-the-clock attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these men aren't used to the open-hearted love they
receive,'' Bosch continues. ``The birds help bring them out of
depressions and teach them coping and socialization skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Birds require patience, time and knowledge if they are to be
nurtured as companion animals in the home. We, in return, are
nourished by their music, beauty and friendship _ rewards that far
surpass the effort.
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL HEALTH CONCERNS
</P>
<P>
   Birds hide illnesses to protect themselves from predators, so
careful daily observation and annual checkups are musts. To find a
vet, try the Web site of the Association of Avian Veterinarians:
www.aav.org.
</P>
<P>
   Birds require balanced diets and constant access to clean water.
Hidden dangers include household fumes from nonstick cookware and
poorly designed toys and perches. For more bird information, try
the ASPCA's Web site _ www.aspca.org _ and the American Animal
Hospital Association's Web site, www.healthypet.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Toni Gardner is a contributing editor of ``Country Living''
magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
