<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: The articles described below moved MONDAY,
JULY 3, 2000, in the 'l' news file. The material was filed by The
New York Times Syndicate for use by LIFEBEAT clients.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement
with the Syndicate. For purchase information, see end of text. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PET BIRDS CAN BE BURDENSOME BUT REWARDING
</P>
<P>
   PETS-BIRDS-LIFEBEAT _ Birds are among the most intelligent pets,
however, their intelligence can lead to unforeseeable care issues.
Bringing a bird into the family should be well considered because
of their challenging physical and emotional needs. An avian
veterinarian can advise on the different kinds of pet birds and
recommend local bird owners and clubs for further advice. By Toni
Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo of woman with cocaktoo available in JPEG format
by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HISTORICALLY ACCURATE, GARDENS OF OLD MONTEREY ARE A FRAGRANT
REFUGE
</P>
<P>
   GARDENS-MONTEREY-LIFEBEAT _ The garden at the Doud House, an
1860s clapboard house built in New England style by a wealthy
entrepreneur, is but one of 12 historic gardens in Monterey, Calif.
Some are so hidden away behind adobe walls that the locals refer to
them as ``secret gardens.'' They're smack in the middle of the
city, part of a public park system that runs through old Monterey,
but you would never find them without a map. Most belong to the
state of California, bequeathed by descendants of their original
owners _ and have been restored by volunteers. By Sara Solovitch.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos of gardens available in JPEG format by calling
William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KIDS CONSIDER CONTACT LENSES FOR COMFORT AND CONVENIENCE
</P>
<P>
   CONTACT-LENSES-CHILDREN-LIFEBEAT _ According to the U.S. Food
and Drug Administration, which began regulating contact lenses in
1976, an estimated 30 million people in this country now wear them.
A rapidly growing number are 16 years old or younger. The benefits
of contacts are especially significant for young athletes. However,
poor hygiene or improper use of contacts can pose serious safety
risks, such as irritation, infection, corneal ulcers and even
blindness. Therefore, before leaving the practitioner's office, a
child needs to learn the essentials of use and care. By Irene S.
Levine.
</P>
<P>
   SOMETIMES EVEN FOR BABIES, HERBAL MEDICINE IS BEST
</P>
<P>
   HERBAL-MEDICINE-KIDS-LIFEBEAT _ Thousands of parents have
recently discovered age-old folk remedies, often with the
recommendation of family doctors who are adding herbal remedies to
their disease-fighting arsenal. Herbal medicine has become big
business. Last year, Americans snapped up nearly $4 billion worth
of herbal products from the shelves of supermarkets, pharmacies and
health food stores. Fueling these soaring sales, at least in part,
is growing scientific evidence indicating that some of these
products really can ease the symptoms of many minor ills. That also
explains why alternative medicine is gaining acceptance by the
medical mainstream and more doctors are getting up to speed on
botanical remedies. By Linda Marsa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
