<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2110 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-DESIGNERSTORE-TEXAS-2     07-03 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESIGNERSTORE-TEXAS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
SALADO, Texas: charity fund-raisers. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was when Loretta Young entered the scene. In the late '60s,
Jones had invited Jean-Louis, a famous Hollywood designer, to
headline a charity fashion show. The plane that carried the
clothing was hijacked to Cuba. Young, who was then married to
Jean-Louis, cleaned out her closets and flew to Texas with her
personal wardrobe to save the show.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' business flourished. Although to hear her tell it,
shopkeeping was a modest profit-maker. She added to her resume.
</P>
<P>
   She hired seminal Texas architect O'Neill Ford to build her
home.
</P>
<P>
   She led the Salado Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   She sat on the board of regents for the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Then came her divorce. He got the ranch, she got the store.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, after 40 years in business, she closed the store.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Days before the finale, Jones is so caught up in the turmoil of
change that she can barely focus on the immediate moment. The town
is clamoring to know what she plans to do with her historic
building. ``Something that will be good for Salado,'' she says, but
what that is, she doesn't know. She is making a list of everyone
who has expressed an interest. ``I will interview them, later,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   This Scarlett O'Hara management philosophy of thinking about it
tomorrow is the best she can muster. Her decision to close was
prompted by the unexpected death of her sister-in-law, Genelle
Rosanky, who had been with her since she first opened the store.
Rosanky handled all the bookkeeping duties.
</P>
<P>
   During the last few days of operation, two of Jones' stalwart
assistants have been called away to attend family funerals. Her
hairdresser is out of town, her housekeeper left her three months
ago. She feels utterly abandoned. If she sits still for more than a
few moments, paperwork begins to pile around her like filings to a
magnet. Messages, checks, papers to be signed. She sighs as she
sorts them and then returns them to their unattended state. She
looks around at the furniture and all-but-empty display shelves and
begins to grow despondent. ``It's terrible to close after so long.
What can I do with this?''
</P>
<P>
   All of ``this'' Jones modeled on the Neiman Marcus of her youth.
When the ranching Rosankys of Smithville needed to do some serious
shopping, Grace and her mother would travel to Dallas. Even after
opening her own store, she continued to shop at Neiman's for things
she did not carry. There was a mutual affection between merchants.
</P>
<P>
   After Jones announced that she was closing, Stanley Marcus noted
she was ``one of the shining retail lights in Texas because she was
able to sell high-fashion merchandise with style and authority in
an unorthodox setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones forged loyal relationships with her customers, and the
past few weeks have seen a parade of them coming by to pay their
respects. They have come to say goodbye to a friend and a way of
life. One local customer and close friend of Jones' ducks in to buy
all the handkerchiefs left in stock. Where else is she going to
find hand-embroidered linen hankies?
</P>
<P>
   ``Where am I going to buy my stockings?'' wails another. She has
just realized that among Salado's restaurants, antique stores and
B&AMP;Bs, there isn't anywhere to buy her hosiery. Jones sadly shakes
her head.
</P>
<P>
   In her early days, Jones says she was criticized by a Neiman
Marcus buyer who watched her as she worked with a customer. Later,
after the customer left, the buyer lambasted Jones, ``You didn't
tell her how nice she looked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the woman,'' countered Jones. ``I don't know if
she looked nice or not. I don't know her. I don't know how good she
can look.''
</P>
<P>
   She says the best moments of owning her store were finding
something a customer needed. It wasn't the fashion shows, or the
purchasing or the travel.
</P>
<P>
   The woman who would go to Paris and New York at least twice a
year, sometimes more often, is now looking forward to spending time
in Texas' tiny towns of Smithville and Gonzales, ``where my mother
and father are from. Do some simple things, and meaningful ones.''
There are cousins to visit, nieces to know better.
</P>
<P>
   The store is suddenly filled with a family from Austin. A woman
ushers in her daughter and three young granddaughters. She wants
the girls to see a dress store the way they used to be. They tour
the empty dressing rooms, with their little stages and huge
mirrors. They dutifully glance at the few remaining pieces of
clothing _ a luscious black lace blouse, on sale for $700,
brilliant yellow Lacroix pants with a burn-out design near the hem
_ no price tag, so no gasp. The girls are obviously not overwhelmed
but they politely introduce themselves to Miss Jones, and shake her
hand when their grandmother nudges them forward. Miss Jones beams
and asks to take a photo of the three pretty little blondes. Had
she stayed open, perhaps they would have become customers. Many of
hers were second and third generation.
</P>
<P>
   While the girls gather around Jones for their photo, two women
hesitantly step in the door. They look around the front room. They
don't see sales racks and the scene looks like a private moment, so
they quickly leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't understand,'' says Jones.
</P>
<P>
   So many people don't know how this sort of store works, ``and
now there isn't any time left to show them.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
