 For Release TUESDAY AMs, July 4, 2000  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-PRI (Mexico City) _ Sunday a meteor hit Mexico. It sent
waves of voters, driven by an intense desire for political change,
to cast their ballots in a historic election that freed them from
their own version of Jurassic Park. And for the first time in
modern history, Mexicans will not be ruled by the PRI. By Richard
Chacon. 950 words.
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-HOSTAGE (Moscow) _ Adi Sharon was chained to a wall for
so long that when Russian police finally freed him, he was
convinced the bandits who tortured and maimed him for 9 months had
come to execute him. The suffering of this 12-year-old Israeli
tourist is over, but Sharon's rescue holds ominous implications for
police searching for at least 850 kidnapping victims believed to be
held in Chechnya. By David Filipov. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-ATTACKS (Moscow) _ The death toll rises to at least 54
in Chechnya from suicide truck bomb attacks that shatter Russia's
claim that its troops control the rebellious region. By David
Filipov. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NONFAMILY-EMBRYOS (Undated) _ Medical clinics around the country
are increasingly trying to help infertile couples conceive by using
frozen embryos that are not the patients' own, a trend that raises
provocative new questions about family relationships and genetic
disclosure. &UR;  &LR; By Adam Pertman. 1600 words.
</P>
<P>
   INSULIN-TRANSPLANTS (Boston) _ In a step toward making
transplants of insulin-producing cells a reality for a large number
of diabetics, researchers at the Joslin Diabetes Center tap a new
source of the scarce islet cells _ pancreatic tissue that's
normally discarded. By Richard Saltus. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   WASHER-DEMISE (Undated) _ The end of an era is drawing near as
the EPA mandates the death of the top-loading washing machine.
Federal energy standards require new washers to be 35 percent more
efficient within seven years. Front-loaders use two-thirds less
water. By Beth Daley. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS-AFTERTAX (Undated) _ The public comment period had ended
for an SEC proposal to require mutual funds to report after-tax
returns alongside pre-tax ones. By Scott Bernard Nelson. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-MIDPOINT (Undated) _ Halfway through what started out as
an auspicious year, money managers discuss where the markets have
settled. By Kimberly Blanton. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEN-WIMBLEDON (London) _ Apparently, Pete Sampras isn't only
playing through pain, he's playing through paranoia. The only
question is whether it's his or everybody else's. By Bob Duffy.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN (London) _ Hercules, the old Greek
body-building champ, would surely sympathize with a little kid
named Martina Hingis, wandering the dangerous grassland of
Wimbledon. By Bud Collins.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-NHIS-PETTY (Undated) _ Kyle Petty, who was scheduled to run
his No. 44 Hot Wheels sponsored Pontiac in this weekend's New
England 00 in Loudon, N.H., has decided not to participate Petty
Enterprises says. By William Kalec.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
