<HEADER>
A2117 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NEWSSTAND04-COX     07-03 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tina Brown's dishy Talk gets back to following its instincts
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tina Brown says the August issue of her Talk ($3.50) magazine is
the best yet. She's right. After the much-hyped debut issue with
Hillary Rodham Clinton, the magazine has been erratic in tone and
content. Now, with a single-image cover and lots of Vanity Fair
touches, Talk seems to be on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   In this issue, the must-read piece is an excerpt from ``Basic
Instinct'' screenwriter Joe Eszterhas' new book, ``American
Rhapsody.'' Part memoir, part political commentary and part
fantasy, the book focuses on the cast of characters involved in
Bill Clinton's personal woes. Eszterhas, of course, provides lots
of juicy details about his own sexual escapades.
</P>
<P>
   Other articles of note include an interview with Liz Hurley
about life after Hugh Grant, a profile of Donatella Versace and an
update on one family's attempt to get justice for a Klan killing in
Alabama 43 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Monday night buzz: Sports Illustrated ($2.99) writer S.L.
Price muses about the impact Dennis Miller will have on ``Monday
Night Football'' _ and his fellow announcers Al Michaels and Dan
Fouts.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Howard Cosell pontificated from ABC's booth has there
been as much excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is taking a surprisingly low-key approach to the new gig.
``I'm not going to go into that booth and turn into Ed Murrow
during the Blitz, for god's sake.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Harry-ied: In case you've been in a bomb shelter for the past
few months, here's the latest big news. The fourth Harry Potter
novel hits stores Saturday with the biggest first printing ever _
3.8 million copies in the United States alone. What does author
J.K. Rowling think of all this? Newsweek's ($3.50) Malcolm Jones
chats with Harry's creator about the upcoming film (Harry hasn't
been cast yet), the future of the novels (``I want them all to grow
up, but not in a way that's unfaithful to the tone of the books'')
and the final installment (``Seven's going to be like the
Encyclopedia Britannica, because I'm going to want to say
goodbye'').
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Revolutionary filmmaking: Mel Gibson's movie ``The Patriot''
may not be entirely historically accurate, but most of the period
details are. The July issue of Smithsonian ($3) magazine describes
how the Smithsonian Institution advised director Roland Emmerich on
everything from uniforms to cooking utensils. There were some
Hollywood compromises, however. For instance, historian Margaret
Vining notes that the film did not adequately represent the major
role women played in the war.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: The fifth-anniversary issue of Doubletake ($10)
draws on emerging photographers as well as past masters such as
Dorothea Lange to showcase everyone from surfers to sharecroppers.
... Time ($3.50) takes a leisurely trip down the Mississippi River,
pausing at cities such as Cairo, Ill., and Vicksburg, Miss., to
take the pulse of America. ... In an excellent New Yorker ($3)
profile, author Tracy Kidder writes about medical doctor Paul
Farmer's crusade to save the world's poor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
