<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DEMOCRACY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHANGING OF THE GUARD IN MEXICO DRAWS PRAISE IN THE U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GARY MARTIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vicente Fox's stunning electoral victory that ended
71-year-old hold on the presidency by Mexico's governing party was
praised and applauded Monday by U.S. officials and scholars who
said the historic event legitimized the political system south of
the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we now have to say Mexico has a legitimate
democracy,'' said Sidney Weintraub, a Latin America trade
specialist at the Center for Strategic and International Studies.
</P>
<P>
   The Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) has controlled
Mexico's government since 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's opposition National Action Party (PAN) tapped into decades
of public distrust of the PRI to stage a victory that included two
state governorships and enough seats in Congress to become the
dominant party. In addition, the party nearly took over the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was right,'' said Weintraub, author of the book,
``A Marriage of Convenience: Relations Between Mexico and the
U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox defeated PRI candidate Francisco Labastida and Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas of the left-of-center Democratic Revolution Party, whose
base of political support is largely within Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Weintraub said the overwhelming victory for the PAN was the
result of Fox's popular personality, a weak PRI candidate,
political reforms and stringent controls that were put in place by
a federal election commission to ensure a fair election.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a former Coca-Cola Co. executive, was quick to claim his
victory represents a ``right foot forward'' for Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton called Fox on Monday to congratulate the
president-elect, and invited him to the White House after he takes
office later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexicans should be proud of the extraordinary steps they have
taken during the last six years to strengthen and consolidate
democratic institutions and set Mexico on a course of economic
growth and prosperity,'' Clinton said from the Camp David
presidential retreat in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico is our neighbor and friend. Mexico's national
elections, the freest and fairest in the nation's history, stand as
a vivid testimony to the depth of the democratic commitment of the
Mexican people,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   A White House aide said Clinton also applauded Fox for his
campaign to fight corruption, help the poor and improve education.
Clinton also thanked outgoing Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo for
putting in place the political reforms that allowed an opposition
candidate to win.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has surpassed Japan as the United States' second largest
trading partner. (Canada is the top American trading partner.) The
United States and Mexico share cultural ties and a 2,000-mile
border.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, Gov. George W. Bush called the Mexican election ``very
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows how powerful change is. When the people want change
or want reform, it's amazing what happens,'' Bush, the Republican
presidential hopeful, said during a news conference at his ranch in
Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic candidate for president,
was in San Diego to address the convention of the National Council
of La Raza, the country's largest Hispanic rights organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish him well,'' Gore said of Fox. ``I compliment the people
of Mexico on an election that was apparently a model election in
many ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Weintraub said there would be few changes in the U.S.-Mexico
relationship, because the U.S. financial community trusts Fox. The
European Union, which has trade agreements with Mexico, also
welcomed the election results.
</P>
<P>
   But narcotics trafficking and immigration will continue to be
issues that test the relationship between the United States and
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there are still many challenges ahead for Mexico and the
United States, the counterdrug cooperation we have built over the
last few years is a foundation which transcends any particular
election or change of administration,'' said Barry McCaffrey,
director of the Office of National Drug Control Policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nations understand the critical importance of continued
action,'' McCaffrey said, referring to the United States and
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fox's first order of business, however, will be to address the
issues on which he campaigned: education, social reforms and
helping the nation's poor.
</P>
<P>
   Weintraub said he expects Fox to form alliances with the other
parties to move some of his proposals through Congress. ``That will
become a necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the PRI has ``been a corrupt, self-enriching and at
time vicious party,'' Weintraub said it was unlikely that Fox would
order a wholesale dismissal of PRI officials within the government
and instead strive toward allegiances for legislative progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``He already has said he intends to make alliances on the
federal level _ take those people from the PRI who are honest and
not corrupt and efficient, and maybe some from the PRD as well,''
Weintraub said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will need those alliances ``if he is going to change the tax
system and increase social spending,'' Weintraub said. ``There are
a lot of things he has to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
