<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2126 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     07-03 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Surviving Team Williams tough task for Hingis
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ It happened at the U.S. Open, and it seems
virtually certain to happen again here. Martina Hingis may be the
No. 1 player in the world, Wimbledon's top seed and the winner of
five major titles before her 20th birthday, but she remains the
underdog _ until she proves otherwise _ against Team Williams.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, she knows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Hingis admitted Monday, ``the tournament begins.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis faces Venus Williams in the quarterfinals today. Her
reward for winning figures to be having to then deal with Serena
Williams in the semifinals Thursday. She is, however, trying to
think positively, because unless weather intervenes, and weather
is, to be sure, known to intervene on this famous greensward,
Wimbledon has a schedule that actually makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the way, now that we're down to the quarterfinals,
the women and the men are scheduled to play on alternating days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I would beat one,'' Hingis pointed out, ``I would get
another day off. I have always had to play them (on) consecutive
days.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the case at Flushing Meadow, and Martina proved
unworthy of the task, succumbing to Serena in the U.S. final in
straight sets after having clawed and scratched her way past Venus
in the semis. While the Swiss miss, who looks like a girl among
women although she is not, may be the vastly superior tactical
player, she falls short physically against both Williamses.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter referred to them during Hingis' post-match interview
as ``a monster with two heads.'' She smiled at the image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, they're not easy,'' Hingis said. ``But anything is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, I lost all the time against the second one when I had
to play them both. But I always had to play them on consecutive
days. That's very hard. You have a three-setter, you're happy you
made it through. Then, the next day, the other one is waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena herself almost sounded sympathetic when she was asked to
reflect on the challenge confronting Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venus and I both run very well; we both have big serves; we're
both attacking,'' she said. ``It's like playing the same person who
is your nemesis, playing them all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when the Wimbledon draw was set, and Hingis wound up
stuck in the same half with the sister-sister act that will dog her
for the rest of her career, her task didn't appear to be as
daunting as at present. Venus had been off the tour for most of the
year with tendinitis in her wrists and hadn't showed a lot in the
French Open despite reaching the quarters. Serena, in turn, hadn't
played anywhere since mid-April because of a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody had a clue what to expect from them, particularly since
neither has shown any special affinity for grass even when fully
fit.
</P>
<P>
   Venus got this far the last two summers before going belly up.
Serena faltered in the third round two years ago in her only
previous Wimbledon appearance. But as these slash-and-burn
teenagers learn their way around the All England Club, they are
only going to improve. In fact, a breakout may be upon us.
</P>
<P>
   Serena has blown through four rounds, losing only 11 games and
spending less than three hours total on the court, although she
insists, ``I've been tested enough. I'm just trying to conserve my
energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus, for her part, suffered a bit of a walkabout in the second
set Monday against Sabine Appelmans _ similar to her loose patch
against Nathalie Dechy earlier _ but she says she feels very good.
Physically anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I missed quite a few easy shots,'' Venus said. ``I
usually don't do that. Yeah, it really is annoying. But I can raise
the level of my game. I just have to get my mind there. There's no
way these girls should be competing like that against me. Unless,
of course, I let them.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't be Venus' option vs. Hingis. For her, the tournament
starts today as well. Martina owns a 9-5 edge in their head-to-head
play, leads 3-0 in Grand Slam meetings and defeated Venus most
recently in the semifinals of the Chase Championships last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been able to beat Venus when it was really
important,'' Hingis said.
</P>
<P>
   But not after having had to beat Serena first. Two of Venus'
wins followed Hingis victories over her sister. But the younger
Williams has won three of the last four meetings against Martina to
even their series at 3-all. And Hingis is 0-3 in the second of
successive Williams matches. The prospects of enduring these
one-two punches for the rest of her career forced Martina to
recognize the obvious. She had to get in the gym and make herself
stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brought a new game to women's tennis,'' Hingis said, ``a
lot more power, a lot more physical ability. (To beat them) you
have to work out more, just hit the ball harder basically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't played them in a while. But I've been playing very
consistent after the second match (a 6-4, 6-1 win over Jing-Qian
Li) and serving very well. If it's going to be enough (against the
Williamses), time will tell. It will show, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   We know.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
