<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HALFWAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HALFWAY THROUGH SEASON, WITH A LONG WAY TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RAY RATTO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With all due respect to the All-Star break,
baseball's halfway point is actually the Fourth of July, and not
just because of the 15 scheduled pyrospectaculars on the card.
</P>
<P>
   That's pyrospectaculars, as in fireworks shows.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the following teams had played at least 81 games before
the Fourth: Anaheim, Arizona, Atlanta, the Chicago Cubs, the
Chicago White Sox, Cincinnati, Cleveland, Florida, Houston, Los
Angeles, Milwaukee, Minnesota, Oakland, Pittsburgh, St. Louis, San
Diego and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   So here's your handy guide to the majors as we hit the turn _
some harder than others.
</P>
<P>
   THE NL WEST, or A LOT WORSE THAN THEY'RE LETTING ON: Arizona has
played .500 ball since early May, so the Diamondbacks plainly can
be had. But by whom? Colorado is still forced by law to play half
its games outside Denver, the Dodgers have no closer, the Giants
are getting to be like the Rockies, and the Padres are just sort of
futzing around until ... well, until forever, as near as anyone can
make out.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to like anyone with any real conviction, because all
the teams have noticeable flaws, but Arizona and Colorado are more
likely to spend money and bodies wisely at the trade deadline. The
midseason MVP would either be Todd Helton, Barry Bonds or Randy
Johnson, but the LVP is Omar Daal, who just lost his ninth game in
11 decisions, pushed his ERA back over seven and is barely breaking
even with the impressive Brian Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   THE AL WEST, or, I DON'T GOT TO SHOW YOU NO STEENKIN' PAYROLL:
The A's aren't paying very much for their record, the Mariners have
lost payroll moving Ken Griffey to the Ohio Valley, and the Angels
... oh, who cares? Texas has put up a dismal show, but could rally
if it had a rotation worth speaking of.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners look best because their bullpen is actually better
than someone else's for a change, and the A's look to be about as
good as they're ever going to be, barring a sudden burst of payroll
generosity from the Brothers No. The MVP is Jason Giambi, and the
LVP is Mark Clark, the one-time Texas starter with the 7.98 ERA.
Look, if we had a better candidate, we'd have told you.
</P>
<P>
   THE NL CENTRAL, or, THE SECRET TO FAILURE IS A REALLY GOOD
TRADE: Cincinnati made one, for Ken Griffey, and looks like it will
lose 20 more games than it did a year ago. The Cubs tried to make
one with Sammy Sosa as the bait and couldn't get anyone to dance
with them. The Brewers sent Jose Valentin and Cal Eldred to the
White Sox for nothing in particular and are now watching those two
help the Sox build the game's best record. Only the Cardinals, who
traded and signed their way to a better rotation and counterweight
to Mark McGwire, did themselves proud over the winter.
</P>
<P>
   The MVP is Jim Edmonds, said counterweight, and the LVP is Jose
Lima, who is turning into a puff of blue sulfurous smoke before our
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   THE AL CENTRAL, or, BUFFALO FINALLY MAKES THE BIG LEAGUES: The
White Sox are the feel-good story of the year, with the redemption
of Frank Thomas, the assembly of a stunningly good starting
rotation (Eldred is the No. 5 starter, and he's 10-2), and Keith
Foulke as closer to make you Giants fans eat your livers.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland just used its 27th pitcher, Andrew Lorraine, and is
beginning to back up the truck at an awfully early stage of the
year. None of the other teams is worth bothering with again. The
MVP is Thomas, and the LVP is Jaime Navarro because, well, he
explains how horribly it's gone for the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   THE NL EAST, or HERE COMES THE CIRCUS: The Atlanta Braves have
destroyed the excuse losers use when they can't admit they stink _
distractions. John Rocker has been everything Jerry Springer hoped
he would be, but the Braves remain so tight that even a pie fight
with feet like Rocker can't upset them too terribly much. Splitting
in New York this past weekend explained nearly everything about the
Braves, no matter how much of a rebuttal Mike Piazza tried to put
up.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal and Florida are interchangeable pleasant surprises
(although there is a move afoot to devalue Marlins closer Antonio
Alfonseca's stats by 20 percent because of the sixth finger on his
throwing hand). Philadelphia is just watching with the bat on its
shoulder. The MVP is either Piazza or Andres Galarraga, and the LVP
is . . . oh, don't make us say it.
</P>
<P>
   THE AL EAST, or TORONTO TORONTO TORONTO!: No, we don't get it
either, but it has something to do with the Yankees and Red Sox
having insufficient pitching. The Yankees are still begging David
Cone to break out of his troubles, and the Red Sox have lost both
Pedro Martinez and Jeff Fassero to the disabled list. That leaves
Toronto, hitting even more home runs than the Cardinals, and having
both David Wells and the best closer in baseball, Billy Koch. The
MVP is Carlos Delgado, and the LVP is the Baltimore bullpen, on a
pace to blow 40 saves this year.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, aren't we all?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
