<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2147 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-VEEP-COX     07-03 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-VEEP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush keeping lid on VP search
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRAWFORD, Texas _ GOP presidential candidate George W. Bush on
Monday held his first news conference at the Waco-area ranch he
hopes will become the Texas White House.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be more conference than news.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into a closed-door session with former Defense Secretary
Dick Cheney, the point man in the hunt for a running mate, Bush
offered little light on the process that has demonstrated the
campaign's first-rate ability to keep a secret.
</P>
<P>
   Courteously and patiently, neither Bush nor Cheney offered much
insight on what's going on inside. Four weeks, or less, from having
to pick a running mate, Bush insisted it's a pretty wide-open
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made up my mind yet,'' he told reporters bused to a
field on the southwest side of his 1,600-acre ranch. ``What I
really don't want to do is have the formal interview process so
that candidates have to walk through the gauntlet of the klieg
lights in order to have a visit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be visiting with people face-to-face, some of whom you
will know about some of whom you won't know about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While no candidates have been in for formal interviews, Bush has
met with potential running mates _ including Michigan Gov. John
Engler, Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge and others _ as he travels
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's session with Cheney was their third meeting since Bush
put his father's former aide on the one-man headhunting committee.
Bush and Cheney speak frequently by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   While declining to say who is on the list, Bush was willing to
say that anyone who has asked off the list has been taken off. That
includes Arizona Sen. John McCain, former Gen. Colin Powell,
Florida Sen. Connie Mack and former Missouri Sen. John Danforth.
</P>
<P>
   Bush talks about the list of potential running mates as if it
were a living, breathing thing that ``kind of grows and shrinks
depending on what I look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides scrambled quickly last week when Oklahoma Gov. Frank
Keating become the rumored candidate du jour. As he does with any
name that crops up, Bush on Monday commended Keating as a friend
whose name brings positive response as a potential running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney insisted his only role is data collector. Potential
running mates are responding to a questionnaire that includes
queries about ``public records, financial records, health records,
all those kind of things that you look at,'' Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   That's about as far as Bush and Cheney are willing to go. Bush
dodged when asked Monday for any kind of details.
</P>
<P>
   How long is the current list of potential vice presidential
candidates?
</P>
<P>
   ``More than one.''
</P>
<P>
   When will the selection be announced?
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be by the end of next week. And I haven't made up my
mind if the announcement will be made at the convention or sometime
prior to the convention,'' he said. ``One thing is for certain, I'm
not going to name the person after the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Convention begins July 31 in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Has everyone under consideration been on a ballot somewhere for
something?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe. Maybe not.''
</P>
<P>
   Are there ethnic minorities on the list?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're considering a wide variety of people, a wide range of
people from all different backgrounds and different states.''
</P>
<P>
   Any thumb on the scale in favor of a female?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're giving women serious consideration. They will get the
same consideration that everybody else gets.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, as Cheney and Bush headed down the road toward the
recently remodeled house that serves as ranch headquarters until a
new house is completed later this year, the candidate said the goal
remains the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a wide variety of factors that go into the
selection,'' he said. ``But the two most important factors are
going to be, can the person be the president and will the person be
able to play a significant and meaningful role in an
administration, which means will we be able to get along well.''
</P>
<P>
   While the only people who really matter in the process met
privately, independent groups stepped up efforts to push their
favorites. Supporters of U.S. Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, billing
themselves as the BplusK Committee, announced it will begin
displaying Bush-Kasich signs at Bush events around the country.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles today, a group called American Women Presidents
will endorse Elizabeth Dole for Bush's running mate and California
Sen. Dianne Feinstein for Democratic candidate Al Gore's vice
presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
