   NATIONAL-GENERAL (moved in the ``a'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   HARRY POTTER AND THE END OF INNOCENCE
</P>
<P>
   HARRY-POTTER-CENTERPIECE _ Harry Potter is the biggest
mass-culture phenomenon to come out of Britain since the Beatles,
and like the Fab Four before him, the young wizard hero of J.K.
Rowling's series of children's books may soon prove to be more
popular than Jesus. Hold your letters! All I mean is that Rowling's
fourth installment, arriving in bookstores July 8, will in all
likelihood do better than the current No. 1 fiction best seller on
the New York Times list, Tim LaHaye and Jerry B. Jenkins' end-times
theological potboiler ``The Indwelling.'' Whatever this might say
about the immediate status of enchantment and faith, its
ramifications in the secular world may be more profound, and more
lasting. By A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   (A.O. Scott is a film critic for The New York Times.)
</P>
<P>
   THE VANITY OF VOLUNTEERISM
</P>
<P>
   VOLUNTEERISM-FAILURE-CENTERPIECE _ I am a volunteer. For more
than a decade, politicians and civic leaders have been looking to
volunteers like me to take over the government's role in providing
vital services to the poor. ``Compassionate conservatives'' would
probably claim that I am the kind of ``caring adult'' who can
transform the lives of disadvantaged kids more effectively than any
government program. I'm all for volunteering, but I would disagree.
To work, mentoring has to be performed consistently, over a
sustained period of time and preferably one on one. For the first
couple of years, I saw my kids as often as twice a week. But now
I'm lucky if I see them once a month, and I almost never see them
individually. In their lives, I'm less a caring adult than a random
one. And my failure is representative. By Sara Mosle.
</P>
<P>
   (Sara Mosle is writing a book about a school explosion during
the East Texas oil boom in the 1930s.)
</P>
<P>
   BROTHERLY LOVE IT'S GOT, AND NOW THERE'S A TOUCH OF ENVY, TOO
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-PHILLY-TECH _ when Philadelphia was omitted from a Wall
Street Journal list of the top 20 technology areas last November,
the slight touched off a quest for attention that would have made
the region's Quaker settlers twitch uncomfortably. Civic leaders in
the City of Brotherly Love want an e-business scene, just as
earlier civic efforts tried to recognize the city's movie,
restaurant and film notables. Here, Philadelphia's search for an
e-commerce glamour tag. By David J. Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING A WARLORD'S ADVICE TO SHAKE UP THE MARKETPLACE
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-JAPAN _ Hiroshi Mikitani's e-ecommerce site, called
Rakuten, has become Japan's largest online bazaar. The site,
www.rakuten.co.jp, draws about 95 million hits a month as a gateway
to about 2,800 merchants around the country selling everything from
eggs to kimonos. Merchants pay 50,000 yen a month, or about $469,
to link their Web sites to Rakuten. In exchange, they receive tips
on jazzing up those sites and access to Rakuten's database and
software, which contain information about customers and their
predilections. Rakuten also offers them low-cost advertising. A
report. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   NAVY SET TO CELEBRATE A CENTURY OF SUBMARINING
</P>
<P>
   SUBMARINE-CENTENNIAL-POPMECH _ One hundred years ago this fall,
on Oct. 12, 1900, the U.S. Navy deployed the USS Holland. While
this fishy-looking, fume-belching submarine would never fire a shot
in anger, it would reshape the fate of nations more completely than
any war. By Jim Wilson. (1,300 words.) WITH GRAPHIC, PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY MECHANIC: REPLACING YOUR WATER PUMP
</P>
<P>
   CAR-CARE-WATERPUMP-POPMECH _ Bombing down the interstate, you
glance at the odometer and realize you've just reached an
automotive milestone: 100,000 miles with no major repairs. Time was
a car that had passed its belly over that much real estate was
considered pretty much used up, but yours still runs great and
looks practically new. Amazing how technology has advanced. Then
you notice the temperature gauge. Holy smokes _ pegged! It may be
time to change the water pump. By Bob Freudenberger. WITH GRAPHICS.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEOWNER-Q&AMP;A-POPMECH _ The question in this edition: 1) How
does one put new vinyl flooring over the top of the old vinyl? 2)
To stain a new Southern yellow pine deck, should a water-repellent
preservative be applied first? 3) A look at a backup power
alternative to generators: A bank of 12-volt batteries that supply
current through an inverter/charger. By Norman Becker.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY-WATCH-POPMECH _ Brief items on technology: SHARKS
REALLY DO GET CANCER; HARVESTING ELECTRICITY FROM DIESEL FUEL;
MISSILE EYES IDENTIFY CHEMICALS; MISSING-LINK FOSSIL DISCOVERED;
PHONE PAD LETS DEAF CALL 911; GENE SPLICING IN SPACE LAB. WITH
ILLUSTRATIONS, PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WEB WONDERS
</P>
<P>
   INTELLIGENT-SPIDERS-ON-WEB-DISCOVER _ Trying to find something
on the Internet is a lot like rummaging through countless cardboard
boxes in a dark attic. Even if the search is eventually successful,
it almost always turns up too much junk. Worse, no search is ever
comprehensive. The dark attic of the Internet is only infiltrated
as far as the very limited capabilities of a particular search
engine. Is it hopeless? Maybe not in the future. Some Web engineers
are trying to develop swifter, more efficient spiders _ spindly
bits of software that meander from Web site to Web site, sucking up
bits of text and making a list of the keywords they find. By
Fenella Saunders.
</P>
<P>
   BREAKTHROUGH BRIEFS
</P>
<P>
   BREAKTHROUGH-BRIEFS-DISCOVER _ Brief reports from the worlds of
science and technology. Among this week's headlines: ``Under T.
Rex's Toes,'' ``Homo Intoxicatus'' and ``Poet of the Pill.''
Compiled by the editors of Discover magazine. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLES (moved in the ``l'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   PET BIRDS CAN BE BURDENSOME BUT REWARDING
</P>
<P>
   PETS-BIRDS-LIFEBEAT _ Birds are among the most intelligent pets,
however, their intelligence can lead to unforeseeable care issues.
Bringing a bird into the family should be well considered because
of their challenging physical and emotional needs. An avian
veterinarian can advise on the different kinds of pet birds and
recommend local bird owners and clubs for further advice. By Toni
Gardner. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   HISTORICALLY ACCURATE, GARDENS OF OLD MONTEREY ARE A FRAGRANT
REFUGE
</P>
<P>
   GARDENS-MONTEREY-LIFEBEAT _ The garden at the Doud House, an
1860s clapboard house built in New England style by a wealthy
entrepreneur, is but one of 12 historic gardens in Monterey, Calif.
Some are so hidden away behind adobe walls that the locals refer to
them as ``secret gardens.'' They're smack in the middle of the
city, part of a public park system that runs through old Monterey,
but you would never find them without a map. Most belong to the
state of California, bequeathed by descendants of their original
owners _ and have been restored by volunteers. By Sara Solovitch.
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS CONSIDER CONTACT LENSES FOR COMFORT AND CONVENIENCE
</P>
<P>
   CONTACT-LENSES-CHILDREN-LIFEBEAT _ According to the U.S. Food
and Drug Administration, which began regulating contact lenses in
1976, an estimated 30 million people in this country now wear them.
A rapidly growing number are 16 years old or younger. The benefits
of contacts are especially significant for young athletes. However,
poor hygiene or improper use of contacts can pose serious safety
risks, such as irritation, infection, corneal ulcers and even
blindness. Therefore, before leaving the practitioner's office, a
child needs to learn the essentials of use and care. By Irene S.
Levine.
</P>
<P>
   SOMETIMES EVEN FOR BABIES, HERBAL MEDICINE IS BEST
</P>
<P>
   HERBAL-MEDICINE-KIDS-LIFEBEAT _ Thousands of parents have
recently discovered age-old folk remedies, often with the
recommendation of family doctors who are adding herbal remedies to
their disease-fighting arsenal. Herbal medicine has become big
business. Last year, Americans snapped up nearly $4 billion worth
of herbal products from the shelves of supermarkets, pharmacies and
health food stores. Fueling these soaring sales, at least in part,
is growing scientific evidence indicating that some of these
products really can ease the symptoms of many minor ills. That also
explains why alternative medicine is gaining acceptance by the
medical mainstream and more doctors are getting up to speed on
botanical remedies. By Linda Marsa.
</P>
<P>
   SNAKE NOT CHARMED? HOW TO SURVIVE AN ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVAL-FOR-REAL-1 _ The hike is going great. You're almost at
the end of the trail, feeling fine, when suddenly you trip over
something that looks a bit like a garden hose. Your good mood turns
to horror as you realize that it's not a hose, it's a snake _ and
it's about to sink its fangs into your leg. What should you do?
This excerpt from ``The WORST-CASE SCENARIO Survival Handbook''
explains how to avoid a snake attack and what to do if, despite
your best efforts, you are bitten. By Joshua Piven and David
Borgenicht. WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK BEFORE YOU LEAP: HOW TO SURVIVE A JUMP INTO WATER
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVAL-FOR-REAL-2 _ Harrison Ford did it in ``The Fugitive.''
So did Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid. OK, unless you're a
movie hero, you'll probably never be forced to leap from a cliff or
bridge into water. But, hey, you never know. And if you should one
day find yourself perched on the edge, with nowhere else to go,
wouldn't you like to be prepared? The following excerpt from ``The
WORST-CASE SCENARIO SURVIVAL Handbook'' offers tips that can raise
your chances of surviving such a leap. By Joshua Piven and David
Borgenicht. WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   HOWDY, SMOKEY. WHAT TO DO IF YOU COME FACE-TO-FACE WITH A BEAR
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVAL-FOR-REAL-3 _ Bears are getting bolder these days.
They're wandering out of the woods and into the suburbs _ where
they have been known to break into houses, surprise backyard
barbecuers and generally wreak havoc. With the number of bear
sightings _ and encounters _ on the rise, it's time to brush up on
your ``bear-proofing'' skills and learn what to do if you come
face-to-face with a 500-pound grizzly. This excerpt from ``The
WORST-CASE SCENARIO Survival Handbook'' can help. By Joshua Piven
and David Borgenicht. WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   THEY SHOOT HORSES, DON'T THEY? WHAT TO DO IF YOU BREAK YOUR LEG
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVAL-FOR-REAL-4 _ OK, Weekend Warrior. Summer is here, and
that means it's time to be out playing basketball, softball,
tennis, soccer or whatever sport you're into this year. It also
means your chances of getting injured are pretty good. What if you
_ or one of your buddies _ breaks a leg while sliding into first or
trying to jump over the net? Be prepared. This excerpt from ``The
WORST-CASE SCENARIO Survival Guide'' explains what to do _ and what
not to do _ to treat a leg fracture. By Joshua Piven and David
Borgenicht. WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   `HE'S GOT A GUN!' HOW TO SURVIVE
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVAL-FOR-REAL-5 _ A quick scan of recent headlines will tell
you something you may not want to know: Random shootings are
becoming more and more common. Would you know what to do if you
suddenly found yourself in the line of fire? This excerpt from
``The WORST-CASE SCENARIO Survival Handbook'' offers strategies to
help you avoid becoming a victim. By Joshua Piven and David
Borgenicht. WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   CAN IT STRIKE TWICE? WHY YOU SHOULD WATCH OUT FOR LIGHTNING
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVAL-FOR-REAL-6 _ Summer is the season for thunderstorms _
complete with dangerous lightning. Lightning causes more casualties
annually in the United States than any other storm-related
phenomenon except floods. No place is completely safe from
lightning, but some are more dangerous than others. This excerpt
from ``The Worst-Case Scenario Survival Handbook'' explains how to
avoid being struck. By Joshua Piven and David Borgenicht. WITH
ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   CAUGHT IN A `TITANIC' SITUATION? HOW TO SURVIVE ADRIFT AT SEA
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVAL-FOR-REAL-7 _ It happened to Elian Gonzalez, and it
could happen to you. You're far from shore when suddenly the boat
you are in capsizes and sinks _ and you find yourself adrift at
sea. How do you stay alive? This excerpt from ``The WORST-CASE
SCENARIO Survival Handbook'' offers tips that can help you save
yourself. By Joshua Piven and David Borgenicht. WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   DIDN'T ENJOY `JAWS'? HOW TO FEND OFF A SHARK
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVAL-FOR-REAL-8 _ The movie ``Jaws'' made scores of
beach-goers afraid to dip even a big toe into the water. If you're
among the leery, you'll want to read this guide to avoiding sharks
_ and what to do if you are attacked. Even if you're not afraid,
you may want to take a peek at this excerpt from ``The WORST-CASE
SCENARIO Survival Handbook'' before diving into the waves _
because, hey, you just never know. By Joshua Piven and David
Borgenicht. WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
