<P>
   TRAVEL (moved in the ``t'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S DOING IN SAO PAULO
</P>
<P>
   SIGHTSEEING-SAO-PAULO-TRAVEL _ Superlatives come quickly to mind
when talking about Sao Paulo. With 18 million people in its
metropolitan area, this is the largest city in Brazil, the largest
in South America, indeed the largest in the Southern Hemisphere.
Those who come to Sao Paulo expecting to find a laid-back seaside
tropical resort in the style of Rio de Janeiro or Salvador are in
for a shock. Sao Paulo is a very different kind of Brazil:
aggressive, sprawling and resourceful, with a different climate,
including temperatures that can drop to near-freezing at night
during the Southern Hemisphere winter (June through September).
What to do, what to see and where to stay. By Larry Rohter. WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE THE GODS ARE NEIGHBORS
</P>
<P>
   WHERE-GODS-ARE-NEIGHBORS-TRAVEL _ ``The first time I was in the
Peloponnesus, it was midwinter, and out of the low fog that was
everywhere goatherds seemed to appear and dissolve as if in a Theo
Angelopoulos film. The narrow roads etched into the mountainside
threatened to fall off into clouds,'' writes Nicole Krauss in this
feature from The New York Times Travel section. Krauss traveled to
Peloponnesus, Greece, in June, to rent a house with a friend on the
beach with no address or phone. Here, a fascinating journal of her
experiences. By Nicole Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   THAT FLYING SENSATION
</P>
<P>
   FLYING-TRAVEL _ However unfashionable it may be to admit it,
Jerry Haines likes to fly on commuter airlines. ``I like to feel
the water when I swim, I like to taste the food when I eat, and I
like to feel as if I'm flying when I fly,'' he writes. In this
humorous feature, Haines explains his obsession. By Jerry Haines.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING AROUND: PLANNING FAMILY TRAVEL ON THE WEB
</P>
