<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2168 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     07-03 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros' rental of Unit bears no second-guessing
<TEXT>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that he will take the mound as the flamethrowing,
rocket-launching enemy capable of lighting up the sky brighter than
any star-spangled Fourth of July fireworks over Buffalo Bayou.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the smoke-belching choo-choo high on the
left-field wall will be only the second most powerful locomotive at
Enron Field once he cranks up that mighty left arm.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the breeze from the home team's bats that will likely
keep the place cooler than any air conditioning on a sultry summer
night.
</P>
<P>
   As the Astros limp into the All-Star break looking like a
collection of anything but, there are more things to question and
criticize than ants at the afternoon picnic.
</P>
<P>
   Trading for Randy Johnson two years ago isn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind what the standings say now. It was still the right
thing to do. At the time.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind how high the American League West-leading Mariners
may be on John Halama, Freddy Garcia and Carlos Guillen.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Johnson and his Arizona Diamondbacks currently
hold down first place in the National League West.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the Astros are the not-so-proud owners of the
worst record in all of the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Well, go ahead, mind that.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't take the bait and run to one of the most
simple-minded, knee-jerk arguments this side of the presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Not unless you can produce a signed, notarized letter of proof
that you stood up and jeered the Astros on July 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Not unless you can look straight in the mirror and say that not
for a moment did you cheer Johnson during his two-plus months in an
Astros uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Not unless you can swear on a stack of Mickey Mantle rookie
cards that you never once pumped your fist when Johnson rang up
another K with that bullwhip left arm, that long, stringy hair and
that vulture's stare in those anything's-possible baseball weeks in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Not unless you can stare through your Craig Biggio eye black and
say with a straight face that you never once nudged anybody on the
block or at the office and made a crack about having the Big Unit
and, thus, a big chance to go the World Series and win it all.
</P>
<P>
   Second-guesses are a part of sports. They might even be the most
fun part of sports. They are why they put bars in stools, have
call-in radio shows and give laptops to guys like me.
</P>
<P>
   If we could use second-guesses in the place of first-guesses,
surely nobody would ever have heard of New Coke, 8-track tapes and
Roseanne singing the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   But to second-guess Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker for
landing Johnson for three prospects is wrongheaded from both a
baseball viewpoint and for revisiting history.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can be Nostradamus predicting the past. If we'd have
known Jose Merengue would do the Lima Limbo this year, that Billy
Wagner would pitch nearly half a season before mentioning that his
arm hurts, sure it would have been nice to have Halama and Garcia
around on the pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, maybe somebody could have done something about
that little art school reject in Germany, too.
</P>
<P>
   But in baseball, as in life, the key is to maximize your
opportunities, and for the Astros, 1998 was it. That was the best
team in franchise history, the winner of 102 regular-season games,
and with Johnson as the ace, should have been a fearsome playoff
contender.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson delivered. He went 10-1 down the stretch with a 1.28 ERA
and struck out 116 batters in 84 innings. He was everything we had
expected or hoped he would be. He gave opponents a sense of awe,
and he gave the Astros a feeling of invincibility.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson gave up a total of three earned runs in his two playoffs
starts against the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   If Jim Leyritz doesn't turn into Reggie Jackson. If Moises Alou
isn't called out at third in Game 3. If the Killer B's weren't the
Killer Fleas again. If the Astros had been able to get over that
first-round hump, maybe they go to the World Series. And if Johnson
still walks away as a free agent, who would have said it was a bad
experience?
</P>
<P>
   Rip them for Carl Everett. Tear into them for Mike Hampton.
Question them about Brad Ausmus and even Ricky Gutierrez and Bob
Abreu.
</P>
<P>
   See through the charade of owner Drayton McLane Jr. for his
undervalued lip-service offer that was never going to turn
Johnson's head away from Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   But don't fall for the cheapest, easiest second-guess of all.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Rent-a-Unit was the biggest, boldest gamble and the
right move. At the time.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
