<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2170 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-SCARY-WAYANS-COX     07-03 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCARY-WAYANS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't look for social messages in 'Scary Movie'
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH _ Never doubt that Shawn and Marlon Wayans know
exactly what they have created. ``Look, this is one of those movies
where you're supposed to check your brain at the door and come
laugh,'' proclaims Shawn, 29, who is 18 months older than his
writing and acting partner sibling. The movie in question is
``Scary Movie,'' a spoof of the teen slasher genre and just about
every other successful film of the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't sit there and try to overanalyze,'' he adds of the
teen-targeted release due in area theaters this Friday. ``This is
not a thinker's movie. You're coming to laugh, and you will
laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wayanses first emerged into public consciousness in 1990, as
utility players in their family's television showcase ``In Living
Color,'' which made a star of older brother Keenen Ivory Wayans,
who directs ``Scary Movie.'' Six years later, Shawn and Marlon
tried their hands at feature films, writing, producing and acting
in an overstuffed parody of black ghetto gang movies, ``Don't Be a
Menace to South Central While Drinking Your Juice in the Hood. ''
</P>
<P>
   For a follow-up, they knew they wanted to spoof the slasher
horror genre and gave their script the title ``Last Summer I
Screamed Because Friday the 13th Fell on Halloween.`` Eventually,
more humor-challenged heads prevailed and the name changed to
``Scary Movie, '' which slasher film fans will recognize as the
original title of ``Scream.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wayans brothers consider themselves slasher fans. ``So much
so that we decided to end them all,'' says Marlon, kicking back on
a couch in a trendy South Beach hotel. ``We decided to kill off all
these young white teens, so we could kill off these movies once and
for all.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that they want to make this a racial thing, but the Wayanses
have noticed there usually aren't many blacks in horror movies. ``I
think it's partly Hollywood, but I think it's also that black
people _ women and men _ are a little too smart to be in those
situations without using their common sense,'' notes Marlon.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up on the comic jab, Shawn adds his own follow-up punch.
``If they heard someone or something at the door, they would get a
gun and blow him away,'' he says, insisting that that was the
original plot of ``Scary Movie,'' but it was abandoned when they
realized it would only be two minutes long from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   So don't look for social messages in ``Scary Movie. ''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, you left your brains at the concession stand. ``This
movie is just a movie,'' says Shawn. ``It's just a comedy, it's not
a black comedy. It's a general response to the movies.''
</P>
<P>
   The two of them made the ultimate sacrifice in the name of
research for their script. To lampoon them, they watched slasher
movies over and over again. ``We watched `Scream' until we wanted
to scream,'' howls Shawn. `` `I Know What You Did Last Summer', but
I don't give a damn.'' (OK, he used an Anglo-Saxon action noun that
is a lot stronger than ``damn.'') ``I can't ever see that movie
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, none of those movies improved with multiple
viewings. ``Nothing made me go, after I've watched it a hundred
times, `Now I really like, uh, Urban Legend.'''
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, the plot of ''Scary Movi'' concerns the
brutal murder of a scantily clad co-ed, whose clueless friends soon
find themselves the targets of a persistent killer. Along the way,
the parody net widens to include spoofs of ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' ``The Usual Suspects'' and ``The Matrix,'' to name a
few.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every parody movie we've ever done, we've always gone outside
the regular genre,'' says Shawn. ``Because you've got to have pop
culture involved in everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have different levels of humor,'' chimes in
Marlon. ``So even people who didn't see ``Scream,'' they'll get
something to laugh at, to enjoy. You've got to pack it.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly one level of ``Scary Movie's'' comedy is lowly
gross-out humor. Suffice it to say, the Wayans outdo the hair gel
scene of ``There's Something About Mary. ''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't put gross-out stuff just to gross you out,'' insists
Shawn. ``It is over the top, but every gross-out thing has to do
with character.'' Shawn looks at Marlon, Marlon looks back at Shawn
and they both burst out laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New York City, Shawn and Marlon are two of 10 children
born to a salesman and a housewife, parents who both helped shape
their senses of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely,'' agrees Marlon. ``My dad is silly and my mom is
funny. My dad ain't funny, he's silly. He was acting silly, got my
mom mad, they had sex and here we are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mom is funnier when she's angry,'' says Shawn, adding that
it wouldn't take much to get her angry. ``It's my father. All he
had to do is walk into the house. It was instantaneous. She'd look
at him and go, `You made me pregnant with 10 kids and you've got a
job that only pays $10,000 a year.' She's very funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the jokes, there is a strong family bond among the
Wayanses, and Shawn and Marlon clearly idolize their oldest brother
Keenen, their comedy mentor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comedy is what he does, and he taught us everything we know,''
says Shawn. ``We kind of look to him as like the guru. Usually
we'll get an idea and we'll go, `Yo, Keenan, what do you think of
this?' and he'll go, `Yeah, that's good, but if you did this ...'
and we go away and work on it some more. Every draft, it gets
better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up for Shawn and Marlon is likely to be their animated
parody of ``Antz'' and ``A Bug's Life.'' Their title? ``Roaches.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, in our world each bug represents a different
race,'' says Marlon. ``So it's an interracial romance between a
roach and a wasp.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like `West Side Story' for bugs,'' adds Shawn.
</P>
<P>
   Their futures do not depend on how well ``Scary Movie'' opens
this weekend, but it would help.
</P>
<P>
   Come Friday, they will have their cell phones poised, as they
wait for reports of the box office grosses. ``Having the champagne
on ice, just in case,'' says Marlon.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the guns and the razor blades, just in case,'' counters
Shawn.
</P>
<P>
   haperstein(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
