<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2177 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-LILY-TOMLIN-IN-THE-KI     07-03 1398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILY-TOMLIN-IN-THE-KID-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`KID' STUFF: LILY TOMLIN IS BACK ON THE BIG SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Lily Tomlin with Bruce Willis in a scene
from ``The Kid.'') 
 By JEANNE WOLF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Jon Turteltaub has directed Anthony Hopkins, John Travolta,
Sandra Bullock and Robert Duvall. His latest movie, ``The Kid,''
stars megastar Bruce Willis.
 &HT;    But when he had an anxiety attack at the thought of meeting an
actor, it was Lily Tomlin.
 &HT;    ``I was really nervous,'' the director says, ``because I
remembered seeing her show, `The Search for Signs of Intelligent
Life in the Universe,' on Broadway, and I had never seen anything
better.
 &HT;    ``When Lily came on the set, I said to her, `You are a comic
genius, I loved you on `Laugh-In' _ just tell me what's funny.'''
 &HT;    Hearing this story, Tomlin giggles. She was just as nervous, she
says, about undertaking her largest movie role in years.
 &HT;    ``Fortunately Jon is like a big kid,'' she says, ``and so
playful that he made it easy to be funny.''
 &HT;    Tomlin has been being funny since even before she first got
famous on ``Laugh-In,'' the seminal 1960s television program in
which she played Ernestine, the irrepressibly impudent telephone
operator, and Edith Ann, that precocious and devilish 5-year-old.
 &HT;    Three decades and a shelf full of Emmys and Tonys later, she
finds herself cast opposite Willis _ who plays the kind of tough
boss that Tomlin tamed in ``Nine to Five'' (1980) _ as his
no-nonsense executive assistant, whose awesome organizational
skills keep his schedule, if not his personal life, on track.
 &HT;    Working with Willis was no problem, the actress says.
 &HT;    ``I've admired him ever since I saw him on `Moonlighting,''' she
says. ``He was charismatic and sexy, and also twinkly and likeable.
When we got together to talk about the movie he was wearing jeans
and a ball cap, and we just started playing around.
 &HT;    ``I know Bruce is an enormous star,'' she adds, ``but he's a
pretty reachable guy. He's accessible. He was everything I expected
him to be, and the best part is that he doesn't take himself too
seriously.
 &HT;    ``I guess in real life he would actually be a good boss.''
 &HT;    It's been a while, but Tomlin still winces at the memory of her
own experience as an office worker.
 &HT;    ``I was the executive assistant for a man in New York who later
became the head of ICM (the prominent artist-management firm),''
she recalls. ``Actually, I was sort of the office flunky, and the
other three women in the office just tortured me. I was a hippie in
burlap skirts and T-shirts, and the women in the office were all
the opposite of me, with long fingernails and bubble hairdos.''
 &HT;    In ``The Kid,'' which will open nationwide on July 7, Tomlin's
character doesn't suffer in silence, keeping her workaholic boss on
his toes with sarcasm and wisecracks.
 &HT;    ``I think my character has a real affection for him,'' the
actress says, ``and she believes that there's a better man inside
him waiting to get out. I'm waiting for that guy to turn the
corner, you know.''
 &HT;    The cue for that change is the arrival of the titular kid
(Spencer Breslin), who through a supernatural twist turns out to be
Willis' character at the age of 8. Against his will, the
high-powered executive finds himself forced to relive the struggles
of his childhood.
 &HT;    That wouldn't be easy for anyone, says Tomlin, who isn't sure
how she's react if she had to confront her 8-year-old self.
 &HT;    ``I would see a kid who still thinks she's pretty great,'' she
muses. ``She wasn't focusing on any problems in her life.''
 &HT;    Tomlin grew up in a blue-collar family in Detroit, not quite
poor but not too far from the brink, either.
 &HT;    ``My mother was very motherly,'' she says, ``but my dad loved to
go to the racetrack. I'd go with him and hang out at the bar
sometimes, but I'd also go to my mother's Tupperware parties.''
 &HT;    Her world was full of people from diverse backgrounds, which
surely enhanced Tomlin's emerging talent to create memorable
characters.
 &HT;    ``We lived in an old apartment house,'' she recalls, ``and it
was full of different kinds of people, all of them were either on
their way up or on their way down. In every single apartment there
was a different kind of life going on, from a different culture. I
soaked it up. Whatever they were doing, I did _ I was always
imitating people.
 &HT;    ``I loved to do shows, to perform for people,'' Tomlin says. ``I
would steal material from television comedians like Jean Carroll,
one of the first female stand-ups who appeared on `The Ed Sullivan
Show.' I stole all of her jokes about her husband.''
 &HT;    When she wasn't performing for the neighborhood, Tomlin was
turning her ability to convey different characters into the chance
to make a few bucks.
 &HT;    ``I had a babysitting business when I was 10,'' she says,
``because I had such an air of competence. I remember one New
Year's Eve when I was 12, I was watching like 16 children. I hired
my girlfriend for $2 to help. Can you imagine? Sixteen children
with a girl who was really just a kid.
 &HT;    ``I guess that's the closest I've ever gotten to the character I
play in `The Kid,''' she adds with a grin. ``As a little girl, I
was very well-organized. Since then I've had assistants who were.
They're also much funnier than I am, quicker with a comeback and
very sarcastic.''
 &HT;    Once one of the most innovative stand-up comedians of her
generation, Tomlin seems alienated from the comedy of today.
 &HT;    ``I personally like humor that is perceptive and, ultimately,
makes you and everyone else feel a little bit better,'' she says,
``rather than loathe yourself and everybody else.
 &HT;    ``I think what's considered to be ground-breaking in comedy
today really seems to be coming out of some sort of profound
repression,'' Tomlin says. ``It's very adolescent and immature. I
remember, when one of the sitcoms first got the word `fart' on TV,
they made a big fuss about it. It was like, `How hip are we?' I
don't see that as ground-breaking at all.
 &HT;    ``Fifteen years ago, in `The Search for Signs of Intelligent
Life in the Universe,''' she continues, ``Jane Wagner wrote a line
for me _ `No matter how cynical you are, it's never enough to keep
up.' I've seen that line quoted over and over. And there's another
one: `I worry that today's reality check is yesterday's culture
shock.'
 &HT;    ``That was written 15 years ago,'' she concludes, ``and now it's
out of control. I think we're just being dumbed down and debased.
Kids are cynical at a younger and younger age.''
 &HT;    In such a climate, she says, a film like ``The Kid'' _ with its
anti-cynical message of hope _ might be all too timely.
 &HT;    ``What I love is that Bruce's character is cut off emotionally
and totally caught up by his ambition,'' she says. ``He's cold,
impersonal and hard-edged. But then, by going back to that little
kid, himself, that he loathed, he breaks through that armor.
 &HT;    ``I wish we could all do that,'' the actress concludes. ``I wish
we were all more soft and tender, toward ourselves and everyone
else.''
 c.2000 Pentacom Productions  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jeanne Wolf is a Hollywood-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Kid,'' consult the
official Web site at www.disneysthekid.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
