<HEADER>
A2178 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-JUDE-LAW-IN-THE-WISDO     07-03 1411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDE-LAW-IN-THE-WISDOM-OF-CROCODILES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULE OF LAW: AFTER THE OSCARS, JUDE LAW IS RIDING HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Jude Law in a scene from ``The Wisdom of
Crocodiles.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    When Jude Law looks in a mirror, he doesn't see a sex symbol
looking back.
 &HT;    ``I see the dark circles under the eyes,'' the British actor
says. ``I see the sunburned skin. I see someone who might have made
a mistake when he cut his hair in the bathroom by himself. I also
see a guy who looks like he could use a few extra hours of sleep.
 &HT;    ``I'm not a sex symbol.''
 &HT;    Thousands of admiring women beg to differ, but as he relaxes in
a suite at Los Angeles' Four Seasons hotel, Law seems entirely
sincere in his protestations. He doesn't think he's sexy, and
doesn't want to.
 &HT;    ``Being sexy is basically something I can't think about,'' he
explains, ``or I'll be doomed to spending two hours in the mirror
before I get out of the house. And, frankly, if I monopolized the
bathroom, my wife and sons would want to kill me.''
 &HT;    Law has been on something of a roll lately, following up
critically lauded performances in ``Gattaca'' (1997) and ``Wilde''
(1998) with ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' (1999), in which he played
a 1950s expatriate-American golden boy so effectively that he
snagged an Academy Award nomination as Best Supporting Actor for
his pains.
 &HT;    As he passes through the hallways of the Four Seasons, no one
seems to connect the soft-spoken Englishman, rail-thin in khaki
pants and a matching green sweater, with the impossibly buff Dickie
Greenleaf he portrayed in ``Mr. Ripley'' _ which is just fine with
him.
 &HT;    ``My reality is my family,'' the 28-year-old actor says. ``It's
my wife and sons. I'm old enough to know that fame is not the
secret to happiness.''
 &HT;    Law's latest movie opens nationwide on July 14, but it's not the
high-profile, big-budget fare most Oscar nominees turn to in an
effort to cash in.
 &HT;    Instead Law picked the low-budget erotic thriller ``The Wisdom
of Crocodiles,'' an offbeat riff on Oscar Wilde's ``The Portrait of
Dorian Gray.'' Law plays Steven Grlscz, a handsome, successful,
witty man who easily seduces women _ and then kills them. He is
bloodthirsty, literally, and may be a vampire.
 &HT;    ``He's a man with a lot of peculiar traits,'' Law says. ``I want
to play men you can't neatly put into a file folder with a label on
them. And this character fits, because he keeps audiences
guessing.''
 &HT;    ``Mr. Ripley'' kept them guessing as well, to the tune of $100
million at the box office _ which came as a surprise to Law.
 &HT;    ``I loved the movie,'' the actor says, ``but, then again, I
always love my movies. For years I've heard people say, `Jude, this
is your breakout role' _ it's always your breakout role. So my
standard response with every movie now is, `Let's wait and see what
happens.'''
 &HT;    Otherwise, he says, the disappointment can be unbearable.
 &HT;    ``You buy into the buzz,'' he says. ``For instance, when I did
`Gattaca' (1997), I kept hearing, `This is it for you.' I thought,
`My God, this is going to be huge.'
 &HT;    ``Listen, I'm still waiting for that movie to happen for me,''
he jokes. ``Maybe it's huge on video.''
 &HT;    ``Mr. Ripley,'' which co-starred Matt Damon and Gwyneth Paltrow,
actually was huge. In fact, the degree of attention it has brought
him is rather off-putting, the English actor says.
 &HT;    ``I've never wanted fame,'' he insists. ``I'm an actor because I
enjoy acting. And it has been that way since I was a child _ my
parents were acting teachers who ran a theater company on and off
in Italy, so they taught me to take it very seriously.''
 &HT;    His parents were serious enough to name their son after the
death-obsessed protagonist of Thomas Hardy's classic ``Jude the
Obscure,'' but lighthearted enough also to have been influenced by
the Beatles song ``Hey, Jude,'' with its message of hope and
consolation.
 &HT;    Law was only 3 when his parents first began taking him to the
London theater, but he was immediately captivated.
 &HT;    ``I just remember sitting there and responding to the
emotions,'' he says. ``I didn't understand exactly what was
happening on stage, but I knew the feelings of love and anger and
rage.''
 &HT;    By age 5, he was on school stages. He's rarely stepped offstage
since.
 &HT;    ``The minute I was put on stage, I felt like I had come home,''
he says. ``I suppose it's the same way an athlete feels on the
field. I felt like I had done this thing about a million times. It
felt natural to me to be on stage. I understood what I should do up
there _ it was where I belonged.''
 &HT;    Youthful roles with the National Youth Music Theater led to work
with the National Theatre, and at 16 Law dropped out of high school
to act full-time.
 &HT;    His first adult job was on the British soaper ``Families.'' Law
went on to tour Europe in Shaw's ``Pygmalion,'' then originated the
role of Michael in ``Les Parents Terribles,'' which came to
Broadway as ``Indiscretions'' (1995) and earned Law a Tony
nomination.
 &HT;    Oh, and he also caught quite a few people's eyes in the second
act, when he stepped out of a bathtub buck naked.
 &HT;    ``Gattaca'' and a role as a murdered bisexual hustler in
``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil'' (1997) followed. His
performance as the tempestuous Lord Alfred Douglas earned rave
reviews in ``Wilde'' (1998), but the film was scarcely seen.
 &HT;    And then came ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' _ and another nude
scene, which certainly didn't hurt his appeal to the younger
females in the audience.
 &HT;    ``Face it, I didn't become a star until I took my clothes off
for `Ripley,''' he jokes.
 &HT;    ``I didn't have any trepidation about it,'' he says more
seriously. ``Frankly, being naked in plays is far more horrifying,
because those theaters are always so chilly.
 &HT;    ``Seriously, I'm not a great fan of doing love scenes,'' Law
adds. ``I don't like seeing naked bodies rolling around. But I do
think nudity to a degree can aid dramatic intention. In `Ripley' I
must get out of a tub _ I can't be wearing swimming trunks. I mean,
please! We're all grownups.''
 &HT;    Next up is Steven Spielberg's ``A.I.,'' about a boy robot (Haley
Joel Osment) in the 21st century. Law also recently wrapped
Jean-Jacques Annaud's ``Enemy at the Gates,'' a thriller
co-starring Ed Harris.
 &HT;    Offscreen, he spends time with his wife, actress Sadie Frost.
The two met in 1994 while filming the British film ``Shopping,''
and she's the inspiration for the tattoo on Law's left arm: ``Sexy
Sadie.''
 &HT;    The two live quietly in London with their children, Rafferty and
Findlay, also finding time to operate Natural Nylon, a production
company they co-founded with two old friends, actors Ewan McGregor
and Jonny Lee Miller.
 &HT;    ``All of us blokes would pool our money in the poor days and
split a plate of fish and chips,'' he recalls.
 &HT;    Now he can afford to buy his own lunch, but otherwise life is
much as it was then, Law says.
 &HT;    ``I'm just that actor who lives down the street,'' Law says. ``I
don't let that other stuff get in the way of living a normal
life.''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
