<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SARAH-JESSICA-PARKER-IN-SEX-AND-THE-CITY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SEX' APPEAL: SARAH JESSICA PARKER ON SEX, THE CITY AND A WHOLE LOT
MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Sarah Jessica Parker with Cynthia Nixon,
Kristin Davis and Kim Cattrall in a scene from ``Sex and the
City.'') 
 By KEVIN DICKSON  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be printed in Canada before July 23. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There is nothing better than rolling out of bed and going to
work,'' Sarah Jessica Parker says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true for Parker, since for her going to work
often involves rolling back into bed _ and rarely alone.
</P>
<P>
   As Carrie Bradshaw, ``Sex and the City's'' wistfully wanton
journaliste d'amour, Parker enjoys fame, fortune and a dream
wardrobe, along with critical bouquets and plenty of time off for
feature-film or stage roles. But for this unabashed New Yorker, the
real treat is the show's location shoots, featuring the city which
she claims is the real star of the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York City is as integral a character as any of the women
on the show,'' she says enthusiastically. ``Otherwise it's not `Sex
and the City.' It's the greatest thing in the world to shoot in New
York City. It's the most romantic, most exciting, most challenging
and most problematic, but ultimately the most satisfying,
especially if you are a New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   The satisfaction is showing _ and nobody is faking it. From New
York to Vancouver, from London to Paris to Sydney, ``Sex and the
City'' has become a television phenomenon of the same magnitude as
its HBO stablemate, ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   And, like the men that Carrie and her cohorts Samantha (Kim
Cattrall), Charlotte (Kristin Davis) and Miranda (Cynthia Nixon)
dream of, the series is rising to the occasion and improving with
age. This third season has seen a considerable deepening of the
emotional textures of the women, without sacrificing any laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Settling down for a quick chat backstage at a Los Angeles awards
show, the 35-year-old Parker shakes her head and looks
simultaneously thrilled and dumbfounded at the show's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very surprised by any success that `Sex and the City'
has had,'' she says. ``It's really been this unexpected, thrilling,
idyllic experience from day one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try not to ponder too much about the show and what people
find resonant,'' Parker adds. ``We're scared to make a show we
think people will respond to. We really just try to tell the story
and produce the best television show we can make, and hope that
people still feel connected to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The central characters' lives continue to evolve, the actress
says, which is one of her favorite things about the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, some things are subtle and some are nuanced and
there are some really amazing surprises that ... '' she trails off,
then resumes at full throttle. ``I'm kind of in the middle of a
story line right now that I can't really believe and I love! I call
my best friend all the time, and I'm kind of like, `Oh my God, I
can't believe what they are going to do now!' Because it is really,
really exciting _ at least for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But everything that happened last season to these women will
inform all the choices they make this year,'' she adds. ``My
character has been hurt and disappointed, and I think she's
resolved as to what that relationship with Mr. Big was. I think New
York has a lot of opportunity and potential, and she's looking for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for it? The ``Sex and the City'' girls seek opportunity
the way Indiana Jones hunts ancient treasure. Rumors abound that
the remainder of the third season will include a wedding _ but
whose? _ and two or three episodes shot in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that's already happened is the return to television of
film actor Kyle McLachlan, still best known as the dogged Agent
Cooper on the cult-classic ``Twin Peaks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's great on the show and great fun,'' Parker says
cheerfully. ``A very nice addition for us this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Her onscreen persona may be television's most prominent single
woman, but offscreen Parker is happily married to actor Matthew
Broderick. Furthermore, she says, even before marrying she was
never as relentlessly single as Carrie. She briefly dated John F.
Kennedy Jr. and Chris Penn before beginning a one-year relationship
with Nicolas Cage, and for seven years dated troubled talent Robert
Downey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   It was Downey's drug use, which she recalls as being
``incredibly difficult to deal with,'' which ultimately ended their
relationship, Parker says.
</P>
<P>
   Accentuating the distance between the onscreen Carrie and the
offscreen Parker is the fact that, in real life, Parker disdains
swearing and is so modest that she insisted that her contract
stipulate that she would not appear nude on ``Sex and the City.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not a moral judgment,'' she says. ``It's not about `I
am pure and good and they are bad.' It's just the way I choose to
communicate with my friends, and the choice of language I choose to
use. And I think that Kim Cattrall and Cynthia Nixon _ there was a
certain comfort level with language that they have on certain
things that I just don't, and they do it beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think it's much better-suited to them,'' she adds. ``I
couldn't pull it off, frankly.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she is very different from her character, Parker hastens
to add that she doesn't dislike her.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot that I admire about Carrie,'' the actress says.
``She lives in a way that I've never lived, but that doesn't mean
that I don't like her. I'm actually very fond of her, fonder than I
thought I would be, although there's just so little about her that
I relate to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never been part of a circle of friends like Carrie
has,'' Parker says. ``My social life has always been much less
public. I've never been somebody that frequented clubs or
experimented. I didn't display comfort with sexuality the same way
she does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I'm awed and fascinated by It, and it's great fun
to play, I don't relate to it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker pauses briefly, shaking her head in thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day I am not entirely positive that the other women
exist,'' she says. ``I don't know if they are not fictional
characters that she makes up for her column. I don't know if she
has all those shoes. I don't know if she has a Fendi bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never talked to the writers about this,'' she adds with a
laugh, ``because I don't want to know. I don't want them to ponder
it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Kevin Dickson is a Los Angeles-based correspondent for TV
Guide Canada.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Sex and the City,'' consult
the official Web site at www.hbo.com/city. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
