<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2180 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-FAMKE-JANSSEN-IN-X-ME     07-03 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMKE-JANSSEN-IN-X-MEN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
X-CEPTIONAL: FAMKE JANSSEN IS AN X-MAN WITH A MIND OF HER OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Famke Janssen in a scene from
``X-Men.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Famke Janssen was exasperated.
 &HT;    Soon after relocating from her native Holland to the United
States in 1984, she had ditched a lucrative career as a model to
pursue acting and to study writing and literature at Columbia
University in New York.
 &HT;    But she was going nowhere fast, and there were moments when the
statuesque and smart Janssen _ she stands 5-foot-11 and can
converse in English, Dutch, German and French _ began to seriously
question her decision.
 &HT;    ``Moments?'' she says. ``Years! It was the hardest time of my
life. Every morning I would wake up and it seemed to me that every
single person in the world was saying to me, `Stop doing this!
You're not making any money. Nobody wants to hire you.'
 &HT;    ``But I'd say to myself, `You can do it,''' she recalls. ``And I
did that for years. It was really hard. It's a competitive world,
very competitive.''
 &HT;    Janssen hung in there, and eventually landed work. By 1992 she
had guest-starred in an episode of ``Star Trek: The Next
Generation'' and made her film debut in the drama ``Fathers and
Sons.'' She got her first taste of stardom in 1995, when she played
a bad Bond girl, the memorably monikered Xenia Onatopp, in the hit
007 adventure ``Goldeneye.''
 &HT;    Since then Janssen has mixed it up, gracing major studio
releases and independent features of varying genres. Her resume
includes ``Lord of Illusions'' (1995), ``The Gingerbread Man''
(1997), ``City of Industry'' (1997), ``Rounders'' (1998),
``Monument Avenue'' (1998), ``The Faculty'' (1998), ``Celebrity''
(1998) and ``The House on Haunted Hill'' (1999).
 &HT;    On July 14 Janssen will return to the screen in ``X-Men,'' an
event movie that, like ``Goldeneye,'' could turbocharge her career.
Based on the long-running Marvel Comics series and directed by
Bryan Singer, ``X-Men'' features an eclectic ensemble cast that
includes Ian McKellen, Patrick Stewart, Anna Paquin, Halle Berry,
James Marsden, Hugh Jackman and Janssen as Jean Grey, a mutant with
both telepathic and telekinetic abilities.
 &HT;    ``Patrick Stewart's character, Professor X, runs this school of
mutants,'' Janssen says, speaking by telephone from her New York
apartment. ``Some of us are students and some of us are people
who've gone through there and are now teachers. So we're the X-Men,
who have special powers and are more developed.
 &HT;    ``At the school,'' she continues, ``the professor teaches us how
to control those powers, and what the movie deals with is the X-Men
versus the Brotherhood. The Brotherhood are mutants, led by Ian
McKellen, who have not really learned how to control their powers,
and they're taking advantage of them and abusing them. So we fight
them.
 &HT;    ``And then I have a whole love triangle between Jean Grey,
Wolverine (Jackman) and Cyclops (Marsden), both of whom are
X-Men.''
 &HT;    Singer went to great lengths to stay true to the ``Uncanny
X-Men'' comic book and its ``Who are the true outsiders?'' theme,
Janssen says. At the same time, however, the director strove to
avoid the over-the-top garishness, stunt casting and plot
contrivances that derailed the later ``Superman'' and ``Batman''
features.
 &HT;    ``He wanted to make it all real,'' says the actress, whose
character doesn't fly, can't shoot beams from her eyes and rarely
gets physical. ``He wanted everything about it to be real. In the
past, comic-book-based movies were a lot more fantastical.
 &HT;    ``To make a comic-book movie more realistic is a much bigger
challenge and more interesting,'' she says. ``It seems to me that
people can relate to it more if it's realistic.
 &HT;    ``But we'll see _ it's all up to the audience and how they feel
about it.''
 &HT;    Bottom line, Janssen stresses, ``X-Men'' is big summer
entertainment that delivers action along with a bit of romance and
a laugh or two. It's also got something to say about tolerance _
which, she hastens to add, should not be mistaken for a message.
 &HT;    ``I don't like message movies,'' Janssen says. ``I don't know
that movies ought to have a message. It's sort of a myth in
Hollywood that you have to have a message.
 &HT;    ``If a movie is a reflection of life and life is very harsh,
then that's enough.''
 &HT;    Though she's signed for an ``X-Men'' sequel, Janssen's next
films are as different from ``X-Men'' as possible. In the
independent feature ``Love &AMP; Sex,'' due out in August, Janssen
plays Kate Welles, a writer who revisits the gory details of her
love life when given 24 hours to pen a magazine article about the
perfect relationship. Jon Favreau co-stars in the dark romantic
comedy as Kate's most recent ex-boyfriend.
 &HT;    Favreau also figures prominently in Janssen's next film,
``Made.'' Directed by Favreau and co-starring Favreau and Vince
Vaughn, the Mafia-oriented comedy is a follow-up of sorts to the
sleeper hit ``Swingers'' (1996).
 &HT;    It seems as if it's all going according to plan for Janssen.
Still, she's paid a price for her reluctance to cash in, for her
desire not to win roles based solely on her looks.
 &HT;    ``I probably could have been a bigger star, maybe, for a moment
in time,'' says Janssen, who is 35 and single. ``But not for the
long run.
 &HT;    ``What I've tried to do is be taken seriously by the people in
the business, work with good directors and do different types of
roles,'' she says, ``so that people can see that I have some range
and don't have to be just some pretty girl in an action movie. I
think, in that respect, I've succeeded.
 &HT;    ``At some point you want to move on and play leads in movies,''
Janssen concludes. ``I've done that with `Love &AMP; Sex,' and it will
be up to the success or failure of that movie to see what happens
in terms of my career. But `Love &AMP; Sex' was a big step for me.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
