<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHIS-PETTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KYLE PETTY OPTS OUT OF N.H. 300 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM KALEC  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kyle Petty, who was scheduled to run his No. 44 Hot Wheels
Pontiac in this weekend's New Hampshire 300 in Loudon, N.H., has
decided not to participate, Petty Enterprises announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle's son Adam was killed in a crash at New Hampshire
International Speedway May 12 while preparing for a Busch Series
race; Sunday's Winston Cup event would have been the first at
Loudon since that weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Dennison of Petty Enterprises told the Associated Press,
``He just didn't feel comfortable. They decided it would be better
just to take a week off.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennison said Petty would return for the circuit's next event,
July 23 at Pocono Raceway in Long Pond, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Grissom, who races in the NASCAR Craftsman Truck series
for Petty Enterprises, will take Petty's place Sunday and also run
in the Craftsman Truck Series New Hampshire 200 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   NHIS president Gary Bahre said, ``We didn't really know one way
or the other, but we are not necessarily surprised at this
decision. It is obivous that this was a difficult situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that (Grissom) has been a very capable race car driver
and has done good things for their team.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Globe last Thursday at Daytona (Fla.)
International Speedway, Petty said, `Sometimes you think about it,
and that's why I say, `Do I want to go back?' Yeah, I want to go
back at some point in time just to tell everybody how much I
appreciate everything they did for Adam.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty is 34th in the Winston Cup standings with 1,124 points. He
has started 14 races, with his only top 10 finish coming April 16
in the DieHard 500 at Talladega (Ala.) Superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   Stock car legend Richard Petty, Kyle's father, also will not
make the trip to New Hampshire this weekend; he had already had
vacation plans.
</P>
<P>
   Following this weekend's action, NHIS will host another Winston
Cup event Sept. 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
