<HEADER>
A2186 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-LEDGER-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      07-03 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEDGER-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSSIE ACTOR HAS STAR CHARISMA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year at this time, Heath Ledger was one phone call away
from packing up his bags, returning to his native Australia and
resuming what had been a successful acting career _ successful,
that is, until he came to the States.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the phone call, courtesy of director Roland Emmerich,
and Ledger was cast in the Revolutionary War epic ``The Patriot,''
playing opposite Australian icon Mel Gibson. Now the only travel
plans Ledger makes revolve around movie projects. He's just back
from Prague, where he's making ``A Knight's Tale,'' another
medieval adventure set for a high-profile opening next summer. Next
up will be the fourth remake of the classic adventure ``The Four
Feathers.''
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a 21-year-old who had been inundated with nothing
but teen movie scripts after making a strong impression last year
in ``10 Things I Hate About You.'' His name not withstanding (Heath
is short for Heathcliff; his mom has a thing for ``Wuthering
Heights''), Ledger isn't much for mush. For a year after finishing
``10 Things,'' he turned down dozens of movies aimed at the
Clearasil set, waiting for a film that he ``would be in love
with.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long year,'' Ledger says, his Aussie accent still
very much intact. ``I went out for jobs that I probably shouldn't
have been going for, things that had another 30 or 40 actors ahead
of me. But I wanted to give it a shot. And I got very close on a
lot of great projects, very close, and then the rug just always was
pulled out from underneath my feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledger was so determined there would be no rug-pulling with
``The Patriot,'' he nearly accomplished the job himself. When he
met with Emmerich (``Independence Day,'' ``Godzilla'') and his
producing partner Dean Devlin, Ledger stopped midway through
reading a scene, apologized to the filmmakers for wasting their
time and walked out of the audition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I had blown my last chance,'' Ledger says. ``And I
was tired from the whole year and I didn't feel like taking it to a
place where I'd almost get the part and then see it go to someone
else. That's why I left. But Roland and Dean must have liked
something about me; either that, or they were curious about what
kind of fool would walk out on an audition like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Devlin admits he and Emmerich were intrigued.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Heath is that he has the one quality that's
hard to find in most young actors, and that's the quality of being
a man,'' Devlin says. ``Most 21-year-olds still feel like boys.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ledger's role in ``The Patriot'' called for a mixture of
impetuousness and composure, a blend that suits the young actor to
a T. In the Revolutionary War film, Ledger plays Gabriel, Gibson's
headstrong son, a young man who enlists in the Continental Army
against his father's wishes. For Gabriel, patriotism comes before
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gabriel represents the new generation and has all the idealism
that goes along with that,'' Ledger says.
</P>
<P>
   The reason behind Ledger's own maturity isn't difficult to
pinpoint. After growing up in rough-and-tumble Perth and getting
his feet wet acting in local theater productions, Ledger decided to
hop in a car with his best friend and move to Sydney. He was 16 at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The train of life was just flying by and I had to jump on
it,'' Ledger says. ``I had 69 cents in my bank account and a bit of
cash that my folks gave me. Looking back, I'm amazed that my
parents were lenient and understanding about letting me follow my
dreams. But I was a kid who was going to do it anyway. It was
either going to be the hard way or the easy way, and I think they
knew that.''
</P>
<P>
   The easy way turned out to be, well, pretty easy, at least at
first. Ledger won parts on two Australian dramas and a sitcom and
then landed the lead on a short-lived, swashbuckling Fox television
series called ``Roar.'' He moved to Los Angeles when he turned 19,
and landed ``10 Things,'' winning the heart of Julia Stiles (and
young female moviegoers) playing the rogueish Patrick Verona.
</P>
<P>
   So when rejection came (and it came often after ``10 Things''),
Ledger didn't have much experience dealing with failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating, but it's all part of the journey, you
know,'' Ledger says. ``And I don't know how long this journey is
going to last, but I'm having a lot of fun right now.''
</P>
<P>
   That casual attitude trickles down to other areas of Ledger's
life, most notably his grooming and attire, which takes artful
dishevelment to new heights. Ledger's hobbies include photography
and tap dancing, the latter a nod to his movie hero, Gene Kelly.
His dream assignment would be to remake one of Kelly's old films,
with ``The Pirate'' being his top choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelly wasn't the greatest actor and he wasn't a great
singer,'' Ledger says. ``But boy could he dance. And he had such a
strong spirit. He could bring light to the screen and just fill it
up. I remind myself of his spirit sometimes when I need to push
through on a particular scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledger may have been thinking of Kelly when he showed up on the
first day of shooting for ``The Patriot.'' He admits he was
initially ``hopeless,'' and needed to grab hold of any inspiration
he could find.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see he had a reverence for Mel because Mel is so big
in Australia,'' Emmerich says. ``I think Heath went home that first
day a nervous wreck; he was so disappointed in himself. But he was
actually pretty good that day, although you wouldn't be able to
tell him that.''
</P>
<P>
   No, you wouldn't. Ledger calls himself his ``own worst critic,''
but he cuts himself some slack, too, saying that he calmed down
once Gibson put him at ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I just soaked up as much information as I could,''
Ledger says. ``Mel is a lovely, lovely man, and that's surprising
because I know not everyone in his position is as friendly as he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Ledger's own position is loftier, he's being courted
for some more high-profile projects, including the ``Spider-Man''
feature film. But Ledger says he's not cut out to be an action
star.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't really interest me,'' Ledger says. ``Too many
action movies are just slapped together and the action always comes
before the story. Look at the last `Star Wars.' It just sucked. It
seemed like it was created just to sell merchandise and video
games. That's not the kind of thing I want to waste my time with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
