A2192 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     07-03 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINGIS, WILLIAMS ENCOUNTER WOULD BE HERCULEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Hercules, the old Greek bodybuilding champ, surely
would sympathize with a little kid named Martina Hingis, wandering
the dangerous grassland of Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   He had to deal with the deadly Hydra, a multiheaded sea monster.
Hingis may have the tougher prospect: coping with the dual-visaged
head-breaker named Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis has been able to handle one-half of the towering,
glowering menace but never the total package: Venus and Serena in
succession. Hingis knows how Hercules felt. When he axed one of the
Hydra's heads, two grew in its place. If she chops down one
Williams, one more springs up in her face, thirsting for familial
revenge. And getting it.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Wimbledon proposition confronting the No. 1 female
tennis toiler on earth as Venus and Serena plot an earthquake for
her. This all came about on a customary afternoon at the Big W: a
little sun, a little rain, a lot of people (38,247) as Venus and
Serena blasted their way into the quarterfinals, skipping through
the house graveyard, Court 2, like happy shovelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Graveyard? I didn't know about that,'' said big sister Venus
of the traditionally hazardous cubicle where so many celebrated
heads have rolled. She was sloppy at the end, missing a ton of
first serves and losing three match points and a 5-1 lead, but
still hammered lefty Miriam Oremans, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Also unaware of Court 2's reputation, getting-bigger sister
Serena got out before Tamarine Tanasugarn (of the Bangkok
Tanasugarns) could even think about building a funeral pyre, 6-1,
6-1.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the ivy-festooned lot, Court 1, Hingis bade
a brisk ``wiedersehn'' to the 11th-seeded German, Anke Huber, 6-1,
6-2.
</P>
<P>
   That set up Hingis for the Herculean labor of Venus Tuesday and,
probably, Serena in a semi Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can beat them. I do beat them,'' says Hingis with a sigh.
``But I never beat them both in the same tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   She's got her history right. Although she's 9-5 against Venus
and 3-3 against Serena, Hingis is 0-3 when they gang up. You might
beat up my sister, kid, but you can't knock off the family; that's
the Williams theme.
</P>
<P>
   It sounded first at Key Biscayne, Fla., two years ago as Hingis
nailed Serena but not Venus, and was reprised at Rome last year.
Reversing the order at the US Open, Hingis cut down Venus but felt
the blade of Serena in the title match, 6-3, 7-6 (7-4).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Serena has to defeat Philadelphian Lisa Raymond
Tuesday to make sure that Hingis must scale a second Everest if she
conquers Venus. Serena, who has ``grown more than an inch, I'm up
over 5-10'' since she carried the US, is looking more and more like
the flamethrower of Flushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got each other,'' says Hingis. ``That really helps, to
practice against each other. They both hit so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearing that, Serena giggles and says, ``She can join the family
and practice with us. We're hospitable people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sisters Sledgehammer, healthy and together in a tournament
for the first time this year, flail so fiercely that they drove
Hingis (a) crazy, and (b) to a gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came into the game with a new game,'' says the dwarfed
Hingis, 7 inches shorter than 6-2 Venus. ``A lot more power, a lot
more physical abilities. Everybody had to improve on their physical
abilities, and so did I have to. Just work out more, get stronger,
hit the ball harder basically. That's what they've meant.''
</P>
<P>
   Going against these siblings consecutively may be like facing
Pedro and Ramon of Our Old Towne Team, one after the other. You can
bet Hingis will be praying for herself and Raymond.
</P>
<P>
   Five years have passed since five Americans have crowded the
last eight here. The champ, Lindsay Davenport, and her foe, Monica
Seles are the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good,'' says Serena. ``It must be the McDonald's
influence. Cheeseburgers. Also milk. I love milk.'' By the way, she
endorses it commercially.
</P>
<P>
   A new training theory, but the sisters are never short of
theories or confidence, even if they are short of the famous beads.
``New stuff,'' says Serena. Her outlook is lilac: hair ribbon,
racing stripes on her dress, fingernails and toenails.
</P>
<P>
   Her outlook is also positive-plus. ``I came here to win, and I
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus says, ``I'm planning on winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis says, ``I'm going to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, the elder of the quartet, says, ``I learned a long
time ago not to make predictions like that. I'll say that I feel
capable of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena, averaging 55 minutes a match, and Venus, 66, have been
hit-and-running as though they were late for their latest
cheeseburger. But Hingis says accurately, ``The tournament begins
Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   She knows what lies ahead, and intends to somehow clean house as
efficiently as Hercules mopped up the Augean stables among his 12
mighty labors.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what he would have done on cheeseburgers and milk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
