u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS &LR;      07-03 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS UNDER ATTACK FROM ALL DIRECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Apparently, Pete Sampras isn't only playing through
pain, he's playing through paranoia. The only question is whether
it's his or everybody else's.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Sampras readily understands _ and doesn't mind _ that his
rivals are out to get him; he is, after all, only three victories
shy of becoming the grandest man in Grand Slam history. It's what
happens when he gets them that bothers him. As if he doesn't have
enough physical injuries, now his feelings are being hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Take Jonas Bjorkman, which Sampras did rather easily Monday on
Centre Court, 6-3, 6-2, 7-5, to reach the Wimbledon quarterfinals
and remain on course to tie the record for male singles titles here
(7) and break it for Grand Slam prizes (13).
</P>
<P>
   Did you see that handshake after Bjorkman got trounced? Looked
pretty skeptical, didn't it? That was the handshake of a man who
doubted Sampras's depleted condition _ the tendinitis in his lower
left leg he suffered before a second-round win over Karol Kucera,
which prompted All England Tennis &AMP; Croquet Club officials to hold
their stodgy breaths until the top seed and defending champion was
able to return to Centre Court Saturday for a somewhat shaky
four-set decision over Justin Gimelstob.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell the way Jonas shook my hand today that, you know,
he was thinking whatever he thinks,'' said Sampras. ``For the first
tine, the pressure's on my opponents a little bit. They know I'm a
little bit injured; the pressure's on them. They're not liking
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, if that's the criterion for this conspiracy theory,
then the plot has been in effect for some time. Sampras has
suffered an assortment of back, shoulder, and leg injuries, and now
that ever-expanding medical list has another entry: He's sick and
tired of talking about them, especially this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is what it is,'' he said. ``I'm going to go out there and
try my best under the circumstances. I'm sure there are a lot of
cynical players out there reading all this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   And if they're reading about him, they must be talking about
him, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I haven't spoken to any guys'' about Sampras overstating
his health problems, Bjorkman claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Well, what about that handshake?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, if he felt that I thought he wasn't injured, what
should I do?'' said Bjorkman. ``I'm very disappointed that I lost
my match. You know, I shake his hand as I do when I'm really
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   That's his story, anyway. But Sampras feels he knows what's
going through his opponents' minds, and it's not nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm sure'' Bjorkman was dubious about the extent of his
injury, said Sampras. ``I'm sure a lot of players think whatever
they think. You can just tell. But that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they're conveying their nasty presumptions
telepathically. At any rate, they're not going to rattle Sampras.
He even made light of his most wretched _ or, more accurately,
retched _ moment on the court. In the 1996 US Open quarterfinals
against Alex Corretja, Sampras became nauseated. And noted
physicians John McEnroe and Jim Courier wondered aloud whether it
was some sort of ploy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, when it's a tough moment, I kind of carry it in my
pocket, the vomit,'' said Sampras. ``I explode it; it comes out.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's tough to digest, this much is indisputable: Sampras
has enjoyed a cupcake of a draw. The final seed _ and not much of
one _ was removed from his half when fellow American Jan-Michael
Gambill erased No. 9 Thomas Enqvist, 7-6, 6-3, 6-4. Gambill is
scheduled to offer a limp handshake to Sampras after Wednesday's
quarterfinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete's not going to fake an injury,'' said Gambill. ``I think
a thing that Pete's not going to do is go out there and act like
it's hurt when it doesn't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Huh. Just read between the lines.
</P>
<P>
   In the semis, one of two mighty obstacles _ either Byron Black
(a 4-6, 7-6, 6-2, 6-4 winner over Gianluca Pozzi) or qualifier
Vladimir Voltchkov (7-6, 7-5, 6-4 over Wayne Ferreira) _ will be
waiting for Sampras. And undoubtedly whispering about him.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the other half of the draw remains studded with
seeds, who are too busy struggling for survival to give much
thought to Sampras. Andre Agassi, last year's runner-up, this
year's second seed, and the world's No. 1-ranked player, leads the
top-heavy bottom half after a 6-4, 6-3, 6-4 decision over qualifier
David Prinosil. He'll face an imposing challenge against No. 10
Mark Philippoussis, who ousted the final Briton, No. 8 Tim Henman,
6-1, 5-7, 6-7, 6-3 6-4. The other quarterfinal pits No. 11 Patrick
Rafter, a semifinalist last year and a 6-3, 6-4, 6-7, 6-1 victor
over Thomas Johansson Monday, against 6-foot-7-inch Alexander Popp,
who downed fellow skyscraper Marc Rosset, 6-1, 6-4, 3-6, 4-6, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras won't reveal a rooting interest, but at least Rafter
gave his supposition some credence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been comments passed in the locker room about it,''
said Rafter. ``But I think all in all, Pete's pretty genuine. It is
funny in the locker room. There's a few comments that fly by. At
the end of the day, you've got to trust the guy and how he's
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   In all probability, someone from Rafter's side of the draw will
find out Sunday whether Sampras is still ailing. Wink, wink. Nudge,
nudge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
