<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-MIDPOINT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT MID-YEAR, INVESTORS IN WAIT-AND-SEE MODE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan is firmly in charge.
</P>
<P>
   As the stock market soared last year and early this year,
investors blithely ignored interest rate increases by the Federal
Reserve aimed at bringing the market back to earth. The Nasdaq's
state of denial finally dissolved and technology stocks plunged in
reaction to a March 21 rate hike, pulling the broader market into a
downdraft that briefly threatened the nation's nine-year economic
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   At mid-year, everything is changed: Investors neither defy the
Fed nor react belatedly to it. Now, they simply wait to see what
central bankers will do next.
</P>
<P>
   During the second half of this year, the Federal Reserve will be
the single biggest factor driving the stock market, says Kathleen
Camilli, director of economic research in New York for Tucker
Anthony Inc. This signals a return to a more normal relationship
between the Fed and the markets, as prospects for an economic
slowdown, slight or steep, weigh on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will determine the performance of the stock market in the
second six months of 2000 is whether or not the Fed has managed to
engineer a soft landing or, in fact, additional tightening of
monetary policy is necessary,'' Camilli said.
</P>
<P>
   At its last meeting, on June 28, the Federal Open Market
Committee voted not to raise interest rates, leaving the discount
rate unchanged at 6.5 percent. Despite this respite from a series
of six rate hikes begun in June 1999, economists said the FOMC may
raise rates again if the economy does not slow appreciably.
</P>
<P>
   Camilli does not see enough strong, consistent signals of a
slowdown and argues the Fed is not done. Despite softer retail
sales, for example, auto sales surged again in June and dealers'
inventories tightened. That may be an indicator the economy will
pick up its pace after the second quarter, the slowest three-month
period of growth in each of the prior three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is still running too fast,'' she said. As a result
of strong growth _ she forecast the economy would grow at a 3.9
percent annual rate in the second quarter, compared with 5.5
percent in the first quarter _ the labor market will continue to
tighten, pushing the unemployment rate down further and wages up.
As for the stock market, she said, ``I don't think the pressure's
off unless we see a deceleration in growth'' to about 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But opinions about the market's direction range widely, from
careful pessimism to optimistic forecasts that the major market
indexes will finish the year with positive returns.
</P>
<P>
   The major markets in June mirrored investors' uncertainty,
moving in a sideways zigzag and remaining in negative territory due
to the March-April plunge. In a shortened trading session Monday
for the July 4th holiday, the Dow Jones industrial average closed
at 10,560.67, up 112.78 points for the day but down more than 8
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq added 25.82 points, closing at 3991.93. The
technology index is still 20 percent below its all-time high, and
has lost nearly 2 percent of its value year to date. So far this
year, the broad Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index's flat performance was
the best among the three major indexes; the S&AMP;P 500 Monday rose
14.72 points, closing at 1469.32.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lapman, president of Independence Investment Associates
Inc., a subsidiary of John Hancock that manages pension fund and
other institutional accounts, predicted the markets would benefit
from election-year optimism that would push the three stock indexes
to post positive returns by year-end, including a 20 percent gain
for the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is very healthy and is being very well managed''
by the Federal Reserve, Lapman said. ``There is nothing in the
general economy that would bring about a recession or severe
slowdown.''
</P>
<P>
   But Marshall Acuff, equity strategist for Salomon Smith Barney
in New York, believes the market has now entered a period of
uncertainty. Looking back over the first half of this year, he
attributed the market's exuberance to a unique combination of a
huge buildup of margin debt at the same time the Fed injected
liquidity into the nation's financial system to preserve calm
during the Y2K transition. Adding to the frenzy, money rushed into
technology mutual funds as investors saw that the high-risk sector
provided high returns.
</P>
<P>
   After the market's peak in March, he said, the Federal Reserve's
rate increases, a drain of liquidity, and a drop in expected
corporate earnings deflated the markets during the second quarter.
Investors, meanwhile, have diversified portfolios out of tech
stocks and into large non-tech companies, such as Coca-Cola and
Johnson &AMP; Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Acuff predicted that although the Fed is nearly
finished with rate hikes, ``there is a chance they're going to do
more.'' The question, looking ahead, ``is not whether the economy's
slowing down _ signals are mixed on that. The question is whether
the economy will slow enough for inflation to cool. We won't know
for a number of months.''
</P>
<P>
   Although inflation is not in the danger zone, economists have
become increasingly concerned about its steady upward creep. The
consumer price index rose 3.1 percent during the 12-month period
ending in May, compared with a 2.1 percent increase over the
previous 12 months. The core inflation rate, which the Fed watches
closely because it excludes oil and food prices, has also
accelerated this year.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern is wages, as measured by the government's
employment cost index. The index spiked 1.4 percent during the
first quarter, driving up the ECI for the year ending in March by
4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Cliggott, managing director and equity strategist for J.P.
Morgan in New York, said worrisome inflation reports late in the
second quarter helped to undermine a stock market that was
vulnerable and overinflated with a flood of liquidity earlier in
the year. While the strong economy provided a floor under the
market, markets are now ``stuck in the middle'' and unsure where to
go, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got this perception that growth is going to slow, and,
because of that, earnings growth is going to slow, but we don't
know how much,'' said Cliggott. ``On the other side of the
equation, inflation's going up and, because of that, maybe interest
rates are going to go up some more but we don't know how much.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted this uncertainty could continue and year 2000 may
continue to be a ``boring year'' in the market, unless inflation
continues to accelerate and causes the market to decline further.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts argue that Fed rate hikes have already begun to
slow the economy and the impact will continue to be seen in
economic statistics in coming weeks and months.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer at First Albany Corp.,
said the Fed's actions this year will be key to the market's
performance, but said the economy already seems to be slowing. ``My
guess is the stock market will break to the upside and technology
will lead us, though every investor should keep in mind one thing:
It's not going to be as exciting as it was early this year or the
past five years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
