u a BC-SF-DIMAGGIO-PARK-NYT &LR;      07-03 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-DIMAGGIO-PARK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESTATE SUES FOR A BIGGER SAN FRANCISCO TRIBUTE TO DIMAGGIO 
</HEADLINE>
   By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As playgrounds go, it is rather old-fashioned.
The rest of North Beach has gone trendy, with neon-signed bistros
edging out spaghetti joints and old tenements transformed into
condos. But the playground is still your basic city model: Two and
a third acres of asphalt, with swings and monkey bars, a baseball
field, a pool no one would be caught dead in past age 10 and a
bocce court where the same men have been playing for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The playground probably looks a lot like it did 50, even 75
years ago. That would be when Joe DiMaggio the fisherman's son was
learning how to turn a bat into a lightning bolt and a hard ball
into a whirling dervish. He played baseball here with three
brothers, good players in their own right, and made North Beach
playground famous as the humble beginning of one of the great
baseball players of all time.
</P>
<P>
   So when DiMaggio died last year, it seemed natural to rename the
playground in his honor. Then kids who played in Joe DiMaggio
Playground would know that this was a special place, where Hall of
Fame athletes could be seeded. It also seemed fitting to choose a
place that DiMaggio would have recognized from the old days.
Whenever he slipped into town to escape his legend, it was to the
old haunts. He avoided the neon signs and the menus with double
nonfat lattes and headed to the wooden bars with grizzled men who
knew that Joe DiMaggio the Yankee baseball star who married the
biggest movie star of his day (if for a little while) was the same
Joe who once wore hand-me-downs and blushed in the presence of
girls.
</P>
<P>
   What DiMaggio would make of the fight over the renaming of the
playground is anyone's guess. He would ignore all requests to
appear at ceremonies in his honor. He was embarrassed, his old
friends, say, by the attention. But Morris Engelberg, the Florida
lawyer in charge with guarding the Joe DiMaggio name, apparently
believes his old friend deserves more. Bigger. An airport, at the
very least. Or a freeway. Last week, when a federal judge tossed
out Engelberg's lawsuit blocking the renaming of the playground,
Engelberg vowed to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg's lawsuit, filed on behalf of DiMaggio's estate,
claims that the city wants to use the DiMaggio name to raise
property values in North Beach. This accusation makes San
Franciscans laugh. Dot-comers have already raised the property
values in North Beach to the stratosphere. Studios rent for $1,800
here and one-bedroom condos are in the $700,000 range. A
playground, even one with a ballplayer's name on it, could only
raise values higher if its fields were turned into a parking lot or
its pool into a cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, Engelberg added a new reason for objecting
to Joe DiMaggio Playground: the city charges 50 cents to use the
park's pool. ``Joe DiMaggio,'' he said, ``would never tolerate and
stand for his name being used on a public facility where you charge
children to use the pool there.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's grandchildren, who live in the Bay area, are said to
be behind the lawsuit, and of the opinion that a playground is too
small a tribute to someone San Francisco can brag about forever.
But in San Francisco, the consensus is that the lawsuit is rather
petty. ``It just seems silly,'' said Carole Suskind, who was
sitting on a bench here Monday afternoon watching her 3-year-old
son Todd toddle after a mourning dove. ``Doesn't the family, or
whoever,'' Suskind said, ``realize how conceited it makes them
seem?''
</P>
<P>
   Gavin Newsom, a San Francisco supervisor who sponsored the
resolution made last year to rename the park, goes further.
``Consensus is a great adjective to use in this case, because it is
so rare to have consensus in this city,'' he said. ``But in this
case, the consensus is that the playground is an appropriate site
for a tribute and that the lawsuit against the city is an absurd
waste of time, money and attention which does a tremendous
disservice to the legacy of Joe DiMaggio.''
</P>
<P>
   Newsom said that the city will be having a big renaming ceremony
at the playground as soon as Dom DiMaggio, Joe's surviving sibling,
can arrange to come here from his home in Florida. Dom, it turns
out, is happy that the playground will be named after his brother.
Joe, Dom DiMaggio said, would love the tribute, too, in his own
quiet way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
