<HEADER>
A2202 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-HNS &LR;      07-03 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Davenport dispatches Capriati
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JODY GOLDSTEIN
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ They were born only three months apart, but
their tennis careers have diverged greatly.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Capriati was a Wimbledon semifinalist in 1991, while
Lindsay Davenport was struggling through the junior draw. Capriati
also was playing in the U.S. Open semifinals in '91, one year
before Davenport won the junior title on those same courts.
</P>
<P>
   But though Davenport didn't turn pro until three years after her
colleague _ and with much less fanfare _ the 24-year-old
Californian has long bypassed Capriati, accomplishing things the
former phenom still dreams about.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Davenport again showed her dominance, ending
Capriati's best Wimbledon since 1993 with a 6-3, 6-3 victory.
Davenport, the No. 2 seed and defending champion, heads to a
quarterfinal matchup today against No. 6 Monica Seles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when you know you're playing a good returner, you
know deep down you have to serve better,'' Davenport said. ``I hit
the ball a lot better, had a lot more depth and power. I felt this
was the best match I've played in months.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, who is trying to overcome a couple of injuries this
summer, won Wimbledon last year and the Australian open this year.
She also owns the 1998 U.S. Open title, giving her three Grand
Slams in a span of six events. Capriati made three Grand Slam
semifinal appearances in 1990 and '91, then reached the semis this
year in Australia. But she has never gone further.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati, who had lost in the second round in both of her other
Wimbledon appearances since leaving the Tour at the end of 1993,
played well in Monday's first set, losing only her first service
game. She was never able to get that break back, however, and lost
the set. She never had a chance in the second, falling behind 5-0.
She did win three consecutive games, including one break of
Davenport's serve, but Davenport held on to close out the match.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-2{ Davenport drilled seven aces past Capriati and had 18
unreturnable serves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all revolves around serve,'' Davenport said. ``If I feel
I'm making good serves, I'm a lot more confident, can go for more
on my ground strokes. If I hit my ground strokes as well as I did
today and serve well, I have a good chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport owns a 5-2 edge in head-to-head competition with
Seles, with her victories coming in their last five meetings. But
none of those has been on grass, and only one came this year.
</P>
<P>
   The other marquee quarterfinal will pit Martina Hingis against
Venus Williams, both straight-set winners in the fourth round.
Hingis owns a 9-5 edge over Williams, though they split six
meetings last year. They haven't played one another yet this year
and have never played on grass.
</P>
<P>
   They have met three times in Grand Slams, with Hingis taking all
three meetings, including the 1997 U.S. Open final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serena (Williams) made up for that for me,'' Venus Williams
said, referring to her sister's victory over Hingis in last year's
U.S. Open final. ``Hopefully, I'll have another opportunity to play
better, at least play the best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   In other women's fourth-round matches, Serena Williams continued
to pound her opponents, Monday's victim being Thailand's Tamarine
Tanasugarn. Williams needed only 51 minutes to knock her out of the
tournament 6-1, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Williams won 100 percent of her first serves, dishing out eight
aces and 19 winners. Tanasugarn had only two winners.
</P>
<P>
   The two sisters could face each other in the semifinals if Venus
Williams can knock off Hingis. Serena Williams should have an
easier time against American Lisa Raymond.
</P>
<P>
   There were no surprises in the women's draw Monday, with every
match decided in straight sets. No. 6 seed Seles is back in the
quarters for only the second time since 1992 thanks to a 6-3, 6-4
victory over No. 9 Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario. Hingis had an easy time
with No. 11 seed Anke Huber. Jelena Dokic is making back-to-back
trips to the quarters, having dispatched American Kristina Brandi.
And Spain's Magui Serna is making her first quarterfinal appearance
after beating American Lilia Osterloh.
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, No. 1 seed Pete Sampras and No. 2 Andre
Agassi both advanced in straight sets. American Jan-Michael Gambill
knocked off No. 9 seed Thomas Enqvist 7-6 (5), 3-6, 6-3, 6-4,
leaving Sampras with no seeded players in his half of the draw.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom half, No. 12 Patrick Rafter advanced, as did No.
10 Mark Philippoussis, knocking out the final British hopeful, No.
8 Tim Henman, 6-1, 5-7, 6-7 (9), 6-3, 6-4. Henman had reached the
quarterfinals or better the last four years, including back-to-back
semifinal appearances in 1998 and '99.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining men's quarterfinalists include Alexander Popp,
Byron Black and qualifier Vladimir Voltchkov.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
