u i BC-MEXICO-PRI-BOS &LR;      07-03 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-PRI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRI SEEN AS VICTIM OF OVERWHELMING CHANGE IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A giant meteor once crash-landed near Mexico's
Yucatan Peninsula and, according to a popular theory, wiped out
Earth's dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   But, as people here are fond of saying, there were a few
creatures left over in Mexico. They formed a powerful group known
as the Revolutionary Institutional Party, the political tribe also
known as the PRI. And for the past 71 years, they've dominated
every aspect of Mexican life, creating monopolies, handing out jobs
and subsidies, and telling people how to vote.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, another meteor hit Mexico. It sent waves of voters,
driven by an intense desire for political change, to cast their
ballots in a historic election that freed them from their own
version of Jurassic Park. And for the first time in modern history,
Mexicans will not be ruled by the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those dinosaurs are finished,'' Enrique Aguirre, a 41-year-old
high school teacher, said Monday. ``This is the beginning of the
21st Century Mexico where the people choose their government, not
the other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI suffered an astounding defeat in Sunday's elections. Not
only did it lose the presidency to an opposition candidate for the
first time since its creation in 1929, but it also became a
minority in both houses of congress.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI lost the governor's races in both Morelos and Guanajuato
states, placed a distant third in the Mexico City mayor's race, and
failed to win a single seat in the capital's 66-member city
council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like the real dinosaurs, the fundamental cause of the
(PRI) defeat was the fact that the environment where they once
prospered has changed,'' Mexican historian Lorenzo Meyer wrote in
Monday's Reforma newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   That sense of change was so pervasive among Mexican voters that
a record 80 percent of Mexico's 59 million voters went to the
polls, and most of them chose Vicente Fox Quesada, a folksy
businessman and former governor, as their new president in a
surprisingly large margin of about 6 percentage points over
Francisco Labastida, the PRI's candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The world's longest ruling political party may soon be out of
power, but it won't be completely out of sight. After all, despite
Sunday's defeats, the PRI still possesses the nation's largest
machine. It still holds most of the state's governorships and city
halls.
</P>
<P>
   The likely fallout from this anti-PRI stampede will be an
internal battle between the party's old guard, who would like the
party to return to ruling with a firm hand, and the reformists,
many of them US-trained technocrats, who use words like ``niche''
and ``marketing'' when talking about how to restructure the PRI in
an era of increased competition.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the party will have to conduct its soul-searching
without the benefit of having a party leader who is also the
country's president.
</P>
<P>
   But with formidable foes now on both sides of the country's
political spectrum, where will the PRI fall?
</P>
<P>
   On the right, there is the conservative National Action Party,
or PAN, whom Fox represents. And on the left, where the PRI once
stood, there are at least three parties, chief among them the Party
of the Democratic Revolution, which controls the capital and a
handful of states.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The PRI) is going to have to do some serious
soul-searching,'' said Eric Olson, Mexico program director for the
Washington Office on Latin America. ``It's always been a two-headed
monster appealing to the super elite or the super poor. Now, it's
kind of stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI has known defeat before and recovered from it. After
losing control of the governor's office in the northern state of
Chihuahua to the PAN in the mid-1990s, it won it back last year by
using a primary election to select its candidate, something it had
never done before.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the PRI's debilitating loss may have been the work
not so much of Fox's charisma or the opposition parties, but of its
own incumbent president, Ernesto Zedillo, who has gradually
dismantled Mexico's old, fraud-riddled election process, and
replaced it with a fairer, cleaner system.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo backed a set of electoral reforms four years ago that
removed elections from government control and created an
independent Federal Electoral Institute. The laws also allowed for
publicly-funded campaigns and restricted parties' ability to
interfere in the voting process.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Zedillo also broke with PRI tradition by refusing to
name a candidate to succeed him, preferring instead to let the
party hold a national primary election. And Sunday night, the
president was the first official voice to appear on national
television and acknowledge Fox's victory. He also pledged a smooth
transition of power _ something Mexico has never experienced.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts, both in and outside of Mexico, drew parallels
Monday between the country's political reforms under Zedillo to the
opening of the former Soviet Union under Mikhail Gorbachev.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine this must be a bittersweet time for (Zedillo),''
said John Coatsworth, director of the David Rockefeller Center for
Latin American Studies at Harvard University. ``He has presided
over his party's worst defeat, but he's also secured his reputation
in history for creating a modern democracy in Mexico.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
