<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS RISE SLIGHTLY IN LIGHT, PRE-HOLIDAY TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
   By DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks rose broadly in light pre-holiday trading
Monday as investors digested the first important data of the month,
a lower-than-expected reading for manufacturing activity in June.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Purchasing Management reported that
its monthly factory index fell to 51.8 in June, below analysts'
expectations and May's number of 53.2. The latest number signaled
that the economy may be slowing and provided further evidence for
those who think the Fed will not have to extend its string of
interest rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   The figure slightly buoyed a session of sluggish trading that
ended early, with the New York Stock Exchange closing at 1 p.m.
Monday. The three main gauges all rose, with the Dow Jones
industrial average gaining 112.78 points, or 1.1 percent, to
10,560.67; the Nasdaq composite index edging up 25.82 points, or
0.7 percent, to 3,991.93; and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
climbing 14.72 points, or 1 percent, to 1,469.32.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was one of the slowest for a trading session this year,
with 452 million shares changing hands on the New York Stock
Exchange. Five stocks rose for every two that fell on the Big
Board.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500 received a lift from Conseco, the beleaguered
insurance and financial services company, whose shares slid 45.3
percent in the first half of the year as its chief executive and
chief financial officer resigned. Last week, Conseco named a
General Electric executive, Gary Wendt, as its chief executive, and
its stock rose 1 5/16, or 16.7 percent, to 11 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of other financial services companies rose on the
manufacturing report. J.P. Morgan rose 5 5/8, to 115 3/4, and
Citigroup gained 2 116, to 62 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq was held back by Oracle Corp., which fell 3 7/8, or
4.6 percent, to 80 3/16, after the resignation over the weekend of
its president and chief operating officer, Raymond Lane.
</P>
<P>
   The market will be closed Tuesday for the Fourth of July, but
investors will be keeping an eye on critical employment data coming
out on Friday and the beginning of the earnings season. Next week,
companies like Yahoo and General Electric will report results, and
the closely watched Producer Price Index will be released.
</P>
<P>
   So far, opinions are mixed on whether signals of slowdown seen
in the first half of the year will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Federal Reserve has labeled the signs of deceleration as
tentative,'' said Thomas McManus, the equity strategist at Bank of
America Securities. ``Therefore, all eyes will be on the numbers to
see if they'll confirm the trend of deceleration, or if they will
concern the Fed. The Fed is clearly uncomfortable in indicating
they are moving to the sidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   The disposition of the Fed and its chairman, Alan Greenspan,
toward interest rates is key to the direction of the market. As one
prominent technology investor, Alberto Vilar of the $7.5 billion
Amerindo Investment Advisors, put it, ``Tell me a money manager
that doesn't listen to Uncle Alan.''
</P>
<P>
   The June manufacturing number of 51.8 should be more palatable
to the Fed than earlier results, said Joseph Liro, chief economist
for Stone &AMP; McCarthy Research Associates. Though a reading above 50
signals that the manufacturing economy is expanding, the June
number was the lowest since January 1999. Liro thinks the ideal
range for the index is between 52 and 54.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a range everybody would be happy with,'' he said,
adding that it is a level with ``strong enough growth to keep
incomes high,'' but not so much growth to aggravate inflation. The
question, Liro says, is whether or not the manufacturing number
will stay in that range, continue to shrink or revert back to its
higher levels.
</P>
<P>
   While the manufacturing data indicated a continued slowdown,
news about earnings did not. About 57 percent of the 312 companies
that have already announced their results have said they would be
lower than expected. That, says Charles Hill, director of research
for First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks company earnings, is
a ``business as usual'' figure. More positive is the forecast of a
19.2 percent growth rate for second-quarter earnings for the S&AMP;P
500.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earnings numbers don't indicate things are cooling off,''
said Hill, adding that the effects of the most recent rate increase
would not be felt until next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a period of some confusion right now, trying to sort
all this out,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
