A2206 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-INSULIN-TRANSPLANT-BO     07-03 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSULIN-TRANSPLANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANCREAS CELLS COULD HELP RESTORE INSULIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a step toward making transplants of
insulin-producing cells a reality for a large number of diabetics,
researchers at the Joslin Diabetes Center have tapped a new source
of the scarce islet cells _ pancreatic tissue that's normally
discarded.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists used special culture techniques to coax
pancreatic ductal cells, which normally secrete very little
insulin, to churn out larger amounts of insulin. The ductal tissue
is routinely discarded when surgeons extract insulin-producing
islet cells from a donor cadaver transplant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are excited because we have taken lead and made gold,''
said Susan Bonner-Weir, a Joslin researcher and lead author of a
paper appearing in the current issue of the Proceedings of the
National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time this has been done, and I think it
shows the promise of this potential new source'' of transplanted
insulin-making cells, she said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The report comes only months after scientists in Edmonton,
Alberta, announced they had succeed in treating eight patients with
Type 1 or insulin-dependent diabetes by transplanting islet cells
from cadaver pancreases. The islet cells provided insulin, which
Type 1 diabetics lack because of a faulty immune reaction that
destroys islet cells.
</P>
<P>
   But the University of Alberta scientists noted at the time that
it required at least two donor pancreases to yield enough cells for
one diabetic recipient. In North America about 30,000 patients are
newly diagnosed with Type 1 diabetes annually, and some 800,000
people already have the disease. But only about 3,000 pancreases
from cadavers become available each year, severely limiting the
number of patients who could be treated.
</P>
<P>
   If the Joslin technique can be made more efficient and routine,
``this would be an enormous step in starting to address the
shortage,'' said Jonathan Lakey, director of the clinical islet
isolation laboratory at the University of Alberta, in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The pancreas is not only the body's source of insulin, which is
a key protein in metabolizing sugar for energy, but also produces
digestive enzymes. These enzymes leave the pancreas through tiny
ducts, and it is the cells making up these ducts that the Boston
researchers exploited.
</P>
<P>
   The duct cells are precursors that give rise to other pancreatic
cells. In addition, mature duct cells make a small amount of
insulin, probably as a backup in case of trauma or injury to the
pancreas, said Bonner-Weir.
</P>
<P>
   She and her colleagues, including her husband, Gordon C. Weir
and John J. O'Neil, devised a way to turn the clock back in the
duct cells, so that they became immature once again, and produce
more insulin.
</P>
<P>
   They removed the ductal tissue, which is normally thrown away
when islet cells are removed from a cadaver pancrease for
transplantation, and grew the cells in culture dishes in the
laboratory. Under these conditions, ``it's in their nature'' to
lose their ductal specialization and regress to become
insulin-producing precursor cells, she said. The scientists also
added a thin layer of ``matrix'' _ made up of skin-like cells _
that encouraged the immature cells to line up in the correct
configuration, said Bonner-Weir.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of a month, the cells cranked up their insulin
production by 10 to 15 times, said the scientists. In this
preliminary study, the researchers estimated, the duct tissue
culture would have generated only about 32,000 new islet cells _
far too few for even a single diabetes patient.
</P>
<P>
   However, they believe the process can be made much more
efficient, and Lakey at the University of Alberta agreed that the
method has great promise. ``They've been able to take what we've
been able to achieve here'' with the transplant success ``and
extend it'' with the hopes of being able to use only one pancreas
per recipient, and later perhaps one pancrease for two, and then
three patients, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
