<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2210 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-JULY-4TH-KENNEDY     07-03 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-JULY-4TH-KENNEDY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRUEST MEASURE OF PATRIOTISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Tuesday, July 4, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a separate-buy' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By DAVID M. KENNEDY    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ Commodore Stephen Decatur, freshly returned
in 1816 from subduing the Dey of Algiers and swollen with
nationalist fervor, rose to his feet at a banquet in Norfolk, Va.,
and offered a notorious toast. ``Our country!'' he said, glass held
aloft. ``May she always be in the right; but our country, right or
wrong.'' Decatur's salute is often cited as the quintessence of
American patriotic feeling. It's also the kind of remark that has
given patriotism a bad name.
</P>
<P>
   In our own time, sentiments like Decatur's have fallen far out
of fashion, but so has a more tempered and cogent kind of
patriotism, a classic case of throwing out the baby with the bath
water. ``A patriot is a fool in every age,'' jeered Alexander Pope,
but perhaps in no age have patriots been deemed more foolish than
in our own. To confess love of country today is to invite sneers
from sophisticates, to court banishment to the supposedly lunatic
fringe, to risk indictment as smug, stupid and reactionary _ or,
vilest of all possible epithets, corny. How did this sorry state of
affairs come to be?
</P>
<P>
   Always a plural people, Americans in recent years have grown
downright fractious _ not a condition that conduces to patriotic
emotion. Loyalties to tribe and race and communities both virtual
and vital, not to mention ardor for mergers and startups and global
networking, have apparently crowded out love of nation. The booming
economy also tends to make mere sunshine patriots of us all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of palmy prosperity are not those most favorable to
the display of public virtue,'' wrote Edward Everett _ the other
speaker at Gettysburg on Nov. 19, 1863, when Abraham Lincoln
managed in just three pithy paragraphs to craft a surpassing
argument for devotion to American nationhood. Only ``in hard,
doubtful, unprosperous and dangerous times,'' Everett claimed in an
1860 essay, do the ``patriotic find their way.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long time since privation and danger have blighted
this lucky land. The Civil War was one such occasion. The era of
the Great Depression and World War II was another _ a
decade-and-a-half-long ordeal when widely shared penury and peril
combined to nurture a feeling of common cause and to inspire a
truly healthy sense of patriotic feeling. It was a momentous era,
one that has lessons to teach us still, not least about our
relation to our country.
</P>
<P>
   The patriotism of the generation that suffered the Depression
and waged the war was no witless endorsement of ``our country right
or wrong.'' So far from being ``the last refuge of a scoundrel,''
their patriotism was the first haven of those who revered the
promise of America even while recognizing its defects.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Roosevelt knew how stricken his land was. He demanded
relief for the one-third of its people who were ill-housed,
ill-clad and ill-nourished. But in the opening words of his first
inaugural Roosevelt also affirmed that ``this great nation will
endure as it has endured,'' and in the next breath gave his famous
warning that ``the only thing we have to fear is fear itself.''
That passage amounted to a fond appreciation of the high value of
American institutions, even as FDR was about to extend their
embrace to that excluded one-third.
</P>
<P>
   Popular culture in the Depression decade reflected the same
fusion of admonition and attachment. Through all the prodigious
outpouring of contemporary photographs, films and writings that
documented the Depression's devastation _ works like Walker Evans'
and James Agee's portraits of busted tenant farmers in ``Let Us Now
Praise Famous Men,'' or Pare Lorentz's dirge for the despoiled
Mississippi in his haunting film, ``The River,'' or John
Steinbeck's indictment of the ravages of capitalist agribusiness in
``The Grapes of Wrath'' _ there beats a clear subtext.
</P>
<P>
   All throb with shame for their country, with anger at its
failures, but they pulse with unmistakable affection for it, too.
The critic Alfred Kazin recognized this distinctively American
attitude of what might be called critical patriotism when he
described the cultural mood of the 1930s as ``born of the
depression and the international crisis,'' but also suffused with a
feeling of ``affirmation,'' with ``an insistence to know and to
love what it knew.'' It was as if artists and writers in
Depression-era America turned instinctively to the better angels of
their nation's nature to guide their countrymen through their
greatest crisis in nearly a century.
</P>
<P>
   World War II, of course, unleashed a further upwelling of
patriotic fervor. But even wartime patriotism was not without its
critical element. Black Americans, for example, embraced the
``double-V'' campaign, demanding both victory over aggressors
abroad and victory over discrimination at home, deftly combining
loyal commitment with constructive criticism.
</P>
<P>
   No less striking was the publication in 1944 of the Swedish
economist Gunnar Myrdal's classic investigation of race relations,
``An American Dilemma.'' Its basic argument was twofold: in accents
that even the most red-white-and-true-blue American could endorse,
Myrdal praised ``the American Creed,'' a set of values that
included ``liberty, equality, justice and fair opportunity for
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also composed a withering condemnation of racial
oppression, inequality, injustice and denial of opportunity _
probing America's most vexed social issue even during the most
anxious months of the war, and thereby helping to lay the
foundation for the triumphs of the civil rights movement in the
succeeding generation. ``Let us go forth to lead the land we
love,'' said John F. Kennedy on the eve of those triumphs. But
Kennedy also branded the current treatment of black Americans as a
``moral crisis,'' and summoned his fellow citizens to honor their
own best beliefs. That second statement was surely no less
patriotic than the first.
</P>
<P>
   The words ``patriot'' and ``paternal'' stem from the same Latin
root, meaning ``father.'' Critical patriotism toward one's country
might be likened to the love that fathers and mothers alike ideally
tender to their children: unconditional, but still demanding. What
good parents do not both love and challenge their young, supporting
them but at the same time pushing them to be all they can be?
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Decatur got it only half right. May our country always
be in the right, to be sure. But the truest patriotism _ critical
patriotism _ will not hesitate to hold up the mirror of this
nation's better, ideal self to expose its wrongs and urge its
citizens to right them. Critical patriotism demands not mindless
veneration, but strict accountability. It judges as well as
celebrates. It is neither foolish nor corny. It is simply necessary
if this nation, conceived in liberty and dedicated to the
proposition that all of us are created equal, is to long endure.
</P>
<P>
   (David M. Kennedy teaches history at Stanford University. His
most recent book, ``Freedom From Fear: The American People in
Depression and War, 1929-1945,'' won the Pulitzer Prize.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
