<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-FIREWORKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS CELEBRATE JULY FOURTH MOSTLY WITH CHINESE FIREWORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: a map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ The rockets' red glare, the bombs bursting in
air, will give proof July Fourth that America's trade deficit with
China is still there.
</P>
<P>
   The United States celebrates its freedom by blowing up tons of
ornamental ordnance put together by the world's last major
communist power. So with every ``oooh'' and ``aaah'' Americans
utter, with every strontium nitrate starburst (red) or
chlorine-laced copper salt flare (blue), that trade deficit
expands. Even many of the little American flags that people wave at
July Fourth parades are made in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is our biggest market,'' said Liu Donghui, head of
Liuyang Fireworks Development Co. in the central province of Hunan,
birthplace of Chairman Mao Tse-tung, who led China's communist
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Fireworks represent only a sliver of the overall U.S. trade
deficit with China, which so far this year exceeds $18 billion. But
Americans spent $122.4 million on Chinese fireworks last year and
are buying more this year, just as they are buying more Chinese
toys, clothes and electronics. And American imports from China
could increase dramatically when China gains normalized trading
relations with the United States and membership in the World Trade
Organization, expected later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the pyrotechnics are prepared in cramped Chinese
workshops where low paid workers put together by hand ``cakes`` of
roman candles or ``display shells,'' the largest of which look like
brown-paper wrapped bowling balls sitting on a squat cardboard
cylinder of black powder. The shells shoot 100 feet in the air for
every inch of their diameter, with some reaching 1,200 feet before
detonating in a spray of colored fire.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the fireworks come from Hunan province.
</P>
<P>
   Fireworks were invented in China, and the Hunanese have been
making them for 1,300 years. In Liuyang, officially designated
China's fireworks capital, more than 400,000 people work in the
industry, or about a third of all the people in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The workers are typically separated from each other by a thick
wooden partition in case of an accidental detonation, though such
precautions don't matter much when a combustion gets rolling: an
explosion ripped through a southern Chinese fireworks factory last
week, killing 36 people and injuring 160 more. As many as 30 others
may have been killed because their bodies have yet to be recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese fireworks present other dangers as well. Residue from
the poisonous compounds that give the brilliant colors sift down
through the atmosphere after a blast. Scientists in Liuyang say
they are looking for ways to clean up their shells because the
United States is banning the import of lead bearing fireworks as of
August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has been urged to stop using lead,'' says the
fireworks boss, Liu.
</P>
<P>
   For those Americans whose hearts beat patriotic at the sight of
a skyrocket exploding into the shape of a star, they should know
the effect was perfected to commemorate the People's Liberation
Army of China, whose emblem is a red star, not to represent the
stars that spangle America's banner.
</P>
<P>
   Americans opposed to increased trade relations with China might
want to forgo the flags and the fireworks displays and stick to
hand-held sparklers. High anti-dumping duties, meant to protect
U.S. manufacturers, have kept Chinese sparklers out of the country
for the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, sparklers were popularized in Britain where they
were first used to celebrate the wedding of King Henry VII, so
lighting them might be seen as a nod to America's former colonial
rulers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
