<HEADER>
A2222 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-SAUCES-RECIPES-LADN-3     07-03 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAUCES-RECIPES-LADN-3Takes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIX YOUR DISHES WITH A SAUCY NEW TWIST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you'll be grilling often this summer _ whether it's succulent
chicken breasts, huge tender steaks or fresh salmon steaks _
consider embellishing your grillworks with tantalizing toppers.
</P>
<P>
   Chic trendy salsas, cold sauces, relishes and even tapenades
require no cooking, can be put together in minutes and offer a
range of different taste sensations.
</P>
<P>
   When you tire of just plain barbecue and want to bump your
dining pleasure upward a notch or two, try a fruity or savory or
piquant creation to fancy things up. You'll find mixtures of
fruits, vegetables, herbs, seasonings and the like _ and many will
even make good dips with chips or crudites. Another plus _ you can
also toss these versatile mixtures on steamed vegetables, rice,
beans or tossed salads for interest and dynamic flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that sauces and salsas know no ethnic bounds and you
can customize them to suit personal tastes. Try sprucing them up
with ginger, soy sauce, a variety of chiles, special vinegars and
even oils. You can make Southwestern-style, Asian, Mediterranean
and other interpretations with ingredients as chunky or saucy as
you like. Some recipes contain less, some have more moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Fruit and vegetable possibilities run the gamut from peaches,
nectarines and mangos to papaya, strawberries, raspberries, jicama,
corn, tomatillos, black beans, tomatoes and beyond. It's even
feasible to make a delicious avocado salsa like one once sampled
with the crab cakes at Fog City Diner in San Francisco. Simply mix
together cut-up avocado pieces (don't mash), chopped onions,
chopped green chiles, lots of lemon juice and salt. Another time,
add some garlic pepper and finely chopped tomatoes or cooked corn
kernels. Or spread herb grilled chicken breasts with a tapenade
like they do at Lucques restaurant in Los Angeles and surround with
a ragout of onion wedges and roasted red pepper pieces sauteed in
olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   When time is really short, whip up a combination of sour cream,
prepared horseradish and Dijon-mustard to serve with beef or
chicken. Or try grilled chicken topped with a mixture of Dijon
mustard and apricot jam zapped a minute or two in the microwave
oven. Interesting mustards are another way to go when mixed with
some snipped fresh tarragon or basil and a little whipping cream. I
also favor cucumber-yogurt or sour cream sauces as well as
pineapple salsas, which can be tossed together with canned
pineapple pieces, chopped red pepper and onions, herbs and
seasonings, and a drizzle of wine vinegar and oil.
</P>
<P>
   If you keep a well-stocked pantry and fresh produce bin in your
fridge, you should have no trouble turning out a medley of
creations on a moment's notice.
</P>
<P>
   There really are no preparation secrets or tricks, but for best
results (except in the case of tapenades) be sure to hand chop the
ingredients rather than using the food processor. Although these
sauces can be prepared just before serving (and they should be made
fresh on the day of serving), in most cases, they're at their best
if the flavors are allowed to mellow for at least an hour or two
prior to using.
</P>
<P>
   For those in a time crunch, don't be embarrassed to rely on some
of the delicious ready-made options. Trader Joe's, supermarkets and
specialty food stores stock a variety of fruits salsas, different
relishes, tapenades and sauces. Peruse the aisles _ you'll be
amazed at the variety of interesting items available.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you call these embellishments, they're bound to add
zest and new dimensions to meals. Now the only problem is deciding
which of the following recipes to make first. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
NATALIE'S MUFFALETTA-STYLE TOPPING &QR;
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups pitted ripe olives, drained and coarsely chopped (a
6-ounce can) &QR;
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups pimiento-stuffed olives, rinsed, drained and coarsely
chopped &QR;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh basil OR 1 teaspoon dried basil &QR;
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped roasted red peppers &QR;
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil &QR;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red wine vinegar &QR;
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon garlic pepper (OR more to taste) &QR;
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, mix together all ingredients. Use to top
grilled fish, burgers, steak or chicken, or use in sandwiches as a
condiment. Makes about 2 1/3 cups. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PEACH AND FRESH GINGER SALSA &QR;
</P>
<P>
   2 peaches, peeled and cubed &QR;
</P>
<P>
   3 tomatoes, seeded and diced &QR;
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sliced green onions &QR;
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar &QR;
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cider vinegar &QR;
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated fresh ginger &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in a medium bowl and stir well. Chill at
least 1 hour. Good on grilled chicken breast or fish. Makes about 2
cups.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Chips, Dips &AMP; Salsas,'' by Judy Walker and Kim
MacEachern, Northland Publishing. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FRAMBOISE SALSA &QR;
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces fresh raspberries &QR;
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, finely diced &QR;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely diced red bell pepper &QR;
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno, seeded and finely chopped &QR;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons rice vinegar &QR;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh parsley &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lime &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in a small bowl and chill 1 hour. Serve
mounded over grilled fish steaks such as halibut. Makes enough for
4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Chips, Dips &AMP; Salsas,'' by Judy Walker and Kim
MacEachern, Northland Publishing.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE RECIPES FOLLOW)
</P>
