<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, July 4. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION (Mexico City) _ Vicente Fox, who swept to
presidential victory as the champion of voters fed up with
corruption and one-party rule, meets with President Ernesto Zedillo
to begin the transition from a republic headed for decades by a
king-like president to one in which everything seems up for grabs.
By Sam Dillon. (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``i''
news file.) 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   The story runs under a 4-column, 2-line hed; graphic inside.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ASSESS (Mexico City) _ News analysis on role of President
Zedillo in paving way for a fair election _ and the defeat of his
own party. By Julia Preston. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
