<HEADER>
A2229 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-PAY-SEXES-COX     07-03 0303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAY-SEXES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: Today in lede is Tuesday
 &HT;    Women make strides, still face salary gap
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women are closing the pay gap in many industries in corporate
America, according to Working Woman's 20th annual salary survey
being released today.
</P>
<P>
   But they still earn significantly less than men for the same
work in almost every job in every industry, including
women-dominated fields such as nursing and secretarial work. Even
women at the highest levels of corporate America take home less
than their male counterparts, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's survey covers more than 40 industries. It
includes fast-growing fields such as information technology and
health care management as well as male-dominated fields where women
are gaining ground: the clergy, science, management and sports. The
sports category includes salaries for players in the Women's
National Basketball Association, where the $50,000 in average pay
is a far cry from the millions male players make.
</P>
<P>
   Women advertising executives have made some of the biggest pay
gains. Female media directors field make 90 cents for every $1 men
in the same job earn, up 6 percentage points from a year ago, the
magazine found. Although women chief executive officers at large
advertising firms make a lot less than male peers, those at midsize
companies take home $10,000 more, according to the survey. If it's
any consolidation, Smyrna, Ga., native Julia Roberts is the first
actress in Hollywood to join the $20 million-per-film ranks, a
males-only club until she signed to star in the movie ``Erin
Brockovich.'' Stars like Tom Cruise, Bruce Willis and Mel Gibson
routinely earn that much per picture.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
