<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX PROMISES COALITION CABINET WITHIN TWO MONTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ As Mexicans hailed the cleanest elections in their
country's history, President-elect Vicente Fox Quesada of the
opposition National Action Party immediately began preparations for
the first non-PRI administration to govern the United States'
southern neighbor since 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Operating on little sleep following nearly all-night
celebrations for his historic victory on Sunday, Fox reached out to
his supporters, spoke via telephone with world leaders, including
President Clinton, met with incumbent President Ernesto Zedillo of
the long-ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, and
promised that he would form a new coalition Cabinet in two months
that would include other parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that every Cabinet member learn their
responsibility quickly for a smooth transition of programs,'' Fox
said Monday. ``Above all so that we can continue or improve upon
existing programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The 58-year-old former Guanajuato governor, who was the
candidate of a conservative coalition led by the National Action
Party, or PAN, defeated the PRI candidate, former Interior Minister
Francisco Labastida Ochoa, by a surprisingly wide margin in a
Mexican election whose cleanliness was as unprecedented as its
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   With 93 percent of the ballots counted by the country's
independent Federal Electoral Institute, Fox had 42.8 percent of
the vote, followed by 36.5 percent for Labastida. A third
candidate, former Mexico City Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, candidate
of a center-left coalition, received 16.5 percent, followed by two
other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In other races, voters also slashed the PRI's presence in
congress, making it a minority party for the first time, elected
opposition governors in two states and reelected an opposition
party for the Mexico City mayoralty.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans everywhere arose with surprise and pride at what they
had done at the ballot box. Even those who hadn't voted for Fox
acknowledged that the country had reached an important democratic
milestone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish somebody else had won, because I don't have much
confidence in Fox or his party,'' said Miguel Herrera, a
40-year-old welder who voted for PRI. ``But at least now we know
that our votes matter and that we can change what we don't like.''
</P>
<P>
   Before boarding a Mexico City subway on her way to work Monday
morning, Beatriz Casas, a Fox supporter, said her country felt
different to her after Sunday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to describe exactly, but it feels like my opinion
matters,'' she said. ``We don't have to put up with bad governments
anymore. We can vote for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the new attitude among voters came from an election
process this year that was extraordinarily transparent and clean.
Under the watchful eye of an independent electoral agency created
four years ago that took balloting away from government control,
stricter laws that restricted private funds and party intereference
and allowed for fairer media coverage, observers noted that the
election was generally clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, a majority of the people were convinced that their
votes were secret and counted,'' said David Huey, a spokesman for
Global Exchange, a California-based human rights group and one of
several national and international observer organizations that
monitored the vote. ``There were lots of minor irregularities that
we found, but nothing blinding that would affect the results.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Mexican voters were so eager to express their opinions
in such a close race that a record number of them _ 80 percent of
the country's 59 million registered constituents _ turned out to
cast ballots. Some of them waited hours to vote because of
technical problems and a lack of ballots at some precincts.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the logistical problems, there were complaints by
observers and voters alike that party representatives, particularly
from the PRI in provincial areas of the country, had illegally
influenced voters to support the party's candidates. The electoral
institute will investigate all formal complaints that it has
received.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Fox's work will now focus on building a new government
in time for his Dec. 1st inauguration and for Mexico's first
transition of federal power to a different party.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding significantly more diplomatic than he did during the
tight and combative campaign, Fox stated repeatedly during his
acceptance speech Sunday night and again Monday that he would work
closely with other political factions.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Zedillo sounded as conciliatory as Sunday night's
losing candidates. In a nationally televised speech Sunday night
immediately after the the electoral agency released its preliminary
results and before Labastida could concede defeat, Zedillo
congratulated Fox and pledged a smooth transfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have offered to Mr. Fox to personally oversee a transparent
and efficient (transition) to the next federal administration,''
said Zedillo, who was prohibited by the Mexican constitution from
seeking reelection.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's stock market and currency, which have historically
reacted negatively to election day results because of concerns of
fraud and political instability, surged in what some called a
``fiesta rally.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mexico City Bolsa rose 6.12 percent, interest rates eased
slightly and the Mexican peso gained 3 percent against the US
dollar to its strongest exchange rate in a month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
