<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2231 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHILDREN-BOOK-REVIEW-     07-03 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHAT WE DON'T KNOW ABOUT CHILDREN': `LORD OF THE FLIES' ON IN-LINE
SKATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This slender novel by the Italian writer Simona Vinci plunges
with such stylistic quiet into forbidden territory that one almost
fails to hear the barriers collapsing. Vinci's forbidden territory
in ``What We Don't Know About Children'' is sex among children. The
novel tells a shocking story, mostly through the muddled
perceptions of a girl named Martina whose desire to be included
leads her to become a member of a clandestine club led by a
disturbed 15-year-old. But ultimately Vinci's theme is the
normative cruelty that lies within the human soul and the fragility
of individual defenses against it.
</P>
<P>
   Though it is a shocking story, it is, as the author notes in a
brief afterward, a plausible one. Still, a question arises about
the purpose and the effect of Vinci's depictions of sexually
explicit acts among children. I found myself torn between two
contrary reactions.
</P>
<P>
   One can admire Vinci for drawing aside the curtain that normally
veils this subject and to treat it bravely, unapologetically and
with psychological subtlety. But I also wondered whether she
transcends the sexual and psychological disturbance that she
describes, or, via her book, participates erotically in it. In the
end, perhaps, the discomfort one feels in reading this novel points
to its underlying message: that moral behavior, civilization, is
based not on the denial of forbidden impulses but on restraint, on
governing those impulses when they disrupt the falsely smooth
surface of repression.
</P>
<P>
   Vinci, described on the dust jacket as a 30-year-old writer who
lives near Bologna, provides an arid setting for her tale, a bland,
featureless apartment building on the edge of a town called
Granarolo, a spot so remote that the courtyard faces a field of
corn. Martina stands alone in the middle of the courtyard singing,
remembering when the other children, absent now, used to play
there. Vinci introduces us to two other characters, Luca, who
spends his days sleeping in a dark room, and Matteo, who runs,
``methodical and steady,'' although until recently he was inactive,
``like a dead pine cone.''
</P>
<P>
   Something, in other words, has happened inside the spare and
standardized environment of the apartment building and the
courtyard, whose cement parking lot, green benches, lampposts,
tubular fencing and iron gates suggest a false and empty normality.
What is missing is an adult presence. Parents play walk-on roles in
the story, but in essence are as distant from the children's
emotional lives as the crows circling the cornfields. If Vinci's
story has any practical message to offer, it would be similar to
that of the antidrug poster displayed at New York City bus stops,
on which a teen-age girl wears a tattoo saying, ``Stay involved in
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinci's children live in their own culture, careering around on
in-line skates, talking about intergalactic travel and playing a
game called nuclear war in which ``they simulated nuclear blasts
with firecrackers that left a cloud of smoke and made the whole
yard stink.'' A subtle, implicit eroticism hangs over the
playground like a mist. While there are no parents in evidence, a
vague sort of adult evil hovers in the form of two men who pick up
Mirko, the 15-year-old leader, in their car from time to time and
give him things in plastic bags.
</P>
<P>
   That was before. Now, the children have gone elsewhere and
Martina sings by herself, Luca sleeps and Matteo runs. Five months
earlier, Mirko began showing the contents of the plastic bags to
Martina, a 14-year-old boy named Luca and Matteo and Greta, both
10. As if these magazines depict models to emulate, the five of
them engage in a secret rite led by Mirko, who has a troubled
``Lord of the Flies'' aura of command about him. They go to a shed
to engage in the sexual experimentation that is at the prurient
heart of Vinci's story.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the way home Martina sat on Mirko's scooter,'' the narrator
writes after the first visit to the shed, ``hanging on to him, with
the unpleasant feeling that somehow she had lost something, and
that she couldn't do anything about it. All that countryside around
them, and something forgotten or lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the children has a story. But Martina, tormented,
powerless and compliant, remains the central figure, the embodiment
of the confusion and longing involved in protean sexuality. The
blending of disassociated images is psychologically brilliant, from
Martina's memory of early auto-erotic desires to a vision of
Greta's hands on her desk, ``her filed nails with their chipped,
dark-red nail polish,'' that somehow disgusts her.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are horses running through the snow, the stars above,''
Vinci writes of Martina's fantasy life. ``There's a leap into
emptiness, like rounding a hill at full speed in a car.''
</P>
<P>
   As the children, in thrall to Mirko, extend their explorations,
matters hurtle toward tragedy. The two men who call Mirko into
their car exercise a strange power; they are an invisible force
that leads the children to carry out their prescribed roles not so
much because they derive pleasure from them but because they don't
know how to escape. But the world the children have created is too
complex, too mysterious, for Vinci's novel to be seen as a parable
about the corruption of childhood innocence by adult malice.
Innocence does not exist in her world of pubescent and adolescent
desire and cruelty, although the corrupting influence of evil
grown-ups who step in when parents are absent is clearly a theme of
the book.
</P>
<P>
   Vinci's book, translated from the Italian by Minna Proctor, is
like nothing else you have read. In its way it is more disturbing
than ``Lord of the Flies'' because the action takes place not on
some abandoned island but in the midst of ordinary life, surrounded
by civilization.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
