<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2235 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-GORBACHEV-COLUMN-JUNE     07-03 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORBACHEV-COLUMN-JUNE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO ABOLISH CHEMICAL WEAPONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: This is the new Gorbachev column. It is for immediate
publication.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's GORBACHEV COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a separate-buy' _ or becoming a client
of the GORBACHEV COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 &HT;    
 By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 c.2000 La Stampa  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picture a fisherman threatened with old, rusting mustard-gas
weapons in his fishnets. Picture a whole neighborhood evacuated
because of chemical weapons unearthed in one family's backyard.
Picture gallons of deadly nerve gas leaking from storage containers
and wafting downwind toward communities crowded with young children
and their parents. Worst of all, picture a terrorist group
releasing nerve gas in a public place _ say the subway in the
middle of rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   These four scenarios are not hypothetical. All have taken place
in the last few years in the United States, Japan and on the high
seas. Chemical weapons, hundreds of thousands of tons of which are
produced in Russia, the U.S., Japan, throughout much of Western
Europe, and now in Asia, continue to threaten us all in many and
varied ways. In addition, large stockpiles _ as well as dumped and
buried munition caches _ still exist.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to understand this growing threat and to destroy
chemical weapons before it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Russia today have more than 65,000 tons of
chemical weapons stockpiled at 16 major sites. U.S. stockpiles _
some 25,000 tons now _ are located in eight states: Alabama,
Arkansas, Colorado, Indiana, Kentucky, Maryland, Oregon and Utah,
and on Johnston Atoll in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Russian stockpiles _ some 40,000 tons _ are concentrated at
seven sites in western Russia and one east of the Urals.
</P>
<P>
   India has also publicly acknowledged an existing stockpile, and
several additional countries no doubt possess smaller stocks of
chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, both the United States and Russia, along
with many other nations, signed an international agreement, the
Chemical Weapons Convention, banning development, production and
stockpiling of chemical weapons. It took 12 years of tough
negotiating, partly under my watch as Soviet president, to bring
about the convention, a historic breakthrough in nondiscriminatory,
verifiable, global disarmament of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement has set an excellent precedent for efforts to
abolish nuclear weapons, And yet, although it was ratified by the
U.S. Senate and the Russian Duma, the CWC has failed to eliminate
much of the chemical weapons threat. Serious progress is needed
immediately in chemical weapons destruction if there are to be no
more accidents or terrorist incidents. If we wait, they inevitably
will happen.
</P>
<P>
   First, we all must recognize that the continued existence of
enormous chemical weapons stockpiles threatens each and every one
of us. Nerve, mustard, lewisite and other deadly gasses kill
indiscriminately, especially when let loose by terrorist groups in
public places or when leaking from stockpile sites and carried by
the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Old arsenals also pose serious environmental and public health
hazards to local communities, but our main concern must be global
security. The proliferation threat is real.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the international community must begin to seriously help
Russia to destroy its chemical weapons arsenal. Russia is fully
committed to abolishing its stockpile, but its difficult
post-Cold-War socio-economic situation has prevented it from
destroying a single weapon.
</P>
<P>
   The American Cooperative Threat Reduction program, established
eight years ago by Sens. Sam Nunn and Richard Lugar, has committed
some $150 million in recent years to planning a destruction center
in the Kurgan region, just north of Kazakstan on the steppes of
Siberia. The Europeans _ Germany, Switzerland, Sweden, Italy and
others _ have committed some $50 million. But the Russian program
is estimated to cost $8 billion to $10 billion to destroy all seven
chemical weapons sites.
</P>
<P>
   Much more coordinated support is needed now to share this burden
more fairly. Recent efforts in Congress to halt the Nunn-Lugar
program are misguided and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Continued development of safe and environmentally sound ways to
destroy weapons is needed. The end product should be a ``toolbox''
applicable to all weapons, chemicals and situations.
</P>
<P>
   Having successfully incinerated 6,000 tons of chemical weapons,
the United States has learned that there is no silver bullet. In
the last five years, much has been learned, though, about safe
alternative destruction methods, knowledge that we all must share.
There are many stakeholders in this process, and they must be
included through the use of advisory commissions, regional and
national dialogues, outreach programs and open decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we must begin to address old and abandoned chemical
weapons that contaminate countries and oceans throughout the world.
The United States, for example, has identified more than 200
suspected dumpsites _ in two-thirds of the states _ that may
contain chemical weapons. Green Cross Russia has recently studied
an open-burn site for lewisite in the Penza region.
</P>
<P>
   And all major powers have sunk bargeloads of chemical weapons to
the bottom of the seas, thus endangering the environment and health
of the global community.
</P>
<P>
   I am concerned about the loss of momentum in eliminating
chemical weapons. I have therefore written to leaders of Russia,
the United States and several other countries urging them to give
serious personal attention to this matter. I appeal to them and to
the world public to join me in an effort to rid the world of the
dangerous, obsolete arsenal of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   (Mikhail Gorbachev is president of Green Cross International, a
global environmental organization with headquarters in Geneva. The
Green Cross Legacy Program addresses the safe and environmentally
sound destruction of weapons of the Cold War and the environmental
impacts of war.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
