<HEADER>
A2238 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-REFUGEES-FILMS-NYT &LR;      07-03 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-FILMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AID FOR REFUGEES ON THE SILVER SCREEN
</HEADLINE>
  By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It sounds like something out of a 1940s film archive: a group of
Americans, driven by great human suffering, travels to a strange
foreign land to offer succor to the needy. But this isn't a movie,
though it is humanitarianism, Hollywood style.
</P>
<P>
   The project is called Filmaid International, and its mission is
to aid refugees worldwide, albeit in a way that has little to do
with such basic needs as water or medicine. Instead, Filmaid's goal
is to import Hollywood's most plentiful natural resource: movies.
</P>
<P>
   Founded last year by Caroline Baron, a film producer, Filmaid's
mission is to bring feature films, children's cartoons and other
screen entertainment to refugee camps, where the horrors of war
have often been replaced by isolation, boredom and bad memories.
</P>
<P>
   Organized in just eight weeks, Barron's group traveled to five
refugee camps in Macedonia over two months last summer, toting
several small movie screens, a pair of video projectors and a
generator. In each, the group's volunteer technicians and
projectionists assembled a makeshift, open-air movie house and
screened movies like ``Titanic,'' ``Mrs. Doubtfire'' and ``E.T.''
for crowds of 300 to 4,000 children and adults.
</P>
<P>
   Working with aid organizations like the International Rescue
Committee and United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees,
Filmaid began to branch out into other services, screening
educational films on everything from AIDS to domestic violence, and
employing camp members as projectionists and technicians.
</P>
<P>
   To pay for all of this, Baron, 38, turned to a source not
exactly famed for its global philanthropy: the film industry.
Despite Hollywood's reputation for self-obsession, Baron said she
found a remarkably receptive audience. Within the project's first
six weeks, Filmaid received donations of cash and supplies from an
array of film industry sources including Universal Studios, MGM and
Miramax Films. Some high-profile names also kicked in their
support. Robert De Niro, who worked with Baron on the film
``Flawless,'' joined the group's advisory committee, as did the
actresses Susan Sarandon and Julia Ormond, and Harvey Weinstein,
Miramax's co-founder.
</P>
<P>
   By the time their trip ended in mid-August, Baron's group had
been invited to visit Kosovo, screening the silent films of Charlie
Chaplin and Tom and Jerry cartoons to audiences of recently
repatriated Kosovars. Along the way, Filmaid also earned the
respect of several more established aid operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised by how successful they were, really
pleasantly pleased,'' said Reynold Levy, president of the
International Rescue Committee. ``One of the major issues for
refugees and particularly children is sheer boredom. They have no
routine, they have no school, their parents are clearly distracted.
The opportunity to engage in group activities helps restore a sense
of normalcy. And that's exactly what Filmaid provided.''
</P>
<P>
   So successful was Filmaid's first endeavor that the rescue
committee has adopted the organization as an official project and
signed off on its next mission: a six-month expedition, beginning
in October, to Guinea in West Africa, which is home to estimated
500,000 refugees from the region's simmering civil wars.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is that Baron, a veteran of the fantasyland of movie
sets and film shoots, has found herself in the unlikely position of
de facto international aid expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is funny to me sometimes,'' she said. ``I mean, I had to
look up Guinea in the atlas.''
</P>
<P>
   Baron says the idea for Filmaid came to her last spring after
she saw a photograph of a mother clutching her dying son on a
street in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just began to go, `What I am doing about this?''' Baron said
in a recent interview. ``I just thought there's got to be something
I can do.'' So she began to make calls. What she found was an
enormous outpouring of support.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first people Baron called was the producer Jane
Rosenthal (``Wag the Dog,'' ``Analyze This''), who had also been
following the refugee crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `What if we send movies over there?''' Rosenthal
recalls. ``I said, `Count me in.' It was really all Caroline. All I
did was second the motion.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with Jeffrey Silver, a Los Angeles film producer, Baron
began to solicit donations: a projector here, a generator there.
The group also received support from more traditional nonprofit
organizations like the William Jelin Memorial Trust and George
Soros' Open Society. Tower Air, which is now bankrupt, donated free
flights for the support crew to run the project's projectors and
generators.
</P>
<P>
   There were some skeptics. ``People were worried that it could be
viewed as frivolous,'' she said. ``We're talking movies here, after
all, not food or shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   But aid officials say that especially for refugee children,
entertainment is a much-needed resource, helping distract and dull
the psychological impact of war and displacement. Indeed, large aid
organizations like Unicef and Save the Children often supply toys
and sports equipment for just that reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think of relief as shelter, food, water, and in truth,
it's not really that hard to raise money for projects like that,''
said Robyn Groves, the senior external relations officer for the
U.N. High Command. ``But not a lot of people think what happens
after the basic necessities are taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   Groves was just one of several aid officials who attended a
party last week celebrating the project's first anniversary, an
event that drew a mix of foreign aid officials and film types like
Mira Nair, the Indian director of ``Mississippi Masala,'' and
``Salaam Bombay.'' (Baron was co-producer of Nair's 1995 film
``Kama Sutra'' and is producing her next project, ``Monsoon
Wedding,'' which begins filming in India next month.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a lot of Hollywood do-gooders,'' Rosenthal
said. ``I seem to think there's a new generation giving back to the
community in a significant way. I think we're far more socially and
politically active.''
</P>
<P>
   The celebration also marked the informal kickoff for Filmaid's
fund-raising for the Guinea project. Budgeted at approximately
$350,000, that expedition will face far more difficult logistical
challenges, including poor roads, a lack of vehicles and a high
crime rate.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation, Baron visited Guinea this year with Mary Soan, a
British director who serves on Filmaid's executive committee and
met with aid workers, teachers and organizations like Doctors
without Borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing to me,'' Baron said. ``They said, `We want to
see hopeful films.'''
</P>
<P>
   Groves, who has visited camps in Angola, Iran, Macedonia and
parts of Southeast Asia, said, ``Refugee camps are really appalling
places,'' but films can make them better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like relief for the soul, relief from the boredom, trauma
and anxiety of those places, she said. ``In there, two hours of
fantasy can go a long way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
