<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-TECH-COLLEGES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech schools' names aimed at new market
 &HT;    By James Salzer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Driven in part by a surge in the need for
computer-savvy workers, technical schools across Georgia have been
overflowing with students in recent years, but not many of them are
coming right out of high school.
</P>
<P>
   So state officials think they've hit upon a solution to make the
campuses more attractive to Georgia's 18- and 19-year-olds and
their parents: Change the name of technical institutes to technical
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   State leaders, including Gov. Roy Barnes, will begin touring the
state Thursday attending name-changing ceremonies for technical
institutes hoping to escape the image of being the second or third
choice for recent high school graduates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those on the college track tend to ignore technical
institutes,'' said Atlanta Tech President Brenda Watts Jones.
``Now, it will become a window of opportunity rather than a last
resort.''
</P>
<P>
   The name-change provision was contained in a little noticed
section of Barnes' school reform law, which took effect last week.
The bill also set up a new funding formula that will provide money
for the first time based on enrollment, a change that will mean
millions of dollars more for the Department of Technical and Adult
Education's 33 schools and 17 satellite campuses.
</P>
<P>
   About half the schools will change names right away, and the
rest should do so within the next year.
</P>
<P>
   State policymakers have been through this name game before.
Lawmakers pressured the University System of Georgia Board of
Regents for years to upgrade state four-year colleges to regional
university status in hopes of gaining new programs and prestige. In
the mid-1990s, the regents changed the names of four-year colleges,
turning them into universities but without guaranteeing anything
more than a new name.
</P>
<P>
   State officials think this new name change will bring more
dramatic results. Students coming out of high school have long
picked state universities and colleges over technical institutes,
or simply gotten a job.
</P>
<P>
   While Ken Breeden, commissioner of the state technical school
system, brags of nonstop enrollment gains at his facilities, only
10 percent or so of his students at many of the campuses are fresh
from high school. More commonly, students don't enroll in technical
schools until they are in their mid-20s, or older.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name change is going to make our institutions more
marketable in the high school markets,'' Breeden predicted. ``For
kids out of high school, it is seven years before we see them.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Tanks Jr., 31, a student at Atlanta Tech, agrees the name
change could help. When he was a senior in high school, he
considered going to technical school, but he knew his parents
wanted him to attend college.
</P>
<P>
   So he got a degree from Georgia State University and works in
Wachovia's credit card business. But he never lost his desire to
study barbering, and last summer he started taking classes at
Atlanta Tech. After graduating, he wants to run his own business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name change will open a lot of parents' minds,'' he said.
``By being called a technical college, it will be considered a
first choice for education more often than it has been in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin Tech President Coy Hodges, who also serves as interim
president of Savannah Tech, noted that the name change will also
put Georgia in line with other Southern states that have technical
college or community college systems.
</P>
<P>
   One question that may need to be answered if the change attracts
more teens: where will technical colleges put them?
</P>
<P>
   Breeden said the state's technical schools have a waiting list
in the range of 6,000-8,000 students, and the problem can be
particularly acute in the system's most popular programs. For
instance, enrollment in computer-related programs has nearly
doubled since 1994, leading to waits for some students wanting to
study information technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The waiting lists will increase, no doubt, particularly in our
computer technotudents drop out or graduate high school without
going on to some type of training.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes good sense not to waste human talent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He expects the average age of technical school students _ now at
age 24 for those taking day classes at his Griffin, Ga., school and
age 28 at night _ to drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you will see the pendulum swing,'' he said.
``Eventually, we will get these students into occupations more
suitable to their potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the cute in the system's most popular
programs. For instance, enrollment in computer-related programs has
nearly doubled since 1994, leading to waits for some students
wanting to study information technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The waiting lists will increase, no doubt, particularly in our
computer technology and allied health areas,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Tech will be getting more space in the next few years,
and Barnes committed $75 million in the mid-year, fiscal 2000
budget to technical school construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The limiting factor over the last five years is we haven't had
the capacity to expand because we haven't had the revenues to hire
more teachers,'' Breeden said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Barnes' bill, technical school funding will be based on
enrollment, rather than the previous formula of needs-based
recommendations made by Breeden's department and the schools.
</P>
<P>
   In an increasingly technology-driven society, Hodges said the
state can't afford to let students drop out or graduate high school
without going on to some type of training.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes good sense not to waste human talent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He expects the average age of technical school students _ now at
age 24 for those taking day classes at his Griffin, Ga., school and
age 28 at night _ to drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you will see the pendulum swing,'' he said.
``Eventually, we will get these students into occupations more
suitable to their potential.''
</P>
