A2241 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-WIMBLEDON04-COX     07-03 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Under Dad's guidance, Williams' sisters advance at Wimbledon
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England -- Serena Williams broke into giggles when
describing her father trying to drive a car on the roads of London.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ride really slow because going on the other side is really
difficult,'' Serena said, laughing, after winning her first-round
match at Wimbledon this year.
</P>
<P>
   British fans laughed almost as much a few days later when
Richard Williams spoke about wanting daughters Venus and Serena,
the fifth and eighth seeds, to retire and become involved in the
Internet because he thinks it would be more lucrative than tennis.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Williams, who coaches the two with their mother,
Oracene, isn't here for his entertainment value to his daughters or
the public. He's here because his daughters asked him to come to
Wimbledon to help them - either of them - win the singles crown.
</P>
<P>
   They usually travel abroad with their mom, leaving Dad to handle
more coaching work at home. But the parents have different coaching
styles, and Venus decided she wanted her father to make his first
trip to Wimbledon. She asked him twice before he agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom says a lot, lot less,'' Venus said. ``At a Grand Slam,
I want more input.''
</P>
<P>
   They've gotten it and so far it's paying off. Both moved into
the quarterfinals Monday. Venus defeated Sabine Appelmans 6-4, 6-4,
despite a concentration lapse late in the second set. Serena beat
Tamarine Tanasugarn 6-1, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the tournament begins,'' top seed Martina Hingis said
after beating Anke Huber 6-1, 6-2. Second-seeded Lindsay Davenport,
Monica Seles, Lisa Raymond, Jelena Dokic and Magui Serna were the
other winners.
</P>
<P>
   Matches jump in difficulty and intensity today, most players
said. Venus, in particular, will get challenged by Hingis. Serena
plays Raymond, and Davenport and Seles meet again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny looking at the draw,'' Davenport said. ``There are
some spots where I think some of us would rather be, and then some
spots of the draw that are just unbelievably tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Wins by the Williams sisters would set up an all-Williams
semifinal Thursday. Raymond, for one, thinks the pressure on them
for that match might help her against Serena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got nothing to lose. She's got everything to lose,'' the
former University of Florida player said. ``She's top 10 in the
world. She's the one 'supposed' to get to the semifinals and have a
matchup with Venus.''
</P>
<P>
   And Hingis, if she defeats Venus, could face the same trouble
she had at the U.S. Open last year when she beat Venus in the
semifinals but ran out of energy against Serena in the final. As
she was in New York, the younger Williams appears to be playing
well.
</P>
<P>
   But Hingis never has beaten the Williams sisters in back-to-back
rounds on consecutive days and admits some concern. Serena can
understand that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's (hard) because we both run well, we both have big
serves, we both are attacking,'' she said. ``It's like playing the
same person, who's your nemesis, all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Nemesis takes on interesting meaning in this context. Davenport
and Hingis have dominated women's tennis this year, building a
rivalry, while Venus and Serena spent much of the year recovering
from injuries and fending off retirement rumors.
</P>
<P>
   But the Williams sisters are never far from conversations about
potential Wimbledon winners, simply because their size, strength,
big serves and volleying abilities mean they should succeed on
grass.
</P>
<P>
   Their father, of course, has been saying that for years - and
saying that each sister would be nemesis to the other as they
dominated the sport at No. 1 and No. 2 in the world.
</P>
<P>
   They seemed well on their way to reaching that status last year.
Venus finished No. 3 in the world; Serena finished No. 4. But wrist
tendinitis for Venus and a knee injury for Serena meant they've
missed time from the tour.
</P>
<P>
   Venus now is ranked No. 5 and Serena is No. 8. Neither likes the
lower rankings, although they think it was best they took the time
off to let their injuries heal. Venus missed five months, while
Serena missed two.
</P>
<P>
   During the Ericsson Open, which Serena played but Venus missed,
Richard Williams created a storm by discussing possible retirement
for both his daughters. It fueled speculation that Venus, in
particular, had lost interest in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Williams does seem resigned to the fact that the
retirement conversations won't be much more than that for several
years. Serena predicted five or six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind them being here,'' Richard said last week. ``I
just don't like to see them on the same side of the draw.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first tournament they've played together since the
Grand Slam Cup in October, when Serena defeated Venus in the final.
It was the younger sister's first victory over the older sister.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, they're enjoying playing doubles, having each
other to warm up with and just hanging out together. As for playing
each other, it's another match to go, both say, but they'd like to
play that match.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to have that opportunity,'' Venus said. ``At least
one Williams would be in the final.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
