<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER04-COX     07-03 1718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: What's important? Be honest
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   American voters are focusing ever more on honesty as the most
important trait for a presidential candidate, according to an
Associated Press poll. The voters are about evenly split on whether
Al Gore or George W. Bush is more honest. Four in 10 voters now
pick honesty ahead of such traits as caring about people like them,
showing strong leadership, standing up for beliefs and having a
vision. In the new poll (4 percentage point margin of error) about
a third picked Bush as most honest and a third picked Gore. Another
one-third said neither candidate or they didn't know. Black voters
put the most emphasis on a candidate who cares about people like
them. But honesty ranked second.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST BIG OIL, NOW BIG DRUGS
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from an attack on big oil, Al Gore toughened his criticism
of drug manufacturers today by blaming ``price gouging'' for the
soaring cost of prescriptions. At a high school in suburban St.
Louis, Gore touted his plans for a ``real, comprehensive
prescription drug benefit'' under Medicare, a proposal that he said
offered a sharp contrast with the Republicans. He was accompanied
on the campaign swing by House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of St.
Louis, who said that prescription drugs would be a key issue not
only in the presidential race but in Democratic efforts to regain
control of Congress. ``It's a huge, huge issue to senior
citizens,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   VICE PRESIDENT? STILL MULLING
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush met Dick Cheney, the head of his vice
presidential search team today, and said he still had a long and
varied list of potential running mates to consider. Meeting with
Cheney, a former secretary of defense, at his ranch in Crawford,
Texas, north of Waco, Bush said he had not even made up his mind
whether he'd announce his choice before or at the convention in
Philadelphia, which begins four weeks from today.
</P>
<P>
   HEY, HE USED TO BE AN OILMAN HIMSELF
</P>
<P>
   While locked in a string of disputes with the Clinton
administration, the oil industry has pumped more than $1.5 million
into George W. Bush's presidential campaign. Oil companies will be
seeking Bush's help on a number of issues, should he be elected.
Across a range of issues _ from drilling in an Alaskan wildlife
refuge to new rules setting the price of oil taken from federal
land to whether to pursue a controversial international agreement
on climate control _ oil company executives seem to believe Bush
and the people he would appoint to key posts will be more receptive
to their point of view.
</P>
<P>
   BIG CHANGE ACROSS THE BORDER
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush congratulated Vicente Fox, the victor in Mexico's
presidential election who broke the governing party's 71-year hold
on the country's leadership. ``I think what it indicates is how far
reform has come in Mexico,'' Bush said today. ``Obviously, there
needs to be legal reform in Mexico. Mexico's got to do a better job
of arresting folks who break the law, but on political reform they
made great process.'' Al Gore's campaign also offered praise: ``We
congratulate Mr. Fox on his election and the Mexican people for
conducting the freest and fairest election in that nation's
history. We look forward to working with him.''
</P>
<P>
   DIFFERENT RESULT FROM NEWSWEEK
</P>
<P>
   A Newsweek poll released over the weekend showed the two
candidates in a virtual dead heat, unlike a series of recent
surveys that gave George W. Bush a comfortable lead over Al Gore.
The survey had Gore leading 46-45 percent, well within the survey's
4 percent margin of error. Nine percent of those surveyed were
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   FREE _ THAT'S ALWAYS A MAGIC WORD
</P>
<P>
   After being nominated by the Libertarian Party to run again for
the presidency, Nashville investment banker Harry Browne
acknowledged today he has scant chance of ever moving into the
White House, but said he hoped his campaign would reinvigorate his
ailing party. ``We're the only political party that's offering to
set you free,'' said Browne, 67, who didn't vote before 1992, when
his wife suggested he run for the nation's top office. ``It's the
most powerful political message in the world.'' The Libertarian
Party advocates individual liberties over expansive and expensive
government programs.
</P>
<P>
   FOR REFORM PARTY, IT'S BUCHANAN VS. HAGELIN
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Republican Pat Buchanan will face John Hagelin, leader of the
Natural Law Party, for the Reform Party presidential nomination _
and the $12.6 million in federal campaign funds that go with it.
Ballots will be mailed to thousands of interested voters around the
country later this week. The deadline for requesting a Reform
ballot has passed. Voters who receive ballots can mail them in or
use the identification number on the ballot to vote over the
Internet Aug. 7-9. Results will be announced at the convention,
Aug. 10-13, but a vote by more than two-thirds of the delegates can
overturn the results.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T EXPECT CAMPAIGNS TO CHANGE MUCH
</P>
<P>
   Congress approved the first significant restriction on campaign
financing in two decades when it voted last week to require
secretive, nonprofit political groups _ the so-called 527
committees _ to disclose where they got their money and how they're
spending it. But the legislation is expected to do little to
prevent outside groups from influencing or even dominating state
and national campaigns this year. ``Soft money,'' the huge
donations that unions, corporations and others give to the
political parties and other groups, remains without limit even
though the parties and advocacy groups, now including the 527
committees, will have to report it.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH'S GOT HIS DUCKS LINED UP
</P>
<P>
   Behind the symbolism of George W. Bush's recent efforts to court
traditionally Democratic minority voters lies a stark reality: He
can afford to focus on expanding his coalition precisely because he
has consolidated his political base far more successfully than Al
Gore. In recent polls, Bush is consistently attracting support from
about nine in 10 Republicans _ a far better showing than either of
the last two GOP presidential nominees. Gore, meanwhile, draws only
about three-fourths of Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   YEAH, BUT WHAT DOES HE REALLY THINK?
</P>
<P>
   Green Party presidential nominee Ralph Nader has no problem
finding words to describe Al Gore: Gore ``is a great environmental
impostor. ... He's a 'gee-whiz techno-twit,' '' Between George W.
Bush and the vice president, ``Gore is the more infuriating because
he is more of a hypocrite,'' Nader declared. ``He doesn't know who
he is anymore. He's a plastic person.'' So what about Bush: ``The
problem with George W. Bush is that he is beyond satire. The
challenge for me is, how do you satire satire? This guy is out of
Central Casting. I refer to his campaign as the Bush Corp. He is
out of the corporation; he is the corporation; he is the corporate
welfare king of all presidential candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   DRIVING FORCE IN CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   He said the stop wasn't a campaign event, but George W. Bush
flew from his Texas ranch to serve as grand marshal of the Pepsi
400 in Daytona Beach, Fla., stock car race and shifted into
campaign mode. Bush made a brief pit stop in the garage area,
shaking hands with NASCAR fans, racing crews and drivers _ people
he said ``work for a living.'' The world of stock car racing is
made up of ``very good Americans,'' he said. ``They not only talk
about family values, they live it.''
</P>
<P>
   SHADES OF GLOOM
</P>
<P>
   It is no secret that even with 130 days to go before the
election, Democrats are unsettled, even gloomy, while Republicans
are confident. One of Al Gore's biggest problems is, simply, that
voters seem to like George W. Bush more and think the vice
president is too politically calculating and relentlessly
ambitious. But Gore aides said they hope to turn that into a virtue
by convincing voters that as president he would channel that
determination and energy into his policy agenda.
</P>
<P>
   AN EASY NAME TO REMEMBER
</P>
<P>
   Voters in a Georgia legislative district will see a familiar
name on the ballot during the July 18 primary: Jimmy Carter.
Carter, 58, of Brunswick, is no relation to the former president
from Plains, 180 miles to the west. He is not even a Democrat. But
the ex-police chief is happy to share the name. ``It is apt to
stick more deeply than if I said my name was Robert Aspenwalt,'' he
said. Carter, running unopposed in the GOP primary, hopes to unseat
Democratic state Sen. Rene Kemp, who has represented the district
along the Georgia coast since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   FOLLOWING IN THE FAMILY BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   Karenna Gore Schiff, oldest child of Al Gore, is traveling
throughout the country to preach her Democratic message of family
and participation. Schiff, 26, is national chairwoman of GoreNet,
the youth support coalition for her father's campaign. One of her
roles, she said, is keeping dad in touch with the needs and wants
of young voters. Schiff, whose mother, Tipper Gore, teasingly calls
her ``the next senator from Tennessee,'' graduated in May from
Columbia Law School. She was a frequent traveling companion of her
father during the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   IN TELEVISION, THEY CALL IT COUNTER-PROGRAMMING
</P>
<P>
   It's an unconventional approach to presidential politics, but
that's the idea. Dismayed that the Republican and Democratic
national conventions have become ``coronations,'' a loose coalition
of political activists, religious leaders, and social satirists has
decided to hold ``shadow conventions.'' In Philadelphia and again
in Los Angeles, the plan is to talk issues during the day and party
into the night, to make Americans think hard about certain issues
and then make them laugh out loud. Sen. John McCain is slated to
speak on the East Coast; ``Politically Incorrect'' host Bill Maher
on the West. Actor and presidential tease Warren Beatty also is
expected to put in an appearance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
