<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2244 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FUNDS-AFTERTAX-BOS &LR;      07-03 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-AFTERTAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC AFTER-TAX RULE ARRIVES WITH NARY A WHIMPER FROM FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less is generally more when it comes to mutual fund documents,
which is why regulators have been pushing the industry to simplify
fund prospectuses and annual reports.
</P>
<P>
   But the Securities and Exchange Commission's latest proposal
does just the opposite, requiring funds to add a new and
potentially complicated category of information to their public
documents.
</P>
<P>
   SEC spokesman John Heine said the plan, mandating the disclosure
of after-tax returns, balances simplicity against the investor's
need to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose it could be seen as complicating things a little,''
Heine said of the proposal. ``But remember that the commission's
job is first to decide what disclosure is important, then to worry
about how that disclosure is presented.''
</P>
<P>
   During a public comment period that ended Friday, the plan
didn't raise much protest from the fund industry. Even the
Investment Company Institute, the national trade group for mutual
funds, submitted a letter of support to the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton Vance funds submitted a letter supporting the plan and MFS
funds submitted one criticizing it, citing high costs for what it
said would be a minimal benefit. Others remained on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, it won't matter to most people either way,'' said
Keith Hartstein, senior vice president at John Hancock, which
didn't weigh in with the SEC. ``Something like 40 percent of fund
assets are held in tax-exempt accounts, (and) the average fund
investor has a household income low enough that taxes aren't a
significant issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Plan supporters agree that many people don't need to know their
funds' after-tax returns. The numbers would be meaningless, for
example, for investors in tax-deferred retirement accounts such as
IRAs or 401(k)s.
</P>
<P>
   But proponents argue that investors in other, taxable accounts
have a right to know how much of a fund's return is theirs and how
much goes to Uncle Sam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, there is a risk that this could be over-emphasized,
since it doesn't matter for half of the shareholders,'' said Tom
Faust, chief investment officer at Eaton Vance. ``On the other
hand, after-tax returns are vitally important for the other half.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, mutual funds distributed $166 billion in capital gains
and another $134 billion in taxable dividends to investors.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC noted in its March 15 proposal that ``more than 2.5
percentage points of the average stock fund's total return is lost
each year to taxes.'' Jack Bogle, former chairman of Vanguard
funds, has said the ``tax drag'' is closer to 3 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, it can make a significant difference for
investors in taxable accounts.
</P>
<P>
   A $10,000 investment in a mutual fund that returns 10 percent
annually would grow to almost $175,000 over three decades. Clip the
return by 2.5 percent a year, though, and you would end up with
$87,550 after 30 years _ roughly half as much.
</P>
<P>
   The higher a fund's return, of course, the less the tax hit
matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure how much the tech-fund investors who earned 100
percent last year cared about taxes or expense ratios,'' said Burt
Greenwald, a fund-industry consultant in Philadelphia. ``When
equity markets lose some of their sizzle, these things will
suddenly seem a lot more important.''
</P>
<P>
   The details of the SEC proposal seem important to fund companies
already.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the plan would require funds to show after-tax
numbers for one-, five-, and 10-year performance in two ways. The
first would show gains or losses for an investor in the 39.6
percent federal tax bracket who held onto his fund shares, while
the second would show what the numbers would be if the same
investor unloaded the shares.
</P>
<P>
   It would also require funds to display the after-tax information
both in the annual report and in the ``risk/return'' section at the
front of the prospectus.
</P>
<P>
   The ICI said in its comment letter it supports the SEC's goal,
but the requirement as proposed ``could be misleading'' for
investors.
</P>
<P>
   It said the rule should be limited to the prospectus, and only
to the tax section near the back of the document. It also suggested
the SEC use the 28 percent tax bracket rather than the 39.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton Vance, which stands to look good if the plan is approved
because some of its funds are managed for tax efficiency, said it,
too, supports the SEC's goals. But Faust said Eaton Vance would
prefer the SEC's original proposal to the ICI compromise and would
even like to see it expanded to include three-year returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people in our industry who want to minimize the
level of disclosure because their funds wouldn't look good,'' Faust
said. ``Almost two-thirds of mutual fund assets are held by people
in the highest tax bracket, so it doesn't make sense to use the 28
percent bracket for these calculations.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEC, for its part, said it chose the top rate because it
provides a worst-case scenario for investors and because the
numbers don't show the effect of state and local taxes as it is.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the next step for the SEC staff is to sift through
the comment letters and make a formal recommendation to the
commissioners. It has the authority to recommend changes as needed.
</P>
<P>
   There's no firm date for completing the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a formal time frame for these things,'' Heine
said. ``(However,) because of the high priority on this issue, I
can't imagine it will take too long.''
</P>
<P>
   The urgency stems in part from the fact that the US House of
Representatives has passed legislation requiring the SEC to improve
after-tax disclosures. The Senate, so far, hasn't followed suit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
