<SLUG> BC-BROWNIE-COLUMN-LADN-2Takes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCH FOR THE ULTIMATE SCRATCH BROWNIES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people opt for making their brownies from a mix while
others wouldn't dream of it. For those who prefer the scratch route
(including me), you not only eliminate the chemical taste of the
boxed product, but if you have a good recipe and you use good
quality chocolate and butter, you can end up with an excellent
textured and flavored result in short order.
</P>
<P>
   Now's it's time for a follow-up to the search for the ultimate
brownie. When I asked readers to share their BEST brownie recipes a
while back, two sent along recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Bassman of Sherman Oaks sent along versions from
Katharine Hepburn and Maida Heatter. The Hepburn brownie recipe _
which is a snap to make _ has made the rounds over the years, and
readers continue to enjoy it. According to notes accompanying the
Heatter recipe, which contains peppermint patties, Heatter found
the original in a Palm Beach, Fla., newspaper. It came from a local
deli, but of course she tinkered with it and added the
chocolate-covered mints, which don't melt but form a middle layer.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lapham of North Hills wrote that he has been experimenting
with brownie recipes for years, trying to come up with the perfect
recipe. The one he's sharing is, in his opinion, the best.
</P>
<P>
   With all my brownie travels and tastings through the years, I'm
sharing two of my current favorites. The first recipe, Fudgy,
Chewy, Cakey Brownies, is one I've made often. It's fabulous, and
the brownies have lots of height (more than an inch thick). The
other recipe for Triple-Chocolate Fudge Brownies is one a friend of
my daughter's recently tried and shared from the Food Network,
courtesy of Sara Moulton of Gourmet magazine. The brownies are rich
and yummy!
</P>
<P>
   Now it's up to you to judge for yourself if any of the recipes
here can pass as the ultimate brownie. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FUDGY, CHEWY, CAKEY BROWNIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Knowing when to pull a pan of brownies from the oven is the only
difficult part of baking them. If you wait until a toothpick
inserted comes clean, they're overcooked. Check your brownies even
before the suggested minimum baking time. If a toothpick inserted
in the middle comes up with really fudgy crumbs, it's time to take
the brownies out and put them on a wire rack for cooling. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
2/3 cup all-purpose flour &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon baking powder &QL; 
Vegetable cooking spray &QL; 
2 ounces unsweetened chocolate &QL; 
4 ounces bittersweet OR semisweet chocolate &QL; 
10 tablespoons (1 stick plus 2 tablespoons) unsalted butter &QL; 
1 1/4 cups sugar &QL; 
2 teaspoons vanilla &QL; 
3 large eggs &QL; 
3/4 cup toasted walnuts, pecans, macadamia nuts OR peanuts
(optional) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adjust oven rack to lower-middle position.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk flour, salt and baking powder in a small bowl; set aside.
Spray an 8-inch baking pan with vegetable cooking spray. Fit a
16x8-inch sheet of foil in pan and up 2 sides, so you can use foil
overhang as a handle to pull cooked brownies from pan. Spray sheet
of foil with vegetable cooking spray.
</P>
<P>
   Melt chocolates and butter in a medium bowl over a pan of
simmering water. Remove from heat; whisk in sugar and vanilla.
Whisk in eggs, one at a time, fully incorporating each one before
adding next. Continue to whisk until mixture is completely smooth
and glossy. Add dry ingredients; whisk until just incorporated.
Stir in nuts, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Pour batter into prepared pan. Bake in preheated 325-degree oven
35 to 45 minutes, until a toothpick or cake tester inserted into
center comes out with wet crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Cool brownies in pan on a wire rack 5 minutes. Use foil handles
to pull brownies from pan. Completely cool brownies on rack, at
least 3 hours. Cut into squares and serve. If not serving
immediately, do not cut brownies. (Whole brownie cake can be
wrapped in plastic wrap, then foil and refrigerated for up to 5
days.) Makes 16 brownies.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Perfect Recipe,'' by Pam Anderson, Houghton Mifflin. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
TRIPLE-CHOCOLATE FUDGE BROWNIES &QL; 
3 ounces fine-quality bittersweet chocolate (not unsweetened),
chopped &QL; 
1 ounce unsweetened chocolate, chopped &QL; 
6 tablespoons (3/4 stick) unsalted butter, cut into pieces &QL; 
3/4 cup sugar &QL; 
1 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
2 large eggs &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/2 cup all-purpose flour &QL; 
1/2 cup semisweet chocolate chips &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Butter and flour an 8-inch square baking pan, knocking out
excess flour. In a heavy 1 1/2-quart saucepan, melt bittersweet and
unsweetened chocolate and butter over low heat, stirring until
smooth; remove pan from heat. Cool mixture to lukewarm and whisk in
sugar and vanilla. Add eggs, one at a time, whisking well until
mixture is glossy and smooth. Stir in salt and flour, just until
combined. Stir in chocolate chips.
</P>
<P>
   Spread batter evenly in pan. Bake in middle of preheated
350-degree oven 25 to 30 minutes or until a tester comes out with
crumbs adhering to it. Cool brownies completely in pan on a rack
before cutting into 16 squares. Brownies keep, layered between
sheets of waxed paper in an airtight container at cool room
temperature, 5 days. Makes 16 brownies. Recipe courtesy of Sara
Moulton, Gourmet magazine. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
KATHARINE HEPBURN'S BROWNIES &QL; 
(Shared by Bobbe Bassman) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 ounces unsweetened chocolate &QL; 
1/4 pound unsalted butter &QL; 
1 cup sugar &QL; 
2 eggs &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
1/4 cup all-purpose flour &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1 cup coarsely chopped walnuts &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Butter an 8-inch-square baking pan. In a heavy saucepan, melt
chocolate with butter over low heat, stirring until completely
melted. Remove from heat and beat in sugar, eggs and vanilla. Stir
in flour, salt and walnuts, mixing well.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon butter into prepared pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 325-degree oven 40 minutes. Cool, then cut
into squares. Makes 1 dozen.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE RECIPES FOLLOW)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
