<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-ITALY-MENSWEAR-FASHIO     07-03 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-MENSWEAR-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE APOTHEOSIS   OF THE HUSTLER:   A MORALITY CYCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ After the 46 shows that made up the spring 2001
men's wear collections ended in Milan on June 29, one was tempted
to calculate just how much it costs the fashion industry, and the
press that brings back news of it, to present men with the
possibility of pairing hot pants with knee socks, wearing metallic
leather jumpsuits unzipped to the navel or styling their hair so
that they look like female extras on ``The Dukes of Hazzard.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill _ a rough estimate _ is in the vicinity of $5.9
million. The figure takes into account about $60,000 to produce a
catwalk show (more for those with the swankiest production values).
It also considers the few thousand dollars in expenses that dozens
of buyers and 312 journalists from 18 countries incur during a
five-night stay.
</P>
<P>
   What the number does not account for is the cost of lavish
promotional dinners and parties given by the fashion houses, like
the one Gucci held in Milan's main railroad terminal last week,
which had Tom Ford dancing with Heather Graham. Nor does it account
for the cost of luring celebrities like Graham to Italy in the
first place. Nor does it include mini-bar raids made after hours at
the Hotel Principe di Savoia, center of fashion-week social
activity and home of the $15 airline-size bottle of Absolut.
</P>
<P>
   All this spending results in little with which the modern man
might build a broad and efficient wardrobe. This is not to say that
there are not some labels that still respect the notion of
wearability. At Burberry, Roberto Manichetti again turned out
handsome jackets in plaid and quietly patterned leather. He also
managed a memorably arch tuxedo, in shiny cotton with pointy
lapels, which nonetheless bore no traces of goofiness. Prada showed
narrow, short-cropped pleated trousers and uncomplicated beachwear,
all of which stayed within the realm of the smart and sensible.
Neil Barrett, a former Prada designer now on his own, proved with
boxy zippered jackets of waxed linen and leather, among other
styles, that he is not simply out for a lark.
</P>
<P>
   But what is ultimately played out each season on runways devoted
to men is something else: the frivolous resurrection of one male
archetype or another from a preciously thin catalog. What will it
be this time, one wonders? The pinky-ringed Harvard senior? The
aspiring biker? The seemingly neutered Carnaby Street lad? The
disaffected Midwestern stud with a tenure at Dairy Queen on his
resume?
</P>
<P>
   Or as it happened last week, the airily coiffed man-boy, whose
open shirts, tight sweaters and gold accessories suggest that he is
for sale?
</P>
<P>
   When fashion spectacles offer so little that can be taken
seriously, there is really no other way to judge them than by the
self-parody they achieve. The Versace show, by this measure, was
the week's most entertaining. It put the archetypal male hustler in
shirts with wild prints and plunging necklines, tight pink and
purple shantung suits and zigzag-pattern knit briefs. Nor did it
forget to give him big sunglasses and bigger hair. The overall
image was absurd enough to overshadow the sordidness at its root.
</P>
<P>
   With this show Donatella Versace accomplished something more
purely Versace-esque than she did with her last ``Fight Club''
collection. ``If Gianni is looking down,'' said Stefano Tonchi,
Esquire's fashion director, ``he is smiling.''
</P>
<P>
   At Fendi, where models wore wide-leg, beltless, low-slung pants,
small purses and tight-fitting knits as they slouched down the
runway, another editor commented that the hustler on view seemed of
a very particular sort: Via Veneto, circa 1973. Eric Wright, who is
Karl Lagerfeld's primary creative hand at Fendi and who designed
the men's wear line for the first time, said his inspiration came
from the typical Roman, so infatuated with his own good looks.
``They are all hustlers in a sense,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   At Byblos, models in gold chain belts and bracelets made a
similar point.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, D Squared, the cultish, five-year old label
designed by Dean and Dan Caten, Canadian twins, paraded models
wearing exceptionally low-slung jeans, who were chauffeured down
the runway in monster trucks. This season they held their show in
an open-air Milan discotheque and offered drinks, fruit kebabs and
models in gold leather jeans, tight gold basketball shorts and
sliced leather shirt-vests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theme was Tony Monero in Mykonos,'' Dean Caten said,
referring to John Travolta's character in ``Saturday Night Fever.''
``That's where he'd go after he won the dance contest,'' Caten
added. ``Maybe he ran out of money on the vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolce &AMP; Gabanna showed men in tight tank tops and caps, gold
thong sandals and gold- and silver-embellished pants.
</P>
<P>
   However cliched the hustler reference might seem, it is one that
never seems to lose its aptness to the fashion business, a world
where favors are really exchanges and the beautiful always get
more. Last week, Gucci flew in celebrities to grace the front row
of its men's show for the first time. It played host to Graham, who
brought a friend, the comedian Molly Shannon. Dylan McDermott came.
And so, too, did the actor Matthew McConaughey, who also brought a
friend, another actor, Cole Hauser. All were put up at the
Principe, wined and dined and, one evening, toured around Lake
Como.
</P>
<P>
   McConaughey's late-night exploits provided much of the week's
chatter, directing more attention to him than to the company that
paid the tariff. At one point, he remained at the Principe's bar
till 11 in the morning, said two people who were there. At 8 a.m.,
he called his official Gucci handler and asked to have the Gucci
retail store opened so that he could do some shopping. The weary
young woman explained he would have to wait until the scheduled
opening at 10.
</P>
<P>
   What Ford hoped to gain from the presence of an actor arguably
less famous than he is remained one of the week's presiding
mysteries. In fact, McConaughey's peripheral antics were so
entertaining that few editors seemed to find time to discuss Ford's
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Which was fortunate, in a way. Throughout his career, Ford has
given birth again and again to the somewhat degenerate 1970s
glamour boy that so many designers embraced last week. Although it
was smart for him to move on, what he delivered instead were
incomprehensible clothes lacking his usual keen irony. There were
kimono-inspired shirts, baggy drawstring leather pants, baggy,
painted jeans and swimming trunks that looked like the male answer
to the string bikini. It felt as though Ford had thrown this
together the morning after an all-nighter of kung fu movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a bit twisted, no?'' Tonchi, the Esquire editor, said
of the hustler look that typified the season. ``A bit corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a decade of sustained affluence has led fashion people to
grow bored with the commodification of genteel sensibilities that
has attended it. Prada's spring 2000 ``Belle du Jour'' collection,
with its allusions to the bourgeois woman who longs to come undone,
subversively tapped into such a mood. By the time the fall 2000
collections took place last February, fashion was selling
well-to-do women an image of themselves bordering on the vulgar and
predatory. The reference was the '80s and the brittle Alexis
Carrington sort determined to sleep her way into a destiny grander
than the one life was going to provide. It only makes sense that
men would eventually receive the same treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But do the wealthy truly hunger for the decadence that fashion
would prescribe for them? If you were to use as a yardstick ``The
Millionaire Mind,'' a best-selling study of how the real rich live
and think, there appears to be no yearning for life styles more
piquant than the mundane ones people already lead. Research on what
millionaires do with their off-hours concludes that the No. 1
favorite activity is ``consulting with a tax expert.'' Casino
gambling and yachting rank 17th and 20th, respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
