<HEADLINE>
RADKE DECIDES TO TAKE $36 MILLION AND STAY WITH TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Good news is not the norm around here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only times I can remember we ever have press conferences
are to announce someone was retiring,'' reflected said Twins
manager Tom Kelly. ``Kirby (Puckett), (Terry) Steinbach, (Paul)
Molitor. ``It's never about a signing.''
</P>
<P>
   Never say never. The Twins had an announcement Monday, and for
once, it was good news. Brad Radke, their ace righthander, has
chosen not to flee for some outdoor pasture. He instead signed a
four-year, $36 million deal to remain with a small-market team that
has gone from a two-time world champion ('87, '91) drawing in
excess of 3 million fans a year to a doormat franchise scraping to
attract half that number.
</P>
<P>
   Radke would have been eligible for free agency following this
season, and the betting was that he would wind up being sacrificed
to a contender during a midseason fire sale. But he has reupped
with the rebuilding Twins, although there is a clause in his
contract allowing him to opt out following the 2001 season, a
clause general manager Terry Ryan says he believes Radke never
would invoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think he will,'' Ryan said. ``He's a loyal kid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for Brad and his family,'' said Kelly. ``He's done a
lot for this organization, and it's nice to see good things happen
to a deserving person.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan views the signing as a reversal of fortune that could have
important ramifications for a franchise that has been victimized by
market forces and changing times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for our scouts, our business people, and
everyone in our organization,'' he said. ``It gives them hope.
We've lost some good people from our organization the past few
years, and this shows people we're headed in a positive
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Twins entered this year with a payroll of $16.5 million,
which is roughly one-sixth of the Yankees'. Ryan admits they
wouldn't have been able to sign Radke without revenue sharing,
which, according to one team official, accounts for more money than
they will take in from ticket sales. The team next will have to dig
down to keep such young talents as Matt Lawton, Jacque Jones, and
lefty Eric Milton, but not for a while, anyway. Most of their core
players are years away from arbitration and/or free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said that the Radke signing reflects the desire of owner
Carl Pohlad to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has taken the money we've gotten from revenue sharing and
put it into personnel,'' Ryan said. ``And he's tired of being
beaten up here. Mr. Pohlad is a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Radke, a 20-game winner in 1997, is 29-38 the
past three years. He is, by modern standards, a workhorse, throwing
between 213 and 232 innings in each of the past four years. He is
5-9, 3.95 this season, and will make his next start Thursday
against the Red Sox and Paxton Crawford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
