<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2257 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-OIL-PRICES-ART-368&AMP;AD     07-03 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-PRICES-ART-368&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAUDI ARABIA ANNOUNCES INCREASE IN OIL PRODUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move to bring down stubbornly high oil prices, Saudi
Arabia, the world's largest exporter of crude, announced plans to
increase production by 500,000 barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   The decision will go into effect within the next few days ``if
the price doesn't decrease,'' according to a statement from the
Saudi Arabian oil minister quoted by the official Saudi Press
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The unilateral step by the Saudis comes less than two weeks
after the 10-member Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries,
of which Saudi Arabia is the de fact leader, decided to increase
production by 708,000 barrels a day, hoping to rein in crude oil
prices that exceeded $30 a barrel. The price of crude instead rose,
driven by the disappointment in the market that the production
increase was not greater, as had been widely expected.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came after commodities markets in London
closed, and the first U.S. reaction will only become apparent after
the Independence Day holiday. Analysts said they believe the
increase in output will dampen crude oil prices. The increase most
likely comes too late to affect U.S. gasoline prices this summer,
analysts said, but they are cautiously optimistic that it will push
down prices for heating oil, which have jumped 10 percent in the
last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any additional oil supply is good news for the American
consumer,'' said John Felmy, chief economist for the American
Petroleum Institute, a trade group in Washington, D.C. ``But demand
continues to grow, so it's not clear how much prices will
decline.''
</P>
<P>
   The 500,000 barrels a day constitute a small fraction of the 75
million barrels a day the world consumes. Typically, for every $1
decrease in the price of crude oil, there follows a commensurate
2.5 cent decline in the price of gasoline and other petroleum
products.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. market will not see the first of the new oil until
early August, because it usually takes about 40 days for Persian
Gulf crude to reach American ports. By that time, gasoline prices
should be tapering off on their own as vacation season winds down
and people begin to drive less. But the oil would arrive just as
refineries begin to build stocks of heating oil for the winter.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Energy Department reported last week that inventories of
distillate, which includes diesel and heating oil, were 21 percent
lower than last year. Surging demand for diesel has drawn
distillate out of refineries as quickly as it flowed in, leading to
a rapid rise in heating oil prices. New Saudi oil could ease the
supply crunch and, as a result, help drive heating oil prices
lower, though perhaps only slightly.
</P>
<P>
   But recent production increases by OPEC have failed to reduce
crude oil prices, primarily because robust economies, especially
that of the United States, demand more oil than the cartel has so
far offered. After weathering years of depressed oil prices, OPEC
cut production drastically in March 1999 to boost prices. But once
crude oil surpassed $30 a barrel earlier this year, OPEC came under
pressure from the world's industrialized nations to raise output.
The high crude prices also worried some OPEC members, particularly
Saudi Arabia, which have seen worldwide recessions unfold because
of costly oil.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC increased output significantly this spring, with little
impact on crude prices. When cartel members met again in Vienna 10
days ago, the oil market had been primed for a second increase, on
the order of 1 million barrels a day. It was widely known that
cartel members were producing an estimated 500,000 barrels a day
more than they had agreed to in spring. So an increase of 1 million
barrels a day would have brought on the market an additional
500,000 barrels of new oil.
</P>
<P>
   When OPEC announced a more modest increase of 708,000 barrels
that would release only about 200,000 barrels of new oil, the
market essentially rejected the gesture and crude prices jumped to
more than $32 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   ``OPEC was really surprised that prices went higher after
Vienna,'' said Leonidas Drollas, chief economist with the Centre
for Global Energy Studies, a London research group. ``Most people
expected 1 million barrels a day. That would have been enough for
the soft landing that people had sought. But that seemed a bridge
too far for the hawks in OPEC.''
</P>
<P>
   Those hawkish OPEC members have little to gain by a more
substantial increase. Of the 10 active members, all but three _
Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates _ are producing
at full capacity. The other seven countries lose revenues with any
increase in output because they lack the capacity to make up for
the fall in crude prices by pumping more. That may explain why
Saudi Arabia acted swiftly and, apparently, unilaterally, although
in their statement the Saudis said they would raise output ``in
consultation with other producers.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers expect Kuwait and the Emirates to also increase
production and contribute to the additional 500,000 barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   The lopsided decision could increase tensions within the cartel,
but that is unlikely to affect Saudi Arabia's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were getting really antsy about prices not coming down
and about their inability to affect market psychology,'' said Roger
Diwan, managing director of the Petroleum Finance Corp., a
Washington consulting group. ``Now, the Saudis have taken the oil
bull market by the horns and pulled it down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
