 PERSONALS: The Anvil Chorus as Yankee Doodle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news
file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
There were July Fourth celebrations in America before the first
firecrackers were imported, in 1787, but the means of revelry _ and
dangers therein _ were different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even while the Revolutionary War raged,'' write  &UR; Warren &LR; 
 &UR; Dotz &LR; ,  &UR; Jack Mingo  &LR; and  &UR; George Moyer &LR;  in ``Firecrackers: The Art
and History'' (Ten Speed; $19.95) soldiers shot their guns into the
air, creating ``a percussive tone that continued into all future
Independence Day celebrations.''
</P>
<P>
   In rural areas, citizens ``shot the anvil,'' placing a
blacksmith's anvil on the ground, covering it with a bag of
gunpowder, topping that with a fuse, and placing another anvil
upside down atop the whole construction. When the fuse was lit,
``everybody scattered. This was to avoid being crushed like a
cartoon character, because the top anvil was propelled into the air
before returning heavily to ground. It was said you could hear the
sound of a good anvil shoot for miles.''
</P>
<P>
   Beware flying hammers and have a safe Fourth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; IT'S THE THOUGHT THAT COUNTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A Washington law clerk who consulted &UR; Newt Gingrich &LR; 's online
wedding registry and sent him a congratulatory note and a $2.50
wooden spoon from Williams-Sonoma received a handwritten thank-you
note from the former speaker of the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Jason,'' the note began. ``Thank you for your wedding
gift. Callista and I appreciate your thinking of us. Your friend,
Newt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy to see that he's observing the social niceties,''
the student,  &UR; Jason Criss &LR; , told the Washington Post. ``I sent the
spoon because I was inspired by the crassness of registering
online. I was amazed that they wanted things as banal as a 12-inch
wooden spoon. It did beg the question: Newt has been through how
many marriages and he still doesn't have a wooden spoon?''
</P>
<P>
   The Post turned to etiquette expert  &UR; Letitia Baldrige &LR; , who
ruled in favor of Gingrich. ``This young man was being a
smart-ass,'' she said, ``spoofing Newt and the wedding registry.
But I think it was lovely of Newt to send a note, even if it's all
a sham.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The  &UR; Duchess of York &LR;  told Biography magazine that come fall,
she is moving to Switzerland. Meanwhile, the first female sentry at
Buckingham Palace, Captain  &UR; Cynthia Anderson &LR;  of Australia, stood
guard at a parade on Saturday morning, July 1. Meanwhile, too, four
royal footmen have been suspended after being accused of stealing
crates of champagne after the Queen Mum's 100th birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   _ The newsletter of the Hoover Institution at Stanford reports
that  &UR; Richard Mellon Scaife &LR; , vehement anti-Clintonite and
 &UR; Vincent Foster  &LR; conspiracy theorist, has received the first Hoover
Institution Award for Uncommon Commitment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Although the actual movie depicts a lot of firepower,
 &UR; Arnold Schwarzenegger &LR;  has refused to appear holding a gun in
publicity posters for ``The Sixth Day,'' reports the Times of
London. ``If people say movies lead to violence,'' said
Schwarzenegger, ``we should make a concession.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In Sweden, Ikea has attracted new employees with hand-written
help wanted ads on the walls of rest rooms, reports the New York
Times. ``After only four days we had received 60 applications,''
said company spokesman  &UR; Jimmy Ostholm &LR; , ``four or five times what
we would get from a normal newspaper ad. In the toilet, people are
more relaxed and receptive to our message.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Nathan Lane &LR;  told Fox news that he will play the lead in a
Broadway production of ``The Producers,'' which is being written by
the movie's screenwriter/director,  &UR; Mel Brooks &LR; . Having played
 &UR; Zero Mostel &LR; 's role in ``A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the
Forum'' and planning to play his role in ``The Producers,'' Lane
said that the big role remaining is Tevye in ``Fiddler on the
Roof.'' ``And I'm not even Jewish!'' said Lane. Mostel is
``probably in heaven saying, `Cut it out, already, will you?' ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
