<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2260 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PRACTICAL-MAN04-COX     07-03 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-MAN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Here's a fish tale about profanity that got away
 &HT;    By The Practical Man
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The practical man got blessed out last
week.
</P>
<P>
   By his son.
</P>
<P>
   It happened at the Juno Beach Fishing Pier, but don't get the
practical man wrong. He's no fisherman. His child, however, is wild
to wet a line.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, the practical man has tried to nip the nonsense by telling
him the truth: Fishing's a fool's game. Invest $50 and five hours
and you'll still need luck to come home with 5 pounds of slimy
seafood. But sense doesn't score with a 12-year-old, so the
practical man downed a double-shot of Cuban coffee and headed out
at 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The pier offers two ways to waste time: Alive and frozen. If you
pick the latter, you buy a bag of rancid shrimp and spend the day
trying to snag porgies, grunts, toad fish and other bug-eyed bottom
feeders that are so bony or bloodcurdling even a starving man would
snub them. If you go live, you first kill an hour catching a bucket
full of baitfish, which swim in huge schools around the pier. Hook
these juniors on and while away hours waiting for barracudas, blue
runners, bonitos and other prettier but no more appetizing fish to
chomp.
</P>
<P>
   The practical pair went live, and that was where the cussing
came in. No sooner had they and their pier partners started jigging
for bait than boats began to appear. Huge signs warn boaters to
stay 500 feet away, but they held no sway. The mobile fishermen,
pausing before heading out into the open ocean, wanted live bait,
too, and soon a fleet of noble vessels was sauntering within a
stone's throw _ flouting the law and flaunting their wealth. The
pier-bound peasants were not amused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Read the sign!'' one hollered. ``500 feet!''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said 500 $%&AMP; feet, (at)$%&AMP;!'' bellowed another.
</P>
<P>
   And it went downhill from there as a cadre of clodhoppers united
and hurled invectives overboard, profanity raining on the boats
like a hail of pitchforks. Until, that is, they started hurling
something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll show those sons of b-----!'' cried one pier-locked looby.
This fellow tied a huge sinker onto his line, shouted ``Merry
Christmas!'' and sent the missile screaming at the nearest boat,
where it clunked the hull with a menacing thunk. His happy cast
brought a cheer from his bumpkin brethren, who immediately began
tying enormous sinkers on their own poles. But the rich-boy brigade
knew how to get even.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get a boat, losers!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, (at)$%&AMP;, aren't you my bug man?!''
</P>
<P>
   Gathered into a profane posse, the boaters then vomited a
counterbarrage of vituperation over the pier railing. Meanwhile,
the practical man was trying to decide whom to favor in this
delicate dispute. Should he cast his lot with the peasants, who had
the law on their side but brought the brouhaha to violence? Or
should he embrace the nobles, who seemed to be rubbing their boats
in the bucketheads' noses but nevertheless couldn't fish without
bait?
</P>
<P>
   It was a tough call, but then _ insight. Just as the head sinker
chucker was heaving back to fire another round, the practical man's
son spoke up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he nails those f-----!''
</P>
<P>
   ``What did you say, boy?!''
</P>
<P>
   Whereupon his son's eyes teared up and he went into mumbling
denial. He hadn't said the f-word, no sir. On the contrary, he had
wished ill on those ``suckers.''
</P>
<P>
   The practical man was tempted to ground his butt and launch a
lecture, but who was he kidding? His kid probably hears 1,000 swear
words a day on TV, in movies, on the radio, from his buddies, from
the practical man himself _ and now in a maritime melee that held
two morals: Pier rats are often as rotten as they look, and money
might buy a 27-foot Mako, but it can't buy class. Surrounded by
these gents, it was hard to blame a boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, son. Suckers it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: I am a woman who belongs to an expensive
gym. Every time I'm in there, big lugheaded muscle-brains leave
45-pound weight plates, three thick to a side, on the machines. Can
you fight my cause, Practical Man? Can you explain that it may be
easy for them to hoist those things, but other people resent their
rudeness and that they have to put away their toys?
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, the practical man isn't going head-to-head with anyone
who slaps 270 pounds on a barbell and means it. He will, however,
tangle with you.
</P>
<P>
   For about what it costs to join a gym for three months, you
could park a weight set permanently in your garage, where you could
exercise at your own pace, to your own music and not have to worry
about gym giants messing up your routine. For no money at all, you
could get a more than ample workout by doing calisthenics and
running around the block. So, for the love of God, why would you
waste money on a gym?
</P>
<P>
   That's a rhetorical question. The practical man knows the
answer, which is that you, like 90 percent of the population, think
buying something is the solution to every problem. But you can't
buy physical fitness, and if you're knuckleheaded enough to try,
get used to being in line behind lugheaded muscle-brains.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: I have a philosophical question. What is
your stance on personal technology _ cell phones, beepers, e-mail,
answering machines, etc.? Have they made the world a better place,
or worse?
</P>
<P>
   Are you kidding? These gadgets are the crowning achievements of
our age!
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones and beepers keep people connected. Important
communicados can reach you 24 hours a day. Have dinner with your
family, have a heart-to-heart with your child, make love to your
wife and not feel guilty because you're always in touch with what
matters most: The office.
</P>
<P>
   And don't get the practical man started on e-mail. How else
could you live thousands of miles away from family members and
still have a clear conscience? So what if your aging mom pours her
heart out to strangers and hires a handyman to trim her tree? At
least you told her about the weather in Oregon and her grandson's
first steps in that last electronic screed.
</P>
<P>
   JUST KIDDING!
</P>
<P>
   The practical man disses these devices for two reasons.
</P>
<P>
   First, he doesn't need them. On any given day, he knows roughly
where the people he loves are hanging out and how to get in touch
with them, either in person or by phone. He suspects cell phones,
beepers and e-mail would put him at the beck and call of people
he'd rather not hear from, so he'd rather not give them the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Second, they don't bring people together, they keep them apart.
Being close to friends and family means being there with a shoulder
to cry on, a pair of eyes to look into or a strong back to help in
the yard. It doesn't mean electronic small talk. By offering the
illusion of ``keeping in touch,'' e-mail lets loved ones live apart
guilt-free. And by intruding on face-to-face gatherings, cell
phones and beepers keep people from being entirely ``there'' in any
situation, driving a wedge between their victims and the people
they care for the most.
</P>
<P>
   Send questions and comments to The Practical Man, Accent, The
Palm Beach Post, P.O. Box 24696, West Palm Beach, Fla. 33416. Or
e-mail PracticalMan (at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
