<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: TAKING THE ADJECTIVES OUT OF MEXICAN DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MEXICO-ELECTION and related stories.) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ At 11 p.m., with the official returns showing that
Vicente Fox had seized the presidency from the governing party, the
man who went before the nation to concede defeat was not the losing
candidate, but President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had telephoned Fox to congratulate him on ``his
triumph'' and promise him a ``transparent, clean and efficient''
handover on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In another country, a president whose crowning achievement was
to hold an election in which his party was humiliated and driven
from the office it had held for seven decades probably would be
regarded as a flop. But in Mexico, where the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, has been in command for seven decades,
the loss of the presidential battle won Zedillo a much greater war
to transform this country into a working democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we have shown for all to see that ours is a nation of
free men and women who believe in the means of democracy and law to
achieve progress,'' Zedillo told Mexican viewers astonished by
Fox's showing.
</P>
<P>
   In his six years as president, Zedillo has been dogged in
pursuing the goals of political reform that he set forth early in
his term, knowing that they could ultimately lead his party into a
political winter. Enrique Krauze, a historian of the Mexican
presidency, recalls a meeting at the presidential offices in 1995
at which Zedillo, still fresh in the job, asked Krauze to look over
the draft of the speech in which he would unveil proposals for a
broad change in the Mexican electoral system.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans had long settled for the appearance of democracy.
During decades when the PRI was an untouchable single party, it
held ritual elections every six years. When real political parties
formed in the 1980s to challenge it, the PRI responded with
bribery, influence peddling and sometimes, critics said, outright
fraud to hold onto its power. Zedillo's own rise to office began in
tragedy, the assassination of the nominated PRI candidate in 1994.
In these circumstances, Mexican democracy was always described as
an ``artificial'' or ``useless'' or ``dictatorial'' one.
</P>
<P>
   Looking over his notes, Krauze recalled, Zedillo mused, ``I am
going to take all the adjectives out of Mexican democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, he did. Fox owed his victory in no small
measure to Zedillo. In his inaugural speech in 1994, the new
president had implied deficiencies in his own election and said
that Mexico needed a fairer voting system. Two years later he
pushed those electoral reforms through Congress, often over the
furious objections of the opposition parties, like Fox's, which
eventually benefited from them the most.
</P>
<P>
   The reforms created the independent elections agency that
organized the voting on July 2, the fairest election in Mexico's
history. They also provided for nearly $1 billion in public
financing for the parties' campaigns, so that Fox was able to buy
broadcast advertising time to blanket the country with his message
of change.
</P>
<P>
   All along it was clear that the big loser in the reforms was
Zedillo's own party. His policies amounted to an ultimatum. No
longer was it the domineering PRI elite's job to spread the spoils.
The president wanted the party to work for its votes.
</P>
<P>
   The need for an opening in Mexico was seared into Zedillo's
awareness before he took office. His predecessor, Carlos Salinas,
became president in a 1988 election that most Mexicans believe he
won by fraud. The tainted mandate came back to haunt Salinas after
the end of his term when the currency collapsed and his legacy was
instantly shattered, sending him into exile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
