A2262 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CAR-PETTY-COX     07-03 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PETTY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Petty bows out of Jiffy Lube 300
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kyle Petty said a few days ago that it has been difficult
returning to any track since the death of his son Adam.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday Petty announced he will not compete in Sunday's
Winston Cup race at New Hampshire International Speedway. Adam
Petty died there May 12 after wrecking in Busch practice. Steve
Grissom, who drives in the Craftsman Truck Series for Petty
Enterprises, will drive for Petty in the No. 44 Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone in New Hampshire will be pulling for the No.
44 or No. 43 (cars of Petty Enterprises) to win this weekend as
much as their own favorite car,'' said Robbie Loomis, the crew
chief for Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Grissom served in the same capacity at the Charlotte race on May
28, but failed to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe everyone can understand Kyle's feelings right now,
and I'm glad I can help out again,'' Grissom said. ``All I want to
do is help out as best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty talked Monday about New Hampshire and about his continued
mourning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at the race track and say that's what killed
Adam,'' Petty said. ``I don't look at the state of New Hampshire
and say that's what killed Adam. I know it could've happened here
or Charlotte or anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I want to go back to New Hampshire? Yeah, I want to, at
some point in time, just to tell everybody that I'm thankful for
everything they did for Adam, thank the doctors or nurses who were
at the hospital with Adam, the guys on the (track) rescue squad.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty has participated in five races since the tragedy and has
received an outpouring of fan support and standing ovations.
</P>
<P>
   The racing community also has embraced the veteran driver. Rusty
Wallace even apologized publicly for knocking Petty off the pole
after qualifying at Sears Point.
</P>
<P>
   Other Winston Cup race teams agreed with Petty's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not want to be in Kyle's situation and go up there,''
Kenny Wallace said. ``None of us could ever relate to his
situation, unless we've been through a tragedy like that ourselves.
My heart just goes out to him and his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Loomis worked for Petty Enterprises for nine years, including
the past two as crew chief for No. 43 driver John Andretti.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kyle and his family will be missed greatly this weekend,''
Loomis said. ``Anybody in his shoes could imagine how tough it
would've been for him to go up there and race.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
