<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JORDAN-MEMOIR-2TAKES-     07-03 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-MEMOIR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEMINIST SURVIVOR WITH THE EYES OF A CHILD 
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICIA R. LEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Childhood is the first, inescapable political
situation each of us has to negotiate,'' says the writer June
Jordan. ``You are powerless. You are on the wrong side in every
respect. Besides that, there's the size thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, a poet and essayist who has written on topics like
apartheid, rape and her mother's suicide, has now ventured into the
territory of childhood with ``Soldier: A Poet's Childhood,''
recently published by Basic &UR;  &LR; Books.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, 63, was in New York recently as part of a tour to
promote the book. She is a professor of African-American studies at
the University of California at Berkeley, where she also directs
the Poetry for the People project, a course for Berkeley
undergraduates that includes a program to introduce poetry to local
high school students.
</P>
<P>
   While Jordan is perhaps most identified with the leftist
political battles and feminist foment of the 1960s and '70s, she
has endured as an artistic force. Dozens of people, many of them
young, had to be turned away at a recent reading she gave at New
York University. At that event, Toni Morrison introduced her in a
kind of literary coronation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first met June Jordan, my familiarity with the lives of
activists-artists led me to wonder what would shrink first: her art
or her progressive activism,'' she told the audience. Neither has,
Morrison said. Jordan is ``as responsive to slaughter in Baghdad as
she is to rape in the kitchen, as outraged by state lies as she is
made delirious by love,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's oeuvre includes poetry, plays, novels, essays,
children's books and the libretto for John Adams' 1995 opera ``I
Was Looking at the Ceiling and Then I Saw the Sky.'' While her work
has been criticized at times as politically strident, it has also
been praised as frank and mellifluous.
</P>
<P>
   A brief review by Johanna Berkman for The New York Times faulted
Jordan's 1998 book, ``Affirmative Acts: Political Essays''
(Anchor/Doubleday), for example, for ``a far-fetched attempt to
extract political significance from her oral surgery,'' as well as
``frequent use of the overwrought prose of politically correct
cliche.'' ``Still,'' the reviewer concluded, ``her lyric writing is
a powerful mix of the inspirational and the dispiriting.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan writes by hand at her dining room table. ``Soldier'' was
a sometimes wrenching journey, she said, because many of her
memories were painful. It took three months of reviewing notebook
jottings about characters and structure before she wrote her first
sentence. She decided the best approach was to write the book with
the consciousness of a child, without the filter of adult
perceptions and judgments.
</P>
<P>
   She reports beatings at the hands of her father, Granville
Ivanhoe Jordan, this way: ``Like a growling beast, the roll-away
mahogany doors rumble open, and the light snaps on and a fist
smashes into the side of my head and I am screaming awake: `Daddy!
What did I do?!'
</P>
<P>
   ``And now he lays on a belt, slapping the leather and the buckle
hard against the blankets or my arm exposed by short-sleeve
teddy-bear pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I am trying to cover my face and he tears away the
blankets and I can barely recognize this man, my father.''
</P>
<P>
   There are happier memories, too. She recalls her first date in a
torrent of words: ``And then there was Herbie Wilson Jr. ringing
the bell. And I went to the gate to open it and he was wearing a
tie and a new suit and the old lace-up shoes he always liked to
wear and we went to the city and we watched this play about a white
girl with her Negro `Mammy' looking after her and at one point the
girl uses this huge knife to slice at something on her foot and
that made the biggest impression on me about `Member of the
Wedding' except for afterward when Herbie Wilson Jr. took me to the
Times Square Crossroads Cafe and we sat at this tiny table with a
blue-and-white checkered tablecloth and he ordered strawberry
shortcake for both of us and a bottle of beer for himself and a
glass of milk for me and I felt pretty sure I must look all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said: ``I feel very proud to try to contribute to the
literature on girls. We have a lot about boys. This story of a
black child, a poet, a girl, is claiming space for those various
groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan grew up in Harlem and Brooklyn, reading Shakespeare and
Edgar Allan Poe before she turned 5, she says. Her family moved
from a Harlem housing project to the Bedford-Stuyvesant area in
Brooklyn because it seemed like a better place to raise a family.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``Soldier'' is a sparely written kaleidoscope of the young June
at school and at home, learning about love and books, about being
smart and being a girl. She recalls her father's using a pot of
boiling water to scald an annoying, howling cat under their window.
And she remembers savoring the feeling of escape in climbing an
apple tree at Robin Hood Camp in ``the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The memoir ends with her scoring high on an intelligence test
and winning a scholarship to the Northfield School for Girls, (now
the coed Northfield-Mount Hermon School) in Massachusetts. Her
father takes her to Track 22 in Grand Central Terminal and tells
his little soldier, ``You gwine make me proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Mildred Maude Jordan, is depicted in ``Soldier'' as
a mysteriously troubled woman in retreat from herself and the
world. Her mother did not assert herself when her husband beat
their only child or insistently referred to his daughter as ``he,''
Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan does not call her father abusive. He also forced her
to memorize long passages of literature and poetry. The book is
dedicated to him, the man who inadvertently paved the way for her
entry into her own world of words.
</P>
<P>
   That is not what her parents intended, she laughed. Doctors, not
poets, are what first-generation immigrant families want, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's parents came from Jamaica. Her father, a postal clerk,
was half Chinese, a self-taught ``race man'' who admired Marcus
Garvey but made derogatory comments about the darker skin of his
wife and his daughter. Her mother was a nurse. The parents often
fought over money, manners and their daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my father,'' Jordan said. ``And he was crazy. He
associated social humiliation with racial identity. He didn't want
what happened to him to happen to me, and it would happen if I was
black and if I was female.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the beatings, she said: ``Anyone can come up with an
adjective, a pejorative. I had committed myself to writing this in
the consciousness of a child, which meant making no judgments. I
hope in a way this is very good news: I'm OK. One can reasonably
say some pretty dire things about my folks, but I love my father.
I'm here to say, I'm here; I'm OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing from a child's perspective was difficult because it
involved shutting out the day-to-day demands of adulthood, said
Jordan, who has a grown son. It was challenging to reconstruct her
life in prose rather than poetry, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was winding up, ready to sing,'' she said. ``I was afraid if
it was poetry, people wouldn't read it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing should be a poem,''except that too many people
fear poetry, Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   In her Poetry for the People course (Jordan calls it a
``movement''), students study the poetry of three cultures each
year and the ways those cultures shape writers. This year they are
surveying Arab, African-American and Chicano cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only in the African-American segment of poetry that you
find people talking about freedom, over and over again,'' she said.
``Why is that? Why do you find the incredible emphasis on the fact
that you exist, the `I am.' You can't understand that until you
understand the history.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan describes herself as a soldier trying to see the world
anew and report her sightings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident that things are changing in a way that is
profound and helpful,'' she said. ``Those of us who have mothers
and fathers who came over here are the children of unlimited
expectations, and those expectations attach themselves to the
abstract idea that is the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise, that would be dishonoring what motivated them _
despite extraordinary contempt and disregard'' for who they are in
their adopted land, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2265 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ELECTIONS-0704     07-03 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTIONS-0704-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOX FACES DAUNTING TASK OF LEADING MEXICO IN TRANSITION FROM 71
YEARS OF ONE-PARTY STATE
 &HT;    EDS: Story will be updated after Fox-Zedillo meeting ends.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Just hours after toppling the country's ruling
party, president-elect Vicente Fox
</P>
<P>
   rolled up his trademark blue shirtsleeves Monday and began
charting a transition toward Mexico's first opposition federal
government in seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   The task will be daunting.
</P>
<P>
   When he takes office Dec. 1, Fox will inherit a troubled country
of stark inequality with a political and social infrastructure that
evolved over 71 years under the ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI. That framework includes a federal bureaucracy and
labor unions tied to the PRI which many Mexicans believe are
riddled with corruption and inefficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Fox met with President Ernesto Zedillo of the defeated ruling
party Monday evening in an unprecedented session designed to
underscore a commitment to a peaceful change of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot fail because we have awakened too many expectations,
too many dreams and desires,'' an ecstatic Fox said Monday in a
Mexico City radio interview after his convincing victory in a
three-way race. With 93 percent of the vote counted, he was nearly
7 percentage point ahead of his second-place PRI opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reiterate my invitation to a government of concordance that
we are going to form, to a unity of Mexican men and women, to an
inclusive project with ideas from everyone, but also for work for
everyone,'' Fox said in a separate televised interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all going to have to work,'' he said. ``Today is barely
the starting point to construct a great nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The president-elect has said he will try to boost job
development with more investment and credit for small businesses.
He has pledged to root out corruption and government ties to drug
trafficking, which has become a sore point between Mexico and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   He also pledged to continue to reach out to Mexican immigrants
in the United States. His plan is a plural government that will
negotiate policies based on ideas from right to left, including
experts from the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton telephoned Fox to congratulate him and later
issued a statement calling the Sunday's elections a ``vivid
testimony to the depth of the democratic commitment of the Mexican
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Former President Jimmy Carter, who was on an election
observation mission here, praised speeches Zedillo, Fox and the
losers made after the outcome became clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will set a tone for the next five months of
transition that will be very beneficial for Mexico,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a former Coca-Cola executive and rancher, is a member of
Mexico's conservative, free-market National Action Party, or PAN.
But he ran as a broad-based coalition candidate _ under the banner
of the Alliance for Change _ with Mexico's small environmentalist
Green Party.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of jubilant street celebrations, analysts compared
the magnitude of Fox's triumph to the collapse of the Berlin Wall.
For seven decades _ a lifetime _ the PRI has controlled the
presidency and most other political offices.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic reforms that have taken effect in recent years _ a
freer press, fairer campaign rules and a new balloting system to
combat fraud _ helped clear the way for an opposition victory.
</P>
<P>
   Fox supporter Cecilia Suarez, 40, a television casting director,
said, ``Thank God we saw change before we die.''
</P>
<P>
   Javier Trevino, a spokesman for defeated PRI candidate Francisco
Labastida, said, ``We have heard the message of the people. We have
heard the message of change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The defeat of the PRI alone is enough to dramatically change
Mexico's political system,'' said political analyst Jose Antonio
Crespo.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's media, less chained but still beholden to the federal
government, will inevitably become more independent, with no clear
master to serve, Crespo said.
</P>
<P>
   A mix of parties in the Mexican Senate and Chamber of Deputies
will provide a democratic balance, Crespo said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has already tried to ``heal'' divisions among all parties,
including Mexico's leftist Democratic Revolution Party, whose
candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas came in third.
</P>
<P>
   In post-election statements, Crespo said, Cardenas was not
especially conciliatory toward Fox. But leftists are already on
Fox's team and others will inevitably join his government, Crespo
said.
</P>
<P>
   An obvious risk for Fox is if Mexicans, especially those of the
left, do not believe his government is dealing satisfactorily with
the country's overwhelming problems of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``An authoritarian regime sometimes generates fantasies that
democracy is a magic wand,'' Crespo said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has raised expectations that corruption might be better
controlled, a difficult task in a country with a tradition of
bribes and low salaries. During his campaign he said he wouldn't
conduct ``witch hunts'' to identify corrupt officials, but would
seek to punish high-profile perpetrators who have raided public
treasuries or consorted with criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between July 3 and Dec. 1,'' Fox said in a pre-election
interview, ``there will be a lot of files burned.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox has assumed a more statesmanlike posture since Sunday night,
taking Zedillo at his word that he will guarantee a smooth,
transparent transition.
</P>
<P>
   Some federal government workers who voted for the PRI said they
feared that if Fox were to win, he would fire massive numbers of
public employees and abolish unions. Some impoverished Mexicans
said they were told Fox would cut welfare benefits for children or
crop subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Fox ran television commercials to counter these rumors. But he
is clear in his goal to improve government subsidy programs to make
them more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   As a PAN governor of Guanajuato state, he streamlined government
and started a system of merit pay on top of salaries, said
University of Guanajuato political analyst Luis Miguel Rionda.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first the workers reacted with fear. Most people just
wanted guaranteed security, not merit pay,'' Rionda said. But
younger government officials now appear to like the system, which
is viewed as a substitute for arbitrary bonuses that have
traditionally been used in Mexico to threaten workers and guarantee
loyalty to the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Government-employee unions linked to the PRI are going to have
to evolve or face competition from independent unions that could
now advance, Rionda said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the bureaucracy is still tied to the PRI,
however,'' Rionda said. ``So Fox is going to have to be careful and
try to reach out to them to include them.''
</P>
<P>
   On election night, members of PRI unions and neighborhood
organizations sobbed openly or stood stone-faced when they heard
the news that their party had finally been defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI was born in power, so the question is can it
survive,'' said Rionda. The party emerged from the tumult of the
Mexican Revolution, which began in 1910 and raged for another
decade. It has shed its ideological skin many times and slid from
socialism to capitalism whenever global conditions seemed
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said the party he toppled had no ideology at all anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Trevino, a PRI activist in his late 30s, said the party has to
reflect on its future.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of its crushing defeat, he conceded, ``Many people
are shocked. We need to take this as an opportunity for young PRI
members like myself to craft a new message.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' e-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
