<HEADLINE>
`SHY' TV BRIDE BARES ALL. WHAT'S NEXT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A random collection of random thoughts because, hey, it's a
holiday. Besides, would you really want to see a whole column on
any of these topics?
</P>
<P>
   _Darva Conger _ you remember: the ever-so-brief bride of ``Who
Wants To Marry a Multimillionaire?'' _ succumbed to Playboy's
blandishments and doffed her duds, so who's next? The wicked women
of ``Survivor?'' The brash babes of ``Big Brother?'' Whatever and
whenever, these (air)brushes with fame will no doubt be handled
with style and good taste to protect the participants', uh,
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   _Envelope, please. The Heights of Hypocrisy Award goes to NBC
for scheduling three hours of previously unaired ``Freaks and
Geeks'' episodes Saturday. ``Freaks'' fans are eternally grateful,
no doubt, but the unmitigated chutzpah of cashing in on the show's
``critical acclaim'' _ NBC uses the term in its promotional
material _ is about as classy as burping at a funeral. If the show
is so good, why was it canceled?
</P>
<P>
   _While we're on the subject of senseless cancellations, it turns
out that ``Sports Night'' will not be resurrected on premium cable.
HBO and ``Sports Night'' creator Aaron Sorkin, who also does ``The
West Wing'' for NBC, couldn't agree on a plan that would let Sorkin
continue writing each episode of ``Sports Night,'' which ABC
canceled after two seasons. 'Tis a pity.
</P>
<P>
   _Football purists are leery about having Dennis Miller in the
``Monday Night Football'' broadcast booth. They seem to think ABC's
telecasts of neckless guys in tight pants committing sanctioned
thuggery is nobler than, say, standup comedy, and therefore
deserving of more specialized commentary. They forget that the late
Howard Cosell, who wrote the book on ``Monday Night Football''
punditry, was an erudite, acerbic non-sportscaster with a gift for
gab and an opinion on everything. So relax, football fans. Now
comes Miller time. Can't wait.
</P>
<P>
   _Sydney Olympics, the local angle: NBC expects to use 16,000
pounds of Starbucks coffee during the summer games, enough to make
320,000 cups of kick-start. (NBC's calculations, not mine.) With
1,800 staffers working the games, that's roughly 178 cups per
employee over three weeks (allowing for setup and take-down), or
8.5 cups a day. No estimate on the number of bathroom breaks.
</P>
<P>
   _Speaking of which, NBC will be testing our bladders by
scheduling only 18 minutes of commercials per hour during the
Sydney Olympics. Four years ago in Atlanta, NBC averaged 19 minutes
per hour.
</P>
<P>
   _Wouldn't want one in the house, and if I see another commercial
for it I may rethink my position on gun control, but Boogie Bass
and its competitor, Big Mouth Billy Bass, are the latest things to
get people around this country buzzing. Go figure. A wriggling,
singing fish-on-plywood is hotter than Britney Spears on a Dallas
sidewalk. Then again, the fish sing better.
</P>
<P>
   _The only thing airing more often than Boogie Bass commercials
last weekend was the ongoing gush fest over Experience Music
Project. MTV and VH1 replaced the print media in fawning over Paul
Allen's monument to American rock with repeated airings of a
program featuring slices of the EMP-launch concerts at Memorial
Stadium. Best Chamber of Commerce moment came when Kurt Loder asked
Richard Patrick of the band Filter: ``Is it worth a trip to
Seattle?'' Patrick's reply: ``Definitely.'' Now can I have my old
MTV back?
</P>
<P>
   _Protesters 1, Dr. Laura O? The TV critics' summer press tour,
which begins Friday in Pasadena, Calif., will have to go on without
Dr. Laura Schlessinger. The tart-tongued radio talker was scheduled
to appear on Day One of the three-week clambake highlighting new
fall fare, but Paramount, the studio producing Schlessinger's
syndicated TV show, opted out. No official reason given, but a
vigorous ``Stop Dr. Laura'' movement by the gay community is happy
to take partial credit. Procter &AMP; Gamble also has decided not to
advertise on the weekday series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
