<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2268 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BLACKBEARD04-COX     07-03 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKBEARD04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Amy L. Royster
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOOREHEAD CITY, N.C. _ On the anniversary of Blackbeard's death,
Phil Masters received a phone call he will never forget.
</P>
<P>
   It was Nov. 26, 1996. His company, Intersal, had just wrapped up
a 10-day search for Blackbeard's ship, Queen Anne's Revenge. He had
returned to his full-time job in New York the day before. Director
of operations Mike Daniels remained in Beaufort for one last day on
the company's last dime.
</P>
<P>
   From the deck of their search boat Pelican, Daniels dialed
Master's number.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sitting down?'' he asked. ``The boat broke. She's
sinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Masters remembers saying, ```Well, we did the best we could. Try
to save the boat.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Daniels interrupted laughing, ``Phil, I'm anchored over a
pile of cannons and anchors.''
</P>
<P>
   The pile turned out to be a significant find for underwater
archaeology _ one rich in artifacts. But, in terms of traditional
treasure, the site believed to be Queen Anne's Revenge is a bust.
</P>
<P>
   No one really expected any different. Researchers knew
Blackbeard had time to relieve the ship of valuables. Her allure,
according to Masters, was always in the chase.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for loot is, in essence, what Intersal is all about,
but chests of gold are not what turn Masters on _ he swears. It's
the challenge of piecing together history that motivates him.
</P>
<P>
   That they found the vessel 278 years to the day of Blackbeard's
bloody death near Ocracoke is a sign to Masters that he values
history more than the next guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blackbeard wanted us to find him. He knew we would treat him
with respect,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Respect is not a word always used in reference to professional
salvors. An antagonistic history exists between underwater
archaeologists, whose primary concern is preservation, and salvors,
whose primary concern is profit. The most notable argument between
the two camps was the high-profile case of Mel Fisher, whose
company found the Atocha off the coast of Florida, and then fought
the state all the way to the Supreme Court over her multimillion
dollar bounty. Fisher won, but the stink is legendary.
</P>
<P>
   Masters insists that his relationship with the state of North
Carolina is unique. David Moore, site director for the Queen Anne's
Revenge Project and coordinator of maritime archaeology at the N.C.
Maritime Museum, agrees. Despite retaining a permit entitling him
to the majority of the artifacts, Masters gave the wreck over to
the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few salvors out there who would have turned
Queen Anne's Revenge over to the state,'' Moore said. ``Now, he
wanted something out of it, which he got, but it's true that it's
unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   What Intersal got out of the bargain were two principal rights:
They have the exclusive right to make limited-edition
museum-quality replicas _ not plastic swords. And they own the
media rights.
</P>
<P>
   The BBC had to get Masters' approval before filming a recent
documentary. His deal with the BBC? Intersal gets access to BBC
footage for its own upcoming documentary.
</P>
<P>
   The media attention, in addition to the relationship Masters
maintains with the State Underwater Archaeology Unit (UAU), is good
business. ``Working on Queen Anne's Revenge gave us publicity, it
gave us credibility and it put us on the map,'' he says. ``The
Blackbeard mystique, I call it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Daniels remains devoted to helping the state's Queen
Anne's Revenge Project through a branch of Intersal named MRI,
Masters is on to bigger fish _ namely, the El Salvador. This
18th-century two-masted, 110-ton Spanish vessel is different from
Queen Anne's Revenge in a big way _ she's full of loot. Masters
says research shows the ship sunk near Queen Anne's Revenge with
four chests of gold and three times as many of silver. Intersal
conservatively estimates her value at $124 million, and their
permit from the state entitles them to 75 percent of whatever they
find.
</P>
<P>
   If the site proves positive, Intersal would have to stop, inform
the state, obtain a more specific permit for excavation, hire an
archaeologist, build a lab and develop an archaeology plan approved
by the state. This would take years and between $5 to $10 million
to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   But that's nothing compared to what Masters believes has the
potential for being ``the richest treasure of the New World.'' He
is hopeful that undocumented treasure aboard El Salvador could send
her potential payoff into the hundreds of millions.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of treasure is attractive. Three other companies have
permits to search for El Salvador in other areas off North Carolina
. Masters is sure he is in the right place.
</P>
<P>
   ``To blow my own horn, the thing I'm really good at is the
research,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His knack for research certainly helped locate Queen Anne's
Revenge. In the 1980s, hot on the trail of El Salvador, Masters
read a research paper written by Moore, then an East Carolina
University graduate student, on Blackbeard's lost treasures.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, he met with Moore and decided to pursue Queen
Anne's Revenge in addition to El Salvador because of the likelihood
of their proximity to one another. His re-examination of the
research led him to the New York Public Library where he found a
previously overlooked deposition including an eyewitness testimony,
of the sinking of Queen Anne's Revenge in the Beaufort Inlet in
1718.
</P>
<P>
   For the history junkie in him, ``It was a moment even more
exciting than when we actually found the ship.''
</P>
<P>
   If Masters' research skills prove magic again, he may hit it
big. Otherwise, at 63, he isn't giving up. If it's not her,
Intersal has at least 50 more sites in the Beaufort Inlet to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Without a trace of doubt in his voice, he says _ ``She's out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
