<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLAR RETAINS LEAD DESPITE CRASHING 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France _ Tom Steels, a Belgian sponsored by Mapei, won
his second successive stage Monday by sprinting to victory in the
100-mile race from the hospitable town of Loudun to this city in
western France.
</P>
<P>
   David Millar retained the yellow jersey of the overall leader
despite crashing with about a mile left.
</P>
<P>
   Steels was clocked in 3 hours 37 minutes 51 seconds for the ride
along rolling terrain in cool weather.
</P>
<P>
   The same time was given to Marcel Wust, a German sprinter with
the Festina team from Spain, who finished second by inches to
Steels. Erik Zabel, a German with Telekom, was in third place with
the same time as were 22 others.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger pack that finished nine seconds behind included Lance
Armstrong, the defending champion, who is second over all in this
race, and Millar, a Scot with Cofidis and the man ahead of
Armstrong by four seconds after three of the 21 stages.
</P>
<P>
   Millar crashed into a crowd barrier with about 1.5 kilometers to
go and was left behind by the riders charging for the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd lost the yellow jersey there,'' Millar said.
</P>
<P>
   With no teammate inexplicably at his side to assist him, Millar
had trouble slipping the bicycle chain back on its ring so that he
could pedal. Finally he got going again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sprinted all out to catch the pack,'' Millar said.
</P>
<P>
   He did hook on and, since Armstrong was in the same group _ and
not the one that was ahead by nine seconds _ the Scot continues
another day in the leader's jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Laurent Jalabert, a Frenchman with ONCE, is third over all, six
seconds behind, and Jan Ullrich, a German with Telekom, is fourth,
seven seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
   Millar seems unlikely to be wearing the yellow jersey after a
long team time trial on Tuesday because his Cofidis colleagues have
been working hard the last two days at the head of the pack,
chasing breakaways to protect their leader's edge.
</P>
<P>
   The team time trial, over 43.5 miles, is expected to be the
first big challenge of the 87th Tour and possibly the only one
before the race starts to sort itself out next week in the
Pyrenees.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its imminence, the race against the clock was not a
subject of conversation Monday among the riders. They preferred to
talk soccer, specifically the European Championship, which was won
by France over Italy on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't watch the match,'' said Paul Van Hyfte, a Belgian
with Lotto. ``I don't have any interest in teams from France and
Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   He was more than willing, however, to discuss the Belgian team
in Euro 2000, an early casualty.
</P>
<P>
   Both Roland Meier, a Swiss with Cofidis, and Jesper Skibby, a
Dane with Memory Card, said that they felt they had more difficult
jobs than the men on the soccer pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have hard work, but it's not an everyday job like this,''
Meier said.
</P>
<P>
   Even less respectful was Wurst, Monday's runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're paid too much money for what they do,'' Wurst
said of soccer players. ``This Euro 2000, they've been going three
and a half weeks and they did 10 hours' work in three weeks. We do
that in two days sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Rodriguez, an American with the Mapei team from Italy,
said: ``I watched it a little bit. It wasn't that interesting to
me. It was more interesting to watch my teammates go crazy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
