<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-BERTELSMANN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERTELSMANN COMMITMENT TO LYCOS DEAL INTACT, CEO SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The chief executive of German publisher Bertelsmann AG says he
remains committed to a planned alliance with Waltham, Mass. Lycos
Inc., although Bertelsmann's exact obligations were revised
downward last week.
</P>
<P>
   When Lycos and its would-be buyer, Spain's Terra Networks,
announced their merger on May 16, they said Bertelsmann planned to
pay their combined company $1 billion over five years for
advertising and e-commerce services. In a filing June 28, Terra
disclosed that Bertelsmann is only ``obliged'' to pay $325 million
and that Terra's parent, Telefonica SA, would replace up to $675
million worth of orders Bertelsmann might cancel.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday, Bertelsmann chief executive Thomas
Middelhoff called it ``very, very unlikely'' his company would
spend less than the full $1 billion. He also said Bertelsmann
expects to go ahead with a plan to acquire a stake in Terra Lycos
in three years or so.
</P>
<P>
   But Middelhoff said Lycos chief executive Bob Davis was right to
insist Telefonica guarantee Bertelsmann's payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great for (Lycos) shareholders, because nobody knows what
will happen in the next three to four years in the Internet
world,'' Middelhoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelsmann's exact role in Terra Lycos has been unclear to
some.
</P>
<P>
   The new venture is counting on access to Bertelsmann's big array
of record and movie studios, books, and magazine titles, all needed
to attract online viewers.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Bertelsmann is barred from investing in Terra Lycos
directly, under its agreements with America Online, once a close
ally until it moved to buy Time Warner Inc. this year.
</P>
<P>
   Middelhoff said Bertelsmann is still committed to paying Lycos
competitor AOL $250 million for advertising over four years, in a
deal announced in March. ``We're best friends,'' he said of America
Online Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But Bertelsmann's relationship with Terra Lycos will go further,
he said. ``It's a special kind of alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Terra's filing mentioned various risks for Terra
Lycos it hadn't previously highlighted. One section of the document
was titled ``Risks Related to Being Part of the Telefonica Group.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Terra noted that other Telefonica companies
``could compete with us, and they may pursue their own
Internet-related business.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Telefonica's Argentine telecommunications unit also
runs an Internet portal targeting the same home users Terra Lycos
aims to attract, the filing said.
</P>
<P>
   Another risk is that Internet use in Latin America may grow more
slowly than expected. Terra said it received 73 percent of its
revenue from Latin American operations. And Terra warned its
free-Internet access offerings in Spain, Brazil, Mexico, and other
countries could prove costly.
</P>
<P>
   A Terra representative in New York declined to elaborate on the
details.
</P>
<P>
   Terra also outlined new five-year employment agreements for
senior Lycos executives including Davis, who would be chief
executive of the new venture.
</P>
<P>
   Davis would get a base salary and bonus of $500,000, plus a $5
million payment in case of severance. He would also receive options
to acquire 2 million Terra Lycos shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
