A2272 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DIGITAL-SIGNATURE-NYT     07-03 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SIGNATURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL SIGNATURE LAW LIKELY TO SPEED UP E-BUSINESS DEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The law that President Clinton signed last week allowing
businesses and consumers to seal a wide variety of legally binding
arrangements with electronic rather than handwritten signatures
raised the speed limit on e-business development, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   They project that many enterprises awash in documents,
especially financial services, real estate and government itself,
will accelerate efforts to use computer transactions to limit
paperwork once the law takes effect in October. Such a transition
is expected to save billions of dollars annually in administrative
costs and cut some online transactions _ like setting up a trading
account or applying for a home loan _ from days to minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be taking a look at every place we require signatures on
a case-by-case basis,'' said Greg Gable, a spokesman for Charles
Schwab &AMP; Co., the stock broker. ``Convenience is important, and if
a new capability has value, you can't afford not to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``E-signing,'' as the new process is called, is also expected to
spur a variety of technologies that provide digital variations on
penning one's name on paper, including the use of coded messages,
pen-like styluses or thumbprints on electronic pads, or camera
shots of the signer's face or eye.
</P>
<P>
   The new federal law came after 46 states and many foreign
countries had adopted laws encouraging online deal-making, and many
online businesses have already incorporated such capabilities. So
it may be hard to calculate the immediate financial impact of the
federal law on the major companies supplying such technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It validates the market, but it won't really add to their
revenue in the near term,'' said Mark Fernandes of Merrill Lynch,
who studies companies that provide the software and support
services needed for electronic business.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, because the law is careful not to favor any particular
technology for signing contracts electronically, it does nothing to
alter the scramble for dominance in the new field. The core of the
business for now belongs to a group of companies, including
VeriSign, Entrust Technologies, RSA and Baltimore Technologies,
that provide ways for those doing business online to use coded
messages and electronic ``certificates'' to complete their
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   All of them rely on public key encryption, a technology invented
in the 1970s but not widely used until the e-commerce wave hit the
Internet. Such systems use a combination of public and private
keys, or snippets of numbers, to pass secure messages through a
trusted third party, or certification authority. The system not
only allows a recipient to be assured the message came from the
party that claims to have sent it, but also that it has not been
tampered with.
</P>
<P>
   The digital signature such systems produce looks nothing like a
scrawled John Hancock _ in fact, it is invisible. As a result, many
entrepreneurs are betting that other systems will be used instead
of public-key encryption, or in addition to it, to complete
e-commerce deals.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton signed the bill into law on Friday with a smart card _ a
credit card-sized device programmed to work in combination with a
password furnished by the user. Such systems are already widely
used in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   One company hoping to benefit is Signature-mail.com, based in
Greenwich, Conn., which allows users to attach a picture of their
actual signature to e-mail. The company's founders figure such a
device may well be unacceptable as a legal e-signature since anyone
could hit the computer key to send it and hackers might easily
forge it. Still, says Michael Lloyd, a Signature-mail co-founder,
such a feature might be attractive to companies like VeriSign as an
added element to make their encryption products more consumer
friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Silanis Technology Inc. of Montreal already has a business
software program to append visual signatures to documents, but its
software makes it impossible to detach the signature, forward the
document without it or alter the document once it is added. It is
designed for use with the public-key systems. Michael Laurie, vice
president of alliances for Silanis, said that in response to the
new law his company had set up a new business called OnSign.com to
distribute free e-signature software to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Communication Intelligence Corp., based in Redwood Shores,
Calif., and PenOp, a privately held New York company, have also bet
that the human signature may retain a role in e-signing. Both
companies have systems for authenticating who is signing a document
based on how the name is written on a digital pad, but what counts
is the pattern of pressures on the pad they are scanning rather
than the visible shapes _ a form of biometrics.
</P>
<P>
   Others say signatures will be overtaken in many applications by
other biometric attributes that are unique to individuals, such as
digitized thumbprints _ possibly captured by placing thumbs to a
pad on the computer keyboard _ or images of the retina of the eye.
In some applications, people might ``sign'' by speaking, relying on
the computer to recognize their voice or some code word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because this legislation is technology neutral, you can use
anything that can be fixed to an individual,'' said Anabella
Hallawell, an analyst for the Gartner Group, a Stamford,
Conn.-based technology consulting and research firm. Hallawell said
she expects strong demand for companies like Valicert that can
manage multiple verification technologies for companies running
e-business sites. Such service providers will also help the
companies keep track of all of the consumer protection requirements
written into the law, such as the restrictions on cutting off
utility service without written notice.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the original public-key encryption companies like
VeriSign and Entrust have long since begun migrating toward
providing a full range of management services to e-business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new law sends a message to the business community that
e-signatures are OK,'' said Kevin Coleman, a specialist on Internet
security issues for KPMG. ``This will be a case of a rising tide
lifting all the boats.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
