<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2273 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-DIERKER-HN     07-03 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-DIERKER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Dierker weathers Astros' first-to-worst decline
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   For three years, Astros manager Larry Dierker was one of the
smartest men in baseball. Now, he's one of the dumbest.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not really, but you'd think so by listening to fans, media
and even some of his players. That's what happens when your team
has the worst record in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   A half-season removed from becoming just the fourth manager to
guide his team to first-place finishes in his first three years,
Dierker finds himself under fire as the leader of a team that has
greatly underachieved.
</P>
<P>
   Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. and general manager Gerry
Hunsicker repeatedly have said Dierker's job security will not be
an issue for the remainder of the season. However, as he does after
each season, McLane will re-evaluate the ballclub from top to
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   While the vote of confidence for the remainder of the season no
doubt was at least partially designed to keep the issue from
becoming a distraction, it's pretty clear there is a faction of the
team that is not in Dierker's corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there is,'' said Dierker, who pitched in the big
leagues for 14 seasons. ``I haven't really sensed it as much as I
assume it. I haven't felt it or seen it. It's nothing that's
tangible, but I have to imagine it's going on. The most difficult
thing when a team is losing or underachieving is that there comes a
time when the players think that maybe there's going to be a
management change.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, it's not a conscious decision, but the teams I
was on like that, it seemed like guys would just be treading water
and waiting for something to happen that would create a fresh
start. Of course, we had hoped that would happen with the (Astros'
recent) coaching changes, but really it's gotten even worse. But I
don't think there's any way to change that, other than to start
winning some games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are wanting a breath of fresh air, something that will
signify that things are going to change or could change,'' Dierker
continued. ``A lot of the teams that I was on, guys were just
waiting for the manager to go, and while they were waiting, they
weren't necessarily playing their best. They weren't consciously
trying not to play their best, but it's just like you're waiting
for something to happen instea of trying to go out and make
something happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite a bit must happen if the Astros are to avoid setting a
franchise record for losses. While Dierker is the man who led the
Astros to a franchise-record 102 wins in 1998, they are on pace to
lose 106 games this season, which would shatter the franchise mark
of 97 losses, accomplished three times, most recently in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros must go 35-46 over the second half of the season to
avoid the embarrassment of losing 100 games. That would require
playing at a .432 clip, a significant upgrade over their .346
winning percentage during the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, players win and lose games. But the manager
generally gets more credit than he deserves when the team is
winning and more blame than warranted when it is losing.
</P>
<P>
   And while there are differences in philosophy and strategy
between players and managers on every team, they're magnified when
the club is struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dealing with the players doesn't seem to be any more difficult
now than it did when we were winning,'' Dierker said. ``They all
have their own wants, needs and desires, whether you're winning or
losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sense that there is a greater level of dissatisfaction in
losing, and there's a tendency for people in whatever occupation _
or whether it's their family life or whatever _ when they have
problems to shift the blame or the responsibility away from
themselves and onto others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, this is the ultimate place on a team _ the manager.
And yet I think because I haven't just blown up or gone crazy, it's
been minimal compared to what it could be. But it's still more
compared to if we were winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Dierker has yet to blow up on his team, but there have
been a few tense moments with the media, particularly on the most
recent road trip, when the Astros won only two of seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, the monotony of losing has made the normally
laid-back manager a bit testy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a little irritable right after games, but I can usually
get that out of my system fairly quickly,'' said Dierker, who spent
18 seasons on the club's broadcast team before taking over as
manager. ``I haven't had any trouble sleeping. After a game is the
worst _ when someone asks me what the level of frustration is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they don't have any way of knowing that everyone has
been asking me that for months. What I thought would be the easiest
part of the job has been the most difficult. Going into this, I
thought the media part would be easy, because I was used to it. But
the same questions over and over again is like torture.''
</P>
<P>
   McLane will have the final say regarding what happens to Dierker
after the season. But whatever happens, it's a safe bet Dierker
will take it in stride. When you've been in the game nearly all
your life, you come to realize managers are hired to be fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are streaks and slumps in managing just like there are
in playing,'' said Dierker, who has two years and $1.5 million
remaining on his contract after this season. ``When you're
streaking, everything seems to work. And when you're slumping,
you're trying your best to help the team win, but it seems like a
lot of things just backfire. We've had a lot of meetings; we've
tried different lineups; we've had a players-only meeting, coaching
changes. No one is satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   With a record of 28-53, no one should be.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
