<HEADER>
A2276 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CARGO-COX     07-03 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARGO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHAT IS ATLANTA?
 &HT;    City a truck, rail powerhouse
 &HT;    Eds: This is the third in a series of five articles.
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Twice a day, almost on cue with the snarling traffic
along the city's highways, hundreds of truck drivers swerve into
Norfolk-Southern's Inman Yard to pick up or drop off containers
full of computers, auto parts and other goods.
</P>
<P>
   By noon, some 400 truckers will unload up to four trains, each
about a mile long, loaded with goods headed for malls, factories
and construction sites.
</P>
<P>
   At about 3 p.m, the tide reverses. An equally large stream of
truckers rolls in the Northwest Atlanta railyard, pulling bus-sized
metal boxes packed with consumer goods and other items headed for
every point on the compass, from Asia to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The nightly exodus of intermodal traffic _ cargo carried by
rail, truck and ship _ won't slack off until well after the evening
rush hour ends.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, a hundred Norfolk Southern trains rumble in and out of
Atlanta. Hundreds of carloads of coal come from Virginia and West
Virginia to feed power plants. Auto parts come in from the Midwest
and Mexico and leave Ford's and General Motors' two Atlanta-area
assembly plants as finished GM minivans and Ford Taurus and Mercury
Sable cars.
</P>
<P>
   Trains carrying citrus and vegetables roll in from Florida and
pull out loaded with containers destined for Florida and Central
and South America.
</P>
<P>
   But such tonnage is just the bottom of the iceberg of goods that
flow through Atlanta each day, powering its historic role as the
economic engine of the South.
</P>
<P>
   The tip of that iceberg consists of a relatively tiny pile of
high-value goods _less than a million tons in 1999 _ that came or
went via aircraft at Hartsfield International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   In between, trucks carried about $8 out of every $10 worth of
all goods originating in Georgia in 1997, according to a U.S.
Census Bureau survey released last year. Truckers also transported
nearly 90 percent of the 374 million tons shipped from the state
that year, according to the federal statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta accounted for a lion's share of the state's cargo
movement. The city is a regional power in the physical movement and
distribution of goods. Chicago is the undisputed railroad capital
of the United States, which has the world's richest rail network,
writes Brian Slack in ``Modern Transport Geography.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Rickman, superintendent of Norfolk Southern's Georgia
Division, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago is probably the most complex interchange in the United
States,'' he says, with at least 16 railroads large and small
converging on the city. It's ``a real challenge'' to thread rail
traffic through the city, he says. But it's ``still strategically
the best location for interchange'' in the nation, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   But by at least one measure, albeit a rather virtual one,
Atlanta is a global cargo-handling powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say that Atlanta is the largest inland port in the
world,'' says Georgia State University economist Donald Ratajczak,
because its accountants, lawyers and trade financiers handle much
of the paperwork for East Coast ports from Charleston to Fort
Lauderdale. ``We have better access to experts in the particular
areas.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's Atlanta's long history as a trade crossroads, then
as a rail center, then as a major airport hub, that positions the
city well to prosper from the continuing drive toward global
markets and electronic commerce, most experts agree.
</P>
<P>
   Counted directly, transportation workers account for only 6
percent of Atlanta's employees, says Ratajczak. But the city owes
its growth to its role as a transportation and distribution center,
he adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a transportation-based metropolitan area,'' he says.
''It's what Atlanta is.''
</P>
<P>
   And will continue to be, he and others say.
</P>
<P>
   On the one front, goods will still go through the same basic
process whether sold over the Internet or a store counter, says
Ratajczak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may make (Atlanta ) more important,'' he says. ``You still
have to move goods. You need distribution centers, and you've got
to account for it. (E-commerce) won't undermine it.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, the trend toward global production of goods and lowered
trade barriers, such as those under the North American Free Trade
Agreement, mean more shipping of parts and finished products, says
Jean-Paul Rodrigue, a geography professor at Hofstra University who
studies globalization's role behind the current transport boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about Detroit. In the past, all the cars and parts came
from within the region,'' he says. ``Today, it's global. You have
thousands of parts from all over the continent and all over the
world, and of course that has to be shipped,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the volume of intermodal cargo shipped between Asia,
the United States and Europe continues to grow rapidly, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   All those trends point toward more shipping activity in the
future, and ``Atlanta will manage that freight,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Norfolk Southern expects more intermodal traffic to hit
Atlanta, its second busiest intermodal hub, this fall from Europe
via Savannah's port, says Norfolk Southern's Rickman.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad plans to add a daily train that will handle
intermodal shipments between Savannah and Atlanta, he says.
</P>
<P>
   And because of the growing intermodal traffic at Norfolk
Southern's Atlanta operations, the railroad is spending $95 million
on a new intermodal yard near Austell.
</P>
<P>
   The new yard will double Norfolk Southern's intermodal capacity
in the Atlanta area when it opens next year, says Rickman.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the new yard, plus regularly scheduled train
departures much like those at Atlanta's airport, have helped
Norfolk Southern regain customers it lost in the past to other
truck and rail carriers, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (tell customers) that if we can bring it into Atlanta, we
can move it a lot quicker,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
