<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2278 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-FOX-0704-1stLD     07-03 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FOX-0704-1stLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHEER CHARISMA AND A RESONATING MESSAGE CARRIED FOX TO VICTORY
IN MEXICO
 &HT;    EDS: Revises 19th graf ( ``Born into an agricultural. . .'') to
reflect Fox is separated from his wife.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Three years ago, Vicente Fox Quesada had already
violated the norms of Mexico's once stuffy and predictable
political scene.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly six-foot-six rancher and former Coca-Cola executive
from the Mexican province of Guanajuato was already unabashedly
running for president. With an obsession to drive Mexico's ruling
party from power after its 71-year reign, he refused to wait for
his own political party to anoint him in a smoke-filled room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to win,'' Fox fumed, obviously impatient to get an
early start on what would become the most competitive and
electrifying presidential campaign Mexicans can remember.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Fox's quest came true when Mexicans handed him an
historic victory that will put him in Los Pinos, (the Pines), the
Mexican White House on Dec. 1. His conservative National Action
Party, or PAN, will take the reins of power in a center-right
coalition from Mexico's Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexicans had a date with history,'' Fox, who turned 58 on
Sunday, told teary-eyed followers. ``We crossed that bridge to a
change in power in a peaceful and legal way. Today we are on the
other side of that bridge and a new road begins.''
</P>
<P>
   The descendent of Spanish and Irish immigrants, Fox is a
multi-faceted personality whose overwhelming charisma helped him
make history. The PRI tried to portray him in scathing television
ads as an uncouth, unpatriotic loudmouth, but in the end his sheer
magnetism and pledge to bring change carried him to victory.
</P>
<P>
   These same characteristics could help his presidency, but they
could rub the wrong way in negotiations with other parties in the
plural government Fox wants to form, said University of Guanajuato
political analyst Luis Miguel Rionda.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a natural leader and he enjoys it. He's passionate. But
he can't let those passions run away with things,'' Rionda said,
crediting Fox with usually working well with other parties while he
was governor. ``One of his biggest risks is losing patience. Others
can be pretty impatient, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Some fear Fox has an authoritarian streak, but he's also viewed
as extremely pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   He was a powerhouse on the campaign trail, often wearing his
trademark black leather cowboy boots and huge silver belt buckle
emblazoned ``FOX.''
</P>
<P>
   He connected with working-class people and young voters who
didn't mind the way he trashed the PRI _ he sometimes employed
obscenities _ and actually admired him for being stubborn. He
connected with farmers, who sensed he knew what he was talking
about when he spoke about running an agricultural business.
</P>
<P>
   When he put on an elegant suit, he connected with entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The desire for change was overwhelming and we positioned Fox
as the one to do that,'' said Francisco Ortiz, who ran Fox's media
campaign. Three years ago Fox probably didn't have more than a 40
percent name recognition, Ortiz said. By September of last year he
had risen to almost 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In February, a month into the official campaign season, Fox's
team coined his slogan, ``Ya!,'' which means either ``Now!'' or
``Enough!'' in Spanish. He also employed a victory sign shaped into
the word Ya to emphasize Mexicans being fed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``People really loved that,'' Ortiz said
</P>
<P>
   Fox did an admirable job, too, at turning blunders into
attributes.
</P>
<P>
   He bickered at one crucial point with rival candidates over when
to hold a debate, repeatedly telling them ``today, today, today''
on live television. But after he was declared by much of the press
as the winner of the actual debate, he turned ``today, today,
today'' into a war cry at rallies.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate, he admitted he was stubborn, but said a
leader needs to be stubborn to ``get rid of 70 years of corruption,
poverty and desperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Born into an agricultural business family, Fox was educated by
Jesuits and is a strong Catholic. He is staunchly anti-abortion,
which is illegal in Mexico except for special circumstances, but he
has vowed not make abortion an issue. He has four adopted children
and is separated from his wife, something some PRI activists tried
to use to question both his masculinity and his commitment to
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have three close friends who told me they were offered money
to offer bad information about me,'' Fox said in an interview
during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He studied business courses at Harvard and for 15 years he
worked for the Coca-Cola Co., eventually becoming president for
Latin America until he resigned in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up with Coca-Cola, the most competitive business in the
world,'' he said. On the campaign trail, he quaffed mostly
Gatorade, but also enjoyed the occasional Coke.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's presidential style could mark an enormous departure in a
country where elected officials have been insulated from the
public. Although he's equally at home wearing a suit and traveling
to meet representatives of foreign powers _ he plans to visit the
United States and other countries before December _ he likes being
out in the street.
</P>
<P>
   Rionda said as chief executive Fox will have to curb that
tendency at some point simply because of the daily demands of the
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't be like presidents of Mexico during the 1930s, like
Lazaro Cardenas, who went from town to town riding around on a
horse,'' Rionda said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is proud of his record as a governor who was rarely in his
office, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only went to my governor's office in Guanajuato four times
in four years,'' he said. ``The governor's job is to be out with
people to inspire them and make them enthusiastic.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' e-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information see www.fox2000.org.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
