<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEERLEADERS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    These cheerleaders yell for more than teams
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - There are a few unwritten rules at the
Fellowship for Christian Cheerleaders camp: Don't say it if you can
shout it. Don't sit if you can stand. And don't stand if you can
jump up and down.
</P>
<P>
   So when a camp counselor asks the 200 10- to 18-year-old girls
sitting on the floor of the Palm Beach Atlantic College gymnasium
if they're ready to work on some stunts, they stand up, leap into
the air and shout: ``Bring it on, baby! Bring it on!''
</P>
<P>
   For a teenage Christian cheerleader, that's ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the pretty girls you knew in high school. The popular
girls, the prom queens who are involved in everything and speak
with exclamation points. The difference for the nation's 6,000 FCC
members is that they cheer not just for their football teams but
for Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   The girls, mainly from Christian schools, come from as far away
as Iowa and as close as West Palm Beach to attend the camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main goal is to teach the girls to accept Jesus Christ as
their personal savior,'' says Cynthia Morrison, who directs the
camp. The day begins with devotions, packs in some flipping,
tumbling and jumping, and ends with skits about prayers and
humility.
</P>
<P>
   Humility is a theme that runs through the four-day camp. Campers
are told that as cheerleaders they will be looked up to and
admired, but they shouldn't let that popularity go to their heads.
``It's not about you. God has given you these talents,'' Morrison
repeatedly tells the girls. ``You are this way because God made you
this way.''
</P>
<P>
   With her face sparkling with glitter, her baby-blue eyeliner
accenting her blue eyes and her blond hair tied back in pigtails,
Paige Armstrong is the epitome of cheerleading perfection. She is
the 5-foot-2, 110-pound ``flier'' who leaps out of her teammates'
arms, twists into the air and lands in their catch without ever
losing her smile. She is 17, the national cheerleader of the year
and she wears a P.U.S.H. bracelet on her left wrist (Pray Until
Something Happens). She's hoping for a full cheerleading
scholarship to the University of Alabama, and with her 4.0 grade
point average, she'll probably get it.
</P>
<P>
   What is the main gripe of cheerleaders, Christian or otherwise?
``There's never, never enough respect,'' says Armstrong. ``No one
will ever understand how much hard work cheerleading is until they
come to one of our practices.''
</P>
<P>
   But being a cheerleader at a Christian school has its
advantages. ``We're not just the peppy, popular squad; we're the
squad that wants to go out and minister. We have spirit. Not just
spirit like pep, but the spirit of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
