r s BC-FBO-7-ON-7-FOOTBALL-T     07-03 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-7-ON-7-FOOTBALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
7-ON-7 FOOTBALL BECOMING A HOT SPORT IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK MAUCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Gaby can't wait for Saturday morning. Come dawn, he's up
to face the day _ and defenses bent on making his day miserable.
</P>
<P>
   Gaby, a Keller receiver, is one of many high school players
across Texas who has fallen in love with seven-on-seven football.
From Lake Worth to Houston, players such as Gaby are participating
in off-season tournaments each week with hopes of capturing a state
championship in College Station on July 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wake up early on Saturday and meet at 7 a.m. and can't
wait to get out there and play,'' Gaby said after his team won the
championship of the Cedar Hill Tournament last month.
</P>
<P>
   Seven-on-seven football became popular in the mid-1990s after
the Legislature removed University Interscholastic League
restrictions on the number of teammates who could compete on a
summer team without the supervision of a coach. Previously, no more
than four teammates could compete together during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The sport's origins mimic a training method used by California
high school football players, where seven players take the field
without pads and pass, pass, pass in a game of touch football.
Meanwhile, seven players on defense try to stop them from going the
length of the field _ 45 yards _ for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   UIL rules prevent coaches for grades 7-12 from supervising the
athletes, and players are responsible for their own entry fees into
any off-season program. The rules are designed to keep the
activities voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches, however, can organize tournaments and contests, which
usually start in May and are played on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as they \Rthe players\S are not under the jurisdiction
of a coach, they can put together as many players as they want on a
team,'' Bill Farney, UIL director, said.
</P>
<P>
   Grapevine and Carroll were among the first programs to play
seven-on-seven football in Texas, beginning shortly after the
participation rules changed in 1995. Carroll defeated Grapevine,
47-33, and was crowned the first state champion in the sport in
1998 by Fox Sports Net, which helps organize the state tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   State tournament director Bobby Burton, who runs the Web site
Rivals100.com and is a broadcaster for Fox, said the network
anticipated the increasing popularity of seven-on-seven football.
</P>
<P>
   Burton said the network helped take the sport beyond off-season
training and into a competition that would give statewide bragging
rights to players who won the annual championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years and two months ago, Jon Heidtke \Rgeneral manager
of Fox Sports Net \S and I sat down and talked about how popular
this was becoming and how we could take this event to a central
site,'' Burton said. ``We had visions, sure, but this thing has
really grown faster than even we hoped.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's state tournament, July 21-22, will have 64 teams,
its largest field yet]. It will feature both championship and
consolation divisions of 32 teams for the first time. The first
tournament in 1998 featured 32 teams and last year's had 48 in the
field, won by North Mesquite over Lake Worth, 31-26.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 11 Fort Worth-area teams have qualified for the state
tournament this year. They are Grapevine, Marcus, Lamar,
Colleyville Heritage, Keller, Grand Prairie, Martin, Carroll,
Stephenville, Brownwood and Celina.
</P>
<P>
   Teams qualify for the state tournament by winning or being one
of two teams to survive selected tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Burton anticipates about 5,000 spectators for the state
tournament at Kyle Field, the largest attendance to date.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing popularity of the sport is largely being driven
by one thing, Burton said: The kids are having fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is these guys are having a great time. It
gives football players something to do other than just train,''
Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, weekend competition for the state tournament hasn't
been enough to satisfy many players. Several programs are forming
leagues with other area schools and playing a weekly round-robin
competition on weeknights.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the weekly leagues are cheaper, said Scott Peach, a former
assistant coach for Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tournaments got so expensive. Every one we wanted to go to
was $15 a kid,'' said Peach, who recently became Sam Houston's
offensive coordinator. ``By putting together a league, the kids get
to play for free. It's still a good idea to play in some
tournaments, especially if you want to qualify for state, but to
the coaches the state tournament is no big deal. We're interested
in the kids getting the reps and the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller assistant coach/passing coordinator Brian Hart said
coach-less football, where players have to make all of the on-field
decisions, is one of the other reasons the sport is popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are out there making decisions, helping each other out.
That's big come September,'' Hart said. ``It's the key to winning
close games.''
</P>
<P>
   Grapevine quarterback Richard Bartel is playing seven-on-seven
for a second season. At one point this year, the Mustangs won 23
consecutive games and three consecutive tournaments, all of which
makes playing even more enjoyable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be running drills and lifting weights or we can be
out doing this, which do you think we'd rather be doing?'' Bartel
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Worth coach Percy Whitmire said he would have his team
participate even if it weren't pass oriented. The sport gives small
schools such as his a chance to get some off-season training.
</P>
<P>
   ``It especially helps the littler schools like those in 3A,
where we don't have spring practices,'' Whitmire said.
</P>
<P>
   Farney warns players and coaches not to get too caught up in the
seven-on-seven hype. He said the UIL is behind the sport as long as
it stays within the rules, and he's still pondering whether the
state tournament is good for the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we're seeing is more pressure on coaches to see
their kids compete and that puts more pressure on the kids,''
Farney said. ``We hear reports of coaches picking teams and telling
kids they have to play. But any time a youngster is able to do this
at his own will and they and the parents have a choice, we're OK
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton said the sport is here to stay. He already is thinking of
ways to expand participation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about going to 128 teams for the state tournament
and maybe going to 5A, 4A and 3A and below divisions,'' Burton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Is a national seven-on-seven tournament on the horizon?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the inaugural ones to have a state champion \Rin
Texas\S. Arkansas has thought about trying it, and Colorado has a
state camp that Grapevine has gone to,'' Burton said. ``I'd say a
national championship would be a ways down the road, if ever. But
who knows?''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
