u p BC-GORE-PRESCRIPTIONS-NY     07-03 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-PRESCRIPTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE HEAPS CRITICISM ON DRUG COMPANIES
</HEADLINE>
  By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAYTON, Mo. _ Vice President Al Gore accused drug companies
Monday of ``price-gouging'' and ``special interest schemes'' to
keep drug prices high and he pledged to a crowd of elderly people
that he would ``fight for you, not for the powerful drug
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's appearance at a community center in this swing state
began a weeklong drive to highlight an issue that has emerged as
one of the most potent this election season: the spiraling cost of
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president worked to tie his opponent, Gov. George W.
Bush, and the Republicans in Congress to the drug industry. ``It is
not all that complicated,'' he said at a news conference.
``Governor Bush is with the big pharmaceutical companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also claimed that the drug companies had written the House
Republicans' recently passed bill that provides a prescription drug
benefit for Medicare recipients. The Republican bill would rely on
private insurance companies to sell drug coverage to the elderly,
backed by government subsidies and incentives. ``I think they
crafted the actual words,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats support a more expansive measure, relying directly
on the Medicare system. Bush generally supports the House
Republicans' plan.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has a history of taking on the drug companies, dating to
his years in Congress, although some of his friends and advisers
now represent the pharmaceutical industry as lobbyists. His
campaign believes the issue allows him to draw a sharp contrast
with Bush, who received more campaign contributions from the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Campaign Study Group, a nonpartisan research
organization, Republican Party committees have received $4 million
in unregulated ``soft money'' contributions from pharmaceutical
companies since January 1999, while Democrats have received $1.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Gore's speech, the Bush campaign released a
statement by Rep. James M. Talent, R-Mo., charging that the Clinton
administration had been ``an obstacle'' to overhauling Medicare.
``After eight years of failing to propose a solution, the vice
president is now saying he wants reform.''
</P>
<P>
   For several years, Democrats have put the cost of prescription
drugs for the elderly at the top of their agenda. With drug prices
rising faster than the rate of inflation, President Clinton a year
ago proposed an expansion of the 34-year-old Medicare program to
cover drugs. House Democrats have been riding the issue hard in
their quest to regain control of the House _ running bus trips for
the elderly to Canada and Mexico, where drug prices are lower.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt, the minority leader from Missouri, was at
Gore's side Monday and said House Democrats would campaign on the
issue across the country this week.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans originally denounced Clinton's plan as a costly
expansion of a program that already faced fiscal difficulties and
said they would not take it up unless it was part of a broader
overhaul of Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   But trying to blunt the Democrats' drive, House Republicans
pushed through on a near party-line vote their own $40 billion
measure just before the July 4 recess, changing the debate to which
party's plan is better. John Feehery, a spokesman for Speaker J.
Dennis Hastert, said Republican House members were also told to
conduct town meetings this week to promote their plan.
</P>
<P>
   Feehery said the Republican bill avoids ``a government takeover
of health care'' and does not rely on a ``huge government
bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore pointed to assertions by insurance companies that the
Republican bill would not work. ``It's a misnomer,'' he said of the
Republican legislation. ``It's nothing. It doesn't work.'' He said
the Republican bill reminded him of a story about a veterinarian
and taxidermist who ``go into work together and they put up a sign
saying, `Either way you get your dog back.''' He added, ``There is
a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore heard stories from hard-pressed elderly, including a woman
who told of buying 16 boxes of macaroni and cheese dinners because
they cost only $4, saving her money for medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've been eating macaroni and cheese for every meal?'' Gore
prompted her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can save a little bit of it for the next day too,'' said
Jacqueline Steele Johnson, 72.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to have a system where you are completely at the
mercy of the big drug companies and no one is standing up for
you,'' Gore said. ``I want to stand up for you.'' He said the drug
companies had too much power over drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore singled out for criticism the manufacturer of Claritin, the
Schering-Plough Corp., because of a provision circulating in
Congress to extend the patent for the top-selling allergy
medication. He said drug patents were not intended to create a
situation ``where we can be just exploited forever by the wealthy
and the powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the Democratic and Republican approaches
on prescription drugs involves both philosophy and detail. The
Democrats rely on the Medicare program, while the Republicans rely
on incentives to private insurers to sell policies to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Republican plan, the government would set the
parameters of a standard drug policy for the elderly, but premiums
and co-payments could vary from one private drug plan to another as
long as the overall values met the government standard. The plan
envisions premiums of $35 to $40 a month. After a $250 deductible,
the policies would pay for half of a recipient's annual drug costs,
up to $2,100.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, like other Democrats, has proposed a more generous benefit
than the Republicans, which would cost $255 billion over a decade.
It would carry no deductible and would cover half of the costs of
drugs, up to $5,000. The premium would start at $25 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's plan and the House Republicans' plan would
both contain subsides for low-income seniors and protections for
those with high drug costs. The Republican plan would provide 100
percent drug-cost coverage after an individual's out-of-pocket
costs reached $6,000. Gore's plan would pay for all expenses after
out-of-pocket costs reached $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   The drug industry is the second industry Gore has gone after in
recent weeks, having just finished a series of broadsides against
the oil companies. Today, he hailed news that Saudi Arabia was
raising oil production and called on the ``big oil companies'' to
pass along price reductions. ``We need some significant relief,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
