r d BC-BROWNIE-COLUMN-LADN-2     07-03 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWNIE-COLUMN-LADN-2ndTake </SLUG>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(UNDATED: ... Makes 1 dozen.)
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAIDA HEATTER'S PALM BEACH BROWNIES &QL; 
(Shared by Bobbe Bassman) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
8 ounces unsweetened chocolate, chopped &QL; 
8 ounces unsalted butter &QL; 
2 cups shelled walnuts &QL; 
5 large eggs &QL; 
2 teaspoons vanilla &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon almond extract &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon salt &QL; 
4 teaspoons INSTANT espresso powder &QL; 
3 3/4 cups sugar &QL; 
1 2/3 cups sifted unbleached flour &QL; 
30 ounces chocolate-covered peppermint patties &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adjust oven rack 1/3 up from bottom of oven. Line a 9x13x2-inch
pan as follows: Invert pan and center a 17-inch length of aluminum
foil, shiny side down, over pan. With your hands, press down on
sides and corners of foil to shape it to pan. Remove foil. Turn pan
right side up. Place foil in pan and carefully press it into place
in pan. Now, to butter foil, place a piece of butter (additional to
that in ingredients) in pan and put pan in preheated 425-degree
oven. When butter is melted, use a pastry brush or piece of
crumbled plastic wrap to spread butter all over foil. Set prepared
pan aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place chocolate and butter in top of a large double boiler over
hot water on moderate heat or in a 4- to 6-cup heavy saucepan over
low heat. Stir occasionally, until chocolate and butter are melted.
Stir to mix. Remove from heat and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Break walnuts into larger pieces; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In large bowl of an electric mixer, beat eggs with vanilla and
almond extracts, salt, espresso powder and sugar at high speed 10
minutes. On low speed add chocolate mixture (which may still be
warm) and beat only until mixed. Then add flour and again beat on
low speed only until mixed. Remove bowl from mixer.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Pour 1/2 of mixture (about 3 1/2 cups) into prepared pan and
smooth top.
</P>
<P>
   Place a layer of mints, touching each other and edges of pan,
all over chocolate layer. Cut some mints to fill in large spaces on
edges. (You will not use all the mints. There will be some left
over.)
</P>
<P>
   Pour remaining chocolate mixture into pan and smooth all over.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 425 degrees F 35 minutes, reversing pan front to back
once during baking to insure even baking. After 35 minutes, cake
will have a firm crust on top, but if you insert toothpick in
middle it will come out wet and covered with chocolate. It's done.
Do not bake any longer.
</P>
<P>
   Remove pan from oven; let stand until cool. Cover pan with a
cookie sheet and invert pan and sheet. Remove pan and foil lining.
Cover cake with a length of wax paper and another cookie sheet and
invert again, leaving cake right side up.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate a few hours or overnight before cutting into bars.
Makes 1 (9X13-inch) pan brownies. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
TOM'S BROWNIES &QL; 
Shared by Tom Lapham, North Hills)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
1 cup margarine &QL; 
3 (1-ounce) squares unsweetened chocolate &QL; 
2 cups sugar &QL; 
1 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
3 eggs &QL; 
1 cup flour &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon baking powder &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon salt &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a large glass bowl, combine margarine and chocolate. Heat in
microwave oven until melted, 1 to 2 minutes. Stir in sugar and
vanilla. Blend in eggs, one at a time. Stir in flour, baking powder
and salt until well blended.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into greased 9x13-inch baking pan. Bake in preheated
350-degree oven 35 minutes. Let cool completely. Makes 1
(13x9-inch) pan brownies. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
Can you help? &QL; 
If you have recipes that can help this reader, please send them
along to us at the address below to share in a future column.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Several years ago you printed a recipe for a Tex-Mex Lasagna
that was out of this world. (Being of Italian descent, this says a
lot). Does anyone have a copy of the recipe? Help! Joseph Nicassio,
Valencia &QL; 
--- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cook's Corner welcomes recipe requests from readers. While we
cannot reply to them individually, we will answer those of general
interest in this column. Also, if you can help another reader with
a recipe request, write to Cook's Corner, Daily News Food
Department, P.O. Box 4200, Woodland Hills, Calif. 91365-4200.
Please be sure recipes specify exact package sizes, can and pan
sizes and baking times and temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Recipes printed are from the source indicated and have not been
tested by the Daily News Food Department unless noted.
</P>
