<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-PRI-NYT &LR;      07-03 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-PRI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN POLITICAL MACHINE DEPENDENT ON POWER LOSES ITS POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (with MEXICO-ELECTION) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The Institutional Revolutionary Party, which has
governed Mexico since 1929, was formed to bring order out of the
chaos of the Mexican Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Its hallmarks were an iron hand, military discipline, and total
control wielded by a maximum leader, the president. It used
political force and fraud to win elections, from the smallest
mayoralty to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   It became a machine designed to keep itself in power, many
Mexican and American historians say. By the 1990s, the party had
been in power for so long that it became indistinguishable from
power itself.
</P>
<P>
   An endless succession of new presidents _ each chosen by the
previous one _ made the government, the party and the president
synonymous. This process of choosing the new leaders was called
``el dedazo'' _ tapping the candidate _ and Mexicans joked bitterly
that they lived under ``dedazocracy,'' not democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Without the presidency and its perquisites, which traditionally
included millions of dollars in political funds, the party is a
machine without its engine, its fuel, its oil and grease.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party had become a mindless tool of the president,'' said
John Bailey, a professor of government at Georgetown University in
Washington. ``What held it together was winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the presidency is lost, and the party may be lost without
it. Out of power, the party may fly apart, break into factions and
cease to exist in its present form, Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Historians often point out that the name of the Institutional
Revolutionary Party contains a contradiction. The party's many
critics say it has lost its old political ideals and simply become
an institution.
</P>
<P>
   But in the first half of its life, from the 1930s into the
1960s, the party's ideals were alive. The PRI, as it is called,
created something out of nothing: it made modern Mexico. It built
roads, schools, hospitals and libraries. It gave land to the poor.
It nationalized Mexico's oil. It gave power to labor unions and
money to peasant groups and received loyalty in return. Through the
1960s, Mexicans had a stable economy and a strong peso, though
millions remained dirt poor.
</P>
<P>
   The party made a peaceful transition from military rule to
civilian power in the 1930s. Ever since, Mexico has been free of
the military coups and dictatorships that have made life miserable
in so many Latin American nations.
</P>
<P>
   A turning point came, though, when the government turned its
guns on protesting students in 1968 in the Mexico City neighborhood
of Tlatelolco. Hundreds died. Mexicans today compare the massacre
to the 1989 killings in Tiananmen Square in Beijing. What happened
in Tlatelolco is still shrouded in official secrecy. But it left
millions of Mexicans believing that the governing party would use
violence, rather than voluntary reform, to preserve its power.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, when President Jose Lopez Portillo ran the
economy aground and nationalized the banks, his missteps gave rise
to the National Action Party, which began winning elections across
Mexico. That led to a pattern of apparent election fraud by the
governing party.
</P>
<P>
   When a mysterious computer breakdown appeared to alter the
results of the 1988 presidential elections, giving victory to the
governing party, millions more came to believe that it would steal
an election to stay in power.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1990s, political killings, an economic crisis and a
succession of corruption cases suggested that the old order in the
party was decaying. In 1994, its presidential candidate, Luis
Donaldo Colosio, appeared to break with the old guard, including
President Carlos Salinas, promising sweeping reforms that would
separate the party from the government.
</P>
<P>
   Colosio was assassinated on the campaign trail, a killing whose
intellectual authorship remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign manager, Ernesto Zedillo, received the dedazo from
Salinas. He would be the last so chosen. To the praise of all but
the party stalwarts, he ended the dedazo and consolidated political
and electoral changes that opened up the system. Those reforms led
on Sunday to the cleanest election in Mexican history, the National
Action Party's victory and the governing party's defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Election returns and polling data suggest that millions of
young, educated and globally minded Mexicans voted against the
party in the belief that the nation would never be a modern
democracy while in the grip of the party's old guard.
</P>
<P>
   And no less an authority than Colosio seemed to have believed
that something sinister thrived behind the closed doors of the old
regime.
</P>
<P>
   According to the historian Enrique Krauze's definitive ``Mexico:
Biography of Power'' (HarperCollins, 1997), Colosio was asked
shortly before his death what he thought of Salinas and his circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you seen `The Godfather?''' he replied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
