<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2293 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SYPHILIS-ERADICATE-2T     07-03 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYPHILIS-ERADICATE-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME IS RIPE TO RID NATION   OF SYPHILIS, HEALTH OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Va., N.C., Ind., Ga.)   By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ The new jail inmate had intimidating arms,
thick as thighs. But he extended one meekly when a nurse, Jean
Graves, told him: ``I have to give you a tuberculosis skin test. I
also have to draw blood for syphilis, OK?''
</P>
<P>
   As she slid the needle into his skin, the city of Nashville took
one more small step in a sweeping national program: a push by
health authorities to rid the country of the scourge of syphilis,
spirochete bacterium by spirochete, chancre sore by chancre, once
and for all.
</P>
<P>
   Even here, where the syphilis rate is the second highest in the
country among major cities, topped only by Indianapolis, the
numbers are less than staggering. Only 250 cases of new _ and thus
still infectious _ syphilis turned up last year. Nationwide, they
dropped below 7,000, down from the most recent peak of 50,000 in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   But that is the very point, health officials say. Now, when new
cases are at an all-time low and so concentrated that about half of
them come from just 25 of the country's 3,100 counties, is the time
to try to wipe it out altogether. They are prosecuting a
multipronged attack that includes heavy reliance on community
activism and stepped-up detective work to track down carriers and
those at risk, as well as expanded clinical and laboratory
services.
</P>
<P>
   Up close, however, this campaign, which officially started last
October, sometimes appears more a slog than a fast strike, a lesson
in the painstaking process of fighting sexually transmitted
diseases even when, like syphilis, they have a cure as easy as a
couple of shots of penicillin.
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing this week in Atlanta, local health officials
reported lessons and patches of progress from the three
metropolitan areas where pilot anti-syphilis programs are already
underway: Nashville, Raleigh, N.C., and Indianapolis, all places
where rates are high. They included word from North Carolina that
the state had begun to see a sharp drop in syphilis rates, by 36
percent last year compared with 1998, and a report that nationwide,
the striking racial disparity in syphilis rates had diminished as
well, from a 43-to-1 ratio of blacks to whites infected in 1997,
down to less than a 30-to-1 ratio in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The local officials also called for continued federal financing
for their program, which is expected to cost $37 million a year
through 2005 but has been allocated only about half that to date.
In his current budget, President Clinton is requesting an
additional $15 million for the anti-syphilis effort in 2001. But
the Senate, seeking to funnel more money instead toward chlamydia
prevention, is considering providing only half that amount for
syphilis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I know about the epidemiology of syphilis tells me
this elimination effort is dead in the water if we're not able to
sustain the president's budget request,'' warned Dr. Judith N.
Wasserheit, who directs the Division of Sexually Transmitted
Disease Prevention at the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Without a full-fledged elimination program, federal health
officials project, syphilis, which tends to rise and fall in
7-to-10-year cycles, could reach 23,000 new cases in 2005. As it
is, they said, treatment for syphilis and its consequences cost
nearly $1 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   For all their focus on money, however, they also emphasized that
money is not enough, that eliminating syphilis takes commitment and
energy.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville, for example, needs workers like Pam Pitts, who
persuades new inmates at the city's jail to get tested and, if
infected, identify their sexual partners; and Tina Lester, who
coordinates the anti-syphilis campaign among dozens of community
groups and churches in the poor neighborhoods where the disease is
most prevalent; and Princesita A.L. Hawkins, who ventures out into
those same neighborhoods every day to track down carriers and talk
them into getting help.
</P>
<P>
   It can be a hard and frustrating job, Hawkins said: ``A lot of
your patients, you're going to be more concerned about their health
than they are.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is a job that must be done, health officials say, as they
struggle to learn how best to eliminate a disease that is easy to
test for and cure but not as easy to prevent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, we don't have vaccines for the majority of
infectious disease now,'' said Wasserheit. ``So a strategy like
this, that allows us to eliminate a disease through a multifaceted
approach, is a new thing and a really important concept that goes
way beyond syphilis itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has tried before to eliminate syphilis, but
never reached the near-total success of European countries _ in
part, experts say, because the efforts failed to reach the poor
areas most affected. This new approach, health officials say,
emphasizes heavier community involvement than ever, from church
sermons to screenings in local libraries, along with more tracking
and clinical services. It seeks to bring syphilis cases below 1,000
nationwide, which is not total eradication but low enough to be
considered elimination.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Here in Nashville, that strategy has translated into innovative
moments, from anti-syphilis church sermons last Valentine's Day to
a graphic ``Syphilis is Scary'' exhibit at a university last
Halloween, to talks by Lester in which her advice to teen-agers
considering a sexual encounter includes, ``Turn on the light, look
at people, don't just trust!''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Nashville, some things are already becoming clear. One is
that focusing syphilis prevention efforts on the city jail is
highly effective.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the cases that the city has picked up in recent
months came from the program to screen new inmates and try to get
them treatment quickly, before they are released on bond or
otherwise move on in the criminal justice system, officials say.
Overall, about 70 percent of people found to have syphilis have a
criminal record, said Dr. Jesse Huang, the city's chief
epidemiologist. Rates in homeless shelters are also
disproportionately high, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Pitts, the public health worker now stationed full time in
the city's main jail, said that perhaps 10 percent to 20 percent of
new inmates refuse to be screened, for all her persuasive powers.
Women tend to refuse out of belligerence, men because they're
scared of the needle, she said. But overall, she is more convinced
than ever that she is stationed in the right place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think without a corrections process you're not going to
eliminate syphilis in your community, you're just not,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another lesson is that word does get around; several public
health workers said that recently, they had begun encountering a
few people who said they had heard that there was a syphilis
problem in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But only a few. More typical was Ricky Carr, 38, a construction
worker who had been lured into a public library for a free
screening the other day. He had mainly wanted an HIV screening to
dispel the rumors that, because he had been looking bad as he
recovered from surgery recently, he had AIDS. But he agreed to a
syphilis test as well, though he had heard nothing of the epidemic
and knew no one who had it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I ain't got no syphilis, I think I can pretty much tell
that,'' he said. But ``it's free, and I'm off today, and I don't
mind looking after me.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In most ways, health officials acknowledge, syphilis has not
been as worrisome as some other diseases since penicillin came into
use, and to this day the bacteria have developed no resistance to
antibiotics, in sharp contrast to gonorrhea and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   In its early stages, syphilis shows up as painless genital
sores, which go away by themselves, and weeks or months later by
rashes, which also tend to heal untreated.
</P>
<P>
   But if left untreated for years, syphilis can damage the brain,
heart and other organs; if a pregnant woman is infected and left
untreated, it can prove deadly for her baby; and its sores raise
significantly the chances of transmission of HIV.
</P>
<P>
   The question remains: If syphilis tends to affect the poorest of
the poor, the homeless, the drug users, the prostitutes, people who
tend to be alienated enough from government and even medical
officials that some resist even efforts to test and cure them, can
it really be eliminated as health officials plan?
</P>
<P>
   Lester and others in Nashville say it can. ``I think that it can
be done,'' she said. ``It's just that we really need to get to the
core of the infection, just keep tracking down those contacts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
