u i BC-MEXICO-U.S.-NYT &LR;      07-03 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S NEW LEADER SEEN AS ENTHUSIASTIC U.S. PARTNER
</HEADLINE>
   (With MEXICO-ELECTION) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration welcomed the transition
of power in Mexico, saying Monday that the election of Vicente Fox
was evidence of the maturing of democratic institutions and that it
set the stage for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton telephoned Fox to congratulate him, and also
spoke to President Ernesto Zedillo, the outgoing leader, to express
his gratitude for his role in strengthening democracy in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexicans should be proud of the extraordinary steps they have
taken during the last six years to strengthen and consolidate
democratic institutions and set Mexico on a course of economic
growth and prosperity,'' Clinton said in a statement released by
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton dealt frequently with Zedillo in the past six years,
especially after the passage of the North American Free Trade
Agreement, which saw trade between the two nations soar. The two
leaders held their 11th meeting here last month when Clinton
praised Zedillo for advancing the process of trade integration with
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, the Clinton administration had been fairly
scrupulous in not showing a preference for either Fox or his main
opponent, Francisco Labastida of the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI. The administration had also expressed
confidence in the integrity of the electoral process.
</P>
<P>
   That confidence was borne out in the conduct of the elections on
Sunday and in the results, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
   For Washington, dealing with a Mexican administration led by the
PRI, which had been in power for 71 years, has been an ingrained
habit that survived countless bouts of economic crisis in Mexico
and American-led financial bailouts. Through all the crises,
Washington was generally grateful to have a stable neighbor even
though it was poor and in recent years had become the major conduit
for illegal narcotics into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox is not unknown in Washington. In an introductory visit
here in May, he met with Under Secretary of State Thomas Pickering
and spoke at several foreign policy institutions. He impressed
people not only as a businessman who once worked for Coca-Cola but
also as a politician who understood the United States, a senior
administration official said. One of his major points was further
expansion of American investment in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to reassure us that the United States would have a
good partner, that he would be reliable and would cooperate across
the board,'' the official said. ``Relations under Zedillo had
reached an all-time high and we would expect Fox to continue the
momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   But this was not to say that Fox would not inject some new ideas
into the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   On the three main issues between Mexico and the United States _
immigration, trade and the flow of drugs _ Fox, as a former
governor of a northern Mexican state, would likely bring some fresh
thinking, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   During his campaign, Fox said he would like a more even
relationship with Washington on the handling of immigration which,
from the Mexican perspective, has largely been treated by the
United States as a criminal justice and police issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is one issue that the new president and the new
president of the United States will have to deal with quite
quickly,'' said Andres Rozental, a business consultant in Mexico
City, who was a deputy secretary of state dealing with American
relations in a former Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   Rozental said he believed that Fox would like to look beyond
``managing'' the question of illegal Mexican immigrants into the
United States and turn toward reaching agreements with Washington
that would allow better terms for semi-skilled Mexican migrants to
enter the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that the AFL-CIO had recently noted the value of
semi-skilled foreign workers to the United States, and that the
Treasury had attributed some of the economic growth during the
Clinton administration to immigrant labor. This presented a
``window of opportunity'' for Mexico to try to persuade Washington
to sit down and take a new look at immigration policies with
Mexico, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite disputes involving trucking and sugar _ two sectors in
which Mexico would like a bigger share of the American market _
Mexico's trading relations with the United States have moved
steadily since NAFTA was signed into law by President Clinton in
1993. An administration official said that Zedillo had refrained
from repeating the practice of his predecessors of ramping up the
Mexican economy in an effort to have his party win the election.
``There is stability, not boom,'' in the Mexican economy, an
administration official said. There was also the prospect of
continuity in the economy with the head of the central bank,
Guillermo Ortiz, slated to stay. It also appeared possible that the
finance minister, Jose Angel Gurria, might remain in office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
