<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2296 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FAMILY-BUSINESS-ART-1     07-03 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-BUSINESS-ART-1800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME DOT-COMS, REVERSE NEPOTISM BRINGS STRESS AND SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT20, NYT21, sent on June 20, are being sent to
NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In some ways, Lucille Lee is typical of many people who have
cast their lot with Silicon Valley start-ups. Early last year,
after many years as a software systems architect at International
Business Machines, she joined eCircles.com, a service based in San
Mateo, Calif. for building virtual meeting places, where she puts
in 60 to 70 hours a week as director of applications development.
</P>
<P>
   But almost every week Lee has the company's chief executive over
for Sunday dinner. Although she does not report directly to him,
she often brings up work-related concerns, but when she does this,
he squirms, telling her he would rather not discuss work. This
usually goes on a bit until Lee's husband chimes in to admonish
their guest: ``Prescott, listen to your mom.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 67, Lee is working for her son, who is 38. And her
situation is not all that unusual anymore. In the world of Internet
start-ups, where a typical chief executive is 30 and a labor
shortage continues even as some Web companies fail, in many cases
dot-commers are recruiting their parents.
</P>
<P>
   These 30-somethings belong to a generation that came of age
comfortable with both technology and the risks that come with
entrepreneurship. Most of their parents are still in the work
force, many of them still years from retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Some say they decided to work for their children's firms because
their skills and experience were a good fit with the firm. A few
say they find the potential financial rewards attractive. But most
do it for the most time-honored of reasons: Who can say no to a
child who needs you?
</P>
<P>
   In the process, this curious form of reverse nepotism is
upending traditional notions about family businesses, where the
younger generations work their way up the ladder. It is also
bringing a new dimension to child-parent relationships and the
questions of authority and approval that usually define them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really new,'' said Mary J. Waller, an assistant
professor at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign who
studies organizational behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Waller noted that except in smaller, family-owned businesses,
nepotism has generally been frowned upon in American companies. But
many young and inexperienced dot-com executives, she said, are the
children of successful entrepreneurs who can offer valuable advice
and experience.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most famous recent example of a parental recruit is
William H. Gates Jr., father of Microsoft's chairman. The elder
Gates, a 74-year-old lawyer, is co-chairman of the Bill and Melinda
Gates Foundation, the largest philanthropic foundation in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The position grew out of a conversation a few years ago with his
son and daughter-in-law during a night at the movies. After that
evening, the elder Gates offered to help his son with his
philanthropic efforts.
</P>
<P>
   For many other parents who go into a child's employ, it starts
with a more active call for help.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case with Josie Herron, a 55-year-old database
designer who uprooted herself from West Palm Beach, Fla., last
January to join the payroll of Mercury2, an e-commerce company in
San Francisco. Her daughter, Christine Herron, a former venture
capitalist and graduate of Stanford Business School is the
company's founder and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Over lunch recently at a cafe close to Mercury2's offices south
of Market Street, the elder Herron, looking slightly out of place
amid the relentless hipness of the restaurant, and her daughter, a
cheerful 30-year-old clearly in her element, talked about how the
recruitment took place.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a shameless lobbying,'' said Josie Herron. ``Heavy
guilt on the `Mom, I need you.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``You use what works with different people,'' responded
Christine, a broad, mischievous smile on her face. ``I know what
works with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc H. Bell, 32, who is chairman and chief executive officer of
the Globix Corp., an Internet infrastructure firm in New York, was
also in need of help. Both of Bell's parents _ who have been
amicably separated but not divorced for more than 10 years _ now
work for him.
</P>
<P>
   The first to join the company, in 1995, was Bell's father,
Robert, 61, an experienced real estate lawyer who started out by
giving informal advice as the company was getting started and
eventually signed on as executive vice president of business
development.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't always been an easy situation to adjust to. ``When
my father came on board, the dynamic was a little weird because my
father was working for me,'' said the younger Bell. ``It required
finding boundaries. There are definitely some tense moments. ''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Bell said, at the same time, ``there's no one you can
better trust than family.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bell did not ask for any shares when the company was
formed. He later took options, the company went public in 1996 and
now he is a multimillionaire. Now 600 employees strong, Globix has
made Marc Bell far wealthier; his stock in the company is worth
about $185 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have in our situation is a pendulum where it's swung
from one end to the other,'' said the elder Bell. ``It evolved from
son coming to father for advice to a father taking total direction
from his son.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell's mother, Ruth, 58, who coordinates events for the company,
was a more difficult recruit. It took several years before Bell
finally convinced her to join the company. She was happy running
her own small business producing what her son calls ``crystal
tchotchkes'' and what she describes as ``hand-crafted personal
accessory items.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in 1998, she relented. Her nickname around the company
is The Corporate Mom.
</P>
<P>
   When a company is just starting out, and one's parents get
involved, the financial and emotional stakes can be enormous, and
young entrepreneurs may want more than a parent's expertise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to me to have not just my mortgage on the line
but my mom's mortgage as well,'' said Courtney Rosen, 33, chief
executive of eHow.com, a how-to Web site with 80 full-time
employees and 200 free-lancers. Rosen's mother, Roberta Kramer, 61,
works there as a senior editor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, investors and colleagues are often skeptical of
such arrangements at first. ``Everyone wants to know, `Is this a
family business I'm getting involved in, or what?' said Matthew
Josefewicz, 27, chief executive of Chapbooks.com, a start-up in
Boston that produces books in small quantities. ``The answer is
definitely `or what,''' Both his parents now work for him.
</P>
<P>
   But, say many chief executives, the skepticism usually fades
once a parent's credentials are trotted out. Further, it doesn't
hurt to demonstrate that at least one highly experienced
``gray-hair,'' as employees over the age of 40 or so are generally
referred to at start-ups, can be found in the company's ranks.
</P>
<P>
   That same experience, however, can breed discord. Bell, who
describes his father as a ``strong-headed person,'' recalled
several disagreements over the years. Gradually, the elder Bell has
come to defer more readily to his son. ``This is a Marc company,
this is not a Bob company,'' said the elder Bell. ``He is the
brains behind it, and I accept that and I respect it. Some fathers
don't want to let go.''
</P>
<P>
   In a variation on the theme of recruiting one's parents, said
Josefewicz, his father and a small group of friends had the idea
for Chapbooks.com and turned to him in 1998 when they were seeking
someone to run it. ``My parents have run their own business and
don't want to be doing that again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Josefewicz said that early in the company's life, he and his
parents had ``one or two major disagreements I'm not comfortable
sharing in print.'' But those differences were quickly resolved, he
said, and all has since gone smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Compensation negotiations can be awkward. Bell said that neither
parent seemed pleased with the stock options he offered them.
``Everybody always wants more,'' he said. Both parents, however,
say they are perfectly happy with their compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen of eHow.com said her mother was surprisingly tough. ``She
negotiated really well,'' said Rosen. ``She did a great job.'' The
negotiations did not take place directly between mother and
daughter, said Rosen, but with the company's vice president of
operations, who happens to be Rosen's husband.
</P>
<P>
   Josie Herron refused to negotiate altogether. ``She said, `Just
pay me what I'm worth,''' recalled Christine Herron.
</P>
<P>
   Many CEOs of companies still in their infancy and strapped for
cash are offering their parent-employees the choice of salaries or
stock options. Lee, for instance, has chosen to take more of her
compensation in options and less in salary, which she considers an
extra vote of confidence for her son.
</P>
<P>
   Deeply rooted patterns that can be found in most parent-child
relationships are also difficult to shut out completely. Lee, for
instance, often criticizes his mother for her pessimistic
tendencies, he said, adding that it isn't until his co-workers tell
him that he is being too judgmental that he rethinks his position.
``Part of the problem we all have with our moms is we expect them
to be perfect,'' Lee confessed.
</P>
<P>
   For parents, pride in one's children, as natural an instinct as
a parent can have, is hard to avoid when working so closely with
one's offspring. ``Sometimes we're at the same meeting and every
once in a while I'll get that rush, that motherly pride thing mixed
with love,'' Josie Herron said. ``But I only let that last a
second, and I say to myself, `That's enough now, we can't do that
at work, and I focus right back to where we were.'''
</P>
<P>
   And, not least, there is the question of what to call Mom or
Dad, in meetings or the workplace. For a while, Bell tried saying
``Ruth'' and ``Bob'' but soon gave up. ``I realized that was just
silly,'' he said. ``No matter how much I want to deny it, it's a
fact _ they're my parents.''
</P>
<P>
   His difficulties are typical, as is the tendency to revert to
habit. Lee said that in more formal settings, such as meetings, he
usually addresses his mother as ``Lucille.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``when we start disagreeing on something, I switch
right back to `Mom.'''
</P>
<P>
   And what if, in the midst of the current wave of dot-com
failures and layoffs, it becomes necessary to hand a pink slip to
the very person who used to set your curfews and order you to clean
your plate?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to lay my mom off, I would be in a horrible
situation,'' said Lee. ``My mom would understand but I know that
deep down she would also be hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Herron said she, too, had thought about this. ``If something
were to happen to the business, though I feel responsible for the
well-being of the entire team here, naturally there's more angst
associated with letting down your mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Herron said that given her mother's experience, she would have
no trouble finding another job. All the same, she said, ``Until she
was settled into something else, I would be quite on edge _ more so
than if I was unsettled myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
