<HEADER>
A2298 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FIREWORKS-MUSEUM-NYT &LR;      07-03 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREWORKS-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY SETTLE FOR THE REAL FIREWORKS? 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sure, the fireworks Tuesday night will be
spectacular. They're spectacular every year, and this time they're
supposed to be bigger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   But four centuries ago, when people really had imagination, they
staged fireworks displays on the Arno River in Florence in which
mock battles between dyers and silk weavers vying for the queen's
favor ended with the weavers' getting tossed in the river and the
god Vulcan erupting in the form of a huge fireball.
</P>
<P>
   Good clean mayhem and educational, too! That and other
historical nuggets can be learned from ``Fireworks!,'' at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art through Sept. 17.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   I suggest you spare yourself the happy crowds, the bombs
bursting in air, the balmy breezes of a long summer evening. Stay
home watching reruns Tuesday night after spending a few hours in
the Met perusing old prints and drawings of long-forgotten
pyrotechnical displays.
</P>
<P>
   Please don't thank me. It's my job to tell you these things.
</P>
<P>
   Some history should enhance your inevitable pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.0
</P>
<P>
   As nearly every child who has ever dreamed of lighting a bottle
rocket in the backyard knows, the Chinese, probably by the ninth
century, hit on the crazy idea of mixing sulfur, charcoal and
potassium nitrate to create gunpowder. It took hundreds of years
more, maybe until the 14th century, for backward Europeans to catch
up, whereupon they celebrated as often as they could by destroying
things.
</P>
<P>
   A print illustrates what happened in Munich in 1530 after the
coronation of Charles V as Holy Roman Emperor. The Bavarian dukes
invited Charles to a big field outside the city where a group of
mock Turkish-looking buildings had been built. A battalion of
cannons fired at the buildings, and ka-boom! So much for the Turks.
</P>
<P>
   What fun. Pretty soon, whenever any king or prince was born,
married, conquered somebody, issued a decree, took religious vows,
recovered from the flu or passed through town, civic leaders
lighted dangerous explosives in crowded places. When the
Cardinal-Infante Ferdinand, the younger brother of Philip IV of
Spain, visited Antwerp in 1635, Peter Paul Rubens, no less, was
enlisted to organize the two-day celebratory spectacle, which ended
with fireworks at the cathedral. A print of the occasion (not by
Rubens) shows the cathedral spire in silhouette against a burst of
streamers.
</P>
<P>
   It is very scenic. Many of the prints and drawings of fireworks
are naturally scenic, artists taking on a subject like this to
demonstrate their own pyrotechnical skill. There is, for example, a
Russian book of color lithographs and wood engravings commemorating
the coronation of Alexander II in 1856 that is three feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Piranesi's colored etching of the Girandola, the
annual fireworks extravaganza atop the Castel Sant'Angelo in Rome,
is a striking example of lighting effects and depicted aerial
acrobatics, capturing the experience Dickens described after he saw
the Girandola half a century later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show began with a tremendous discharge of cannon; and
then, for 20 minutes or half an hour, the whole castle was one
incessant sheet of fire and labyrinth of blazing wheels of every
color, size and speed,'' he wrote in 1845. ``In half an hour
afterwards, the immense concourse had dispersed; the moon was
looking calmly down upon her wrinkled image in the river, and half
a dozen men and boys, with bits of lighted candle in their hands,
moving here and there, in search of anything worth having that
might have been dropped in the press, had the whole scene to
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   By Dickens' era, fireworks had become so commonplace that
artists interested in social interaction, like Daumier and Winslow
Homer, began to focus on faces in the crowds rather than on the
explosions. Then photographs started to outpace prints as popular
documents of notable firework displays. Times were changing.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't quite the end of the story. Anyone who goes to
the Guggenheim's ``1900'' show, which is based on the art that was
in the Paris Exposition Universelle, will especially want to see
the prints and a so-called Chinese toy theater in the Met show that
lovingly simulate the fireworks over the Seine when the exposition
opened.
</P>
<P>
   No red-blooded New Yorker should miss the bird's-eye view of the
opening of the Brooklyn Bridge in 1883. People crowd the bridge and
river. Ships choke the harbor. Rockets blast from the bridge and
from the docks. The celebration reportedly lasted more than an
hour. In the lithograph, orange and yellow streaks across the gray
sky make half the image look almost abstract.
</P>
<P>
   What more could you want to celebrate the holiday? So forget
going to see the real fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the lines in the cafeteria at the Met are bound to be
shorter than the ones for hot dogs at the celebration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
