<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2299 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT &LR;      07-03 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINGIS WALTZES TO A DANCE WITH VENUS WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ The wicked edges that typically mark the
corners of Martina Hingis' mischievous Garfield smile suddenly
vanished. At the mention of Venus and Serena Williams on Monday,
Hingis was less biting and all but cuddly as she unveiled a humble
front.
</P>
<P>
   She was respectful, complimentary and credited both sculpted
sisters for pointing her in the direction of the gym. Just after
Hingis advanced to the quarterfinals by dismantling a beleaguered
Anke Huber, 6-1, 6-2, she refused a chance to snip at the Williams
sisters, fully aware of her predicament.
</P>
<P>
   To reach the Wimbledon final, she will have to escape the sling
blade groundstrokes of Venus Williams in the quarterfinals and
potentially Serena in the semis. With straight-set victories in the
Round of 16 as a kick start the second week of Wimbledon, Serena
and Venus Williams began closing in on Hingis like walls in a
claustrophobic nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're happy you make it through one of them,'' Hingis said.
``And then the next day, the other one is waiting. Hopefully, if I
can beat one, I'll get a day off. Definitely they're not easy, but
anything is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Hingis fancies herself too clever on the court to be
vulnerable, but after Venus Williams drained her during a three-set
semifinal of the United States Open and Serena Williams finished
her off in the final, her increasingly fragile confidence was
cracked in half. So although Hingis is No. 1 in the world, she
could not have been surprised at the response Venus Williams gave
when reminded of her next opponent's top ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what?'' the elder Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a day to show any fear for the Americans. Although she
had to overcome the current reincarnation of her fellow
hard-hitting countrywoman, Jennifer Capriati, Lindsay Davenport
pummeled the lines in a 6-3, 6-3 victory on Center Court. Joining
Davenport and the Williams sisters to form a quarterfinal assembled
by Uncle Sam, Monica Seles and Lisa Raymond also advanced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is,'' Serena Williams said. ``Maybe it's
McDonald's. Definitely their cheeseburgers. Not too much the fries,
but the cheeseburgers, yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a fast-food feel to the day. Wasting little time,
Andre Agassi and Pete Sampras pulled away with their fourth-round
matches in straight sets. And Jan-Michael Gambill, the giddy,
effusive American once billed as the next Agassi or Sampras,
finally greeted high expectations with a karate-like kick and a
pumped fist when he advanced to his first quarterfinal in a Grand
Slam event with a 7-6 (5), 3-6, 6-3, 6-4 upset of ninth-seeded
Thomas Enqvist.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old Gambill eliminated the last seeded player in
Sampras' half of the draw, and became the top-seeded player's next
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Moving freely with tendinitis in his lower left shin, and
uncoiling his body to hit 17 aces, Sampras oozed health. That image
only fed into the skepticism around what some of Sampras' peers are
referring to as his ``so-called injury.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They can believe or read what they want to read,'' Sampras
said. ``It's still two guys playing out there.''
</P>
<P>
   After match point, Sampras felt as if he had a brush with such a
skeptic when his opponent, Jonas Bjorkman, barely shook his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell by the way Jonas shook my hand today that, you
know, he was thinking whatever he thinks,'' Sampras said. ``For the
first time, the pressure is kind of on my opponent a little bit.
They know I'm a little bit injured, the pressure is on them.
They're not liking it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bjorkman described his limp handshake as merely a sign of his
disappointment with losing, but side-stepped the issue of Sampras'
health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if he's faking it or not,'' Bjorkman said. ``I
just go out and be prepared to play a guy who has been dominating
Wimbledon for the last seven years.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Sampras has been viewed as a drama major when
injured. Already slumped-shouldered by nature, he once punctuated
his bedraggled appearance when he became physically ill on the
court during the 1996 United States Open. At the time, John McEnroe
and Jim Courier reportedly said Sampras was faking it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when it's a tough moment, I kind of carry it in my
pocket, the vomit,'' Sampras said when reminded of McEnroe's and
Courier's comments. Then Sampras smiled a little more when he was
asked why so many doubt him. Could it be envy over his ability to
play hurt?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go, don't we?'' said Sampras as he left the
interview room. ``Cry me a river.''
</P>
<P>
   However painful his shin, Sampras' chase of history has the
potential to overshadow the women. But on Tuesday, with a
women's-only day of singles to showcase the quarterfinals, the
attention will be on Hingis and Venus Williams, as well as another
intriguing match between second-seeded Davenport and a fit Seles.
Playing as a survivor of a sometimes emotionally difficult and
tragic career, Seles believes she still has a shot at a Wimbledon
title that has always eluded her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I can't say I'm a shade below the top players
because I'm playing one of them tomorrow,'' Seles said. ``That's
would be a terrible way to go into the match. But up to this
moment, I'd have to say I'm probably behind. Martina and Lindsay
have beaten me the last couple of times I've played them.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Hingis, who has bounded through the tournament with
ease, appeared a step ahead of Venus Williams. In her match against
Appelmans, Williams had to persevere through 12 deuces before
slamming a forehand winner to break Appelmans' serve in the first
game of the second set. Williams wasn't displeased with the 6-4,
6-4 outcome, but she wasn't happy about how she has allowed her
last couple of opponents second chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is annoying,'' Williams said. ``But I can raise the
level of my game. I just have to get my mind there. There's no way
these girls should be competing like that against me in these sets,
unless of course I let them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis will search for any crack. She is quick to exploit the
weaknesses of her opponent and sneak inside their head by chasing
down every point. In 53 minutes, she picked apart 11th-seeded
Huber's psyche by staying in every point and breaking her
opponent's serve on 7 of 11 chances. For now, her confidence is
beneath the surface. If she believes she can take the Williams
sisters, she wasn't letting on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they came into women's tennis, with a lot more power and
physical abilities, everybody had to improve,'' said Hingis, who
holds a 9-5 lead in head-to-head matchups with Venus Williams. ``So
I had to improve. I feel very good. Now the tournament begins.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
