<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2300 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-BUSH-COMPARE-ART     07-03 1453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BUSH-COMPARE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES GRAPPLE OVER WHO CAN BEST TAME THE NEW ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAYTON, Mo. _ With their competing array of policy speeches,
Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush seem to be turning
this election into a referendum on which candidate can best reshape
government to meet the challenges of the New Economy.
</P>
<P>
   From health care to education to tax cuts to Social Security,
Bush and Gore are placing before the voters significant questions
about how some of the most fundamental public institutions should
be shaped for a global, digital age that offers the prospect of
unprecedented prosperity _ and enormous uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers say that the high technology-based economy and
the growth of a middle-income investor class will make voters far
more responsive to Republican ideas for decentralizing government
and reshaping the New Deal and Great Society programs for the
elderly. He would like the private sector to provide more
government services and make people less dependent on
one-size-fits-all government programs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, on the other hand, wants to expand the traditionally
Democratic entitlement programs. His aides argue that the lower and
middle classes need more government assistance with education and
health care and retirement pensions at a time when knowledge is
ever more important to success and when employers offer less
generous and less secure health and pension plans.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the candidates were on display again
Monday when Gore promoted his plan for a Medicare prescription-drug
benefit and assailed a House Republican version, supported in
concept by Bush, that subsidizes private insurers to offer the
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a misnomer,'' Gore said here in Clayton of the Republican
legislation. ``It's nothing. It doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   The face-off may not have the same high drama that Democrats and
Republicans engaged in during the Cold War era. Nor have the two
candidates focused in a sustained way on hot-button social issues
the way the presidential rivals did in 1988 when crime, welfare and
flag-burning were on the agenda. But analysts in both parties say
the stakes are high.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party that seizes the wave of change sweeping our economy
is the one that is destined to lead for the coming generation,''
Peter Ross Range, the editor of The New Democrat Blueprint, a
magazine of centrist Democrats, wrote in its latest edition.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Goldsmith, Bush's chief domestic policy adviser, said,
``There's a big fault line here.''
</P>
<P>
   Some talk of the new economy is as much about symbolism as about
substance. It allows Gore to try to capitalize on what should be
his greatest strength, the extraordinary economic expansion of the
Clinton years. And for Bush, analysts say, presenting himself as a
managerial reformer lets him look less ideological than other
Republicans, particularly those in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also true that since the last presidential election
the economy has changed sharply. Robust growth has turned deficits
into surpluses. Internet use and electronic commerce are exploding.
And the stock market, while cooling somewhat in recent months, has
generated huge new pools of wealth.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, new issues have arisen about the ``digital
divide'' separating the winners and losers in the New Economy, one
that has produced less stable jobs and less stable benefit plans
and left millions of Americans without health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge of the New Economy, one of the biggest
challenges, is to expand the winners' circle so you don't leave
people behind,'' said Al From, president of the Democratic
Leadership Council, the centrist Democrat organization. ``Because
one of the dangers of the New Economy is if you leave too many
people behind, you have a backlash.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush agree on some broad themes. They both embrace free
trade in the increasingly global economy, in contrast to the
third-party contenders, Pat Buchanan and Ralph Nader, and many
congressional Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   They also each call for the federal government to take a
stronger role in education policy at a time when the
knowledge-based economy rewards the higher educated. And they each
speak frequently of helping those whom prosperity has left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the two have fundamental differences on how to shape
government.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Gore would expand three government entitlement
programs, Medicare, Medicaid and Social Security. He would bring
more of the uninsured under the auspices of Medicaid, the health
insurance program for the poor. He would create a new Medicare
prescription-drug benefit for the elderly. And he would offer more
Social Security benefits to women, and also would create a new
retirement benefit for the working poor and the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   Bush argues for more individual choice. So he would allow
workers to divert an unspecified part of their Social Security
payroll tax to private investment accounts. And he would turn
Medicare from a fee-for-service guaranteed benefit program to one
that lets people buy different levels of health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   And while he, too, would create a prescription-drug benefit for
the elderly, he wants to do it by creating subsidies for private
insurers so that they, not the government directly, would offer the
benefit. He would give tax credits for health insurance but send
people to the private market to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   A similar contrast concerns education. Both men would invest in
schools and teachers _ Gore putting in about 10 times more money
than Bush _ and both have plans for how to improve accountability
and performance. But two proposals are particularly telling.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would extend the reach of public-school systems by giving
states grants to create public preschools. Bush, as a lever against
failing schools, would give vouchers for private-school tuition to
low-income parents whose children attend public schools that do not
improve.
</P>
<P>
   And while both candidates favor tax cuts, they differ in methods
and degree.
</P>
<P>
   Bush calls for a $1.3 trillion across-the-board tax cut over a
decade, saying, ``A government with unlimited funds soon becomes a
government of unlimited reach.'' Gore offers $500 billion in tax
cuts intended to reimburse people for particular needs _ like child
care or college tuition _ and phasing them out as income rises.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides call the top-down, big-government structures
outmoded relics of the Great Depression. ``Governor Bush will put
more control over decisions _ whether they are health, retirement
or savings _ in the hands of individuals,'' said Ari Fleischer, a
spokesman for Bush. ``The vice president will maintain them in the
hands of government.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats reply that Bush's ideas would erode the common
commitment to many government institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big danger with a lot of the Bush programs is what we call
cherry-picking,'' said Robert Reich, President Clinton's former
labor secretary. ``The healthy, the wealthy or the well-educated
will be the first to opt out, leaving the poor, the sicker and the
lesser-educated behind in the general insurance pools or in the
education system. This is a sure-fire recipe for social
stratification.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides are also trying to turn the debate to the question
of who gets helped under the competing plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush takes the old-fashioned approach of cutting everybody's
rates which ends up really, really, really helping wealthy people
because they pay so much and being of marginal help, if any, to
people in lower brackets,'' said Elaine Kamarck, Gore's policy
director.
</P>
<P>
   Bush promotes his tax cut by saying that it would remove 6
million low-income families from the tax rolls. But critics say it
would also give most of its benefits to higher-income groups simply
because they pay the most taxes.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis by Citizens for Tax Justice, a liberal public policy
group, found that the top 1 percent of tax payers would get 42
percent of the tax cuts in Bush's plan while the bottom 20 percent
of tax payers would get less than 1 percent of the reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides counter that their approach to tax cuts gives
individuals more choice on how to use their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore views government's roles as manipulating people and uses
people's own tax money to manipulate their behavior,'' said
Lawrence B. Lindsey, Bush's chief economic adviser. ``Bush says
it's your money. You keep it. Do what you think is best with it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A similar debate is brewing over Social Security. Depending on
how it is structured, Bush's plan to switch some Social Security
payroll tax to individual savings accounts could prove more
lucrative for upper-income groups.
</P>
<P>
   If 2 percentage points of payroll tax were diverted to IRAs,
someone earning $76,000 annually would have slightly more than
$1,500 a year to invest in private markets. Someone earning $25,000
would have $500 to invest. Critics of the idea say it is not hard
to see which taxpayer is likely to build up the better retirement
account.
</P>
<P>
   Some plans on Capitol Hill try to address this by cutting the
basic Social Security benefit more for higher-income individuals
than lower-income ones or by giving extra contributions to
low-income workers. Bush has said the idea of matching funds for
lower incomes should be considered. But he has not committed to it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would preserve the current Social Security system, as well
as create a new retirement plan that would be similar to a 401(k)
and would be geared toward helping lower-income groups.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the government would give couples earning less than
$30,000 a year $3 for every dollar they put in this savings
account; the government match would then reduce as income grew. The
program would not be available to couples earning more than
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides also that Gore would make Medicare and Social
Security more expansive and costly at a time when the boomer
generation's impending retirement threatens to bankrupt the
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental challenge facing the next president is to
solve this problem,'' said Lindsey. ``What Gore just proposed is
layering another new unfunded entitlement on top of what's already
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides also prefer to steer the debate to how people are
helped. They say that they want to give people with lower incomes
the same kinds of choices the wealthy have _ whether it is the
choice of attending a private school or the choice of investing
their retirement money in the stock market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
