r l BC-MEDICAL-LEGENDS-LIST-     07-03 0243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-LEGENDS-LIST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: Runs with MEDICAL-LEGENDS
 &HT;    Don't fall for medical myth-information
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   How do you recognize and stop the spread of a health-related
urban myth? Experts at the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, the American Council on Science and Health and
About.com, an information clearinghouse, generally agree on these
guidelines:
</P>
<P>
   _ If the story seems suspicious or its explanations are only
somewhat plausible, it's probably not true.
</P>
<P>
   _ When the message says, ``Please forward this to everyone you
know,'' that's a dead giveaway. Have you ever seen press releases
from the Johns Hopkins School of Public Health or the New England
Journal of Medicine that made such an urgent request? Don't forward
the message, even if you think it's funny. E-mail forwarding is how
the story's credibility grows.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beware of messages with lots of exclamation points. Real
health scares don't need schoolkids' punctuation.
</P>
<P>
   _ If the message refers to an expert, do an Internet search on
that person. Chances are good that the name won't come up as an
expert on anything.
</P>
<P>
   _ When doubts remain, two of the best sources to check are the
CDC and About.com Web sites on medical hoaxes. If you're still
scared or confused, don't hesitate to call your local public health
department or family doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
