u l BC-DENTAL-EMERGENCY-COX     07-03 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENTAL-EMERGENCY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer poses threat to children's teeth
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The kids are playing baseball and basketball,
swimming, climbing trees and hanging from jungle gyms. They're on
skateboards, in-line skates and trampolines.
</P>
<P>
   And some end up in dentists' offices, with broken, chipped or
knocked-out teeth. Summer is prime time for accidents, dentists
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the season when kids are playing hard _ especially the
boys,'' said Dr. Arva Lumpkin, a dentist. ``They're playing sports,
and they're doing anything that they think will help them fly. Of
course, that means they're getting hit with baseballs, smacked with
elbows in basketball or falling off the top of cars, jungle gyms
and trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, more than 5 million teeth get knocked out each year,
with such accidents accounting for 15 percent of children's dental
emergencies, according to the American Academy of Pediatric
Dentistry.
</P>
<P>
   When a child shows up with a bloody mouth, parents who know what
to do can save a permanent tooth _ and headaches in the years to
come.
</P>
<P>
   If a tooth is knocked out: The first task is to find it, said
Dr. James Hall III of Macon, Ga., a past president of the Georgia
Dental Association and a pediatric dentist for more than three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to immediately call your dentist _ generally,
you have a window of about an hour to get the tooth back into place
and stabilized to save it. Ideally, your child should be sitting in
a dentist's chair within a half-hour of the accident, Lumpkin said.
</P>
<P>
   After finding the tooth, you should gently wash it with water to
get off any debris. But you don't want to use soap, and you don't
want to damage the fibers on the root. Tap water would be fine.
</P>
<P>
   Next, you have some choices. If the child is old enough, stick
the tooth back into his mouth, storing it either in a cheek or the
place it was knocked from until you get to the dentist. If the
child is young and you think he might swallow it, you can _ brace
yourself _ put the tooth into your own mouth.
</P>
<P>
   If that's more than you bargained for when you signed up for
parenthood, dentists say a tooth can also be stored in milk. Again,
when handling the tooth, be careful to handle the crown and not the
root.
</P>
<P>
   To save the tooth, dentists typically will take X-rays to see
exactly how it should be placed back into its socket, then
stabilize it by bonding the tooth to flexible wires attached to
other teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like creating a hammock,'' explained Hall.
</P>
<P>
   And, perhaps surprisingly, children are smart enough not to mess
with the splint.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a tooth is damaged, they'll play with it with their
tongue, or they'll put their finger in their mouths,'' Hall said.
``But once it's stabilized, in all my years of being a dentist,
I've never had a child that came in with a splint off because he
monkeyed with it.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes about a week to determine whether the tooth has
stabilized. If it has, the dentist then has to evaluate whether a
root canal is needed.
</P>
<P>
   If the tooth is chipped or cracked: If it's a minor chip, a
dentist might be able to smooth it off. If the chip is more
substantial, he might be able to bond it. But if the nerve is
exposed, parents and dentists will have to discuss the best
options, which might include a replacement tooth.
</P>
<P>
   If the tooth is a baby tooth, the dentist will try to determine
whether a permanent tooth is near the surface of the gum. If so,
the child's only crisis will be finding the best location for the
tooth fairy to visit.
</P>
<P>
   If not, the dentist will put in a spacer, which looks like a
tooth if it's in the front but not if it's in the back. The spacer
is attached with wire and stays in place until the child's
permanent tooth shows up.
</P>
<P>
   Parents can try to protect their Indiana Joneses or Janes from
such mishaps. Most dentists will custom-mold mouth guards. Such
molds, which cost between $25 and $50, are more comfortable than
standard ones.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want to pay that much, Hall recommends that you buy
a pre-formed guard, put it in hot water and mold it to your child's
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are going to be kids,'' he said. ``All you can do is take
care of the basics and hold your breath.''
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : American Academy of Pediatric Dentistry:
www.aapd.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
