<HEADER>
A2308 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-ALLSTAR04-COX     07-03 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLSTAR04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AL All-Star squad will lack familiar faces
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - When the final vote totals are announced today,
Baltimore's Cal Ripken will again be the American League leader at
third base. But barring a quick recovery, he won't start his 17th
consecutive All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken, out with a bad back, is on the disabled list. So is
Cleveland outfielder Manny Ramirez, another AL starter, and Boston
pitching ace Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The American League has won three All-Star Games in a row. But
with Ken Griffey Jr. now in the National League and with Ripken,
Ramirez and Martinez injured, the AL has several holes to fill.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star Game is July 11 at Turner Field. Atlanta has hosted
the game once before: In 1972, the NL won 4-3 in Atlanta-Fulton
County Stadium on Joe Morgan's RBI single in the 10th inning.
</P>
<P>
   Few surprises are expected when the final totals in the fan vote
for the starters are announced. Voting at major-league stadiums
ended June 27, but fans could cast votes on the Internet through
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The closest races are at first base in the AL and second base in
the NL. Oakland's Jason Giambi (484,737) led Cleveland's Jim Thome
(455,614) at first in the AL. In the NL second base race, Houston's
Craig Biggio (452,863) was ahead of the New York Mets' Edgardo
Alfonzo (387,893).
</P>
<P>
   Six regular National League second basemen are hitting over
.300, so it will be one of the toughest positions to pare down when
the All-Star reserves are announced Wednesday, along with the
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox makes the selections for the NL, New
York Yankees manager Joe Torre for the AL. It won't be easy for
either. But Cox must have at least one player from each of the 16
NL teams on his 30-man roster. The AL has 14 teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will have one starter, third baseman Chipper Jones,
and Greg Maddux is a cinch to be named to the pitching staff. Other
Braves candidates are first baseman Andres Galarraga, outfielder
Andruw Jones, second baseman Quilvio Veras and pitcher Tom Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   The only Braves representatives last year were outfielder Brian
Jordan and pitcher Kevin Millwood. The AL won 4-1, with Martinez
winning the MVP award at Fenway Park. The Boston right-hander,
sidelined because of a strained oblique muscle, struck out the
first four batters and five of the six he faced.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
