<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACADEMY-RAPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO NAVY FOOTBALL PLAYERS CHARGED WITH RAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two star football players at the U.S. Naval Academy
were charged Monday with raping a female midshipman at a party
off-campus, according to the police and officials at the military
school.
</P>
<P>
   The football players, Cordrea Brittingham and Arion Keith
Williams, both 21, were charged with raping and performing other
sexual offenses on a fellow student who had passed out after
drinking at a party in the suburban town of Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   The victim, whose name was not released, awoke to find herself
being assaulted and pushed the men away, said Sgt. Joe Jordan, a
spokesman for the Anne Arundel County Police. She was treated at a
local hospital after midnight Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The two suspects were being held on $250,000 bond. If convicted
of second-degree rape, they would face a maximum prison sentence of
20 years, Jordan said. It was unclear whether the victim knew the
men, who had just completed their sophomore year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident is likely to revive a new round of soul-searching
at the academy, which has groomed future naval officers for a
century and a half, but has grappled with a prominent cheating
scandal and various crimes over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   The case could also renew debate over what some critics view as
a climate of privilege and leniency that surrounds the school's
most valued athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a cornerback from Detroit who is studying naval
architecture, is considered one of the team's best athletes,
according to a Web site of the Naval Academy's sports programs.
Known by the nickname Bas, he started in 11 of Navy's 12 games last
season and had more than 60 tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Brittingham, a running back from Berlin, Md. who is studying
economics, is known as one of the fastest players on the team and
has ``an impressive 40-inch vertical leap,'' according to the
team's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   An academy spokeswoman Monday declined to say whether the school
had taken any action against the suspects. She referred inquiries
to the police.
</P>
<P>
   Although local police officials said they could not recall
similar incidents at the school recently, the academy was rocked by
a series of scandals during the 1990s. The most prominent case
involved the theft of an examination for electrical engineering in
December 1992, in which 133 midshipmen were found to have violated
the honor code by lying to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   During a three-week period in 1996, a midshipman was arrested
for assaulting four female students, another student was charged
with sexually abusing a toddler, and two midshipmen and three
former academy students were indicted for operating a car theft
ring.
</P>
<P>
   Investigating the series of problems, a 20-member panel led by
former CIA director Stansfield Turner concluded there was no
``systemic flaw'' at the military college.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2045EDT &QL; 
