<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2315 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-03 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A FOURTH OF JULY ADDRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My fellow Americans.
</P>
<P>
   We stand here today on the bridge to the 21st century. Some may
decry this bridge as unnecessary, and argue that since we have
already been in the 21st century for some months now, no new
infrastructure is needed.
</P>
<P>
   To them I say: Consider the feelings of the many Americans who
believe that the new century does not really begin until Jan. 1,
2001. We have not heard their voices recently. They cower silently
in our midst, fearing that one careless word might trigger a new
flood of millennium roundups. But they are out there, and they
deserve their bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are dawdlers on the road to the future, milling
sullenly like frequent fliers at La Guardia Airport during a
monsoon. However, even they must know that we are on the brink of
something new, something so unique it has not even been stolen from
European TV programming. It is a new era, and to begin it, we will
be electing a new president. That campaign has already begun _
indeed, it has been going on for longer than the combined
administrations of William Henry Harrison and James Garfield.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to believe that this is still the same race as the
one that had Bill Bradley and Steve Forbes in it, in which Lamar
Alexander once frolicked and Orrin Hatch romped. And where are they
now, my friends? Not gone, surely, but only on summer hiatus, like
the Sopranos.
</P>
<P>
   Soon we will bid farewell to Bill Clinton, our companion through
so many civic adventures, from the New Covenant to the V-chip. We
can be confident that his successor will be a man who listens to
the lessons of the past. In fact, both Al Gore and George W. Bush
are so soaked in the lore of bygone elections that they might well
be called the metaphorical equivalent of history's drowned kittens.
</P>
<P>
   We all realize that Bush is the son of one former president. But
how many of you know that he is also a direct descendant of
another? Yes, some of Bush's genomes were once worn by Franklin
Pierce _ the man known as ``Young Hickory'' to his supporters in
New Hampshire and ``The Fainting General'' to his troops in the
field. He was also called ``the victor over many a hard-fought
bottle,'' but only by political opponents wishing to harp on
isolated incidents, all of which, I believe, occurred before his
40th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Our candidates are both the products of great traditions of
public service. Gore is the son of a senator, Bush is the grandson.
America has been blessed with many presidents who spring from such
well-hoed political truck gardens. Perhaps this year's winner will
find it in him to become another John Quincy Adams or Benjamin
Harrison, or even a second, smaller, William Howard Taft.
</P>
<P>
   There are some among you, I know, who feel that electoral
politics are not what they once were. Where, you may ask, are the
election rallies of yore, the bonfires, the parades? Whatever
happened to the old-fashioned civic spirit that once inspired our
citizens to raise incredibly tall poles or roll extremely large
balls from town to town in support of a favorite candidate? When
people ask, as they so often do, ``Where are the Grover Clevelands
for the new millennium?'' I can only shake my head and say that we
get the leaders we deserve.
</P>
<P>
   Some people go further and claim that there are not even any
issues worth fighting for in this flaccid new era. They miss the
days when the mere mention of ``free silver'' or ``Remember the
Maine'' or ``Save Checkers'' set passions quivering. Today, our
blood runs cooler. Still, who among us did not feel a twinge of
excitement as we watched the Al Gore Prosperity and Progress Tour?
Who did not feel relief at the news that George W. Bush intends to
be a Reformer With Results?
</P>
<P>
   No issues? Speak on, you prophets of doom _ what say you of
Bush's war against the ``tollbooth on the road to the middle
class,'' a loathsome structure he intends to destroy with copious
tax reductions? Bush hates that tollbooth, even on the days he
refers to it as ``toolboth.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore says he would use our excess money to pay down the national
debt, and make the nation totally solvent for the first time since
1835, an era when Franklin Pierce was just a pup and America was
preparing to celebrate the Panic of 1837.
</P>
<P>
   ``The precedents are not particularly instructive,'' the vice
president said recently. It is a sentiment we can all take to
heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
