<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO ELECTION BRINGS FEELING OF EMPOWERMENT TO THE PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MEXICO-ELECTION) 
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For three generations, Juan Quiroz's family has run a
fruit-and-vegetable stand in the market that sits in the shadow of
the presidential mansion, los Pinos. But given the impenetrable
nature of Mexican politics, he said he has never felt close to
power.
</P>
<P>
   But several hours after he cast his vote on Sunday, Quiroz said
he realized he had touched power for the first time. His choice for
president, Vicente Fox, would be the first man in 70 years to oust
the ruling Revolutionary Institutional Party, known as the PRI,
from the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought that Fox would win, even if all the votes were
for him because the PRI was so powerful,'' Quiroz said. ``The
people finally showed that we are more powerful than any political
party _ even a dictatorship like the PRI. Now the people are in
control.''
</P>
<P>
   That euphoric feeling of empowerment echoed across Mexico on
Monday, among people of various backgrounds, professions and
political stripes, in newspaper columns and radio commentary, in
bookstores and cafes. A day after the most historic election in
recent memory, the nation seemed stunned and excited by Fox's
decisive triumph over one of the longest ruling political machines
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, people said, marked more than a challenge for
Mexico's president-elect. In words full of optimism, people
expressed pride in the peaceful way their votes were cast and
counted, in the way they overcame their fear of change and embraced
it. And almost everyone interviewed, no matter which candidate they
had supported, emerged with some personal feeling of triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new day for me,'' said Francisco Rosales, 50, while
browsing through classics at a popular bookstore called Ghandi.
``The PRI has been defeated and once they are going everything else
in our lives will be easier. There will be less corruption, less
manipulation, less fear and more participation.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at the market near los Pinos, people like Luis Manuel
Dominguez said that they did not expect all of Mexico's troubles to
vanish quickly and that they would be happy with slow, steady steps
toward progress.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans took the first step on Election Day, Dominguez, 38, a
telephone repairman, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time,'' he added as he ate stewed chicken at a
lunch counter, ``we are entering a government that was really
created by the people. This is not a cosmetic victory. It is
real.''
</P>
<P>
   Along a commercial strip in the working-class town of
Nezahuacoyotl, just east of the capital, the celebration of Fox's
victory stretched into the late afternoon Monday. Students waved at
passing cars, holding up their first two fingers, now a well-known
gesture from Fox's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents used to say it was better to vote for someone who
is bad but familiar rather than someone who is good but unknown,''
said Alejandro Robles, a student of veterinary medicine at the
National Autonomous University of Mexico who stood smiling among a
group of Fox supporters even though he had voted for Cardenas. ``I
think young people are ready to try something new.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager of a clothing store showed off the ink that was
rubbed on his thumb at the polls to indicate that he had voted. He
said he had voted for Fox, but he saw the election as a victory for
many.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox became president,'' the manager said, ``but the people of
Mexico became a democracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2320 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-03 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: JUST DO IT 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As it says in Ecclesiastes, for everything there is a season _ a
time to be born and a time to die; a time to plant, and a time to
pluck up what is planted. The same is true in diplomacy _ there is
a time to stall and a time to yak, a time to hide and a time to
decide. For Israelis and Palestinians, this is the season for
deciding, and President Clinton should usher it in by summoning the
Israeli and Palestinian leaders to Camp David for one last
cards-on-the-table, in-your-face, put-up-or-shut-up summit to
finally, finally put an end to this conflict.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has been deftly
squeezing the parties to help ensure that a possible Camp David
summit would have a reasonable chance of closing the remaining
gaps. In some cases those gaps have narrowed, in others they remain
a chasm. Never mind. There is only one way to find out whether that
chasm can ever be bridged and that is by bringing together a U.S.
president like Bill Clinton, who is trusted by all the parties; an
Israeli leader like Ehud Barak, who understands what Israel will
have to give for a secure peace; and a Palestinian leader like
Yasser Arafat, who has the stature, and the interest in his dying
days, to make the hard concessions for his own people.
</P>
<P>
   At this moment the Clinton team is considering whether to shake
the dice and just invite the parties to Camp David, even though the
chances of success are 50-50. The Palestinians have been resisting,
until they are assured that they will get all they want and won't
be trapped in a Clinton-Barak vice. Barak has been pushing for the
summit, arguing that the only way he can make big concessions is a
one-time, finish-it-all deal. Clinton has been worried that if the
summit tries and fails, the whole fabric of Arab-Israeli
peacemaking could unravel.
</P>
<P>
   All these concerns notwithstanding, you are never going to have
a better alignment of the stars for making a deal than you have now
in the Clinton-Arafat-Barak trio. If these three leaders can't
close the deal, no one can, and we need to know that now. Trying
and failing won't be any worse than not trying, because without a
framework deal for a final peace, the situation will unravel anyway
_ the Palestinians will unilaterally declare a state by Sept. 13
and Israel will unilaterally annex the West Bank Jewish
settlements, and Lord only knows what will happen after that.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem will be Jerusalem. Barak can muster an
Israeli majority for giving back some 90 percent of the West Bank
(while retaining the 10 percent where 80 percent of the Jewish
settlers live), provided he doesn't appear to be redividing
Jerusalem. Arafat can give up some West Bank land, provided he
doesn't give up the Arab-Muslim claim to Jerusalem. Everyone knows
the solution: Let the Palestinians also have a capital in
Jerusalem, based outside the current municipal boundary in Abu Dis,
and give them authority over the Arab neighborhoods in East
Jerusalem, while the Israelis retain authority over the Jewish
neighborhoods, which become part of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis rarely go to the Arab neighborhoods anyway, and they
certainly don't need to worry about their garbage collection. The
Palestinians already have control over the Muslim holy places in
East Jerusalem and the Palestinian neighborhoods there already vote
in Palestinian elections. This sort of practical solution would
still leave Israel with control over the biggest Jewish Jerusalem
in Jewish history _ one that would unite the Jewish neighborhoods
in East and West Jerusalem under Israeli sovereignty, with
international recognition. Better to share the city this way, so
Jews will feel free to go anywhere there, than maintain a formal
control everywhere, and Jews will only dare go into their own
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   This is the hard price of peace. You can have it now or after a
lot more bloodshed, but it's not going to change. So let's try now.
If you summon them, they will come; if they come, they will
compromise; if they compromise enough _ maybe you'll have a deal.
The only people who would criticize Bill Clinton for trying and
failing would be those who either don't want a deal or hate him to
begin with _ in other words, the same people who would never give
him credit if he tried and succeeded. So just do it. As it also
says in Ecclesiastes: ``He who observes the wind will not sow; and
he who regards the clouds will not reap.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2322 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-ART-N     07-03 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO, VOTING IN NEW LEADER, BEGINS POLITICAL SEA CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MEXICO-FOX, MEXICO-ASSESS and related stories.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Swept to power by younger, better-educated voters
fed up with corruption and one-party rule, President-elect Vicente
Fox on Monday began the transition of Mexico from a republic headed
for decades by an autocratic president to one in which political
power suddenly seemed up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   As Fox fielded congratulatory phone calls Monday from world
leaders, including President Clinton, and met with President
Ernesto Zedillo, election returns showed that Mexican voters on
Sunday had handed him a substantially more decisive victory over
the governing party than any poll had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   With 93 percent of the ballots tabulated, the Mexican electoral
agency reported that Fox had won 43 percent of the votes, while
Francisco Labastida, the candidate of the ruling party, won 36
percent and Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a leftist candidate, won 17
percent. Fox will take office on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   For many Mexicans, it was still sinking in Monday that after 71
years, the Institutional Revolutionary Party, which evolved from a
alliance of revolutionary generals into a model nationalist party
imitated across Latin America before degenerating into a clique of
corrupt insiders, had finally been deposed from the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But when the dust settles on the first democratic transition of
power in this country's history, for the first time none of the
major parties _ the deposed one, Fox's center-right party, or the
largest leftist grouping _ will be in control of either house of
Congress. Fox will preside over a government unused to coalition
politics but one in which all major business will require the
consent of one or the other of his rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the parties are going to have to relearn the art of making
politics,'' said Carlos Elizondo, a political scientist who is
rector of the Center for Research and Teaching in Mexico City.
``The fundamental pillars of Mexico's political system have
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   These unsettled results were reflected around the country. Fox's
National Action Party won the two governor's seats up for grabs on
Sunday and will now govern in seven of Mexico's 31 states. In
Mexico City, Fox's leftist rivals in the former opposition retained
control of the mayor's office but the president-elect's party took
control of the Assembly, the legislative body in this city-state.
</P>
<P>
   As president, Fox will face the ticklish task of meeting the
hopes for quick and sweeping change of the diverse voters who
backed him. He has promised, simultaneously, to modernize the
economy and spur 7 percent growth, carry out sweeping political
reforms, and initiate an ``educational revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   He has pledged to better the lot not only of the largely young,
middle-class professionals in his own center-right party, but also
of millions of poor urban workers and farmers who have in the past
supported the governing party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all got to get to work right away,'' Fox said in an
interview early Monday, after his triumph. ``I want to be certain
to deliver good results to the people of Mexico, to govern and to
govern well.''
</P>
<P>
   The election results provoked a debate over how successfully
Zedillo's party would navigate its journey from its powerhouse
position into the ranks of the opposition. Some said that the party
had already proved its adaptability and resilience in states where
Fox's party had already won control of the governor's chair.
</P>
<P>
   But others, comparing the position of the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI, to some communist parties in
Eastern Europe, argued that without presidential support and
control over federal patronage, the party would crumble.
</P>
<P>
   The party's president during the presidential campaign quickly
announced her resignation, and some party officials said they
feared that a sweeping exodus could follow.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the elections to fill all 128 seats in the Senate
and all 500 in the Chamber of Deputies indicated that Fox's party
would finish with its powers significantly enhanced, mainly at the
expense of the leftist party with which it shared opposition powers
during the last Legislature, but that it would not control a
majority of votes.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI lost the Senate majority it had enjoyed since the
party's creation and without the power of the president to
coordinate its efforts, the PRI's entire legislative delegation
will wield considerably less clout.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's party was receiving 38 percent of the votes for Congress,
the returns showed. The PRI was receiving 36 percent and Cardenas'
party, 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As the ballot-counting continued, Zedillo met privately in the
presidential compound with the top PRI leaders, whose power now
rests almost entirely in the provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that Zedillo outlined his views of the unprecedented
survival challenges facing the party, which had gone undefeated in
presidential voting _ often through the simple exercise of its vast
powers of patronage and pork and sometimes through outright ballot
fraud _ for 71 years, longer than any other party in the world.
</P>
<P>
   In a second encounter, Zedillo addressed the 21 of Mexico's 31
state governors who belong to his party, urging them to cooperate
fully with Fox's government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to work with the new president in a relation of
respect and collaboration,'' Fernando Silva, the PRI governor of
the north central state of San Luis Potosi, told reporters after
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   If Mexico was entering absolutely new political terrain with the
PRI's defeat, neither foreign nor domestic investors appeared
concerned. The Mexican stock market surged 6.1 percent on news of
Fox's victory, and the peso, which had been battered in recent
weeks as nervous Mexicans converted savings to dollars,
strengthened 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
