<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-WOMAN-WEIGHTLIFTE     07-03 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WOMAN-WEIGHTLIFTER-1750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WOMAN WEIGHT LIFTER CARRIES STRENGTH, AGILITY, INTELLECT AND
HUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Around the gym, 17-year-old Cheryl Haworth goes
by the nickname Fun. She merrily sings a ``Simpsons'' ditty about
our most ineffective presidents, rattles off the polysyllabic names
of the body's most obscure muscles, knows most of ``The Raven'' by
heart and is an award-winning artist whose lifelike drawings
resemble photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet a senior in high school, Haworth is also the best
American hope, man or woman, for an Olympic medal in weight lifting
at the Summer Games in September, and she has picked up two phrases
of Chinese that may help in communicating with her top competition
in Sydney, Australia. The problem is, she learned the words from
television's most irreverent character, Bart Simpson, who taught
her to say, ``Here are your eyes, sir,'' and ``You can never have
enough slave laborers.''
</P>
<P>
   So maybe this is not exactly in keeping with the Olympic spirit
of international brotherhood. She might as well slip a whoopee
cushion to Juan Antonio Samaranch, the Olympic president, at the
opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I won't be saying those things to anybody,'' Haworth said
with a laugh. ``How do you know if they're true? I heard them on
`The Simpsons.'''
</P>
<P>
   Women's weight lifting will be a medal sport for the first time
in Sydney, and at 5 feet 9 inches and 300 pounds, Haworth will
provide a riveting presence in the superheavyweight division with
her size, agility, speed, balance and ballistic strength. She took
a bronze medal at the 1999 world championships and won a
preliminary Olympic event four months ago in Sydney, having deftly
translated her raw power into the technique and velocity necessary
to succeed in international weight lifting.
</P>
<P>
   She can run the 40-yard dash in 5.5 seconds, has a 30-inch
vertical leap, has the flexibility to do a full split and, from a
standing start, jumps on and off wooden boxes standing two and a
half feet high to increase the fast-twitch explosiveness in her
legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of football coaches come in here, and I think they would
die for someone that fast, flexible and strong,'' said Michael
Cohen, Haworth's personal coach, who will also coach the American
women in Sydney. ``I've never seen another woman that strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Haworth, 19, was sitting in a restaurant with her family,
urging a visitor to squeeze her sister's arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feel her biceps,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one city in which a woman flexing her biceps in a
family restaurant would not be considered out of place, it is
Savannah, immortalized for its florid eccentricities in the book
``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil.'' A tour group had just
trooped through the restaurant, looking for the tunnel that pirates
once used to smuggle forced laborers onto ships in the Savannah
River.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go ahead, feel,'' Beth Haworth insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Haworth flexed her left arm, and the muscle was as hard as the
restaurant's peach cobbler was soft. Her left arm is the smaller,
Haworth said, but the biceps still measures 17 inches in
circumference, the same size as the visitor's neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now feel her quads,'' Beth Haworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Haworth flexed her thigh muscles, which felt as sturdy as the
moss-draped canopy oaks that tower over Savannah's historic
district.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-two inches,'' Beth Haworth said proudly. ``Bigger than
my waist.''
</P>
<P>
   Haworth wears her hair pulled tightly behind her head, and
sometimes, she said, people see her wide face and dark features and
ask whether she is Samoan. Once, for television cameras, she
hoisted her sister overhead as if she were a barbell. Another time,
she and a group of friends lifted another friend's car and moved it
across a parking lot. People are always asking her to pick them up.
On ``The Tonight Show,'' the actor Damon Wayans jumped into her
arms.
</P>
<P>
   Good-naturedly, she declines to lift people when they ask. She
is an athlete, not a sideshow performer. Yet she also appears to be
extremely comfortable with her size in a society that often demands
that women be sliced as thin as corned beef.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of 17-year-olds don't weigh 300 pounds, but I was
never really discouraged because I was so big,'' Haworth said.
``It's who I was, who I am. I knew I wasn't the right size or shape
for certain things, but I didn't let it bother me. I decided to
look for something else.''
</P>
<P>
   A sickly child, Haworth had her tonsils and adenoids removed
when she was 6, and as she grew healthier, she began to gain
weight, says her mother, Sheila, who is a registered nurse. Sheila
Haworth consulted dietitians, but she decided that it was not
proper to put a young girl on a diet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my daughter sits down and says she is still hungry, I'd
feed her again,'' Sheila Haworth said. ``I don't want her hating me
or for this to be a battleground. I give her fat-free milk at home,
fruit, good food. If she's going to be big, she'll be big.''
</P>
<P>
   At 13, looking to increase her strength for playing softball,
Haworth visited the Paul Anderson-Howard Cohen Gym, where Team
Savannah, a weight lifting club, does its training. The Haworths
are an athletic family. Bob Haworth, the father, played freshman
football and wrestled at the University of Nebraska in the early
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Haworth always appeared to be strong as a young girl, her father
said. She built treehouses in the family's rural neighborhood.
``And she arm-wrestled boys on the bus _ once,'' he said, laughing.
But it was her first day in the gym that showed him just how
extraordinary her strength could be. Haworth lifted 110 pounds to
her chest ``like it was a broomstick,'' said Cohen, who would
become her coach.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Sheryl Cohen, worked with Haworth for 10 minutes and
then reported to him, ``She's the strongest girl I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   As her weight-lifting skills improved, so did her
self-confidence, Beth Haworth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember people would pick on her, call her fat, and you
could tell her feelings were upset,'' Beth Haworth said. ``Now, I
don't think anyone would be caught dead calling her a bad name.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years after she began lifting, Haworth entered the 1999
Pan American Games in Winnipeg. During the competition, she grabbed
the bar with 246 pounds attached and moved it slightly, away from a
stationary television camera. The crowd gasped. She won the event.
Her coach said a veteran Colombian lifter, Maria Isabel Urrutia,
was so inconsolable, she vowed to retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I quit,'' Urrutia said, according to Cohen. ``I let a
16-year-old beat me.''
</P>
<P>
   In competition, Haworth has lifted 264 pounds in the snatch and
319 in the clean and jerk, the two types of Olympic lifting. This
combined weight of 583 pounds is about 20 pounds short of the world
record. If she remains with the sport through the 2004 Summer
Olympics in Athens, Cohen said, he expects that she will be lifting
700 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   On an afternoon in early June, Haworth was simply warming up for
a state competition the next day. She placed 100 pounds on the bar
and snatched it over her head with little effort, then did several
lifts with 150 pounds. In a snatch lift, the bar is brought from
the floor to overhead in one ballistic motion lasting seven-tenths
of a second, which requires remarkable speed, flexibility and
balance in getting under the bar, along with tremendous strength in
the legs, hips and back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at her hamstring,'' Cohen said as Haworth rested in a
chair between lifts, the muscle hanging like a hammock on the back
of her right leg. ``In a normal person that size, that would be
fat. But that is muscle dripping off her leg.''
</P>
<P>
   In the clean and jerk, the bar is brought first to the
shoulders, then propelled over the head with an explosive
scissoring of the legs. Speed and position are not as important as
in the snatch, but strength is far more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's just playing with it,'' Cohen said as Haworth lifted 255
pounds over her head. ``She's never missed a jerk. If she gets it
to her chest, she'll get it over her head.''
</P>
<P>
   Is she in good health at 300 pounds? Yes, said Mike Popson, the
head trainer for Team Savannah and the USA Weightlifting. Haworth
received a clean bill of health on a thyroid checkup, and while
weight increases the risks for diabetes and heart problems, Popson
said, Haworth is being monitored. ``She's healthy and strong as an
ox, as far as I'm concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The staff at Team Savannah would like Haworth to lose some
weight eventually, and she will begin working closely with a
dietitian, Popson said. As she gets older and continues to train
vigorously, Popson and Cohen also expect Haworth to replace some of
her body fat with lean muscle. Her only health concern at the
moment is a bulging disk in her back _ a chronic weight lifting
concern _ for which she receives weekly treatment from a
chiropractor.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen is a former high school health teacher, and he believes
that anorexia and bulimia pose a bigger hazard than overeating does
for teen-age girls. ``Girls are taught that they've got to be under
100 pounds and wafer thin,'' Cohen said. ``That's ridiculous.
That's dangerous. If a child is healthy and comfortable, that's
what you want. Cheryl says: `I'm bigger than most people and I
don't care. Like me or not for what I am.' If you're not healthy,
you're not going to be lifting that kind of weight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Haworths live on the southwestern edge of Savannah, in a
bucolic neighborhood that was once the Wild Heron Plantation.
Behind the family house in a fenced-in, overgrown area is a slave
graveyard. Overlooking the backyard, in her father's home office,
is a drawing board at which Haworth excels at her other passion,
art.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth grade, she stunned her mother with a reproduction
of Van Gogh's ``Starry, Starry Night.'' She will be a senior in the
fall at the Savannah Arts Academy, and with a pencil drawing of one
of her training partners, she recently won first place in a contest
sponsored by the Savannah College of Art and Design.
</P>
<P>
   She has an IQ of 135, and like many highly intelligent children,
she said she found herself growing unenthusiastic about things that
did not interest or challenge her. But art and weight lifting have
engrossed her, because she is good at both, because they are alike
and because they are different _ one wholly subjective, the other
completely objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both take a lot of concentration, and technique, and they
both force you to finish something,'' Haworth said. ``In weight
lifting, you are always improving. It's always structured. You
never wonder if you're good or not.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sydney, she could be good enough to be called the strongest
woman in the world. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
