<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2331 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-BROWNSTONE-REVIVAL-AR     07-03 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWNSTONE-REVIVAL-ART-2TAKES(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE IT OR NOT, BROWNSTONE IS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., R.I., N.J., N.Y., Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo, NYT8, is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Conn. _ Mike Meehan, a geologist who once explored for
coal in the Appalachian Mountains, is supervising a crew of four
men and a canary yellow backhoe, clawing away at the cliffs of the
country's only operating brownstone quarry, trying to fill the
orders that come pouring in every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``See those chunks with the CU on 'em?'' he asked, pointing to
some big rocks the color of fudge and the size of a Doberman's
doghouse. ``They're for the Cooper Union in New York City. And
those over there are going to the Cathedral of St. Peter and Paul
in Providence, and that's a stoop going to Yale. Those pieces there
are for the cornice trim on a new house going up in the Farmington
Valley.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brownstone is back. That somber yet elegant cloak for more than
50,000 row houses, from Baltimore to Boston, was revered during the
so-called Brown Decades of the mid-19th century, then reviled by
the century's turn, when gleaming white limestone and marble
captivated the public.
</P>
<P>
   For the past six decades, Portland's quarries _ which produced
an estimated 80 percent of New York City's brownstone _ have been
largely forgotten by the outside world. Already moribund by the
start of the Great Depression, they filled with water after the
flood of 1936 and the hurricane of 1938, were discovered by
teen-agers as a make-out spot and were adopted by fishermen who
stealthily hunt big bass near the towering brownstone cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   But preservationists and planners are beginning to see a new
future for the formidable stone. Architects have started using it
to give a touch of historical sobriety to gaudy mansionettes, and
conservators have begun renewing the elegant facades of grand
monuments like the Cooper Union on Astor Place in Manhattan, where
Abraham Lincoln addressed crowds before the 1860 election. On May
16, the Department of the Interior gave three quarries in Portland
status as a national historic landmark, recognizing a role that
dates to colonial times.
</P>
<P>
   But just as this Connecticut River town in the center of the
state sponsors brainstorming sessions on how to lure visitors to
its first would-be tourist attraction, the two defunct quarries,
the re-opening of the third Portland quarry has set off a debate on
whether brownstone should be used at all.
</P>
<P>
   Because the terrible secret is that brownstone _ ``the very
blood and fiber of New York City,'' in the words of Vincent Scully,
a professor emeritus at Yale University _ is not really much good
as a building material. The same quality that gives brownstone its
charm, making it easy to quarry and easy to carve, also makes it
exquisitely vulnerable to harsh weather and the passage of time,
especially if the stone is installed improperly and is maintained
poorly.
</P>
<P>
   At the Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception in Albany, built
in 1848 from Portland stone, its preservation architect, John
Mesick, said, ``you can take your hand and pull off chunks as big
as apple pies.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Brooklyn and Manhattan, many of the most magnificent
brownstone houses, the ones that date from the Civil War era, are
in danger of losing their sweeping balustraded staircases and their
entire facades. At the National Arts Club, in Gramercy Park in
Manhattan, the brownstone, like a chocolate bar left on the
dashboard on a summer day, just seemed to melt.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Herrera, director of technical services at the New York
Landmarks Conservancy, said that the brownstone veneer on the
facades on some of the houses began to fall off a few years after
they were built. ``Historical records state that some started
deteriorating 10, 20, 30 years later,'' he said. ``Brownstone is
not a consistent material: some of it is OK, and some is perfectly
awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone is building all-new brownstone houses; the
architect Philip Johnson was the last to use it in a major way, for
the Bobst Library at New York University back in the 1960s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today, it is brownstone repair and replacement that is being
debated in classrooms, at special seminars and landmark
commissions. Should the real brownstone be used, or a cheap ``cut
and cover'' brown stucco coating favored by contractors?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very controversial subject right now,'' said Paul
Byard, dean of Columbia University's preservation program, and the
architect for the Cooper Union's $12 million brownstone
restoration, the largest in history.
</P>
<P>
   Byard has chosen Portland brownstone, which he says is authentic
and should last for at least six decades if maintained, and the
joints kept properly full of mortar.
</P>
<P>
   Mesick says he will not use it on the Albany Cathedral and is
combing the Ruhr Valley in Germany and southern Scotland for
brownstone that doesn't spall, or flake off, the way he says the
Connecticut stone does. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is even a long-running debate on whether it is
aesthetically pleasing. While many still find the stone beautiful,
Edith Wharton could not stand the stuff. In a memoir published four
years before the Portland quarries shut down, she told of her
childhood return to New York from Europe, her writer's voice
dripping with disappointment at ``this low-studded rectangular New
York, cursed with its universal chocolate-colored coating of the
most hideous stone ever quarried.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The brownstone of the Portland quarries was formed roughly 200
million years ago, when Connecticut was a hot and humid savanna,
with a major rainy season that created streams and rivers that
eroded the Paleozoic rocks of the Eastern Highlands.
</P>
<P>
   As the rains tapered off, the dinosaurs lumbered through,
leaving their footprints in the mud _ footprints that are still
being uncovered by Meehan's crew at the quarry, who spend part of
their time each day showing off the prints to schoolchildren and
other visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The streams left deposits of mudstone, shale and sand. This
sediment, composed of quartz, mica and feldspar, became
brownstone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The English first settled Portland in the 1600s, using the
reddish-brown stone _ far easier to carve than granite _ for
gravestones. During the 1700s, the town operated one of the
quarries and offered the stone free to its inhabitants. By the
mid-19th century, the quarries were controlled by three main
companies, and they employed 1,500 workers, a third them Irish.
Over the years, the quarries sent more than 5 million cubic yards
of brownstone down the Connecticut River.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While some blasting was involved, much of it just fell away from
the cliffs, not unlike the way it is now falling from facades.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Lewis, a geologist who was in Portland for a recent
seminar on the quarries, said brownstone ``erodes very quickly,
it's very soft,'' adding, ``And if you build with the wrong layer,
it flakes off.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That is what happened with so many of New York City's
brownstones _ they were built with the wrong layer.
</P>
<P>
   Everett H. Ortner, who in 1968 helped found the Brownstone
Revival Committee in New York City, said, ``In the beginning, they
selected the very best material.'' But with the speculative rush in
the post-Civil War years, the quality went downhill fast. ``Stone
had always been the material of the aristocracy, and wood or brick
that of the middle class,'' Ortner said. ``Suddenly the middle
class could have the permanence _ an impression of permanence that
wood never could have.''
</P>
<P>
   In the brownstone heydey, quarries operated up and down the East
Coast, from Patterson, N.J., to Longmeadow. Mass., and beyond.
Portland's was the biggest, but alas, its stone was one of the
softest. Ten years ago, the Society for the Preservation of New
England Antiquities bluntly declared in a brochure on brownstone
care, ``Portland brownstone is notorious for its poor durability.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan, the quarry owner, as well as the local town officials
here, dispute that contention.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan, 50, plans to ship 1,250 tons from his small quarry this
year, about $500,000 worth of stone. He just sent out 11 truckloads
of brownstone to add decorative accents to a 40,000-square-foot
house going up in Michigan. A new saw from Italy is on order,
designed to bore down into the rock after he has exhausted the
cliffs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked about brownstone's reputation as a fragile building
material, Edward L. Kalinowski, Portland's First Selectman, said
``I don't believe it.'' Kalinowski's grandfather worked in the
quarries until the mid-1930s, when a giant slab of rock crushed his
leg.
</P>
<P>
   The reason that Portland stone did not last, he and others say,
was either because it was installed improperly, or because bad
stone was used.
</P>
<P>
   When the quarries were running at a normal pace, half of the
brownstone was thrown away, used for railway embankments or crushed
for gravel. But in the mid-1800s, the pressure was on to produce
more and more stone for building facades in America's major cities.
According to historians, Portland began shipping some substandard
material. ``In the brownstone heyday, the speculators didn't
care,'' said Alison Guinness, the curator of the Connecticut River
Museum and the author of a paper on the Portland quarry history.
``They just wanted it, and they slapped it up,''
</P>
<P>
   The brownstone was meant to be installed with its striations
facing out and the flat side facing up. Unfortunately, it was
easier, quicker and cheaper (and better looking, too) for the
builders to place it on the front of a building with its flat side
facing out. Meehan, the quarry owner, explained: ``It's like a
book; if you put it out in the rain with its spine facing up, the
water will run down the pages. If you lay it down flat, the water
won't get inside.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why there are so few gravestones left: they were stuck
in the ground with the flat side facing the front. The rain soaked
into the striations, and the stone fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last century, decaying stone was largely repaired by
chipping it off and applying a brown-colored stucco. How many row
houses have been treated this way? ``Are you kidding?'' Herrera
responded. ``Thousands.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the patches fade and change color, they begin to look like
camouflage. The stucco mixture also must be perfect, he said,
``otherwise, it's like chocolate pudding.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, experts say, masonry contractors are persuading
some homeowners to chip away everything and replace the whole
facade with a stucco that includes cement, at a cost that can range
from $20,000 to $60,000, depending on the contractor. This
approach, which critics say lasts 20 years at the most, makes
preservationists tremble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially since they re-opened the Portland quarry, I like to
see real stone for replacement,'' said Ivan Myjer, a stone
conservator from Boston who directed the restoration at St. John
the Divine in New York City. Myjer, who hand-picked the stone for
the Cooper Union and is supervising its use, argues that real
brownstone can be installed for probably no more than $60,000 and
lasts longer than a cement job, between 60 and 100 years, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the favored method in New York City is still cement, even
for the rich.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Adami, a masonry contractor who specializes in brownstone
restoration, recently finished a brownstone-colored cement job and
total renovation on Garfield Place in Park Slope, Brooklyn, which
he said cost over $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's in the stock market _ he makes $300,000 a minute _
and he had his own face, his wife's face, his two daughter's faces
cast and put at the top of columns in front of his house,'' the
contractor said. ``Now that's a brownstone restoration job!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
