s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     07-03 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO MANY WAYS TO DIAL HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use on Sunday, July 9) 
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Technology has eliminated certain problems of calling home from
Europe: Belle Epoque hotel instruments, non-English-speaking
operators and wavering connections. The new problems arise from the
technology and its overflow of possibilities: you can buy a cell
phone compatible with European services, or rent one; sign up for
an international program with your regular phone company, or sign
up for another overseas service.
</P>
<P>
   For those preparing for a trip, here is a review of a very few
of the newer possibilities. It's impossible to be comprehensive in
a field that is changing so fast: on June 27, the Justice
Department moved to block Worldcom, which absorbed MCI in 1998,
from acquiring Sprint. Before picking any of the options below, be
sure to ask how _ and if _ the service works in your destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Experts describe the international cell-phone picture as a Tower
of Babel. Almost all wireless companies in Europe and the Middle
East use the same digital technology, GSM, or global system for
mobile communication. But the United States apparently got left
behind on this. Most companies here use quite a number of other
technologies and frequencies, so most cell phones in the United
States will not work overseas.
</P>
<P>
   This gave rise to the idea of renting cell phones to passengers
going overseas. International Mobile Communications, in Bethesda,
Md., offers its WorldCell for rent. Patrice Brown, a marketing
executive, said the company ships rental Nokia and Motorola phones,
which work in 100 countries, to clients by overnight courier. It
costs $75 for the first week, $50 for extra weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Calls on these phones may be charged to calling cards, or a plan
may be established with WorldCell. Brown said that a typical call
to the United States from France would cost $2.69 a minute, from
Britain, $2.91, and from Italy, $2.34. If the renter elects prepaid
air time, flat rates of $3.99 or $4.99 a minute would apply
worldwide. International Mobile Communications: (888) 967-5323,
www.worldcell.com.
</P>
<P>
   Nextel Communications has brought out a dual-mode Motorola phone
that operates in a number of United States metropolitan areas and
70 countries overseas. It incorporates GSM with iDEN, the company's
frequency for the Western Hemisphere. Daisann McLane, who writes
the Frugal Traveler for The Times, took a Nextel to Spain in the
spring. When she called from Madrid, her editor said it sounded as
if she were next door. McLane said that the outgoing calls worked
much better than incoming ones from overseas; she said most calls
to her were routed to her e-mail or to a recording saying her line
was busy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big advantage was the ability to make local calls,'' she
said. ``Once, I got lost looking for my house rental in the Canary
Islands. I used it to call the rental agent, who guided me to my
destination.''
</P>
<P>
   Away from major metropolitan areas in rural Spain, the
connection sometimes faltered, McLane said. She said a cell phone
in her backpack reduced her worry about hiking alone. Asian
coverage is a mixed bag.
</P>
<P>
   The Nextel Motorola i2000 costs $199. Per-minute rates range
from 99 cents in France to $5.99 in Russia. Nextel: (800) 639-8359;
www.nextel.com/worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   VoiceStream Wireless, formerly Omnipoint, sells two dual-band
cell phones, the Ericsson I-888 and the Motorola L-7089, for
$299.95 each. The monthly service plan is $19.99; calls are
additional. To take the phone overseas, the owner must have a
credit record acceptable to VoiceStream; otherwise there is a delay
of six months after purchase. VoiceStream also has a rental plan
for various models for $29 a week, which includes overnight
delivery and prepaid return of the phone. Peter Sandusky, head of
international marketing, said the rental rate was lower than the
competition because VoiceStream's business is selling phone calls.
A freeze of $300 is put on the client's credit card against return
of the phone and $300 more for the data card, or SIM, that is put
into it. Per-minute rates from Britain start at $2.20; from Italy,
$1.40; and from France, $1.60. VoiceStream: (877) 666-4246;
www.omnipoint.com. Other Choices
</P>
<P>
   In many GSM countries, inexpensive cell phones are available
with prepaid cards, a way to use a cell phone for a few weeks
without monthly charges. Small European towns often have cell-phone
sales offices. The www.gsm.org site lists all GSM countries,
service providers in each and some of their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The older possibilities are international calling plans offered
by domestic phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint created a program this spring that is not linked to its
regular domestic billing or to calling cards: It uses credit cards.
A call made through the program, called You, costs $3 for the
connection, plus $1.25 a minute. The plan is available in 50
countries, islands and cities worldwide, with the focus on the
Caribbean. In each country there is an access code that leads to an
English-speaking operator. Travelers overseas may learn the access
code through a collect call to (913) 624-5336; wallet guides are
also available at some airports and Sprint centers in the United
States. Sprint: (800) 877-4646. The Web site, www.youcallhome.com,
is incomplete but contains the access codes.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom this spring began a sign-up plan with a $3 monthly
charge, local access numbers and per-minute charges based on the
country where the call is made or going to. Weekend rates are
lower, with the weekend starting at midnight Friday in the place
being called. A call from France is 17 cents a minute during the
week; 9 cents weekends; from Britain, rates are 10 cents and 9
cents, and from Italy, 17 cents and 9 cents. Access codes are on
the Web site. MCI International Weekends: (800) 759-1697,
www.mci.com/international.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Direct also uses local access numbers for an operator or
dial tone in the United States. The call is billed to an AT&AMP;T
calling card or Universal Card, some local phone cards or is placed
collect. A directory of access numbers is available at the Web
site. Various rate plans bring prices down toward costs of domestic
calls. Without these plans, all AT&AMP;T Direct calls have an initial
fee of $4.50 on the first minute, bringing a one-minute call home
from Britain to $7.32; from France, $7.15; from Italy, $7.40. AT&AMP;T
Direct: (800) 331-1140, www.att.com/traveler.
</P>
<P>
   Under call-back systems, the overseas caller dials a special
number, lets it ring once and hangs up. The caller then gets a call
back, which offers either a dial tone or a computerized voice
prompt or United States operator asking for the customer by name:
the call is then placed as a domestic call.
</P>
<P>
   To set this up, the traveler must first call to establish the
overseas number being used. This was ideal for a colleague's
daughter staying in an apartment in Florence; not so good for
someone changing cities daily. Kallback in Seattle says it is the
oldest company in this line of business. One plan costs $10 a
month, plus $2 a month for each overseas number in the system;
rates are less than a dollar a minute for most European countries.
Kallback: (800) 959-5255, fax (800) 949-5255.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
