<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-INFLATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN CONSIDERING TIGHTER MONEY SUPPLY TO CURB INFLATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By SABRINA TAVERNISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's president, Vladimir Putin, warned Monday that
inflation is rising an annual rate of nearly 35 percent, a trend
economists say could severely strain incomes of ordinary Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who is making his first attempts at formulating economic
policy, was quoted as suggesting at a Kremlin meeting that the
government should take steps to slow the pace of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The president met with cabinet ministers and with the chairman
of the Russian central bank, Viktor Gerashchenko, according to the
Interfax news agency, but it was unclear from the accounts of the
meeting what such anti-inflation steps might be.
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities included restricting the sharp growth in the
supply of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money supply is more than what the economy can consume,''
Putin said. ``If these processes continue, every citizen will feel
the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Inflation is a pressing concern for Russian households, which
have suffered devastating losses in the value of their savings
because of price spirals and currency devaluations since the
collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Although the exchange value of the ruble has risen markedly the
last few months, many Russians are still suffering the effects of a
ruble devaluation nearly two years ago, when the government
defaulted on billions of dollars worth of debt payments. Russian
exporters, conversely, have benefited because a cheaper ruble has
lowered production costs at home and increased sales abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's problem today, paradoxically, is that its economy is
doing too well. The trade surplus, a barometer of export strength,
is nearing $30 billion, and economic growth exceeded 8 percent in
the first quarter. Now with the economy growing quickly, the high
demand for rubles has expanded the money supply, spurring
inflation. Industries may now lose some of the benefits of the
devaluation if the government tightens monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clock is ticking,'' said Roland Nash, chief economist at
Renaissance Capital in Moscow. ``The window of opportunity they
have from the devaluation is closing _ more quickly than the
government was expecting.''
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary inflation figures showed that June consumer prices
rose 2.5 percent from May. That is an annual rate of about 35
percent, which economists say is unsustainable for Russia's
economy. The money supply is up about 29 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, company profits have improved sharply. Oil companies, the
country's main exporters, have reported strong 1999 profits, in
part from the rising price of petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great problem to have,'' said Peter Boone, director of
research here at the brokerage firm Brunswick Warburg. ``Companies
are so cash-rich at the moment that even a 10 percent appreciation
of the ruble wouldn't make that much difference in their daily
lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2338 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FEATURE-HENDRIE-LADN-     07-03 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURE-HENDRIE-LADN-2ndTake </SLUG>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(UNDATED: ... hasn't happended yet.'')
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not everyone, however, is enamored of Hendrie. For instance,
Thousand Oaks homemaker Miriam Jaffe, who is in her 70s, says she
has complained to KFI about Hendrie, because his obviously fake
interviewing style so upsets her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just stirs up trouble to boost his ratings,'' Jaffe said.
``And he's raunchy. I listened for several months before I realized
he was doing all the voices. When he went on the air and said
people who own powerful cars should be entitled to drive faster
than everyone else, even in the rain, I got absolutely livid. Some
punk could be listening and could take it seriously. I wrote to the
station and said, `Please, don't you realize people could be
killed.' It's gone beyond entertainment. He's dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Hendrie says there are already enough disclaimers
in the world and he doesn't feel he should have to offer one on his
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, the research shows 90 percent of my audience knows
exactly what's going on,'' Hendrie insists. ``And the 2 percent we
let on the air has absolutely no idea. I mean, is there an honest
show out there? We're all in this thing for ratings, and we all
have to swim in the same water. Even Michael Jackson is putting it
on for everybody. Stern is putting it on. Mr. KABC is putting it
on. There is no such thing as honest dialogue. All we care about is
holding onto our jobs from one month to the next.''
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing to think so many apparently miss the point. The
giveaway is always the mad opinion expressed by the ``guest,''
Hendrie says.
</P>
<P>
   Those guests include Wireman, a 78-year-old retired San Marino
civil rights attorney; Gray, a 53-year-old journalist whose
syndicated column is called ``A Little Bird Told Me''; Bozell, a
lawsuit-happy 40-year-old construction crew manager from Corona;
and Collins, a thick-as-a-brick 16-year-old Chatsworth high school
kid.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, Hendrie posed as the author of a book that
claims angels are indeed living on Earth with mortals, but they've
begun molesting humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played the part of this guy who wrote a book called `Groped
by an Angel,''' Hendrie said. ``You would think that something so
far out couldn't possibly be taken seriously. But we got about a
half-hour's worth of callers who believed this might be taking
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer adds: ``People who think they like Phil's show like it
a lot more when they know it's him doing the voices.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrie's menagerie includes about 20 voices, of which he uses
about a dozen regularly. It all started when he was a kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was around 6 when I began doing James Mason,'' Hendrie
recalled. ``And I grew up laughing at people like Laurel and Hardy
and Jackie Gleason. Then, I got turned on to Lenny Bruce, which was
a life-changing event. And Frank Zappa came into my life when I was
a teen-ager, and I threw it all together. I started looking at
radio as a theatrical enterprise and thought it would be fun if we
could take old radio theater and utilize modern idioms. I always
thought radio could be viewed as an entertainment medium rather
than this embarrassed stepsister to TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Daily show preparation takes three hours, beginning when Hendrie
writer Melissa Morgan comes in with a pile of ideas and begins
kicking them around with the host.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrie admits that without prep, the program would fall flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I did wing it, I would kill myself,'' he said. ``I'm not
that good. I have to sit down for three hours with our writer and
producer and slug it out to come up with material.''
</P>
<P>
   As for competition on the dial, Hendrie refuses to discuss
Leykis except in general terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of guys in L.A. wanting to keep their jobs, so
they get really conservative,'' he said. ``You have a market where
the very thing that got you here, you stop doing when you get
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrie believes his show will begin to show real growth after
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to stabilize the audience and bring Phil Hendrie fans
on board,'' he said. ``There won't be a 90-day turnaround. But I
have no doubt we have the most entertaining show in
afternoon-drive. It's new for KFI and some people don't know what
to make of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something I've had to battle for the last 10 years.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who: Phil Hendrie. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where: KFI-AM (640). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When: 4 to 7 p.m. weekdays.
</P>
</TEXT>
