<HEADLINE>
THE MANY VOICES OF PAUL HENDRIE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phil Hendrie talks to himself for a living.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, you know what that entails if you've ever flipped
over to news-talk radio KFI-AM (640) any weekday from 4 to 7 p.m.
and heard Hendrie jawing with such outrageous guests as Harvey
Wireman, Margaret Gray, Steve Bozell or R.C. Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, those are just a few of Hendrie's many alter-egos _
men, women and children _ and if you listen long enough, it becomes
plain the host is doing ALL the talking.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Hendrie is getting paid to carry on seamless,
artful and often overheated conversations with himself. Hendrie's
meticulously crafted act reaches from a high-tech studio in Sherman
Oaks to 61 cities across the country.
</P>
<P>
   By holding a telephone about seven inches from his face and
disguising his voice, Hendrie interviews Wireman, Gray, Bozell and
all the rest during what's probably the most theatrical and
subversive program on the radio waves.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Hendrie's daily three-hour performance art piece
continually draws uncomprehending callers who haven't figured out
the show's plain- as-day secret: that it's Hendrie and only Hendrie
behind the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   The show hinges on those listeners from places like Tampa, Fla.;
Atlanta; Culver City; and Long Beach who are angered at the crazed
opinions Hendrie (as Gray or Bozell, etc.) puts on the air. Call it
interactive improv.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent show, for example, Hendrie, playing the part of
favorite made-up character Colleen Christen Brewster, a Laguna
Beach travel agent, argued that Darva Conger, the woman who married
TV's multimillionaire and recently took her clothes off for
Playboy, was actually a pretty good role model for women.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a wonderful role model,'' Hendrie-as-Brewster said.
``She gives me the strength to go on. She's a highly intelligent
woman who took control of her own life and called the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   In a cramped control room at the Premiere Radio Network's
offices on the fifth floor of a Ventura Boulevard high-rise,
Hendrie's producer, Mike Schaefer, fields calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darva Conger's not a role model,'' a 34-year-old Manhattan
Beach female insists. ``She's a gold digger.''
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer hears and smiles: ``Those are the people we want on the
show _ the ones who don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   When a caller listening on a new affiliate in Tampa asks the
screener if it really is Hendrie doing all the voices, Schaefer
keeps the woman off the air but lets the cat out of the bag: ``It's
Phil talking to himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrie, who rarely gives media interviews and never allows TV
crews in the studio, developed his act while working at Ventura
talk station KVEN-AM, where the biggest struggle involved getting
listeners to pick up their phones _ a major problem when you're
running a call-in show.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I launched into uncharted territory and decided to make up
my own calls,'' Hendrie explained a few hours before his Thursday
show.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Pasadena, the squat but powerfully built Hendrie spent
15 years in music radio before moving into talk. He arrived in Los
Angeles after handling morning-drive in Miami, starting at KFI the
first time in 1989 before relocating to San Diego, Minneapolis and
back to Miami. In the fall of 1996, he rejoined KFI and was moved
in March into afternoon-drive against top-rated motor-mouth Tom
Leykis on talk rival KLSX-FM (97.1).
</P>
<P>
   ``No calls are set up,'' Hendrie explains. ``We don't pay people
to call, and there are no other character voices. I've had George
Carlin, one of the great mimics and comedians, offer to do a
character on my show. And for me not to get back to him on that was
painful. I've politely declined all these offers because I learned
the hard way the only way I can be successful is to have complete
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Howard Stern's legion of copycats, there have been no
known Hendrie imitators. Speaking of Stern whose business agent
Hendrie and Leykis, incidentally, share the superstar morning jock
was so taken by tapes of Hendrie that last year he visited the
Sherman Oaks studio to see for himself how it's done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flattered he liked my work,'' said Hendrie, 47, who
lives in Westlake Village with his wife and four stepkids. ``He
came to L.A., and we had lunch, and he watched the show. But if my
act could spawn imitators, it would have by now. It's a tough act
to rip off. They would have to do it better than me, and that's a
tough thing to do. I know it angers Howard when people rip him off,
but for me it hasn't happened yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
