<HEADLINE>
FOR PRI, DISBELIEF AND DESPAIR AS STRING OF VICTORIES IS BROKEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MEXICO-ELECTION) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The headquarters of the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, with its titanic statues of dead leaders and
its monumental political machinery, was going to be the site of a
grand election fiesta on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the party's stage set became the scene of a political
funeral.
</P>
<P>
   When the first televised returns came in, showing the party
being crushed in the provincial races, four political operatives
watching the news physically recoiled from the screen, screwing
their eyes shut, as if hit by a blinding flash. One, a young woman
in a white polo shirt emblazoned with the party's red, white and
green insignia, opened her eyes wide and began to cry.
</P>
<P>
   Like frolickers at a company picnic struck by a thunderstorm,
party supporters called off the festivities. They furled their
flags and banners and hugged one another for comfort. Yuppie
lawyers wept into their cell phones. Budding politicians stared
into space, seeing their futures evaporate in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the will of the people,'' Pedro Haces, a lawyer and
lifetime adherent of the governing party, known as the PRI, said in
a voice filled with sadness, bitterness and resignation. ``We live
in a democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote against the PRI was in part a rejection of their oldest
and wisest leaders, known universally in Mexican political circles
(except at party headquarters) as ``the dinosaurs.''
</P>
<P>
   The dinosaurs and their offspring were holed up in the party's
headquarters on Sunday night when the bad news started flooding in.
They listened in silence as their candidate, Francisco Labastida,
who was to have proclaimed the latest in an unbroken string of
victories reaching back a lifetime, told them that things looked
grim.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida and the old guard filed into the auditorium to face
the party faithful before the television cameras. As he made a
short, bittersweet speech, the dinosaurs who took the stage stood
as far away from him as physically possible. The crowd stood and
applauded, cheered and wept, shouted and punched the air with their
fists.
</P>
<P>
   Then the faithful dimmed the lights and, by the hundreds, walked
out, marching silently past the black-shirted security guards and
the bronze statues of the old heroes, through the gates of what had
until that moment been the world's longest ruling party, out into
the streets of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   And out in the streets, thousands of people were shouting for
joy in the heart of a transformed nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
