<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO BURN $73 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   With George W. Bush breaking all fund-raising records, a lot of
people in the political consulting and media business are reaping a
windfall. A new report by the Center for Responsive Politics shows
exactly how Bush spent the $73 million raised for his primary bid.
The big-ticket item was $21.7 million in campaign advertising,
mostly for television. Air charters came in second at $4.7 million,
and other forms of travel expenses _ buses, cars, parking and
hotels _ added another $1.4 million. Then came direct-mail expenses
at $4.2 million, with another $4.1 million on postage, printing and
delivery of those direct-mail pieces, plus $2.9 million for
payroll, $135,741 for consultants and _ of course _ $672,210 for
fund-raising. ``Bush's spending seems more fitting for a small
corporation than a campaign for president,'' said Holly Bailey, who
wrote the study. Put another way, since Bush announced his
presidential candidacy in March 1999, he has rolled up a money
``burn rate'' of $1.3 million a week, or $180,000 a day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THE POLLS
</P>
<P>
   BIG LEAD MISLEADING?
</P>
<P>
   Although most national polls have shown Gov. George W. Bush with
a healthy lead over Vice President Al Gore, a new survey by
Newsweek magazine has found them in a dead heat. In a two-way race,
Gore has the support of 46 percent of voters, with Bush at 45
percent, the survey found. A four-way race also produced a deadlock
with Bush at 41 percent, Gore at 40 percent, Ralph Nader at 6
percent and Patrick J. Buchanan at 2 percent. The survey polled 752
people in late June and had a margin of sampling error of plus or
minus four percentage points.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THE REFORM PARTY
</P>
<P>
   WEB VOTING FOR PRIMARY
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party's presidential primary will feature not only
traditional paper ballots but also voting via the Internet, yet
another sign that balloting on the Web, once only a topic of
discussion, is slowly becoming a reality. In the March primary in
Arizona, more than 45 percent of the 85,970 votes cast were sent
via computers from homes, schools and Internet connections at
polling places. For the Reform primary, party members will be
mailed a ballot packet with a traditional ballot and instructions
for online voting, to be conducted at www.eballot.net. The packet
gives voters a personal identity number and a guide to locate the
ballot on the Web. Electronic votes can be submitted for a limited
time before the party's Aug. 9 convention. ``A mixed-media election
provides our nationwide constituency with greater choice,'' said
Michael Farris, chairman of the party's election committee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH
</P>
<P>
   Belton, Tex.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE
</P>
<P>
   New York, Washington
</P>
