<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-STPAUL-LADN-2Takes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNOOPY, KEILOR ADD CHARM TO FORGOTTEN TWIN CITY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by LANG only) 
By Edward M. Eveld 
Kansas City Star 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IF YOU GO &QL; 
Events and attractions in St. Paul:
</P>
<P>
   St. Paul Saints: Midway Stadium, 1771 Energy Park Drive. Adult
ticket prices range from $4 to $7. Phone: (651) 644-6659.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota State Fair: One of the country's largest, runs this
year from Aug. 24 through Sept. 4 at the state fairgrounds. Phone:
(651) 642-2200.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peanuts on Parade'': More than 100 decorated Snoopys will be
on display all over town, an exhibit that runs through early
October for the 50th anniversary of the Peanuts comic strip. The
late Peanuts creator Charles Schulz was a St. Paul native.
</P>
<P>
   Wabasha Street Caves: Down in History Tours, 215 Wabasha St.
South. Phone: (651) 292-1220. St. Paul Gangster Tour is $18 and is
offered on Saturdays. Reservations are required.
</P>
<P>
   Grand and Summit avenues: Parallel streets worth some heavy
strolling. Grand offers fun, artsy, quirky shopping along a 4-mile
stretch. Summit is St. Paul's street of mansions and the location
of various F. Scott Fitzgerald homes.
</P>
<P>
   St. Paul Winter Carnival: Annually celebrates winter's frigid
days with ice-sculpture competitions, a torchlight parade, foot
races and other events. Runs from the end of January through the
beginning of February. Phone: (651) 223-4700.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald Theater: 10 E. Exchange St. Phone: (651) 290-1221.
This is headquarters for ``A Prairie Home Companion,'' Garrison
Keillor's folksy radio show. Tickets cost $17 to $27. Call ahead to
see whether he's broadcasting while you're in town.
</P>
<P>
   Cathedral of St. Paul: 239 Selby Ave. Phone: (651) 228-1766.
Sits high on a hill above downtown; its magnificence helps give St.
Paul a bit of a European look. Speaking of saints, the cathedral is
modeled after St. Peter's in Rome, including a 300-foot dome.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: The St. Paul Convention and Visitors Bureau is
located at 175 W. Kellogg Blvd., Suite 502, St. Paul, Minn. 55102.
Phone: (651) 265-4900 or (800) 627-6101. Web: www.stpaulcvb.org. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ST. PAUL, Minn. _ ``Train.''
</P>
<P>
   The word came over the stadium loudspeaker with no inflection.
Just the word.
</P>
<P>
   What train?
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the outfield, a freight train, chugging from left field
to right. It was actually just beyond the fence at the minor league
stadium where the St. Paul Saints were playing the Winnipeg
Goldeyes. But just.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this the line for a massage?'' I heard someone ask as I
climbed the stadium steps. ``On the left,'' came a cheery reply
from another fan.
</P>
<P>
   I scooted past the massage chair and nodded at the massage
therapist, then squeezed by the beer man wearing a Nixon mask. I
made my way to the stands behind home plate, where a hairstylist
tossed a barber's apron around her next customer. He settled in for
his haircut and a great view of the batter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really slow train.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the same monotone baritone, and I couldn't help but look
toward the outfield, where the walls were plastered with ads, which
also climbed the light poles. A second train, this one incredibly
sluggish, had just appeared beyond left field.
</P>
<P>
   Here at Midway Stadium, a Saints game is more than baseball.
It's a happening, embraced by residents. But even more, it's about
the way St. Paul, always the lesser twin in this northern
metropolis, handles its second-string status.
</P>
<P>
   Is it that St. Paul finally got fed up with comparisons to
Minneapolis and decided to stop worrying about it? Not quite. But
nowadays St. Paul seems to revel in its second-rate status. Its
quirkiness is a matter of pride. St. Paul is cool.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the Saints is one of the best ways to experience this.
Home games nearly always sell out, even though the Minnesota Twins,
major leaguers, play just a few miles away. There are other ways,
such as poking around the shops along St. Paul's Grand Avenue,
rather than making a pilgrimage to the Mall of America in suburban
Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Another is to take the St. Paul Gangster Tour. While other
cities have been reluctant to play up their gangster ties, the St.
Paul tour has been popular with locals and tourists for years. More
on that later.
</P>
<P>
   I headed to the Saints game from my downtown Minneapolis hotel
in an inadvertently symbolic way, by zipping past the Metrodome.
That's where the Twins play their home games _ indoors.
</P>
<P>
   It was a Thursday evening last August, with a few puffy clouds
in a blue sky and a game-time temperature of about 75 degrees. The
stadium had one place to buy tickets and one entrance, in front of
which a three-piece Dixieland band played. The blue stands were
decorated with potted petunias and geraniums. Fans shuffled in from
their pregame tailgating parties. It would be another sellout, with
more than 6,000 devoted followers on hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Saints fans,'' called the announcer. ``Are you ready for
some baseball _ outside?''
</P>
<P>
   Not just baseball, of course. Soon contestants in the ``public
humiliation'' event would be called forth. Another fan would be
chosen to race a giant Subway sandwich around the infield. Coming
up was the new car giveaway: ``At least it will be new to them,''
said the announcer. But first, a pig, the Saints' mascot, trotted
onto the field with the game ball in its mouth.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
