<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   MONGOLIA: FORMER COMMUNISTS WIN
</P>
<P>
   The country's former communist rulers won a landslide victory in
elections on Sunday and vowed to push ahead with economic reforms
while doing more to combat the social costs of the painful 10-year
transition from Soviet satellite to a free market. Unofficial
results showed the Mongolian People's Revolutionary Party won 72
out of the 76 open parliamentary seats. The party had ruled
Mongolia from the 1920s until 1996, when it was ousted by a
democratic coalition.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: SRI LANKA PEACE PLAN
</P>
<P>
   India said it had devised a package to end fighting in Sri Lanka
and was ready to take part in talks between the Sri Lankan
government and Tamil rebels. Junior Foreign Minister Ajit Panja
said India favored a united Sri Lanka but did not disclose details
of the proposed package. Officials said Sri Lanka's president,
Chandrika Kumaratunga, would send a special envoy to India this
week.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: U.S. MARINE ARRESTED IN OKINAWA
</P>
<P>
   The police arrested a U.S. marine for allegedly molesting a
14-year-old girl, threatening to stir up already tense relations
between island residents and American forces weeks before a meeting
of the world's leading industrialized economies. The 19-year-old
marine, accused of breaking into a home and molesting the girl in
her room, denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: TRUCE TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Government officials and leaders of the country's main guerrilla
movement, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, met in Los
Pozos, 435 miles south of the capital, to exchange proposals aimed
at bringing an end to decades of fighting. Their plans for an
eventual cease-fire, however, were expected to contrast sharply.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: MOSSAD AGENT ADMITS SPYING
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli secret service agent testified that he took part in a
bungled wiretapping two years ago in the Swiss capital, Bern. The
agent, using an alias for the trial, is accused of having tried to
bug the apartment of a suspected Hezbollah sympathizer.
</P>
<P>
   SLOVAKIA: PRESIDENT'S POWERS TRANSFERRED
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mikulas Dzurinda and the parliament speaker,
Jozef Migas, have assumed the powers of President Rudolf Schuster,
66, who remains hospitalized in Austria after emergency abdominal
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   LITHUANIA: NAZI CRIMES TRIAL HALTED
</P>
<P>
   A court called an indefinite halt to the country's first
Nazi-era war crimes trial, citing the poor health of 93-year-old
defendant, Aleksandras Lileikis. Lileikis, a former American
citizen stripped of his passport, has denied charges that he turned
over Jews to Nazi executioners during the German occupation of
Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: VIOLENCE OVER MARCH
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of Protestant militants attacked police in Drumcree,
Northern Ireland, with bricks and bottles after the province's
Parades Commission barred members of the Protestant Orange Order
from parading after services July 9. The commission said they could
march at a future date if they agreed to speak with Catholic
residents who object to the march coming through their
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: WHITE FARMERS' BID
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe's white farmers union said more than 200 white-owned
farms would be offered for immediate sale to President Robert
Mugabe's government for black resettlement. The offer came on the
last day for commercial farmers to object to Mugabe's plan to seize
804 white-owned farms for redistribution to landless peasants.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: DISPUTE ON CAUSE OF AIDS SWIRLS
</P>
<P>
   President Thabo Mbeki's administration fired back at 5,000
scientists who signed a letter affirming HIV as the cause of AIDS,
saying their declaration was a ``waste of time'' and a distraction
days before the International AIDS Conference opens in the South
African city of Durban. Mbeki, whose country has more HIV-positive
people than any other, has angered many AIDS researchers and
activists by his position.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   EGYPT: PROTESTS OVER ARRESTS
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups called for the release of Saad Eddin
Ibrahim, an American-Egyptian sociologist who was arrested Friday
night. Ibrahim, a professor at the American University in Cairo and
head of an Egyptian think tank, said he was charged with preparing
a documentary about elections that harms Egypt's image and
receiving foreign funds without government permission.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: MILITARY EXEMPTION BILL
</P>
<P>
   After long debate, parliament passed a preliminary bill that
would legalize a practice of granting draft exemptions for
ultra-Orthodox seminary students. The bill, sponsored by Prime
Minister Ehud Barak, would change the present system, which keeps
some religious men in school and out of the work force well into
middle age to keep their exemptions. It would allow religious
students who left school to serve four months in a special unit in
place of three years of mandatory service.
</P>
<P>
   PACIFIC
</P>
<P>
   FIJI: CIVILIAN GOVERNMENT
</P>
<P>
   Defying the gunmen holding the deposed government hostage, the
military leader appointed a temporary civilian government, but said
he would retain power until the captives are freed. Commodore Frank
Bainimarama, who took power 10 days after rebels stormed parliament
on May 19 and seized top officials, appointed the new government
without consulting the gunmen, who demanded a role.
</P>
</TEXT>
