<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-GASOLINE-PRICES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH GASOLINE PRICES LEAD TRAVELERS TO DOWNSIZE VACATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, July 9)  
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heather and James Westrin of Lansing, Mich., looked forward to
driving to Traverse City, Mich., for a long Fourth of July weekend.
But as gasoline prices soared, the prospect of paying $2 or more a
gallon for the 350-mile round trip lost its appeal. ``It's too much
to pay,'' said Westrin, a travel agent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Noble Small and his wife, Skip, a retired couple living in
Ardmore, Okla., look forward to jumping into their Dodge pickup
every August and pulling a trailer to California, then heading back
home by way of Colorado. But they will omit California from their
itinerary next month. For after estimating the cost of gasoline,
Small, who before retiring owned a wholesale oil company,
calculated that by taking the shorter trip they could save as much
as $400 on gasoline. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a summer in which 121.9 million American adults planned to
take vacations, according to survey results released May 10 by the
nonprofit Travel Industry Association of America and the AAA, the
Westrins and the Smalls do not represent most adult Americans. But
they are representative of an apparently large segment who are
canceling or shortening summer vacations because of sky-high gas
prices.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The $1.54 average cost of a gallon of gasoline in March was the
highest since July 1981, when it was $1.38, according to the AAA.
But by mid-June, after weeks of increases, the average price had
risen to $1.65, up from $1 a gallon much of last summer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, regular unleaded gasoline rose above $2
a gallon in parts of Kansas, Michigan and Missouri, and into the
$1.90s in Wisconsin and Illinois. In Chicago, it climbed as high as
$2.33. South Dakotans were paying almost $1.90 for unleaded regular
in late June, and $2.03 for premium. Premium gasoline also topped
$2 a gallon in Connecticut and Hawaii. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Resistance to rising gas prices should come as no surprise. In
the joint Travel Industry Association-AAA survey, conducted in
April when gasoline prices were rising but not yet out of sight, 46
percent of respondents (56.1 million adults) said that they would
consider canceling summer travel plans if gas prices rose to $2 a
gallon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the National Press Club on June 22, William S.
Norman, the president of the Travel Industry Association, said that
although travelers were worried about rising gas prices, the
``average American family traveling by auto will spend only about
five percent of its total vacation budget on gasoline.'' With the
average length of a pleasure trip by car about 700 miles round
trip, he said, the difference in fuel cost is about $13 _ about the
cost of a large pizza at Domino's. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But motorists do not necessarily make such direct comparisons.
``Gas prices tend to be a psychological barrier,'' said Jerry
Cheske, who has monitored fuel prices for the AAA for 27 years.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A random sampling of destinations, including the Six Flags theme
parks, the Jersey Shore and the nation's two most popular tourist
sites, Las Vegas and Orlando, Fla., found no appreciable falloff in
visitors. Yet there are many indications that, like Noble and Skip
Small, lots of travelers are economizing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had people tell us they won't be driving this
summer, but plenty of them have said they're going to downsize,''
said John A. Craig, the owner of Pathfinder Travel Service in
Olathe, Kan. ``They say they don't plan to stay as long or go as
far.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aileen Vining, a travel agent in Joplin, Mo., said: ``If there
are only two or at the most three people traveling together,
they'll give a lot of thought to flying, because gas prices are so
high around here. But if it's a family of four or more, they'll
likely drive or stay home, because there aren't many air-fare
bargains this summer.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not only are there few air-fare bargains, air fares have risen
each of the past three months, jumping nearly 16 percent in June.
Fuel prices played a big part, according to the Air Transport
Association, the airline industry trade organization. It noted that
aviation fuel skyrocketed to 77 cents a gallon in the first quarter
of this year from 44 cents over the comparable period last year,
and is likely to remain high for much of the rest of 2000. To
offset that, seven major airlines imposed a $30 surtax in May on
domestic round-trip tickets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com recently added gasoline to its growing list of
items for which members can ``name your own price,'' and other
Internet companies are said to be working on plans that they say
will lower fuel costs for drivers. In the meantime, analysts at
Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co., J.P. Morgan and Banc of America Securities
have warned that even increased oil output by the major producers
is not likely to return gasoline prices to anywhere near normal
before the end of summer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
