<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday pivotal for U.S. PostalTeam in Tour de France
</P>
<P>
   ByHalliburton-- NANTES, France _ Coming into the Tour de France,
the plan was for American Lance Armstrong to be wearing the
leader's yellow shirt on July 4 and celebrating Independence Day in
style.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan could have been moved up one day, thanks to the
volatility of the riders Monday afternoon. Conversely, that
ever-changing quality of the pack, caused primarily by cyclists
jockeying for final position, almost set back Armstrong's plans by
a day or more.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian Tom Steels won for the second straight day in Monday's
third stage, on a day that started calmly enough, under a
crystal-blue sky with temperatures in the low 70s. The 177 riders
rolled through the French countryside, much like the group did
Sunday afternoon when it ended the trek to Loudun. Instead of
Sunday's wheat fields, the main scenery Monday was acres of grapes
used to make chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   As the riders rolled into Nantes, this port city 270 miles west
of Paris, the race took on a scary air as the true sprinters of the
bunch nervously struggled for the position needed to win stage
three.
</P>
<P>
   Then disaster struck.
</P>
<P>
   With the group a half-mile from the finish, the front wheel of
Markus Zberg's bike clipped that of a competitor's and the two
cyclists went down in a heap.
</P>
<P>
   As the braked to avoid the fallen, a chain reaction started. And
for several agonizingly long seconds, Tour leader David Millar, a
23-year-old from Scotland, was flat on the pavement, struggling to
get up and back on his bike.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong found himself in the pileup behind Millar. ``It's best
not to panic, because you have to make your way past the carnage,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both cyclists struggled to get back toward the front. By the
finish line, both were able to finish with the same time, allowing
the two to remain first and second in the race to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   But Laurent Jalabert and Jan Ullrich, who were safely in front
of the pileup, made up nine seconds on the leading pair. Millar
still owns a four-second lead over Armstrong. Jalabert is now only
five seconds behind Millar and one second behind Armstrong.
Ullrich, the 1997 Tour champion, is seven seconds out of first.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mapei's Steels picked up his second straight stage
win, edging Festina's Marcel Wust and Telecom's Erik Zabel.
Although the gap between the leaders grew tighter on Monday, the
leader of the team that wins today's time trial will take over the
yellow jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The odds point to Armstrong's U.S. Postal Team, Ullrich's
Telekon squad and Jalabert's ONCE team.
</P>
<P>
   The team time trial is a unique stage for an event that focuses
on individuals. Each team will start together and ride together,
taking turns at the front of the line. The time assigned to each
team will be that of the fifth-place finisher. The stage goes 43.4
miles west from Nantes to St. Nazaire, an Atlantic port. Given the
nearness to the coast, the course will be affected by wind and
possibly rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we have to work together to get from point A to
point B as fast as possible,'' said Tyler Hamilton, one of the
Postal Service's top time trialers.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has pinpointed the team time trial as a key stage to
make an early move before the Tour hits the mountain stages. Time
trials are his strength - he won all three last year and was second
to Millar in Saturday's prologue.
</P>
<P>
   His squad, given that they have been first in the overall team
placement since Saturday, will start last this afternoon, giving
them an advantage of knowing the splits to beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be a perfect present for an American team to
win on Independence Day,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
