<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2371 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-EYRE-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT     07-03 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYRE-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LUCIA,' MOVE OVER: `JANE EYRE' AS OPERA 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL GRIFFITHS  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHELTENHAM, England _ About 100 miles west of London, Cheltenham
grew up two centuries ago as a spa town, for which purpose it
acquired fine public buildings, a few comfortable hotels and street
after street of modestly handsome houses faced with honey-colored
stone from the local Cotswolds. Behind those regular, flat facades
it would be easy to imagine families of Jane Austen characters who
have arrived to take the curative waters, stroll in the parks and
dance with young officers. Now, though, the place has to find other
ways to attract visitors and to serve its permanent population,
which includes a high proportion of retired people.
</P>
<P>
   Hence its festivals, among which the music festival is the
oldest and most distinguished, having been started right after
World War II. This year's program is typical. The opening weekend
included a recital by Alfred Brendel, an orchestral concert, and
chamber-music mornings with young and established ensembles. It
also included the world premiere of an opera based on a classic
novel, not one of the Austen books that might have suited the
location (if not the operatic form), but rather Charlotte Bronte's
``Jane Eyre.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a second opera for the British composer Michael
Berkeley and his librettist, the Australian novelist David Malouf.
Like their first _ ``Baa Baa Black Sheep,'' based on episodes from
the life and writings of Rudyard Kipling _ ``Jane Eyre'' is an
attempt to use late-20th-century means to understand the minds and
situations of Victorian characters. The mixed perspectives suit
Berkeley's music, which sometimes consorts with the 19th century
(even to the extent, unwisely, of quoting liberally from the mad
scene in ``Lucia di Lammermoor'') and sometimes sounds resiliently
contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   Malouf concentrates the capacious narrative into a compact and
fluid psychological drama for Jane and the Rochester couple, with
their housekeeper Fairfax and their ward Adele on the fringes. He
makes it possible for the central characters to be present almost
throughout, often seen when they are not heard ( Rochester pacing
in the attic of the set) or heard when they are not seen (Jane
disturbed by words from Rochester that he will not utter directly
to her).
</P>
<P>
   One big problem is that the resulting atmosphere of unease, and
of an outsider's gradual recognition of malignancy within a
household, brings the opera close to two models it cannot match. A
scene from Debussy's ``Pelleas et Melisande'' is closely recalled
when Jane questions Adele. More generally the piece evokes
Britten's ``Turn of the Screw,'' not only in its subject but in its
scoring for a few voices with a chamber orchestra of soloists.
</P>
<P>
   While he cannot come near Britten in expressing sinister erotic
appeal, Berkeley is good at murky scene-setting, as in the opening
low glissando figures, and at moments of exasperation, like the
passage where Rochester's baritone seems to be pushed up and
tightened by an insistent piccolo. But continuity is lacking, and
the final catastrophe comes suddenly out of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the main musical tension serve the subject. When the
instrumental weave is broken by percussion sounds, the effect is
not so much to suggest the hedonism and otherness of the
Rochesters' Caribbean existence as to hint, rather wistfully, at an
opera ``Jane Eyre'' is not: an opera cut loose from period costume
and waltz tunes. Perhaps Berkeley's and Malouf's next enterprise,
``A Winter's Tale,'' will be that piece.
</P>
<P>
   The performance, by Music Theater Wales, was up to this
company's high standards, with Michael Rafferty conducting and
Michael McCarthy directing. Natasha Marsh provided everything the
title role needed: a strong but quiet beautiful presence, sensitive
acting and a finely handled lyric soprano voice. Also excellent
were Andrew Slater as Rochester, Emily Bauer-Jones as Rochester and
Tabitha Watling as Adele.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
