<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PEDERSEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOBS CHANGE, BUT NOT PEDERSEN'S PASSION FOR RACING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Pete Pedersen will mark his 80th birthday
today in the same place he has celebrated practically every year
since he was 13 - at the races.
</P>
<P>
   The particular tracks and Pedersen's jobs have changed through
the decades - ranging from Longacres, near his native Seattle,
where he earned his first paycheck as a teletype operator, to
Hollywood Park, where he is the dean of the state-appointed
stewards, the three-man board that administers justice on and off
the ovals.
</P>
<P>
   But to Pedersen, who has also been a reporter and a publicist at
tracks up and down the West Coast, the exact location has never
mattered as much as the races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still look forward to going to the races. I'm still
fascinated by it,'' said Pedersen, who has maintained homes in
Arcadia and the San Francisco Bay Area since a permanent move to
California in 1967. ``I figured out that I've been an official for
over 100,000 races. You say, 'Well,then, you've seen everything.'
But the truth is I haven't seen everything. The races are all
different. That's what makes it interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver-haired and elegant in suits and hats, Pedersen brings a
dignified air to the tense situations stewards are bound to
resolve, ruling on everything from jockeys' rough riding and
trainers' medication violations to petty financial disputes and
parking citations.
</P>
<P>
   Since he indicates no plan to retire, and doesn't much like the
idea of a newspaper drawing attention to his age, Pedersen will be
heartened to learn that most people at Hollywood Park are surprised
to hear he is turning 80.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always been a very nice man, a very classy man, a very
fair man,'' said jockeys' agent Scott McClellan.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether an 80-year-old is up to one of the most powerful
jobs in racing: ``I don't think anybody can fill his shoes,'' said
George Slender, who serves with Pedersen and Tom Ward in the
Hollywood Park stewards' stand.
</P>
<P>
   Pedersen, one of four sons of an Irish mother and a Danish
father, a master mechanic in the Seattle sawmill industry, was born
less than a month after Man O'War won the 1920 Belmont Stakes. He
went to work on the Longacres backstretch when the track opened in
1933, gravitated to the press box, where he disseminated results
via the teletype, and soon becoming publicity director.
</P>
<P>
   A $99.90 winner Pedersen remembers the horse's name, Crystal
Chief helped to pay for his education at the University of
Washington. There he rowed on a national-champion crew.
</P>
<P>
   After serving in the Naval Air Corps in World War II, the only
time he wasn't at the races on the Fourth of July, Pedersen became
a 26-year-old steward while continuing as the Longacres PR
director. He said he would have liked to be a freelance writer but
chose a more secure career.
</P>
<P>
   As PR man at Golden Gate Fields in Albany, Calif., Pedersen
watched Bill Shoemaker ride his first winner in 1949. He names
Shoemaker the greatest jockey he has seen and Citation the greatest
horse though gutty little Determine was his favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Pedersen, California's senior steward for more than a decade,
presided over the first Breeders' Cup in 1984 at Hollywood Park,
participating in the disqualifications of Fran's Valentine from the
win in the Juvenile Fillies and Gate Dancer from second in the
Classic, dramatic decisions captured by NBC cameras in the booth.
Pedersen remembers having a role in ``five or six'' million-dollar
DQs.
</P>
<P>
   The accumulation of milestones is not the only sign of age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to more funerals than weddings,'' said Pedersen,
whose wife Jeanne, mother of his sons Craig and Michael, died in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time I was the youngest steward in the country, and now
I hate to think I'm the oldest,'' Pedersen said.
</P>
<P>
   Pedersen doesn't work a full year. He'll be off during the Del
Mar season that opens July 26.
</P>
<P>
   But the vacation will include stops at Bay Meadows, in San
Mateo, and Emerald Downs, Longacres' replacement near Seattle. Not
surprising for a man whose enthusiasm for racing doesn't wane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
