<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2389 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GETTYSBURG-TOWER-NYT &LR;      07-03 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETTYSBURG-TOWER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK SERVICE RIDS GETTYSBURG OF MUCH-DERIDED TOWER
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GETTYSBURG, Pa. _ One hundred and thirty-seven years after Union
troops bested Gen. Robert E. Lee and his Confederate legions in
their desperate gamble known as Pickett's charge, the National Park
Service demolished an observation tower that has been a magnet for
criticism from historians, park officials and battlefield
preservationists.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:02 Monday afternoon, after four minutes of delay and two
countdowns, a group of Civil War re-enactors, some in Confederate
gray and others in Union blue, fired their cannon toward the tower.
Less than 10 seconds later, 15.5 pounds of demolition charges that
had been placed on the tower exploded, collapsing the structure.
</P>
<P>
   Taking down the 307-foot structure, the Gettysburg National
Tower, was the first step in an effort to restore the battlefield
to its appearance in 1863, Park Service officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is sacred ground,'' Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt
said. ``Americans come here to learn of their past, to understand
how it was in those days when we remade ourselves as a new
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, while observing Earth Day at Gettysburg, Babbitt
promised: ``This tower is coming down on my watch.''
</P>
<P>
   For nearly three decades, the tower, which was a privately
operated tourist attraction, loomed over the battlefield. Union
troops had once gathered near the site of the tower, setting up
defensive positions on what was known as Cemetery Ridge. For years,
preservationists and Civil War enthusiasts have criticized the
tower as an intrusion on the historic setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been our long-term wish to get rid of what we consider
a major eyesore,'' said Walter L. Powell, the president of the
Gettysburg Battlefield Preservation Association.
</P>
<P>
   Controlled Demolition Inc. of Baltimore donated its services and
explosives to raze the tower, a donation the Park Service valued at
$1 million. Park officials said the donation was the largest
corporate contribution toward preservation in the park's 105-year
history.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the company retained media and salvage rights for the
collapsed steel tower. The company recently demolished the Kingdome
in Seattle and the ruins of the federal building in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer representing the company that had owned the tower,
Overview Limited Partnership of Baltimore, criticized the
demolition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government, for reasons yet to be articulated, has chosen
to destroy a classroom in the sky,'' the lawyer, Irwin W. Aronson,
said. Aronson said the demolition would actually cost only about
$40,000, arguing that the $1 million government figure was grossly
exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy behind decisions made by the Union commander, Gen.
George G. Meade, and General Lee, he said, could be appreciated
only from the tower, which had opened in 1974 and included
photographs and maps of the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only vantage point to see the entire spectrum of the
battlefield,'' Aronson said. For about $5, visitors could view the
battlefield, which covers about 6 acres, from the tower.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Hower, 52, an executive for a tour company in Adams
County, Pa., where the battlefield is situated, said the demolition
had caused ``more unrest than I've seen in the 22 years I've lived
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The citizens of this area don't believe that we need to take
down the tower,'' Hower said.
</P>
<P>
   The Commonwealth of Pennsylvania had tried to prevent
construction of the tower because of its proximity to historic
land. Then, in December, the Department of Justice filed a federal
suit to acquire the property. The court granted the Park Service
ownership in June, laying the groundwork for the demolition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2155EDT &QL; 
