A2390 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRITAIN-MOBILE-LICENS     07-03 0375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MOBILE-LICENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S DOCOMO AND ROYAL KPN ANGLE FOR STAKE IN BRITISH MOBILE
LICENSE HOLDER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British wireless telephone venture TIW UMTS is in talks
to sell about a third of the company to NTT DoCoMo of Japan and
Royal KPN, the Dutch mobile phone operator, for as much as $2
billion, executives close to the discussions said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   TIW UMTS is backed by the Hong Kong conglomerate Hutchison
Whampoa and Telesystem International Wireless of Canada and owns
one of the five highly coveted third-generation wireless licenses
in Britain, allowing it to offer consumers high-speed Internet
access over mobile telephones and other portable devices. The
venture recently bought the license for $6.4 billion after a fierce
bidding war.
</P>
<P>
   If the sale proceeds, it would give NTT DoCoMo, Japan's largest
mobile phone company, and Royal KPN a foothold in the highly
competitive British mobile communications market.
</P>
<P>
   NTT DoCoMo bought a 15 percent stake in Royal KPN's mobile unit,
KPN Mobile, for about $4.5 billion in May, hoping to create an
alliance that would, in part, allow it to pool resources to
aggressively buy third-generation mobile telephone licenses across
Europe. The two companies were expected to bid for Orange PLC,
Britain's third-largest mobile telephone operator, but were
outmaneuvered by France Telecom, which bought Orange for $37.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the talks said NTT DoCoMo would acquire
about 20 percent of the TIW and that Royal KPN would acquire about
15 percent. Hutchison Whampoa would retain a controlling stake.
</P>
<P>
   The executives cautioned that the negotiations could still break
down.
</P>
<P>
   NTT DoCoMo is aggressively seeking to expand in Europe, which is
considered to have the greatest potential for growth in the global
mobile market during the next several years. NTT DoCoMo is
especially eager to enter the European market because it wants to
introduce the market here to its widely popular i-mode technology,
which allows customers to gain access to the Internet over their
mobile telephones. I-mode is already the largest mobile Internet
access service in the world, with 8.2 million subscribers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
