<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI BACKS OUT ON UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The UCLA football team has been notified by
Missouri that the Tigers will not honor the contract to play a
home-and-home series with the Bruins in 2001 and 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Sports information director Marc Dellins, who does UCLA's
scheduling, said Missouri is overscheduled with too many tough
opponents. In addition to its Big 12 schedule, Missouri has a
home-and-home series with Michigan State in 2000 and 2001.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's schedules were set through 2008. Now, Sept. 8, 2001, and
Sept. 7, 2002, are open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee, I feel really bad,'' Dellins said, ``although I shouldn't
sound sarcastic. But our 2001 schedule has us playing Alabama and
Ohio State.''
</P>
<P>
   Dellins said Missouri notified UCLA in writing six months ago of
its desire not to play. UCLA said it was OK if the two schools try
to find a suitable replacement. Dellins said UCLA wants a
comparable Division I-A opponent so the games could be televised.
Kansas and Kansas State were two possibilities discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Dellins said, Missouri athletic director Mike Alben
told UCLA's Peter Dalis the Tigers won't honor the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get the contract and go over it with our legal counsel
and talk to their legal counsel,'' Dellins said.
</P>
<P>
   Commitment: Ed Blanton, a 6-foot-9, 300-pound offensive lineman
from Napa, has orally committed to the Bruins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
