<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALES FALL AT U.S. AUTO MAKERS
</P>
<P>
   Americans bought fewer autos than expected from General Motors,
Ford and DaimlerChrysler in June, opting to buy vehicles made by
Japanese and European companies or to keep the vehicles they
already own.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of North American-built cars and trucks fell 5.8 percent
at G.M. and 3.1 percent at Ford. DaimlerChrysler, beset by an aging
minivan lineup, said its sales excluding Mercedes-Benz fell 9.8
percent. Industrywide sales rose 0.2 percent, to 1.61 million cars
and light trucks. Shares of DaimlerChrysler rose $1, to $53.0625,
while G.M. rose $1.5625, to $59.625. Shares of Ford rose 93.75
cents, to $43.9375.
</P>
<P>
   SILICON ALLEY START-UPS STRUGGLE
</P>
<P>
   These are trying days for New York's Silicon Alley, an industry
made up of as many as 7,000 enterprises, most of them tiny
start-ups. They tend to specialize in content rather than
technology, making them more vulnerable to gyrations on Wall
Street. Several high-profile Internet companies in New York have
gone under or are barely hanging on, and more are expected to
succumb in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   NAPSTER SEEKS TO FORESTALL CLOSING
</P>
<P>
   Napster, the Internet start-up, asked a federal judge not to
shut down its service, asserting in a court brief that individual
Napster users are doing nothing illegal by making personal
collections of copyrighted music they download over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   MANUFACTURING GROWTH SLOWS
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing expanded in June at the slowest pace in 17 months,
according to the National Association of Purchasing Management,
which said its monthly factory index fell to 51.8 in June from 53.2
in May. A separate report from the Commerce Department showed
construction spending rose 0.1 percent in May after falling 1.1
percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS UP IN LIGHT TRADING
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose broadly in light trading before the holiday as
investors reacted to a lower-than-expected reading for
manufacturing activity in June. The Dow Jones industrial average
gained 112.78 points, or 1.1 percent, to 10,560.67. The Nasdaq
composite index edged up 25.82 points, or 0.7 percent, to 3,991.93,
while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index climbed 14.72 points,
or 1 percent, to 1,469.32.
</P>
<P>
   TREASURY PRICES UP
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices rose as the yield on the 10-year note fell to
5.98 percent from 6.01 percent and the yield on the 30-year bond
fell to 5.87 percent from 5.89 percent.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT BOLSTERS DEFENSE TEAM
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft added more firepower to the defense team in its
antitrust case by hiring Carter Phillips, a leading appellate
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA FACING HIGHER INFLATION
</P>
<P>
   Russia's president, Vladimir Putin, warned that inflation is
rising at an annual rate of nearly 35 percent, a trend economists
say could severely strain the incomes of Russians. Putin, who is
making his first attempts at economic policy, was quoted as
suggesting at a Kremlin meeting that the government should take
steps to slow the pace of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   CABLE &AMP; WIRELESS HKT SHAREHOLDERS OK BUYOUT
</P>
<P>
   Minority shareholders of Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT in Hong Kong voted
overwhelmingly to be acquired by Pacific Century Cyberworks, an
Internet company run by Richard Li. The deal needs to be ratified
by a judge on July 25, but analysts say the vote guarantees that
Li, 33, who runs Pacific Century will soon own Hong Kong's flagship
telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH WIRELESS VENTURE MAY SELL STAKE
</P>
<P>
   A British wireless venture backed by the Hong Kong conglomerate
Hutchinson Whampoa and Telesystem International Wireless of Canada,
and which holds one of Britain's five third-generation mobile
communications licenses, is in talks to sell about a third of the
company to NTT DoCoMo and Royal KPN for as much as $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. FINANCIAL MARKETS CLOSED
</P>
<P>
   The stock market and other financial markets in the United
States will be closed Tuesday in observance of the Fourth of July.
Most overseas markets, however, will be open. U.S. markets will
reopen Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
