u k BC-EDIT-WELFARE-NYT &LR;      07-03 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WELFARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WASHINGTON RENEGES ON A BARGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, July 4:
</P>
<P>
   Congress made a welfare deal with the states in 1996 that it now
threatens to tarnish. Under the deal, the states relinquished their
60-year-old entitlement to additional federal money when their
welfare rolls rise. In exchange, every state received a big fixed
annual grant to cover its welfare costs. Congress also gave 17
needy states extra help in the form of supplemental grants.
Congress now threatens to reclaim part of these supplemental
grants.
</P>
<P>
   This misguided proposal would punish poor states with high rates
of child poverty. It would also send the terrible message that
states will be better off if they spend money quickly and foolishly
rather than slowly and well.
</P>
<P>
   Congress provided the supplemental grants partly to help states
that were paying low benefits to existing enrollees. The idea was
to close some of the huge gap in benefits paid by rich and poor
states. But as a soaring economy and stiff welfare reforms drove
down welfare rolls by 30 percent in the years following the 1996
law, states found they did not need to spend every last federal
dollar. In addition, the families left behind were often the most
disadvantaged and hardest to help. Some states, needing time to
figure out how to reach them, held on to their money until they
could develop the right strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The administration proposed many months ago to raise revenue for
budget purposes by reclaiming some of the unspent supplemental
grants _ an idea embraced by the House and now under consideration
by the Senate. But according to the Center on Budget and Policy
Priorities, a liberal research group, the supplemental grants are
essential in helping poorer states achieve parity in federal
grants. In the beginning, these poorer states spent a smaller
portion of their federal allotment than the wealthier states,
creating the impression that they did not need the extra money. But
their hesitancy was temporary. Now, according to the center, the
states receiving supplemental grants are using more of their
federal dollars than other states.
</P>
<P>
   Money is not the sole answer to poverty. But a recent evaluation
of an ambitious program in Minnesota shows that it can produce
startling results. The Minnesota welfare program combined generous
work incentives with child-care assistance and support for
enrollees after they find work. The result was a decline in the
number of poor living solely on welfare and a rise in employment
and marriage rates among enrollees. At a time when the federal
treasury is flush with cash, Congress need not deprive states with
high rates of child poverty of the money they were promised. It is
also money they desperately need to help the families left behind
by prosperity and facing federally imposed time limits on cash
assistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2202EDT &QL; 
