<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE MORE DODGERS TO APPEAL SUSPENSIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After filtering through the information during the weekend,
players association associate general counsel Gene Orza said
another round of appeals would be filed on behalf of Dodgers left
fielder Gary Sheffield, outfielder F.P. Santangelo and left-handed
pitcher Carlos Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Each player had their five-game suspension upheld by Paul
Beeston, chief operating officer of the commissioner's office, last
week. Chad Kreuter, whose eight-game suspension wasn't reduced by
Beeston, already appealed his suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's likely all of them will be appealed,'' Orza said
Monday. ``(Mike Fetters) won't because his is one game, but it's
likely the others will be appealed.''
</P>
<P>
   Fetters had his suspension reduced from four games to one. He
wanted to appeal the suspension because he maintains he did nothing
wrong in the May 16 fight with fans at Wrigley Field, but was
convinced by others that one game is not worth fighting over for a
reliever.
</P>
<P>
   While there is talk Kreuter's appeal would be heard during the
All-Star break in Atlanta, Orza said it doesn't mean everyone will
have their appeals heard then.
</P>
<P>
   Orza said the appeals could be filed as early as Wednesday.
Sheffield was slated to begin serving his suspension Saturday,
Perez on July 16 and Santangelo July 22.
</P>
<P>
   Orza confirmed this round of appeals will be heard by
commissioner Bud Selig and not independent arbitrator Shyam Das.
Officials from the Dodgers and throughout baseball are skeptical
Selig will overturn Beeston's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: In bringing middle infielder Mike Metcalfe into
the fold to replace outfielder Shawn Gilbert, a move expected
before today's game in San Diego, the Dodgers may finally have a
base-stealing threat who can swipe a bag late in a game to get into
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Metcalfe is still learning the art of base-stealing, but he had
34 stolen bases in Double-A San Antonio and nine more in 28 games
at Triple-A Albuquerque. Metcalfe played shortstop with the Dukes
but may be able to give second baseman Mark Grudzielanek a
much-needed day off.... Right-hander Gregg Olson had no problems in
throwing one inning for Single-A San Bernardino on Sunday. He's
slated to make a few more rehab appearances before the Dodgers even
consider activating him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
