<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2403 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-ROCKER-ARREST-NYT     07-03 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE MAY DROP CHARGE ON FAN WHO THREW BACK ROCKER'S BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   By C.J. CHIVERS    
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ City law enforcement officials were skeptical Monday
that the fan who was arrested for throwing a baseball onto the Shea
Stadium outfield near John Rocker would be prosecuted. But
prosecutors in Queens said they had not yet reached a decision on
the merits of the case.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the police charged Gregory Sweeney, 25, of Prospect
Heights in Brooklyn, with second-degree reckless endangerment after
he threw back to the grass a ball Rocker had tossed into the
stands. Rocker, who had been warming up left fielder Reggie
Sanders, had left the field before the ball landed in the outfield.
It did not land near any other player.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state penal code, second-degree reckless endangerment
is any ``conduct which creates a substantial risk of serious
physical injury to another person.'' It carries a maximum penalty
of one year in prison.
</P>
<P>
   But some police officers quietly scoffed at the charge Monday,
saying the arresting officer had mistaken for a crime an action
that clearly resembled the baseball tradition of throwing back a
visiting team's home runs as a sign of disgust. They also noted
that Sweeney had been handed the ball by a police captain that it
had accidentally struck, and, as he held it, fans were chanting for
him to unload it. The ball landed harmlessly in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rocker was already out of the way when the ball came down,''
one police supervisor said. ``It wasn't even near him.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at City Hall Monday, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani defended
the police department, saying that it had handled with great skill
the security issues surrounding Rocker, who antagonized people
across the country with remarks in Sport Illustrated last year
about members of minority groups, gays, single mothers and
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   But even Giuliani, a former prosecutor, suggested the charge
might not hold up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is understandable that if a ball came down on the field in
a situation like that, they arrest the person who threw it and then
have to sort it out afterwards,'' the mayor said. ``If it turns out
to have an innocent explanation, it will work out.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the fate of the charge rests with Richard Brown,
the Queens Country district attorney. Brown's office said Monday
that it had gathered footage of Sweeney's toss and had not decided
how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to review our videotapes and make the decisions
accordingly,'' said Sherry Hunter, a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Because Sweeney was issued a desk appearance ticket, he is not
expected in court for about a month. And another official said that
before Sweeney appears, the prosecutors will probably drop the
charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would appear that the criminal activity, if any, was
minimal,'' the official said. ``But we do have an obligation to
review it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney did not return two phone messages Monday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
