<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VORBE A PLEASANT SURPRISE FOR GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ There are not too many strikers in Major League
Soccer who can outrun D.C. United defender Eddie Pope, and that
includes speedsters Cobi Jones and Luis Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   So you can imagine how Pope felt last week against the Galaxy as
he chased a ball behind him. Jones and Hernandez weren't around,
but flying in came Sebastian Vorbe, who not only sprinted past Pope
but also finished a beautiful one-touch strike to the far post to
even the match, 1-1. The Galaxy went on to win, 2-1, after a late
Jones goal.
</P>
<P>
   Vorbe, a key performer on Haiti's national team, has been the
Galaxy's biggest surprise since the allocation of Luis Hernandez.
When the Galaxy lost Costa Rican midfielder Roy Myers in the
Hernandez deal, there was a foreign slot available for Vorbe, who
impressed Schmid in preseason workouts especially in a February
match in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Vorbe loves to take defenders one-on-one, but it is his speed
that may end up paying big dividends for the Galaxy, which plays
host to the Columbus Crew tonight at 7:30 at the Rose Bowl, with
the traditional Fourth of July fireworks show following.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's faster than he shows,'' said Schmid. ``The one thing I
would like to see is that speed more often.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shows it periodically during a game, maybe two or three
times, but when we played against Talleres in Argentina he smoked a
lot of their players over 50 and 60 yards and you saw that same
speed against Pope.''
</P>
<P>
   With Jones and Hernandez getting most of the attention, Vorbe
admits he's left alone to roam the front, and he's taking advantage
of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know me here so they don't know what I can do,''
Vorbe said of MLS defenders. ``They key on the big names on our
team so I'm able to sneak in the back or just force my way through.
</P>
<P>
   ``My speed is something they do not expect. Once I kick it (to
space), I feel I can get by a lot of these guys and create chances
for myself and my teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Vorbe will get most of the attention soon. After Saturday's
match at Miami, the Galaxy will likely lose Robin Fraser, Greg
Vanney and Jones to the U.S. National team and Hernandez to the
Mexican team for two weeks and two games for World Cup qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
   Vorbe, asked if he'll feel the pressure of having to perform
when the National team players leave, laughed at the notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of confidence and I've adjusted to the league and
the level of play,'' Vorbe said. ``But I don't know if there is any
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back home I'm under more pressure because of our crazy fans.
Here, the fans are more quiet, they sit down and clap their hands
or boo. If you play bad in Haiti you have to worry about getting
stuff thrown at you. If you (mess) up, you know, you're looking
over your shoulder to make sure you don't get hit with something.
</P>
<P>
   ``But seriously, I'm looking forward to that challenge when our
guys leave. We're going to see how much depth we have, everyone is
going to need to step up on this team for us to win, including
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S GAME: Columbus Crew (7-8-4, 25 points) vs. Galaxy
(8-5-7, 31 points), Rose Bowl, 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   RADIO: KTNQ 1020-AM (Spanish); KRLA 1110-AM (English)
TELEVISION: Fox Sports West 2 SERIES: Teams tied, 2-2, April 8;
Columbus leads 7-3-1 all-time.
</P>
<P>
   MATCH UPDATE: Columbus is struggling without injured U.S.
national team striker Brian McBride, but the Crew always seems to
play well against the Galaxy. Galaxy midfielder Danny Pena had
surgery on his right knee to repair at torn ACL and is expected out
two to three months, otherwise, the Galaxy is at full strength for
the first time in six weeks. Cobi Jones, who is playing with a cast
because of a third-degree sprained right thumb, has dropped to
midfield and Haitian striker Sebastian Vorbe has earned a starting
spot. The Galaxy expects a crowd of 50,000 tonight because of the
traditional Fourth of July fireworks show which follows the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
