<HEADLINE>
GAMBILL EARNS AN APPEARANCE ON CENTER COURT  
 PHILIPPOUSSIS' NEW LIFE  
 A BRIEF INTERRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Jan-Michael Gambill was too numb from his
victory Monday to let the reality of playing Pete Sampras in the
quarterfinals on Wednesday crash his feel-good moment.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Gambill has played under the burden to be the next
great American player. Early this evening, he levitated above the
Wimbledon grass after serving 33 aces and upsetting ninth-seeded
Thomas Enqvist, 7-6 (5), 3-6, 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say I'm one of the luckiest people on earth,'' said the
56th-ranked Gambill, 23, who makes his home in Colbert, Wash. ``I
get to go out there in the quarterfinals of Wimbledon and play on
Center Court, play Pete Sampras, the king of Wimbledon, the best
player to ever play the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to go out there and have a lot of fun. I'm
going to play great tennis. It's something to look forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   He has arrived at this point after a so-so year. In the spring,
Gambill tried a new racket, ditched it to return to his old one and
then regained his confidence. Now, his performance at Wimbledon
might land him on the Davis Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davis Cup is something I hold very special,'' Gambill said.
``There are a lot of players who could play. To be named to the
team is huge. It would be very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   There has always been a lot of buzz around Gambill. Named after
the actor Jan-Michael Vincent by his mother, who liked the ring of
the name, Gambill was at the center of some hype when his ranking
popped up to 31 in March 1999. From there, he slipped down the
ranking and out of sight, until this week. Before Wimbledon, he had
never advanced past the third round of a Grand Slam tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's all the rage. In a tabloid report, he was linked to
the pop singer Britney Spears and was asked about another teen
idol, Christina Aguilera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never met either of those girls,'' said Gambill, who
recently signed a contract with the Ford Modeling Agency. ``That's
really funny. I have a girlfriend. My girlfriend lives in
Connecticut. She's a model, not a singer.''
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPOUSSIS' NEW LIFE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the months since Mark Philippoussis toned down his night
life, his energy and focus have given him a new life on the court.
Monday evening, he continued his march through the men's draw with
a 6-1, 5-7, 6-7 (9), 6-3, 6-3 victory against Britain's last hope,
Tim Henman. Philippoussis' victory came just two days after his
five-hour third-round match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got a couple of massages,'' said Philippoussis, who
ripped 43 aces on Saturday and 34 Monday. ``I stayed relaxed. I
just wanted to leave everything on the court again.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Philippoussis will take his big serve and face the
best returner in the game, Andre Agassi, during a quarterfinal
match. Mentally and physically, he said, he is prepared to go
another five sets if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 23, and I feel pretty young,'' Philippoussis said. ``I'm
sure I've got a few more in me.''
</P>
<P>
   A BRIEF INTERRUPTION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A streaker interrupted play on Court 14 during a doubles match
between the teams of Anna Kournikova and Natasha Zvereva and Amy
Frazier and Katie Schlukebir. With a slogan off a Kournikova ad for
sports bras written across his chest, the streaker was quickly
grabbed by security as he darted across the court. In response,
Kournikova buried her head into a towel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't paying attention,'' said Kournikova, whose team
advanced to the fourth round, 6-2, 6-1. ``That's why we probably
are professional athletes. We kind of are used to everything
around. I was just trying to think about the match and about the
next game especially because it was important.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
