<HEADLINE>
9 OFFICERS FACE DISCIPLINE OVER CENTRAL PARK ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police Commissioner Howard Safir said Monday that
nine police officers, including six supervisors, would be
disciplined for mistakes that allowed an unruly mob of men to turn
a section of Central Park into a menacing gantlet where they
sexually assaulted dozens of women after the National Puerto Rican
Day Parade.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the nine officers, Safir said, the two
high-ranking chiefs who were in charge at the June 11 parade will
be given letters of instruction noting the shortcomings of the
operation, and three civilian 911 dispatchers will be punished for
improper handling of calls reporting the riotous behavior, thus
delaying the police response.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious that mistakes were made before, during and after
the parade,'' Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   The department's internal review, based on interviews with 236
officers, painted a detailed picture of the attacks, in which bawdy
horseplay on a sweltering day degenerated into sexual abuse. The
review found that some commanders failed to deploy officers
properly and failed to adjust to changing crowd conditions when the
parade ended earlier than expected and large segments of the 1
million spectators began to move about. In the grossest failures,
the review found, some officers disregarded women who complained
that they had been attacked.
</P>
<P>
   The officers cited Monday face a variety of punishments, from
letters of reprimand to formal misconduct charges, which carry a
maximum penalty of dismissal. A senior police official said,
however, that it was unlikely anyone would be fired.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine officers cited, two were accused of failing to
respond properly to women who had tried to report sexual assaults.
Another officer and one supervisor were faulted for leaving their
posts on Central Park South near where some of the attacks
occurred. Five supervisors, including an inspector and two deputy
inspectors, were cited for mistakes in deploying officers or for
letting officers go home even as the unruly crowd was growing
inside the park.
</P>
<P>
   The report immediately started discussion by representatives of
police unions and victims of whether the sanctions were too strong
or too weak.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. John Driscoll, president of the Captain's Endowment
Association, which represents supervisors up to the rank of deputy
chief, said the captains and inspectors cited were scapegoats who
had done nothing wrong. There was no one assigned to work the
problem area of the park, he said, and no way for the line
supervisors to have known a problem was developing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel that by offering up these people at high-ranking
levels, they will appease the media and the politicians,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Lynch, president of the Patrolmen's Benevolent
Association, was more muted. He released a statement that said the
union would defend its members but did not criticize the internal
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Several victims said Monday that the department did not seem to
have done enough. Although six victims have reported that about a
half dozen officers failed to take their complaints seriously, only
two officers were cited for such misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Susan M. Karten, a lawyer for one of the victims, said, ``This
doesn't make any women in this city, which is supposed to be safe,
feel any safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said their investigation had been complicated
by the fact that two victims would not cooperate while others had
difficulty identifying the officers involved.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 59 women have reported to police that they were
assaulted in the park or its environs by men who doused them with
water and beer, tried, successfully at times, to remove their
clothes, and groped them. So far, 29 men have been arrested and
officials have said they are looking for 17 more.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Department officials also said it was a coincidence that the
city chose to release its findings about the embarrassing incident
on July 3, when much of New York is away or preoccupied with
holiday celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We released this report when I believed it was done,'' Safir
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
