<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOURNOTES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Royalty in the Postal Service
</P>
<P>
   NANTES, France - Benoit Joachim, the U.S. Postal Service's
youngest competitor in the Tour de France, is getting grief about
his new nickname. The media in his home country of Luxembourg refer
to him as ``Prince.''
</P>
<P>
   He gained popularity in his tiny country after winning its road
race national competition last month. Joachim also is the first
rider from Luxembourg to ride in the Tour since Lucien Didier in
1984.
</P>
<P>
   We're not in Texas ...
</P>
<P>
   The route leading from Loudun west to Nantes on Monday afternoon
went right through wine country. The riders were flanked by miles
of muscadet grapes, which are used to produce the area's wine.
</P>
<P>
   In one small village, a man and two women stopped any car that
looked like an official Tour vehicle and handed the occupants boxed
bottles of cold local wine. The riders, however, were not given the
same treat.
</P>
<P>
   Tour traditions
</P>
<P>
   Monday's stage allowed for an unusual Tour tradition _ Le
Regional d'Etape. Any rider who makes his home near the stage route
or has family in the area can make a stop to say bonjour to family
and friends. Numerous fans held up signs Monday afternoon welcoming
``Franck.'' The rider they were referring to was Franck Bouyer, who
grew up in Vihiers and now rides for team Bonjour, which is making
its first appearance in the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Travelogue
</P>
<P>
   Monday's stage ended in Nantes, Britanny's largest city, with
its port and high-tech industries feeding its bustling economy.
</P>
<P>
   Nantes, like so many cities and villages in the country, has a
rich history. It was here that the Edict of Nantes was issued in
1598 by Henry IV. The edict gave religious freedom to Protestants,
although it was later revoked.
</P>
<P>
   Henri made his proclamation from the Chateau des Ducs de
Bretagne, a castle, complete with moat and drawbridge, that was
built in the ninth and 10th centuries and renovated in the 15th
century. The chateau served as a prison for Gilles de Retz, the
mass murderer better known by the nickname ``Bluebeard.'' Louis XII
also married Anne of Britanny there in 1499.
</P>
<P>
   In more recent history, Nantes served as the arrival city for
the fifth and next-to-last stage of the original Tour in 1903. The
original race, which numbered only 20 riders, then went from Nantes
to Paris to finish off the world's biggest bike race. That year,
Maurice Garin rode the 292 miles from Nantes to Paris to cap off
his three-hour victory over the field.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
