u s BC-GLF-LAWSUIT-NYT &LR;      07-03 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PGA SEEKS A HIGH-COURT REVIEW OF MARTIN CART SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARCIA CHAMBERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does the Americans With Disabilities Act trump the authority of
golf's organizing bodies to make their own rules? Or are
professional golf organizations exempt from the act because the
competitive nature of the sport would be forever changed?
</P>
<P>
   The Professional Golfers Association Tour has asked the U.S.
Supreme Court to review these questions in its petition seeking
review in the Casey Martin golf-cart lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The tour said it needs clarification of the act because this
year two federal appeals courts interpreted it differently. The
tour argues that the golf's governing bodies oversee the rules of
their competitions.
</P>
<P>
   The cases centered on two professional golfers, both with
congenital degenerative circulatory diseases that prevent them from
walking in tournaments. Golf's organizing bodies are hoping the
Supreme Court will resolve the conflict the tour and the U.S. Golf
Association now face in the many states where their tournaments are
held and where different rulings apply.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals permitted
Martin, who now plays on the PGA Tour, the right to use a cart
because he has a rare disorder that has deformed his right leg. The
act applied to Martin, the appeals court said, because tour events,
even ``within the ropes'' and involving the most elite players in
the world, are held at a public accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that Ford Olinger, a
golf pro from Indiana who has a degenerative hip, was not entitled
to a cart for qualifying events for the U. S. Open because a cart
would change the nature of the competition. These decisions, the
court ruled, were ``best left to those who hold the future of golf
in trust.''
</P>
<P>
   This unsettled state of affairs became even more complicated in
May when a Texas resident who has polio, JaRo Jones, sued the USGA
in federal court in Austin for the right to use a cart to qualify
for the U.S. Senior Open.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a federal judge ruled in favor of Jones, in a case
that is similar to Olinger's. Texas is part of the 5th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals, and thus the Olinger decision did not apply. Even
with a cart, Jones shot an 84 and did not qualify.
</P>
<P>
   A tour spokesman, Bob Combs, said Monday that he believed the
tour's chances of obtaining Supreme Court review are increased ``if
requests to review both the Olinger and Martin decisions are before
the court.''
</P>
<P>
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals recently denied Olinger's
request for a rehearing before its entire bench. The stage is now
set for Olinger to appeal to the Supreme Court. Olinger's lawyer,
John C. Hamilton, has said he will do so.
</P>
<P>
   Three members of the Supreme Court are known to be golfers _
Sandra Day O'Connor, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Anthony M. Kennedy.
Four votes are needed to accept a case for review. The court may
act by October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
