<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MARTIN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN HITS STRIDE DESPITE OFF-FIELD WOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES The bold-faced headlines from a Pittsburgh newspaper
detail an unsavory side of the Al Martin story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good guy Martin has run into bad times off the field,'' said
one publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin's image is probably ruined forever,'' the same
newspaper reported the following day.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 32, left fielder for the San Diego Padres and graduate
of Rowland High School, came under scrutiny this season after he
was arrested in March for alleged spousal abuse. There were
allegations of bigamy and paternal absenteeism that further clouded
his status.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the charges continue to hang over his head, others
were investigated and dropped. And, Martin vehemently denies he is
guilty of anything. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Back when he was still playing for the Pittsburgh Pirates,
Martin was known as much for his off-field philanthropy as his
on-field performance. But on the night of March 20, that all
changed when police in Scottsdale, Ariz. received a call from a
woman who said she was beaten by her ``pretend husband.''
</P>
<P>
   When police arrived, a woman, identified as Shawn
Haggerty-Martin, 31, said she had recently married Martin in Las
Vegas. She said she and her husband were arglen by her ``pretend
husband.''
</P>
<P>
   When police arrived, a woman, identified as Shawn
Haggerty-Martin, 31, said she had recently married Martin in Las
Vegas. She said she and her husband were arguing. Blows were
exchanged, then Haggerty-Martin claimed her husband threatened to
``O.J.'' her.
</P>
<P>
   The two were arrested and each charged with domestic battery.
</P>
<P>
   Just one problem with her story: Police claimed that Martin was
already married to another woman one who lived just seven miles
away. Investigators said felony bigamy charges might be in the
works for the ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   Haggerty-Martin returned to court and agreed to a year's
probation and entered a spousal abuse counseling program. Al
Martin's case is still pending. Maricopa County prosecutors
forwarded their bigamy investigation to Clark County authorities
who declined to file charges.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Padres' media guide, Martin continues to live
in Scottsdale with his wife Cathy and their son Brandon.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Martin expressed sadness about the whole situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 32 years of doing everything exactly right and being
thought of as a pretty decent guy, it's a long fall from glory,''
he said in a March interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might be what hurts the most you feel like you let so
many people down. Then you realize that there is nothing you can
really do or say that's going to make it better for the world. You
just go on faith on your past and hope that people understand the
type of person you are.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   On field, Martin is having a much better year. A career .289
hitter, Martin is batting .308 this season, has 22 RBIs, 49 runs
and 10 home runs through June. He's stolen six bases and has an
on-base percentage of .354. He loves his return to California and
is pondering a move from Scottsdale to La Jolla.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far it's been pretty good,'' Martin said of his first year
with the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact his team was 35-42 and 10-1/2 games out of
first at the end of June, Martin praised his organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably on a whole the best group of guys I've been
around as far as getting along with everybody and everybody getting
along with each other. We're battling and this year has been
awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   In his seven years with Pittsburgh, Martin had become something
of an institution. As a Pirate, he created ``Al's Army,'' which
provided tickets to 20,000 inner city youths between 1996 and 1999.
His 62 lifetime home runs at Three Rivers Stadium ranks fifth on
the ballpark's all-time list along with Pirate greats Willie
Stargell, Barry Bonds, Dave Parker and Bill Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw that last year, I thought, `What in the world is
Martin's name doing up there,''' he said. ``It made me smile.''
</P>
<P>
   But, at the end of last season, Martin felt it was time to move
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``In so many ways, I forced the trade,'' he said. ``I wanted to
go somewhere where I was happy and enjoyed life. So far that's been
the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who was born in West Covina and grew up in Diamond Bar,
said the trade to San Diego meant coming home. It also meant
playing in the same division as longtime friend Dave Hansen of the
Dodgers. The two played football and baseball together at Rowland
High School and remain friends.
</P>
<P>
   The two even share a birthdate: Nov. 24. Martin was born in
1967, Hansen in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my hero,'' Hansen said. ``He didn't even start playing
baseball until he was in high school and look where he is today.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who was a standout football player at Rowland, never
considered baseball as an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person who really made me like it was Hansen,'' Martin
said. ``He'd tell me a lot and help me. It was great hanging around
him.''
</P>
<P>
   A nephew of former Oakland Raider great Rod Martin, Al Martin
believed his future was on the gridiron. Although the Padre media
guide says Martin earned a scholarship to USC and played two
seasons at strong safety with the Trojans, USC officials have no
record of his presence, said assistant sports information director
Paul Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   A former coach recalled that Martin was drafted by the Braves
straight out of high school in the June 1985 free agent draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember him ever being at USC,'' said Rowland High
School assistant football coach Craig Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Martin was traded to the Pirates and made his major
league debut in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Although he no longer plays it, Martin still follows football
closely especially his favorite team, the Raiders. He's such a fan,
he even drives a silver and black car.
</P>
<P>
   He's said he hopes that somehow football's bad boys find their
way back to the glory of their heyday of the mid-1980s when he was
still in high school and spent time as a Raiders' ball boy.
</P>
<P>
   Considering his off-season brush with the law, Martin speaks
from experience when he offered his assessment of the Raiders'
chances in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they'll be in it this year,'' he said. ``If they can
keep their kicker (Sebastian Janokowski) out of trouble.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Martin's troubles aren't over just yet. He faces a pre-trial
appearance in Scottsdale on July 26 and could be sentenced to a
year in jail if convicted. It's likely he will receive probation, a
fine and community service, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, who remembered Martin as a ``happy-go-lucky'' youth with
a big smile and low profile, said he began seeing a change in
Martin's personality last season. Snyder, who coached Martin at
Rowland, said he always paid a visit to the ballplayer when the
Pirates came to town.
</P>
<P>
   But the last time he saw Martin, Snyder said the ballplayer
practically ignored him and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe something was brewing then,'' Snyder said. ``I could
tell last year when he gave me the cold shoulder that something had
changed. I could tell something was up.''
</P>
<P>
   But, like others who knew Martin from his days at Rowland High
School, Snyder said he was stunned to hear of the March
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of shocked,'' Snyder said. ``I guess you hope
something like this isn't true ... people at school are all hoping
for the best for him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
