<HEADER>
A2532 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-TECHSTOCKS-VALUATIONS     07-03 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHSTOCKS-VALUATIONS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TECHNOLOGY STILL DRIVING ECONOMY  &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Last year you could have made loads of money in
high-technology stocks simply by throwing darts at the Nasdaq
newspaper listings and buying whatever you hit.
</P>
<P>
   This year, as you may have noticed, it has gotten harder.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-laden Nasdaq composite index went up in flames
between early March and late May, losing a horrifying 37 percent of
its value. Despite a sputtering attempt to rise from the ashes in
recent weeks, it still stands roughly 20 percent below its all-time
high.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is it considered prudent to blindly buy any tech stock
with a glitzy name and a vaguely plausible business model.
</P>
<P>
   Today, investors in tech stocks must focus as well on such
old-fashioned criteria as earnings, market share and management
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules have changed,'' says David Readerman, an analyst and
partner with Thomas Weisel Partners in San Francisco. ``People are
more aware of, and sensitive to, stock valuations.''
</P>
<P>
   Some investors, devastated by the spring market collapse, have
vowed never to risk their money on tech stocks again.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a mistake, says Gary Schlossberg, an economist
with Wells Capital Management in San Francisco. It is technology
that is driving the economy, he points out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current expansion is a tech-based expansion,'' Schlossberg
observes. ``Computers, semiconductors and telecommunications
equipment may account for only about 10 percent of manufactured
goods, but they also accounted for three-quarters of the growth in
industrial output in the past year. The growth prospects should
continue to hold up quite well.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlossberg cautions, however, that the Nasdaq index continues
to be priced at more than 100 times earnings for the latest 12
months. By contrast, the broader-based Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
is selling at somewhat more than 30 times earnings _ and even that
is extraordinarily high by historical standards.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the largest, most mature high-tech companies sport
triple-digit price-earnings ratios.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, the giant producer of networking products,
recently was selling at 133 times trailing earnings and 122 times
estimated fiscal 2000 earnings. Oracle, the softwaremaker, was
selling at 116 times trailing earnings and 89 times estimated
earnings. For computermaker Sun Microsystems, the figures were 103
and 94 respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Premium P/E's are generally warranted if a company is in a
market space that has very fast growth,'' says Martin Pyykkonen, an
analyst with CIBC Oppenheimer in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Pyykkonen notes that Cisco _ thanks to its vital role in helping
to build the Internet infrastructure _ has confounded tradition and
common sense by growing faster as it has grown larger. As a result,
its P/E also has grown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has done so well against so many competitors,''
Pyykkonen says. ``It has size, critical mass, resources _ it is
very difficult to compete with.''
</P>
<P>
   But can a price-earnings ratio of 100 ever be justified?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, says Alfred Goldman, market strategist for A.G. Edwards &AMP;
Sons in St. Louis. P/E multiples aren't arrived at by scientific
method, he says. Rather, they reflect a ``guess'' about future
earnings, mixed with whatever is the prevailing ``state of mind''
among investors.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart J. Pillette, of Pillette Investment Management in San
Francisco, is less comfortable with the lofty high-tech P/E's.
</P>
<P>
   However, he says he would be willing to buy such stocks as
Cisco, Oracle and Sun at present levels because their prices have
been depressed, and they might bounce back toward their old highs.
</P>
<P>
   Pillette suggests buying these stocks near the bottom of their
``trading range,'' and selling them near the top of that range.
</P>
<P>
   The current trading range, he figures, is bounded by the highs
the stocks reached in March, and the lows they hit during the
tech-stock bloodbath in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   For Cisco, the range would be roughly 80 on the high end and 50
on the low end. The stock closed yesterday at $64.63.
</P>
<P>
   For Oracle, the range would extend from 88 to 62 (current price:
$80.19), while for Sun the range would be 105 to 71 ($90.44).
</P>
<P>
   Riding stocks up and down their trading ranges can be profitable
as long as the range boundaries remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, stocks eventually break out of their trading
ranges, and there is no telling when that might happen.
</P>
<P>
   You can get into big trouble if you buy a stock near the bottom
of its range and it then drops through the floor, or if you sell it
short near the top of the range and it then goes through the roof.
</P>
<P>
   All the experts agree that you had better do a lot of homework
before you buy any tech stock.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Bakar, director of research with Chase H&AMP;Q in San
Francisco, says that investors interested in a particular company
must first pull back and take a critical look at the industry in
which the company operates.
</P>
<P>
   Bakar advises that you ask yourself: ``What is the market they
serve; is it an attractive one; what's its growth rate; what are
the competitive dynamics; what are the barriers to entry? You have
to put everything in context.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are charmed by the industry, Bakar says, you next have to
ask ``what is the company's positioning within its market?'' You
want to be sure that the company is ``a leader or future leader.''
It has to be profitable now, or ``on a clear road to
profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   Limit yourself to companies with strong management teams that
can ``execute their strategy'' and that hold positions in their
markets that are ``defensible,'' Bakar adds.
</P>
<P>
   Such comprehensive research might seem like a tall order to most
investors. It is time-consuming, and it may require an
understanding of arcane technological concepts.
</P>
<P>
   But if you have the time and the will, there are plenty of
resources that could prove helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Your broker probably can supply you with in-depth reports from
the leading Wall Street analysts. Sometimes these reports can be
found on the broker's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   There also are countless financially oriented sites on the Web _
such as  &LR; www.yahoo.com &LR;  and  &LR; www.freeedgar.com &LR;  _ that will help
you dig out news, statistics and other facts about virtually any
publicly held company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
