<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-LAWYER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NAPSTER BEING BULLIED, LAWYER SAYS  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Napster Inc.'s high-powered lawyer, who was the
trust-busting attorney who led the government's prosecution of
Microsoft Corp., said Monday that the recording industry wants to
squash his client to maintain its tight control on record sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dominant firm or a trade association shouldn't have the
ability to use its power to stifle a new technology,'' said David
Boies, speaking for the first time publicly about the San Mateo,
Calif., startup's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Recording Industry Association of America who are
suing Napster for copyright infringement control the distribution
of all but a small percentage of popular recording artists, Boies
said. But Napster's popular file-sharing program is ``opening up
access to the public to a wider number of artists,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Napster claims it has lined up more than 17,000 new
artists who approve of sharing their music through the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The RIAA sees Napster as a threat, not because it's going to
reduce record sales, but because it's going to reduce the RIAA's
control over music sales,'' Boies said while discussing Napster's
legal strategy for fighting a preliminary injunction to stop the
file-swapping program.
</P>
<P>
   Napster filed its objection to the injunction, along with
results of a poll showing Napster has not harmed record industry
sales, yesterday in U.S. District Court in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The association represents record industry giants such as A&AMP;M
Records, Sony Music, BMG Music and Warner Bros., which sued Napster
in December for copyright infringement. The suit claims the
file-swapping program is nothing but a vehicle for music piracy.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, the music labels asked U.S. District Court
Judge Marilyn Hall Patel to order Napster to prevent the more than
10 million Napster members from using the program to swap and trade
their copyrighted songs.
</P>
<P>
   The association bolstered its case with a flurry of declarations
from music industry executives and the results of a Field poll that
showed Napster has harmed CD sales.
</P>
<P>
   Napster returned fire, noting in its response that five other
independent polls showed the program increased CD sales, while a
sixth poll found no significant drop.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Napster hired Boies, who was the lead trial attorney
for the Justice Department's antitrust suit against Microsoft.
Boies said the cases were ``quite different,'' but there was a
similarity in ``the principle of how consumers benefit by having
access to new technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Cary Sherman, the recording association's executive vice
president and general counsel, scoffed at the suggestion his
organization was acting like Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is silly since the RIAA is not even a plaintiff in the
case,'' Sherman said in a written statement. ``Individual music
publishers and record companies are the plaintiffs, all of whom
have partnerships with multiple legitimate technology companies.
Furthermore, Napster has never even sought licenses for their
activities. They are engaged in wholesale piracy.'`
</P>
<P>
   Boies said the company's main legal defense remains basically
the same as it has been since December. The company maintains it is
sheltered by the Digital Millennium Copyright Act of 1998, which
shields Internet service providers from the illegal actions of its
members.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Napster members were swapping pirated songs, Napster
still would not be liable for copyright infringement because
Napster just ``provides a directory service that allows individuals
to engage in the sharing of music,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Patel rejected Napster's motion to throw out the case,
ruling it still did not prove it qualified as an Internet service
provider.
</P>
<P>
   Napster also contends laws like the Audio Home Recording Act of
1992, meant to discourage music piracy on Digital Audio Tape, leave
room for new technology used for both legal and illegal uses.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Napster members are using the service to sample songs
and later buy the music, Boies said. ``The mere fact that some
people might be able to use Napster for inappropriate purposes does
not mean the service ought not to be provided,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman attacked that defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Napster cannot hide behind what consumers might be able to do,
individually and on their own, to build its own commercial
business,'' Sherman said. ``The courts have repeatedly rebuffed
attempts by businesses to hide behind the `fair use' privileges of
their customers.''
</P>
<P>
   A hearing on the injunction is scheduled for July 26.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
