<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2534 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH-MUTUAL-SFCHR     07-03 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-MUTUAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET WORTH: BIOTECH STOCKS MAKE FOR A THRILL RIDE _ IF YOU
CAN  STOMACH IT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Perhaps biotech companies should develop an
ulcer medication for their shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen of the top 20 mutual funds for the second quarter
ended Friday were biotech or health care funds, according to
Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean their shareholders got a good night's
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: the Dresdner RCM Biotech fund.
</P>
<P>
   Run by Faraz Naqvi, a San Francisco doctor-turned-money manager,
the fund ranked No. 2 out of all domestic stock funds during the
quarter, with a 27.3 percent return.
</P>
<P>
   That looks mighty appealing, unless you were watching it day by
day.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of February, the fund was up more than 100 percent
for the year. Like everything biotech, it had been benefiting from
several months of excitement surrounding the impending completion
of the human genome project.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in mid-March, President Clinton and British Prime Minister
Tony Blair made a statement that was widely misunderstood to mean
that drug companies should not be able to patent genes, and biotech
stocks went into cardiac arrest.
</P>
<P>
   From early March until mid-April, Naqvi's fund lost half its
value. It limped along until mid-May, when biotech stocks got
another jolt of hype from the human genome project.
</P>
<P>
   Year to date, the fund is up 73.7 percent, fifth best overall.
</P>
<P>
   Naqvi manages a second fund, Dresdner RCM Global Health Care,
which is ahead 24.6 percent for the quarter (No. 5 overall) and
53.4 percent for the year (No. 12). It is more diversified, and
hence less volatile than the biotech fund.
</P>
<P>
   Those weren't the only Bay Area medical funds topping the
charts. Franklin Global Health Care and Franklin Biotech, of San
Mateo, and Murphy New World Biotech, of Half Moon Bay, made it into
the top 15 for the quarter and the year, according to Bloomberg.
</P>
<P>
   Because the universe of biotech stocks is not large, biotech
funds end up owning a lot of the same companies, and hew fairly
closely to the American Stock Exchange Biotech Index (BTK). One
thing that sets them apart is how they move between biotech stocks
and cash.
</P>
<P>
   Naqvi says his fund excelled largely because ``we rode the last
biotech wave up a lot more than our competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most conservative, Murphy Biotech ``went to 40
percent cash in early March, then went to 60 percent pretty
quickly,'' says manager Lissa Morgenthaler. ``Several weeks ago I
was at 90 percent cash.''
</P>
<P>
   That helped her small fund's performance in the spring, but
proved to be a drag when biotech went bonkers again in late May and
June. Now she's back down to 20 percent cash.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Naqvi's biotech fund, by charter, must keep at
least 75 percent of its assets in biotech, and can't have more than
15 percent in cash. The rest can go into other stocks, generally
drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   Although Naqvi got as defensive as he could in the spring, he
charged back into biotech before the ``second wave.''
</P>
<P>
   He also managed to own some real winners, such as Millennium
Pharmaceuticals (up 72 percent for the quarter), Human Genome
Sciences (up 60 percent) and Vertex Pharmaceuticals (up 125
percent).
</P>
<P>
   He predicts that the second half of the year won't be as robust
for biotech as the first, ``but it wouldn't surprise me if we were
up another 30 percent between now and year end.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason: Fall is the season when biotech companies get to
show off their latest drugs at a slew of medical meetings. Also,
``You're going to see money flowing out of big-cap
pharmaceuticals,'' Naqvi predicts. ``They're facing a really
negative political environment. Typically, when institutions start
moving money out of drugs, they put some of it in biotech.''
</P>
<P>
   His favorite stocks:
</P>
<P>
   -- Amgen (AMGN). The biotech giant has filed a
patent-infringement suit against a Boston company called TKT, ``and
that has held down the valuation a little,'' he says. The suit
revolves around Amgen's key drug, Epogen, which helps the body
create more red blood cells. ``We've done a lot of work with
lawyers and are pretty sure Amgen is going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Millennium (MLNM). This was the best performing big-cap stock
in the country in the second quarter, but Naqvi says it could go
even higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a genomics company that has already made the transition
to become a pharmaceuticals company,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium uses its vast understanding of human genes to develop
drugs on its own and in partnership with big drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   His least favorite stocks:
</P>
<P>
   -- Biogen (BGEN). Its core product, a multiple sclerosis
treatment called Avonex ``is a good drug but not a great drug.
Better drugs are being developed by others,'' Naqvi says. Despite
its ``robust valuation (nearly $10 billion) it has one of the worst
(drug) pipelines in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Chiron (CHIR). ``Again, their core portfolio of products is
not very good, and their development pipeline is not very
inspirational either. I don't own it based on fundamentals alone.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Gilead Sciences (GILD). This company targets viruses, ``a
notoriously hard thing to develop drugs for,'' Naqvi says. Its
leading drug, a flu pill called Tamaflu, ``did OK last year. The
problem is, it's totally dependent on the flu season, and the
manufacturers of flu vaccines are making such good progress'' that
flu treatments are becoming less important.
</P>
<P>
   ``A really good drug is not something you use for a few days
every few years. It's something you take for the rest of your
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilead is also developing AIDS drugs, but that market, he says,
is ``very poor, fragmented and not growing,'' at least not in
countries and populations that can afford expensive drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullish argument (on Gilead) is that they have a pretty
good royalty stream on Tamaflu, and a lot of their AIDS drugs will
make a big enough splash in the AIDS community to become an
earnings driver. And they're a big-enough company ($3 billion in
market cap) to acquire or end-license products from smaller
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Or Gilead itself could be acquired. ``The reason why Chiron and
Gilead have maintained their valuations is that people think they
really do have smart scientists and great scientific
infrastructure'' that could make them takeover targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to like Gilead,'' Naqvi says, ``but I never walked
away thinking they're a great company.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at  &LR; kpender(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
