r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-PARK-LADN     07-03 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PARK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK LEARNS TO KEEP IT SIMPLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chan Ho Park used to pace around behind the mound, tormenting
himself about a pitch he threw two innings ago, or creating anxiety
thinking about a pitch he was going to throw two batters later.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, fastballs were thrown when a curveball was the right
pitch. Curveballs were thrown when the situation dictated a
changeup, and the more it was explained to Park, the more confused
he got.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson helplessly watched it unfold last
year, and was ready to do anything not to repeat it again. So a
month into the season Johnson made Park and veteran catcher Chad
Kreuter an inseparable pair.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Park, whose popularity nosedived in Korea during a dreadful
1999, is again regarded as one of the game's top young pitchers.
And he's doing it thanks to a big KISS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep It Simple, Stupid,'' Park said. ``That's what they tell
me, so that's what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   It's worked wonderfully. Park enters the final week before the
All-Star break leading the Dodgers with a 9-4 record. He has a 4.17
ERA and he's won five straight decisions.
</P>
<P>
   It comes from a trust built on five months of constant talking
and listening between Park and Kreuter. Park recently recalled a
moment from a game earlier this season in which he wanted to throw
a fastball and Kreuter was calling for a curve.
</P>
<P>
   It took a pair of trips to the mound, but Kreuter won out. Park
threw a curve, got an out in a key situation, and the two have been
on the same wavelength since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm more comfortable, and I'm thinking the right
thing, and that's important,'' Park said. ``I talk to (Kreuter) a
lot in the game, on the mound, in the dugout, before the game, even
on days I don't pitch. We talk a lot. We talk about what we will
do. That makes me more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has experience. He told me he learned from Nolan Ryan,
Charlie Hough, the veterans. He knows. He has so much experience. I
trust him.''
</P>
<P>
   How that translates into performance isn't lost on manager
Johnson. A year ago, Johnson quipped the other day, Park didn't set
up his fastball with anything, and he didn't use his fastball to
set anything up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see a guy that's not overthrowing, that's comfortable
and it looks like he's playing catch, that's pitching,'' Johnson
said. ``Normally, looking at a pitcher, (you want) good rhythm,
under control, not maxing out every pitch. Chan Ho gets into
trouble sometimes when he tries to overthrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter became Park's personal catcher after the right-hander
was pounded for eight runs in 3 innings May 8 at Arizona. In Park's
10 starts since, he's 6-1 with a 3.28 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are still times Park resists Kreuter's lead, pitching
coach Claude Osteen says, and a look at the walks says it all. Park
is tied for fourth in the National League in wins, but he leads the
major leagues with 66 walks.
</P>
<P>
   In his nine wins, Park has averaged 3.86 walks per nine innings.
In his four losses and four no-decisions, he's walked 7.61 per nine
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``By trusting Kreuter more, it made quite a few less that he had
to worry about,'' Osteen said. ``He got away from it a little in
his last game (Park walked six). It wasn't a bad game, but it had
some looks of the things he used to do. You saw some balls going
out of the strike zone and everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw a 'pen the other day, and afterward he said
'Sometimes, I don't have confidence in a certain pitch.' I said,
`Well, you used to say that, but you have to trust Kreuter enough
so that choice of pitches is based on what you have thrown to the
hitter before. The sequence of the pitches.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A usual June swoon has been replaced by a month in which Park
has positioned himself to become one of the top No. 2 starters in
baseball. He was labeled as such by virtue of his 29 combined wins
in the 1997 and 1998 seasons, but a 13-11 mark and a 5.23 ERA last
season instead cast doubt on Park.
</P>
<P>
   A cerebral pitcher with a country worth of pressures on him,
Park, who turned 27 on Friday, began to crumble long before St.
Louis' Fernando Tatis hit a pair of grand slams off him in one
inning last season.
</P>
<P>
   But Park, who was 0-3 with an 8.18 ERA in June last season and
was 6-8 with a 5.29 ERA in his career in June, by far the worst
month of his career, went 4-0 with a 3.67 ERA last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always try to work with him, and the situation dictates how
I do that,'' Kreuter said. ``Sometimes, I have to talk him through
it and tell him his stuff is fine and that he can get a hitter out.
Other times, I'll get mad at him and tell him, 'Do you want this
win? If you do, it's time to get it. This is the time.' It's just
dealing with situations in different ways.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
