u a BC-NY-LAZIO-NYT &LR;      07-03 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO STARTS SECOND BUS TOUR, TAKING STANDS AND SHOTS
</HEADLINE>
  By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ Rep. Rick A. Lazio began a five-day bus tour
across the state Monday, balancing an effort to direct his U.S.
Senate campaign toward issues against consistent attacks on his
Democratic opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   At times, he managed to do both.
</P>
<P>
   After beginning his tour with a visit to a Long Island health
clinic, where he called for more money for breast cancer research
and took credit as the ``point man in the House'' on cancer issues,
he labeled Clinton's effort to come up with a universal health care
plan a ``monstrosity.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, he overlooked apparent incongruities.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally in Yonkers before about 75 supporters, Lazio said
Clinton ``can't get out of the motorcade'' to empathize with
drivers frustrated with high gasoline prices. But he did so while
standing in front of his large, idling, customized campaign bus _
hardly a model of fuel economy _ which had just been escorted by
motorized police through city streets.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, a Republican, is on his second bus tour since beginning
his campaign May 20. He is making the most of a congressional
recess after a few weeks of being largely pinned down in Washington
while Clinton went on the offensive with strident language on the
stump and a barrage of attack television advertisements. She, too,
plans a tour upstate this week, as both candidates court voters in
a region campaign officials see as crucial to victory in November.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's tour, orchestrated down to the clothing he will wear at
certain stops, will include campaign staples like parade
appearances, including three planned for Independence Day. But as
he rides a bus called ``Mainstream Express,'' he will also use
campaign stops to highlight legislation he has sponsored or
supported and make pointed contrasts to Clinton. Mixed in will be
traditional party rallies, like one here Monday night that drew
about 50 people to a park under a steady drizzle.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio used strong language Monday, but some of the strongest
words came from his surrogates, including Mayor John Spencer of
Yonkers, a Republican who at the rally in his city railed against
``elite Democratic liberals looking down the nose of the people of
Yonkers.''
</P>
<P>
   And as he boarded his bus, Lazio's campaign aides blasted a
snippet from a Ray Charles song, ``What'd I Say'': ``Tell your ma,
tell your pa, going to send you back to Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Lazio said he was merely reciprocating the
negative campaigning that Clinton started, a claim the Clinton
campaign disputes. ``We were in the race for less than a month
before she personally went on the attack and began airing these
negative distortion ads,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   He told supporters at the Schenectady rally that ``character
does count,'' as well as integrity, without directly accusing
Clinton of lacking either.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's theme Monday was health care, and he toured a hospital
and a clinic to speak on women's health issues. He referred to
legislation he co-sponsored last year that provides Medicaid to
poor women needing treatment for breast and cervical cancer. He
counts the bill, which eventually passed, among his signature
achievements, although House Democrats often assert that the
Republican leadership stalled its passage.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also urged the passage of a bill he introduced last week
that would continue financing for breast cancer research through
the sale of postage stamps. ``We need to make sure we put the foot
on the research accelerator,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign office issued a statement deriding Lazio's
record on health care and criticizing him for not supporting a
``patient's bill of rights'' backed by Democrats last fall that
would have allowed people more latitude to sue their health
maintenance organizations over mistreatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carefully staged photo ops won't change the fact that Rick
Lazio has committed legislative malpractice,'' Howard Wolfson, a
spokesman for the Clinton campaign, said in the statement. ``He
voted against a real patient's bill of rights, against a
prescription drug plan that will cover all seniors, and voted to
cut Medicare by $270 billion. For New Yorkers looking for real
health care solutions, Rick Lazio's rhetoric is a bitter pill to
swallow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
