<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2539 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1STLD     07-03 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN TROOPS KILLED BY SUICIDE BOMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs entire story with updates and clarifies time elements.)  
(ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Chechen suicide bombers have set off a series of
devastating blasts throughout the breakaway Russian republic,
killing at least 37 Russian soldiers and wounding 74, officials
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a carefully coordinated rebel attack late Sunday night, five
trucks laden with explosives blew up in towns and cities that were
ostensibly under Russian control.
</P>
<P>
   The bombings caught the Russian military unprepared and occurred
just a week after the military had declared that the war was all
but won.
</P>
<P>
   As the toll of dead and wounded continued to climb _ one
unofficial count put it at 44 soldiers killed and 120 wounded _
Moscow vowed to break the back of the rebel resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one thing that can be done _ to find and crush
them,'' said Col. Gen. Valery Manilov, the deputy chief of staff of
the Russian forces, who called off a trip to Britain because of the
attacks. ``Talks will not help. You can see what is happening
there.''
</P>
<P>
   But the rebels said they were planning still more bombings, and
Grozny, the Chechen capital, was rife with rumors that it was about
to be attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen fighters won de facto control of the region in a war
with Russia in 1994-96. Russian forces returned last year after
militants based in Chechnya attacked villages in the neighboring
region of Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   The use of suicide bombings represents a new stage of the war.
</P>
<P>
   In the nine months of fighting, Russian forces have swept
through the northern plains, seized Grozny, taken the major cities
and towns in the Chechen lowlands and pursued the Chechen rebels in
the southern mountains. What they have not been able to do is
pacify the restive population and weed out the rebels in their
midst.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to take on the heavily equipped Russian military on its
own terms, the Chechen militants are mounting a guerrilla war.
Rebels have infiltrated the major towns, drawing support from local
Chechens who are embittered by the indiscriminate Russian attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Gen. Gennadi Troshev, the commander of Russian forces in
Chechnya, insisted that he had recently instructed his troops to be
especially vigilant, particularly in inspecting trucks.
</P>
<P>
   But trucks full of explosives operated by suicide drivers still
managed to elude Russian checkpoints on Sunday and approach several
major towns, possibly leaving from a base near Serzhen-Yurt, a
settlement the Russians said they had seized last week in a fierce
battle.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence of Russian laxity was painfully evident on Monday
in the aftermath of the bombings Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   In Argun, a town east of Grozny that has been fought over
several times during the year, a truck filled with explosives
smashed into a dormitory housing militia from the region of
Chelyabinsk in Russia's Ural Mountains. The militia's tour of duty
had just ended and they were set to go home. At least 30 died in
the blast, which created a huge crater, 5 yards deep and 10 yards
wide.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials conceded the dormitory had been poorly
protected. ``The dormitory building was not well enough defended
from the outside,'' said Sergei Yastrzhembsky, a Russian government
spokesman. ``As far as I know, the entrance to the territory was
blocked only by a Kamaz truck. There were no concrete barricades.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Gudermes, which functions as the administrative capital of
the region, the Russian military was more successful. Two trucks
full of explosives were stopped at the outskirts of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers were killed and a Russian as well as Chechen
soldiers died when the trucks exploded. One of the drivers was
believed to be trying to kill Akhmad Kadyrov, the Chechen official
picked by Russian President Vladimir Putin to govern Chechnya,
according to Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
   Another truck full of explosives, also believed headed for
Gudermes, was stopped near the settlement of Novogroznensky. It
rammed into an Interior Ministry unit, killing three and wounding
20.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another truck exploded near the office of the military
commandant in Urus-Martan. It blew up as it tried to ram the
building, killing two soldiers in a concrete shelter.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians later announced that they had detained 18 people
suspected of involvement in the blast.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,100 Russian soldiers have been killed and 6,000
wounded since Oct. 1. The nation is weary of the war, but not to
the point where the Russian public is willing to cede control of
Chechnya to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   With each bombing or ambush, the Russians seem to have become
more bitter. And with each air strike or artillery barrage, the
Chechens seem to have become angrier at the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   On the Russian side, the Chelyabinsk region is an example. It
had promised to help restore the town of Argun, one of the targets
of the bombings on Sunday. But stung by the loss of fighters, the
Chelyabinsk governor said the region would no longer help, ensuring
the restoration of Chechnya would take longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as they kill our guys I won't give them a ruble,''
said Gov. Pyotr Sumin. ``And nobody will make me do this.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Chechens, much of the enmity is directed not only at
Russians, but also at Chechens who are cooperating with the
Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Aslan Maskhadov, the separatist president of Chechnya before the
Russian intervention, essentially called for the death of Kadyrov,
the Russian-appointed leader of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   In an address that is recorded on videocassette and available in
Chechnya, Maskhadov called Kadyrov ``the main enemy of the Chechen
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people will appreciate the services of the one who manages
to remove him more than all the heroic deeds performed by Chechen
fighters in all wars in the course of the last 400 years,''
Maskhadov said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
