<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-1STLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PIAZZA ILLUMINATES AN OBSCURE RBI RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS with update in 9th graf, bgng: That's where...)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first glance, the streak seems to be one of those arcane
achievements that only a statistics freak could know or care about.
How significant could it be that Mike Piazza was approaching the
major league record for driving in runs in consecutive games when
the record-holder wasn't Hack Wilson or Lou Gehrig or Babe Ruth or
anyone else of that stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the importance of the streak record is judged by who
holds it rather than by what it represents,'' said Steve Hirdt, an
executive with Elias Sports Bureau, keeper of Major League Baseball
statistics and records. ``I think there would be general unanimity
in baseball that driving in runs is at least as important as
getting a hit. Yet there are 5-year-olds who would know chapter and
verse of Joe DiMaggio's hitting-streak record while people who make
their living playing or covering baseball try to belittle this
record simply because the guy who holds it is someone whom they
have never heard of.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Grimes was not Joe DiMaggio, or Lou Gehrig or Babe Ruth, for
that matter. In 1922, Grimes, a first baseman with the Chicago
Cubs, drove in runs in 17 consecutive games. Chances are no one
thought much about it at the time, but nobody had produced such a
streak before Grimes did it and no one has done it since.
</P>
<P>
   Grimes was an unexceptional player. He had a relatively short
career, playing 432 games in five seasons after getting into one
game in 1920. The season in which he established the record was a
career year for him because he drove in 99 of his career 263 runs
batted in. But Grimes' record stands 78 years later. DiMaggio's
56-game hitting streak is only 59 years old.
</P>
<P>
   When Wilson knocked in what remains a major league-record 191
runs in 1930, he didn't threaten Grimes' record. Elias research
found that the longest stretch in which he drove in at least one
run was 11 games. The next season Gehrig drove in what continues to
be the American League record, 184 runs. His best streak: 10 games.
In 1937, Hank Greenberg drove in 183 runs. He knocked in runs in 11
successive games at one stretch.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Sammy Sosa drove in 299 runs for the Cubs the
previous two seasons, and each season his longest consecutive-game
RBI streak was 5. Five games (twice) was the limit, too, for Manny
Ramirez last year when he knocked in 165 runs for Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   While Ramirez was unable to go beyond five in a row, Mike
Sweeney of Kansas City made it to 13 games in succession a year ago
Tuesday, tying the American League record set by Taffy Wright of
the Chicago White Sox in 1941, the year of DiMaggio's hitting
streak.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza reached 13 last Friday night when he beat Atlanta with a
dramatic three-run home run in the eighth inning. A two-run home
run in the third inning the next day extended the catcher's streak
to 14, and in what appeared at the time could be his last at-bat of
the day, he reached 15 Sunday by lashing a home run in the seventh
inning.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the streak ended as the Marlins shut out the Mets,
2-0, Monday night in Florida. Piazza batted in the first and third
innings with runners at first and second but hit a fly ball to
right field each time. In the eighth, he came close to hitting a
home run, but the ball landed at the base of the left-field fence
for a double.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's hitting streak is often cited as the record least
likely to be broken. But why has it received so much attention over
the years while Grimes and his record have been completely ignored?
Is Steve Hirdt right, that the identify of the player determines
the perceived importance of the record?
</P>
<P>
   A reasonable argument can be made that maintaining an RBI streak
is harder than running off a hitting streak. A batter needs no help
in building a hitting streak. A single here, a double there, and a
streak continues. To build an RBI streak, a player needs help. His
teammates have to get on base so he can drive them in. He can do it
himself occasionally with a home run, but no one has ever hit home
runs in 17 consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Piazza's RBIs in the 15 games were critical to the
outcome. He won the Friday night game against Atlanta, he gave the
Mets the lead in six other games and he knocked in the tying run in
three games. The home run Piazza hit Sunday was his eighth in his
RBI streak and raised his RBI total in that span to 28.
</P>
<P>
   The streak has catapulted him to the front of the race for the
National League Most Valuable Player award. Although one view might
have it that Piazza has been the league's MVP the first half of the
season, some more cautious people like editors might want to slip
in the hedge word ``perhaps,'' leaving open the possibility that
someone else has been the MVP. It says here without equivocation
that if there were a half-season award, Piazza could step right up
and collect it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
