<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES DELIVERS, BUT WENDELL AND METS' HITTERS DON'T 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Mets got six shutout innings from one struggling
pitcher. Another struggling pitcher followed by striking out the
side.
</P>
<P>
   It was not Bobby J. Jones or Dennis Cook who allowed the only
runs Monday night in a 2-0 loss to the Florida Marlins. Turk
Wendell, who has been one of the more reliable pitchers on the
staff, surrendered a two-run homer to Derrek Lee with one out in
the bottom of the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza extended his hitting streak to 21 games, but his
streak of 15 games in a row with a run batted in ended. He had a
double in four times up but fell two RBIs shy of a 78-year-old
record held by Ray Grimes of the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell (4-4) had been scored on only once in his last seven
appearances. But while he has had a fine season, he has been prone
to allowing home runs. Lee's homer was the fourth game-winning home
run Wendell has allowed this year. San Francisco's Jeff Kent,
Colorado's Bubba Carpenter and Los Angeles' Kevin Elster beat him
with homers in May.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' offense was shut out by three Marlins pitchers,
including the former Mets farmhand Jesus Sanchez, who worked eight
scoreless innings. Armando Almanza was the winning pitcher in
relief, retiring Todd Pratt and Melvin Mora with runners in scoring
position in the top of the ninth. The Mets were 0 for 11 with
runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Jones started the season miserably, and his overall numbers are
still smarting because of it. His 8.10 earned run average entering
the game was the highest among the pitchers who started National
League games Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones has been a much different pitcher since accepting a
10-day assignment to Class AAA Norfolk in the middle of June. He
started twice there, adjusted his delivery and came back with a
sharper curveball and a fastball with better downward movement.
</P>
<P>
   In three starts since returning, Jones has worked 20 innings,
allowing 16 hits and five runs while striking out 16 and walking
three. Monday night's start was his first since April _ also at Pro
Player Stadium against the Marlins _ in which he did not allow a
run.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was magnificent, overcoming an aggressive Marlins running
game that put runners in scoring position in the first, fourth,
fifth and sixth innings. The Marlins stole four bases, two by
Preston Wilson. He singled with two out in the fourth, then stole
second with Mike Lowell batting. But Jones dropped to a sidearm
delivery with two strikes, and Lowell bounced a breaking ball to
first for the final out.
</P>
<P>
   Lee doubled off the left-field wall to open the fifth, then
advanced to second when Alex Gonzalez bunted for a single. Jones
tried to field the ball but slipped, and Gonzalez stole second. It
was a dangerous spot _ even with the Marlins' Nos. 8, 9 and 1
hitters coming up _ and Jones survived, striking out Paul Bako,
Sanchez and Luis Castillo.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza came up with runners at first and second and one out in
the first inning and in the third. Both at-bats had the same
result: a popout to short right field that advanced no runners.
Both times, Sanchez retired the next hitter, Todd Zeile, to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Though Piazza's RBI streak ended Monday night, he has
established one record with his torrid run production. During the
Mets' weekend split in a four-game series with the Atlanta Braves,
he set a Mets' record for runs batted in before the All-Star break.
Piazza has 71 RBIs, two more than Dave Kingman had at the break in
1976.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza was not the only Met to squander a chance to drive in
runs. Robin Ventura doubled to lead off the second inning, but
Benny Agbayani popped up, Joe McEwing grounded out and Jones struck
out.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, after Sanchez hit Jones to start the inning, Mora
and Derek Bell struck out and Edgardo Alfonzo flied to left.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez lasted through the eighth, when he survived another Mets
charge. Piazza lofted a two-out double to the left-field warning
track, and Zeile was intentionally walked. Then Sanchez got Ventura
to fly to center, ending the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
