<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR TAKES ISSUE WITH ISSUE OF HIS HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It has become an almost weekly routine. Reporters
press Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for details on his cancer treatment
deliberations. The mayor, sometimes in an irritated voice, other
times in a stern but calm way, then tells them, in essence, to bug
off.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the matter flared yet again, prompted by a report in The
Daily News on Saturday, citing unnamed sources. The newspaper said
that Giuliani, who announced in April that he had a treatable form
of prostate cancer, had started a preliminary hormone therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a media, press-created craze,'' Giuliani said, staring
down from a City Hall Park stage toward the familiar pack of
reporters gathered for his daily news conference. ``The invasion of
my privacy, the invasion of my doctor's office, the almost-crazed
atmosphere that's created is not conducive to good medical
treatment, either for me or for anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   The lashing was so intense that while the mayor did not confirm
or deny the news, no one asked a follow-up question. Instead, the
mayor indicated that he would disclose his decision only when it
meant he had to disrupt his work. And there are few hints that that
has happened yet, with Giuliani scheduled to rush Tuesday from a
late-morning inspection of the New York Harbor parade of tall ships
for Operation Sail 2000 to a Fourth of July parade on Staten
Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm ready and I believe it is in my best interest to
announce something, I will,'' the mayor said Monday, before moving
to other topics. ``So far, nothing that I'm doing or not doing has
any impact on my work.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's approach to the news media regarding his prostate
cancer has been relatively consistent from the start. He was
praised in April for his immediate and forthright disclosure of the
diagnosis. But when it came to discussing details of the disease,
he has declined all questions other than to acknowledge about the
time he dropped out of the Senate race in May that choosing from
among the treatment options had been extremely difficult.
</P>
<P>
   In the early-stage cancer that mayor has said he has, the most
frequent alternatives are surgery or radiation treatment, said Dr.
William G. Nelson, an associate professor at Johns Hopkins
University in Baltimore and an oncologist who has not been involved
in the mayor's care. The report that the mayor is undergoing
hormonal therapy with a drug called Lupron does not necessarily
mean he has made up his mind, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   By reducing the testosterone levels, Lupron merely slows cancer
growth and sometimes shrinks the prostate cancer tumor in
anticipation of a more intense treatment, Nelson said. It is more
frequently a precursor to radiation treatment than it is to
surgery, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise that the mayor's reticence has led to friction
between Giuliani and the news media, several medical ethicists said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The public's expectation that certain elected officials will
divulge private and even non-life-threatening health matters dates
at least to 1965, when President Johnson, following gallbladder
surgery, proudly showed off his scar.
</P>
<P>
   During President Reagan's tenure, a small spot of cancer on his
nose inspired regular news updates with headlines like
``President's Nose `Terrific''' and ``Reagan's Nose Unbandaged.''
In New York, a similar type of cancer, considered rarely
life-threatening, was found on Mayor Edward Koch's nose in 1988,
again drawing a flurry of news reports.
</P>
<P>
   But three experts who have studied issues related to politicians
and their health said Monday that as far as they could determine,
the mayor appeared to be justified in declining to answer questions
about his treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Given that there are no signs that his condition or any possible
treatment is affecting his performance as mayor, he is not
currently obliged to discuss the matter further, said Dr. James F.
Toole, a professor of neurology at the Wake Forest University
School of Medicine in Winston-Salem, N.C, and co-chairman of a
group that recently released a report titled ``Disability and U.S.
Presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been times when politicians have not been forthcoming
about the seriousness of their conditions. Paul E. Tsongas of
Massachusetts, a presidential candidate in 1992 who concealed that
he had had a recurrent cancer, died in 1997, as his first term
would have been ending. But Toole said that even if the mayor's
case was somewhat more severe than he had indicated, it would not
be relevant because he remained on the job and was not seeking a
new term or any other elected office.
</P>
<P>
   George J. Annas, chairman of the health law department at the
Boston University School of Public Health, and Dr. Joseph J. Fins,
director of medical ethics at the New York Weill Cornell Center,
said Monday that the mayor should be allowed to decide on his
treatment privately.
</P>
<P>
   But Annas said that the mayor's reaction to the news media's
questioning seemed somewhat naive, given an era of intense
fascination with politicians like Giuliani and the public's
heightened interest in matters related to health.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is mostly what you can kindly refer to as gossip,
voyeurism,'' Annas said. ``The public wants to know as much as it
can about celebrities, and he is a celebrity politician.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
