<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-PLANE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANE TOWING AD BANNER CRASHES AT NEW JERSEY AIRPORT, KILLING
PILOT 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE STRUNSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pilot of a three-passenger single engine plane towing an
advertising banner was killed Monday in a crash at a municipal
airport near the Jersey Shore.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, Robert Lewis, 44, of Omaha, Neb., was pronounced dead
at Kimball Medical Center in Lakewood, N.J., shortly after his
plane crashed at 12:30 p.m. on the runway at Lakewood Airport, said
Chief Michael Lynch of the Lakewood police.
</P>
<P>
   A Federal Aviation Administration spokesman, Jim Peters, said
initial reports indicated that there might have been a passenger,
but Lynch said the pilot was the only one on board.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the crash is under investigation by the National
Transportation Safety Board, Peters said.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Sakowitz, the first assistant Ocean County prosecutor, said
he had been told that the plane was taking off when it crashed. The
plane, an Aeronca Champion single-engine propeller craft that seats
three, was used to tow the kinds of advertising banners seen along
beaches in New Jersey and elsewhere, Lynch said. Officials said
they did not know what the banner said.
</P>
<P>
   Peters said the airport, which is owned by Lakewood Township,
serves general aviation aircraft and does not have a control tower
to guide takeoffs and landings, so there were no recordings of
last-minute radio calls from the plane. Without a tower, the pilot
would have been taking off or landing under his own direction,
using visual sighting and general radio broadcasts to inform any
other aircraft in the area of his intent, Peters said.
</P>
<P>
   The airport is about six miles west of the shore, and a company
known as O'Brien Aviation runs a banner towing operation from
there. O'Brien's telephone number is the same as the main number
for the airport; no one answered the telephone Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was registered to Aimada Corp. of Wilmington, Del.,
said Peters, the FAA spokesman. Another spokesman for the agency,
Roland Herwig, said Aimada had no outstanding violations or any
record of crashes or other significant incidents. Herwig said he
could not immediately provide information about the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said that Monday's accident was the first fatal plane
crash at the airport that he could remember in his 31 years with
the department.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
