<SLUG> BC-NJ-BISHOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLICS IN ESSEX COUNTY GET NEW SPIRITUAL LEADER  
 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II has chosen a son of Newark, N.J., and a
longtime educator to be the spiritual leader of Roman Catholics in
Essex County, N.J., the Archdiocese of Newark announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Monsignor Arthur J. Serratelli, the rector of St. Andrew College
Seminary at Seton Hall University, was named regional bishop for
Essex County, one of four counties, along with Hudson, Bergen and
Union, that make up the archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   Serratelli, 55, was appointed to fill a vacancy created last
summer, when Auxiliary Bishop Nicholas A. DiMarzio was made bishop
of Camden, one of the state's five dioceses, with Trenton,
Metuchen, Paterson and the Newark archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   In his regional role, Serratelli is essentially the spiritual
and administrative head of the county's Roman Catholic parishes and
church programs, said Jim Goodness, a spokesman for the
archdiocese. He is also one of five auxiliary bishops in the
archdiocese who assist Archbishop Theodore E. McCarrick, New
Jersey's highest Catholic official.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the regional bishops, a fifth auxiliary, Bishop Paul
Bootkoski, serves as vicar general and moderator of the diocesan
curia, handling the day-to-day affairs of the archdiocese. While
the regional bishops assist McCarrick, who turns 70 on Friday _
five years short of the mandatory retirement age for bishops _ they
do not form a line of succession, and a new archbishop will be
appointed by the pope regardless of geography.
</P>
<P>
   The new bishop grew up in Newark and attended Seton Hall Prep in
nearby West Orange. He then studied philosophy at Seton Hall
University in South Orange, before attending the Immaculate
Conception Seminary in Darlington, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
