<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-OAKLAND-REBUILDING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBUILDING GRADES OUT AS ALL A'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ When the Oakland Athletics stumbled through a
97-loss season and finished 25 games out of first in 1997, manager
Art Howe knew there had to be better days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Jason Giambi was developing into a nice player,
and that Ben Grieve kid showed some flashes after he was promoted
in September.
</P>
<P>
   When the A's lost 88 games and again finished last in '98, Howe
knew the team was getting closer. Grieve was the American League
Rookie of the Year. Two more youngsters brought up during the
season, shortstop Miguel Tejada and Eric Chavez, looked like
keepers.
</P>
<P>
   When the A's traded for Kevin Appier, Omar Olivares, Randy
Velarde and Jason Isringhausen in late July last season, Howe knew
his young team was ready to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still learning. We're still very young,'' Howe said.
``But we feel we're competitive now.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's indeed have taken the step from talented young team to
contending team. They were 46-34 before the first of a three-game
series against the Rangers last night, 1 1/2 games behind the
first-place Seattle Mariners in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   They led the wild-card standings by fourgames over the New York
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gone from a team that was rebuilding with a bunch of
young guys, to those young guys getting older and adding some
veterans to mix in with them, and then becoming a good team,'' said
Grieve, the starting left fielder and a former Arlington Martin
High School standout.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation from potential to results came when the A's
made their trades last season.
</P>
<P>
   Giambi had become one of the best sluggers in the league.
Grieve, Chavez and Tejada were coming on after slow starts. The A's
were a much-improved team from the 97- and 88-loss outfits.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they were hovering around the .500 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a three-day period, general manager acquired Olivares
and Velarde from the Anaheim Angels, Appier from the Kansas City
Royals and Isringhausen from the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were an OK team in the first half, making our mistakes, but
then Billy Beane made those trades,'' Giambi said. ``Ever since we
picked those guys up, we turned the corner and became a good ball
club.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's were 52-50 when they made the final trade last season.
Since then, they are 81-59.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year when we made our trades, that's when we bridged the
gap,'' Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   The A's finished with 87 victories last season, and stayed
within six or seven games of the first-place Rangers for most of
the second half. They finished eight games out, but surprised most
people by finishing second.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they no longer are a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a year older, more experienced,'' Velarde said.
``There's no substitute for experience. It breeds confidence. It
gave us hope last year. It opened some eyes as to what we were
capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Howe, Giambi suffered through the lean seasons. But with
the talent the team already had on hand, Giambi figured this day
might come.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been talking about trying to get to this point for a long
time,'' Giambi said. ``Billy Beane said when we get to the point
where we feel like we have a good team, we're going to try and get
some players and make this team better. That's what you have to do,
especially with the way we built this team with youth. You get your
young players, and you let them take their lumps. But then you say
OK, this is our core group, and you start pulling pieces together.
I think we did it at the right time. We knew what we had with
Grieve, with Chavez, with Tejada. Then we brought in Randy Velarde.
We starting pulling the pieces together.''
</P>
<P>
   The new players might prove to be the final pieces of the
puzzle, but only because a solid core already was in place.
</P>
<P>
   Entering last night's play, Giambi was batting .342 with 22
homers and 76 runs batted in, second in the league. Grieve was
hitting .303 with 15 homers and 62 RBI. Tejada had 13 homers and 60
RBI. Chavez has recovered from a slump to bat .277 with 12 homers
and 41 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of a few seasons ago now is being realized. The A's
no longer just hope to win. They expect it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nice run last year, but there was some unfinished
business,'' Velarde said. ``That's our goal this year, is to bring
home a pennant.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
