<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2553 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-RISKY-BEACHES-NYT &LR;      07-03 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RISKY-BEACHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME BEACHGOERS, AN INVITATION TO TEMPT FATE
</HEADLINE>
  By SARAH KERSHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At 7 p.m. last Wednesday, an hour after the
lifeguards had left their perches along Rockaway Beach in Queens
and whistled everyone out of the water, the Atlantic Ocean, wild
and menacing as it can be, was still too tempting for some to
resist.
</P>
<P>
   It was about the same time of night June 25 that a Manhattan
woman and her 6-year-old daughter drowned, several miles west on
that same beach, in an area near Far Rockaway that is so rough with
riptides that the lifeguards call it the ``death trap.'' Five days
later, an 11-year-old Queens boy drowned after swimming in an area
of Jamaica Bay where bathing is not allowed and lifeguards are
never stationed.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen others in New York, New Jersey and Connecticut
have drowned since Memorial Day, most after venturing into the
ocean, lakes or ponds when lifeguards were off duty or after
swimming into areas that were off limits.
</P>
<P>
   But neither the drownings nor the posted bans on swimming
without a lifeguard stopped a handful of people from taking an
evening swim Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   After the lifeguards disappeared from sight, a few swimmers made
their way to the water's edge, then splashed and bobbed in the sea.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, as the sun was setting and there was almost no
one left on the beach but a few scattered fishermen and a batch of
seagulls, a couple from Flushing waded into the ocean and swam out
about 30 feet from the shore, staying in the water for about 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When the woman came out of the water, she said she found the
beach too crowded during peak hours and was desperate for a swim
that night. ``I don't know if it's safe or not,'' she said. ``But
I'm not afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent drownings underscore a dark but seemingly inevitable
side to summer: Some people tempt fate in the water, whether
unwittingly taking risks or brazenly defying the rules, and lose
their lives every year.
</P>
<P>
   The number of deaths may ebb and flow, parks departments may
strengthen their patrols, hire more lifeguards _ although New York
City has struggled with a shortage _ or post more warning signs
around their beaches in response to a drowning. But as officials
face the grim possibility of more drownings, they say the ocean
cannot be locked up or the seduction of the water stamped out.
</P>
<P>
   On Long Beach in Nassau County, N.Y., where the three miles of
beach is easily accessible from a boardwalk, like Rockaway and
Coney Island, three people drowned last year while swimming after
the lifeguards were off duty, and three weeks ago, 15 minutes after
lifeguards left at 6 p.m., a 12-year-old boy from Brooklyn was lost
in the water and drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Nyman, city manager of Long Beach, said there are one or
two drownings on the beach every year, typically when the
lifeguards, who work from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m., are off duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the U.S. Army couldn't keep people off our
beaches at night,'' Nyman said. ``I wish there was a way we could
close our water.''
</P>
<P>
   While many people heed the warning signs, those who take the
risks think, ``It won't happen to me,'' said a Rockaway Beach
lifeguard, Omar Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, more drownings occur on ocean beaches, like Rockaway,
which stretches seven miles along the eastern edge of the city, and
Coney Island, which has many entrances along the street that make
the water easily accessible. But rivers, lakes and basins beckon
thrill seekers and people escaping the heat or the crowds of the
guarded beaches. In Connecticut, several drownings have occurred
this year in rivers and ponds.
</P>
<P>
   In the city last year, three people drowned off city beaches,
two when there were no lifeguards on duty. Both drowned in the
morning, before lifeguards went on duty at 10, one at Coney Island
and the other at Orchard Beach in the Bronx, said officials from
the City Parks and Recreation Department. The department is in
charge of safety on the city's 12 miles of public beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Orchard Beach was the scene of another fatal
accident when a teenager jumped off his boat for a swim, 200 feet
offshore, and drowned.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the Rockaway drownings, the Parks Department has
extended beach patrols to 8:30 p.m. from 6 p.m. Rangers in
four-wheel drive vehicles roll across the sand at Brighton Beach,
Coney Island and Rockaway Beach to order defiant bathers to leave
the water. The patrols were not deployed to Orchard Beach, parks
officials said, because the Police Department covers that area.
</P>
<P>
   Henry J. Stern, the parks commissioner, said that rule-breaking
in city pools and beaches ``is an issue we've been plagued with for
years,'' but that he is aware that the evening patrols, which were
begun this year, can do only so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do what you can to prevent tragedies,'' he said, ``But
unfortunately, people simply motivated by the desire to cool off
can jeopardize their lives. It's very sad.''
</P>
<P>
   It was easy to see on Wednesday night that Rockaway, because of
its expanse and easy access, is a difficult beach to patrol. The
rangers rode up to a group of five girls celebrating graduation
three times before they finally left. When the couple from Flushing
was bobbing in the water, the rangers' vehicle was crawling along
the eastern end of the beach, miles away.
</P>
<P>
   At Brighton Beach on Saturday night, between 7 and 8, the beach
was still packed, and the water filled with dozens of swimmers.
They had been chased out by lifeguards or told to leave by the park
patrol, but they had simply waited until the lifeguards and rangers
were out of sight and had returned to the water.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Santana and her three children, who live in Manhattan,
ventured to the beach by subway to have dinner and take an evening
swim. It was about 7:30, and Santana kept an eye on her children,
especially her 9-year-old son, Edwin Espinosa. ``I like the waves
and I go far,'' Edwin said as he rushed back into the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's dangerous,'' Santana said. ``But they like to
play. And I watch to make sure they don't go too far.''
</P>
<P>
   She turned to look at the water, spotted her son, and screamed,
``Edwin!''
</P>
<P>
   He turned to look at her and paddled back toward the shore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
