u a BC-NY-WEB-WINE-COLUMN-NY     07-03 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WEB-WINE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: A TEA PARTY LIKE BOSTON'S, OVER WINE?
</HEADLINE>
 By JOHN TIERNEY   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As we celebrate our independence from one form of
tyranny, many New Yorkers may be consorting with a new foreign
menace. They may be drinking out-of-state wine.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them won't even know the danger in their glasses. They
haven't heard of the arguments over New York's liquor laws that are
set to begin this month in Federal District Court in Manhattan.
Vintners in California and Virginia have joined with consumers in
New York in a suit seeking to overturn the law prohibiting
out-of-state wineries from shipping directly to New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   This menace is tricky to understand. There are whole states,
even apparently functioning ones like Connecticut, that blithely
allow their citizens to order wine directly through catalogs and
the Internet. There are even some New York legislators who tried to
win this same right by passing a bill in 1995, but it was vetoed by
Governor Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The governor was not swayed by arguments from consumers desiring
wines not available in stores. He was not moved by traditional
Republican arguments on the benefits of free trade. Pataki was not
even persuaded by the many small wineries in New York state that
favored opening the border. Although they could legally ship to
customers within New York, they were shut out of larger markets in
states allowing shipments only from states with reciprocal open
borders.
</P>
<P>
   The governor was concerned instead with the licensed cartel of
wholesale distributors and their unionized drivers with a monopoly
on out-of-state wines. ``A significant increase in mail-order
wines,'' Pataki warned, ``could, in turn, lead to a decrease in
sales for New York liquor stores and their distributors.''
</P>
<P>
   The wholesale distributors insist that they're not merely
concerned with profits. ``Direct shipping is a Pandora's Box to
under-age access,'' declares the Americans for Responsible Alcohol
Access, a national advocacy group financed largely by alcohol
wholesalers and retailers seeking to preserve the exclusive
distribution systems in New York and 29 other states.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the group arranged a press conference on ``cyberbooze''
at which Dennis C. Vacco, then the New York state attorney general,
announced a sting operation in which teen-age children of his staff
members had successfully ordered wine from California over the
Internet. Vacco, however, was not able to point to any minors in
New York state who had ever ordered wine on the Internet without
the assistance of his office.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you believe that teen-agers across New York are scheming
to order cases of merlot, it's not clear how much good is being
accomplished by the current prohibition against interstate
shipments. As long as it's legal to order from wineries in the
state, teen-agers could presumably get just as drunk on merlot from
Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the law argue that New York is justified in
discriminating against out-of-state wineries because they're harder
to police. ``New York can take away the license of a winery in the
state that sells to minors,'' said C. Boyden Gray, a former White
House counsel, who represents wine wholesalers. ``It doesn't have
jurisdiction over one in California.''
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-state vintners say the best way to stop minors from
ordering wine is for New York to pass a law, as other states have,
requiring all shipments of alcohol to carry a warning label and all
shippers to obtain a signature from an adult before releasing the
package.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York's law protects wholesalers, not minors,'' said
Deborah Simpson, a senior attorney at the Institute for Justice, a
public-interest law firm in Washington that filed the suit seeking
to overturn New York's law as an unconstitutional infringement on
interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law preserves a monopoly that collects 18 to 25 cents of
every dollar spent on a bottle of wine,'' Simpson said. ``It's even
illegal to send an out-of-state price list into New York, which
means that an out-of-state winery is violating the law if it
maintains a Web site with its prices. This is allowing the
protectionist policies of the 18th century to rule 21st-century
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Internet wine merchants have managed to ship to New York by
making arrangements with licensed wholesalers, but the process can
be cumbersome, and it adds what is essentially a tax to the
transaction. Pataki may be worried about depriving the wholesalers
of their cut, but a surcharge on imported beverages can lead to
other sorts of local happiness, as another sovereign named George
discovered at the Boston Tea Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0463 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2562 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MEXICO-NYT &LR;      07-03 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MEXICO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MEXICO'S DEMOCRATIC BREAKTHROUGH
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, July 4:
</P>
<P>
   Never before in the memory of living Mexicans has presidential
power passed peacefully to an opposition party. But just such a
transition is now under way, following the decisive victory of
Vicente Fox and his center-right National Action Party, or PAN, in
Sunday's Mexican elections. It is a great advance for democracy in
Latin America's second-largest country and Washington's
second-biggest trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico began prying lose the authoritarian grip of the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, more than a decade ago,
as its citizens came into contact with the democratic currents
sweeping Latin America and the world. Initial electoral challenges
were repulsed by intimidation and fraud, or bought off with
patronage. But opposition parties persisted, and during the
six-year term of President Ernesto Zedillo important reforms opened
up the electoral system. Statehouses fell to opposition governors.
Three years ago the combined opposition won a congressional
majority. That allowed scrutiny of the federal budget and cabinet
ministers. But Mexico's constitution concentrates power in the
presidency. Its passage into opposition hands is a transforming
event in the political life of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's transition toward a modern democracy also has
significance for the United States. No major policy differences
divide Fox's PAN from the long-ruling PRI. But the inauguration of
democratic competition at every level of Mexican politics can have
a salutary effect on a wide range of issues. It can provide a check
on official corruption in Mexico and mitigate the feelings of
political and economic powerlessness that have driven so many
Mexicans to emigrate illegally to the United States. Some officials
in Washington may miss the predictability of permanent rule by the
PRI. But wiser heads will see the positive potential in this week's
change.
</P>
<P>
   Besides winning the presidency, the PAN will also be the largest
party in the Congress. But to command a majority, it will have to
make deals with other political groups. This need for a broadly
based government should prove healthy, encouraging the PAN to reach
out to members of the center-left opposition as well as the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic intellectuals formed the PAN more than 60 years ago to
fight the secularism and land reform programs of Mexico's
post-revolutionary governments. More recently, the PAN has evolved
into a moderate pro-business party, well represented by Fox, a
former chief executive of Coca-Cola in Mexico. In building his
victory margin, Fox attracted considerable support from
left-of-center voters, many of whom felt that ending the PRI's
enduring grip on the presidency was the most important issue in
this year's election.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI, associated with so many electoral manipulations in the
past, behaved wisely and responsibly in defeat. Its candidate,
Francisco Labastida, conceded early and gracefully, getting the
lengthy five-month transition period off to a firm start. The PRI's
constructive new attitude owes much to Zedillo's enlightened
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo correctly understood that the only way to restore public
confidence in elections was to create an independent electoral
institute to supervise campaigning, balloting and the tallying of
votes. Without that crucial reform, this year's generally clean
campaign and Sunday's reliable count might not have been possible.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will not take office until Dec. 1. Past presidential
transitions have been marred by economic turmoil. In 1994, the
administration of Carlos Salinas failed to coordinate its financial
policies with Zedillo's incoming team, badly undermining
international confidence in the peso. The result was a painful
recession, which cost Mexicans dearly. Zedillo should draw the
appropriate lesson from that experience. Having given Mexico its
cleanest election ever, he can make a further contribution by
working closely with Fox and his advisers through the crucial
months ahead.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-03-00 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000703.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2564 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CYC-TEXAN-ROUND-TRIP-     07-03 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TEXAN-ROUND-TRIP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
56-YEAR-OLD TEXAN CYCLING AROUND STATE TO CELEBRATE BEATING CANCER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAWN REISS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Every few minutes, Jarrett ``Buddy'' Boren drinks a
50-50 mixture of mouthwash and water to stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   The back of his mouth and saliva glands were so badly burned
during radiation treatment for cancer six years ago that he must
use the concoction to keep his mouth moist enough to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Boren can no longer swallow dry foods like potato chips, and,
because his taste buds were scorched during the treatment, most of
what he ingests has no flavor at all to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss having a Coke and a Baby Ruth,'' said Boren, 56. ``But
there are a lot of people who have it worse than I do. At least I'm
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   And kicking.
</P>
<P>
   Starting today in Gainesville, Boren begins a 3,500-mile bicycle
trek around the state in celebration of his will to live and the
sixth anniversary of his victorious fight against cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas native and resident hopes his ``Ride for Life'' tour
will raise money for the Center for Cancer and Blood Disorders at
Children's Medical Center of Dallas. Most of all, he wants to
encourage those with cancer to keep fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a scary thing when the doctor tells you you have a 20
percent chance of living,'' Boren said. ``But that doesn't mean you
are not going to make it. Your decision not to give up is very
important to your survival. If you give up, it'll get you.''
</P>
<P>
   Boren has always dreamed big and fought the odds. He founded the
Grand Prix of Dallas, a now-defunct Sports Car Club of America
Trans-Am street race that he struggled to keep alive from 1988 to
1996. He has since retired, but he's still making big plans.
\Nsubheds:AN INSPIRATIONAL RIDE From Gainesville, Boren will head
west at about 2:30 p.m. today, outlining the Texas border as
closely as he can. His route will take him through Wichita Falls,
Dalhart, El Paso, Laredo, Brownsville, Marshall and back to his
starting point.
</P>
<P>
   Boren will camp in desolate areas when there aren't any hotels.
He hopes to ride 50 to 70 miles a day and complete the trip in
about 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Boren's mother, 83-year-old Oney Boren, said she is a bit
nervous for her son, but happy for him as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that if anything happened to him, I would come get
him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The temperature will top 100 degrees at times, but Boren said he
prefers sweltering in the sun to dealing with the heavy winds of
spring and fall.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trip, Boren will pass out yellow flyers detailing
his experience with cancer. He also will try to give speeches and
tour hospitals along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Boren will be riding a 24-gear Trek bicycle and is taking four
saddlebags filled with essentials: camping stove, cellphone, tent,
spare tires, thermometer, first-aid and shaving kits, clothes, maps
and sunblock. All this and two bottles of mouthwash, with more in
the mail to motels he will stay in and friends along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Boren plans to check in with friends every evening to update
them on his condition and whereabouts, which they will post on a
Web site, www.therideforlife.com.
</P>
<P>
   The total bill for the trip is approximately $10,000. Boren's
picking up most of the tab with help from a few sponsors, including
Bicycles Plus of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's soft-spoken and very humble,'' Bicycles Plus owner Marsha
Gorczyca said of Boren. ``He's not going to let anything stop him
in life. I wanted to help him out because he's a courageous guy
with a lot of guts and a lot to say to those have been struggling
like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Boren knows the trip won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, cancer survivor Lance Armstrong rode 2,255 miles
to win the 1999 Tour de France. Armstrong is currently second at
this year's Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he went through is an inspiration, and his winning
attitude certainly lent itself to what I'm trying to do,'' Boren
said. ``I want to make people realize that they can win, whether
it's the Tour de France or going back to work.''  &LR; subheds:AN
INSPIRATIONAL FIGHT Boren's road to recovery has been a long one.
</P>
<P>
   He first noticed a problem when he felt a lump the size of an
egg in his right shoulder in March 1994. He thought it was a
swollen gland, but his doctor told him it was cancer. The disease,
called squamous cell carcinoma, had started in Boren's nose and
spread to his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   That May, Boren had 36 cancerous tumors in his shoulder removed
and, shortly thereafter, he began radiation treatment for his nose,
throat and shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Boren lost 50 pounds in a six-month period after being put on a
liquid diet, reducing his already slender 5-foot-11 frame to a bony
shell of 118 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It slowly just takes you down,'' Boren said. ``A lot of times
people will confuse the cure with the disease. The radiation makes
you feel so bad that you think you are dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Boren continued running the Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrible because he was trying to work out of his bed
and it kept getting worse,'' said Boren's longtime friend, Alan
Garonzik of Argyle.''He just tried to keep a sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Boren's mother and a few close friends took care of him during
his recovery. A father of two, Boren and his wife had divorced in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Since his recovery, Boren has counseled 12 of his friends and
acquaintances with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would call me up and say, `I have just been diagnosed
with cancer, what do I do?' '' Boren said.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Morrison of Arlington was one such friend. Boren knew
Morrison, co-founder of Reher-Morrison Racing Engine in Arlington,
from his days with the Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt particularly close since I could tell him from my
standpoint what he could and couldn't expect,'' Boren said. ``The
radiation deals with people differently. He didn't have any
problems eating, but a year after his radiation, it came back and
he died. I couldn't believe it, because he was doing so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Boren said Morrison's death in December, 1998, helped motivate
him to do something extraordinary for cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wished I could talk to more people and tell them not to give
up because you just have to fight,'' Boren said.
</P>
<P>
   The trip, he hopes, will do that.
</P>
<P>
   Boren's not sure why he chose a bike, only that he thought it
would attract more attention than, say, a motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to think of a way to get my point across,''
Boren said. ``I wasn't sure if 3,500 miles was even possible, or 10
miles.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, Boren began training along city streets in Dallas for
the ride. It was the first time he had ridden a bike in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sore,'' Boren said of his first few days of training.
``Finally after riding a couple of hundred miles it was OK, so I
said I'm going to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   By June, Boren was occasionally riding 70 miles a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to do it this year,'' Boren said. ``I'm not getting any
younger. I felt like it was now or never.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
